</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SPURS-ROBINSON-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Time News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MURPHY  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
SAN ANTONIO _ When David Robinson steppe out of his Navy dress
whites in 1989 and slipped on the silver and black of the San
Antonio Spurs, he had visions of a long string of NBA
championships.
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was easy to see why.
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs were young and stocked with talented players like
Terry Cummings, Rod Strickland, Willie Anderson and Maurice Cheeks,
and most everyone thought they were the team of the future.
</P>
<P>
   Well, everyone was right. The Spurs were the team of the future
_ the distant future.
</P>
<P>
   After 10 years of waiting, Robinson and the Spurs are finally on
the verge of their first NBA Finals appearance, playing the Knicks
in Wednesday's Game 1 at the Alamodome, and Robinson couldn't be
happier.
</P>
<P>
   Well, that's not exactly true. He would have been happy to have
had a few more shots at a title. But he's not complaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like we would develop a lot quicker, especially that
first team that we had,'' Robinson said. ``I thought, `This team,
if we keep it together, we'll be in the Finals real soon.' But that
didn't happen. So I'm real pleased with just being here.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson appears so giddy about his first Finals appearance that
he might be asking people to stop and pinch him. But that would
probably only serve to remind him of all the knocks he's suffered
over the years.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson has been labeled as too soft. Too passive. Not
emotional enough. Too much of a goody-two-shoes ever to win it all
in the rough-and-tumble NBA.
</P>
<P>
   But you have to wonder what they'll be saying about Robinson,
who is the only American player to play on three Olympic basketball
teams (including the original Dream Team) and was named one of the
NBA's 50 Greatest Players, should the Spurs win it all.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy has been an MVP, a first-team All-NBA and a
(first-team) All-Defense player, so all he has to do is win a title
this year, and he'd shut everybody up,'' said teammate Mario Elie,
who spent considerable portions of the early season verbally
hammering the passiveness out of Robinson. ``He can be a soft
player with a ring.
</P>
<P>
   ``What does Charles (Barkley) have to say? What does Karl
(Malone) have to say? Whoever all the tough guys are, all the
supposed enforcers, they don't have a ring. It's good to be an
enforcer, but if you don't have a banner, you haven't accomplished
anything. If Dave can put a banner up in San Antonio, what bad
thing are you going to say?
</P>
<P>
   ``He will have accomplished everything in his career. I think in
the back of his mind he wants to shut everybody up.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is why Robinson has been so eager to make way for Tim
Duncan. Many questioned Robinson's heart when he voluntarily
stepped aside to let Duncan become the No. 1 option in the Spurs'
low-post attack, but Robinson shakes his head as if everyone else
just doesn't get it.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson points to the fact that while he had the lowest scoring
average of his career (15.8 points to Duncan's 21.7), this has been
the Spurs' most successful season.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the thing that draws all the attention, the numbers,''
Robinson said. ``But when you win, and you're a close-knit group,
then you need attitude. You need strength and a lot of things.
Those are the things I try to provide for the guys _ just a good,
solid balance.
</P>
<P>
   ``They know my energy defensively. The know that when things get
tough, they're looking at me. They're like, `Hey, we're down 15
points. What are you going to do?' So I know those are the areas I
need to be strong in, and going through a lot of the (negative)
things I've been through, it's helped me out.''
</P>
<P>
   And now he wants to help himself to a title.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson and Duncan figure to be the focal points for the Spurs
since the Knicks are vertically challenged after losing starting
center Patrick Ewing to a torn left Achilles' tendon. All the
Knicks have in reserve are 6-11 Chris Dudley, 6-11 jumping jack
Marcus Camby and 6-11 Herb Williams, the oldest player in the
league at 41.
</P>
<P>
   That could mean plenty of opportunities inside for Robinson and
Duncan.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's an advantage in this series,'' Robinson said.``They
have some incredible shooting guards, and we have good big men, so
we have to take advantage of what we have.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is an advantage. We'll see. Obviously it (a height
disadvantage) hasn't hurt them too much. They're here with a 4-2
(series) win over a good team (the Indiana Pacers).''
</P>
<P>
   And after 10 days of waiting, Robinson is itching to get on the
floor and see just how good those Knicks are. And how good his
Spurs are.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is awesome,'' Robinson said. ``At certain levels, my team
has been the best. But finally, at this level, here's an
opportunity to have a team that's the best. I'm not a stranger to
it, but it just feels good to be in that position and have that
opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm enjoying it already. I'm spending my afternoons with the
kids and then coming out here and enjoying this time. We've had a
lot of days here to let it all soak in. It's an opportunity that
doesn't come every day, so it's nice. We're preparing ourselves for
it the right way.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
