<SLUG> BC-BKW-LIBERTY-MYSTICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLDSCLAW AND MYSTICS BEAT LIBERTY, 83-61 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By LENA WILLIAMS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The last time Chamique Holdsclaw played at Madison
Square Garden, she went two for nine and had nine rebounds. That
was last January when she was still a college senior playing for
the Tennessee Vols, who went on to defeat Rutgers.
</P>
<P>
   Monday night, Holdsclaw made a triumphant return to her hometown
and the arena she admits she had hoped to play in as a pro, this
time as a heralded rookie with the Washington Mystics of the
Women's National Basketball Association. The butterflies were gone
and Holdsclaw's game _ the one her former coach, Pat Summitt,
predicted would return Monday night _ returned just in time to help
the Mystics muster their first victory of the season and hand the
Liberty its first loss.
</P>
<P>
   Behind Nikki McCray's game-high 24 points and Holdsclaw's 20
points and nine rebounds, the Mystics sailed to an 83-61 victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm definitely excited right now,'' Holdsclaw said. ``Number
one, we didn't expect to beat such a great team, especially such a
strong defensive team, but we didn't get down and it was great to
get that first win.''
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Darsch, who was fired as Liberty coach last year only to
end up in Washington, said the victory wasn't any sweeter coming
against her old team.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a bittersweet moment,'' said Darsch. ``Anytime you're 0
and 2, you're anxious to get that first win. We would have liked to
get it before our home crowd, but we'll take it where it comes.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Holdsclaw, who was greeted to warm cheers from the 12,563
partisan crowd, Darsch was met with a smattering of boos.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought that's what I heard,'' she said with a shrug. ``I
don't know why they were booing. I didn't leave here.''
</P>
<P>
   The Liberty, playing without Rebecca Lobo, who suffered a
season-ending knee injury in the opener last week, missed the
6-foot-4 center's presence in the low post, where they were
outrebounded 32-26. Sue Wicks, Kym Hampton and Theresa Weatherspoon
combined for 15 rebounds, but the team shot only 34 percent from
the field and played a loose, nervous game that never matched
Washington's intensity.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were a step slow in every situation,'' said Liberty coach
Richie Audabato. ``They were getting us on the board. We only shot
34 percent which was awfully tough.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the game, Summitt telephoned Holdsclaw, the player who
helped her win three national championships, the third such call in
24 hours. ``I was concerned about her,'' explained Summit, an
analyst for ESPN. ``She's 0 and 2.'' Summitt's advice to Holdsclaw
was to play her game.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, ``post up, get inside the paint, take the
shot.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Score over somebody,'' Summitt told her. Holdsclaw said her
former coach told her not to get depressed and to be the leader she
was capable of being.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do the job,'' she said Summit advised her.
</P>
<P>
   It's no secret that the WNBA is looking to Holdsclaw to do for
the league what Michael Jordan ultimately did for the NBA. Still,
she's just a rookie, and Holdsclaw said playing against veterans
like Weatherspoon and Houston's Cynthia Cooper, night after night,
has taken some adjustments from her college days. Some of the
Liberty players said they lost Monday night to a hungrier team.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Mystics played great, Chamique and Nikki played great,''
said Weatherspoon. ``But my main concern was about our intensity.
We didn't come and do it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
