<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-RANGERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES DEFEAT RANGERS, 8-2 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Hideki Irabu dug at the mud around the pitcher's
rubber on Monday night to gather his footing. He wiped the
perspiration and rain off his face with his glove, gazed in at the
Texas Rangers and kept challenging them. It was a rigorous night
for Irabu, regardless of what his impressive statistics were. The
Rangers made Irabu work, Irabu worked relentlessly and the Yankees
won, 8-2.
</P>
<P>
   Before a gray afternoon turned into a soggy night at Yankee
Stadium, Manager Joe Torre spoke about how the Yankees needed to
see consistency from Irabu. Torre almost seemed to be pleading with
Irabu to end the mystery about his Jekyll-and-Hyde performances by
giving the Yankees the same steady effort every time he grips the
baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Torre will definitely take a succession of reliable starts like
Monday night's from Irabu. The right-hander pitched seven innings
and permitted two runs on five hits. Toss in Chili Davis' three-run
homer and four runs batted in off Mark Clark and the Yankees, a
Jekyll-and-Hyde team themselves with an ordinary 6 victories in
their last 11 games, looked like the first-place team they are.
</P>
<P>
   ``The byproduct of working hard is winning,'' Torre said. ``I
can't sell them on not being frustrated. I would rather have guys
who are frustrated than guys who say: `We're in first place. What
are you worried about?'''
</P>
<P>
   What made Irabu's second victory in three starts so rewarding to
the Yankees is how feisty and effective he was with runners on
base. Irabu uncorked 71 pitches through four innings and was not
overpowering. He had to be creative and he had to fight, which he
did in forcing the Rangers to go 0 for 10 with runners on base and
0 for 7 with runners in scoring position over the first five
innings.
</P>
<P>
   That is when it mattered the most because the Yankees followed a
49-minute rain relay in the fifth with four runs on run-scoring
singles from Davis and Jorge Posada and a two-run single from Scott
Brosius. It increased their lead to 8-0 and allowed everyone in
pinstripes to relax. Even Irabu, who struck out five, walked one
and was no mystery.
</P>
<P>
   ``He needs to be consistent,'' Torre said. ``I know it's a lot
to ask. We expect a lot of ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Irabu started toiling from the first batter as Mark McLemore
opened with a double to right field. But Irabu got Ruben Mateo to
squib back to him, then engaged in an eight-pitch duel with Rusty
Greer before striking him out on a split-finger fastball. When Juan
Gonzalez lined a bullet to third base, Irabu exhaled.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez's two-run homer in the sixth was the only damage off
Irabu, who has allowed seven earned runs in the last 172/3 innings
while pitching decently in three straight starts.
</P>
<P>
   There were more minefields to avoid in the second, however, when
Rafael Palmeiro's single and Chuck Knoblauch's throwing error, the
second baseman's 11th of the season, put Rangers on first and
second. Again, Irabu remained calm. He struck out Todd Zeile on a
2-2 fastball and Knoblauch helped him out by snaring Lee Stevens's
grounder and starting a nifty double play.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers threatened again in the third after McLemore slapped
a one-out single and pilfered second, but Irabu induced Mateo to
pop out and pumped a 2-2 fastball past Greer, whom he whiffed three
times.
</P>
<P>
   Torre had canceled batting practice and told his players not to
show up until two hours before last night's game. He wanted them to
be rested after a long trip and wanted them to forget about
Sunday's dreadful 8-2 loss to the Marlins in Florida. When Torre
was asked if the listless Yankees were close to finding a groove,
he said, ``Not after yesterday.''
</P>
<P>
   But maybe the Yankees were a bit closer after Monday night.
After Clark walked three batters in the first and the Yankees
managed one run on Tino Martinez's sacrifice fly, Davis stared at
Clark's 1-2 pitch and struck out with the bases filled. When he
batted with two out and two on in the third, however, Davis stayed
back on a 2-1 changeup and hammered it into the right field seats
for a three-run homer that put the Yankees in front, 4-0. Irabu
handled the rest.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're pulling for him,'' Torre said. ``Every start is
important. Not for any other reason than we want him to be
consistent. We're not trying to penalize him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
