<HEADLINE>
WITH TENTATIVE PACT AVERTING STRIKE, TWA SHARES TAKE OFF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RANDOLPH HEASTER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Shares of {Trans World Airlines} rose Monday
after the airline's weekend announcement of a tentative contract
agreement with the {Machinists} union.
</P>
<P>
   TWA's common stock was up and closed at 5 in heavy trading on
the American Stock Exchange. The stock was up more than 1 point at
one time during the day.
</P>
<P>
   Investors reacted favorably after a month of uncertainty at the
St. Louis-based airline. TWA and the Machinists were in the midst
of a countdown toward a strike deadline. Last week, TWA workers
appeared to be voting down a previous contract proposal that union
negotiators had urged workers to reject.
</P>
<P>
   Now company and union officials are hoping TWA's 16,000
mechanics, flight attendants and passenger-service employees will
ratify the new contracts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, we think it's good news,'' said Linda Bannister,
airline analyst with {Edward Jones}. ``I don't think management
would agree to a contract they can't afford.''
</P>
<P>
   Had the June 30 deadline approached without a tentative
agreement, TWA faced losing many travelers during the crucial
summer months, said David Levine, contributing editor of
/{PlaneBusiness/}, an industry financial newsletter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think both sides were feeling the pressure of what might
happen,'' he said. ``The union got a chance to let the members vent
their frustration by rejecting the company's proposal, and
management got to show stockholders that they took the process as
far as it could go.''
</P>
<P>
   Some reports have indicated that the contract will run for 18
months, an unusually short period for a labor agreement. Company
and union officials have declined comment. Details of the new
package are expected to be released today.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
