<SLUG> BC-SPRINT-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPRINT NAMES FIRST MINORITY BOARD MEMBER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TED SICKINGER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OVERLAND PARK, Kan. _ Meeting in Paris over the weekend, Sprint
Corp.'s board of directors elected Louis W. Smith, president and
chief executive officer of the Ewing Marion Kauffman Foundation, to
the company's board.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, an African-American, is the first minority elected to
Sprint's board, which has 12 executives.
</P>
<P>
   His appointment comes as the company is being pressured to add
minorities and women to its boardroom and executive ranks and to
provide more opportunities to minority contractors in the
construction of its $750 million campus in Overland Park.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint officials acknowledge the need to promote diversity at
the company, but they say Smith's appointment has no connection to
recent discussions with the Coalition of Concerned Clergy or Jesse
Jackson's Rainbow//PUSH Coalition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Louis Smith is an extraordinary businessman and outstanding
leader, recognized here in this city and across the country,'' said
Mark Bonavia, a Sprint spokesman. ``Those are the reasons why he
was selected.
</P>
<P>
   ``Speculation about any pressure relative to Mr. Smith's
election is dead wrong. Our board of directors' strategy is and
always will be to select the people that we need who possess proven
business and leadership skills. Lou Smith fits that description.''
</P>
<P>
   Before joining the Kauffman Foundation, Smith worked for 29
years with AlliedSignal, retiring in 1995 as president of the
Kansas City division.
</P>
<P>
   He serves on the boards of H&AMP;R Block Inc., Western Resources
Inc., Commerce Bank of Kansas City, Midwest Research Institute and
the Civic Council of Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   Smith was returning from Paris on Monday and could not be
reached for comment. But his appointment was applauded by local
minority groups involved in recent discussions with the company.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lou Smith will bring a new dimension to the board,'' said L.
Henderson Bell, president of the Coalition of Concerned Clergy in
Kansas City. ``He has a unique capacity to understand the civil
rights of business and the community. He's someone who understands
the tilt of the field.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith has not yet been appointed to any board post or committee.
But Bonavia said the board probably would seek his input relative
to diversity issues.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint became a focus of minority groups' attention in February.
The Rev. Wallace Hartsfield was asked by a group of local minority
contractors to question Sprint about what the group considered a
lack of women and minorities being used to construct its new
campus.
</P>
<P>
   Those discussions gathered more steam last week when Jackson
came to Kansas City to raise money for his Rainbow//PUSH Coalition.
While in town, Jackson met with several Sprint executives to
discuss diversity issues and spoke with Sprint Chairman William T.
Esrey by phone.
</P>
<P>
   His coalition also bought $2,000 worth of stock in Sprint to
make it a part of Jackson's Wall Street Project, an effort to buy
stock in major corporations as a means of gaining access to those
companies.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson started the project about a year ago at the national
level, and he is encouraging similar efforts in local communities.
</P>
<P>
   Out of the estimated $750 million it will cost to build the
Sprint campus, the company has committed to spending at least $40
million with businesses owned by minorities and women. So far, it
has reached $7 million in contracts with minority businesses.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
