<SLUG> BC-FAIR-CEO-PAY-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHAREHOLDERS DON'T SEEM BOTHERED BY CEO-WORKER SALARY GAP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE STAFFORD  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, MO. _ An effort to tie CEO pay more closely to
average worker salaries met with limited support at eight corporate
annual meetings this spring.
</P>
<P>
   {United for a Fair Economy}, a Boston-based organization that is
trying to reduce the pay gap between top executives and their
employees, reported Friday that more than 500 million shareholder
votes were cast in favor of gap-shrinking resolutions.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, all of the resolutions failed by wide margins.
</P>
<P>
   The greatest support for pay equalization came from shareholders
of {R.R. Donnelley}, which met in March. A resolution on gender-
and race-based pay equity received 16.6 percent of the vote at the
printing company.
</P>
<P>
   The Fair Economy organization selected the eight corporations as
those where corporate leaders received large pay increases while
rank-and-file jobs were being cut.
</P>
<P>
   At seven of the corporations, Fair Economy-backed resolutions
called for CEO pay to be tied to a multiple of the lowest-paid
worker's pay at the company. The seven companies and the vote
percentages:
</P>
<P>
   {AlliedSignal}, 12 percent for and 88 percent against.
</P>
<P>
   {AT&AMP;T}, 7.6 percent for and 92.4 percent against.
</P>
<P>
   {BankAmerica}, 6.7 percent for and 93.3 percent against.
</P>
<P>
   {BankBoston}, 4.8 percent for and 95.2 percent against.
</P>
<P>
   {Citigroup}, 10.8 percent for and 89.2 percent against.
</P>
<P>
   {General Electric}, 5 percent for and 95 percent against.
</P>
<P>
   {Huffy}, 8.3 percent for and 91.7 percent against.
</P>
<P>
   The shareholder resolutions were sponsored by Responsible
Wealth, a project of United for a Fair Economy that is a network of
more than 400 affluent Americans who are concerned about economic
inequality.
</P>
<P>
   Responsible Wealth spokesmen said they were not dispirited by
the vote percentages in favor of their pay-equity resolutions. They
said annual meeting voting procedures typically favored management
in proxy voting.
</P>
<P>
   Responsible Wealth spokesmen also said they were glad to have
started a dialogue on the pay issue. Management at AT&AMP;T,
BankAmerica and BankBoston issued statements acknowledging that
growing pay gaps were a social and business problem.
</P>
<P>
   The group intends to continue its efforts in August by
introducing a shareholder resolution at Computer Associates' annual
meeting. Next year, it intends to resubmit resolutions at several
of the corporations and do more resolutions.
</P>
<P>
   Members also are pledging to push mutual fund managers to
disclose their proxy voting records, something that typically is
kept secret by most mutual funds.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
