<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAYNE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAYNE CHRISTENSEN FORMS ALLIANCES WITH MINING COMPANIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RANDOLPH HEASTER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ {Layne Christensen Co.} has formed two joint
ventures involved in the mining industry.
</P>
<P>
   {International Directional Services} is owned by Layne's
{Directional Drilling Services} division and {Silver State Surveys
Inc.} With headquarters in Salt Lake City, the company has drilling
projects in Canada, Latin America, eastern Africa and the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   Another Layne subsidiary, {Stanley Mining Services Ltd.}, has
merged its supply and logistics operations with {Supply Direct
Ltd.}, which is owned by {Ausdrill Ltd.} The name of the joint
venture is {Supply Direct South Africa Ltd.}, which is in
Johannesburg, South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   The merged company will have the resources to expand Stanley and
Ausdrill's mineral drilling businesses. Layne also has joined with
Ausdrill on mineral drilling services in west Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Despain, Layne's senior vice president, said these moves
were part of the company's efforts to restructure its mineral
exploration business, an industry that has been sluggish recently.
</P>
<P>
   Based in Mission Woods, Layne provides services and products for
the water supply, mineral exploration, geotechnical construction
and environmental markets.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
