<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-15 00:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5537 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-KINGS-MURRAY-LADN     06-15 0561
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-MURRAY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MURRAY HAS EYE FOR DETAIL, PASSION FOR THE GAME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Immaculately dressed in dark-blue suit, starched
white shirt and gold tie, his graying hair only a few misplaced
strands shy of Jimmy Johnson perfection, the Los Angeles Kings' new
coach had his coming-out party Monday and appeared every bit the
detail fiend he's purported to be.
</P>
<P>
   In short, Andy Murray looked the part, and during a media
gathering near the Staples Center construction site, he did nothing
to dispel the workaholic image he brings with him after 20-plus
years as a career coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are certain variables you can control,'' the 48-year-old
Murray said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was very prepared,'' general manager Dave Taylor said. ``He
had a lot of knowledge of our team. He came in prepared for the
interview and I was very impressed throughout. It wasn't just what
I knew about him. I made a lot of calls. I didn't hear one bad word
about him.''
</P>
<P>
   When Murray arrived for his initial interview, he brought
printed breakdowns on Kings players, a statistical analysis of the
dreary 1998-99 season, and a plan that included speaking to each
player on the team, visiting some in their homes in North America
and abroad, and conditioning objectives.
</P>
<P>
   Attention to detail? Murray a former Canadian national team
coach who spent this season at a Minnesota prep school, said he
wants to send flowers to each of the players' wives on the first
day of training camp to remind them of their importance to the
Kings' success.
</P>
<P>
   There's no word on whether Robinson resorted to such niceties.
But calling FTD will be the easy part. The hard part will be
improving a team that allowed too many shots on goal last season
while struggling at the other end of the ice.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll play a hard-working defensive game,'' Murray said. ``I
want the players, when they don't have the puck, to know their
responsibilities. But when they have the puck, I want them to be
creative, because that's what the fans want to see.''
</P>
<P>
   Murray also will need to shore up team discipline. Captain Rob
Blake and left wing Luc Robitaille criticized Robinson last season
for not being firm with teammates who weren't performing well.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a guy's not working, why is he playing?'' Robitaille said.
``... With this coach, I think that's going to change.''
</P>
<P>
   Blake played for Murray two years ago when Canada won a gold
medal at the World Championships, and said he expects the Kings'
new coach to be tougher than the old one.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone's not fit to do that,'' Blake said. ``Andy uses a lot
of words like `passion.' But he really believes in that and the
players will buy into it.'' Asked if he felt prepared to discipline
highly paid professional athletes, Murray said, ``I didn't need
this job. I wanted this job. I find there's nothing worse as a
coach after lack of success than to say, `I didn't do it my way.' I
don't know how not to challenge the players to be the best they can
be.''
</P>
<P>
   Questioned about his stint at the high school level, Murray said
he was refreshed by spending the year working with enthusiastic
young players.
</P>
<P>
   ``Leadership,'' Murray said, ``is all about getting people to do
what you want them to do because they want to do it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
