r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JEDI-REVENGE-LADN     06-15 0851
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JEDI-REVENGE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`PHANTOM' SHOWS US THE DARK SIDE, AND IT IS US
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Tad Cronn is assistant copy chief at the Los Angeles Daily News) 
BY TAD CRONN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The critics have spoken: ``Star Wars: Episode 1 _ The Phantom
Menace'' is a farce, a violent travesty, a waste of digitized
footage.
</P>
<P>
   If the world wasn't sure that George Lucas had spent his last
iota of talent long ago, it is now. And Lucas' latent racist
tendencies are on full display with that Jar Jar Binks _ a Stepin
Fetchit for the new millennium.
</P>
<P>
   Blah, blah, blah.
</P>
<P>
   If you're like me _ and the Force informs me that most of you
are _ you don't give a Jawa's heinie what critics say. You've long
since realized that the vast majority of professional film
reviewers are agents of the Empire _ or at least aspire to be.
</P>
<P>
   I say enough. It's high time the overwrought lemonheads who have
been slamming ``Phantom Menace'' pony up a quarter and buy a clue.
</P>
<P>
   On behalf of all people who don't watch films by looking past
their nostrils, I feel compelled to speak up on behalf of ``Phantom
Menace'' and its troupe of intergalactic misfits.
</P>
<P>
   The real reason some people loathe the ``Star Wars'' films so,
quite simply, is that the entire philosophical outlook of the
series is inimical to them. The old theme of good vs. evil is
perpetually recycled by Hollywood hacks, but when a director like
Lucas gets hold of it, revitalizes it and makes it resonate, it
becomes a challenge to the audience.
</P>
<P>
   Let's face it: We are not a society that rises swiftly to meet
the attack of evil. We're more inclined to rationalize our misdeeds
than face up to why they might be wrong. Just ask the guy in the
Oval Office _ he knows that number by heart.
</P>
<P>
   If Darth Maul were a real person, it's not difficult to see
people defending him as not evil, only ``differently socialized.''
Without a doubt, he would be a celebrity, and probably a
politician.
</P>
<P>
   Make no mistake, seduction by evil is very much what the ``Star
Wars'' series is about. Giving in to evil is very much what our
culture is about.
</P>
<P>
   Think about that for a moment. What does Yoda tell us are the
tools of the Dark Side?
</P>
<P>
   !bbox!Anger. Think abusive bosses. Think talk shows. Think
parents beating their kids. Think gangsters. Think Columbine High
School.
</P>
<P>
   !bbox!Fear. Consider the reasons underlying Neighborhood Watch.
Or handgun legislation. Or gated communities. I have a lock on my
door _ how about you?
</P>
<P>
   !bbox!Aggression. Ever yell at someone for cutting in front of
you in line? How about while driving? Have you gotten even lately
or tried to put someone in his place?
</P>
<P>
   And what's the ultimate goal of the Dark Side? Darth Vader tells
several times: Power. Luke Skywalker may not have sought the power
of the Dark Side, but we would like to. Ever thought about climbing
the corporate ladder? That's a desire for power. Have you ever
tried to accumulate more money? That's a kind of power. Who are our
cultural ``heroes'' these days? Generally not people who give of
themselves, but people who have ``made it,'' i.e., who have gotten
the wealth and success _ the power _ we wish we had.
</P>
<P>
   ``Phantom Menace'' has struck many a nerve because it shows us
the antithesis of what we are. One of the themes of ``Phantom
Menace'' is innocence, the opposite of the corruption represented
by the Dark Side of the Force.
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, the story is deliberately told with a very
childlike point of view, embodied by the heroes Anakin ``Spinning
is a Good Trick'' Skywalker, Queen Amidala and the allegedly
offensive Jar Jar Binks, who by temperament if not age is a klutzy
preteen goofball. (If you think he's a racist caricature, then
answer this question: Which ethnic group has historically been
portrayed as 7-foot tall trachodons with floppy bunny ears and bell
bottom pants?)
</P>
<P>
   If Jar Jar, Amidala and Anakin are difficult for some people to
relate to, it's because we are not very much like them. We're more
akin to the evil Trade Federation _ true Yankee traders if ever
there were such in space.
</P>
<P>
   The droid army is the very image of the perfect capitalist
corporation _ run by identical, efficient, unquestioning automatons
that can overpower all opposition. You can almost imagine the
battle droids with Microsoft and Nike logos on the sides of their
heads and droning, ``Obey your thirst. Obey. Obey!'' as they march
over some helpless community of nonconsumers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Phantom Menace'' is a well-crafted film. It makes some folks
uncomfortable because accepting it on its own terms means looking
at ourselves. If George Lucas did not set out to create a social
commentary, the virulence and bitterness of critics has provided it
for him as they let loose their own anger and aggressive impulses.
</P>
<P>
   Anakin Skywalker is the innocence each of us once had. Darth
Vader is the person many of us would like to become: fear-inspiring
lords of the greedy Empire. We are our own phantom menace.
</P>
<P>
   Where's Luke Skywalker when you need him?
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-15-99 0109EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
