</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ENERGY-EAST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENERGY EAST SET TO ACQUIRE CMP GROUP 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Maine, N.Y.) (sw) 
 By AGIS SALPUKAS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Energy East Corp., the parent company of the New York State
Electric and Gas Corp., will acquire the CMP Group, the parent
company of Central Maine Power, in a transaction valued at $957
million, the companies said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, which was scheduled to be announced on
Tuesday, Energy East will acquire all 32.4 million common shares of
the CMP Group for $29.50 a share in cash and assume $271 million in
preferred stock and long-term debt.
</P>
<P>
   The merger will bring together two major utilities in the
Northeast, a region in which most states are deregulating utilities
to give customers a choice of suppliers.
</P>
<P>
   This has put great pressure on utilities to find merger partners
so that they can increase the size of their service areas and cut
costs.
</P>
<P>
   New York State Electric serves 820,000 electric customers and
240,000 natural gas customers in upstate New York and employs
4,000.
</P>
<P>
   Central Maine serves 530,000 electric customers in central and
southern Maine, which contains three- quarters of the state's
population. The utility employs 1,800 workers.
</P>
<P>
   David T. Flanagan, the president and chief executive officer of
the CMP Group, said that while there might be a reduction of some
traditional utility jobs as a result of the merger at Central Maine
Power, there would also be opportunities to create new jobs.
</P>
<P>
   While CMP will become a wholly owned subsidiary of Energy East
it will keep its corporate headquarters in Augusta, Maine. Flanagan
will be chairman, president and chief executive of the CMP Group
after the merger and will also become president of Energy East,
which is based in Ithaca, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Welsley W. von Schack, the chairman, president and chief
executive of Energy East, said in an interview on Monday that
``we're trying to create a new company that will be a leading
energy distribution company in the Northeast and that will have the
size to give customers a new array of products and services.''
</P>
<P>
   As states such as New York and Maine deregulate, they have
required that their utilities sell off power plants and become
transmission companies that deliver power and natural gas to
customers.
</P>
<P>
   Both Energy East and CMP have sold off their generating plants.
</P>
<P>
   Deregulated utilities have also been seeking ways to market
services such as energy audits and ways of making factories, retail
outlets and homes more energy efficient. Some are also seeking to
get into the telecommunication business.
</P>
<P>
   Energy East, for example, announced in April that for $617
million in cash it was acquiring the Connecticut Energy Corp.,
whose subsidiary, the Southern Connecticut Gas Co., delivers gas to
160,000 customers in southern Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   Energy East stock closed at $26.25, up 6.25 cents, in trading on
the New York Stock Exchange. CMP stock was unchanged, closing at
$20.625, in trading on the New York Stock Exchange. Energy East has
been buying back its stock purchasing nearly 10 million shares. Von
Schack said that the merger would not affect its stock repurchase
program.
</P>
<P>
   Flanagan said that both utilities had worked together in the
past and therefore already had ties.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've dated before we tied the knot,'' he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-15-99 0111EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
