<DOCNO> NYT19990615.0012 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-15 01:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5557 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     06-15 0781
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MURRAY BRINGS FRESH PERSPECTIVE TO KINGS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It was 70 degrees in the shade Monday in L.A.'s
concrete city center, the kind of weather that leaves Angelenos
salivating for iced tea, maybe, but certainly not ice hockey.
Whoever says there is no change of seasons in Southern California
cannot be a sports fan. Just try selling us on the NHL in June. You
might as well be pitching open-toed sandals to Minnesotans in
January.
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo versus Dallas in the Stanley Cup Finals? Please. Our
neighbor's yard sale attracted more interest locally over the
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Into this abyss strode Andy Murray, looking amazingly crisp for
someone battling the heat and jet lag and indifference toward any
new coach in town not named Phil Jackson. He began to speak, this
man who just had been handed the job that had turned Larry
Robinson's hair gray, and his words hit his audience in the
downtown office building like a blast of air conditioning.
</P>
<P>
   People sat up a little straighter in their seats. There were
murmurs of approval _ one guy whispered loud enough for one whole
side of the room to hear, ``He speaks very well.'' And it was true.
</P>
<P>
   A crowd that only hours before had thought Anne was the only
Murray of any note to come out of Canada, sat transfixed as he
stood in the sweltering room, dripping passion while everyone else
sprouted beads of sweat.
</P>
<P>
   Five minutes into his first speech as the Kings' head coach, it
was obvious why general manager Dave Taylor was sold on this man
with no previous NHL head-coaching experience. Suddenly it didn't
seem at all a stretch to picture this man who had spent the past
season coaching at a prep school in Minnesota directing the Kings
into the next millennium.
</P>
<P>
   Rob Blake will be riding shotgun on this venture and he couldn't
be more comfortable. The Kings' captain and star defenseman stood
in the back of the room, grinning, as Murray's intensity washed
over the room, transforming everyone it touched.
</P>
<P>
   This wasn't the first time Blake has seen Murray turn skeptics
into apostles with one fiery address. In 1997, one of Murray's
motivational speeches convinced Blake to represent Canada in the
World Championships. Another one of Murray's talks coalesced the
hastily thrown-together band of patriots, who then went out and won
the gold medal.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he was up there speaking, I could see people in the room
were responding to his passion,'' Blake said. ``I looked over at
(teammate) Luc (Robitaille) and he was feeding off Andy's
intensity.''
</P>
<P>
   It should surprise no one that Murray talks with the zeal of an
army recruiting officer. For three years he was one, in a manner of
speaking. From 1996 to 1998 he scoured the plains of Canada and the
outposts of the NHL, looking for a few good men to carry the Maple
Leaf flag into battle.
</P>
<P>
   Murray served on the coaching staff of Team Canada during the
1996 World Cup of Hockey and the 1998 Olympics in Nagano and in
between ran the Canadian National Team like an arm of the military.
</P>
<P>
   When Murray said of the Kings, ``We expect to be a disciplined,
energetic, hard-working team,'' bet on it. His teams tend to be as
good as his word.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings may not challenge Dallas right away for Western
supremacy. But they won't skate like they did far too many nights
en route to missing the playoffs with a 32-45-5 record.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get from people that which you expect of them,'' Murray
said. ``I'll never question a player's pride. But I may at times
question his work ethic.''
</P>
<P>
   Murray, 48, has been coaching long enough to have figured out
that players, stripped of their pretensions and paychecks, are just
big kids at heart. Like his own three children, his players might
think they know what's best for themselves and occasionally
challenge authority. But deep down it's discipline and direction
they crave.
</P>
<P>
   So he won't insult them by giving them sovereignty and control.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think we know how to prepare,'' Blake said, chuckling.
``I'm probably the worst at saying we don't need to watch video,
let's just go out and play the game. You won't get anyone cutting
corners like that with Andy. He'll install discipline.
</P>
<P>
   ``Players will question him at first. But I don't think
anybody's going to stray. If they do, there'll be consequences to
pay.''
</P>
<P>
   To which we say, hallelujah, Lord have mercy. It's about time
somebody held the players accountable. If nothing else, he brings
to the job a fresh perspective. After years of the same stale
results, that's as welcome as a summer breeze.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
