<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-15 01:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5560 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-BRAVES-ASTROS-HNS     06-15 0933
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-ASTROS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH DUARTE  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
It's only June, right?
<TEXT>
<P>
   Somebody forgot to tell the Astros.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Hampton pitched seven strong innings and Craig Biggio had
three doubles Monday night as the Astros pounded the Atlanta Braves
10-4 in an early-season meeting of National League division
leaders.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros, playing without manager Larry Dierker for the first
time this season, extended their winning streak to four games and
tied the best start in club history after 61 games (38-23).
</P>
<P>
   Dierker will undergo brain surgery today after suffering a
seizure in the dugout during Sunday's game with San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the questions everybody asked was how we were going to
bounce back from yesterday's adversity,'' interim manager Matt
Galante said. ``I think you saw the kind of makeup this club has.
We've bounced back from adversity all season.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, Jeff Bagwell and Craig Biggio were among
players, coaches and management personnel to visit Dierker at
Methodist Hospital. As a tribute to their stricken manager,
Dierker's No. 49 jersey hung in the Astros' dugout during the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Larry has done a lot of good things for people here, and we
are going to continue to hang it everywhere we go until he
returns,'' Biggio said. ``We're going to dedicate the rest of the
season to him.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros broke open a 4-3 game with a four-run sixth inning to
send the Braves to their fourth straight defeat. Atlanta, reeling
from a 22-1 loss to Baltimore on Sunday, has been outscored 32-5 in
the last two games.
</P>
<P>
   Hampton, who won for the eighth time in his last nine decisions,
held the Braves to three runs and seven hits in seven innings. He
struck out five and walked one in extending his lifetime record to
4-1 against Atlanta in the Astrodome.
</P>
<P>
   In his last 10 starts, Hampton is 7-1 with a 2.49 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   Hampton (8-2) said his thoughts during the game were with
Dierker.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was definitely on my mind,'' Hampton said. ``We just want
him to get well and back to being the old Larry. We're just going
to try and go from here and do what he wanted _ for us to beat the
Braves. I think we really wanted this game for him and to continue
playing well in his absence.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the Astros' offensive highlights: Derek Bell drove in
three runs, Bagwell hit his 21st homer, Carl Everett went 4-for-5
and Biggio increased his major-league-best doubles total to 29.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros wasted little time jumping on lefthander Odalis
Perez, striking for two runs in the first. Biggio led off with a
double and, after two walks, scored on Bell's infield grounder.
Richard Hidalgo's sacrifice fly made it 2-0.
</P>
<P>
   Javy Lopez sliced the lead to 2-1 in the second, sending
Hampton's first pitch of the inning over the left-field wall. Lopez
added an RBI double in the eighth off reliever Jay Powell.
</P>
<P>
   ``After Javy hit that home run, I blamed it on Larry,'' Hampton
joked. ``That was his home run.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros pushed the lead back to two in the second inning when
Everett led off with a single and scored three batters later on a
grounder by Hampton.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta pulled back within one run in the fourth inning as
Biggio made just his third error of the season. With two outs,
Biggio mishandled a grounder by Lopez, and Andruw Jones followed
with a triple to make the score 3-2.
</P>
<P>
   But every time the Braves scored, the Astros had a response. In
the fourth, Tony Eusebio walked, Tim Bogar singled and Biggio's
second double scored Eusebio.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta threatened in the sixth when Chipper Jones led off with
a single and Brian Jordan's double cut the lead to 4-3. With nobody
out, Hampton got the next three hitters to ground out, including
two to shortstop Ricky Gutierrez, as the Braves stranded the
potential tying run at third base.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros put the game away in the sixth by sending nine
batters to the plate against Perez and reliever Kevin McGlinchy.
Hampton walked, and then the Astros took batting practice.
</P>
<P>
   Biggio hit his third double, and two batters later Bagwell was
intentionally walked to load the bases. Bell followed with a
two-run single to left, giving him seven RBIs in the last two
games. Hidalgo and Everett followed with run-scoring singles to put
the Astros ahead 8-3.
</P>
<P>
   Bagwell added a home run off John Rocker to lead off the eighth.
Of Bagwell's 21 home runs, Monday's was his third at the Astrodome.
</P>
<P>
   Perez allowed six runs and seven hits over five innings. He
struck out five and walked seven (one intentionally). During the
past two games, Braves starting pitchers have surrendered 13 runs
and 14 hits in 7 innings.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros are 15-3 against lefthanders this season.
</P>
<P>
   Trever Miller pitched the last 1 innings for his first save,
lowering his ERA to 1.98.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's my job to stay ready, no matter if I have a hundred days
off,'' said Miller, who hadn't pitched since June 5.
</P>
<P>
   Whether it was against the Braves or any other team, Monday's
victory was a much-needed lift.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time you face the Braves, you know you're in for a
battle,'' Galante said.
</P>
<P>
   Dierker's absence marked the first time he had missed a game as
manager in two years. He missed two games May 21-22, 1997, after
the death of his father, Charles. The Astros went 1-1 with Bill
Virdon as interim manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the news from the hospital really picked us up,''
Galante said. ``I think we had good news, after we probably
expected worse than it was. We were able to talk about it, and we
all felt a lot better.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
