<SLUG> BC-GEN-AWARD-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LONG BEACH STATE'S MAY NAMED TOP FEMALE ATHLETE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILLY WITZ  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONG BEACH, Calif. _ Misty May's perfect season got a little
more perfect Monday night when the Long Beach State volleyball star
was awarded the Honda-Broderick Cup, given annually to the top
female athlete in collegiate sports.
</P>
<P>
   May, a two-time national player of the year who this season
helped the 49ers become the first team in women's volleyball to
ever go undefeated in winning national championship, was presented
the award at a dinner in Reno, Nev., where the National Association
of Collegiate Directors of Athletics convention is being held.
</P>
<P>
   Past winners include soccer player Mia Hamm, heptathlete Jackie
Joyner-Kersee and basketball players Cheryl Miller, Ann Meyers,
Chamique Holdsclaw and Rebecca Lobo.
</P>
<P>
   May is only the second volleyball player to win the award since
its inception 23 years ago and the first since Deitre Collins of
Hawaii won the honor in 1983. She is also the second area athlete
to win the award, joining UCLA softball player Lisa Fernandez, a
St. Joseph High graduate who was given the award in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   May, who arrived in Reno late Monday afternoon from Colorado
Springs, Colo., where she was practicing with U.S. national team,
could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Long Beach State coach Brian Gimmillaro, who joined May for the
presentation, was thrilled.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a win for the school, for Misty, for the volleyball
program, for the whole city,'' Gimmillaro said. ``What she's done
for our sport and how she's represented our school, she's certainly
deserving of this. She's been the Wayne Gretzky or Magic Johnson of
our sport she's a person who revolutionized the position (of
setter).''
</P>
<P>
   May, widely considered the top high school player in the country
at Newport Harbor High, lived up to even the great expectations she
brought to Long Beach State four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   She quickly demonstrated that just because she was a deft
passer, it didn't preclude her from becoming a force blocking,
spiking or serving roles often left to middle blockers or outside
hitters.
</P>
<P>
   May became the fourth 49er to win national player of the year
honors joining Tara Cross, Antoinette White and Danielle Scott and
led Long Beach State to final four appearances her last two
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   She ended her 49er career with a flourish, setting a record with
20 service aces during the tournament and posting 70 assists, 11
digs, nine kills and four blocks in the title match against Penn
State. She was chosen MVP of the final four as Long Beach State
concluded its season 36-0.
</P>
<P>
   ``We planned it like this, but it doesn't always go the way it's
planned,'' Gimmillaro said of his expectations for May. ``She had a
special personality and a special way that she viewed the game and
played the game. She used to come to our camp and the way she
listened and interpreted the information was very unique. I
believed there wouldn't be any limits on her ability to develop.''
</P>
<P>
   Long Beach State assistant coach Debbie Green, the setter on the
U.S. national team in the 1984 Olympics and long considered the
best this country has produced at the position, worked with May for
four years. She says May never stopped wanting to improve.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of players in the country that when they go into
college have the potential to be the best,'' said Green, a finalist
for the award in 1978 while she played at USC. ``She made it
simple. She's so athletic and understands the game so well and I
didn't have to motivate her.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every day in practice she'd go hard and every day she was
willing to hear input, even up until the final practice at the
final four. She was always making adjustments and never made me
feel like, `I already know this.' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
