<DOCNO> NYT19990615.0016 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-15 02:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5562 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-     06-15 0839
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN </SLUG>
 -HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
DaleRobertson
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
FIRST of all, let's get something straight here. There is no such
thing as minor brain surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Although Larry Dierker's condition isn't believed to be
life-threatening and he was joking Monday about returning to the
dugout in a couple weeks, it's possible he won't be back at all in
1999.
</P>
<P>
   The operation he'll undergo early this morning _ called a
craniotomy _ will take at least three hours and will be very
invasive. I'll spare you the gruesome details, but it's safe to say
you won't see Dierker out in public for a while without his ball
cap on. Good thing he's accustomed to wearing one.
</P>
<P>
   However, the prognosis for his full recovery is excellent. It's
practically guaranteed, barring unanticipated complications. He'll
manage again, assuming he wants to, and we must assume he will.
Dierker doesn't consider baseball to be work. For him, going to the
ballpark happens to be the same thing as stopping to smell the
flowers. He didn't need to learn any lessons in perspective. He was
already an expert on the subject.
</P>
<P>
   How many baseball managers do you know who are aspiring
novelists and songwriters, who are wont to ponder their place in
the grand scheme of things, who appreciate a fine bottle of wine
and who eagerly jump at a friend's invitation to attend a
performance of the Carmina Burana _ without first asking what
position Burana plays?
</P>
<P>
   Also, people with Dierk's makeup tend to heal quickly because of
their mindset. They have fun and live expansively, and they don't
sweat the details, except the very few that really matter.
</P>
<P>
   Honestly, that's why Dierker is such a good manager. And that's
why he leaves the Astros in such good stead, possessing the
glossiest record in the National League despite a procession of
on-field injuries and off-field maladies. He lets his players do
what they do best, with no dissonant, ``me``-driven interference.
And his interim replacement, Matt Galante, seems certain to do
likewise.
</P>
<P>
   Side by side, Dierker and Galante may be Mutt and Jeff, but they
process information in almost exactly the same way. Matty was as
much a right-hand man to Larry as a man can be. The Astros have a
tremendous confidence in Galante and also a deep, longstanding
affection for him. It's a tribute to everybody in the clubhouse _
coaches, players and the stricken skipper himself _ that Dierker
shouldn't be missed at all.
</P>
<P>
   Except, of course, as a person. You can replace the manager. You
can't replace the person.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just keeping Dierk's seat warm,'' says Galante, a guy who
has long wanted, and deserved, to be a manager _ but never under
circumstances such as these. ``Let's get Larry better. Let's add to
the (division) lead he left us.
</P>
<P>
   ``Me, I'm thinking day-to-day only. If it's for a short time,
fine. If it's for a longer time, that's fine, too. All that matters
is that Larry gets well and, while he's getting well, we carry on
for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Galante admits he won't soon forget seeing Dierker collapse onto
the floor of the dugout Sunday, then begin to convulse. Grand mal,
the kind of seizure he suffered, means big and bad. It was both.
</P>
<P>
   One moment Dierker and Galante were rising, almost in unison, to
watch Derek Bell's grand slam clear the fence. Practically the next
moment, Dierker's neurons were misfiring crazily. His arms and legs
were thrashing about while vomit spewed from his mouth, choking
him. Had he been driving a car or crossing a busy street instead of
merely managing a ballclub, he'd probably be dead today.
</P>
<P>
   ``It scared me to death,'' Galante said. ``I've never been so
scared in all my life.''
</P>
<P>
   So, no, taking charge of the Astros won't be any big deal. Matty
knows them. They know him. As the boss, he can't always be their
best buddy, but hopefully they can handle that and accept the
occasional tough decision he must make.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been with these same people for many years,'' Galante
said. ``They're quality players, quality people. You saw that in
how they reacted (Sunday).
</P>
<P>
   ``They're going to keep playing hard. They'll handle the
transition like they've handled everything else that's happened to
us.''
</P>
<P>
   Like having the entire left side of their starting lineup and
the catcher go down _ plus losing two coaches to boot. Yet here
they were Monday night, having to again pick up the pieces against
Atlanta's NL team-of-the-decade Braves, leading the East as per
usual. And who, worse, came to town having been humiliated 22-1 the
previous night in Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're going to want to take it out on us tonight,'' Galante
mused before his debut. ``Bad timing, huh?''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, it was the Astros acting as though they intended to
one-up the Orioles, loading the bases on Odalis Perez before he got
his first out. They would score 10 runs before the evening wrapped,
six more than the Braves.
</P>
<P>
   Galante is 1-0. Now, hopefully, Dierker adds an easy ``W''
today.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
