<HEADER>
A5579 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKL-MERCURY-MONARCHS-     06-15 0793
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKL-MERCURY-MONARCHS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLOWOUT, BUT NO CANDLES  
 LOSS SPOILS MER CURY BIRTHDAY PARTY PLANS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF METCALFE  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - What began as a birthday party ended in a wake Monday
night as the Mercury bombed in its home opener, losing for the
second time in three days to the Sacramento Monarchs, 74-64.
</P>
<P>
   The birthday girl, 35-year-old Jennifer Gillom, produced a
double-double, but her 29 points were 16 more than the rest of the
starting lineup combined as Phoenix drops to 0-2 for the first time
in its three-year existence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to apologize to the fans of Phoenix for that display of
bad basketball,'' said Mercury Coach Cheryl Miller. ``That was
embarrassing. It was humiliating. They took that momentum (from a
96-85 win Saturday), brought it here and pulled out a can of
whoop-ass and got the job done.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one thing that was good was the final buzzer and us
getting off the court.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller, who missed much of training camp because of her
broadcasting obligations, took responsibility for her team's lack
of effort and promised changes before Saturday's game against
winless Cleveland (0-3).
</P>
<P>
   ``That's my team, they're a reflection of me, and I let this
organization down,'' she said. ``I take all the blame for what
happened out there. That's my fault.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played soft. I've been coaching soft.''
</P>
<P>
   Lest anyone forget in the rush to mea culpa, Sacramento (2-1)
had something to do with the wreck. Four players reached
double-figure scoring as the Monarchs refused to crack before a
crowd of 13,228 and ghosts of its 0-8 1997-98 past vs. the Mercury.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-4 Yolanda Griffith was nowhere near the offensive
force that she was on Saturday, scoring 13 instead of 31, but
hauled down 18 of Sacramento's 37 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yolanda's the biggest threat in the league so far,'' said
Bridget Pettis, who had 16 points off the bench and was the
Mercury's only producer aside from Gillom. ``She's a very talented
young lady. She can bring the ball down the court, offensive
rebounding like the men. She makes some tips from 10-15 feet out,
that's something rare.''
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix never led, trailed 35-29 at halftime and was hit by a
17-5 run early in the second half in falling behind, 53-38, with
11:16 remaining. From then on, the Mercury got no closer than nine
(58-49), taking 12 more shots than the Monarchs, but shooting just
37.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The starting perimeter of Michele Timms, Edna Campbell and
Clarissa Davis-Wrightsil went 0 for 14 until Campbell hit a
three-pointer with 7:35 left.
</P>
<P>
   Davis-Wrightsil went scoreless and got just 10 minutes of
playing time as Pettis played 27 minutes. It was Pettis, coming in
at 10-4, who hit a three-pointer and layup on an assist by Gillom
then dove to the floor to tie up Ticha Penicheiro and bring
something of a recognizable look to the 1998 WNBA runner-ups.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still in the jelling process,'' Pettis said. ``We made
some crucial cuts (former starters Umeki Webb and Toni Foster)
before the season started, and everybody was in shock a little bit.
But we've got to work with what we have, and let's make the best
out of it. It's easier said, but a little bit harder doing it.
That's something that's noticeable now.''
</P>
<P>
   Gillom, averaging 26 points, was in something close to shock
afterwards, speaking almost in a whisper to the media.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm serious when I walked off the court, I wanted to hang my
head as low as I could even though people probably thought I had a
good performance,'' Gillom said. ``But it's embarrassing as a team
to let them see what kind of effort we put out there. You give me
100 percent effort, you can keep your head up high. But this is not
acceptable.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to play for 40 minutes every game. I'm going to say it
over and over. This league as tough as it is this year, we're going
to be in trouble if we keep this up.'' &QL; 
Note &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mercury starters Jennifer Gillom, Michele Timms, Edna Campbell
and Clarissa Davis-Wrightsil are among 27 Western Conference
choices on the WNBA All-Star ballot released on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Gillom, the 1998 WNBA most valuable player runner-up, is in
competition with Los Angeles' Lisa Leslie, the early league scoring
leader (24.5 ppg).
</P>
<P>
   ``I just hope everybody votes for me,'' said Gillom, who more
accurately should be listed at forward, her new starting position.
</P>
<P>
   Fans will select the starters in voting through June 30 with
head coaches Van Chancellor (Houston) and Linda Hill-MacDonald
(Cleveland) selecting the six reserves. The inaugural All-Star Game
will be July 14 in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Voting can be done on line at WNBA.com, from June 20-30, at
Sears stores, and in the arena. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
