<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-15 02:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5580 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DBACKS-MARLINS-AZ     06-15 0683
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DBACKS-MARLINS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SICK JOHNSON LEAVES MARLINS FEELING QUEASY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD OBERT  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Marlin was being served at the press lounge and seared
at the plate Monday night at Bank One Ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   Randy Johnson, pitching despite an upset stomach, had the
Florida Marlins looking ill and Tony Womack caught the
Diamondbacks' home run bug in a 2-0 victory before 37,144.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said he took some pain medication for his back on an
empty stomach Sunday night and began to get flu-like symptoms.
</P>
<P>
   He was sick all day Monday, but it didn't keep him from taking
the mound. He gave up only two hits, struck out eight and retired
12 straight, before Manager Buck Showalter lifted him for a
pinch-hitter in the seventh inning after watching his left-hander
vomit in the dugout garbage can.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was ready to go out there in the eighth inning, but I threw
up in front of him,'' Johnson said. ``That changed his mind a
little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson (9-2), in establishing a club record with five straight
victories, pushed the Diamondbacks (38-26) 12 games over .500 for
the first time. They gained a game on the San Francisco Giants in
the National League West. The Giants, three games behind Arizona,
lost to Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told Buck, if I'm going to pitch like this every time I've
got the flu, then come on flu,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   Although Johnson said he lacked energy, he didn't lack intensity
and found himself in a duel with 22-year-old right-hander Ryan
Dempster, who shut down the Diamondbacks' dangerous hitters in
order, before Johnson ripped a single up the middle in the third.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona had 98 home runs coming in, none by Womack, until the
sixth inning, when he made Dempster pay for his only mistake. After
fouling off three straight pitches, Womack lined a shot into the
right-field seats for a 1-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   How did it feel?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how it's supposed to feel,'' he said ``I never
hit them. I leave that up to the big boys.''
</P>
<P>
   Showalter left it up to the bullpen after Johnson's stomach
failed to cooperate.
</P>
<P>
   Like Sunday's 13-inning, 3-1 victory in Anaheim, it came through
again.
</P>
<P>
   Byung-Hyun Kim, cleared of the bandage controversy by the
National League earlier in the day, struck out Kevin Orie and got
Danny Bautista to ground out to second. Newly acquired left-hander
Dan Plesac came in and got left-handed pinch-hitter Cliff Floyd to
fly out to left fielder Luis Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   Plesac started the ninth and retired the first two batters _ on
a tapper back to him and strike out _ before Showalter brought in
Gregg Olson for the final out.
</P>
<P>
   Plesac got a big out Sunday in his first game as a Diamondback.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been a real shot in the arm for me,'' said Plesac,
who struggled with an ERA of 8.00 in Toronto. ``I mean I really
didn't have a very good beginning of the season. The first two
months were rough. I kept persevering and grinding. I knew I was a
better pitcher than what I've been, and I'm sure there were a lot
of people a little taken back by the trade if you look at the
numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I know that I'm a hell of a lot better pitcher than what
I've shown the first seven to eight weeks of the season.''
</P>
<P>
   Showalter, who said he didn't want to ``overexpose'' Plesac,
gave the ball to Olson to pitch to Dave Berg. Olson, riding a
roller-coaster year, was greeted with boos.
</P>
<P>
   Olson gave up a single to Berg and to Bruce Aven, before getting
left-handed Tim Hyers to ground back to him for the final out. It
was Olson's 10th save.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks improved to 21-8 at home, best in the major
leagues.
</P>
<P>
   Sick or not, Johnson is settling in at BOB.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 93 pitches Johnson threw, 75 were strikes. Johnson didn't
walk a batter.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's performance overshadowed that of Dempster, who started
the year in the minor leagues.
</P>
<P>
   Dempster left in the seventh inning, after striking out catcher
Damian Miller, who, like Johnson, had the stomach flu but suffered
through an 0-for-3 night, all via the strikeout.
</P>
</TEXT>
