<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-COYOTES-BICKLEY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMITH GOT HIS MAN, A PUPPET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN BICKLEY  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Now that Bobby Smith has his perfect piece of clay,
what will become of Coyotes hockey?
</P>
<P>
   Is this the prelude to downsizing _ gutting a team into
quick-sale shape? Or a sign that the general manager will need an
extra hotel room this season? One for himself and one for his ego.
</P>
<P>
   You don't have to be downwind to know this one stinks. And if
you're wondering why Smith didn't officially anoint himself as the
next head coach of the Coyotes, well, that's easy. Coaches get
fired.
</P>
<P>
   Can we bring back Jim Schoenfeld, please?
</P>
<P>
   So the manual on ``How Not To Hire A Head Coach'' ends. And it
yields a strange new beginning, the Bobby Francis Era. And now that
you're done trembling with excitement, understand this great goose
chase has become a fiasco. You know it. The players know it. Even
an analyst on ``Hockey Night in'' ``Canada'' knows it. &QL; 
Surplus of drivers &QL; 
Two things have become clear during the past 12 months. Richard
Burke is a meddling owner, and Smith is a meddling general manager.
Burke should be hailed for his passion and Smith his eye for
talent, but there are too many back-seat drivers for one
organization, and word is beginning to spread that Phoenix is
becoming the dark hole of coaches.
</P>
<P>
   I'm a little dizzy here, so let's review: After the Coyotes win
a Game 4 in St. Louis, Burke goes out of his way to compliment
Schoenfeld's coaching ability. After losing Game 7, Smith insists
that Schoenfeld's job paranoia existed only in his mind. Why, to
the contrary, Schoenfeld was about to be reprieved until he talked
himself out of a job.
</P>
<P>
   Until he wouldn't yield power to Bobby Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Schoenfeld was known to bristle when Smith suddenly dropped a
player in the room, a la Brian Noonan. But he balked when Smith's
heavy touch became too much. Good for Schoenfeld. Everyone should
respect a man who so fiercely guards his integrity.
</P>
<P>
   Before you know it, an interview with John Tortorella goes
``extremely'' well. He suddenly emerges with glowing player
testimonials and an unquestioned reputation, a charismatic
straight-shooter unafraid to set the room straight.
</P>
<P>
   Tough to tell which hurt his chances more, the wave of good
publicity or Tortorella's insistence that he was nobody's cabin
boy. Whatever, he is gone, soon to be someone else's prize.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing against Francis, who formerly coached minor league
hockey in Providence and drew rave reviews from youngsters he sent
to the parent club, the Boston Bruins. But he is walking into a
sticky situation and inheriting a dressing room stocked with strong
personalities.
</P>
<P>
   How long until they buy into Francis? How long before they
believe Smith isn't pulling his strings? &QL; 
Smooth transition nixed &QL; 
Tortorella was no Mike Keenan, but at least he offered intrigue. He
had a bit of momentum and the explicit trust of his players. The
transition would've been smooth, if not successful.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a notebook a mile long of things I wanted to do with
this team,'' Tortorella said. ``I felt my personality was a perfect
match for this team.''
</P>
<P>
   If you haven't heard the latest, word is circulating that Smith
has already handpicked two assistants, Ryan Walter and Wayne
Fleming. If true, what kind of self-respecting coach walks into a
situation so short on control?
</P>
<P>
   So, not only must Francis justify a hire straight from left
field, he must first win over a dressing room full of suspicion:
That the new guy is one of them, that all secrets are safe, that
the new coach is not a mouthpiece to the front office.
</P>
<P>
   In this game, no one ever goes to war with a puppet.
</P>
<P>
   For all of Smith's brilliance in talent evaluation, he has
failed miserably as a purveyor of coaches, and maybe that's what
this is all about. Don Hay didn't work, and Schoenfeld wouldn't
conform. A general manager rarely gets three strikes, and this
time, who better to trust than yourself?
</P>
<P>
   So say hello to the next coach of the Coyotes: Bobby Francis
Smith. &QL; 
Dan Bickley can be reached at (602) 444-8253 or at
dan.bickley(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
