<SLUG> BC-COYOTES15-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COYOTES' SEARCH ENDS  
 BRUINS' ASSISTANT TO BE NAMED COACH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - The Coyotes will have a new head coach before they
head to the NHL Draft later this month in Boston. And they won't
have to fly him there to join them.
</P>
<P>
   That's because they have selected Boston Bruins assistant coach
Bobby Francis, who will be introduced on Wednesday as the Coyotes'
third head coach in four seasons, which ``The Arizona Republic''
first reported Monday on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement will be made at 1 p.m. at the Canadian Pacific
Scottsdale Princess resort.
</P>
<P>
   Francis' name hadn't been publicly linked to the job until
Monday morning, but he apparently has had several conversations
with General Manager Bobby Smith in the past few weeks and
impressed Smith so much that he offered him the job during the
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Reached Monday in San Diego, where he is vacationing with his
family, Smith would neither confirm nor deny the hiring.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've gone this far,'' he said, ``let's just wait until
Wednesday when we have the announcement.''
</P>
<P>
   Francis, 40, has spent the past two seasons as an assistant on
Bruins Coach Pat Burns' staff, along with fellow assistant Jacques
Laperriere, who spent 16 seasons as an assistant with the Montreal
Canadiens.
</P>
<P>
   After notifying Coyotes assistant coach John Tortorella Monday
morning that he no longer is in the running to replace the recently
fired Jim Schoenfeld, Smith immediately finalized contract
negotiations with Francis regarding the length and salary of the
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   It is believed Francis will get a three-year deal worth at least
$350,000 a season. Schoenfeld, terminated after two seasons despite
a 74-66-24 record _ including a 90-point season this past year, the
team's second-best finish in its 20-year history _ had one year
remaining on a three-year deal worth $400,000.
</P>
<P>
   Francis declined to be interviewed Monday. A Bruins'
spokesperson said Francis had no comment other than to say he has
spoken with Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Francis' two years with the Bruins are his only experience
behind an NHL bench. Before joining Boston, he spent two seasons as
the head coach of the club's top affiliate in the American Hockey
League, the Providence Bruins, where he compiled a 65-82-13 record.
</P>
<P>
   Providence won the AHL's Calder Cup championship Sunday night,
defeating Rochester in five games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know anything about it,'' Coyotes center Jeremy
Roenick said Monday afternoon. ``You (media) guys know more than I
do, which is kind of sad . . . I don't really know who he is. I
talked to a couple of (Boston players) and they're saying good
things about him, but I can't make a comment about him because I
just don't know. That would be unfair.''
</P>
<P>
   Francis' coaching career began with the Calgary Flames'
organization in 1986-87, first as a player/coach with the Salt Lake
City Golden Eagles of the International Hockey League. The team won
the Turner Cup that season as the IHL champion and successfully
defended its title the following year with Francis as a full-time
assistant.
</P>
<P>
   In 1988-89, he became the Golden Eagles head coach and held the
job for four seasons, which included a 50-win campaign in 1990-91.
When Calgary shifted its affiliation to Saint John in 1993-94,
Francis made the move as well and continued coaching the team until
joining Providence in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   His father is Emile Francis, a former NHL goalie with the
Chicago Blackhawks and New York Rangers, who went on to become the
head coach and general manager of the Rangers from 1964-65 to
1974-75. He also coached the St. Louis Blues for parts of three
seasons and was the Blues' GM from 1976-77 to 1982-83. He served as
GM of the Hartford Whalers from 1983-84 to 1988-89.
</P>
<P>
   Two possible assistant coaches who already have been confirmed
as viable candidates by Smith are New York Islanders assistant
Wayne Fleming, who has previous coaching experience with the
Canadian National team and in Europe, and former NHL player Ryan
Walter, who has spent the past five seasons as an NHL analyst in
Vancouver.
</P>
<P>
   Smith has said he will wait until he hires the head coach before
offering any jobs to assistants.
</P>
<P>
   Attempts to reach Fleming and Islanders General Manager Mike
Milbury have not been successful. Walter, who spent 15 years in the
NHL with Washington, Montreal and Vancouver, said last week he
would be interested in a coaching opportunity in Phoenix. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
