<HEADLINE>
TYSON FACES UNCERTAIN VALLEY FUTURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By NORM FRAUENHEIM  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Mike Tyson returned to the Valley Monday with a future
that includes a busy, disciplined schedule outside of the ring and
an uncertain one within it.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson met with the Maricopa County Probation Department,
according to public information and court liaison officer Gael
Parks, who said he would be subject to most of the same conditions
he had been under in Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   ``The officer assigned to the case met with him,'' Parks said.
``We basically parroted what Maryland's terms are. Our requirements
really don't differ much.''
</P>
<P>
   According to a compact between the 50 states, Arizona will
assume Maryland's jurisdiction of Tyson, who was released from a
Montgomery County, Md., jail on May 26 after serving 3{ months of a
one-year sentence for a misdemeanor assault charge.
</P>
<P>
   His management has yet to announce an opponent or a date for his
next fight. Late August or September have been mentioned.
Speculated opponents include Axel Schulz of Germany and Brian
Nielsen of Denmark. He is still under contract for three fights at
Las Vegas MGM Grand.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are just servicing their (Maryland) client,'' said Parks,
who also said Tyson will have to perform community service and
re-register as a sex offender, because of an earlier conviction for
sexual assault.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson asked Maryland for permission to return to Arizona,
because it is expected he wants to resume training at the former
Madison Square Garden, a downtown Phoenix gym where he worked
before his victory on Jan. 16 over Francois Botha.
</P>
<P>
   He did not show up at the gym on Monday, but he is expected,
according to owner Ricky Ricardo. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
