r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-TURF-SANTA-ANITA-     06-15 0508
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-TURF-SANTA-ANITA-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TURF CHIEF HEADS FOR `MAJORS' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK ARMIJO  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Likening it to a promotion from minor league baseball to the New
York Yankees, Turf Paradise President Lonny Powell on Monday
accepted a position as president and chief executive officer of
renowned Santa Anita Park.
</P>
<P>
   Powell, 39, begins the new job next month.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a chance to move up from one of the greatest farm
clubs (Turf) in the country to the majors,'' Powell said. ``It's
awe-inspiring. Everybody knows about Santa Anita and what it means.
My father (a former jockey) rode there, and I used to go there as
kid.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a dream come true, and it wasn't a dream, quite frankly,
that I thought of constantly. I feel very privileged this
opportunity came my way.''
</P>
<P>
   Powell also was named vice president of Ventures, a newly formed
subsidiary of Magna International Inc., which purchased Santa Anita
in December.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to racetracks, Ventures will be involved in leisure
real-estate development and the potential development of media,
sports and wagering activities in North America and Europe.
</P>
<P>
   It is believed Churchill Downs also was attempting to lure
Powell, who, despite increased gaming competition from nearby
casinos, helped Turf reach a record overall handle of nearly $263
million last season. When Powell first arrived, Turf's yearly
handle was about $100 million.
</P>
<P>
   Churchill Downs owns Hollywood Park, but the contract doesn't
include Turf. Turf is owned by Hollywood Park Inc., a separate
entity from the Hollywood Park racetrack.
</P>
<P>
   A replacement for Powell at Turf is expected to be named by the
end of next week.
</P>
<P>
   Powell said he hadn't decided whether he would recruit any of
his current staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's too early,'' Powell said. ``I'm a fan of good people, and
there's a ton of them at Turf and at Santa Anita.''
</P>
<P>
   Purses during the recently concluded Turf meet averaged about
$70,000 a day. It was about $35,000 five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Before arriving at Turf, Powell previously held similar
positions at several racetracks owned by Hollywood Park. Powell is
a University of Arizona graduate and for four years was director of
the school's racetrack industry program.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'm leaving a place that's in considerably better
shape than it was when I arrived,'' Powell said. ``But I don't
think (Turf) is at the top of the roller coaster ready to slide
down. There's still significant potential, especially if Turf's
signal can get into California on a regular basis.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I really believe we've seen the worst of what the impact
will be from (casino gaming). I think Turf has proved it is a
survivor and can survive in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Powell will get a new challenge at Santa Anita, in Arcadia,
Calif. The racetrack is a regular stopover for the annual Breeders'
Cup, and its average daily purses approach $500,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Santa Anita has the best horses and the best racing in the
country,'' Powell said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
