<HEADLINE>
BOSTON IS HEAL ING, BUT PLAYING IT SAFE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, ARIZ. - Cardinals rookie wide receiver &UR; David Boston won't
be diving over the middle to try to make any shoe-top catches this
week.
</P>
<P>
   The fractured bone in his left shoulder is healing nicely, but
the team isn't going to take any chances during the four days that
remain of rookie camp.
</P>
<P>
   X-rays on the injury on Monday were favorable, but he wasn't
cleared for full participation. Boston, the team's top draft pick,
will do only limited work this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``My shoulder feels great, but they haven't released me to go
full speed,'' said Boston, who suffered the injury in last month's
minicamp. ``I'm right on schedule. (Training camp) is six weeks
from now. I'm going to be in good shape. But even now, I feel
fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Boston felt good enough to run some pass patterns in Monday's
workout.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main thing we want to get out of the next four days is the
mental part, getting our terminology refreshed in his mind,'' Coach
 &UR; Vince
 &UR; Tobin said.
</P>
<P>
   Monday was the first time Boston had been back at the Cardinals'
training facility since suffering the injury when he collided with
cornerback &UR; 
 &UR; Corey Chavous on the final day of minicamp.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the play was over, I hopped up (for the next play),'' he
said. ``But the second or third play later, I felt a twinge. I knew
something wasn't right.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't hold anything against Corey. We both were going full
speed. In those kind of drills, anything can happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Boston, the Ohio State product picked eighth overall, said he
was in pain for the next couple of weeks. Once the pain subsided,
he started jogging.
</P>
<P>
   For the past two weeks, he has felt good enough to participate
in workouts in Boca Raton, Fla., with Minnesota Vikings wide
receivers  &UR; Cris
 &UR; Carter and  &UR; Randy Moss.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are showing me some of the little things they've
learned,'' Boston said.
</P>
<P>
   He learned Monday that his father,  &UR; Byron, will be part of the
NFL officiating crew for the Cardinals' preseason opener at Denver.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a wonderful deal, but I don't expect to get any breaks
from him,'' Boston said. ``He's a straight-up guy and honest
person. That's why he has been so successful as an official.''
</P>
<P>
   Boston's dad, an NFL line judge, has done the past two NFC
championship games.
</P>
<P>
   Contract talks
</P>
<P>
   Negotiations have heated up between the team and several of its
late draft picks.
</P>
<P>
   The agents for sixth-round picks  &UR; Melvin Bradley and &UR; Dennis
McKinley and seventh-rounder &UR; Chris Greisen said they have had
several discussions with Cardinals officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're moving positively forward,'' said agent  &UR; James
Divergilis, who represents McKinley, a fullback from Mississippi
State.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Kyle Rote Jr., the agent for sixth-rounder &UR; Coby Rhinehart, was
unavailable for comment. But Rhinehart said Rote told him the two
sides had begun negotiating.
</P>
<P>
   Each is expected to sign a three-year deal for annual salaries
of $175,000, $250,000 and $325,000. Most of the negotiating is on
the signing bonuses. &QL; 
Briefly
</P>
<P>
   As expected, starting middle linebacker  &UR; Ronald McKinnon signed
his one-year tender offer of $937,000. The only remaining
restricted free agents are strong safety  &UR; Tommy Bennett and tight
end &UR; Johnny McWilliams, who could sign as early as today. Both have
been offered one-year deals worth $429,000.
</P>
</TEXT>
