<HEADLINE>
BATES ALTERS CONTRACT TO HELP CARDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. - Running back Mario Bates has reworked his
contract to try to help the Cardinals solve their salary-cap
problems, team officials confirmed Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Bates, who was scheduled to earn $1.2 million this season in the
second year of a two-year, $1.8 million deal, received a one-year
extension that reduced his salary-cap figure for 1999 by about
$500,000.
</P>
<P>
   He will earn $725,000 this season _ a $150,000 bonus and a
salary of $575,000 _ and is scheduled to make $575,000 next year.
</P>
<P>
   On most NFL contracts, only the signing bonus is guaranteed.
</P>
<P>
   Bates, the Arizona State product who was a second-round draft
pick of the New Orleans Saints in 1994, rushed for six touchdowns
in the 1998 regular season and also had three scores in the NFC
second-round playoff game at Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals, who were about $1.5 million under the $53.7
million salary cap before reworking Bates' deal, are trying to trim
at least $3 million off their payroll so they can sign their 11
draft choices. They have been given a rookie pool of $4.6 million
by the league.
</P>
<P>
   Bates and his agent, Jim Steiner of St. Louis, were unavailable
for comment. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
