<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-COYOTES-TORTORELLA-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TORTORELLA DIDN'T EXPECT TO GET JOB 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - When John Tortorella got the phone call he had been
waiting for Monday morning from Bobby Smith, the news, he said,
didn't take him by surprise.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kind of knew last week they were going to go in a different
direction,'' said Tortorella, an assistant coach with the Coyotes
the past two seasons. ``It's a pretty small league, and you hear
things. I got tidbits here and there and after a while, I felt
pretty strongly I would not be the new head coach here.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith made that official Monday, ruling out Tortorella from
consideration. The task of replacing Jim Schoenfeld behind the
Phoenix bench next season will belong to Bobby Francis, who has
spent the past two seasons as an assistant coach with the Boston
Bruins.
</P>
<P>
   Francis will be introduced Wednesday at a news conference set
for 1 p.m. at the Canadian Pacific Scottsdale Princess resort.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know who's going to be coaching here,'' said
Tortorella, 41, ``just that Bobby (Smith) wants whoever it is to
play a more offensive and up-tempo style. That's fine. I'm just
going to miss the opportunity to coach those guys, because I was
really looking forward to it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are the guys that count, the players. That's what a
coach hangs his hat on. You deal with those guys 24 hours a day for
eight months a year and you care about people. You want to see them
be successful both in life and in hockey. I care about them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, if I'm coaching another team, we're going to come
in here and kick their (expletive).''
</P>
<P>
   Smith would neither confirm nor deny that the job belongs to
Francis, but he said Monday the position came down to Tortorella
and one other finalist.
</P>
<P>
   ``It came down to a gut feeling,'' Smith said from San Diego,
where he was vacationing with his family. ``John would have made an
excellent coach for us. It was a difficult decision, but when I
weighed everything out, I concluded it was just a gut decision and
it was the right decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having said that, if I were to name John Tortorella as our new
head coach on Wednesday, I'd be thrilled with that. I've known John
for two years, and there's no reason why he wouldn't make a good
head coach here.''
</P>
<P>
   Tortorella said he would not consider remaining with the club as
an assistant. Instead, he plans to look elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Two likely possibilities are the New York Rangers and the Tampa
Bay Lightning. Tortorella is good friends with John Muckler, the
Rangers' head coach, and Rick Dudley, who was just hired to take
over the hockey operations of the Lightning. Many in the NHL are
expecting Dudley to make wholesale changes on the coaching staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I was the right guy for this job, but in Bobby's
eyes, I'm not,'' said Tortorella, who spent six years as an
assistant with the Buffalo Sabres and two coaching Rochester, whom
he guided to the American Hockey League championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a whole list of changes I was prepared to make, right
from the conduct in the locker room to their actions on the ice.
It's not going to happen, but I had two great years here, this was
a great place to live, I enjoyed the community, and now it's time
to look elsewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Tortorella said he wasn't sure why Smith chose Francis.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're asking the wrong guy,'' Tortorella said. ``That's
Bobby's call. I thought my two interviews went pretty well, but I
have strong convictions. I don't know any other way to answer
things than from my stomach. If it doesn't fit, it doesn't fit.
Obviously, it didn't with Bob.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
