<SLUG> BC-BBN-DBACKS-GOMEZ-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NDERSON SHOULD EXPLOIT GRACE PERIOD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - It's not like tonight will make or break Brian
Anderson's career as a Diamondbacks starter.
</P>
<P>
   But make no mistake, it would definitely behoove the likable
Anderson if he turned in a positive effort against the Florida
Marlins at Bank One Ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks' brass is searching for something to make them
believe Anderson is capable of remaining in the rotation, where he
was placed last month to take the spot of injured pitcher Todd
Stottlemyre.
</P>
<P>
   Now that he's in does not mean Anderson will remain in the
rotation. The stakes this season have been raised to a far-higher
level than at any time in the franchise's short history. Leaving
someone in the rotation who is not shouldering his share of the
responsibility will not go on forever.
</P>
<P>
   One look at struggling Gregg Olson's banishment as the primary
closer (no matter that he has recorded the past two saves) is all
the evidence anyone needs to know this will not be an open tryout.
Especially not with a playoff spot hanging in the balance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll do what's best for the club,'' Manager Buck Showalter
said. ``Right now, we think Brian's that guy.''
</P>
<P>
   The key point in that statement being, ``Right now.'' Showalter
is loyal to his players. Sometimes to a fault. But it's that fault
that makes most of those he comes in contact with want to return.
</P>
<P>
   But Showalter's first priority is to field a winner. It's also
his second and third priorities. With one-third of the season gone,
he has done a remarkable job and, it can be argued at this stage,
is probably the leading candidate for National League Manager of
the Year.
</P>
<P>
   In order to keep his spot in the rotation, Anderson must reverse
what he's done in three of his four starts since returning from the
minors.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers so far have been ugly. Almost horrendous. His 9.58
ERA as a reliever before being inserted can be excused to a degree,
mostly because he's never spent any serious amount of time
relieving.
</P>
<P>
   But his 9.16 ERA as a starter is startling and probably won't be
tolerated for long. Nor should it. Anderson has failed to make it
through five innings in three of his four starts. With runners on
base, opponents are batting .426 against him.
</P>
<P>
   Right-handed hitters, who have the percentages against a lefty,
are batting an unsightly .337 against Anderson. Lefties are hitting
a whopping .463. Overall, they're hitting .369 off Anderson, which,
if he had enough innings to qualify, would be the highest mark in
the league by 37 points.
</P>
<P>
   What may be the most disturbing statistic working against
Anderson is his home run-to-walk ratio of 8-5. It's revealing in
that it underscores how Anderson is dangerously close to the strike
zone too often.
</P>
<P>
   Walking a batter here or there is not necessarily the worst
thing a pitcher can do. Anderson must be able to be counted on and
that simply has not been the case so far.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to throw out everything he did for us last
year,'' Showalter said. ``Hopefully he'll get back into the swing
and pitch like he's capable of doing.''
</P>
<P>
   But what if Anderson's downward spiral continues, you may ask.
What options do the Diamondbacks really have at this point? Well,
Nelson Figueroa's numbers at Triple-A Tucson (7-2, 4.00 ERA and 67
strikeouts in 74 innings) could very well merit a big-league shot.
</P>
<P>
   Figueroa is currently on the disabled list because of a mild
case of tendinitis in his shoulder but it's nothing that seriously
concerns the club and he is expected to return to action within a
week.
</P>
<P>
   The other option, a more viable one the club is seriously
pondering, is to start Byung-Hyun Kim. Yes, it's true.
</P>
<P>
   Kim was very successful as a starter for the Triple-A
Sidewinders (going 2-0 with a 2.60 ERA in three starts). In
addition, he made his name as a starter in his native South Korea,
where it can be argued he was the more formidable starter on the
national team over a guy named Chan Ho Park.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, Showalter has some options. As is always the case
with any player, it's now up to Anderson to keep his manager from
making a move. &QL; 
Pedro Gomez can be reached at (602) 444-2364 or at
pedro.gomez(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
