<HEADLINE>
NO SUSPENSION OR FINE FOR KIM OVER BAN DAGE INCIDENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD OBERT  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - The Diamondbacks were notified on Monday by the
National League that pitcher &UR; Byung-Hyun Kim will not be suspended
or fined over the heat-balm bandage that came out of his sleeve
during a pitch against the Chicago Cubs last Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Manager &UR; Buck Showalter could crack a smile over the
incident that turned into bandage-gate since Kim's ejection.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, it's a little funnier,'' Showalter said.
</P>
<P>
   The 20-year-old Kim said he wore the bandage containing a heat
balm to loosen a tight shoulder and had forgotten he had it on
before entering the game in the eighth inning.
</P>
<P>
   After Cubs first baseman  &UR; Mark Grace handed the bandage to the
umpire between innings and pointed out the balm, Kim was ejected
for having a foreign substance on his body.
</P>
<P>
   The bandage, videotape and umpires' report were sent to NL
President &UR; 
 &UR; Leonard Coleman's office for review.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he reviewed everything, he realized it was inadvertent
and there was no intent to gain an advantage,'' General Manager &UR; Joe
Garagiola Jr. said. &QL; 
Another honor &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Another week, another Diamondback honored. It was third baseman
 &UR; Matt
 &UR; Williams' turn. Williams was named NL Player of the Week for the
second time this season, after collecting 24 total bases and 13
hits.
</P>
<P>
   Pitcher &UR; Randy Johnson and center fielder  &UR; Steve Finley garnered
the award the previous two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just everybody is playing good,'' Williams said. ``You
have somebody different (picking us up) every week.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams batted .481 (13 for 27) on the week with two homers,
six RBIs, eight runs, three doubles and a triple. Lost in the
offensive numbers, Showalter said, is Williams' play at third.
</P>
<P>
   ``He seems to make a play every game that a lot of third basemen
don't make,'' Showalter said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
