<SLUG> BC-SCHWAB-ONLINEFORUM-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHWAB TO OPEN ONLINE STOCK FORUM  &HT;     BY SAM ZUCKERMAN
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
In a bid to avoid the Wild West atmosphere of most online
stock-discussion forums, Charles Schwab will launch a tightly
controlled investment message system for its customers during the
next few months.
<P>
   Internet investment forums are fraught with misinformation,
disinformation and outright fraud perpetrated by people seeking to
manipulate stock prices, regulators have warned.
</P>
<P>
   To avoid those pitfalls, the nation's largest online broker
plans to take ``baby steps'' in building the investment discussion
sections on its Web site, said Alexandra Roddy, the Schwab vice
president supervising the program.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll be piloting a very small number of message boards,''
Roddy said. The test program will start sometime between July and
September, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Schwab is following in the footsteps of Palo Alto's E-Trade, the
No. 2 Internet broker, which has operated online discussion boards
for nine months. E-Trade now has hundreds of boards on general
investment themes and individual stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Although they acknowledge the risks, Schwab officials say
letting customers communicate with one another about investments is
a vital part of their strategy to build an online ``community.''
</P>
<P>
   Making customers feel they are part of a larger group is key to
cementing their loyalty to Schwab, which is in a cutthroat industry
in which the basic commodity _ the online stock trade _ can be
bought for as little as one-sixth of Schwab's standard $29.95
commission.
</P>
<P>
   One way to instill a sense of community is to offer online
investment discussion boards, such as those sponsored by Yahoo and
Motley Fool. Such boards, which allow Web surfers to post messages
about investment ideas or specific stocks, have become popular
tools for investors looking for ideas.
</P>
<P>
   But because participants can easily hide their identities,
message boards have become the vehicle of choice for spreading
false stories aimed at moving stock prices.
</P>
<P>
   In one notorious case in April, someone posted a phony news
report on sites operated by Lycos and Yahoo that telephone
equipment-maker PairGain Technologies was about to be acquired by
an Israeli company. PairGain shares rocketed up more than 30
percent before the hoax was exposed.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of the Securities and Exchange Commission publicly
have sounded the alarm about the hazards of stock message boards
and have urged online brokerages to keep tight reins on such
discussions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We respect the concerns of regulators,'' Roddy said. ``This is
pretty tricky turf.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, letting tipsters and rumor mongers onto message
boards would run counter to the trustworthy image Schwab seeks to
project, Roddy said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The very problematic things that have occurred on other boards
don't fit with who we are,'' Roddy said.
</P>
<P>
   The company still hasn't decided whether pilot message boards
will cover specific stocks in addition to general investment
issues, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Roddy said Schwab is working on a formula to preserve privacy
while not allowing participants to use their anonymity to
manipulate stocks, Roddy said. Schwab will police its message
boards heavily to remove manipulative, obscene and insulting
messages.
</P>
<P>
   E-Trade uses an outside company to inspect its boards and take
off offensive or manipulative messages, said Jeff Tidwell, who
manages the firm's community-building programs.
</P>
<P>
   If Schwab's message board program is successful, the company
will add chat rooms in which customers can have real-time
discussions with each other, Roddy said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-15-99 0307EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
