<DOCNO> NYT19990615.0041 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-15 03:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5597 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AREACODE-VOTE-SFCHRON     06-15 0978
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AREACODE-VOTE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUC MAY DERAIL LOS ANGELES AREA CODE OVERLAY  &HT;     BY DEBORAH SOLOMON
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
State regulators may consider halting California's first area code
overlay, which took effect just two months ago in West Los Angeles.
<P>
   Faced with mounting complaints from customers, pressure from
legislators and technical glitches, the state Public Utilities
Commission plans to vote on July 8 whether to temporarily suspend
the area code overlay so that it can debate the merits of 11-digit
dialing.
</P>
<P>
   The overlay _ designed to address a shortage of phone numbers in
the region _ went into effect in the 310 region on April 17,
forcing all residents in that area to dial 1 plus the area code and
phone number for every call. After July 17, new phone customers in
the 310 region will get 424 as their area code.
</P>
<P>
   However, if the PUC temporarily suspends implementation, phone
companies could not give out any numbers with a 424 area code.
Instead, new phone customers would be assigned 310 numbers. State
regulators would use the suspension time to decide whether to ditch
or keep the overlay. Eleven-digit dialing would not be affected
while the PUC considers its options. &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The decision is important to the Bay Area, which is slated to
get get overlays in the 408, 415, 510 and 650 regions during the
next two years. If the 310 overlay is scrapped, it could lead to a
reversal of some Bay Area overlays because more people here came to
public meetings to object to an overlay than in the 310 region,
industry watchers said.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Residents of 310) came closer to favoring (an overlay) than
any other population in the state,'' said Natalie Billingsley, a
telecommunications expert with the PUC. But when the overlay went
into effect, ``the people in 310 hit the roof. ... I can't imagine
408 will be any calmer.'' Residents in 408 will be the first in the
Bay Area to get an overlay, starting in October.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the PUC decides temporarily to suspend implementation of
the 424 area code, that does not mean the West Los Angeles overlay
will be scrapped. The suspension merely would give state regulators
time to consider whether the overlay was the right policy for 310.
</P>
<P>
   The 310 overlay has not gone smoothly. Customers had trouble
getting through to some numbers with 11-digit dialing, some alarm
systems don't work with the overlay, and people have been confused
by the change.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, state Assemblyman Wally Knox, D-Los Angeles, and
U.S. Representative Henry Waxman, D-Los Angeles, filed a petition
asking California regulators to halt the overlay in 310, saying
that it was hurting consumers and that phone companies had not
shown it was necessary.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of AREACODE () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  Although the PUC took public comment into consideration before
voting for the overlay, Knox argues that not enough people gave
their opinions at the public hearings held before state regulators.
</P>
<P>
   He and Waxman want the overlay halted indefinitely until phone
companies prove they actually need area code relief.
</P>
<P>
   Knox contends that there is no area code crunch and that there
are more than 145 million telephone numbers in the state that have
been assigned to phone companies but are not being used.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know now that there's no need to impose additional area
codes on California,'' Knox said. ``The big lie was always that the
consumers were at fault because they carried cell phones and
pagers, which created a demand for new numbers that could only be
sated by the creation of new area codes. That's not the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Knox said, phone companies have been hoarding phone
numbers, artificially draining the supply of available digits.
</P>
<P>
   Knox has a bill pending in the Assembly that would force phone
companies to disclose how many phone numbers they have and how many
are in use before consumers are inconvenienced with an overlay. His
bill is scheduled to be heard by the Senate Energy, Utilities and
Communications Committee on June 22.
</P>
<P>
   Once the state knows how many phone numbers actually are in use,
the PUC could force phone companies to return any unused numbers so
they could be given to other phone companies. Until phone companies
supply that data, Knox said, the state should refuse to allow an
overlay.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, phone numbers are assigned in blocks of 10,000,
regardless of how many customers a company has. So even if a phone
company only has 300 customers, it still must request 10,000
numbers. With more than 150 phone companies operating in California
and requesting new phone numbers, the supply of available numbers
in each area code has quickly dwindled.
</P>
<P>
   Knox's bill would require that numbers be assigned in blocks of
1,000 instead of 10,000.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Communications Commission recently opened a
proceeding to look into how numbers are assigned and could issue
new rules within the next year.
</P>
<P>
   John Britton, a spokesman for Pacific Bell, said that though
people might not like overlays, West Los Angeles is in need of area
code relief.
</P>
<P>
   Britton said Pac Bell, which supported the overlay along with
other phone companies, is using about 86 percent of the numbers
it's assigned in the state.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 2 of AREACODE () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  ``Just under 32 million numbers are assigned to Pac Bell, and
just over 27 million are in use,'' Britton said. ``What Pac Bell
supports and what's going to ultimately benefit customers most is a
system where all competitors can get phone numbers to compete
effectively.''
</P>
<P>
   If the overlay is overturned, it would be only the second time
11-digit dialing has been halted.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, Texas regulators stopped an overlay in Houston several
months after it began because they felt it was too disruptive. The
state then implemented a geographic area code split, but six months
later, it reimplemented the overlay.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-15-99 0312EDT &QL; 
