<SLUG> BC-FINBUDGET-FINBUDGET </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
<TEXT>
<P>
   These are the stories The San Francisco Chronicle Business
section plans to move for Monday, June 14, on the New York Times
wire. For questions, please call the business desk at 415-536-5172.
For business stories running in main news, call the news desk at
415-777-7074.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
FOR MAIN NEWS
</P>
<P>
   PRISONPHONES _ Jennine Grigsby was evicted from her Oakland
apartment, her car was repossessed and she was forced to move in
with her mother after she could no longer make her rent or car
payments. Grigsby had not lost a job or fallen ill. Instead, the
single mother had amassed $400 monthly phone bills by accepting
collect calls from the father of her two children _ an inmate at
San Quentin State Prison. Like many people who have loved ones
behind bars, Grigsby was forced to pay just about the highest phone
rates in the market. That is because prisoners can make collect
calls only from pay phones run by the company that has won the
exclusive contract to offer phone service at their prison.
California, which awards the contracts, collects a big commission _
as much as 44 cents per dollar _ on prison pay-phone charges. By
Rebecca Smith.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
FOR BUSINESS
</P>
<P>
   BONDS _ (Louis) The specter of inflation has revived interest in
inflation-adjusted Treasury bonds. CENTERPIECE: illustration /chart
</P>
<P>
   MONEYBAG _ Question-and-answer column on money matters. By
Arthur Louis.
</P>
<P>
   SCHWAB _ Charles Schwab will launch investment message boards
for its online customers in the next few months, using special
techniques to keep out the kinds of market manipulators who have
plagued systems like that of Yahoo. By Sam Zuckerman.
</P>
<P>
   EBAY _ (Swartz) Ebay still experiencing problems. Meanwhile, its
stock is down $14 today and the company is saying the computer
glitches have caused it to cut it revenue estimates for the second
quarter by $3 million to $5 million. By Jon Swartz.
</P>
<P>
   GREENSPAN _ Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan Monday
cautioned that recent increases in productivity _ a principal
factor in holding down inflation _ are not likely to continue
forever. Private economists viewed Greenspan's remarks as hinting
at future Fed interest rate increases. By Carolyn Lockhead.
</P>
<P>
   VIRUS _ Antivirus experts warned Monday that the Explorer.Zip
virus is slightly more dangerous than first thought. Researchers
discovered over the weekend that the program can spread itself
through files shared on a company's network, meaning that one
infected desktop missed by antivirus updates can spread Explorer.
Computer security experts also say the spate of damage-causing
viruses in the last three months points to a need to change how
viruses are detected, including having Internet service providers
doing some of the screening. By Benny Evangelista.
</P>
<P>
   AREACODE _ State regulators will consider whether to halt the
new 424 area code that's supposed to go into effect on July 17 in
the current 310 region. The West Los Angeles area was the first to
get an overlay area code and has since had numerous problems. A
state Assemblyman asked the California Public Utilities Commission
to halt the overlay and abandon 424. Regulators said they will
first consider ``temporarily suspending'' the implementation of 424
and will then consider getting rid of the overlay. The PUC plans to
rule on July 8. By Deborah Solomon.
</P>
<P>
   NETFILES _ In Silicon Valley, where the buzz over ``dot com''
startups has reached a cacophony, venture capitalists are swarming
over ITIXS, Round-One and Tellme. Who? They're mysterious Internet
startups run by twentysomethings with pedigrees from Microsoft,
America Online, Yahoo, AtHome, Apple Computer, Netscape
Communications and Wired Ventures. Column by Jon Swartz.
</P>
<P>
   BIOSCOPE _ Everyone in the industry knows the joke about
BioBucks _ except perhaps the small investors who own biotech
stocks. BioBucks is the term used to describe the inflated value of
partnership deals that small biotech firms sign with pharmaceutical
companies. Such deals are the only way most small biotech firms can
raise money, now that institutional investors and venture
capitalists have backed away from biomedical stocks. Column by Tom
Abate.
</P>
<P>
   CAMERAS _ A roundup of digital cameras. By Benny Evangelisa.
</P>
</TEXT>
