<SLUG> BC-GREENSPAN-ECONOMY-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 GREENSPAN SINGS HIGH-TECH'S PRAISES
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By CAROLYN LOCHHEAD &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; C.1999 SAN FRANCISCO CHRONICLE &QC;  &LR; 
WASHINGTON _ Congressional Republicans kicked off a three-day paean
to Silicon Valley on Monday with Federal Reserve Chairman Alan
Greenspan testifying that ``something special has happened to the
U.S. economy'' _ a high-tech revolution that has fueled an
unprecedented economic boom.
</P>
<P>
   Technology has vastly improved the economy's efficiency,
Greenspan said, lifting productivity and living standards while
keeping inflation at bay.
</P>
<P>
   But Greenspan sounded a characteristically cautious note in
warning that, while the productivity will continue to increase,
some sort of slowdown is inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rate of growth of productivity cannot increase
indefinitely,'' Greenspan told Congress' Joint Economic Committee.
``While there appears to be considerable expectation in the
business community, and possibly Wall Street, that the productivity
acceleration has not yet peaked, experience advises caution.''
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan was the lead speaker in a star-studded ``National
Summit on High Technology,'' the three-day parade of some two dozen
high-tech chief executives sponsored by the committee.
</P>
<P>
   The committee offered a raft of statistics to demonstrate
technology's increasingly prominent role in the economy, including
the fact that San Francisco is the ``most-wired U.S. city,'' with
72 percent of adults now online, followed by Miami, Houston,
Seattle/Tacoma and Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Intel Chief Executive Officer Craig Barrett, appearing by remote
video, predicted that within six years, the Internet will boast 1
billion connected computers. Barrett said Intel took its first
order over the Internet last July and now does half its business,
about $15 billion this year, over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan said the economy's nearly two-decade run is rooted in
better and faster information flows to businesses and consumers
alike.
</P>
<P>
   Everything from supermarket bar codes to computer-aided design
to online stock trading has eliminated layers of costly
intermediaries and inventoris, Greenspan noted.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the economy becomes even more efficient as
technology improves. That means the same number of workers using
the same value of equipment can produce more and higher quality
goods at lower cost, allowing living standards to rise
dramatically.
</P>
<P>
   Productivity has increased at an annual rate of 2 percent for
the past three years, a period that dovetails with the emergence of
the Internet as an economic force, double the rate of the 1970s and
1980s.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we did not have the dramatic changes in productivity that
we have seen, it is extremely doubtful that the economy would be
behaving anywhere near as well as it has in recent years,''
Greenspan said. Rising productivity, he said, has been as ``a
crucial factor in the remarkable economic performance of this
business expansion.''
</P>
<P>
   IBM chief executive Louis Gerstner testified as well, in person,
and compared the information technology revolution to the invention
of the printing press in the Middle Ages or the automobile at the
turn of this century.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are witnessing nothing less than the rise of the digital
economy and a new global medium that will be the single most
important driver of business, economic and social change in the
coming century,'' Gerstner said.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet will even challenge the very idea of the
nation-state, he predicted. ``A world connected by global networks
has more fluid borders,'' he said. ``It will put pressure on basic
organizing mechanisms like the nation state, where borders were
determined by rivers or mountain ranges or languages or where the
last war was fought. The Internet is borderless.''
</P>
<P>
   Gerstner warned that government regulations that applied to old
technologies like telephones are ill-suited to the Internet. ``It's
a grave error to think the Internet and e-business will develop
under the kind of regulation we could apply, say, to the phone
system back in the dates when coal and steel were determinants of a
nations' greatness,'' Gerstner said.
</P>
<P>
   The executives urged Congress to aid their industry by doing
such things as funding basic scientific research and easing export
controls on computers and encryption technology. They also urged
making the research and development tax credit permanent as part of
their push for a light regulatory hand.
</P>
</TEXT>
