<SLUG> BC-JAVA-SUN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 PROGRAMMERS GATHER TO TALK OVER JAVA  &HT;     By HENRY NORR 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
The largest-ever assembly of software developers begins  &LR; Tuesday
 &LR; in San Francisco as more than 20,000 users of Sun Microsystems'
Java programming language gather at the Moscone Convention Center.
<P>
   They are coming for the annual JavaOne conference, which runs
through Thursday. The programmers will hear Sun announce new
initiatives to bring Java to handheld computers and to expand the
language's growing role on corporate networks and Web servers.
</P>
<P>
   Java is designed to create software that can run on many types
of computing hardware. Sun will bolster that claim Tuesday by
announcing a new version of the technology that is small enough to
run on miniature devices such as handheld organizers and ``smart''
cell phones.
</P>
<P>
   Among the companies endorsing Sun's streamlined ``Java 2 Micro
Edition'' will be 3Com, which will integrate it into the Palm
series of pocket organizers. 3Com will offer the Java software free
for Palm developers beginning Tuesday. It eventually will become a
standard part of all future Palm devices.
</P>
<P>
   That move will allow developers to use Java to create programs
for the popular Palm line, which dominates the market for handheld
computing devices. To encourage developers to seize the
opportunity, Sun and 3Com plan to sell up to 10,000 PalmV
organizers to JavaOne attendees at less than half price.
</P>
<P>
   The deal could mean a wider selection of commercial and
shareware software for the more than 3 million users of the Palm
devices. Sun officials said, however, that they have tested the
Java software only on the Palm III and later models, not on the
original Palm Pilot products.
</P>
<P>
   Motorola also will announce plans to roll the new version of
Java into its two-way pagers, and NTT Dokomo, Japan's largest
provider of cell-phone service, will add support for it in cell
phones. Eventually, Sun said, the Java Micro Edition will also go
into new ``information appliances'' such as set-top boxes and
Web-enabled telephones, as well as into automobiles.
</P>
<P>
   The Micro Edition can run on as little as 100 kilobytes of
memory, far less than previous versions required, Sun said. It does
not support all Java features, just a subset required when users
are ``untethered'' from the Internet or a corporate network. When
they connect to a network _ via modem, wireless link or local-area
network _ new companion software Sun will supply for its network
server computers will give the handheld device additional
capabilities.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the portion of the Micro Edition loaded on handheld
devices does not include Java's ``byte-code verifier,'' software
that scans Java program code to make sure it is not about to do
something malicious to the user's system.
</P>
<P>
   That feature could be left out because it is of no use as long
as the device is untethered, according to Alan Baratz, president of
Sun's Software Products and Platforms division. Once the user
reconnects to the network and therefore is again at risk from rogue
software, the verifier would be run from the server computer.
</P>
<P>
   Sun will announce another new Java package, called the
Enterprise Edition, designed for developers writing programs to run
on corporate networks. By next year, according to Forrester
Research data cited by Sun, 72 percent of Fortune 1000 companies
are expected to have Java programs running on their servers.
</P>
<P>
   The Enterprise Edition will be supported by a ``who's-who in
server software,'' including Hewlett-Packard, IBM and Oracle,
according to Jon Kannegaard, vice president and general manager of
Sun's Java Platform group. In addition, Sun will announce that it
has licensed Java technology to the Apache Group, the developer
cooperative responsible for Apache, a free software product that
runs more than 50 percent of all Web servers.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Java has not lived up to some of its early hype, it
is increasingly popular among software developers, especially those
writing programs for big corporations.
</P>
<P>
   More than 1 million programmers have now signed up with Sun's
Developer Connection program, the company said. Java has enjoyed
strong support in most of the software industry, but Microsoft, the
industry powerhouse, has offered only lukewarm support. Microsoft
licensed Java from Sun, but the two companies are locked in a legal
battle over Sun's charges that Microsoft violated the terms of its
license by adding Windows-specific features to its version of the
language.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
