<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIRUS-COMPUTER-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 COMPUTER WORM TAKES A MORE DEADLY TURN  &HT;     By BENNY EVANGELISTA 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
A virulent computer program that wiped out files on tens of
thousands of computers worldwide since last week is more dangerous
than first thought, security experts warned Monday.
<P>
   The malicious software _ the third such plague to strike
Internet users in the past four months _ can continually spread
itself within a company's computer network, experts said.
</P>
<P>
   The software deletes information in computer documents created
with Microsoft applications, such as Word, Excel and Power Point.
When discovered last week, experts thought it was spread only
through an attachment sent by e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   However, researchers at the Carnegie Mellon Computer Emergency
Response Team this weekend found that once activated, the software
can spread itself to other Microsoft Windows 95, Windows 98 and
Windows NT documents that are shared on a network.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  For example, if a company is using the Windows ``share''
function to allow an Excel spreadsheet to be used by various
employees, the software _ called Worm.Explore.Zip _ can copy itself
to that document and then spread itself to other desktops on the
same network.
</P>
<P>
   That makes the software more insidious and harder to stamp out
because one unchecked machine could spread it even if desktops in
the rest of the network were inoculated by antivirus software.
</P>
<P>
   The software also can copy itself when a user logs onto another
machine, said Shawn Hernan, a CERT team leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``An infected machine will continue to attempt to reinfect other
machines on the network,'' Hernan said. ``Attempts to clean up
machines one at a time may be futile because other machines may be
reinfected.''
</P>
<P>
   The worm doesn't delete files, but tells the computer system
that the files have no data, said Dan Schrader, a vice president
for antivirus software-maker Trend Micro Inc. in Cupertino.
</P>
<P>
   Antivirus software firms said their help lines had a steady
stream of calls Monday from people whose computers were infected.
</P>
<P>
   The exact number of computers hit was unclear, but the program
reportedly has struck tens of thousands of computers in more than a
dozen countries.
</P>
<P>
   Wes Wasson, director of security products for Network Associates
Inc., said the Santa Clara antivirus-maker saw a slight decrease in
calls from corporate customers seeking help Monday though the
volume of calls still was twice what it was on a normal Monday. And
Network Associates tracked about 10 million downloads of its
software on Friday and Saturday alone.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of VIRUS15 () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  New reports of infections were coming from Eastern European
countries, such as Romania and the Czech Republic, Wasson said.
</P>
<P>
   Worm.Explore.Zip first was detected in Israel and spread quickly
on Thursday and Friday, striking at major U.S. corporations such as
AT&AMP;T, Boeing, General Electric and Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   The program is attached to an e-mail that looks like a reply to
a previous message. The e-mail invites the recipient to ``look at
the attached zipped docs.''
</P>
<P>
   It is the third serious malady to hit the computer world in four
months. The Melissa virus in March was the most widespread but
caused little damage other than clogging corporate e-mail servers.
</P>
<P>
   The ``CIH'' or Chernobyl virus in April was more contained but
still disabled hundreds of thousands of computers around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Schrader said viruses and other types of malicious software are
becoming more sophisticated, moving so fast that even
antivirus-makers are having trouble keeping up.
</P>
<P>
   He said that in the near future, the virus protection
``battlefield'' is going to have to shift past the individual
desktops to the Internet as a whole. He called on major Internet
service providers to start screening e-mails sent and received by
their users for viruses _ just as the airline industry screens
baggage for bombs.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Hoffman, director of the Internet Mail Consortium, a trade
association representing 30 service providers like America Online
and the Microsoft Network, agreed that Internet virus screening
would be good.
</P>
<P>
   However, he noted that antivirus software-makers have not come
up with a product that is cost-effective and doesn't slow down an
Internet provider handling millions of pieces of e-mail a day.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unreasonable for anyone to say you should do this unless
it is clear that it is viable,'' said Hoffman, whose own computer
was infected by Worm.Explore.Zip even though he checked it with two
different antivirus programs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
