<SLUG> BC-EBAY-STOCK-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 OUTAGE HAS EBAY STOCK IN THE DARK  &HT;     By JON SWARTZ 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
Shares of eBay short-circuited Monday after the online auction site
continued to malfunction over the weekend, following a nearly
22-hour outage on Friday.
<P>
   The San Jose company's stock plunged $29.88, or 18 percent, to
$136.74. The holdings of eBay founder Pierre Omidyar, the company's
largest shareholder, plummeted $1 billion, to $5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   EBay's technical travails and nosedive on Wall Street prompted
financial analysts to ponder whether many of eBay's 3.8 million
customers will become fed up with the frequent disruptions and bolt
to competing auction services from Amazon.com and Yahoo.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no question people will leave, and there is a
longer-term risk that eBay will be considered an unreliable
service,'' said analyst Derek Brown, of Volpe Brown Whelan &AMP; Co.
LLC in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Users of eBay encountered sluggish service and an inoperable
search engine on Saturday and Sunday _ after the service was
offline most of Friday. Customers also complained of missing
auction results and fewer listings throughout the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``We limited functions while bringing the system back up,'' eBay
spokesman Kevin Pursglove said, noting that 1.8 million items were
listed the past few days versus 2.2 million last week. He expects
eBay to reach 2.3 million items in seven to 10 days.
</P>
<P>
   A team of 55 engineers worked all weekend trying to avoid a
repeat of the embarrassing technical glitch that plunged eBay into
darkness from 7:50 p.m. Thursday until 5:30 p.m. on Friday. EBay
lost an estimated $3 million to $5 million because of the outage.
</P>
<P>
   EBay blamed the daylong blackout on a corrupted database caused
by faulty software from Sun Microsystems.
</P>
<P>
   Sun officials agreed _ to a point.
</P>
<P>
   ``Software is a complex environment where products from several
vendors have to interact,'' said Alan Baratz, president of Sun's
software products and platforms division. ``We're doing a
postmortem to determine exactly what happened, why it happened and
to make sure it never happens again.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do know that our hardware and software are products that
thousands of customers depend on,'' Baratz said.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of EBAY15 () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  EBay's network problems could extend beyond balky Sun software,
industry experts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it were just one piece of software, then other companies
would be reporting similar problems,'' said Frode Odegard, chief
executive of Odegard Labs Inc., a software research firm in San
Diego. ``A large number of Internet service providers, e-commerce
sites and online trading companies use Sun hardware and software
without reports of failure.''
</P>
<P>
   The frequent breakdowns _ eBay has suffered at least five since
early May _ are likely to tax the patience of millions of consumers
who routinely buy and sell everything from sports memorabilia to
``Star Wars'' action figures. With 80 percent of the market, eBay
is the world's biggest digital auctioneer.
</P>
<P>
   EBay officials moved quickly to remain in its customers' good
graces. In a conciliatory online message, Omidyar and eBay chief
executive Meg Whitman vowed to refund all fees for auctions held
Thursday and Friday, as well as any future outage longer than two
hours; extend by 48 hours the bidding on items affected by the
blackout; and offer free auction listings next month to everyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``EBay has done a good job of acting quickly to appease the
public,'' Brown said. ``Their immediate actions strongly suggest
they apologize and accept the blame.''
</P>
<P>
   Chronicle staff writer Henry Norr contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
COL. 2 of EBAY15 () &QL;
</P>
<P>
   END OF STORY  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
