<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BONDS-SHELTER-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 INDEXED TREASURY BONDS A HAVEN FROM INFLATION  &HT;     By ARTHUR M. LOUIS 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
Now that Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan is warning about a
possible surge in inflation, cautious investors might want to
consider a largely neglected financial vehicle _ inflation-indexed
U.S. Treasury bonds.
<P>
   These bonds were first issued in January 1997, but they haven't
been nearly as popular as standard Treasuries. They look less
attractive on the surface, because they offer a relatively low
interest payment _ currently about 3.9 percent per year for 10-year
bonds, compared with about 6 percent for standard Treasuries.
</P>
<P>
   However, inflation-indexed bonds will produce more lucrative
returns than other Treasuries if inflation stays significantly
above 2 percent for a prolonged period.
</P>
<P>
   That's because the redemption value of the indexed bonds _ the
amount you receive from the U.S. Treasury when the bonds mature _
is adjusted upward semiannually at the rate of inflation, as
measured by the Consumer Price Index.
</P>
<P>
   Here's how it works:
</P>
<P>
   _ If you buy an indexed bond with a $10,000 redemption value,
and six months later the CPI has increased by, say, 1.5 percent,
the redemption value of the bond automatically rises to $10,150.
The inflation adjustments are compounded semiannually each year
until the bond matures.
</P>
<P>
   _ The size of the interest payment also rises with inflation. If
the initial interest rate on a $10,000 bond is 3.9 percent
annually, you would start out with interest payments totaling $195
semiannually. So your total income from the bond after six months
would be $345 (interest plus inflation adjustment).
</P>
<P>
   Then, with the redemption value of the bond adjusted to $10,150,
your semiannual interest payment would rise to $197.92.
</P>
<P>
   _ You get downside protection if the economy goes into a
deflationary spiral. In that case, the redemption value of the bond
will never fall below $10,000.
</P>
<P>
   With standard Treasuries, by contrast, the redemption value
isn't adjusted for inflation and the interest rate doesn't change.
At an interest rate of 6 percent on a standard $10,000 bond, you
get a steady $600 per year, no more and no less, and at maturity
you get your $10,000 back _ period.
</P>
<P>
   Sustained inflation of slightly more than 2 percent would cause
inflation-indexed bonds to slightly outperform standard 10-year
Treasuries. That's because a 2.1 percent inflation adjustment is
needed to bridge the gap between the interest rates on the two
securities.
</P>
<P>
   If the annual inflation rate were to jump to 4 percent or higher
and stay there, buyers of inflation-indexed bonds would receive far
better yields than those who buy standard Treasuries.
</P>
<P>
   But how likely is that?
</P>
<P>
   In the 12 months ended in April, the CPI did indeed rise by more
than 2 percent _ 2.3 percent, to be precise. That was the first
time inflation edged above the 2 percent mark since the 12-month
period ending in October 1997.
</P>
<P>
   However, not since the 12-month period ended June 1991 has
inflation exceeded 4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The inflationary surge during the past year was due largely to a
0.7 percent spike during April. That was fueled by soaring energy
costs _ something any buyer of gasoline must have noticed.
</P>
<P>
   No one knows for certain whether April was the start of an
inflationary trend or just a hiccup. We'll have more evidence
tomorrow, when the Bureau of Labor Statistics reports the CPI
figures for May.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of the April CPI report, Greenspan and his
colleagues expressed concern that the economy may be heating up to
the point where inflation could become a menace once again.
</P>
<P>
   Some say the mere fact that Greenspan suddenly seems more
worried than usual about inflation is enough to justify a red
alert.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of BONDS15 () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  ``You have to listen to what Alan Greenspan says,'' remarks Jay
A. Kellett, chief executive of KCM Investment Advisors in Larkspur.
``He has more information than any of the rest of us, and he tells
the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Most inflation-indexed bonds, officially known as Treasury
Inflation Protection Securities, are sold to institutions and
wealthy individuals in denominations ranging from $1,000 to $5
million. Several billion dollars worth are sold quarterly, with
5-year, 10-year and 30-year maturities. (A new issue of 10-year
bonds is scheduled for July 7.)
</P>
<P>
   Starting late last year, the Treasury also began issuing
inflation-indexed savings bonds, in denominations as small as $50,
to stimulate interest among middle-income investors.
</P>
<P>
   Many financial experts think the Fed will raise interest rates
this month to forestall any further inflationary outbursts.
</P>
<P>
   They figure the rates will go up immediately after a meeting of
the Fed's Open Market Committee, scheduled for June 29 and 30. If
so, it would be the Fed's first rate boost in two years.
</P>
<P>
   If the Fed does raise rates, that could cool off the economy and
help nip inflation in the bud _ in which case the argument for
buying inflation-indexed bonds would weaken.
</P>
<P>
   But there will always be a rationale for these bonds, because
they are the only investment whose returns are guaranteed to exceed
gains in the cost of living.
</P>
<P>
   That is no small virtue in itself, and on top of that, the bonds
are backed _ as the familiar saying goes _ by the full faith and
credit of the U.S. government.
</P>
<P>
   With indexed bonds currently providing a 3.9 percent yield above
and beyond inflation, buying them ensures that the real value of
your assets will increase by 47 percent over a 10-year period. Over
a 30-year period, your buying power would more than triple.
</P>
<P>
   ``A 3.9 percent real return, locked in, is a high real return,''
says Ray Dalio, president of Connecticut's Bridgewater Associates,
which manages an indexed-bond fund for institutional investors.
``Over the last 30 or 35 years, bonds have averaged a 2.7 percent
real return, so 3.9 percent is good.''
</P>
<P>
   Such returns may seem puny compared with the 30 percent per year
that many stock-market investors have earned during the past four
or five years.
</P>
<P>
   But investors should remember that there have been many years
when stocks rose by less than the inflation rate _ to say nothing
of the many years when the market actually fell.
</P>
<P>
   ``These bonds might be suitable for people who are very
concerned about the stock market,'' says Beverly Tanner of the
Tanner Financial Group in Larkspur.
</P>
<P>
   One problem with standard inflation-indexed bonds is that they
are not taxpayer friendly. (As we shall see, that is not the case
with the inflation-indexed savings bonds.)
</P>
<P>
   Not only must you pay federal taxes every year on the interest
you receive, but also on any inflation-adjusted gains that are made
in your bond's par value. Like other Treasuries, the bonds are
exempt from state and local income taxes.
</P>
<P>
   If the par value is adjusted upward for inflation, the amount of
the increase is taxed that year, even though you don't actually lay
hands on the money until the bond matures. So you would have to dip
into your other assets to pay the tax bill.
</P>
<P>
   For that reason, financial advisers suggest that investors buy
indexed bonds strictly for tax-free or tax-deferred portfolios,
such as Individual Retirement Accounts. That way, you can escape
the year-to-year tax hassle.
</P>
<P>
   Happily, the strict tax rules don't apply to the new
inflation-indexed savings bonds. The tax on any increase in their
value is automatically deferred until the bonds are redeemed.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 2 of BONDS15 () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  Tax on the savings-bond interest is also deferred, because the
interest automatically is reinvested in more bonds.
</P>
<P>
   So there is no strong need to buy the savings bonds for a
standard, tax-deferred IRA account. However, you might consider
buying them for a Roth IRA, where all investment gains accumulate
tax free.
</P>
<P>
   You can buy inflation-indexed Treasuries directly and
commission-free through an account with the Federal Reserve. If you
don't already have an account, you can apply electronically on the
Web at www.frbsf.org or by calling the Federal Reserve Bank of San
Francisco at (415) 974-2000.
</P>
<P>
   You also can buy the bonds in the secondary market, through a
broker. Depending on the broker, you will have to pay a commission
in the range of about $30 to $50 per bond.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
COL. 3 of BONDS15 () &QL;
</P>
<P>
   END OF STORY  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
