<HEADER>
A5748 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VIRGINMARY-DISPUTE16-     06-15 0375
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIRGINMARY-DISPUTE16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Attorneys try to settle fight over messages
 &HT;    By Duane D. Stanford
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Attorneys for Nancy Fowler and her former support
organization are trying to settle a dispute over the rights to
messages Fowler says she receives from the Virgin Mary.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Robert Kelley, Fowler's friend and a former member of
Our Loving Mother's Children, said attorneys for both sides are
abiding by a self-imposed gag order while they attempt to negotiate
a settlement.
</P>
<P>
   The disagreement appears to center on the messages Fowler gave
at her White Road farm in Conyers after her visions of the Virgin
Mary. In a prepared statement, Fowler blamed her dissatisfaction
with OLMC on the group's president, Robert Hughes.
</P>
<P>
   ``After I disassociated myself from OLMC Inc., I requested the
return of all the books and videos prepared and published in
support of my mission,'' the statement read. ``The material was
prepared with donations from pilgrims. Mr. Hughes claims that he
and his wife own the material. They continue to market the material
at many times its cost to produce. They do so without my
blessing.''
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta Journal-Constitution was unable to reach Hughes for
a response to Fowler's allegations.
</P>
<P>
   Last Wednesday, Fowler asked Rockdale County, Ga. Superior Court
Judge Sidney Nation for a temporary restraining order against OLMC.
Nation's office confirmed the judge signed an order for Fowler, but
a secretary said Nation couldn't remember specifics about what the
order said or what Fowler specifically asked the judge to stop.
Nothing on the case had been filed in the clerk's office by the
close of business Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Fowler's messages ended in 1998 after eight years. During that
time, thousands from the U.S., Mexico and Latin America made the
trip to Conyers to hear the messages, which always were
disseminated on the 13th of the month. During the largest turnouts,
roads were often clogged around the farm, forcing local sheriff's
deputies to direct traffic and monitor the crowds.
</P>
<P>
   Duane Stanford writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
