<DOCNO> NYT19990615.0052 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-15 10:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5749 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLA-SUPERBOWL-MONEY16     06-15 0564
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-SUPERBOWL-MONEY16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Palm Beach County to NFL: Show us the money
 &HT;    By Marcia Gelbart
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ For their $210,000 to the last two Super
Bowls played in South Florida, Palm Beach officials expect the
National Football League to show the same gratitude it did in
Broward and Miami-Dade counties: a $1 million contribution toward a
new youth center.
</P>
<P>
   That would be something real they could point to as they decide
whether to continue donating in the face of doubts about whether
Palm Beach County's investment is worth it.
</P>
<P>
   The three counties pitch in hundreds of thousands of dollars to
jointly host the games. Boosted with private money, Miami-Dade used
its NFL donation to build a youth facility in 1995; Broward will
open a center this fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Next time, it'll be our turn,'' said Palm Beach County
Commission Chairwoman Maude Ford Lee.
</P>
<P>
   Not necessarily, according to the NFL. Since 1993, the football
league has built the inner-city facilities, which it calls Youth
Education Towns, in each Super Bowl host city as a tangible legacy
of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Since football's ultimate showdown is a tri-county effort when
it's played in South Florida, Palm Beach County officials say they
always thought the benefits would be split three ways.
</P>
<P>
   ``The commitment was, we'll do one in Dade and one in Broward,''
said Jim Steeg, the NFL's vice president of special events. The
league agreed to nothing else, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm unaware of any understanding'' among the three counties
and the NFL, said Hank Adorno, chairman of the 1999 host committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people may have made some natural assumptions,'' Adorno
continued, ``but nobody should be saying we're getting a new (youth
center), or, even if we did, where it would be.''
</P>
<P>
   Next spring, South Florida will make a bid to host the Super
Bowl in Pro Player Stadium in 2004.
</P>
<P>
   But talk of the NFL contribution surfaced last week at the
county's Tourist Development Council as members discussed what Palm
Beach County got for its $120,000 contribution to this year's game.
</P>
<P>
   Broward gave $450,000; Miami-Dade donated $600,000, plus about
$1 million in free services, Adorno said.
</P>
<P>
   During the Super Bowl festivities, fewer people stayed in Palm
Beach County hotels than those farther south because it's cheaper
to sleep in Fort Lauderdale, concluded a new report by a consultant
to the tourist council.
</P>
<P>
   A wise investment? Tourism officials couldn't agree.
</P>
<P>
   But Assistant Palm Beach County Administrator Bill Wilkins
reminded the group of the anticipated youth center. ``We'll get
value for the money we put in,'' Wilkins said. Lee, who chairs the
council as well as the county commission, agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a bad trade-off,'' said Warren ``Mac'' McLaughlin,
the county's Convention and Visitors Bureau president and a member
of the host committee board.
</P>
<P>
   If it were built, Lee's impoverished commission district could
be a prime contender. Ultimately, it'll be up to county
commissioners _ who each had the opportunity this year to buy two
Super Bowl tickets at face value from the NFL _ to decide whether
the county contributes to the nextarea Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Marcia Gelbart writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
