<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LATHAM-COLUMN16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    When children clean rooms it must be 'the last of days'
 &HT;    By Phil Latham
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MARSHALL, Texas _ My 17-year-old son cleaned up his room the
other day.
</P>
<P>
   Voluntarily.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, he did it well.
</P>
<P>
   I cannot overstate just how eerie this is. Parents may want to
sit down before reading this next part but, he actually went
downstairs, located the vacuum cleaner, took it upstairs and used
it, and all without needing extensive instruction! He even changed
the burned-out lightbulbs, something I have never seen a child do.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, he cleaned a small portion of the room used by his
brother.
</P>
<P>
   And the coup de grace? He cleaned the bathroom. I should mention
here, for those parents who feel faint at the idea of a child
cleaning the bathroom, that is has been less than a week since that
bathroom had been cleaned by an adult, so it was not terribly
dirty.
</P>
<P>
   But I personally was shocked that a child _ particularly a boy _
would ever even come up with the notion that a bathroom needed to
be cleaned, much less take it upon himself to do it.
</P>
<P>
   Most of you who are experienced parents are waiting for the
punch line, here, you have to be asking yourself, ``OK, what did he
want?''
</P>
<P>
   The answer is: Nothing. He did not ask for a penny (possibly
because he knows he wouldn't have gotten it). He didn't want to go
to the movies, to stay out late or even to stay up late.
</P>
<P>
   We've made appointments for extensive testing at the Mayo
Clinic. I figure it has to be some strange virus that has entered
his bloodstream from eating one too many gummy bears, maybe some
weird germ mutated by the CIA or the Russians.
</P>
<P>
   Or perhaps this, at last, is proof positve that aliens really
are taking over the bodies of our children. If so, the intelligence
is clearly superior. In any case, I suppose the government will
want to study him, probably at Area 57.
</P>
<P>
   For a fact if Moldy and Sculler (or is that Scoulder and Mully?)
were ever looking for the X-files, the chances were excellent that
they were hidden in my son's room, beneath dirty clothes, candy
wrappers and Mad magazines, safe from detection from any source in
the universe.
</P>
<P>
   I watched the procession of refuse coming from that room on the
suspicion that I might see the X-files, but with no luck. It is,
possible, however, that I saw some X-flies buzzing their way to
freedom.
</P>
<P>
   I had wondered what had happened to most of the eating utensils
in the house. No more, they came out of my son's room and, though
now discovered, may be retired or put into quarantine. Since I need
to lose some weight, I intend to keep the memory of that silverware
coming out of the room. It will certainly make me lose my appetite.
</P>
<P>
   Oddly, much more silverware came out than paper plates, which
leads me to the grim conclusion that my son was recycling his paper
plates, or perhaps he was eating his chicken pot pies directly off
the carpet. I avoid, at almost all cost, monitoring any of my
children's eating habits, so I wouldn't really know.
</P>
<P>
   I have, in fact, attempted not to enter any of their rooms, for
fear of what evil might lurk within.
</P>
<P>
   But when I went into my son's room, there was nothing but clean.
The professionals tell you that when a child suddenly changes
habits it is a sign of possible drug use.
</P>
<P>
   If this is so, all I want to know is, where can I enough for the
other three children?
</P>
<P>
   Phil Latham is editor and publisher of the Marshall News
Messenger, Marshall, Texas. E-mail: platham(AT)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
