<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROSENFELD-SHORTTAKES16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SHORTTAKES: Lucky Lindy's nightmare
 &HT;    By Arnold Rosenfeld
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The traveler began to speak:
</P>
<P>
   ``Every airline has one, but this guy was the original. He was
the one who, in a moment of misconceived altruism, eliminated
smoking. It gave him, strangely, no pleasure. Nothing, it seemed to
him, was like eliminating previously undiscovered cost centers. He
never discussed cutting costs, only efficiencies.
</P>
<P>
   ``He started by getting rid of complimentary meals in coach. The
savings, when annualized, were astounding. What he really liked was
the sight of agreeable passengers trooping lemming-like into
airplanes carrying brown paper lunch bags filled with meals made of
sawdust. `They're doing it to themselves,' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He got rid of peanuts by convincing a civil-rights group to
demand peanut-free zones. Soft drinks were next. Common courtesy
was found to have associated costs. He is now at work on a plan to
catheterize passengers as they enter the plane, explaining the
procedure is for 'your comfort and convenience.' Covertly, the
airline will cut the number of restrooms to one.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is now working on a schedule of fines, the ultimate
objective of which is the total elimination of passengers, who only
impede the air travel process. No-shows objecting to further
efficiencies would be fined. Travelers who showed up with residual
expectations of service would also be fined. Anyone could
eventually be fined for anything the airline perceived as
graceless.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is considering eliminating the standard announcement, 'If
there is anything we can do to make your flight more enjoyable,
please do not hesitate to ask.' In 1991, a passenger seems to have
asked to talk to the captain about the ideas of the German
philosopher and mathematician Gottfried Wilhelm von Leibnitz. If
allowed to get out of hand, the costs would be incalculable.''
</P>
<P>
   The traveler made a curious gesture, then moved off into the
shadows.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold Rosenfeld is editor-in-chief of the Cox Newspapers.
E-mail: arnold.rosenfeld(at)cox.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
