<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New apartment, new appliances _ same old ugly pet
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ In August, my son Kristofor is going to be
married. Now that he's finished school in Columbus, he'll be moving
to Philadelphia where Amy, his bride-to-be, already lives. The job
of apartment hunting was dropped onto her most capable shoulders by
default. She recently struck pay dirt. Kristofor filled me in.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a newly renovated old home that has been turned into two
apartments. Ours is the second and third floor AND,'' he adds with
emphasis, ``it has all new appliances. That's really important, you
know?''
</P>
<P>
   Sure, I know. I can still remember the first apartment his
father and I rented, almost 40 years ago. It was two rooms and a
bath near Chicago's Midway Airport ... $135 a month, furniture and
utilities included. And best of all, the stove and refrigerator
were brand new. No matter the floors were a skating rink in winter,
or the upstairs neighbors sounded like elephants line dancing, I
was thrilled with my new appliances (and of course, my new
husband).
</P>
<P>
   ``And the rent is (SET ITAL)only(END ITAL) $850 a month,'' he
slips in and catches me pretty much unaware. ``That's the bottom
end of what we figured we could afford. Isn't that great?''
</P>
<P>
   As a mother and future mother-in-law, I know that my only job is
to wear neutral colors and keep my mouth shut, but in spite of
myself, I flinch.
</P>
<P>
   Kristofor rattles on in praise of virgin stoves and washing
machines while I work on coming to grips with reality. This is not
1959, I remind myself. Get over it. A nasty picture of where these
kids might be living on $135 a month, even without furniture and
utilities, slams home. Does flophouse ring a bell?
</P>
<P>
   Then he tells me they had to cough up two months' rent plus
another $850 pet deposit for Tattinger (his beloved 10-year-old
part-Siamese cat). While I'm focused on how I might have monthly
CARE packages delivered, another creepy (really) thought pops up. I
ask him if he's told (SET ITAL)all(END ITAL) in his pet declaration
to the owner. He pretends not to know what I mean.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fluffy,'' I remind him. ``Aren't you taking him with you?''
</P>
<P>
   Kristofor registers surprise that I could even bring myself to
ask about his alternative pet and assures me the landlord wouldn't
be concerned about a cockroach in a cage. I tell him he's lucky
because if it were up to me he wouldn't be allowed within the city
limits with that ugly bug.
</P>
<P>
   Fluffy is a Madagascan hissing cockroach. My son found the bug
homeless, wandering the halls outside Kristofor's lab in the
zoology department at Ohio State, and since he was apparently an
escaped experiment, took pity on him. ``I couldn't just let him
die, could I?'' were his exact words. I suggested that cockroaches,
unlike little boys, could make it very nicely on their own and
reminded him they were the only life form known to survive an
</P>
<P>
   atomic blast.
</P>
<P>
   That's how my son ended up sharing his apartment with a roach
the size of a shoebox _ one that he feeds monkey chow and grapes.
</P>
<P>
   Really, I shouldn't have been shocked. This was not his first
attempt to domesticate vermin. A couple of years earlier he had
liberated another pet of the genus (SET ITAL)cockroachus
giganticus(END ITAL). That one he named ``Spot.''
</P>
<P>
   Spot was not well when my son found him, in fact, his crusty
little body was covered in mites. So Kristofor sat down and for the
better part of an afternoon, held the giant cockroach in one hand
and tweezers in the other, picking and grooming until Spot came out
looking like a new roach. Spot thrived until his three-score and
ten (in bug years) was up and his little antenna went belly up. And
now there's Fluffy.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia, don't say you haven't been warned.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Mail: 320 West
Madison, Gibsonburg, OH, 43431 or e-mail: eschuett(AT)nwonline.net.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
