<SLUG> BC-TODAYSHOW16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Good mornings, competitive mornings ahead for networks
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A commercial break during the ``Today'' show, and
deep inside Rockefeller Center, the old Warren Zevon song
``Werewolves of London'' is blasting in the production booth for
Studio 1A.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ahh-ooooh!'' executive producer Jeff Zucker, his necktie flung
back over his left shoulder, howls along. Even though the 6 million
or so viewers around the country are watching a string of ads,
NBC's ``Today'' show is rockin' 'n' rollin'.
</P>
<P>
   Is it ever. ``Today,'' the first of the morning news shows when
it debuted in 1952, is amazingly dominant in the late '90s _ it's
been the No. 1 morning show for 181 straight weeks, almost 3 1/2
years, and its ratings' lead over ``Good Morning America'' and
``CBS This Morning'' is enormous.
</P>
<P>
   It's had two of the most talked-about TV news interviews of the
year _ Matt Lauer's relentless questions to Monica Lewinsky and
Katie Couric's long interview with two surviving relatives of the
Littleton, Colo., victims.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today'' doesn't even need a Ricky Martin concert to make the
crowd outside go nuts, but it had that, too, last Friday.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, look out ``Today,'' 'cause it's only getting harder
from here on out. In September, ``Good Morning America'' (which has
been moving back up in the ratings with Diane Sawyer and Charlie
Gibson) moves into its new studio overlooking Times Square, which
means ``GMA'' can play to adoring crowds outside as well. And in
November, CBS unwraps its new revamped show with Bryant Gumbel as
anchor and its own street-side studio on Central Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole thing worries me,'' acknowledges Lauer. ``I don't
walk around feeling all that confident.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Do I think about it?'' says Zucker about the competition.
``How about every hour?
</P>
<P>
   ``In the fall,'' Zucker adds, ``everybody is going to be paying
attention to the prime-time schedule and who's going to win which
time slot. But the toughest battle is probably going to be here in
the morning.''
</P>
<P>
   In the breakfast wars, it's all about the anchors, obviously,
and how they connect with viewers, making them feel, ideally, like
they're inviting wise and warm friends into their kitchens and
bedrooms. And it's all about the news, and who delivers it fast,
smooth and in the right-size chunks. But maybe, most of all, it's
all about having a studio that opens out onto a Manhattan street
and gathers a big, noisy crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say that nobody leaves a Broadway musical humming the
set,'' says Steve Friedman, a former veteran ``Today'' producer
who's been tapped by CBS to oversee the new Gumbel show. ``But you
gotta compete in the location wars.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It brings an instant energy,'' says Lauer of the several
hundred people (many more when ``Today'' does one of its Friday
summer concerts) who gather each day in Rockefeller Plaza to wave
their signs and jostle for on-camera face time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was skeptical at first,'' says Couric. ``But people enjoy
it, they feel like it's a happening.''
</P>
<P>
   On the ``Werewolves of London'' morning, the crowd outside in
Rockefeller Plaza is typical, armed with instant cameras, signs
(``You talked to my grandma _ Why not me?'') and autograph books.
Jim Raskob, a pharmaceutical salesman from Minneapolis in town for
a convention, has shown up carrying a sign that says ``Hi, Mom!''
for his mother's 60th birthday.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the best I could do,'' he says of the unoriginal sign.
``But I didn't misspell anything!''
</P>
<P>
   Couric comes out to play on a trapeze set up in the plaza
(``Sometimes I can't believe the things they ask me to do!'' she
says later, but she also knows she's a former gymnast and could
manage it).
</P>
<P>
   ``She's so perky!'' gushes a woman in the crowd, who then
quickly adds, ``I'll bet she gets tired of hearing that.'' She
does.
</P>
<P>
   This is some of what ABC and CBS hope to copy, or capture,
although both say they'll do it differently from ``Today.''
Producers of both competitors say they'll use the window on the
crowd less, and ``Good Morning America's'' studio will be on the
second floor rather than on the ground floor such as ``Today.''
</P>
<P>
   As for copying, Friedman laughs. He was executive producer of
``Today'' when the street-side studio was being planned. ``If I
can't rip myself off, who can I rip off?''
</P>
<P>
   ``So much is made of the race and the ratings,'' Couric says in
one of her two offices after she's done outside. ``It's very
cyclical. Things change, but they change very slowly in morning
television.''
</P>
<P>
   It's that truism _ that it takes a very long time for viewers to
change their morning habits _ that is working against ABC and CBS
as they strive to catch ``Today.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When people go out to dinner, they order Italian one night,
steak the next night, whatever they're in the mood for,'' says
Shelley Ross, executive producer of ``Good Morning America.'' ``But
for breakfast, they want their toast dry, their bacon crisp, their
eggs a certain way, the same way every day.''
</P>
<P>
   What's working in their favor is that morning news is the only
area in network television where the audience is growing rather
than shrinking.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last four years, the total audience for the three
morning shows is up, from 12.1 million to 12.8 million _ about six
percent. During that same period, the audience for ``ER,'' the No.
1 show in prime time, is down almost 20 percent, typical of what's
happening to the broadcast networks everywhere but in the morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are asking why would Diane Sawyer come to morning
television, why would Bryant Gumbel come back?'' says Zucker.
``(It's because) morning news is the only growth market in all of
network television.''
</P>
<P>
   The reasons, all three morning show producers agree: people are
getting up earlier because commutes are longer, some people are
working out in the mornings, and more people are seeking quick hits
on news, as well as traffic and weather information from local
morning news, which is also up in the ratings.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't get up at 6:30 in the morning and put on an HBO
movie,'' notes Friedman.
</P>
<P>
   Still, ABC and CBS face formidable odds. ABC's ``Good Morning
America'' squandered strong ratings, clumsily shuffled anchor teams
and de-emphasized hard news until it brought in Sawyer and Gibson
to stabilize the show. The ratings have finally climbed back to
where they were under the old team of Gibson and Joan Lunden, but
the buzz in the news biz is: How long will Sawyer, a $7 million a
year superstar, continue to get up at 4 a.m. to save ABC's morning
bacon?
</P>
<P>
   She's signed through May of 2000, and may stay longer to make a
smooth transition to the next anchor or team. ``The errors that
'GMA' made in the past of just popping in new people won't
happen,'' vows Ross.
</P>
<P>
   At least ``GMA'' has success in its past; in the '80s and early
'90s, it was the No. 1 morning show, well ahead of ``Today.'' CBS's
morning track record is 40 years of utter failure, with hosts
ranging from Walter Cronkite to Paula Zahn (and a younger Diane
Sawyer) never getting out of third place.
</P>
<P>
   ``Either we're doomed or we're due,'' says producer Friedman,
fatalistically. With his studio under construction, Friedman is
looking for a co-anchor for Gumbel, and the rumor mill has churned
out names such as Deborah Norville and Elizabeth Vargas so far.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking for someone who is fun, who can stand up to
Bryant,'' Friedman says. ``With all due respect to Katie Couric,
who was Katie Couric before she got the job?''
</P>
<P>
   On this day, she's the center of attention in Rockefeller Plaza,
dangling from a trapeze and grinning gamely as the crowd chants
``Katie! Katie! Katie!'' There is no doubt, at least for right now,
who's Number One.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Kloer writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
