<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-USENET-TAKEOVERS16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Small groups kidnap forums for their own purposes
 &HT;    By Charles Stough
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ The Usenet forum was for owners of Chia pets,
those ceramic animals from mail-order TV. And there in the list of
subjects was a query from someone desperate to keep her dog from
chasing cars.
</P>
<P>
   A chia dog that chases cars? That would be worth sending a
photographer, if those TV prowl vans don't beat us to it.
</P>
<P>
   And there was another pottery-pet question asking whether a
mother cat would adopt a kitten from someone else's litter. And
some advice on controlling fleas (another startling problem,
considering recent advances in ceramic technology). And someone
complaining that her landlord won't let her keep a ferret.
</P>
<P>
   Wondering why a landlord would object to a pottery ferret, which
after all is no noisier nor destructive to drapes than a pottery
turtle, I had to look. And I found technological kidnapping, right
there in cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   A group of pet owners had found the abandoned Usenet newsgroup
alt.pets.chia and simply adopted it as a mini-forum of their own.
</P>
<P>
   There are plenty of pet owners' newsgroups, covering many breeds
of dogs and cats, exotic birds, aquariums, horses, farm animals,
and even one for dragons. But they can be big and noisy, with
hundreds of postings a day. That might mean a glutted mailbox for
those who read newsgroups as e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   The alt.pets.chia group seems to be about 12 people, and they
have many kinds of pets. But they have come to know each other in
the Net and enjoy one another's electronic company, so they meet in
``a.p.c.''
</P>
<P>
   In small towns of the world, the same thing happens face-to-face
at park benches or coffee shops or beauty parlors. Why not in
Usenet, which is very much like a meeting place? Anyone on the
Internet can go there for free.
</P>
<P>
   There are more than 20,000 Usenet forums. How alt.pets.chia ever
was formed is a mystery. Starting forums used to involve writing a
charter for the group, announcing it, letting all users vote on
whether it's worthwhile or not, and waiting for the results.
</P>
<P>
   Some groups got voted down, though with alt.pets.chia there, I
can't imagine what the losers must have been.
</P>
<P>
   Intrigued, I went looking for other abandoned forums. But unused
groups are hard to find. Here are some early search failures:
</P>
<P>
   _ Alt.angst. Sorry, big crowd. Suffice to say that the times are
not as untroubled as the Dow Jones industrial average would imply.
</P>
<P>
   _ Alt.bogus.group. Already taken over. Many users seem to be
refugees from alt.devilbunnies, a fun fantasy group who pretend
that the world has been invaded by alien raiders disguised as
cuddly bunnies, evil and predatory and indistinguishable from
genuine cuddly bunnies. A harmless game. Or maybe they're right.
</P>
<P>
   _ Alt.barney.dinosaur.die.die.die. In use. Don't even go there.
</P>
<P>
   _ Alt.culture.oregon. Surprise, there's culture in Oregon. There
is no group named alt.culture.ohio, by the way. Draw from that any
conclusion you want. They have Sasquatch, oceanfront and year-round
temperate climate. We have bankrupt schools, a ballpark being built
on a poison pool under eight inches of concrete, and E-check. Who
needs culture?
</P>
<P>
   _ Alt.fan.dan-quayle. Yes, well, if we could trust people from
Indiana we wouldn't make them live in another time zone.Alt.fan.u2.
Rock music fans just won't give up.
</P>
<P>
   Usenet forums are accessible through local Internet service
providers or by going to Deja News' Web site, www.dejanews.com. Go
there and form your own friendships.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Stough writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
E-mail: charlesstough(AT)coxohio.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
