<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-15 10:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5766 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BLACK-FARMERS16-COX     06-15 1959
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLACK-FARMERS16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Black farmers reap benefits from years of discrimination
 &HT;    By Jenny Staletovich
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PAHOKEE, Fla. _ In the land of sugar barons, C.R. Martin is an
unusual thing indeed.
</P>
<P>
   Not only is he a farmer, but he is a black man.
</P>
<P>
   It would be nice to say it has not always been this way. That
once, when the fields of rich muck stretching east from Lake
Okeechobee were farmed by farmers, not corporations, there were
many C.R. Martins. That after riding on the back of a cattle truck
50 years ago _ two days and two nights wrapped in a quilt as much
to keep out the cold as the angry stares _ Martin and other black
men recruited as cheap labor from the red clay hills of North
Mississippi arrived to find white men willing to sell them seed,
tractors and land.
</P>
<P>
   But that would not happen. Sharecropping was fine for a black
man. But owning a farm?
</P>
<P>
   Even the U.S. Department of Agriculture, formed in 1862 to
assist farmers, turned its back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went to borrow money one time and the man said, 'We can't
loan you the money because it won't be in the budget.' They wasn't
going to loan it to me if they had it in the budget,'' Martin
recalled.
</P>
<P>
   It would take 38 years of hard work and saving. Long days
hunched in a white man's field, long days pumping gas and then
years and years _ 27 in all _ working the loading dock for a local
produce broker.
</P>
<P>
   After all that, C.R. Martin got his farm in 1988; a 20-acre bean
field near Pahokee that even with his savings he had to borrow to
buy. And then, it took only one bad freeze to nearly lose it.
</P>
<P>
   Why? Because being a small farmer is hard and being a small
black farmer is nearly impossible. When a crop is lost, credit is
the only way to survive and credit can be hard to come by. Black
farmers for years have struggled with the USDA, their government
loans delayed past planting time or inexplicably rejected. At last
count in 1997, only 18,000 of America's 1.9 million farms were
owned by blacks. Palm Beach County had only 18; only four earned
more than $10,000.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, as small farms collapsed under the weight of
competition from mega growers, black farms perished at nearly twice
the rate of white farms. Black farmers understood why it was so
difficult. But it wasn't until April that the rest of the world
learned: A federal class-action lawsuit initiated by a third
generation North Carolina farmer against the USDA was settled for
an estimated $2.25 billion, the largest civil rights settlement in
history.
</P>
<P>
   Under the settlement, farmers who were discriminated against
between 1981 and 1997 will get $50,000 each and have their debts,
many amounting to hundreds of thousands of dollars, erased.
(Farmers with strong proof of discrimination may pursue larger
damages.)
</P>
<P>
   Farmers like C.R. Martin, largely concentrated in the South, are
now filing claims. They have met by the hundreds in Tallahassee and
Tampa. South Florida farmers meet next month at the University of
Miami. Eventually, attorneys anticipate between 20,000 and 30,000
claims nationwide, said Miami attorney Sidney Calloway, whose Miami
firm is handling the Florida claims.
</P>
<P>
   In a scathing opinion approving the settlement, U.S. District
Judge Paul Friedman blamed the USDA.
</P>
<P>
   ``Forty acres and a mule. The government broke that promise to
African-American farmers. Over one hundred years later, the USDA
broke its promise to Mr. James Beverly (a hog farmer from Nottaway
County, Va.). It promised him a loan to build farrowing houses so
that he could breed hogs. Because he was African-American, he never
received that loan,'' Friedman wrote.
</P>
<P>
   But not everyone is happy. At a hearing in March in Washington,
400 farmers, including the lead plaintiff, packed a federal
courtroom to object.
</P>
<P>
   The problem, they say, is while the settlement provides money _
a meager amount in farm dollars _ it doesn't give the farmers back
their land. It doesn't force the government to set up rules to make
sure this never happens again. And, to be eligible to file a claim,
farmers must have filed a discrimination complaint before 1997.
Many, conditioned by years of oppression, never did.
</P>
<P>
   ``The attorneys sold us out,'' said Gary Grant, a
second-generation farmer and president of the North Carolina-based
Black Farmers and Agriculturalists Association, which hosted a
meeting this weekend to decide what to do. ``They get to see the
money at the end of the tunnel and forget, if not for us, they
wouldn't have'' the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   For years, reports on the status of black farmers have warned of
their march toward extinction.
</P>
<P>
   Just before the turn of the century, 60 percent of employed
blacks were farmers or worked on a farm, according to a 1982 report
by the U.S. Commission on Civil Rights. At a peak in 1920, black
farms numbered 926,000.
</P>
<P>
   Overcoming lynchings (62 percent of the cotton-growing counties
had at least one between 1900 and 1931), bans on voting rights and
difficulty buying decent land, fertilizer and even seed, they
succeeded on their own terms, creating banks and black agricultural
universities such as Florida A&AMP;M University, which opened in 1887.
</P>
<P>
   Essie Robinson's father tried to escape the racism of the deep
South by starting over in South Florida. What he found in Delray
Beach in 1901 was a brutal sharecropping system _ a new form of
slavery.
</P>
<P>
   ``After daddy harvested the first crop, he found out the man
wanted to take (more than half his crop). He said no, it isn't
going to happen that way. So by moonlight he would harvest his
crop,'' said Robinson, 81. ``He did that the whole season and after
that he said no more sharecropping. So he bought land and farmed
himself.''
</P>
<P>
   When the bottom fell out of the cotton market in 1914 and the
boll weevil decimated crops seven years later, no one suffered more
than black farmers.
</P>
<P>
   Between 1930 and 1978, the number of white farms dropped from
5.4 million to 2.4 million. Black farms vanished at a much more
precipitous rate: from 882,852 to 57,271.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know Dad couldn't get a loan. He had to scuffle,'' said
Osborne Woods, 73, whose father migrated from the Bahamas and
farmed in what is now Boca Raton.
</P>
<P>
   When Charles Massengill, the son of a sharecropper who moved
from Dawson, Ga., in 1939, quit his job at Everglades Flower
Growers to start a gladiola farm, he found a white partner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't have farmed on my own,'' Massengill, 77, said.
``Things started to change up in the '60s. But before that . . . a
black man couldn't drive a bulldozer.''
</P>
<P>
   While the civil rights movement grew, much of the farming world
remained mired in racism.
</P>
<P>
   As early as 1965, a Civil Rights Commission study found the USDA
discriminated against the 250,000 remaining black farmers. In 1980,
the agency suggested loans and other programs to help small and
minority-owned farms. But in 1981, 95 percent of the loans on
average still went to whites.
</P>
<P>
   When in 1982 the Civil Rights report warned that black farmers
would disappear altogether by 2000 if the agency failed to help,
USDA officials scoffed, saying they had no ``jurisdiction to make
loans for social purposes.''
</P>
<P>
   Racism had so thoroughly infected the agency that many farmers
began speaking out. Still, in 1983, President Reagan disbanded the
USDA's Office of Civil Rights.
</P>
<P>
   Black farmers repeatedly had loans denied or faced demands for
excessive collateral, Judge Friedman found.
</P>
<P>
   A Virginia farmer received a loan, but was forced to get
approval from a county official to make withdrawals. The Rev.
Walter Campbell, the son of a Georgia sharecropper, received
thousands in loans, but almost always too late. In 1997, he lost
the Pompano Beach house he built himself after his debt grew to
$338,929.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got the money when we didn't need it and didn't get it when
we did need it,'' said Campbell, 77. ``We knew what they was giving
us, we wouldn't be able to pay back. But they said when we sold
(our crops) they'd take a certain percentage. They said they'd
never take my house.''
</P>
<P>
   When his house was auctioned, Campbell's attorney bought it.
Campbell now pays him $400 a month to rent it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wound up in the hole really bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Moses Crawford joined him there. Crawford leased 250 acres in
Immokalee, but in 1987 a freeze wiped out his crops. He borrowed
$200,000 to get back on his feet, he said. Instead, the government
took his house.
</P>
<P>
   ``I bought the house the day President Kennedy got killed,''
said Crawford, who now runs a produce stand and butcher shop in
North Miami and rents an apartment. ``I paid $13,000 and added on
to that house. It had five bedrooms by the time I was finished.''
</P>
<P>
   In December 1996 black farmers marched on Washington and finally
got the USDA's attention, Gary Grant said.
</P>
<P>
   After a series of meetings around the country, Secretary of
Agriculture Dan Glickman conceded discriminatory practices in
February 1997 and vowed to reestablish a civil rights division.
</P>
<P>
   More than a year later, Judge Friedman certified a lawsuit filed
by the North Carolina farmer as a class action.
</P>
<P>
   Martin heard about the lawsuit after a segment aired on 60
Minutes and called his brother, who worked for Jet magazine. The
next day his brother called with an attorney's phone number. Martin
attended meetings in Alabama, Georgia and Tallahassee and filed his
claim in May.
</P>
<P>
   At a Tallahassee meeting in May organized by attorney Calloway,
about 100 farmers waited hours to talk to lawyers in an auditorium
at FAMU. Among them was Gurley Anderson, 77, who lost his left arm
feeding sugar cane into a mill 50 years ago and farmed for another
40 years, growing corn, okra and peanuts on his Whigham, Ga., farm
before his home and equipment were sold to pay debts.
</P>
<P>
   ``They took everything,'' he said. The $50,000 claim ``sure will
be some help to me.''
</P>
<P>
   But others say money is only a quick fix.
</P>
<P>
   ``The secretary of agriculture and the department view the
settlement as the answer to the problem and it's only part of the
answer,'' said John Zippert, a spokesman for the Federation of
Southern Cooperatives. ``We also want to encourage their children
and young people to see the possibility of making a decent living
farming. Of those 18,000 (remaining black farmers), less than 1,000
are under the age of 35 and less than 200 are under 25.''
</P>
<P>
   Calloway said the lawsuit was never intended to resolve all the
problems. ``There's probably other lawsuits down the road.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Martin, who received a letter demanding
repayment of $285,000 within a month of filing his discrimination
complaint in 1997, sits ``blowing in the wind,'' waiting for his
claim.
</P>
<P>
   Yet he and others persist, following the seasons, tied to a
cycle that has shaped their lives. Martin keeps his Pahokee field
plowed, hoping his children will lend him seed and fertilizer money
for his fall bean crop.
</P>
<P>
   And this year, against all odds, another black farmer appeared
in Palm Beach County. Fitzroy Douglas, 40, a Jamaican, started his
own farm of spinach, cabbage and other vegetables on 19 leased
acres in the Glades after working at U.S. Sugar for 21 years.
(Starting as a cane cutter, he rose to assistant manager of an
11,000-acre farm.) It has taken him five years to get it off the
ground, a struggle that has left him bitter but determined.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to do so good I can give up my job and I can take care
of my family. But I know it's a long way down the road.''
</P>
<P>
   Staff writer Charles Elmore contributed to this story.
</P>
<P>
   --ENDIT--
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The POST, WEST PALM BEACH, FLORIDA
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-06-13-99 2338E
</P>
