<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-KOSOVO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIA IS CRUCIAL TO PEACE IN KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ALEX A. VARDAMIS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARMEL, Calif. _ While President Clinton bragged about how
bombing won the war, President Boris Yeltsin felt betrayed. Russia
had played the key role in securing Yugoslavia's acquiescence to
the peace settlement. In return Yeltsin had expected a major role
in the administration of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   But once the peace treaty was signed, Russia's legitimate
expectations were brushed aside.
</P>
<P>
   The stage was set for a fait accompli. In a breathtaking display
of political audacity, the Russians moved swiftly into Pristina.
NATO spokesman Jamie Shea and its commander, Gen. Wesley Clark of
the United States, were caught unaware. So were Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright and Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott.
</P>
<P>
   Even Russian Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov seemed in the dark.
Lt. Gen. Sir Michael Jackson of Britain, head of the NATO security
force, hit a stone wall. A Russian victory column rolled past the
cheering crowds in Pristina in full view of CNN cameras. The first
NATO contingent was not due to arrive until the next morning.
Whether Washington liked it or not, Moscow had asserted its right
to play a central role in Kosovo. And to remind the world that the
United Nations, not NATO, was supposed to be in charge of the
operation.
</P>
<P>
   NATO's goal, since its inception in 1949, has been to maintain
U.S. influence in Europe, to hold Germany down and to keep Russia
out.
</P>
<P>
   In Kosovo, NATO's plan was to include the United States, Germany
and the rest of the alliance at the core of the peacekeeping
effort. Russia would be excluded until alliance troops were firmly
ensconced in their various sectors. Eventually the Russians would
be permitted entry, in limited numbers, ``folded in'' under NATO
command and control. They would not have their own sector.
</P>
<P>
   Nor would they have a voice in controlling the Pristina airport,
an essential entry point in a landlocked country with a degraded
infrastructure. Moscow would have had no independent voice in
NATO's governance of Kosovo. If Russia wanted to send in additional
troops, it would have to secure permission from NATO.
</P>
<P>
   Thus the Russian dash into Pristina to establish their presence,
to challenge NATO dominance, and to provide a safe haven for the
Serb minority.
</P>
<P>
   Washington may proclaim the myth that NATO bombing alone made
Milosevic desperate to get a peace treaty. But after 78 days, was
Milosevic all that desperate? He is still the ruler of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   NATO did not win this war militarily. Rather, this war ended in
a negotiated settlement. Ultimately, it was not NATO bombing nor
hollow threats of land warfare, nor fear of war crime indictments
that brought about peace. NATO is in Kosovo today because of
Russia's good offices.
</P>
<P>
   Had it not been for Russian participation, there would be no
peace treaty, we would be still bombing Belgrade, and the Americans
and the British would be gearing up for an unpopular ground war
that would begin as winter sets in.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Germany, Italy, and certainly Greece would be
distancing themselves from the conflict. Russia's diplomacy
prevented catastrophe, not merely for the Serbs, but for the
Balkans and NATO.
</P>
<P>
   Now is not the time to challenge the Russians in Kosovo. The
situation is far too polarized and dangerous and NATO needs all the
help it can get.
</P>
<P>
   Russian engagement in peacekeeping will help dispel anti-NATO
suspicions and allay Serbian concerns. Ethnic hatreds are at a
boiling point. The Russians can help ease the pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Unless we want to start the Cold War all over again, with the
fault line running through the Balkans, Russia must be incorporated
into the effort as an equal partner.
</P>
<P>
   Russia is still a potential threat to American security, as
Serbia never was nor can be. It would be unwise to forget that the
Kremlin still has nuclear weapons and missile systems against which
the United States has no defense.
</P>
<P>
   Russia is, in fact, the essential ally that can provide
credibility.
</P>
<P>
   NATO, after its bombing campaign, is perceived as having a bias
against the Serbs. True, the bulk of Yugoslav troops have
withdrawn, but neither side has been disarmed. Of all things, the
allies must avoid a protracted guerrilla war in Kosovo with Serb
paramilitaries on one side, the Kosovar Albanians on the other and
peacekeeping forces in the middle.
</P>
<P>
   Russia, as an integral part of the allied force, just might
provide the necessary balance.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Alex A. Vardamis, a retired colonel, is the former director for
European studies at the Army War College in Carlisle, Pa.)
</P>
</TEXT>
