<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LYNCH-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIGGER WORRIES THAN BURNING FLAGS 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN LYNCH  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ It was a good question, an excellent one to deal
with, actually, just after Flag Day.
</P>
<P>
   The guy who'd called me said his name was Joe. ``What I want to
know,'' he was saying, ``is how this flag desecration amendment is
going to work. What if the thing I burn isn't really a flag? What
if it's, say, a tablecloth with the image of the flag on it? What
if it's a towel with the flag printed on it?
</P>
<P>
   ``What I'm getting at,'' Joe was saying, ``is whether I can get
arrested if I burn an old flag _ say, one with 48 stars instead of
50? If it's not an official flag any more, can they throw me in
jail for that?''
</P>
<P>
   I asked him, do you plan to burn any flags anytime soon? If so,
please call me first so I can watch you do it. And then punch you
right in the mouth.
</P>
<P>
   No, Joe said, he would never burn a flag. He was in the service.
He'd served under that flag. He just was unclear on how the
flag-burning amendment would work.
</P>
<P>
   He also wasn't all that crazy about it, either. Why do we need a
thing like this, he wanted to know?
</P>
<P>
   I explained to him that the American Legion is pushing the
flag-desecration amendment to the U.S. Constitution in a big way.
The courts have been pretty clear that burning a flag is protected
activity. It's free speech under the meaning of the First
Amendment. But, according to the polls, four in five Americans want
flag desecration treated differently, so Congress probably will go
along.
</P>
<P>
   You can expect this thing to pass and to go out to the state
legislatures for ratification. Rep. John Sweeney, R-N.Y., is one of
the sponsors of this thing. The amendment reads, ``The Congress
shall have the power to prohibit the physical desecration of the
flag of the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   I pointed out to Sweeney's people that the amendment's wording
does nothing to clear up questions like the ones Joe had asked.
</P>
<P>
   Nope, they agreed, it doesn't. All this does is give Congress
the power to pass a law to punish flag desecrators. How that law
would read and how the flag would be defined hasn't been dealt with
yet, much less how the courts would respond to that language and to
the enforcement of the law.
</P>
<P>
   Well, if 80 percent of Americans want to exempt the flag from
free speech considerations _ and if that majority holds up long
enough for the amendment to go through the whole, lengthy, arduous
process _ then fine. So the flag will get special treatment.
</P>
<P>
   But I served under that flag, too, and this does strike me as
much ado about nothing in particular. It's pandering to people who
worry too much about symbolism and too little about real problems
and their potential solutions.
</P>
<P>
   I've seen flags burned. When I was breaking into the news
business, flag-burning was all the rage at anti-war demonstrations.
It's a stupid, silly thing to do. It convinces nobody of the wisdom
and justice of your political position. All it does is annoy most
people.
</P>
<P>
   But, just as the world will continue spinning on its axis if
this thing passes, so, too will the world get along just fine if
some jerk burns a flag and doesn't go to jail for it.
</P>
<P>
   Let's talk about Kosovo, Social Security and youth violence.
</P>
<P>
   You know, stuff that's real.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Lynch is a columnist for the Albany Times Union, P.O. Box
15000, Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
