<DOCNO> NYT19990615.0071 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-15 13:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5901 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-NEW-AZR &LR;      06-15 1012
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-NEW-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW AND NOTABLE BOOKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE STEPHENSON  
 c.1999 Special to The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A survey of recently published books:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; TIMBUKTU &QL; 
 &UR; Paul Auster (Holt, $22)
</P>
<P>
   Auster's new novel is told from the point of view of Mr. Bones,
the canine companion of the dying Willy G. Christmas. Willy is a
homeless poet, a rambling man whose devotion to Mr. Bones is such
that he is determined to find a new home for the dog before he dies
(and goes to Timbuktu, which is what the next world is called; it
is, Willy has told Mr. Bones, an ``oasis of the spirit''). With
that in mind, they have traveled to Baltimore, with the secondary
purpose of finding Willy's old English teacher and entrusting to
her 74 notebooks that Willy has filled with poems, stories, diary
entries and an epic-in-progress. Mr. Bones has been with Willy
since he was a pup, and they are a poignant pair, especially if
you, the reader, are a dog lover. If not, Mr. Bones might seem
rather cloying, a persona built on wishful thinking and canine
caricature (he is devoted, smart, watchful, patient, good-natured
and deeply vulnerable to the loss of his human partner _ everything
we want our dogs to be). And so Mr. Bones' adventures after he
parts ways with Willy are fraught with our intense desire to see
him treated well, to see him not just survive but find a new home
in which he will be loved. If you have the stamina for it, this is
an interesting look at the human race through the eyes of Willy's
best friend. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; LAPHAM'S RULES OF INFLUENCE &QL; 
 &UR; Lewis Lapham (Random House, $19.95)
</P>
<P>
   Here is Lewis Lapham's intellect on display; it is so impressive
that there were moments when we had no idea what he was talking
about, but we pretended we did and that would have made Lapham
proud. He has written a primer, of sorts, on fawning, on
sycophancy, on that widespread strategy identified by two words
that begin with a ``k'' and an ``a'' and end with an almost
inevitable spurt of career advancement. It is Lapham's sad but
funny premise that all of the conviction and backbone have gone out
of the career-building process, that we are a nation of fawners and
flatterers with our success tied to our skill at ``bowing and
smiling in eight or nine different directions, forever turning,
like a compass needle or a weather vane, into the wind of new
money.'' His advice to the ambitious is funny and delightfully
withering. On cliches: ``Make unsparing use of them. The empty word
is the correct word. Contrary to the opinion of snobbish New York
intellectuals, the placid murmur of cliche is always preferable to
sharp insight or strong feeling. Think of waterfalls in the lobbies
of Hyatt hotels. Practice the sound by reading aloud the essays of
Roger Rosenblatt or the editorial page of the Washington Post.'' On
curiosity: ``Too much is a mark of inferior rank. You will be
mistaken for a tourist or a waiter.'' On meetings: ``A good meeting
is one at which nothing happens. . . . Sit erect, second all the
motions, remember everybody's name.'' On lies: ``Always more
welcome than the truth. The word is ugly, but the service never
fails to please.'' Lapham is editor of ``Harper's Magazine,'' and
we think he's witty, handsome and beyond brilliant, oh yes, we
truly do. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; BUSINESS DAD &QL; 
 &UR; Tom Hirschfeld (Little, Brown, $23)
</P>
<P>
   First, the credentials: Hirschfeld is a venture capitalist who
serves on the boards of six corporations and one non-profit
institution, and he was previously assistant to the mayor of New
York City and vice president in corporate finance at Salomon
Brothers. He also is the father of two children. So, does he write
like a businessman, or like a dad? Neither _ he sounds like a
slightly stilted man who is beginning to understand the angst that
women have felt all along as they tried to balance the demands of
family and career. This book _ its subtitle is ``How Good
Businessmen Can Make Great Fathers (and Vice Versa)'' _ is
laughable as Hirschfeld applies terms such as ``transferable
skills,'' ``human capital,'' ``customer support'' and ``power
fathering'' to the home front in an effort to establish common
ground with the office. In the end, it sounds like remedial lessons
in fathering for the corporate simpleton. We're not sure Hirschfeld
gets his message across, but it's interesting to watch him try. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; 250 WAYS TO MAKE AMERICA BETTER &QL; 
 &UR; The editors of ``George'' magazine (Villard, $12.95)
</P>
<P>
   Here's the first problem with this book: There's no index and no
table of contents, and any book that advertises such strange
bedfellows as Sen. John McCain and rapper Ice T should have both.
Furthermore, it contains words of wisdom _ suggestions on how to
make the country a better place _ from 250 Americans (or 249 _ Al
Franken suggests putting mirrored ceilings above airport luggage
carousels, a wise idea only by the standards of chiropractors and
personal injury lawyers), but the biographical information is
limited to one or two words: ``Mollie Katzen, cookbook author.''
``Esther Williams, swimwear executive.'' ``Dan Rather, reporter.''
We've reached the conclusion that ``George'' wants to emphasize the
ideas rather than the celebrities who suggest them, but if that's
the case why ask Connie Stevens (``performer'') in the first place?
Which brings us to the biggest problem here: So many of the ideas
are predictable (improve education, fight teenage pregnancies) or
even mildly embarrassing. Roy Blount Jr.'s paragraph is lazy
nonsense, and fashion designer Todd Oldham pushes vegetarianism
even as he laments his weakness for suede shoes (``I've tried to
rationalize these shoes as being a by-product of other people's
diets, etc., and I know there are cruelty-free options _ but vinyl
shoes are known to rot your toenails off!''). Other contributors
include Garry Wills, Tabitha Soren, Pete Seeger, Dr. Ruth
Westheimer, Helen Gurley Brown, Larry King and Pat Boone. &QL; 
(You can reach correspondent Anne Stephenson at
amstephenson &LR; worldnet.att.net, via e-mail.) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
