<HEADLINE>
AIR FORCE RECRUITS FACE TOUGHER BOOT CAMP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SIG CHRISTENSON  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Reacting to criticism that basic training isn't
tough enough, the Air Force this fall will require its recruits at
Lackland Air Force Base to endure a seven-day test of war-fighting
skills.
</P>
<P>
   The idea behind ``Warrior Week'' is to create an Air Force
``that is more ready to go to a forward-deployed location and live
in an austere environment,'' Lt. Col. Steven Ray said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Similar events have been instituted in the Army, Navy and Marine
Corps in recent years. Lackland is the Air Force's sole site for
basic training of enlisted personnel.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's probably one of the biggest changes to Air Force basic
military training in over 50 years,'' said Ray, commander of the
737th Training Support Squadron at Lackland.
</P>
<P>
   The 33,000 recruits graduating from Lackland's six-week basic
training course each year spend just two days and one night in the
field. Warrior Week will change all that when it begins Oct. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Recruits in their fifth week of basic training will live in
tents. They'll practice target shooting at an M-16 firing range,
complete a 5.8-mile march over hilly terrain, eat MREs (meals ready
to eat) and learn to defend air bases in potentially hostile areas.
</P>
<P>
   Successfully completing Warrior Week is a requirement for
graduation from basic training, Lackland spokeswoman Irene Witt
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Warrior Week will give the airmen a chance to be in a weeklong
deployment situation, rather than the 24-hour one currently
included in BMT,'' Gen. Lloyd W. ``Fig'' Newton said in a recent
address to the 97th Air Mobility Wing at Altus Air Force Base in
Oklahoma. BMT stands for basic military training.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to change the culture, so when these airmen get to
their first duty station after technical school they will already
know the deployment basics,'' added Newton, commander of the Air
Education and Training Command at Randolph Air Force Base in San
Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   Warrior Week was recommended by the Federal Advisory Committee
on Gender-Integrated Training to improve physical training
standards. Defense Secretary William Cohen declined to adopt a
recommendation made by the panel to end mixed-gender basic training
in the Air Force, Army and Navy.
</P>
<P>
   But the Air Force and other services already had moved to
toughen training even before the commission's report was issued in
December 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The Marines instituted ``the Crucible'' in 1996. The Navy's
variation of the concept is called ``battle stations.'' The Army
includes a four-day field exercise dubbed ``Victory Forge'' that
began two years ago at Fort Jackson, S.C., the service's largest
basic training facility.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
