<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRESIDIO-LUCAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`STAR WARS' CREATOR PLANS HIGH-TECH CAMPUS AT OLD ARMY BASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYCHE HENDRICKS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ ``Star Wars'' director George Lucas has won
approval to transform 23 acres inside the Presidio into a grassy
campus for more than 2,000 technical wizards of the Lucasfilm
empire.
</P>
<P>
   The Presidio Trust announced Monday that after a rigorous
eight-month selection process, the Lucas plan for the new Presidio
National Park had trumped a competing development proposal.
</P>
<P>
   The trust's presidentially appointed board of directors said it
would begin exclusive negotiations with Letterman Digital Arts Ltd.
to develop more than 800,000 square feet of office space for
several Lucas enterprises, along with the nonprofit George Lucas
Educational Foundation and new Visual Effects Archive.
</P>
<P>
   The old Letterman Army Hospital would be razed to make way for
the project, which also is to include 15 acres of park-like public
open space.
</P>
<P>
   The Presidio, an active military garrison for more than 200
years before it was turned over to the National Park Service in
1994, covers some 1,400 acres in the northwestern corner of San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon Radley, the president of Lucasfilm, said he believed the
project would ``allow the Presidio to become known not just for the
beauty of its setting and its historical location, but for the
ideas that come from this place.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great opportunity for Northern California to solidify
its position in the world as a global center for the digital age,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Lucas project beat out a rival proposal pitched by
Shorenstein Co. of San Francisco and Interland of San Mateo for a
residential development and office park.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Willie Brown had endorsed the Shorenstein proposal last
month. On Monday, the mayor offered cautious congratulations to
Lucas on ``the opportunity to continue with the exclusive
negotiations.''
</P>
<P>
   The development at the Letterman site is expected to be the cash
cow of the effort to make the former Army base self-sufficient by
2013. If negotiations proceed smoothly, Lucasfilm will sign a land
lease with the Presidio Trust in October and agree to pay at least
$5 million annually.
</P>
<P>
   That would be the single largest contribution to the $36 million
that must be generated yearly by 2013 to cover operating costs of
the national park. The remaining $31 million will come from office
and residential leases elsewhere in the Presidio.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Letterman Digital Arts Center would feature a global
institute of digital learning and a library of digital arts open to
scholars. It would include a 7-acre great lawn with cafes and a
lagoon near the Presidio's Lombard Gate. More than two-thirds of
the total 23 acres will be open space for public use. All 1,500
parking spaces at the site would be underground.
</P>
<P>
   The campus is to house five Lucas companies _ Industrial Light
and Magic, Lucas Arts Entertainment Co., Lucas Learning Ltd., THX
Group, and Lucas Online _ which currently are dispersed in offices
around Marin County. Those companies now employ about 1,600 people,
said Radley, but that could eventually increase to 2,500.
</P>
<P>
   The Lucasfilm headquarters will remain at Skywalker Ranch in
Marin's bucolic Lucas Valley.
</P>
<P>
   In August, 18 developers responded to an initial query about
interest in developing the 23-acre Letterman site.
</P>
<P>
   On Jan. 5, the Trust announced the selection of four
semifinalists to present detailed proposals for the site:
Lucasfilm; Shorenstein/Interland; Walsh Higgins and Co. of Chicago,
which proposed construction of a Marriott Hotel and senior living
center; and LNR Presidio Partners, which proposed a mixed-use
project that included the Goldman Institute on Aging and a Joie de
Vivre Hotel.
</P>
<P>
   The list was narrowed to the two finalists on May 3, although
Presidio Trust Executive Director James Meadows said that should
lease negotiations with the winner fail, the trust could begin
negotiations with any of the semifinalists.
</P>
<P>
   Meadows said Monday that both the Lucas and Shorenstein
proposals were strong, but that the board decided in favor of a
single user rather than a collection of different tenants, and was
swayed by the influence Lucasfilm has had on special-effects
filmmaking.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've totally changed the film industry over the last 10
years almost single-handedly,'' he said. ``The deciding factors
were that we felt the educational outreach, the scientific research
and the cutting-edge technology most closely fit our goals for the
future of the Presidio.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-15-99 1340EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
