<SLUG> BC-BKN-COMMENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THEY'RE THE SPURS OF THE MOMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ We've been so immersed in the improbable story of
the Knicks over these past few weeks that we've had little time to
recognize and salute the team that emerged from the Western
Conference.
</P>
<P>
   This is a first for the San Antonio Spurs; they're in virgin
territory. They also are the first team from the defunct American
Basketball Association to appear in the NBA Finals. They have not
played since June 6, when they finished off a sweep of the Portland
Trail Blazers in the Western Conference finals.
</P>
<P>
   Theirs is an interesting history. They started in Dallas as the
Chaparrals, toiling there for six years (spending one of those
years as the Texas Chaparrals) before moving south to San Antonio
in 1973. They've had such luminaries as Doug Moe, Larry Brown, John
Lucas, Cotton Fitzsimmons, and Jerry Tarkanian as head coaches.
</P>
<P>
   They are the only team to play all of their home games in a
dome, the Alamodome, which opened in 1993 with the expectation that
a football team would soon arrive. It hasn't come, and the Spurs
are now in search of a new home. A ballot initiative will be held
later this year (or possibly in January) for a new arena. If it
fails, the Spurs may have no choice but to leave town.
</P>
<P>
   What else do they have going into Wednesday night's Game 1?
Well, here are some instructive things to know about San Antonio in
its first venture into prime time:
</P>
<P>
   A RING FOR ONE OF JOHN'S GUYS: This championship series will
produce a first: a championship ring for a Georgetown player
coached by John Thompson. We're all familiar with Patrick Ewing's
quixotic quest, but the first Thompson-bred Hoya to claim a title
may well be the Spurs' Jaren Jackson. You would think that
somewhere along the way a much-traveled player such as Reggie
Williams or David Wingate would have gotten a ring. (Actually,
Wingate will get one if the Knicks win; he's on the playoff roster,
although he's injured.) But no. The closest? After Ewing (who lost
in the 1994 Finals), there's Sleepy Floyd, who left the Rockets the
year before they won the first of their two, and Othella
Harrington, who joined them two years after they won the last of
their two.
</P>
<P>
   THE GUARDS: Has there ever been such a motley assemblage of
guards representing a team in the NBA Finals as this Gang of Four?
They have played for a combined 23 NBA teams, five CBA teams, two
from the World Basketball League, one from the United States
Basketball League, as well as teams in Portugal, Argentina, and
Ireland. Two of the four, Jackson and Avery Johnson, weren't
drafted. Starter Mario Elie was a seventh-round pick, and Steve
Kerr, who rarely plays, was a second-rounder. Johnson was cut twice
by the Spurs and also owns the distinction of being cut by the
Nuggets on Christmas Eve in 1990. Jackson has been in the NBA for
parts of nine seasons, the first eight with eight teams.
</P>
<P>
   SEAN ELLIOTT: Back in 1994, when the Rockets were in the NBA
Finals, Robert Horry was asked repeatedly about having been traded
earlier that year, only to have the trade nullified. The guy he was
traded for? Sean Elliott. Elliott, then with Detroit, failed the
physical and the deal was called off. Horry helped the Rockets to
two world titles. Elliott, meanwhile, started his career in San
Antonio (he came the same year as David Robinson) and was traded to
Detroit for Dennis Rodman. He lasted one year there and was sent
back to the Spurs for Billy Curley and a second-rounder. Guess who
made out the best in that trade?
</P>
<P>
   THE BOSTON CONNECTION: There's a slight Boston connection here,
starting with the depressing sight of Tim Duncan, whom M.L. Carr
tried so hard to get, only to see the balls bounce another way. The
Spurs were once coached by Cliff Hagan, whose rights the Celtics
traded to St. Louis for the draft pick that went for Bill Russell.
The Spurs' third-round pick in 1978 was a swift guard from Virginia
Commonwealth named Gerald Henderson. He was the last player cut in
training camp. If he had stuck around, who would have stole James
Worthy's pass in Game 2 of the 1984 Finals? The Spurs have drafted
Dwayne Schintzius, who we think is still on the Celtics, as well as
Boston College's Curley and a fellow named Glen Fine from Harvard
in the 10th round of the 1979 draft. When the Spurs were in the
ABA, among the players they drafted were Jo Jo White, Robert
Parish, Tiny Archibald, Curtis Rowe, and Bill Walton.
</P>
<P>
   THE CHAMPIONSHIP CONNECTION: For a team that has never been here
before, the Spurs have a fair amount of guys who have. They have
two players who can relate Michael Jordan stories until the cows
come home. Kerr, of course, was a member of the Bulls' last three
title teams. Will Perdue was a member of their first three before
being traded to San Antonio for Rodman. Elie won two rings while
playing a big bench role for the Rockets, and Jerome Kersey was a
member of Portland teams that reached the Finals in 1990 and 1992.
Jackson won two championships in the CBA with Wichita Falls and La
Crosse.
</P>
<P>
   IT'S HARD TO MESS UP THE TOP PICK: San Antonio has had the top
pick in the draft twice: the year Robinson was available and the
year Duncan was available. Duh. They are the only players on the
roster who are soup-to-nuts Spurs (and that's a short
entree/dessert in Duncan's case), while Elliott is the only other
player drafted by San Antonio. He went No. 3 in 1989 but, as we've
seen, is one who went away but came back.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
