<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-LEBANESE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEBANESE ALLIED WITH ISRAEL FACE NEW FEAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALIZA MARCUS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   METULLA, Israel _ As far back as he can remember, Simon Abu
Umrah has lived in rhythm with Israel, which for nearly two decades
has been both his occupier and protector in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   Six days a week the 38-year-old resident of the Lebanese town of
Marjayoun gets up before dawn to cross the border in time for his
job as a janitor in Metulla. In the summers, his children receive
passes to come over and splash in a pool that is just a 15-minute
drive away. When someone in his family needs special medical care,
they ask for a permit to visit a hospital in Israel.
</P>
<P>
   In exchange, his family has been a staunch backer of the Israeli
Army, which has occupied south Lebanon since 1985. Three of his
brothers are soldiers in the Israeli-financed militia that battles
Hezbollah guerrillas and two cousins died fighting for the cause.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know Israel better than I know Lebanon; nobody in my family
has even been to Beirut in years,'' said Abu Umrah.
</P>
<P>
   ``But sometimes at night I can't sleep, because I am worried
about the future, about what will happen to us when Israel leaves
Lebanon,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While Israelis clamor for Prime Minister-elect Ehud Barak to
make good on his promise to get Israeli troops out of south Lebanon
within a year, Lebanese who cast their lot with the Jewish state
are wondering what will happen when the soldiers leave, the border
is closed, and they are left alone.
</P>
<P>
   More than 2,000 Lebanese, mostly relatives of soldiers in
Israel's local militia, have the coveted white slip of paper that
allows them to work in Israel, while about 2,500 are soldiers in
what is called the South Lebanon Army.
</P>
<P>
   There are few job opportunities in south Lebanon, ravaged by
years of war, forcing many people to turn to Israel whether they
want to or not. South Lebanon Army soldiers are paid $500 a month
and workers in Israel can earn about $700 a month, a healthy sum of
money in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   But the Lebanese government, which is officially at war with
Israel, views South Lebanon Army soldiers as traitors. People
working in Israel worry that they may not be seen as much better.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are all afraid,'' said Janice, 31, who cleans house in
Metulla for $27 a day. Like all Lebanese workers in Israel, she
must pay 10 percent of her salary to the South Lebanon Army.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Israel leaves Lebanon there could be a big problem for
those of us working here; they will kill us,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The ``they'' she referred to is Hezbollah guerrillas, the
Iranian-backed Shiite Muslim militia trying to oust Israeli forces
from its 9-mile-wide occupation zone in south Lebanon, where about
90,000 people live. Israel set up the zone in 1985 to protect its
northern border from attack.
</P>
<P>
   Some residents of Marjayoun interviewed in Metulla said they
fear that if Israel pulls out its troops and the Lebanese Army does
not take over the area, Hezbollah guerrillas will move in and exact
revenge on the largely Christian-led South Lebanon Army force and
their families.
</P>
<P>
   But pressure is mounting inside Israel for an end to what
critics call the country's Vietnam War.
</P>
<P>
   Since Israeli troops carved out their security zone, 247
soldiers have died, in addition to the 655 killed during Israel's
invasion of Lebanon from 1982 to 1985, when troops went as far as
Beirut. About 500 South Lebanon Army soldiers have been killed
since 1985.
</P>
<P>
   Some Israelis say a unilateral withdrawal is better than no
withdrawal. But without a peace deal with Lebanon _ and its patron
Syria _ Hezbollah guerrillas could move closer to Israel's northern
border and keep up attacks. For Syria, Hezbollah has been a good
way to pressure Israel for return of the Syrian Golan Heights,
occupied by Israel in the 1967 war.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, there are signs that the South Lebanon Army is also
tiring of the fight in south Lebanon, and that Hezbollah is gaining
ground. Earlier this month, South Lebanon Army forces suddenly quit
the Jezzine enclave they had occupied for 14 years just north of
Israel's security zone.
</P>
<P>
   In a possible sign of what Israel could expect if it pulls out
without a deal, the Lebanese government has refused to deploy its
army to the enclave, a move that would have hampered Hezbollah
guerrillas. Beirut has also indicated there would not be any
outright amnesty for South Lebanon Army soldiers who stayed behind
to surrender rather than withdraw.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me and my friends, now we have nothing,'' said a South
Lebanon Army officer who spirited his wife and children out of
Jezzine as the withdrawal took place. The family was hiding in a
cheap hotel in Metulla while they waited for expected help from
Israel.
</P>
<P>
   But some Lebanese may be prepared to reintegrate after an
Israeli withdrawal. Some members of the South Lebanon Army are said
to be playing both sides.
</P>
<P>
   ``If anyone tells you they love Israel, it's not true; they love
the money,'' said a 34-year-old Lebanese woman working in Metulla.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
