<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEE CHANGES BY FIDELITY RAISE QUESTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kurt Kuberek was a typical customer when he bought into
Fidelity's Destiny funds nine years ago, a military man prepared to
invest for the long haul.
</P>
<P>
   The two Destiny funds, an original and a clone, were known for
their onerous upfront sales charges and an arcane contract-style
investment plan that committed shareholders to modest monthly
payments for 15 years or longer.
</P>
<P>
   But they also had George Vanderheiden, one of Fidelity's premier
money managers, directing the investments in both funds and a
performance-based fee arrangement that aligned the company's
interests with those of its customers.
</P>
<P>
   Fast forward to the present: Vanderheiden has struggled with a
conservative investment style in a hot stock market. Both Destiny
funds and their combined $12.9 billion have failed to match their
bogey, the S&AMP;P 500 index, for the last four years running.
Vanderheiden, who took an extended leave to recharge himself last
year, gave up management of the Destiny II fund.
</P>
<P>
   Now Fidelity is asking shareholders to vote down the arrangement
that bases its fees on performance and replace it with a flat
charge. If that change had been in effect last year, Fidelity
reports it would have earned $8.6 million more on Destiny I alone.
</P>
<P>
   Proxies will be counted this week at a fund meeting in Boston.
If it runs true to form for mutual fund meetings, virtually no one
will attend and the proposal will win easy approval. That doesn't
mean everyone is satisfied.
</P>
<P>
   ``The (sales) loads and fees are high by anyone's standards,''
said Kuberek, who has since left the Air Force but continues to
contribute $166.66 per month to his Destiny II account. ``To try to
get more kind of stepped across the line as far as I'm concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   The Destiny proposal has more significance than the shuffling of
a few numbers to the right of a decimal point and none of the
implications are especially flattering.
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity has been a performance-based fee leader in a business
that makes a staggering amount of money, typically at a rate
without regard to how well managers actually perform. Our question:
Is this the beginning of a larger shift at Fidelity?
</P>
<P>
   People familiar with the company say Fidelity first conducted
preliminary market research into the potential reaction of dumping
performance-based fees as far back as 1994, when many of its funds
struggled badly.
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity executives point out they run more than three dozen
funds that are compensated based on performance, including giants
like Magellan and Contrafund. By their account, Fidelity runs more
money on a performance-fee basis than the rest of the mutual fund
business combined. Some relatively new Fidelity funds like
Contrafund II and Small Cap Stock were created with fees that
depend on performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a strong proponent of performance fees,'' said David
Jones, a vice president of FMR Co. ``This doesn't represent any
back-away from performance fees.''
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity said the Destiny proposal was prompted by marketing
complications. A new class of Destiny fund shares, offered for the
first time last month, change the mix of upfront sales charges and
imbedded annual marketing fees that make a consistent calculation
of investment performance difficult.
</P>
<P>
   If nothing else, a change in the fee arrangement at Destiny is a
case of galling bad timing.
</P>
<P>
   The Destiny funds have struggled mostly because Vanderheiden
maintained a relatively conservative portfolio as the stock market
soared in recent years. His stock picks were fine, but the results
were hampered by a big investment in long-term bonds.
</P>
<P>
   Destiny II was turned over to manager Beth Terrana, who has been
outrunning Vanderheiden since then. The basic difference: She
hasn't held herself back with defensive investments. But Destiny II
hasn't been able to keep up with the market, either.
</P>
<P>
   Destiny I hasn't been a disaster _ more like a disappointment.
It fell behind the S&AMP;P 500 by no more than 4.4 percent (1996) and
once by as little as 0.58 percent (1995). But with a sales charge
that can run more than 8 percent, nobody wants to hear about
disappointments and they certainly shouldn't have to read about
disappearing performance fees.
</P>
<P>
   These days, Vanderheiden is ``tilting'' the fund toward value
stocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've used this approach many times during the 19 years that
I've been running the fund,'' Vanderheiden said in Destiny I's most
recent report to shareholders. ``In this case, however, perhaps my
prediction was a bit early. . . . But I still think that value is
the most attractive part of the market.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite his struggle in recent years, few people would recommend
betting against Vanderheiden. But Fidelity would be better off if
it took the same kind of performance risks as the customers it has
already charged so dearly.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
