<HEADLINE>
SUMMER OF FUN IN THE APPLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was in early March when we departed Pennsylvania Station and
grabbed a cab to our hotel to avoid the rain.
</P>
<P>
   Rain? It wasn't raining _ it was snowing. And we didn't realize
it until we started to gaze at St. Patrick's Cathedral well below
our 45th floor room at the New York Palace. Suddenly, we realized
those were snowflakes in front of us, but that they turned to rain
at street level. New York is full of wondrous sights, and those at
street level can be quite different 45 stories above.
</P>
<P>
   In any season, in any weather, New York City can be fun, but
summer is special.
</P>
<P>
   Dining and shopping are two of the more popular things to do, so
check out Restaurant Week June 21-25 when 100 of the top
restaurants in the city offer three-course, prix-fixe meals at
$19.99. If you're in the city Friday (June 18), join in a tasting
of the city's best foods. Restaurants will have tasting portions of
their signature dishes outside their doors, selling for $3 to $5
during lunchtime. From July 1 to Aug. 31, stores on Madison Avenue
and in SoHo are offering special values, especially to those paying
with an American Express card.
</P>
<P>
   From July 1-Sept. 30, more than 50 of the city's museums, art
centers, zoos, and historic sites will be offering one-hour tours
highlighting their best offerings. Music also will be popular this
summer with free performances by the Metropolitan Opera throughout
the five boroughs. The JVC Jazz Festival runs June 14 through June
27, and other concerts are planned. Almost every week there will be
street fairs in various neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   In the museum world, art exhibits range from Cezanne to Van
Gogh, and June 12 the American Museum of Natural History opened the
Gottesman Hall of Plant Earth, which includes frozen ice-core
samples from Greenland, towering sulfide chimneys from the ocean
floor, and life-size casts of rock outcrops from Switzerland.
Everything in the hall is designed to explain our planet's inner
workings.
</P>
<P>
   For information on planning a visit to NYC, call 800-NYC-VISIT
or stop by the new Visitor Information Center at 810 Seventh Ave.
at 53rd Street or log on to www.nycvisit.com or www.
newyork.citysearch.com. With more than 62,000 rooms, there should
be no problem finding accommodations, but the city is very
accommodating and offers assistance with a one-stop hotel rate and
availability line: 800-846-7666.
</P>
<P>
   New York City's hotels all offer special packages, and great
experiences. The New York Palace (800-NY-PALACE) features a weekend
shopping getaway that includes a discount at neighboring Saks Fifth
Avenue along with personal shopping assistance and complimentary
gift wrap. The package begins at $245 a room. The hotel also
features a ``hotel within a hotel'' called The Towers with
luxurious features, including room service from Le Cirque 2000
restaurant (including its legendary creme brulee), which is located
in the Villard House, part of the hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Looking for a touch of the Irish? The Fitzpatrick Grand Central
Hotel at East 44th Street and Lexington Avenue, and the Fitzpatrick
Manhattan Hotel at Lexington and 56th streets, offers Irish
amenities in every room. The Manhattan has 52 suites with separate
living area that have sofa beds for the kids. Rates begin at $199
at the hotels (call 800-367-7701).
</P>
<P>
   The Times Square area's newest luxury hotel is The Premier with
features such as oversized baths, full- length windows, luxurious
beds, and Premier signature champagne Popsicles, alone worth a
visit. The hotel is adjacent to the Millennium Broadway hotel and
the Hudson Theater. Weekend rates are $279 through June 30. Call
212-789-7778.
</P>
<P>
   The Benjamin, 125 East 50th St. on the corner of Lexington
Avenue offers an intimate, boutique-style setting, and the promise
of a better night's sleep than at home. Benjamin guests can choose
from its 11 Sound Sleep Pillow Menu for just the right one to place
your head on. For information, call 888-4-BENJAMIN.
</P>
<P>
   The Holiday Inn Wall Street is the first new hotel in the area
in eight years. The hotel is filled with the latest technology.
Weekend rates begin at $150. Call 212-232-7800.
</P>
<P>
   Or, maybe you're looking for some history. The Roosevelt Hotel,
circa 1924, is celebrating its 75th anniversary with rates
beginning at $175 through Sept. 6. The hotel has been throughly
restored while retaining all the glamour of its past. This is where
Guy Lombardo began welcoming in New Year's Eve.
</P>
<P>
   Two turn-of-the-century hotels that have been refurbished but
offer a taste of old New York are the Herald Square Hotel
(212-279-4017) and the Wolcott Hotel (212-268-2900), both on 31st
Street between Broadway and Fifth Avenue. The hotels offer rates of
about $130 for two.
</P>
<P>
   For a ``Suite Family Value,'' consider Manhattan East Suite
Hotels, nine distinct all-suite properties with rates beginning at
$220 a night through July 31. The package offers separate rooms for
parents and kids, a free guide, and more. Suites offer kitchens
with microwavee. Call 800-ME-SUITE.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere in New York State
</P>
<P>
   The Adirondack Museum in Blue Mountain Lake is featuring
``Rockwell Kent's Adirondack Legacy,'' with rarely exhibited
paintings, drawings, and books. Kent, an outspoken proponent of
leftist causes, became the subject of Senator Joseph McCarthy's
Committee on Un-American Activities, and as a result his work was
shunned in the United States in the '50s.
</P>
<P>
   Saratoga Springs, best known for its thoroughbred racing, which
this year runs July 28 through Labor Day (the biggest race, the
Travers Stakes, is Aug. 28), is also a place famed for its healing
waters, history, and honors: Among recent awards are the American
Heritage's first Great American Place, and the National Trust for
Historic Preservation's designation as a Great American Main
Street. For information, call 800-526-8970.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cruise the Hudson
</P>
<P>
   NY Waterway's ``American Castle'' cruises offer a day trip along
the Hudson River, visiting historic sites such as the Rockefeller
Estate at Kykuit and Lyndhurst, the country's finest Gothic Revival
mansion. The Lyndhurst cruise includes an optional visit to
Sunnyside, the home of Washington Irving. Cruises depart from Pier
78 at West 38th Street on Saturdays, Sundays, and holidays at 10:30
a.m., returning at 6 p.m. The Lyndhusrt cruise is $49 for adults,
$25 for children; the Kykuit cruise is $60 a person. For
information, call NY Waterways at 800-533-3779 or visit
www.nywaterway.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Vermont heritage
</P>
<P>
   The first Vermont Heritage Weekend will be June 19-20.
Thirty-six community historical societies in central and
northeastern Vermont will open their doors for visits, along with
holding walking tours, historic performances, pot-luck meals, and
more. Cabot Creamery is sponsoring the event to mark its 80th
birthday. On June 19 from 10 a.m. to 4 p.m. the Cabot Creamery
Heritage Festival at the Cabot Plant will feature tours,
demonstrations, music, and dancing. For information on the weekend,
call the Central Vermont Chamber of Commerce at 877-229-5941 or
visit www.central-vt.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
