<HEADLINE>
BIG APPLE, MINUS BIG BUCKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD P. CARPENTER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   We've said it before and we'll say it again: New York City
doesn't have to be expensive. Here, from the New York Convention &AMP;
Visitors Bureau, are just some examples of free good stuff:
</P>
<P>
   --With a Big Apple Greeter leading the way, you can see New York
from a New Yorker's point of view. These experienced volunteer
guides share the secrets of their neighborhoods at no charge. But
make an appointment at least 10 days in advance. Call 212-669-8159
or visit www.bigapplegreeter.org.
</P>
<P>
   --Concerts and dance performances are yours to enjoy under big
palm trees at the World Financial Center's Winter Garden, a
handsome glass-enclosed business and shopping complex on Lower
Manhattan's waterfront. Special summer events are held outdoors.
Call 212-945-0505 or visit www.worldfinancialcenter.com.
</P>
<P>
   --You can take in folk paintings, pottery, furniture, quilts,
and other 18th-century decorative arts at the American Museum of
Folk Art, which is free Tuesdays through Sundays until 7:30 p.m.
Call 212-595-9533 or visit www.folkartmuse.org.
</P>
<P>
   --Money, money, money: Watch millions of dollars worth of
commodities change hands at the New York Mercantile Exchange Monday
through Friday from 8:30 a.m. to 3:30 p.m. The exchange's museum is
open 9 to 5. Call 212-299-2499.
</P>
<P>
   --Whether you like classical music, jazz, drama, opera, or
dance, you'll relish the free warm-weather performances in NYC
parks by the New York Philharmonic, City Opera, Shakespeare in the
Park, and many more groups. Call 212-360-3444. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Travel Trivia: For what is New York City's 47th Street best known?
(Answer at end of column.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
In a name: Times Square was originally called Longacre Square.
</P>
<P>
   Quotable: ``He adored New York. . . . He romanticized it all out
of proportion. To him . . . this was still a town that existed in
black and white and pulsated to the great tunes of Gershwin.'' _
Woody Allen in ``Manhattan.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
You're the star: The NBC Experience is a new, interactive,
high-tech attraction at NBC headquarters, 30 Rockefeller Plaza.
Through blue-screen technology (and for a price), you can be
interviewed by Jay Leno, ride Conan O'Brien's desk, or forecast the
weather with Al Roker of ``Today'' _ then take home a tape of these
or other encounters. In addition, you'll find a high-definiton TV
theater, a memorabilia museum, a sweet shop, and lots of
merchandise for sale. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Big mouth: The Statue of Liberty's mouth is three feet wide. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Bubbly treat: Champagne Popsicles are served in the lounge of the
Premier Hotel in Times Square. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Mailbag: We mentioned a report that the Boston University Bridge is
the only one where a boat can sail under a train driving under a
car driving under an airplane. But James L. Woodward of Somerville
writes: ``I can think of two places each in New York and Chicago,
and one place each in London and New Zealand that fit the bill.
Closer to home, bridges over the Kennebec at Bath, Maine, and over
the Piscataqua at Portsmouth/Kittery also are exact matches for
your description. . . . Even if you require that the highway and
railroad bridges must be separate, which they are at BU . . . I
would be very surprised if the situation is unique.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Did you guess it? New York City's 47th Street is best known for its
diamond and jewelry district. The block contains about 2,500
jewelry-related businesses. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
(Send comments and questions to Travel Tidbits, Boston Globe,
Boston, MA 02107. Send e-mail to carpen(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
