<HEADLINE>
REVOLUTION PLUGGING AWAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Walter Zenga has spent the last few months trying to
hermetically seal the Revolution defense. But leaks have been
springing up all over the field lately.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution have surrendered three goals in three of their
last four games, including an exhibition, and only an 89th-minute
equalizer by Edwin Gorter allowed them to survive against the Miami
Fusion Sunday. They will likely need to recover their
earlier-season form to maintain their third-place Eastern
Conference standing when they visit Columbus Wednesday and Tampa
Bay Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were awful at the back,'' central defender Dan Calichman
said. ``I'm glad we came back and we showed great fight. But we've
got to step it up in the back.''
</P>
<P>
   The Fusion presented a dynamic attack, with Colombian Diego
Serna and Brazilian Welton. Midfielder Henry Gutierrez provided
excellent opportunities for them, but Zenga made two spectacular
stops of Serna to keep the Revolution in contention.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution had held Miami to one goal, and Serna had been
scoreless in two previous matches. But they seemed vulnerable to
the Fusion's combination of skill and speed.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are dangerous,'' Calichman said, ``only when we play bad
defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of the Revolution's problems stemmed from injuries and
lineup changes. Mike Burns (hamstring) was playing only his second
complete game since April 24. Richard Goulooze (calf) had not
played a full match since April 24, then likely overextended
himself by playing 90 minutes of a 3-0 exhibition loss to CD Santa
Clara last Thursday. Ted Chronopoulos, the left back starter in 11
games, missed the match to join the US national team. And even
Zenga (strained groin) was off form, miskicking a clearance, which
led to Serna's go-ahead goal in the 87th minute.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last 20 minutes we were tired, but we showed spirit,''
Goulooze said. ``We gave away a couple of goals, but we kept the
faith and I don't think anybody gave up.''
</P>
<P>
   Chronopoulos will return for the Columbus visit. And the left
side will be reinforced by the signing of Chaka Daley, who
performed for the Revolution in exhibitions against the Boston
Bulldogs and Santa Clara.
</P>
<P>
   Daley, a Toronto native who qualifies as a US citizen, can also
play central defense. He moved to Fort Lauderdale at age 16 and
played at Providence College and with the Rhode Island Stingrays,
Worcester Wildfire, and Bulldogs.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution waived Manny Motajo, who had played in two games,
none since May 1 . . . John Harkes (left ankle and Achilles' tendon
strain) is probable for Columbus.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
