<HEADLINE>
HOW TO AVOID A CASE OF TENNIS ELBOW IN YOUR CAREER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAVE MURPHY  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Whatever doesn't kill you only makes you
stronger, a philosopher once said. If you don't understand why, you
should have watched the French Open tennis tournament. It offered
more career advice and inspiration than a dozen seminars.
</P>
<P>
   Such as:
</P>
<P>
   _ The game gets harder as you get older.
</P>
<P>
   The singles champions in Paris, Andre Agassi and Steffi Graf,
are both 29 years old, which is as rare these days as a Silicon
Valley company hiring two 55-year-old computer programmers. We're
in an era in which youth is served _ and age is smashed back in
your face.
</P>
<P>
   Andrei Medvedev clobbered Agassi in the first two sets. In his
youth, Agassi was infamous for crumbling in situations like that;
he would have had to last five sets to win, and the stamina just
wasn't there.
</P>
<P>
   But the 1999 Andre Agassi could compensate. He knew his body
wasn't as fresh as it used to be, so he trained harder. When he
lost the first two sets, he changed tactics, rushing the net more
and forcing Medvedev to hit the ball past him.
</P>
<P>
   Agassi played smart tennis. That is a sentence that couldn't
have been written 10 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Workers run into the same challenges. Studies have shown that
academic intelligence fades somewhat as we get older, but you can
build your street smarts. Learn to write things down instead of
forgetting them. Manage your work time instead of trying to do
everything at once. Solve problems instead of turning them into
losses or tragedies.
</P>
<P>
   _ There are many paths to success.
</P>
<P>
   Venus and Serena Williams both were upset in early round singles
matches. But by the time the French Open was over, they were
champions. They won the women's doubles title.
</P>
<P>
   Mahesh Bhupathi and Leander Paes won in men's doubles, and
Katarina Srebotnik and Piet Norval won in mixed doubles. If you
recognize any of those four names, you're a better tennis fan than
I.
</P>
<P>
   Don't let your ego fool you: Sometimes partners can take you to
a higher level than you could reach on your own. Bill Gates might
have been a mere millionaire without Paul Allen, and God knows what
would have become of Moe without Larry and Curly.
</P>
<P>
   _ Sometimes finishing second is a victory, too.
</P>
<P>
   At age 24, Medvedev was going downhill, ranked No. 100 in the
world. He didn't win the championship, but he certainly wasn't a
loser.
</P>
<P>
   You won't get every job or promotion that you try for, even if
you think you're the best candidate. But if you learn from it, just
as Agassi realized he needed to be in better condition, you'll
increase your chances the next time around.
</P>
<P>
   Figure out why you lost, even if it means asking for a candid
answer. If a prospective employer won't grant you an interview,
it's probably because you aren't qualified, you sent in a sloppy
resume or you didn't network well enough to get an introduction to
someone in power.
</P>
<P>
   If you were interviewed but didn't become a finalist, either you
gave a poor interview or your qualifications were only OK. If you
were a finalist, but didn't get the job, either you gave only an OK
interview or the winner was simply better. It happens.
</P>
<P>
   What can you do to be a stronger candidate six months from now?
</P>
<P>
   _ You don't have to share your every waking thought with the
world.
</P>
<P>
   It's a good thing Martina Hingis has small feet; that way both
of them can fit in her mouth.
</P>
<P>
   Hingis had already alienated enough people with nasty comments
about Amelie Mauresmo, an openly gay French player. Then the
18-year-old went on to say that Graf was too old to win another
major championship.
</P>
<P>
   Those comments pretty well made sure that most of the crowd was
rooting for Graf, and then Hingis began pouting and whining when
things didn't go her way. That just made the crowd root even harder
for Graf.
</P>
<P>
   When you're young and talented, it's easy to become arrogant.
It's also easy for people to resent you, even if you have done
nothing wrong. If you mix brilliance and humility, though, they'll
have one less reason to resent you.
</P>
<P>
   _ The heart is a pretty resilient little muscle. That's from
another philosopher _ either Woody Allen or Edgar Allan Poe.
</P>
<P>
   Graf was the villain a decade or so ago, but only because she
was the brilliant upstart, and crowds like to cheer for the older
heroes, the ones fighting back from injuries and personal setbacks,
those trying for one last afternoon of glory.
</P>
<P>
   Agassi and Graf have spent years drawing on their physical
abilities, but this time the strength came from inside. And when
they won, both of them had tears in their eyes. Sometimes emotions
get stronger, too.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Murphy is the careers editor of the San Francisco
Examiner, P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His e-mail
address is murphy(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-15-99 1350EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990615.0085 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-15 13:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
