<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMEN'S GAME HAS ARRIVED, IN BIG NUMBERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   US women have taken the initiative in expanding the scope of
soccer in recent years. But the pioneers, as in men's soccer, were
the English.
</P>
<P>
   When the Dick Kerr Ladies team began its North American tour
with a game Sept. 24, 1922, in Clifton, N.J., the Englishwomen
expected to be playing against women. Instead, the opposition was
provided by a men's professional team, the Paterson Silk Sox, who
took a 6-3 victory before 5,000 fans at Olympic Park. Six days
later, the Englishwomen managed a 4-4 tie with J&AMP;P Coats, another
men's pro team, before 8,500 in Pawtucket, R.I.
</P>
<P>
   According to US Soccer Federation historian Colin Jose,
``Reports indicate the Ladies played very well but that the men
took it easy on them.''
</P>
<P>
   The Ladies returned home after a few more games, and little was
heard from women's soccer for nearly 70 years. But since the first
international matches were organized in the 1980s, the game's
popularity has grown rapidly. Today there are more than 7 million
registered female players in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Those players and their families will compose a high percentage
of the crowds at the Women's World Cup, which begins Friday. More
than 450,000 tickets have been sold for the tournament, expected to
be the largest women-only sporting event in history.
</P>
<P>
   ``Foxboro Stadium will have a typical Revolution-type crowd, a
good mixture,'' Revolution general manager Brian O'Donovan said.
``We have sold a lot of group tickets to women's teams and families
who are interested in soccer and play the game, and who have been
following the US women's team.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are definitely more females buying tickets. But people
are also buying tickets who know this is a world-class event. It's
only a few days away, but I don't it has sunk in that this is
happening. That will change once the event starts.''
</P>
<P>
   The US-Denmark opener at Giants Stadium is expected to attract a
crowd of 60,000. Three Foxboro Stadium dates should have a total of
about 100,000 spectators. Defending champion Norway will meet
Russia in a doubleheader also involving Australia and Ghana at
Foxboro Stadium Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Gaining ground? &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The US' 1-0 victory over Argentina in Washington Sunday
confirmed Bruce Arena's winning touch, and how graphically
perceptions and performances can change with a new coach.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, the US was stumbling through the France '98 World
Cup, its image tarnished at best. Now, the team's confidence has
been restored, and it seems capable of achieving results.
</P>
<P>
   But many questions arise from this game:
</P>
<P>
   --Is the US Soccer Federation prepared to capitalize on such
success? There might not be another game of such stature in the US
until next year, leaving the 40,119 in attendance, plus the TV
audience, with a feeling of anticlimax.
</P>
<P>
   --Why is goalkeeper Kasey Keller not more highly valued?
</P>
<P>
   --How can the price of any one Argentinian player _ such as
Killy Gonzalez, Ariel Ortega, Diego Simeone, or Javier Zanetti _
exceed the worth of the entire US national team?
</P>
<P>
   --For a long time, the game in the US was faulted because of low
skill levels and tactical naivete. Those gaps are being closed.
Plus, some of the best athletes in the US are playing soccer and
advancing to national team levels.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the MLS has to figure out how to raise the worth of those
players. Someone is defintely missing an opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Paying a price &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The best indication of the inflation of player prices was
Inter's $48 million purchase of Christian Vieri from Lazio. The
strongest criticisms of the transfer came from L'Osservatore
Romano, the newspaper of the Vatican, and German media.
</P>
<P>
   Inter's ``patron,'' Massimo Moratti, was placed in an
uncomfortable situation when questioned about the transfer just
before he made a donation worth about $200,000 to Emergency, an
organization dedicated to land mine victims. The donation,
designated for construction of a hospital in Afghanistan, was
inspired by Moratti's wife, Milly, who is president of Emergency.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am aware that the money we have given to Emergency is
nothing compared to the millions for Vieri, and I feel
embarrassed,'' Moratti said. ``I understand that these figures are
worrisome. They worry me also. I feel guilty when talking about so
many millions. But when you are the head of a business like Inter,
you assume the responsibility to offer a quality product. These
figures that are circulating for Vieri are normal in the industrial
world, but they are not so well-known, while in soccer, everything
is public.''
</P>
<P>
   German newspapers predicted that the Italians' inflated prices
would lead to a catastrophe, and DFB president Egidius Braun called
for a salary cap. But the climate favors escalation over austerity.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not possible to limit spending, mainly because laws and
regulations give freedom to the clubs,'' Bayern Munich vice
president Karl Heinz Rumenigge said. ``And even if there is a new,
more restrictive law, there will be ways to hide things, and the
players will want to be paid under the table.''
</P>
<P>
   In the US, sports entities usually have been able to discover
new revenue streams, though often by compromising the integrity of
the game. Soccer also will find those sources. The key will be to
adjust while retaining the essence of the sport.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
