<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEVINGSTON-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE CASE OF THE LEGAL LEVIATHANS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN LEVENGSTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I invited my stockbroker, T. Rex, to lunch to wish him a happy
extinction.
</P>
<P>
   We'd had a terrific business relationship for, what, a hundred
million years or so, but in the past few weeks things had really
changed and now it was time for me to say good-bye. I was going on
line.
</P>
<P>
   The final straw was that Merrill Lynch bombshell. Now the
nation's largest full-service securities firm was offering Internet
trading. All the big brokerage houses were jumping on the
bandwagon. Paine Webber announced two days after Merrill that would
it would provide on-line trading services. Prudential Securities
said in May that it would let its customers trade on line. They're
all chasing after the established Internet trading firms, such as
Charles Schwab and ETrade.
</P>
<P>
   At lunch, T. Rex looked glum as he chomped with his big,
serrated teeth on a plate of turtles and lizards. His little arms
dangled helplessly in front of him.
</P>
<P>
   In a switch that was possible only in our modern, high-tech
world, my broker was now the one asking me for advice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can it really be,'' he was crying into his ginko cocktail,
``that I'm going the way of the elevator operator and the
milkman?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Face it, pal,'' I said gently, ``you're history.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But you need me,'' T. Rex insisted.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're stuck in the Cretaceous, old man,'' I told him.
</P>
<P>
   ''But I've got expertise _ experience!''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all experts now, T. Rex,'' I informed him, ``and after a
week or two at anything who isn't experienced?''
</P>
<P>
   With his small, vacant eyes, Rex looked confused and haunted.
</P>
<P>
   I tried to be sympathetic. ``Look, Rex,'' I said, ``I've enjoyed
our eons together. It'll be tough for me, too. I don't know what
I'll do with all the money I save not paying your commissions.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was nothing if not honest and wise,'' my broker said.
</P>
<P>
   ``A fine pitch for another era,'' I answered. ``What did you
charge me for your honesty and wisdom?''
</P>
<P>
   ``A hundred and fifty bucks a trade is fair,'' Rex offered.
``Why? What're you doing now?''
</P>
<P>
   ``$14.95.''
</P>
<P>
   T. Rex nearly choked on a Compsognathus egg. ``How am I supposed
to survive that?'' he growled.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you know anything about evolution?'' I asked.
</P>
<P>
   Rex shook his giant head.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a self-service world now,'' I explained, ``But you, T.
Rex, are still standing there with your stubby little claw out
forever expecting a cut. Get into another line of work, or I'm
afraid I'll be dusting you off one day in some fossil bed.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You get what you pay for!'' Rex came back combatively. ``Sure,
you can trade on line for a few bucks but . . .but . . .'' He
searched for the right word, but his face went blank. He blinked
his dull eyes and I wondered whether anything was going on inside
that famously tiny brain of his.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've had a good run,'' I told him. ``Once you're long dead,
everyone will be fascinated by you. Kids will memorize every detail
of your life. They'll make movies about you and play you up like
you're a terrible predator, and try to scare everyone with how
ferocious you were. But I know better, pal. I know you were never
anything but a big, lumbering, empty-headed pitchman.''
</P>
<P>
   T. Rex didn't hear a word. He was mumbling, ``This on-line
thing, it came out of nowhere like a humungus meteorite.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Levingston can be reached at
dollarsnonsense(at)hotmail.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
