<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-HOMOPHOBIC-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON WALL STREET, GAYS KEEP A LOW PROIFLE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRED KAPLAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A secret society haunts Wall Street. By day, its
members lie low, taking pains to fit in with the other brokers and
bond traders, waiting until night falls, when they can gather with
their own and, finally, be themselves.
</P>
<P>
   They are the homosexuals of big finance, and, despite New York
City's reputation as a mecca for gay culture and tolerance, most of
them stay in the closet _ while on the job, anyway _ as if they
worked in a small Midwestern town in the 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I were to proclaim myself gay,'' said one officer in a
major New York bank, who asked not to be identified, ``I would
definitely be fired.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Industrywide, Wall Street is the most homophobic place you can
work in this city,'' said a securities analyst at a major financial
company.
</P>
<P>
   This aspect of the culture seeped to the surface recently when
Christian L. Curry, a 25-year-old securities analyst, filed a
lawsuit against his former employer, Morgan Stanley Dean Witter &AMP;
Co.
</P>
<P>
   Curry is demanding an attention-grabbing $1.35 billion, charging
that Morgan Stanley's executives fired him for reasons of
discrimination, partly because he is black, partly because they
thought he was gay. He was fired days after nude photos of him
appeared in a gay pornography magazine.
</P>
<P>
   The Curry case is complicated. Morgan Stanley insists that Curry
was fired for padding his expense account and also contends that he
was caught fabricating racist e-mail on the firm's computer system
to back up his lawsuit. In a further twist, two of the firm's legal
executives were recently forced to resign for paying $10,000 to an
informant who supposedly trapped Curry in his e-mail scam.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever really happened and however the suit turns out, few
gays in the industry have trouble believing that someone on the
Street could get fired for suspicions of being gay.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not at all surprising,'' said Jennifer Hatch, co-owner of
Christopher Street Financial. The incidence of such firings, she
added, is ``common enough to keep people very much in the closet.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a rough-and-tumble world, where steely nerves, hard drive,
and skyscraper stacks of money are seen as the markers of
manliness. Those whose lifestyles defy the equation often find
themselves hounded out the door.
</P>
<P>
   Hatch's company, named after the most famously gay street in
Manhattan's West Village, is the city's only all-gay financial
firm. A former ``high-heeled bond trader'' at J. P. Morgan and Bear
Stearns, Hatch bought Christopher Street from the estate of the
original owner, who died of AIDS two years ago, because she was
weary of role-playing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wall Street is a bunch of really insecure people, playing for
very, very high stakes, who don't tolerate any differences,'' she
said. ``I mean, this is a place where everybody's pinstripes are
the same width.''
</P>
<P>
   Hatch, 38, came to Wall Street right out of college. ``I
remember thinking it was crazy that I'd chosen this field,'' she
said. ``I thought I was the only gay person on Wall Street.''
</P>
<P>
   Through reading the gay press, she learned of the New York
Bankers Group, a social and networking organization for gays and
lesbians in the city's financial industry. Even today, the group
remains as low-key as its moniker. It is not listed in the phone
book. Its president, a bank executive, does not want his name to
appear in print.
</P>
<P>
   About 300 people belong to the group. They meet regularly at
restaurants, wine tastings, gallery openings, or at each other's
homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having a group like this, knowing you're not the only one,''
Hatch said, ``it makes things easier.''
</P>
<P>
   But, many would add, not a lot easier.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Daniels, 36, was all set to be named a vice president at the
North American branch of Dresdner Bank. ``My name was up on the
door; the business cards were printed up,'' he recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in April 1997, he announced he was gay. Within days, he
was fired. The firm said he was let go because of ``downsizing.''
</P>
<P>
   Employees of securities firms are required to sign a form _
known as the U-4 agreement _ when they join, pledging to settle any
dispute with their employer through an arbitration committee, not
through the courts.
</P>
<P>
   Suzanne Goldberg _ head of Lambda Legal Defense, a gay
civil-liberties organization _ objects to the arbitration rule,
pointing out that lawsuits have been responsible for breaking down
racial and sexual discrimination across many realms of American
social and business life.
</P>
<P>
   ``The U-4 clause,'' she said, ``is what has allowed
discrimination to continue to flourish on Wall Street.''
</P>
<P>
   Daniels found a way around this obstacle. He sued Dresdner's
parent company _ which is based in Germany, where securities law
contains nothing like a U-4 clause _ and asked for $77 million in
damages.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, with the agreement of all parties, the federal judge
handling the case turned it over to arbitration, ruling that
Daniels was technically not an employee of the parent company.
</P>
<P>
   Daniels's lawyer, Madeline Bryer, is hopeful of winning anyway.
While the case was still facing federal trial, she conducted a
formal discovery process, taking depositions and amassing evidence,
which are generally not allowed in arbitration cases.
</P>
<P>
   Many are watching the Daniels case as a possible
precedent-setter, as well as Curry's case against Morgan Stanley,
though with mixed feelings because of its more perplexing nature.
</P>
<P>
   Still, no one expects dramatic changes overnight.
</P>
<P>
   The bank officer who said he worries about being fired if he
came out of the closet has reason for his fears. In the last Wall
Street firm where he worked, he told his boss he was gay not long
ago, in order to complain about harassment from a colleague. ``That
was on a Friday,'' he recalled. ``On Monday, I was fired.''
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street generally is ``a macho culture,'' he went on. ``Most
of the executives are married men, not from Manhattan, who want to
talk about sports, their wives, their kids. Homophobic jokes are
unbelievably commonplace.''
</P>
<P>
   Hatch observed that some older executives _ who long ago rose to
the top, made big bucks for their firms, and stashed away enough
money for themselves _ do feel secure enough to come out or at
least to adopt a blithe indifference to what others might think.
</P>
<P>
   But for the still-rising young star, the coast is far from
clear.
</P>
<P>
   One gay securities analyst, who asked not to be identified, is
worried that some of his supervisors suspect he is gay. ``They look
at me funny at meetings,'' he said. ``I think I make them insecure,
as if they worry that I might be looking at their crotches.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``It's a job where you don't want to take any chances.
There's probably not another profession where you can make so much
money, so quickly. It's very competitive. People will use anything
against you. I'm always very worried about the security of my job.
Being gay is just an added weight. The paranoia goes very deep.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-15-99 1355EDT &QL; 
