<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SILVER CHARM SIMPLY RAN OUT OF STEAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON INDRISANO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Simply put, Silver Charm went sour. It happens to many
thoroughbreds; they reach the point where they don't want to race
anymore. Some get ``smart'' and come to realize, after suffering
various nicks and bruises, that it hurts when they extend
themselves, so they stop doing it. Some just lose interest in
competing; they get bored with the game. For the 5-year-old Silver
Charm, who was always a bit quirky and difficult to train, it took
24 starts to throw in the towel.
</P>
<P>
   After Silver Charm ran an uninterested fourth in the $827,250
Stephen Foster Handicap at Churchill Downs Saturday, his fourth
loss in a row, his connections had seen enough. Owners Bob and
Beverly Lewis and trainer Bob Baffert made the decision to retire
the big gray Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Silver Charm became a popular horse after winning the Kentucky
Derby and Preakness in 1997. He also ran well in the Belmont, but
missed the Triple Crown when Touch Gold passed him nearing the wire
to win by 3/4-length. The Lewises and Baffert had been known in
racing circles, but it was Silver Charm that vaulted them into
national prominence.
</P>
<P>
   It's a matter of record that Silver Charm logged a lot of miles.
He made the arduous trip to Dubai twice, winning in '98 and
finishing sixth this year, and raced at tracks all around this
country. That was good for the sport but probably contributed to
Silver Charm's early retirement. He also was bothered, off and on,
with a bleeding problem, and that didn't help.
</P>
<P>
   The last hurrah for Silver Charm came Jan. 10 at Santa Anita,
when he won the San Pasqual. After that, he ran third in the Donn
at Gulfstream, third in the Santa Anita Handicap, then came the
Dubai World Cup and the Foster. A son of Silver Buck, out of a
Poker mare, Silver Charm goes to stud with a record of 24-12-7-2
and earnings of $6,944,369, behind only Skip Away ($9,616,360) and
Cigar ($9,999,815). Not bad for a $35,000 purchase.
</P>
<P>
   ``Retiring Silver Charm was something that's been in my mind for
some time,'' said Bob Lewis. ``He ran a creditable race in the
Stephen Foster, and he came out of it in grand style, but he
certainly didn't show the ability to run with that class of horses
any longer. He doesn't seem to have the late kick he did have, and
he doesn't seem to have the high level of competitive spirit he
showed when he performed so magnificently in the Triple Crown races
and in Dubai.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rather than demean the horse after such a great career, we
feel it's the appropriate time to go on to the next stage in his
life, out in the pasture, serving as a stallion.''
</P>
<P>
   As so often happens in this mercurial sport, the Lewises,
racing's greatest ambassadors, went from the top to the bottom in
less than a month. On May 15, Charismatic, also owned by the
Lewises, won the Preakness after taking the Derby, and, like Silver
Charm before him, had the chance for the Triple Crown, which
carries with it both a page in the record books and a $5 million
bonus. However, Charismatic broke down while finishing third in the
Belmont June 5, and he, too, was retired. Truly, the Lewises took
three strikes, because their Exploit, probably the best of the
3-year-olds and the winter book favorite to win the Derby, was
injured in the San Felipe at Santa Anita March 13, and also was
sent to stud.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Galloping to victory
</P>
<P>
   Victory Gallop, who had run third in Dubai March 28, dominated
the Foster, pulling away through the stretch to win by nearly 6
lengths under Jerry Bailey. It was a dazzling performance by the
4-year-old, who ran 1 1/8 miles in 1:47 1/5, shattering the track
record by one and one-fifth seconds, the equivalent of 6 lengths.
Victory Gallop was 6-5 ($4.60 to win), while Silver Charm was 7-5
with Chris Antley.
</P>
<P>
   The victory proved that a horse based in the United States can
bounce back in a reasonable amount of time from the rigors of the
Dubai trek. Up till now, the record had not been good, as most of
the US steeds had come back knocked out.
</P>
<P>
   A son of Cryptoclearance, Victory Gallop won last year's Belmont
Stakes to deny Real Quiet the Triple Crown. He also ran second in
the Derby, Preakness, Haskell, and Travers, and fourth in the
Breeders' Cup Classic. There is no doubt that Victory Gallop, who
is trained by Elliott Walden, has joined Behrens at the top of the
handicap ranks.
</P>
<P>
   ``He broke alertly, but dropped farther back than I thought he'd
be,'' said Bailey. ``When we got to the far turn, he gave me the
most powerful move around a turn from any horse I've ever been
on.''
</P>
<P>
   Next for Victory Gallop could be the Whitney at Saratoga Aug. 1,
but the big summer goal is the $1 million Pacific Classic at Del
Mar Aug. 29.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A `Stag' party
</P>
<P>
   If there was one horse who could have given Victory Gallop a run
Saturday, it was Running Stag, who was nearly as sensational in
winning the $350,000 Brooklyn Handicap at Belmont.
</P>
<P>
   Most recently second behind Behrens in the MassCap at Suffolk
May 29, Running Stag, an invader from England, stormed through the
lane to tally by more than 7 lengths with Shane Sellers in the
irons. Running Stag covered the 9 furlongs in a rapid 1:46 1/5, but
he was not about to break the track record, which was established
when Secretariat ran 1:45 2/5 in 1973. Running Stag was 7-2,
returning $7.90 to win.
</P>
<P>
   Trainer Philip Mitchell and Sellers switched tactics for the
score. In the MassCap, Running Stag went right to the front; he
came from far back in the Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was just relaxed, and he made a huge move on the turn,''
said Sellers.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell now intends to bring Running Stag back to England.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Material from racetracks was used to compile this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
