<HEADER>
A5953 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-OCEAN-BOS &LR;      06-15 0865
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-OCEAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LINDA GREENLAW'S `OCEAN' MAY LEAVE READERS HUNGRY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE DANIEL  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
THE HUNGRY OCEAN 
A Swordboat Captain's Journey 
By Linda Greenlaw 
Hyperion, 265 pp., $22.95 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Linda Greenlaw sums up the reason for her book ``The Hungry
Ocean'' in the first sentence of the preface: ``I have been fishing
commercially for seventeen years, and up until the summer of 1997
nobody cared. With the publication of Sebastian Junger's `The
Perfect Storm' came attention and opportunity. In general, people
are intrigued with my life as the captain of the Hannah Boden,
sister ship to the Andrea Gail,'' the ship Junger profiled.
</P>
<P>
   My hunch is that the intrigue Greenlaw mentions is largely due
to her gender: She was the first and so far only female commercial
swordfish captain. She has since, inexplicably, retired from the
Hannah Boden helm, according to the book's epilogue, and now fishes
inshore for lobster in the waters surrounding her home on Isle au
Haut, Maine.
</P>
<P>
   Upfront, Greenlaw eschews drawing attention to her womanhood
(``I am a fisherman''), though it comes out unavoidably in many
ways during the book. Her gender certainly shouldn't be the book's
sole subject, but one would think it has played a part in her
working life _ or at least in getting a book contract. But she
says, ``I never anticipated problems stemming from being female,
and never encountered any. . . . People, women in particular, are
generally disappointed when they learn that I have not suffered
unduly from being the only woman in what they perceive to be a
man's world.'' Perceive? She's the only woman mentioned in the
book.
</P>
<P>
   Feminist theory aside, ``The Hungry Ocean'' is a so-so read.
Maybe it's like fishing: There's a lot of routine, chores, minutiae
_ and now and then you get a bite. Greenlaw doles out only a few of
those nibbles, but has spared no detail about a particular 30-day
cruise with a five-man crew out of Gloucester in late August 1992.
I liked the idea of going on one trip with the gang, but was
disappointed that there was scant character development or action
and that much of the writing is cliched. Poetic phrases pop up here
and there, but ``The Hungry Ocean'' has none of the thrills or
chills of ``The Perfect Storm.'' Its drama is instead found in the
little things _ finding fish, jockeying for position and
aggressively holding a 40-mile-long piece of the sea, keeping
sharks from ruining equipment, trying to maintain an orderly and
energetic crew, and praying that the price of fish will be decent
when it's time to cash in the catch.
</P>
<P>
   A friend tells me that her lobsterman brother-in-law and his
fisherman friends love this book, and I'm not surprised. It really
gets inside their jobs (not so much their lives). Problem is, those
jobs aren't always very exciting. Fishing can be dangerous, and
it's unbelievably difficult work, but it can also be quite tedious.
If, however, you're interested in learning about longlining, how
dopplers and down temps work, the latest in mapping technology, and
all the other technicalities, Greenlaw will teach you tons. And I
certainly have a greater appreciation for the swordfish on my
dinner plate.
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Perfect Storm'' Junger wrote of Greenlaw with
admiration, for she is a top-notch captain. She tells us that
``getting to the top of the heap was a painful journey,'' but never
explains how.
</P>
<P>
   She treats the crew members, who call her ``Ma'' (no attention
to her gender there, huh?), mostly with respect. They often comment
to her, ``not bad for a girl.'' There's a disturbing scene in which
crew member Kenny blurts out the boat's position and amazing daily
catch (which Greenlaw had publicly downplayed) over the radio,
thereby cluing in the competition. She calls him a moron, among
other things, and berates him nonstop for a day. Enough already.
Then she goes on to say: ``I thought, if I were a man, I would be
punching him right square in the nose for his stupidity.'' But
she's a fisherman, isn't she?
</P>
<P>
   Part of her reaction to that event was based on the guilt she
felt about telling fellow fishermen that the Hannah Boden's catch
was low when in fact it was record-breaking. ``I wasn't sure what
made me feel worse, the certainty that we would now have to share
this productive piece of water with the competition or having been
exposed as a liar. . . . As mad as I was at Kenny, I was just as
ashamed of myself for lying in the first place.'' She then spends
several pages reflecting on the ethics of the situation. Again,
this is just a hunch, but I don't think a man would do that.
</P>
<P>
   She alludes to matters of the heart, and even to abstinence, but
isn't forthcoming on the subject. Considering that she was the only
female aboard her fishing vessels for a month at a time, one can't
help but wonder if any romances blossomed, or if sexual tension
ever interfered with work.
</P>
<P>
   Greenlaw does, however, share her passion for the sea. And that
is really what makes her story worthwhile. It is genuine and, in
some ways, a love story: a lifelong love of the sea and the
seafaring life.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
