<HEADER>
A5956 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LANGUAGE-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      06-15 0760
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANGUAGE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BLOW TO POETIC POPPIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAN FREEMAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A recent Sunday's perfect weather was a double blessing: It
meant readers were too busy enjoying life to notice my misquotation
of a famous line of poetry. (A pessimist might wonder if the real
reason is that nobody knows ``In Flanders Fields'' at all anymore,
but I prefer to blame, or credit, the June sunshine.)
</P>
<P>
   At any rate, the exception was Willie Lockeretz of Brookline,
Mass., who shot off an e-mail before I was even conscious on Sunday
morning. He agreed that memorizing poems beats memorizing spelling
words, but, he chided, the poetry has to be memorized accurately:
`` `In Flanders fields the poppies blow' (not grow).''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed: ``In Flanders fields the poppies blow/ Between the
crosses, row on row,'' the World War I poem begins. The poppies do
``grow'' eventually, but not till the 14th of 15 lines. A shocking
gaffe, one week after Memorial Day, and the more so because I was
looking at the text, not relying on memory. It was a moment of
brain burnout, pure and simple.
</P>
<P>
   That circuit must have been shorting out two weeks earlier, too,
when I wondered in this space why crispy would be (even
momentarily) a slang word for badly hung over. Elementary, my dear,
said readers: Fried is slang for drunk (or stoned), and it takes
only a bit more cooking to get to crispy. Calvin Saxton of
Willington, Conn., pointed to those sizzling eggs in the TV public
service ads: ``This is your brain. This is your brain on drugs.''
</P>
<P>
   Crispy may have been a flash in the pan, in the
substance-abuse-slang department, but fried is practically a
classic: Under ``Intoxication,'' the Oxford University Press slang
dictionary quotes Noel Coward, in 1923, writing ``After a gay
reunion party . . . I retired to be slightly fried, blissfully
happy.'' This was apparently only the latest in a series of
alcoholic synonyms accumulating as the '20s roared along:
``Princeton has completed the idiom of the cuisine by adding fried
to boiled and stewed,'' according to a 1926 source.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, fried has worked hard in other realms of slang _ to
mean angry (or steamed), for instance, and as a synonym for
electrocuted. It can still refer to alcohol's effects, but any kind
of drug is covered: French fries, mere potatoes in Noel Coward's
partying days, are also a kind of crack cocaine. More benignly,
though, fried now seems to be poaching on the territory of burned
out. For people too busy to stay out late, ``my brain is fried'' is
more likely to suggest overwork than overindulgence.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Remember the alamode &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Out of the frying pan for a brief vacation, I was at lunch with
friends in California last month when we asked for a serving of
berry pie to share. It was delicious, and so was the new verb that
came with it: ``Would you like to alamode that?'' asked the waiter.
</P>
<P>
   It's tempting to blame it on California, but let's be fair: All
over the country, menus have ``beef with au jus'' and ``today's
special du jour,'' along with waiterly transgressions of all sorts.
It could happen here.
</P>
<P>
   And in the waiter's defense, English has played fast and loose
with a la mode for centuries. We stole it in the 17th century,
freely throwing it around as adverb, adjective, and noun, and
writing it in various ways, says the Oxford English Dictionary. It
was alamode and all-a-mode and a-la-mode _ but at least it still
meant ``in the fashion.'' In America, we gave it a whole new
meaning _ ``with ice cream'' _ and pretty much dropped the old one.
</P>
<P>
   But even this had happened before. Alamode Beef, an 18th-century
dish made of boiled larded beef scraps, was once a menu standard;
as recently as 1992, chef Pierre Franey wrote about this close
relative of the New England boiled dinner.
</P>
<P>
   No, it's never been a verb before _ as far as we know. But some
anonymous cook might have turned to her spouse, one day in 1799,
and asked, ``Shall we alamode the leftovers?'' English has always
been free with its parts of speech _ empty and sober up are also
adjective-to-verb conversions _ and if this one had caught on two
centuries ago, we wouldn't be batting an eye at it now.
</P>
<P>
   So the next time a waiter asks ``Shall I alamode that?'' I'm not
going to fuss; instead, I'll give thanks that he's not offering
boiled beef, and just say yes.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (What's the word? Write or e-mail yours to Jan Freeman at The
Boston Globe, Boston, MA 02107-2378; freeman(at)globe.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
