<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-MARKETS (Tokyo) _ Why Japan needs a new stock trading
system. By Stephanie Strom.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ At midday, the Dow industrial average was up
96 points, or 0.9 percent, and the Nasdaq index was up 26 points,
or 1.1 percent. Elsewhere, prices were up 0.5 percent in Tokyo and
were down 0.5 percent in Hong Kong. They rose 1 percent in
Frankfurt, gained 0.3 percent in London, rose 1 percent in Brazil
and jumped 2.1 percent in Mexico. On the American debt market, the
long bond was up 12/32 point, with the yield at 6.06 percent.
</P>
<P>
   COKE-EUROPE (Undated) _ The ban on Coca-Cola products expands
from Belgium to France and Luxembourg. By Constance L. Hays.
</P>
<P>
   OCEAN-CASINOS (Undated) _ Ocean Fund International, which says
it runs the world's largest Internet sex site, claims it has
offered $3.6 billion in cash to buy the eight Caesars Palace
casinos that Starwood Hotels and Resorts Worldwide Inc. is selling
to Park Place Entertainment. But Starwood says it has never heard
of the company. By Edwin McDowell.
</P>
<P>
   ORACLE-EARNINGS (San Francisco) _ Oracle is expected to post
fourth-quarter earnings of 32 cents a share. By Lawrence M. Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS-TRAVEL (Undated) _ The business travel column.
</P>
<P>
   KOREA-ECON (Tokyo) _ Tiger Management LLC, the hedge fund group
operated by Julian Robertson, has objected to plans by the SK
Telecom Co. to issue additional shares and is calling for a special
shareholders' meeting on the matter. The rights offering is being
construed as yet another sign that the momentum of South Korea's
economic reform is slowing as the country regains economic
strength.
</P>
<P>
   HONGKONG-TELEDOM (Hong Kong) _ In another triumph of globalism
over localism, Hong Kong's local telephone company, Hong Kong
Telecommunications Ltd., will change its name to Cable and Wireless
HKT to tighten its ties with its London-based parent, Cable and
Wireless PLC. Hong Kong Telecom said the new name was intended to
convey the company's broader ambitions. But to some people here,
the move is more discouraging evidence that Hong Kong is losing its
brand-name prestige as a commercial center. Last November, the
parent of Hong Kong Shanghai Bank announced plans to drop ``Hong
Kong'' from its flagship bank in favor of the abbreviation HSBC. By
Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   TIME-APPOINT (Undated) _ Time Warner said its chief financial
officer, Richard Bressler, would take a new job heading the
company's expansion on the Internet. By Geraldine Fabrikant.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The daily Marketplace column.
