<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-15 14:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5963 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN16-CO     06-15 0651
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TALL TALES &AMP; SHORT STORIES: To change one mind, change a hundred
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Nothing worse than being broke in the big city. And
I'm as good as broke if I can't break this $100 bill.
</P>
<P>
   That's all I have in my wallet. I need to take a taxi back to my
hotel, about a $5 ride. No way I can ask a cabbie to make change
for a bill that size.
</P>
<P>
   So here I am, standing in a long line, a stranger in a strange
bank, hoping I can trade in this hundred for some twenties and
tens. But I have my doubts.
</P>
<P>
   I just know what the teller is going to do. I'll hand him the
bill and, in the nicest possible way, ask for change.
</P>
<P>
   He'll look at the hundred for a long moment, almost as if he's
never seen one before, and then he'll look at me, and for sure he's
never seen me before. I know what he's going to ask.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you have an account with us?''
</P>
<P>
   Well, no, I'm from out of town, just visiting here for a week or
so. But the hundred is all I have with me and I need to get a cab
back to my hotel, but you know how cab drivers are _ I'll smile and
shrug _ so I was hoping that you could ...
</P>
<P>
   He won't even let me finish, shoving the bill through the window
at me, and not even looking at me _ already looking past me at the
next person in line _ and saying what I know he'll say.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sorry. You have to have an account here to do business here.''
</P>
<P>
   And I know what I'm going to do. I'm going to get angry. For a
fact, I'm already getting angry just thinking about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look,'' I'll say, poking the bill back through the window.
``This is no big deal for you, but it'll help me out. Like I said,
I'm a visitor, and all I need is some change. Surely, breaking a
hundred isn't going to break you, huh?''
</P>
<P>
   I'm smiling, but my voice has an edge to it, and by now I'm
leaning into the window.
</P>
<P>
   But in that same tired, couldn't-care-less kind of voice that
people in the big city use, I can hear him repeating himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sorry. You have to have an account here to do business here.''
</P>
<P>
   That's when I'll explode.
</P>
<P>
   ``What kind of bank is that?'' I'll demand, my voice rising.
``All I'm asking is some lousy change for a lousy $100 bill! For
cripes sake, as one human being to another, help me out!''
</P>
<P>
   Now I've got his attention. Now he's looking at me, his eyes
widening, and so is everyone else in the bank, including the
security guard who is beginning to move in my direction. I don't
care. There's just so much a man can put up with.
</P>
<P>
   That's what I'm telling the rest of the people in line.
</P>
<P>
   ``How about you?'' I'm asking the poor, frightened lady behind
me, all but shouting. ``You've got an account here, haven't you?
Well, haven't you?!''
</P>
<P>
   She bites her lip and nods.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here then,'' I say, trying to push the $100 bill into her
hand. ``You get change for me. Is that asking too much. Is it,
huh?!''
</P>
<P>
   She pulls away, so I turn my attention to the rest of the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody? Won't anybody help out? Tell you what, then! Five
bucks. Get me change for the hundred and I'll give you $5. Nobody?
Then how about $10 ...''
</P>
<P>
   At this point I was interrupted by a voice, this one for real.
</P>
<P>
   ``May I help you, sir?'' said the teller, and I realized that
I'd finally moved up to the window.
</P>
<P>
   ``Change for a hundred?'' I snarled.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tens and twenties OK?'' he said, already counting them out.
</P>
<P>
   I nodded. He smiled. I took my money and moved away from the
window.
</P>
<P>
   Nice bank. If I lived here, I think I'd open an account with
them.
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin Daily News,
is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. Mailing address is P.O. Box
151108, Lufkin, Texas, 75915; e-mail, jmurray(at)lcc.net; website,
www.geocities.com/SoHo/Bistro/7147.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
