<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRIEF-STUDIES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRESS MAY INTERFERE WITH THE THRILL OF GIVING BIRTH 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: Bellevue Woman's Hospital is CQ)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SYLVIA WOOD  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NISKAYUNA, N.Y. _ Theresa O'Connell felt nothing but joy when
she held her baby for the first time last month.
</P>
<P>
   ``The minute I saw her, it was like, `What was I worried
about?''' O'Connell said about her daughter, Devon Grace, born May
24.
</P>
<P>
   Chances are O'Connell won't have anything to worry about beyond
the usual stress and fatigue of new parenthood. But for one in
every 10 new mothers, the months after delivery offer a profound
sense of sadness, hopelessness, mood swings and insomnia.
</P>
<P>
   Postpartum depression, as it's known, is fairly common, though
not well understood and often underdiagnosed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The American myth is that when you have a baby, you should be
glowing, blossoming,'' said Dr. Norman Possner, an obstetrician and
gynecologist at the Albany Medical Center Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, for a variety of reasons, childbirth can trigger severe
depression in some women, making it difficult for them care for
themselves and an infant that needs round-the-clock attention.
</P>
<P>
   Left untreated, such depression, in rare causes, can lead to
suicide or infanticide.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something that's not really recognized,'' said Deborah
Chesky, the social work manager at Bellevue Woman's Hospital in
Niskayuna, a town north of Albany. ``Often the woman feels ashamed,
`The baby is fine, why do I feel this way?'''
</P>
<P>
   Researchers are learning more about how a mother's mood may
affect her baby's long-term development.
</P>
<P>
   Though 50 to 75 percent of new mothers suffer from the ``baby
blues'' in the days after delivery, such sadness disappears after
two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Postpartum depression, on the other hand, can occur anytime
within the first year of the baby's birth and the symptoms persist
longer than two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   A recent study at Emory University in Atlanta found that both
depressed mothers and their babies have increased amounts of the
hormone cortisol in their blood, an indication of stress.
</P>
<P>
   Such high levels can make these infants vulnerable to
overreacting to stress later in life.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, a depressed mother is more likely to withdraw from
her baby, reducing the amount of positive interaction between the
two, Possner said. Such interaction is important for the baby's
overall development.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's much more serious than a lot of things that obstetricians
take care of during pregnancy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem with postpartum depression has been
diagnosing it. Women with the problem are often the last ones to
admit something is wrong, because of fear and shame.
</P>
<P>
   Possner and researchers at Union College in Schenectady, N.Y.,
are studying ways to help predict, before the birth, which women
might be most at risk.
</P>
<P>
   ``Postpartum depression is almost always treatable with
medications and psychotherapy,'' said Karen Williams, an associate
professor of biology and the Health Professions Counselor at Union
College. ``There's no reason for people to suffer through it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bellevue Woman's Hospital has been participating in the research
by distributing the questionnaire to women before and after they
have their babies.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sort of a psychic PAP test,'' Possner said, referring to
the common screening test for cervical cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers believe women without the support of close family or
friends are often most at risk.
</P>
<P>
   Health experts say that women with a personal or family history
of depression are more likely to experience it. And women who have
had postpartum depression in an earlier pregnancy also are at
greater risk in subsequent births.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on the level of depression, a combination of
medication and therapy may be recommended. Most women who are
prescribed medication, which requires them to stop breast-feeding,
see improvement in three to six months.
</P>
<P>
   Possner believes one simple question can help gauge the
well-being of any new mother.
</P>
<P>
   ``My favorite question is, `Are you happy?''' he said. ``That's
a shocker to most ladies. If there's a sudden blank pause and they
break into tears, you've got a problem.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-15-99 1417EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
