<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The Cox News Service spot news budget for Wednesday, June 16,
1999.
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Photo and graphics information and editors' names can be found
at the end of this budget.
</P>
<P>
   YUGOSLAVIA-KOSOVO
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-KLA _ STARIE KACANEK, Kosovo _ The KLA flexes its mucle.
Hundreds of Serb civilians, fearing for their lives, fled this town
Tuesday after it was taken over by Kosovo Liberation Army rebels
who discovered a mass grave. The KLA fighters, angered by
eyewitness accounts of how Serb soldiers had executed Kosovar
residents, began firing their weapons in the air and ordered the
Serb residents to leave. About 30 carloads of Serbs soon fled. It
may be the first documented case of ethnic cleansing by ethnic
Albanians and illustrates the difficulty NATO peacekeepers will
have in preventing acts of revenge. And for the first time in a
year, KLA commander Drini was able to come into town, have coffe
and along the way declare that this is the first city that the KLA
controls ``100 percent.'' He said the KLA will cooperate with the
Military-Technical Agreement but are not prepared de-militarize.
The German NATO commanders in the area say that they are not going
to crack down on the rebel fighters at this point.
(Albright-Kaplow, Cox News Service). 20.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-PEC _ PEC, Yugoslavia _ This city that is the center of
Serbian Orthodoxy look like a ghost town. Home to Serbia's largest
Orthodox Church, the core of downtown is virtually untouched, the
only people visible on Tuedsay were a dozen Serb men sitting on a
park bench. In a region that saw the worst of the Serb ethnic
cleansing campaign, the efficiency of that campaign in Pec is
frightening. Developing.
</P>
<P>
   (Kaplow, Cox News Service) 20.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-DEATHS _ KUKES, Albania _ Peace did not come soon enough
for Halil Emini. He did not get killed by Yugoslav forces or NATO
bombs. He just drowned last Friday while swimming with his children
near their refugee camp. Now, instead of planning a return to his
homeland, Emini lies under a mound of dirt on a plateau with 140
other deceased ethnic Albanians who fled Kosovo during the Serbs'
ethnic cleansing campaign. In a new section the local city
cemetery, their graves show the signs of a people dispossessed.
(Kaplow, Cox News Service). 20. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   ROSA-PARKS _ WASHINGTON _ Civil Rights activist Rosa Parks is
awarded the Congressional Gold Medal at a Capitol Hill ceremony
attended by President Clinton, House Speaker Dennis Hastert,
R-Ill., and others. (Hill, Cox News Service). WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   GUNS _ WASHINGTON _ President Clinton is turning to women for
help in the congressional showdown this week over new gun control
restrictions as he struggles to keep Democrats from crossing party
lines. Members of that key Democratic constituency are joining him
at a White House rally at 12:45 p.m. today for an amendment by Rep.
Carolyn McCarthy, D-N.Y., which Democrats say would tighten
background checks at gun shows. Other developments as warrant.
(Foskett, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   DRUGS _ WASHINGTON _ National Drug Control Policy Director Barry
McCaffrey joins members of Congress to announce five new High
Intensity Drug Trafficking Areas. The areas include some not
usually identified with major drug imports, such as northern Ohio
and New England. (Hill, Cox News Service). 15.
</P>
<P>
   SOCIAL-SECURITY _ WASHINGTON _ The Senate is expected to vote
Tuesday on its version of ``lock box'' legislation to prohibit and
spending of surplus Social Security taxes. (Lipman, Cox News
Service). 18.
</P>
<P>
   TECH-SUMMIT _ WASHINGTON _ Microsoft Chairman Bill Gates
testifies Tuesday before the Joint Economic Committee's National
Summit on High Technology, which examines the crucial role the high
tech industry plays in the U.S. economy. (Glass, Cox News Service).
25.
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
</P>
