   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   BUSHWRAP _ Covering last morning of Bush's campaign trip and
wrapping up high points/lessons learned. (Greenberger, Austin
American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   BAPTISTS-MAIN _ ATLANTA _ Southern Baptists from around the
country will gather in the Georgia Dome today and Wednesday. About
14,000 ``messengers'' are expected to register. Headlining today's
agenda is the election of the first vice president. Among those on
the ballot is Frank Cox, a minister from Lawrenceville, Ga.
(GWhite, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 18.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   BAPTISTS-NOTEBOOK _ ATLANTA _ A notebook on happenings at the
Southern Baptist Convention. (GWhite, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   WRONG-CONVICTION _ Sixteen years after he was sent to prison
after he was convicted of rape in Clayton County, Calvin Johnson
was to be back in court Tuesday, asking to be freed. New DNA tests
cleared him. Johnson was sentenced to life in prison after trials
in Clayton and Fulton counties on two different rape incidents. He
was convicted in Clayton and acquitted in Fulton. (Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 20.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIESTARS _ American Film Institute releases its latest list:
the top 50 movie stars of all time. Humphrey Bogart leads the men's
list and Katharine Hepburn tops the women's list. (Longino, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 15.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (a) General News and (e) Entertainment
categories.
</P>
<P>
   VIRGINMARY-DISPUTE _ VIRGINMARY-DISPUTE _ ATLANTA _ Nancy
Fowler, whose visions of the Virgin Mary have brought hundreds of
thousands of people to her suburban Atlanta farm, has once again
distanced herself from Our Loving Mother's Children, the
organization that has supported her visions for years. Fowler says
the group is charging too much for tapes and other vision
materials. There is talk of a lawsuit, but nothing has been filed.
(Stanford, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   DETAIN _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Two years ago, Ralph Richardson
was a small businessman who coached his church soccer team and
dreamed of turning his commercial cleaning firm in suburban Atlanta
into a big success. An unlucky convergence of a new immigration
law, a weekend trip to Haiti and a 7-year-old cocaine-trafficking
charge doomed the 33-year-old immigrant's plans. He's spent the
last 20 months at Krome Detention Center near Miami as a criminally
tainted immigrant, awaiting deportation. Richardson's luck could be
changing. Converging in his favor are a growing dissent over the
1996 immigration law and a favorable June 1 ruling by the U.S.
Supreme Court in his lawsuit, Richardson vs. the U.S. Immigration
and Naturalization Service. (Douthat, Palm Beach Post) 38''. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   BLACK-FARMERS _ PAHOKEE, Fla. _ Being a small farmer is hard and
being a small black farmer is nearly impossible. When a crop is
lost, credit is the only way to survive and credit can be hard to
come by. Black farmers for years have struggled with the USDA,
their government loans delayed past planting time or inexplicably
rejected. At last count in 1997, only 18,000 of America's 1.9
million farms were owned by blacks. Over the years, as small farms
collapsed under the weight of competition from mega growers, black
farms perished at nearly twice the rate of white farms. Black
farmers understood why it was so difficult. But it wasn't until
April that the rest of the world learned: A federal class-action
lawsuit initiated by a third generation North Carolina farmer
against the USDA was settled for an estimated $2.25 billion, the
largest civil rights settlement in history Farmers are now
beginning to file claims. (Staletovich, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   FLA-SUPERBOWL-MONEY _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ For their $210,000
to the last two Super Bowls played in South Florida, Palm Beach
officials expect the National Football League to show the same
gratitude it did in Broward and Miami-Dade counties: a $1 million
contribution toward a new youth center. That would be something
real they could point to as they decide whether to continue
donating in the face of doubts about whether Palm Beach County's
investment is worth it. (Gelbart, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
