<P>
   Add N.Y. Times News Service budget for papers of WEDNESDAY, June
16:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DINING &LR;  (``d'' code)
</P>
<P>
   ZUCCHINI-BLOSSOMS (Undated) _ Zucchini blossoms are the fragile,
edible precursor to the fruit on a zucchini plant. They are so
visually remarkable that it is easy to see them as nothing more
than decoration. But they have long been a part of Italian, French
and Mexican cooking, the leaves chopped like an herb and sprinkled
into soups and pasta dishes, or filled with stuffings like cheese
and anchovies, or simply dipped into a light batter and fried. The
blossoms have a subtle flavor and a wildly beautiful shape, which
happens to make a perfect package for stuffing. By Amanda Hesser.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   With recipes.
</P>
<P>
   EDIBLE-FLOWERS (Undated) _ Cooking with edible flowers. By
Melissa Clark.
</P>
<P>
   With recipes.
</P>
<P>
   SIMPLE-COOKING (Undated) _ The column: Minty beef salad. By Mark
Bittman.
</P>
<P>
   With recipe.
</P>
<P>
   RARE-COOKBOOKS (New York) _ On the plight of rare cookbooks in
the New York Public Library. By Florence Fabricant.
</P>
<P>
   MASTER-CHEF (Undated) _ The column: Skate with eggplant chutney.
</P>
<P>
   With recipes.
