<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIMPLE-COOKING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THAI-STYLE BEEF SALAD 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By MARK BITTMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The wonderful mesclun that is sold at some farm stands and green
markets contains a variety of flavorful baby greens _ herbs, kale,
dandelion, arugula, beet, turnip, mustard _ that have the potential
for becoming a salad of great complexity.
</P>
<P>
   The mesclun that is sold in almost every food store these days,
however, is less ideal, as it is essentially just small-to-medium
lettuce leaves, maybe with some radicchio or escarole thrown in.
</P>
<P>
   But it doesn't take much to turn supermarket mesclun into a
wonderful salad: simply toss it with a handful of flavorful, mild
herbs, like parsley or mint. I find that mint, especially, gives
this salad a Southeast Asian flavor.
</P>
<P>
   With the addition of some grilled steak _ chicken, pork or
shrimp does nicely, too _ the salad can become a meal. Since steak
doesn't need any seasoning, cooking it takes only 10 minutes. You
can, of course, also roast the steak in the oven in your kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   I make a light but assertive vinaigrette, based not on olive oil
but on a neutral-flavored oil like canola. I use relatively little
oil, since its job is only to help the remaining dressing
ingredients coat the greens. To this I add rice vinegar or lime
juice, both of which are high in flavor but low in acidity. The
vinaigrette is rounded off with mustard, shallots, and nam pla
(Thai fish sauce) or soy sauce.
</P>
<P>
   MINTY THAI-STYLE BEEF SALAD
</P>
<P>
   Time: 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   1 to 1{ pounds thick sirloin, rib-eye or other boneless steak
</P>
<P>
   6 to 8 cups mesclun greens
</P>
<P>
   1 cup mint leaves
</P>
<P>
   \ cup neutral oil, like canola
</P>
<P>
   \ cup rice vinegar or lime juice
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon mustard, optional
</P>
<P>
   1 chopped shallot, about 1 tablespoon
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons nam pla, or 1 tablespoon soy sauce mixed with 1
tablespoon water
</P>
<P>
   \ teaspoon or more freshly ground black pepper.
</P>
<P>
   1. If you're grilling, start a charcoal fire or preheat a gas
grill. Grill steak about 4 minutes a side for medium rare. (If
you're cooking inside, preheat oven to its maximum, 450 to 500
degrees. Heat ovenproof skillet on stove over high heat until it
smokes. Place steak in skillet, and transfer to oven. Roast about 4
minutes a side for medium rare.)
</P>
<P>
   2. Meanwhile, wash greens and toss with mint. Whisk or blend
remaining ingredients together, taste, and adjust seasoning.
</P>
<P>
   3. Let steak rest for a minute before slicing, and then place it
atop greens, with its juices. Dress with vinaigrette, and serve.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   Variations: Use cilantro or Thai basil instead of mint, or
combine a bit of these with the mint. Parsley, chervil, Italian
basil or dill, separately or in combination to taste, also work
well. With this last group of herbs, prepare a more standard
vinaigrette, which will give this salad a European character.
Combine 1/3 cup extra virgin olive oil with about 1/3 cup lemon
juice and the mustard and minced shallot.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-15-99 1455EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990615.0118 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-15 14:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6023 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MASTER-CHEF-NYT &LR;      06-15 0890
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MASTER-CHEF-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAUTEED SKATE WITH EGGPLANT CHUTNEY 
</HEADLINE>
   This is the fourth of eight columns by Thomas Keller, the chef and
owner of the French Laundry in Yountville, Calif. His collaborator
is Michael Ruhlman.  
(jt) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Skate is all about visual impact and texture. I love its dense,
ropy flesh. It has a wonderful bite and flavor _ not as mild as
sole but rather flavorful and meaty like monkfish. And it is also
easy to cook.
</P>
<P>
   The fish is not so delicate that it falls apart at high
temperatures, so the exterior becomes deliciously crisp. Its
tolerance for heat is also high. Unlike cod or salmon, which will
quickly overcook, skate will hit the right point of doneness and
stay there. I use Atlantic spotted skate because it is a little
smaller than other types and its ropes are more compact.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, fish is my favorite protein to work with because of
the extraordinary variety of textures and flavors available. Most
people know the basics of buying and storing fish, but please
remember how delicate it is and handle it gently. When you cook it,
turn it with a spatula or palate knife, never with tongs.
</P>
<P>
   (In my restaurant, I don't allow my line brigade to use tongs
for anything because tongs so easily damage the food.)
</P>
<P>
   Fish is also exciting to work with because it is such a great
vehicle for garnishes. Think of fish as a pedestal for other
flavors. This chutney is an excellent concoction in itself; it
would go well with sole or chicken, or you can stuff zucchini with
it and roast it for a vegetarian dish.
</P>
<P>
   But here it provides a perfect example of how fish magnifies the
complex flavors in the garnish, which combines strong spices
(curry, cinnamon, clove), acids (wine and citrus juices) and sugars
(granulated and in the sweet vegetables).
</P>
<P>
   And it shows how these flavor components in turn enhance the
fish. I call the preparation a chutney because of the sweet-sour
elements, but if you look closely, you'll notice that it is really
a ratatouille in disguise.
</P>
<P>
   I have looked no further than a Provencal combination of
vegetables _ eggplant, zucchini, squash, bell peppers _ because it
is summer and these vegetables are excellent and abundant.
</P>
<P>
   SAUTEED SKATE WITH EGGPLANT CHUTNEY  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 25 minutes  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1{ pounds skate wing, trimmed of cartilage and red areas
</P>
<P>
   Canola oil
</P>
<P>
   Flour
</P>
<P>
   Kosher salt
</P>
<P>
   Eggplant chutney (see recipe).
</P>
<P>
   1. Cut skate into six rectangular portions, 3 by 4 inches, about
3 ounces each. The actual size of the pieces will depend on the
thickness and size of the skate wing. If the piece of fish is very
thin, cut a larger piece and fold it over.
</P>
<P>
   2. In a large saute pan over medium heat, add canola oil to a
depth of [ inch. While oil is heating, lightly dust each portion of
skate with flour, patting off any excess. Season with salt to
taste.
</P>
<P>
   3. Place skate in hot oil, and saute, basting occasionally with
oil, until fish is golden brown on bottom, 1 to 2 minutes. Turn
fillets, and continue to saute until fish is opaque and fully
cooked, another minute or two.
</P>
<P>
   4. To serve, divide eggplant chutney among six plates. Top each
with a portion of skate.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 6 servings.
</P>
<P>
   EGGPLANT CHUTNEY  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 1 hour  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   \ teaspoon curry powder
</P>
<P>
   1 1-inch piece cinnamon stick
</P>
<P>
   1 clove
</P>
<P>
   2 2-inch strips orange zest
</P>
<P>
   2 2-inch strips lemon zest
</P>
<P>
   8 tablespoons extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   \ cup minced shallots
</P>
<P>
   1 cup peeled, seeded, finely chopped tomatoes
</P>
<P>
   { cup red wine
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons orange juice
</P>
<P>
   3 cups finely diced eggplant
</P>
<P>
   1{ cups finely diced zucchini
</P>
<P>
   1{ cups finely diced yellow squash
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons unsalted butter, cut into several pieces
</P>
<P>
   \ cup finely diced roasted red peppers
</P>
<P>
   \ cup finely diced roasted yellow peppers
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon chopped parsley
</P>
<P>
   Kosher salt and freshly ground black pepper.
</P>
<P>
   1. In a small skillet, combine curry powder, cinnamon stick and
clove. Place over medium heat, and toast to eliminate widowthe
spices until they give off an aroma. Remove from the heat, and wrap
in cheesecloth with the orange zest and the lemon zest. Tie the
cheesecloth to make a sachet.
</P>
<P>
   2. In a medium saucepan, combine 2 tablespoons of the olive oil
and the shallots. Place over low heat, and saute until the shallots
have softened, about 4 minutes. Add tomatoes, red wine, sugar,
lemon and orange juice, and sachet. Simmer until liquid has reduced
and texture resembles marmalade, 20 to 25 minutes. Remove from
heat, and discard sachet.
</P>
<P>
   3. In a large skillet over medium heat, heat 2 tablespoons olive
oil. Add eggplant, and saute until tender, about 5 minutes. Drain
on paper towels. Return the skillet to medium heat, and add 2 more
tablespoons of the oil. Add zucchini and yellow squash, and saute
until tender, 4 to 5 minutes. Drain on paper towels. (Chutney may
be prepared to this point several hours in advance.)
</P>
<P>
   4. Reheat tomato mixture, and whisk in remaining 2 tablespoons
olive oil. Add butter one piece at a time, whisking to emulsify the
sauce. Add sauteed eggplant, zucchini and yellow squash, and mix
well. Fold in red peppers, yellow peppers and parsley. Season with
salt and pepper to taste. Serve warm.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 6 cups.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
