<HEADER>
A6029 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WINE-TALK-NYT &LR;      06-15 0875
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-TALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MANY FACES OF CABERNET FRANC 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By FRANK J. PRIAL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHINON, France _ In their hearts, all Frenchmen truly believe
the old axiom that insists ``a wine's first duty is to be red.''
And yet there are parts of France where red wine definitely plays
second fiddle. Champagne, of course, and Alsace, where riesling and
gewuerztraminer reign supreme.
</P>
<P>
   And then there's the Loire Valley, the great garden of France,
where chenin blanc is king and all the other grapes its vassals.
Except one _ cabernet franc, a red grape. If chenin is king,
cabernet franc is queen.
</P>
<P>
   It is primarily grown in the Chinon region, in Bourgueil and
Saint-Nicolas-de-Bourgueil, and it's important in Saumur-Champigny
and Anjou. Chinon reds are among the most popular reds in Paris; it
is mostly to quench the capital's thirst that the plantings of
cabernet franc around Chinon have tripled in the last 25 years,
from 1,500 acres to 5,000.
</P>
<P>
   Cabernet franc is also an important component of the best wines
of Bordeaux. At some famous Bordeaux chateaus, like Cheval-Blanc,
in St.-Emilion, it is the principal ingredient. Napa Valley
winemakers, looking for tannins and structure, regularly blend
cabernet franc with cabernet sauvignon. The North Fork of Long
Island has also proved to be a friendly venue for the grape. But
attempting to detect a family tie between a young Chinon and a
California cabernet franc would be tough even for an expert.
</P>
<P>
   The cabernet franc grape arrived in the Loire Valley over a
thousand years ago. Locally, it is often called Breton, possibly
because it came through Brittany to get to the central Loire
Valley. Although some historians trace it back to an Abbe Breton
who grew it in his gardens, Jacqueline Friedrich, an authority on
the Loire, says Francois Rabelais, the 16th-century writer who was
born near Chinon, wrote of ``the good wine of Breton'' 200 years
before the abbot came on the scene.
</P>
<P>
   In any event, cabernet franc has spent the outgoing millennium
adapting to the local soil and climate, so it should be no surprise
that it performs differently elsewhere. Along the Loire, local
growers say there are really two Chinons, one from cabernet franc
grown on gravelly soil near the riverbanks and one grown on chalk
and clay up the slopes from the river. The first is the light,
fruity wine drunk in Paris bistros when it's a year old. The latter
is a bigger, more complex wine that will age well for many years.
</P>
<P>
   How many years depends on the grower and on the specific terroir
he cultivates. Terroir is that elusive French word that encompasses
the site and the weather _ the vineyard's complete ecosystem _ and
agriculture's impact on the place over the years.
</P>
<P>
   The wine known as Chinon is produced in Chinon, of course, and
in 18 other contiguous communes that make up a zone between the
Loire and the little Vienne River, eastward from the spot where the
two rivers meet near Chinon. A typical local grower will own or
rent parcels of land all over the Chinon appellation and will make
two or three different styles of Chinon.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Bernard Baudry at Cravant makes a light, easily
drinkable version; a second version made from old vines but not
aged in wood, and a third made from old vines and aged in oak. Some
growers age their best wines for two or three years, then recommend
that they be matured in the bottle for another three or four years.
</P>
<P>
   The best-known producer of Chinon is Charles Joguet. Joguet, an
artist who works in his Paris atelier during the week, is known not
only for the quality of his wines but for the variety of his
offerings. They include young wines like the Cuvee Jeunes Vignes,
blended from grapes from various plots, and complex single-vineyard
wines like his Varennes du Grand Clos, from 25-year-old vines, and
his Clos de la Dioterie, from 90-year-old vines.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, I sampled the 1996 Clos de la Dioterie at Jean Bardet,
the two-star restaurant in Tours. It was too young, but for someone
only vaguely familiar with the best Chinon, it was a revelation.
There was a wholly unreasonable urge to say, ``Let's try five or 10
other vintages; this is a remarkable wine.''
</P>
<P>
   The strongest impression from the wine is fruit, but not the
fresh fruits of summer, as in the young Chinon. Rather, the taste
is more of fruit jams and spices.
</P>
<P>
   I like Ms. Friedrich's description in her book, ``A Wine and
Food Guide to the Loire'' (Henry Holt, 1996): ``I often think of
old Bretons as the embodiment of memory _ not of a specific memory,
but of memory itself. I have an image of an old handkerchief made
of fine cloth softened after years of being folded into purses,
still carrying whiffs of many exquisite perfumes, mingled, muted
and fugitive.''
</P>
<P>
   There is plenty of moderately priced Chinon to choose from in
the major wine markets in the United States, where it has to
compete, of course, with merlot, the current favorite.
</P>
<P>
   Cabernet franc, California cabernet franc, is leaner, more
tannic and less accessible. French cabernet franc, as expressed in
Chinon and other Loire reds, is a different wine altogether. Like
any truly interesting friend, it takes time to get to know.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
