<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FISH-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`FISH': ENGLISH DISHES THAT DISPEL ENNUI 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By MARIAN BURROS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   I'm tired of gorgeous picture books that call for my very own
kitchen staff before I can even get to the stove. I'm bored with
over-the-top fusion cooking fatefully headed in the direction that
spelled the decline of nouvelle cuisine.
</P>
<P>
   But after trying three recipes from ``Fish'' by Sophie Grigson
and William Black (Headline Book Publishing, London, 1998), I have
lost my cooking ennui. Ms. Grigson has produced bright, fresh
dishes with a modern sensibility that illustrate why London is one
of the hottest eating towns in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Grigson has not discarded what was good about British
cooking _ potted shrimp, the Anglo-Indian kedgeree, fried whitebait
and marinated kippers. But she has added the occasional modern
touch, like cayenne to make the whitebait spicy and peas to give a
sweet note to the kedgeree. She has also borrowed judiciously from
other cuisines to produce a collection of dishes to please a
reasonably competent cook.
</P>
<P>
   I say reasonably competent because ``Fish,'' unlike many
American cookbooks that spell out everything, expects cooks to use
their judgment. As the author comments in the headnotes for salsa
verde: ``The quantities sound vague _ how big is a bunch of
parsley? _ but that is in the nature of the sauce. Variations
abound, and the key is to taste and play with the balance of
flavors until it pleases you.''
</P>
<P>
   Nach Waxman, the owner of Kitchen Arts and Letters in New York,
has tipped off his customers to this book. ``Our customers are
interested in what is happening, what kind of innovative thinking
there is in the field, what other professionals are thinking, new
ideas, new approaches,'' he said, ``and what they are more
stimulated by is this very fresh bunch of people who are working in
London and Sydney and Melbourne. What blows me away is that they
are home-grown, even though they are from countries that had very
paltry culinary traditions.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Grigson had good home-grown training: she is the daughter of
the late, great cookbook author Jane Grigson, who wrote ``Fish
Cookery'' in 1973 (it included a recipe for halibut with Welsh
rarebit crust that she served her family; Sophie Grigson reprints
it). She also roams the world, adding lemongrass to a bright
octopus salad from Thailand, star anise from China to a plum
compote served with seared sea bass, and creme fraiche from France
to just about everything else.
</P>
<P>
   William Black, Ms. Grigson's husband, provides instructions for
buying and storing fish and information about the severe problems
of overfishing and the indiscriminate use of antibiotics. Each
recipe also provides alternative species, which is helpful not only
when an American is working with an English cookbook, but also when
the fishmonger doesn't have a particular fish.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing's perfect, though. If the book is going to include a
recipe for Manhattan clam chowder, there must be one for the New
England version. That's an unfortunate omission but hardly in
league with the suggestion that frozen soft-shell crabs are
acceptable. For a book that emphasizes the primary importance of
fish quality, shame, shame.
</P>
<P>
   Though it has not yet been published in the United States, the
book is available at www.amazon.co.uk for $26 plus $8 shipping. It
can also be ordered from Kitchen Arts and Letters, 1435 Lexington
Ave., New York, N.Y., (212-876-5550), for $55.
</P>
<P>
   BAKED FILLETS WITH CREME FRAICHE, CHERRY TOMATOES AND PARMESAN
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from ``Fish'' by Sophie Grigson and William Black &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 30 minutes  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1{ pounds skinless brill, John Dory, turbot, bass, sole, hake,
pollock or cod fillets
</P>
<P>
   Salt and white pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   5 ounces cherry tomatoes, washed and halved
</P>
<P>
   7 ounces creme fraiche
</P>
<P>
   8 large basil leaves, shredded
</P>
<P>
   4 ounces freshly grated Parmigiano-Reggiano.
</P>
<P>
   1. Preheat the oven to 425 degrees. Season the fish with salt
and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   2. Use half the butter to grease a baking dish large enough to
hold the fillets in a single, snug layer. Lay the fillets in it.
</P>
<P>
   3. Dot the cherry tomato halves over them. Smear the creme
fraiche over the fish and tomatoes, covering the fish more or less
evenly. Scatter the basil over, and then sprinkle the cheese evenly
over the top. Grind a little more pepper over the whole thing, and
dot with the remaining butter.
</P>
<P>
   4. Bake 15 minutes, until the fish is just cooked through. Serve
bubbling and sizzling. Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   FRIED MONKFISH WITH SALSA VERDE
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from ``Fish''
</P>
<P>
   Time: 30 minutes  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1 large bunch parsley
</P>
<P>
   Generous handful large fresh basil leaves
</P>
<P>
   4 anchovy fillets in oil
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons capers, rinsed or thoroughly soaked if salted
</P>
<P>
   2 large garlic cloves, coarsely chopped
</P>
<P>
   1{ ounces pitted green olives, roughly chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon white wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1 slice good quality white bread, crusts removed, then bread
torn into pieces
</P>
<P>
   5 to 9 ounces extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2 to 3 pounds monkfish tail, John Dory or cod, filleted
</P>
<P>
   Olive oil for frying
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste.
</P>
<P>
   1. Wash and slash the leaves from the bunch of parsley. Put them
into a food processor with all the other ingredients except the
fish, olive oil, and salt and pepper. Process in short bursts,
scraping down the sides until finely chopped. With motor running
trickle in enough olive oil to make a thickish sauce. Taste and
adjust seasoning. The sauce is best served immediately, but it can
be covered and refrigerated.
</P>
<P>
   2. Slice the monkfish fillets across the grain into pieces about
\ inch thick.
</P>
<P>
   3. Just before serving, season and saute the monkfish slices
briskly in olive oil over high heat. Be very careful not to
overcook, to prevent toughening. Drain briefly on paper towel, and
serve with salsa verde.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 to 6 servings.
</P>
</TEXT>
