<SLUG> BC-CAT-B&AMP;B-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAT LOVERS OPEN INN FOR FELINES ON THE GO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BETSY FELDSTEIN  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   QUEENSBURY, N.Y. _ Cat owners who don't want to consign their
beloved kitty to a standard-issue kennel can take their feline
friends to a ``cat bed and breakfast.''
</P>
<P>
   Kip and Jean Grant of Queensbury, owners of four cats, designed
the Country Kitty B&AMP;B to provide ``an affordable alternative for
cat owners who must decide how and where to care for their pets
while they're away from home.''
</P>
<P>
   After almost 30 years of caring for family and stray cats, the
Grants decided a year ago to get into the business.
</P>
<P>
   The idea for the boarding facility came when one of the Grants'
own cats required a brief stay at the veterinarian. According to
Jean Grant, ``This was her first time in a cage, and we could tell
it was very stressful for her. We wanted to create an alternative
for folks who prefer not to board their cat in a cage or depend on
a friend or relative to `cat sit.'''
</P>
<P>
   The boarding facility for cats is located next to their home in
upstate New York. Cost of the facility was about $130,000. The
Grants invested about $15,000 for furnishings and equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Each of the 10 guest rooms, which measure 45 square feet, is
named after one of the Grants' past or present cats. They include a
large window and seat, cubbies for playing hide and seek, plush
beds, cat chairs, toys, private litter boxes and plenty of food and
water.
</P>
<P>
   When finished, each room will be furnished with one vinyl
lawnchair covered by fabric with cat designs, and one or two cat
beds. Cat-themed wallpaper will decorate each room's walls, and
linoleum covers the floors. Cats may catch their reflection on door
mirrors in each room. Up to three cats from the same household may
rest comfortably in one room. Baths and grooming are available and
arrangements can be made for special diet and health concerns.
</P>
<P>
   In order to make the felines even more comfortable, temperature
control is planned for each room. For the cats' pleasure, music
will be piped into the rooms.
</P>
<P>
   The ``inn's'' reception area offers a ``Kitty Corner,'' filled
with books containing both cat stories and cat care. An office and
a small kitchen complete the facility. A typical daily schedule
includes breakfast served at 8 a.m., dinner at 5 p.m. and bedtime
at 8 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Jean Grant said a family may bring in its own food for cats.
Playtime and catnaps are offered to the feline guests throughout
the day. Cats who enjoy being outdoors may be taken for a stroll,
weather permitting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guest fees'' at the Country Kitty B&AMP;B are $12 daily and $10
per day for a week's stay. Discounts on the daily rate are offered
for each additional feline guest.
</P>
<P>
   The Country Kitty B&AMP;B is not alone. Cat's Pajamas Inn, in Salem,
Mass., offers 18 ``townhomes'' that look like tall cabinets with
four levels. The inn has a country garden theme with little garden
areas for cats.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
