<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-REVIEW-HANNIBAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`HANNIBAL' IS A SAVORY SEQUEL FOR HARRIS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (note: Chateau d'Yquem is cq; add circumflex over first ``a'' in
Chateau) 
 
By FRITZ LANHAM 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The iron law of sequels, in books or movies, boils down to this:
To succeed, they must exceed.
</P>
<P>
   If the previous book was violent, the sequel must be even more
violent. If the previous book had a bad guy, the sequel should have
a viler villain _ or better yet, two.
</P>
<P>
   If cannibalism, say, was a motif in the predecessor, then the
new book ought to render a weakness for the flesh in even more
flamboyant, exquisitely imagined ways: Pop the cork on that Chateau
d'Yquem! Let loose the pigs!
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Harris could be the poster boy for the law of sequel
success. ``Hannibal'' (Delacorte Press, $27.95), the just-released
continuation of his best-selling 1988 ``Silence of the Lambs''
(itself a sequel to the 1981 ``Red Dragon''), fairly bursts with
lurid violence and sleek, brainy bad guys.
</P>
<P>
   Toss in an appealing heroine _ FBI agent Clarice Starling,
reprising her role in ``Lambs'' _ a thick dollop of pop Freudianism
and at least one daring plot twist, and you have the stuff of
superior entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   None of it is particularly plausible, of course, but Harris
paces the action well, and his villains are engaging in a
larger-than-life way.
</P>
<P>
   As the title suggests, Dr. Hannibal Lecter, the serial murderer
with a penchant for consuming his victims, takes center stage in
this book, although he must share it with Starling and a third
figure, Mason Verger, one of Lecter's early victims.
</P>
<P>
   The setting is seven years after the end of ``Lambs,'' which saw
Lecter escape from custody and flee to South America. There, an
apparently limitless supply of money and the offices of a fine
plastic surgeon have given him a new life.
</P>
<P>
   As this novel opens, Lecter has moved on to Florence, Italy,
where he has turned himself into an expert on Tuscan literature and
is living the life of a retiring but painfully cultivated
gentleman-scholar.
</P>
<P>
   He drinks the finest wines, wears the most elegant suits, amuses
himself by playing Bach's ``Goldberg Variations'' on his antique
clavier. Lecter is quite the dandy.
</P>
<P>
   Later in the novel, Harris flashes back to Lecter's childhood,
to events that ostensibly explain his psychopathologies.
</P>
<P>
   Inevitably, this psychologizing and the attention to domestic
detail tend to diminish Lecter as a villain. In ``Lambs'' he was an
elemental force of evil, beyond comprehension, beyond humanity.
Here he falls into a more familiar category _ the filthy rich,
super-intelligent, seemingly infallible evildoer. More like Dr.
Moriarty, or some of those cartoon baddies in the James Bond
movies.
</P>
<P>
   But in this novel Hannibal is more quarry than hunter. Weighing
almost as heavy on the scale of villainy is Verger, child molester,
scion of a meat-packing fortune and a man nursing a serious grudge
against the good doctor.
</P>
<P>
   As a young man, Verger was a patient of Lecter. One thing led to
another, and now Verger lies paralyzed from the neck down.
Moreover, he won't be needing a shave for a while.
</P>
<P>
   But his brain is very much alive, and as he lies in a room at
Muskrat Farm, his northern Maryland estate, a giant eel his
principal companion, he's plotting a particularly nasty revenge.
Sardinian thugs and man-eating pigs figure into his scheme.
</P>
<P>
   Starling, the third main character, has seen her promising FBI
career flounder since ``Lambs.'' A combination of traditional
good-old-boy sexism and her own sometimes-abrasive manner has left
the 32-year-old agent adrift, with few allies.
</P>
<P>
   In the opening pages of the book, she participates in a botched
and bloody drug raid that leaves five bodies on a Washington, D.C.,
street, including that of a woman Starling shoots in self-defense.
With Justice Department Deputy Assistant Inspector General Paul
Krendler working against her behind the scenes, Starling's days in
the FBI seem numbered.
</P>
<P>
   The plot of the novel involves the competing searches for Lecter
by Starling and Verger.
</P>
<P>
   All three principals eventually come face to face (O.K., in
Verger's case ``face'' perhaps isn't the right word). The
Lecter-Verger scrimmage works out in fairly predictable fashion,
although Harris keeps the tension level high. ``Hannibal'' is
nothing if not a page-turner.
</P>
<P>
   The Starling-Lecter relationship is more problematic. In
``Lambs'' Harris allowed Lecter to probe Starling's painful
childhood _ the death of her beloved father, a low-level lawman
killed in the line of duty; her class insecurities; the trauma of
witnessing the deaths of horses and lambs as a foster child. A
dramatic tension flowed from the psychological duel between Lecter,
the doctor/daddy/evildoer, and Starling, the
patient/child/representative of moral order.
</P>
<P>
   In this novel, Harris works some surprising twists on this
complicated affair of attraction and repulsion. By the end of the
book, it's hard to know what we're supposed to think of Hannibal
the Cannibal.
</P>
<P>
   Harris works some well-drawn minor characters into the
narrative. Margot Verger, Mason Verger's body-builder lesbian
sister, is a study in frustration as she tries to persuade her
brother to donate semen so she can have a child with her lover.
</P>
<P>
   Even better is Barney, the hospital attendant who was in charge
of the incarcerated Lecter in ``Lambs.'' A man with just the
ordinary amount of larceny in his heart, Barney hires on with the
Vergers but ends up desperately searching for a way to extricate
himself.
</P>
<P>
   Fans of Harris' previous books _ who have been waiting 11 years
for this one _ won't be disappointed. ``Hannibal'' isn't great
literature, but it's gaudy fun.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXX END OF STORY XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
