<HEADER>
A6101 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-BUENA-COX     06-15 0351
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-BUENA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ``Buena'' documentry revolves around music
 &HT;    
 &HT;    EMBARGOED UNTIL FRIDAY, JUNE 18. DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN.
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you're not already a fan of the crossover hit record, ``Buena
Vista Social Club,'' you might feel lost during the documentary
that bears the same name. Shot by German auteur Wim Wenders, the
movie follows musician Ry Cooder and his son Joachim back to Cuba,
where he rediscovered the near-forgotten musical artists of the
pre-Castro era.
</P>
<P>
   Low-key and almost defiantly shapeless, ``Social Club'' doesn't
bother to explain the genesis of the album until around the
75-minute mark. It spends its time shifting back-and-forth between
the faded, jalopy-clogged streets of Havana, and concert halls in
Amsterdam and New York, where the reinvigorated musicians
(including singers Ibrahim Ferrer and Omara Portuondo) fill the air
with their melancholy, sexy ballads.
</P>
<P>
   Their music saves the movie, which treats them less as
individuals than exotic, found objects. We never learn to what
extent these 70- and 80-something musicians, whose bare-bones homes
the filmmakers visit, profited from the Cooder album. When the
camera stops moving around long enough to learn a little bit about
the aged musicians, Wenders elicit only the most perfunctory
stories from them about how they got into the music biz. It's as if
he were more interested in his nifty digital camera than in the
people he aimed it at. (Wenders himself calls the movie a
``musicmentary,'' maybe to dodge responsibility for the ways
``Social Club'' fails as a documentary.)
</P>
<P>
   If you're a fan of the album, you'll enjoy seeing the artists in
action. If you're new to the ``Buena Vista'' phenomenon, spend your
money on the album.
</P>
<P>
   ``Buena Vista Social Club''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B -
</P>
<P>
   A documentary by Wim Wenders. Rated G. One hour, 41 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Go for the music, but don't expect to learn much
about the musicians.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-15-99 1538EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
