<HEADER>
A6102 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-YESTERDAY-COX     06-15 0395
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-YESTERDAY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Romantic fantasy awkward but gleams with promise
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL FRIDAY, JUNE 18. DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN.)
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The romantic fantasy ``Twice Upon a Yesterday'' starts out with
flat-footed awkwardness but gradually grows deeper, nimbler. Its
ideas about love and destiny gleam with promise, even if the movie
never quite finds the structure to show them off properly. It's a
near-miss.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas Henshall plays Victor, a wreck of a London actor pining
for the girlfriend he lost a year ago. That's when Sylvia (Lena
Headey) found out about his fling with an actress, and quickly
tumbled into love with a man she's met at her health club, David
(Mark Strong).
</P>
<P>
   The night before the new couple is to wed, Victor ties one on
and stumbles into two magical Spanish garbage collectors (don't
ask). These would-be whimsical wizards are a jarring element, as is
Elizabeth McGovern, playing a bartender who lends Victor a heavily
symbolic umbrella. These ``magic'' characters stick out awkwardly;
the screenplay, by Rafa Russo, is like a promising stew full of
oddly-flavored lumps like this.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, the garbage guys send Victor back in time to save his
relationship with Sylvia. It's hard to care at first, since Victor
(played by the bug-eyed, sweaty Henshall) doesn't seem to rate a
second chance. But as he glows with joy at having Sylvia again _
and schemes to keep her from encountering Mark at the health club _
his scruffy-puppy charm expands.
</P>
<P>
   Here's when the movie finds its most interesting theme: What if,
even with the help of magic and foresight, you discovered that love
follows its own, unpredictable rules of destiny? ``Twice'' becomes
much more lively as Sylvia becomes an active character in the
drama, and Penelope Cruz (``Open Your Eyes'') turns up as the
world's most luscious bartender. You can almost forgive director
Maria Ripoll for letting the garbagemen reappear in the last scene.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIE REVIEW
</P>
<P>
   ``Twice Upon a Yesterday''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C +
</P>
<P>
   Starring Douglas Henshall, Lena Headey. Rated R for language and
a scene of sexuality. 1 hour, 35 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: An awkward but sometimes appealing fantasy about
the vagaries of love.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
