<DOCNO> NYT19990615.0127 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-15 15:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6104 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-LEVENDOSKY-COLUMN-N     06-15 1034
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-LEVENDOSKY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HYDE ATTACKS FIRST AMENDMENT AND PARENTAL AUTHORITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (Repeating for all needing)  
 (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 (EDITOR'S NOTE: Charles Levendosky, editorial page editor of the
Casper, Wyo., Star-Tribune, has a national reputation for First
Amendment commentary. His e-mail address is
levendos(AT-sign)trib.com.)  
(mk) 
 By CHARLES LEVENDOSKY   
 c.1999 Casper (Wyo.) Star-Tribune   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill., who failed to lead his GOP cohorts to a
conviction of President Clinton on any articles of impeachment, is
now leading a charge against parents and the First Amendment. Let
us hope he has the same measure of success with this ill-conceived
effort.
</P>
<P>
   On June 8, Hyde, who chairs the House Judiciary Committee,
introduced the ``Children's Defense Act of 1999''(H.R. 2036), a
bill with such broad language that newspaper carriers under 17
years of age (defined as minors in the bill) may be forbidden to
read the newspapers they carry.
</P>
<P>
   And the newspaper company that puts a newspaper into the hands
of minors may be fined _ if that newspaper contains ``detailed
verbal descriptions or narrative accounts of explicit sexual or
violent material.'' How does one cover a war without such violent
details, or report on the horrors of genocide without such
descriptions?
</P>
<P>
   The bill does not spell out the amount of the fine, but anyone
convicted of allowing a minor to read Stephen Crane's ``Red Badge
of Courage'' or letting a 16-year-old see the move ``Schindler's
List'' could be imprisoned for five years and fined. Yes, these
powerful tales of war and the Holocaust also fall under the
material prohibited to minors by Hyde's bill.
</P>
<P>
   The bill defines violent material as ``sadistic or masochistic
activity, including flagellation or torture by or upon a person,
acts of mutilation of the human body, or rape.'' That covers just
about all the inhumane acts that occur during war or are
perpetrated by dictatorial regimes. Shall we then hide these truths
from our 16-year-olds, when two years later, they could be faced
with fighting on some distant shore?
</P>
<P>
   Shall we keep them naive about the horrors of war, the violence
in inner cities, the history of genocide, the despicable acts of
torture done in dictatorships around the world?
</P>
<P>
   The material forbidden includes ``any picture, photograph,
drawing, sculpture, videogame, motion picture film, or similar
visual representation or image, book, pamphlet, magazine, printed
matter, or sound recording.''
</P>
<P>
   The bill uses a three-prong test to determine what sexual or
violent material is prohibited. If taken as a whole, the material
``1) predominantly appeals to the prurient, shameful, or morbid
interests of minors; 2) is patently offensive to prevailing
standards in the adult community as a whole with respect to what is
suitable material for minors; and 3) is utterly without redeeming
social importance for minors.''
</P>
<P>
   The language is vague. How does an adult know what is ``utterly
without redeeming social importance for minors''? A bookseller
might purge his store of the Greek tragedies, Greek mythology, the
medieval epic ``Beowulf,'' Dante's ``The Inferno,'' Richard
Wright's ``Native Son,'' John Gardner's ``Grendel,'' Erich Maria
Remarque's ``All Quiet on the Western Front'' _ to name only a few
that might fall victim to this legislation.
</P>
<P>
   This bill and others like it have been sparked by the school
shootings at Columbine High School. The aim of these bills is
misdirected and based upon false premise. H.R. 2036 claims that
``hundreds of studies have proven conclusively that children who
are consistently exposed to violence on television have a higher
tendency to exhibit violent and aggressive behavior, both as
children and later in life.'' No so.
</P>
<P>
   Social scientists who conduct such studies about violence have
arrived at differing and mixed results. A child's aggressive
behavior is more a result of drugs, alcohol and physical or sexual
abuse within a family.
</P>
<P>
   Studies have also shown that males who have just completed some
aerobic exercise and then are angered will show more aggressive
behavior than they would had they not exercised. Shall we then
criminalize aerobic exercise?
</P>
<P>
   The National Research Council, an agency within the National
Academy of Sciences, did an exhaustive study on the causes of
violence and aggressive behavior in 1993 and did not consider the
media a significant problem. Truth is, some test subjects do
exhibit more aggressive behavior for a short period of time after
viewing a violent movie or TV show _ some, but not most.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, if parents feel that TV is contributing to the
aggressive behavior of their children, the solution is simple. Turn
the thing off.
</P>
<P>
   Pull the plug. Lock all the TVs in a room or a closet. We don't
need the government telling us what we or our children
``should''view.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde's bill gives no latitude for parents to decide what their
children should read or see or hear. The government will do that
for us. If parents show any of the prohibited material to their
children, they can be fined or imprisoned. There is no parental
exception built into this proposed legislation.
</P>
<P>
   We're beginning to see the price we pay when we think of the
government as the Santa who will give us all we wish. When we ask
the government to help us raise our children, it will. And it will
tell us what is prohibited and what is best. It will force its
rules and regulations between parents and child. ``Government knows
best'' is the new TV show, starring Henry Hyde.
</P>
<P>
   With all the problems in H.R. 2036, no wonder that the bill is
not scheduled to have any public hearings. Not a single one. Keep
the public out. Keep parents from knowing how the Congress will
structure their lives. The House Rules Committee is expected to
send the bill to the floor of the House this week for a vote.
</P>
<P>
   Now is the time for members of the public to call their
representatives to object. Later will be too late. This bill is not
only an attack on the First Amendment right of free speech and
freedom of the press, it is also an assault on parental authority _
and the family itself.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
