</P>
<P>
   ANCIENT MAN: Humans, armed with cellular phones and laptop
computers, still basically carry the genes of the hunters and
gatherers of the Paleolithic Age, more than 15,000 years ago. And
some scientists think that we cannot possibly understand why we get
sick today unless we examine what we ate and how we lived back
then. (Includes 4-column color photo of scientist in front of a
series of skulls of ancient man.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: FUSSY BABIES: Geometric shapes and familiar objects, as
seen on the Fussy Baby Help Page Web site, often prove a calming
influence for fussy babies. (Includes 18-pica B&AMP;W photo of
geometric shapes poster from web site.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH SCIENCE BRIEFS: Details of a crater probably dug by an
asteroid that might have been 500 miles in diameter and evidence of
ancient seas gone dry are among the earliest findings of a
topographic mapping satellite that began beaming data back from
Mars two months ago, scientists say. (Includes 1-column color photo
of Mars.
</P>
</TEXT>
