<HEADER>
A6118 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      06-15 1043
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VARIETY OF PLANTS AT HOME ON DUNES &HT;     

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KATHY HUBER 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
(Undated) Q: What can I plant on the dunes and in the garden at my
beach home? &QL; 
_ J.P.M. &QR;
<P>
   A: James Webb, an associate professor in Texas A&AMP;M University's
marine biology department, recommends various grasses to help
stabilize sandy dunes. Three found on Texas Coast dunes that top
his list are bitter panic (Panicum amarum), a common dune grass
that matures to 2 or 3 feet in height; seashore dropseed
(Sporobolus virginicus), a Bermudalike grass that prefers the lower
front area of the dune, where it traps soil and allows the dune to
grow naturally; and marshhay cordgrass (Spartina patens), which
reaches a mature height of about 2 feet.
</P>
<P>
   These three grasses are available at the Texas A&AMP;M's commercial
nursery at 200 Seawolf Parkway on Pelican Island in the Galveston
area. Call 409-740-4542 for hours and information.
</P>
<P>
   The sporadic need of dune plants fluctuates and is heavily
influenced by storms that destroy the beachfront and dunes. This
sporadic need, in turn, affects availability of plants and, not
surprisingly, these plants can be difficult to find.
</P>
<P>
   For example, one native perennial grass with ornamental
seedheads on Webb's dune list is sea oats (Uniola paniculata), but
this plant is not currently available at the nursery.
</P>
<P>
   Other stabilizing vegetation includes the sand-hugging sea
purslane (Sesuvium portulacastrum) and the goats-foot morning glory
(Ipomea pes-caprae), but, again, finding these commercially is
difficult. The goats-foot morning glory is a beach plant that binds
soil above tide levels. It is rather pretty with cloven-hooflike
6-inch foliage and 2-inch pink-purple flowers. This plant is mildly
poisonous.
</P>
<P>
   The beach evening primrose (Oenothera drummondii) is attractive
and useful on the dunes, as is Indian blanket (Gaillardia
pulchella), a familiar Texas wildflower. Large-leaf pennywort
(Hydrocotyle bonariensis), a perennial, has round, shiny green
foliage that hovers above the sand.
</P>
<P>
   If you do not have any of these plants on your dunes, perhaps
you have a neighbor with one or more who could share a start with
you. It is possible that local nurseries will have supplies of the
evening primrose and gaillardia at some time.
</P>
<P>
   A great number of plants, most of which are not difficult to
find in local nurseries, can grow behind the dunes where they are
afforded some protection from the constant and drying wind and salt
spray.
</P>
<P>
   You may need to modify the sandy soil somewhat to boost moisture
retention and nutrient supply. This can be easily done by amending
the sand with compost; use a layer of mulch in flower beds to help
modify soil temperature and encourage moisture retention.
</P>
<P>
   Windbreaks _ whether you rely on the dunes themselves, your
house or even large shrubs _ can increase gardening possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   Plants that serve as windbreaks or simply as larger permanent
fixtures in the garden should be low-maintenance once established,
especially if they must survive with neglect when you are away from
your house for extended periods.
</P>
<P>
   Large, low-maintenance shrubs that serve as windbreaks or simply
as evergreens include:
</P>
<P>
   Chinese palms top out at about 6 feet and are widespreading.
</P>
<P>
   Coppertone loquat is an attractive medium-size tree/shrub cross
between a loquat and a hawthorn.
</P>
<P>
   Elaeagnus, a large, billowy shrub with silvery-green foliage and
tiny but fragrant fall blooms, is one of the easiest plants in any
garden.
</P>
<P>
   Ligustrum is a bushy, tall evergreen with glossy foliage and
white, fragrant spring flowers. It can be pruned up into a small
tree so that you can grow annuals and perennials beneath its
canopy.
</P>
<P>
   Oleanders (dwarf and standard) are island favorites.
</P>
<P>
   Pineapple guava is an underused large shrub/small tree that
matures to about 12 feet in height. The white blooms with red
stamens in spring are followed by fruit that can be used to make
jelly. Foliage has gray undersides.
</P>
<P>
   Wheeler dwarf green pittosporum and variegated pittosporum are
also candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Wax myrtle, an easy, native evergreen, has dense, aromatic
foliage. Birds like the berries. Mature height is around 15 feet,
width is about 12 feet. This, too, can be pruned up into a small
tree. Dwarf cultivars also are available.
</P>
<P>
   A deciduous large plant/tree that should also grow at the beach
is the vitex _ a great ornamental tree that reaches 12 or 15 feet
in height. This easy-care plant has aromatic gray-green foliage and
produces purple spikes during the summer. Remove these for extended
blooms.
</P>
<P>
   The crape myrtle also grows on Galveston Island.
</P>
<P>
   Don't forget that hibiscus _ hardy or tropical _ are excellent
seashore suggestions. These will provide high color. Or plumeria, a
drought-tolerant island plant with highly fragrant blooms used in
leis.
</P>
<P>
   The spring-fall flowering Cassia corymbosa produces yellow
flowers on plants that can reach 10 feet in height. Yellow bells
(Tecoma stans) produces showers of golden-yellow, tubular blooms,
on a deciduous plant that can be used as a shrub or small tree.
</P>
<P>
   Perennials that help bring color to the beach garden include:
daylilies; firecracker plants with orange-red tubular flowers that
attract nectar-lovers and expansive tufts of ferny, green foliage;
gaura, a native, with white flowers that resemble butterflies;
lantana; lazy daisy, which has small white flowers with yellow
centers that open around midday and is an excellent candidate for
sandy soil; pentas to attract butterflies; society garlic;
spiderwort; verbena; and wedelia, a vigorous, spreading groundcover
with dark-green foliage and bright yellow, daisylike blooms.
</P>
<P>
   Ornamental grasses such as zebra grass (Miscanthus sinensis)
with its yellow-banded green foliage, and bamboo muhly
(Muhlenbergia dumosa), highly textural with clouds of feathery
foliage, are good choices. These would pair nicely with daylilies
and black-eyed Susans.
</P>
<P>
   Mail garden questions to Kathy Huber, garden editor, Houston
Chronicle, P.O. Box 4260, Houston, Texas 77210. The bulk of mail
prevents replies to all unpublished letters.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
