<P>
   INTERNATIONAL NEWS (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-EUROPE (Paris) _ The war in Kosovo obscured something of
a revolution in another part of Europe. Over the past few months,
the leaders of Britain and Germany have formalized a centrist,
Clinton-style manifesto to further distance their leftist parties
from decades of higher taxes, stringent government economic
controls and a social welfare system that is cushy by American
standards. By CRAGG HINES.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SOCIAL-SECURITY (Washington) _ House Ways and Means Committee
Chairman Bill Archer urges his congressional colleagues to forget
their partisan ties and work to rescue Social Security. Archer's
comments follow the release of a survey that revealed Americans
want Congress to preserve, protect and defend Social Security. By
STEVE LASH.
</P>
<P>
   Y2K-SENATE (Washington) _ The Senate approves a bill aimed at
preventing a potential onslaught of lawsuits blaming companies for
failing to overcome Year 2000 computer glitches. The measure would
give businesses a chance to fix any problems before a lawsuit can
be filed. By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN.
</P>
<P>
