<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEAVE ME ALONE, OR ELSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court sometimes hands down a startling
decision that initially seems silly but on close examination turns
out to be a wise preemptive strike against a growing but barely
perceived cultural problem.
</P>
<P>
   The high bench produced such a decision May 24 when it ruled
that school boards may be held liable if they do nothing to stop
the sexual harassment of one student by another. It immediately
prompted loud wails that the ruling would spawn endless, expensive
lawsuits and drag school administrators into an area of childhood
behavior that is none of their business anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Justice Anthony Kennedy, writing for the four
dissenters, warned against this very prospect, grimly predicting an
``avalanche of liability.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy also argued that local school discipline should be
capable of handling ``routine problems of adolescence'' without
invoking Title IX, the federal law that prohibits sex
discrimination in educational institutions. He described the
concept of sexual harassment as behavior exclusive to adults, not
the normal conduct of youngsters ``just learning to interact with
their peers.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps he had in mind the notorious case of a six-year-old in
North Carolina who was suspended from school for kissing a
classmate on the cheek a few years ago. Public outrage at that
ridiculous overreaction was so overwhelming that the school was
forced to renounce the suspension.
</P>
<P>
   But Kennedy sounded out of touch with today's reality. Nowadays
children grow up faster than they did in his youth and mine. They
are bombarded with images of explicit sex and violence. They are
not the innocents we used to be at their age.
</P>
<P>
   It does come as a shock to us older folk that the teasing and
flirting among boys and girls that is standard childhood behavior
might become so overtly offensive as to warrant a lawsuit. But that
is what happened in the case confronting the court.
</P>
<P>
   The victim was LaShonda Davis, an 11-year-old girl in the fifth
grade of an elementary school in Monroe County, Ga. She complained
repeatedly to her teachers and to the principal that a male
classmate persistently tried to touch her breasts and genital area
and pressed her to have sex with him. Her grades fell off. She
wrote a suicide note.
</P>
<P>
   School officials did not take her charges seriously and did
nothing _ after all, the boy was only 11. Her mother sued the local
school board for $500,000 in damages. Although she lost in the
lower courts, the Supreme Court has now reinstated her suit. A jury
will determine if the allegations merit a financial remedy.
</P>
<P>
   In her majority opinion, Sandra Day O'Connor tried to draw a
line between crude adolescent horseplay and serious sexual
harassment. To be illegal, she said, it must be ``so severe,
pervasive and objectively offensive that it can be said to deprive
the victims of access to the educational opportunities or benefits
provided by the school.''
</P>
<P>
   In real life, this is going to be a difficult line to draw
except in the most extreme instances. There are no clear guidelines
here. Early flirtations between the sexes are awkward and sometimes
misunderstood at any age.
</P>
<P>
   What if a child exaggerates the conduct of another? What if
officials think boys are merely being boys? What if girls don't
understand the emotions they can arouse with overt flirting? Who is
at fault when trouble arises and what can schools do about it?
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy is right. This will mean a big headache for school
administrators.
</P>
<P>
   But the court's ruling was a necessary decision. Otherwise, the
justices would have signaled that anything goes in determining what
is acceptable conduct between classmates of the opposite sex.
</P>
<P>
   Educators now know that they cannot simply ignore behavior that
is embarrassing and hurtful beyond the psychological bumps of
routine childhood interaction. They must put up at least the
appearance of concern, no matter how imperfect their ability to
monitor what the students are doing.
</P>
<P>
   Sexual harassment is no longer a legal problem just for adults.
Now our kids have a remedy for it too.
</P>
<P>
   (Marianne Means can be reached at 202-298-6920 and, by e-mail,
at means(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
