<SLUG> BC-JAIL-ART-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WANTED: DIRECTOR FOR ALBANY'S OLD JAIL ART CENTER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JANET TYSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, Texas _ The Old Jail Art Center has added a unique twist
to its profile of candidates for the next museum director's job:
It's looking for an executive who can talk cattle as well as art.
</P>
<P>
   Situated in the historic cattle and oil town of Albany _ about
an hour east of Abilene _ the Old Jail has been without an
executive director since January, when Joeliene Magoto resigned to
accept a post that would take her closer to her family in Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Admittedly, it sometimes seems as if the Old Jail Art Center
could run on its own.
</P>
<P>
   It enjoys national exposure. Word has spread via television with
a segment on ``CBS Sunday Morning'' and in a variety of popular
publications.
</P>
<P>
   American and European tourists have responded favorably.
</P>
<P>
   The museum's professionalism is praised by art administrators
ranging from Jack Nokes, president of the Texas Association of
Museums, to Ted Pillsbury, independent consultant and former
director of the Kimbell Art Museum.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Old Jail is almost an aberration,'' Nokes says. ``It's
such a fine gem of a museum in such a small community.''
</P>
<P>
   Pillsbury points to the museum's wealth of support from patrons
throughout its region. The Old Jail is ``a community organization
in the best sense,'' he says. ``Everyone is encouraged to take part
in it, to take responsibility for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Its collection is solidly based on key groups of pre-Columbian
ceramics, Tang Dynasty tomb figures, modernist works by European
and American artists, and works by Texas artists, primarily of the
20th century. Several of the museum's key holdings _ including an
exquisite Calder mobile and a late painting by Paul Klee _ were
featured in the recent exhibition ``Bill Bomar: The Collector and
the Artist.'' Bomar, who died in 1991, and his cousin Reilly Nail
co-founded the Old Jail in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   The original jail building _ which has been augmented by two
modern additions _ is a national landmark, built in 1877 of
hand-hewed local limestone.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a $2 million endowment and a financially prudent
board,'' Nail adds. ``And we just completed a capital campaign of
about $3.2 million in six months for the new building and its
endowment.''
</P>
<P>
   And the museum's four full-time staff members, board of 12
trustees and host of volunteers are precisely focused and
passionately dedicated.
</P>
<P>
   But as gracefully as the Old Jail flew on autopilot, Nail is
adamant about its need for a new executive.
</P>
<P>
   ``If nothing else, we need a director in order to keep our
accreditation,'' he says. Not to mention its standing as a serious
organization: The Old Jail receives unqualified support from
Albany's substantial population of wealthy, Ivy League-educated
citizens. Unmediated by professional administration, that kind of
enthusiasm can turn an institution into a patrons' plaything.
</P>
<P>
   ``And that's the last thing we want,'' Nail says.
</P>
<P>
   The stumbling block is the pay scale, which is in the
neighborhood of $30,000-$35,000, Nail says. It's the kind of
compensation that would only be attractive to someone starting out
(as Magoto was) or coming to the end of a career _ in other words,
someone motivated by interests other than income.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're at a point where we've gotten practically nowhere with
this search,'' Nail says. ``We're looking at graduate programs in
arts administration. We have people of some importance out looking
for us.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not desperate,'' he adds. ``But we're feeling frustrated
_ and that's frustrated in italics.''
</P>
<P>
   So if patience is one of your virtues and you know a polled
Hereford from a horned, then the Old Jail Art Center may have an
offer you can't resist.
</P>
<P>
   (Janet Tyson is art critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online serviATQ0Z ATQ0Z +++UFHi &QL; !r1e!
</P>
</TEXT>
