<HEADLINE>
QUITAQUE'S GUINEA DROP TRADITION IS UP IN THE AIR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ART CHAPMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Quitaque is a small, hard-to-spell community of 500 that sits
just beneath the Caprock in Northwest Texas. For most of the year,
people don't pay much attention to the town, unless they go to
Caprock Canyon State Park to see the buffalo, or pass through on
the way to Turkey for Bob Wills Days.
</P>
<P>
   But early each June, Quitaque makes headlines with its annual
National Trails Day celebration and the controversial guinea drop
that goes with it.
</P>
<P>
   This year, things were supposed to be relatively quiet because a
faint-hearted chamber of commerce decided to do away with the
guinea drop and have a guinea bed race instead. Folks were supposed
to sit in the middle of a bed on wheels while holding a guinea.
Teammates pushed them down the main street in town.
</P>
<P>
   Restaurant owner Mary Pigg said phooey to that. She wanted a
real drop.
</P>
<P>
   The original guinea drop was the idea of Mary's husband, Roye
Pigg, who used to be a more adventuresome head of the Quitaque
Chamber of Commerce. Roye Pigg had local farmer and pilot Coy
Franks fly over town and drop a guinea out the window of his
single-engine plane. Below, kids craned their necks to see exactly
where the bird would glide.
</P>
<P>
   Guineas aren't great fliers, but they can glide like a condor.
The kids would rush to where the bird landed, capture it, take a
coupon for $100 off its leg and present the bird and coupon to Roye
Pigg. He inspected the bird for damage, then paid off.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, the celebration received national attention from animal
rights groups who insisted that dropping the guinea from an
airplane was ``alien to a bird's evolutionary experience'' and
could cause the guinea to ``easily sustain unseen internal
injuries, or be killed, in the trauma of being dropped, followed by
being chased.''
</P>
<P>
   United Poultry Concerns, a Maryland-based animal rights
organization, and several humane societies threatened to send
protesters to Quitaque, but they never showed up. The birds were
not injured.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the current chamber of commerce became worried about
youngsters falling down and skinning their knees while chasing the
fleeing guineas; they worried about liability.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Pigg worried about tradition.
</P>
<P>
   Roye Pigg was killed last year and Mary Pigg wanted to honor his
memory. She insisted that she would continue the guinea drop. She
bought five guineas and wanted Franks to drop them over town. But
Franks had other commitments and couldn't oblige.
</P>
<P>
   So, Pigg decided to climb 20 feet to the top of her Sportsman
Restaurant and drop them from there. ``If we have to drop them off
the top of the Sportsman,'' she announced, ``we're going to have
the guinea drop.''
</P>
<P>
   Three of the guineas flew away and only one swooped to the
ground as it was supposed to. Pigg had advertised three drops, so
that guinea had to make the leap three times.
</P>
<P>
   The other birds showed up at area coops.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was kind of nerve-wracking,'' Pigg told a Lubbock reporter
after the drop. ``But it went off without a hitch, I guess.''
</P>
<P>
   She hasn't announced plans for next year.
</P>
<P>
   (Art Chapman writes a weekly column on things Texas for the Fort
Worth Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7422, or e-mail:
Artc(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
