<HEADER>
A6167 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-FRENCH-ALPS-$A     06-15 1124
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-FRENCH-ALPS-$ADV20-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEIDI COUNTRY, WITH FRENCH FOOD 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., June 20) 
(jt) 
 By GLENN COLLINS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The great lightning summer getaway to the French Alps began as a
timeout during the dream tour, a 30th wedding anniversary trip to
France with our two sons. We reasoned that after days of
togetherness exploring Normandy last July _ examining the Bayeux
Tapestry, poking into nearly every pillbox on the Calvados coast
and standing awe-struck in the great American cemetery at
Colleville-sur-Mer _ it might be wise to separate for a while.
Then, we could appreciate one another even more when we reunited.
</P>
<P>
   Thus the plan: our sons, Brian and Alex, generously agreed to
endure four days of residence in the Paris we love, without the
inhibiting presence of their parents. They reassured Sarah and me
that this would be an acceptable sacrifice for two handsome,
unattached guys in their mid-20s.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Mom and Dad, the madcap anniversary revelers, would
zoom off to the Alps in a rented Mercedes (OK, this was the big
anniversary, not the budget trip). A week later, after the older
generation marveled at snowcapped vistas, the baby boomers and the
Gen-X'ers would meet up in the eighth arrondissement with many
exciting tales to tell.
</P>
<P>
   The only problem with this plan was our utter ignorance of the
French Alps, which we had never visited, and therefore were
passionate about. Friends fueled our rabid Alpinism by contending
that, in the Haute-Savoie, we'd have all the joys of Heidi country,
but with French food.
</P>
<P>
   If the French Alps at a distance seemed initially confusing to a
couple of neophytes, we had two firm but humble ambitions: we
wanted to test ourselves with some strenuous mountain hiking, and
we wanted to have the garden-variety tourist experience of riding
the Aiguille du Midi cable car to its famous 12,600-foot view of
Mont Blanc.
</P>
<P>
   But where to stay? For weeks beforehand we scouted the
guidebooks, and Sarah zapped Alpine Web sites. It seemed that
Chamonix, site of the first Olympic Winter Games in 1924, was
definitely the center of the action for nonwinter visitors. But
there were all of these other legendary towns with marquee ski
names such as Albertville, Courchevel, Megeve and Val d'Isere.
</P>
<P>
   At last we chose Megeve because the Web site pictures were
wonderfully quaint and because the town was the home of an unusual
hotel that intrigued us from its Internet presentation: Les Fermes
de Marie, an Alpine mini-hamlet that seemed to offer a country
paradise.
</P>
<P>
   And so, soon enough, we were braving suicidal Citroens in the
counterclockwise bedlam of l'Etoile during the morning rush. Within
an hour we were rolling along the A6 past field after field of
sunflowers under cloud-flecked skies.
</P>
<P>
   We arrived in Megeve in late afternoon, after a 380-mile drive
and a lunch stop in Beaune. Tooling about as we quested for Les
Fermes de Marie, Megeve appeared beyond-belief picturesque: narrow,
winding cobblestone streets, village squares, weathered fountains,
ivy-covered walls of Savoy ocher and a 14th century church with a
bulbous bronze-green belltower.
</P>
<P>
   As we learned during our stay, Megeve is a curious mixture of
chic and rustic, balancing luxury boutiques and agricultural
festivals, with accommodations ranging from four-star hotels to
farmhouse rooms. Days were warm, with low humidity, and mountain
nights were refreshing; ever visible were the surrounding Alps and
the lush expanse of meadows beneath granite peaks.
</P>
<P>
   We discovered that unlike Chamonix (with its importunate
traffic, its 100,000 summer day-trippers and its hodgepodge of
hotels) and unlike Courchevel (with its planned ski developments),
Megeve is a true village, a center of commerce for 80 surrounding
farms. Thanks to the serendipities of Savoy history, many Megevan
buildings survive from the 15th and 16th centuries. Preservation
and building codes have discouraged the high-rise mania rampant in
other Alpine villages, and Megeve bans autos in the town center.
</P>
<P>
   Les Fermes de Marie turned out to be a hotel that is an ersatz
Savoy village of eight chalets on two acres, with 69 guest rooms,
virtually all of them affording a postcard view of the Rochebrune
Alp.
</P>
<P>
   The owners, Jean-Louis Sibuet and his wife, Jocelyne, are both
second-generation hoteliers who have crafted Les Fermes into their
one-of-a-kind statement, almost as if it were an interconnected
hamlet of Frenchified Joseph Cornell boxes.
</P>
<P>
   The public rooms are a charm festival of antiques, folk art and
warm plaids, seemingly arrayed by a Savoyard Ralph Lauren. In the
homey spaces of Les Fermes, visitors walk under ancient exposed
farmhouse beams on creaky floors through hallways lined with
equally ancient agricultural implements and bosky artifacts:
200-year-old Savoyard pottery, 100-year-old cheese presses, and
sheaves of wheat. There are antique prints as well as folk-art
paintings and wood carvings in a Savoyard naif style, many of them
created by both Sibuets, who have used the hotel as a gallery for
their own art. If on first view the ambiance is aggressively
hospitable, it all works somehow. So does the spa.
</P>
<P>
   Our cozy ground-floor room in a wing of the warrenlike compound
was furnished with French country pieces including a 17th century
armoire, a 200-year-old walnut table, a rose-figured rustic
bedspread; the large well-appointed bathroom was lined with glowing
tiles of rose, pink and white from Salernes.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, the 10-year-old Les Fermes has not been
discovered by Americans, who form only 4 percent of the summer
clientele. ``It is famous in Italy and France, and the concept is
being much imitated in Europe,'' said Andre Seigneur, director of
the Megeve Tourist Office, when we encountered him later in the
week. But, he said, copycats have a difficult time duplicating the
Sibuets' construction techniques.
</P>
<P>
   To build Les Fermes, Sibuet spent most of a decade visiting the
farms of Megeve, surviving endless courtesies, negotiations and not
a few libations, while asking farmers if he could buy the
centuries-old wood from venerable abandoned barns and shepherd
outposts. The antique lumber collection he amassed _ some of the
wood 300 years old, from 60 barns and houses _ became his inventory
for new construction, the frame upon which he built Les Fermes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each piece of wood has a story, and each farmer told me that
story,'' said the 43-year-old Sibuet, after I introduced myself and
asked about Les Fermes. ``Ultimately the farmers would have put the
wood in the fire. But now it has a place. And now the farmers are
proud of their wood and come here to visit it.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Sibuet said she sees Les Fermes as an expression of
mountain life and Savoyard culture _ ``the wood, the antiques, the
artifacts, the cuisine.'' As for the last, we sampled the offerings
at the Grand Salle, the hotel's main restaurant (there are two
others), which seats 140, with its floor of worn 200-year-old
terra-cotta tiles rescued from ancient Savoy castles. We tasted
appetizers (a bacon souffle and fat little grilled bacon-wrapped
langoustines with risotto and local mushrooms) and entrees (sea
bass and pork) and accompanied it all with a robust local $20 gamay
that perfectly complemented the puissant Savoy food.
</P>
<P>
   The next day we took a stroll into town, a seven-minute
streamside walk by the River Arly. We discovered not only Hermes
and Faconnable, but also Le Comptoir, an antiques store that has a
Paris headquarters and is filled with Black Forest treasures. We
also took in the legendarily upscale Aallard ski emporium, where
stretch ski pants were pioneered and where, in winter, jet-setters
secure not just their skis but also their more essential apres-ski
accessories.
</P>
<P>
   We visited the tourist office at the Maison des Freres on Rue
Monseigneur Conseil, a former monastery and school with
three-foot-thick walls that was built in 1730. ``Our goal is to
maintain our Savoy identity and quality of life while increasing
our international clientele, and making the summer season longer,''
Seigneur said. ``But we cannot grow too much.'' Megeve has 5,000
residents but swells to 40,000 in the winter and summer tourist
seasons. Summer tourism in Megeve _ which was established in the
11th century and became a small but fashionable health resort 100
years ago _ actually preceded the winter invasions of the beautiful
people. It wasn't until 1916 that the Baroness Maurice de
Rothschild decreed that Megeve should become a French ski resort
akin to St. Moritz in Switzerland. She attracted kings, queens,
moguls, politicians and the idle rich.
</P>
<P>
   The director Roger Vadim shot ``Les Liaisons Dangereuses'' with
Jeanne Moreau at the Hotel Mont Blanc, which we found in the Place
de l'Eglise. Jean Cocteau, who decorated the bar in the hotel
(which the Sibuets now own, in addition to four other Megevan
hotels), named it Les Enfants Terribles. Encountering so many
Parisians, he dubbed Megeve the 21st arrondissement of Paris.
</P>
<P>
   Near the tourist office, the staff of the Mountain Guide Office
at Maison de la Montagne told us that no fewer than 31 guides from
Megeve were available for personal or group mountain jaunts. Among
the recreational options are hiking, summer bobsledding, fishing,
riding, paragliding, mountain biking, rafting, cycling, rock
climbing, long-distance glacier walks and even a six-day climbing
course with a guide leading to the summit of Mont Blanc. And yes,
there is tennis and swimming and golf.
</P>
<P>
   Megeve is also a paradise for randonnees _ rambles, or
unstructured hiking _ with marked trails offering walks that flaunt
Alpine views while threading past farms and waterfalls, through
forests, extravagant wildflower meadows and cool forests of pine.
For newcomers, there are several lovely three-to-four-hour hikes
from the top stage of the cable lift at Rochebrune; these and
longer hikes are depicted on a map (available at the tourist
center) that details nearly 100 miles of walking trails.
</P>
<P>
   And then, we took time out from four days and uncounted miles of
glorious hiking to achieve our other goal. Following the directions
of Ghali Bennani, the concierge at Les Fermes, we drove 22
mountainous miles on improbably scenic roads to Chamonix, the
overcrowded Mont Blanc mecca that is the staging area for the cable
car to Aiguille du Midi, the splinter of granite that affords a
dramatic view of Mont Blanc. When we arrived, the famously long
lines had dispersed that morning because it was foggy and overcast.
We chose to take the cable car up into the fog anyway, even though
we were told at the ticket booth (round-trip tickets $32) that
there was no view of Mont Blanc.
</P>
<P>
   Soaring past the spectacular Bossons glacier as we ascended, we
hit the fog bank, as promised. Miraculously, though, near the top
of the Aiguille, we punched through the fog to the brilliant sun
above. After ascending to the terrace, we had a startling panorama
of Mont Blanc and the surrounding Alps rising from pillowy mist.
</P>
<P>
   On our last day in Megeve we visited L'Alpage du Pre Rosset, a
chalet renovated from a shepherd's barn high on Rochebrune, where
the Sibuets invite the guests from their five hotels to mingle and
meet for lunch. When we arrived, the great silence of the mountains
was broken only by the distant chime of cowbells and a burr of a
breeze. Then some 46 of us sat for a rollicking alfresco meal at a
long communal table under the Alpine sun.
</P>
<P>
   Next day, we drove back to Paris for the grand reunion. Our
celebratory toast in our room at Hotel Le Bristol was spontaneous,
and heartfelt: we vowed not to wait 30 years to return, touched our
glasses and said, ``Bonnes vacances!''
</P>
<P>
   A picture-postcard village, plus high-altitude excursions &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Getting There
</P>
<P>
   Megeve itself can be done on a day trip, but a minimum of four
days is advisable for those wishing to explore the town and its
hiking trails, while using it as a base to visit Chamonix, Le
Montenvers, the great Mer de Glace glacier, and the cable-car
thrills of the neighboring Alps.
</P>
<P>
   By car, Megeve is an hour from Geneva, two hours from Lyons and
six hours from Paris (with no stops). It is also possible to take
the TGV from Paris to Sallanches, which is seven miles from Megeve.
Information
</P>
<P>
   Although Megeve has 37,000 tourist beds, it is often tightly
booked in August, during the annual vacations taken by what
sometimes seems like the entire French population. But during June,
July, September and early October the crowds are gone and, except
during festivals, such as the week around July 14, there are hotel
bargains.
</P>
<P>
   The venerable, busy tourist office at the Maison des Freres on
Rue Monseigneur Conseil is referral central for visitors. Its Web
site is www.megeve.com; telephone (33-4) 50.21.27.28; fax (33-4)
50.93.03.09.
</P>
<P>
   Megeve Reservation is a travel collective that books hotel,
restaurant and excursion packages in two- to four-star hotels;
apartments and weekly rentals are also available; (33-4)
50.21.29.52; fax (33-4) 50.91.85.67.
</P>
<P>
   The Mountain Guide Office at 76 Rue Ambroise Martin offers
dozens of individual and group mountain jaunts and individual or
group courses in such activities as hiking, fishing, paragliding,
mountain biking, rafting and climbing. Information: (33-4)
50.21.55.11; fax (33-4) 50.21.55.03;
www.montblanconline.fr/pages/megvguid.htm.
</P>
<P>
   Where to Stay
</P>
<P>
   Double rooms at Les Fermes de Marie, on Chemin de Riante
Colline, cost $142 to $232 a person (based on six francs to the
dollar), including breakfast and dinner. Six-day packages,
including breakfast, dinner and one lunch in the charming Alpages
chalet on Rochebrune, plus a one-hour treatment in the Ferme de
Beaute (massage, mud baths, skin-toning poultices and herbal
treatments by Anne Semonin, a Parisian skin-care expert), cost
$1,167 to $1,267.
</P>
<P>
   Telephone (33-4) 50.93.03.10; fax (33-4) 50.93.09.84. You can
also refer to the hotel's Web site, www.c-h-m.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
