<HEADLINE>
CABLESS IN LONDON: STRANDED AFTER DARK 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., June 20) 
(jt) 
 By ALAN COWELL    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Eleven p.m. in London's West End: The theaters have
emptied. The movie crowd is spilling onto the streets. The pubs,
regulated by Britain's licensing laws, are about to close. The one
thing that's missing: a taxi ride home. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As Mae West didn't quite say: so many people, so little
transport. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For months now, an outcry has been building among Londoners and
visitors to the city about the erratic late-night behavior of the
traditional London black cab, a creature of increasingly
unpredictable nocturnal habits, particularly in the West End area
between Oxford Circus and Piccadilly Circus that is crammed with
pubs, clubs, theaters and cinemas. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Even the black-cab drivers themselves admit it. ``Virtually
every taxi driver I know now regards the West End as a no-go
area,'' said Keith White, a cabdriver, in a recent letter that was
published in the Evening Standard. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The need for cabs has blossomed, according to Bob Oddy, general
secretary of London's Licensed Taxi Drivers Association. ``There's
been a dramatic upsurge in the number of pubs and clubs in the last
couple of years,'' he said. ``Demand has gone through the roof.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Supply hasn't. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   According to the official count, London has around 24,000 black
cabs _ most of them driven by their owners _ which sounds as if it
ought to be enough. But of those, around 6,000 operate through
computerized central booking systems, and do not routinely pick up
passengers who hail them on the streets. And the majority of the
rest of the black cabs, Oddy said, work days only. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the numbers is a tale of two conflicts. One pits licensed
drivers of the traditional London taxicab against the drivers of
what are called mini-cabs _ private automobiles used as cabs, with
or without a radio link to a dispatcher. The other pits the
black-cab drivers against would-be passengers who want to travel
where the driver does not. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Either way, the would-be passenger is the loser. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Unlicensed mini-cabs are thought by the police to number some
50,000, and their drivers have no qualms about muscling into the
late-night theater crowd _ technically illegal because they are
unlicensed and thus barred from cruising for business. These are
the cars, according to many licensed black-cab drivers, that park
unlawfully, clog the streets and make it impossible for black-cab
drivers to make a living. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And since the surcharge to ride a black cab between 8 p.m. and
midnight is only $1 above the fare on the meter, said Oddy, there's
not much incentive for drivers to work nights. But taking mini-cabs
can be problematic.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mini-cabs may be uninsured. They have no meters, so the fares,
theoretically lower than black-cab fares, are a matter of
negotiation. To make things more confusing, many older black cabs
have recently been sold off to private buyers because of new laws
requiring black cabs to provide wheelchair access. That means that
what looks like a black cab to the untutored eye may in fact be a
decommissioned black cab with a mini-cab driver at the wheel. (The
only way to spot the difference is to check for a meter: unlicensed
cabs don't have them.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, mini-cab drivers are not obliged to learn what
black-cab drivers call ``the knowledge'' _ the compendiumlike
familiarity with London's highways and by-ways that is required to
secure a license. And far more chilling, there have been frequent
reports of men masquerading as mini-cab drivers in order to pick up
women passengers, drive them to secluded places and sexually
assault them.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So that leaves waiting for a black cab, right?  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Well, not quite. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By law, Oddy said, as soon as a black cab stops for a passenger,
the driver is obliged to take the passenger anywhere within a
six-mile radius. But it doesn't always work that way. Sometimes
black-cab drivers will turn down a passenger because it suits them
to do so _ witness the following exchange near Oxford Circus at
around 11.15 on a recent Friday night between this correspondent
and the driver of a black cab. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Highgate, please.'' ``That's north, not east. I'm going east.
Going home.'' Exit black cab.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There are attempts to improve the situation. A law has been
enacted that will at some stage require mini-cabs to be licensed,
meaning that the cars will be inspected for road-worthiness and
that certain categories of driver _ including criminals, illegal
immigrants and moonlighting welfare recipients _ will be barred. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Equally, most London residents and hotel concierges know of
reputable mini-cab companies (some will provide female drivers and
carry only female passengers) or black-cab companies that can be
booked in advance to meet the passenger outside a theater. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On the eve of the millennium, though, you might plan to walk.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Even at New Year's in an ordinary year, only about one fifth of
black-cab drivers go to work. And on Dec. 31, 1999, according to
Oddy, black-cab drivers will demand a $40 bonus from every single
passenger if they are to work at all.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
