<HEADLINE>
TV NOTES: KEN BURNS AND GM; CABLE BUSINES SHOWS; NBC'S `LATER
TODAY' 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A 10-Year Bet on Ken Burns  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Contortions of envy may well ripple through the documentary
filmmakers' world Thursday. That is when General Motors plans to
announce an unusual 10-year commitment to underwrite the future
film projects of Ken Burns.
</P>
<P>
   General Motors has been the sole corporate underwriter for
Burns' earlier films, like ``The Civil War,'' ``Baseball'' and one
coming out in the fall, ``Not for Ourselves Alone: The Story of
Elizabeth Cady Stanton and Susan B. Anthony.''
</P>
<P>
   But these have been financed on a film-by-film basis. The
arrangement being announced Thursday will commit GM to financing 35
percent of every documentary project that Burns undertakes for the
next 10 years, and to paying for 100 percent of the extensive
educational projects that accompany his films, which are produced
for public television.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because I'd worked for 20 years and had not made a real
clunker, I thought they might take a flier on me for more than one
film at a time,'' Burns said by telephone from his editing studio
in Walpole, N.H.
</P>
<P>
   The grant's dollar value cannot be specified since the films
have not yet been budgeted or even conceived. Burns' breakthrough
documentary, ``The Civil War'' in 1990, cost about $3.5 million to
produce, but it was 11 hours long. The three-hour ``Frank Lloyd
Wright,'' shown last fall, cost less than $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   Burns said the deal would provide financial stability not only
for himself and his company, Florentine Films, but also for the
scores of associates who work on his films on a freelance basis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having a long-term commitment allows you to do some real
long-range planning,'' Burns said. ``I still have to go out and
raise the other 65 percent, and that's not a snap of the finger.
But now, if we have a good idea and it stands the test of our own
poking and prodding, at least we've got this head start on a
budget. And it gives comfort to other underwriters when we approach
them, because they can see it has a shape and a form already.''
</P>
<P>
   For General Motors, it is a chance to burnish a prestigious
relationship with an established ``cultural icon,'' as Phil
Guarascio, vice president and general manager for marketing and
advertising, the executive in charge of the arrangement, described
Burns.
</P>
<P>
   Guarascio said the company had usually spent more on promotion
and on educational programs for a Burns film than on the film
itself, providing booklets, posters, CDs and so on to schools and
libraries.
</P>
<P>
   Also, General Motors also prides itself on sponsoring a
filmmaker who has trained many others. The company and Burns
calculated that 20 to 25 of those who have worked with him through
the years have ``graduated'' to decision-making creative positions
on Burns' films or on those of other documentary filmmakers.
</P>
<P>
   Among them are Stephen Ives, Ric Burns ( Burns' brother) and
Michael Hill, who have gone on to make their own documentaries, and
Lynn Novick, Paul Barnes and Dayton Duncan, who have become
co-producers with Burns on his projects. Several others who began
as apprentices at Florentine Films have become renowned sound
editors, film editors or writers.
</P>
<P>
   Burns has 8 to 10 full-time employees, he said, and about 40
people at work when a major project is under way, like ``Jazz,'' a
20-hour series scheduled to be shown on PBS in November 2000.
</P>
<P>
   After the Stanton-Anthony film (Nov. 7 and 8 on PBS) and the
jazz series, Burns plans to make a film about Mark Twain. He is
contemplating one about the Rev. Dr. Martin Luther King Jr., as
well as a series on the National Parks system.
</P>
<P>
   _ By LAWRIE MIFFLIN
</P>
<P>
   Financial Competitors  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Wasting no time in seeking to capitalize on the departure of Lou
Dobbs from CNN's ``Moneyline'' program, CNBC announced Tuesday that
it was rushing to complete an expansion of its own evening
financial news roundup to a full hour, from 30 minutes. Starting
Monday, the program, ``Business Center,'' will begin at 6:30
weeknights, the same time as ``Moneyline.''
</P>
<P>
   CNBC left no doubt about the reason for the expansion, citing
``recent changes in the financial news arena.'' Dobbs quit as the
anchor of CNN's ``Moneyline'' last week. That program has had the
highest advertiser price-per-thousand viewers of any on CNN,
higher, in fact, than that of virtually every other news program on
any channel.
</P>
<P>
   CNBC's ``Business Center'' has been the main competitor for
``Moneyline'' for advertisers. (``The Nightly Business Report'' on
PBS competes for financial news viewers but of course does not run
commercials.) Yet ``Business Center'' attracts only about half as
many people as the CNN program.
</P>
<P>
   CNBC spokesman George Jamison said the network was ``bringing in
its big guns'' as co-anchors to try to raise the profile of
``Business Center.'' The big guns are Ron Insana and Sue Herera,
the two most prominent daily anchors for the network.
</P>
<P>
   Insana, anchor of the two-hour afternoon program ``Street
Signs,'' will cut back to one hour on that assignment. Ms. Herera
will give up her role on ``The Edge,'' which now runs from 6 to 7
p.m. but will be shortened to a half hour.
</P>
<P>
   Maria Bartiromo, the current anchor of ``Business Center,'' has
signed a new contract with CNBC that will include taking over the
first hour of the daily ``Street Signs'' and serving as the anchor
for a new program every Friday evening at 7, due to start in the
fall.
</P>
<P>
   _ By BILL CARTER
</P>
<P>
   Here's a Story ...
</P>
<P>
   Though word has leaked out all over the television industry, NBC
News refused Tuesday to make official the news that it has hired as
a co-host of its planned ``Later Today'' program no less a cultural
icon than Florence Henderson, the once and forever mother Brady of
``The Brady Bunch'' and onetime purveyor of ``Wessonality'' in a
memorable series of television commercials for Wesson Oil.
</P>
<P>
   But NBC executives confirmed unofficially Tuesday that she would
be joining the previously announced Jodi Applegate, who is leaving
``Weekend Today'' to lead the new program as host, as well as Asha
Blake, a former news anchor from NBC's station in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   If that triumvirate makes ``Later Today'' sound like NBC's
version of ABC's daily all-female talkfest, ``The View,'' NBC's
unofficial response is that its program will be more news-oriented.
</P>
<P>
   Even Ms. Henderson has news credentials, the NBC executives
pointed out. In 1959 she was one of the ``Today girls,'' as they
were known back then, doing interviews and other related work for
the ``Today'' show with Dave Garroway.
</P>
<P>
   More recently she has been a frequent contributor to
``Politically Incorrect'' on ABC.
</P>
<P>
   ``Later Today'' will start Sept. 7 at 9 a.m., part of an NBC
effort to hold onto the huge audience now commanded by ``Today,''
which has been flowing into programs not owned by the network.
</P>
<P>
   _ By BILL CARTER
</P>
</TEXT>
