<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Each week, The Chronicle offers readers the recipe
for an outstanding dish at a Bay Area restaurant, plus the chef's
secrets for making it a success. Tips and recipe follow in optional
trim.    SECRETS OF SUCCESS: Noodle Dish Offers a Study in Contrasts  
   
 By Michael Bauer  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  Larry Tse, who opened his charming The House
restaurant in North Beach in 1994, characterizes his food as a
``modern and relevant expression of Asian American food.'' The
combinations he prepares are cross-cultural blends that Tse
prepared at home in his pre-restaurant days as an accountant.
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the most expressive dishes is his Warm Wasabi House
Noodles with Grilled Pork. The dish is a masterful study in
contrasting tastes, textures and temperature. The noodles take on
smoky nuances from being stir-fried in a hot wok; the spicy warmth
of wasabi adds even more complexity. The pork is grilled and placed
on top of cool cucumbers to create a vibrant dish.
</P>
<P>
   Naming the restaurant The House was natural for Tse because he
considers what he does to be home cooking. The interior has a
modern but comfortable feel, and the care that Tse puts into his
food is evident in the warm surroundings.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  The House, 1230 Grant Ave. (near Vallejo), San Francisco; &LR; 
 &LR; (415) 986-8612. Open for lunch Monday- &LR;   &LR; Friday and dinner
Monday-Saturday. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; SECRETS OF SUCCESS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The temperature of the noodles. &LR;  The noodles are allowed to sit
after cooking so they're just warm, which intensifies the flavor
and sets up a contrast to the cool cucumbers and the hot grilled
pork.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A hot wok. &LR;  Called ``wok hay,'' stir-frying the noodles in an
extremely hot wok adds a smoky flavor that can't be achieved any
other way. &QL; 
 &QL; 
THE HOUSE'S WARM WASABI NOODLES WITH GRILLED PORK
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   For the pork
</P>
<P>
   1 pound pork loin
</P>
<P>
   11/2 tablespoons minced garlic
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon crushed Korean red pepper flakes (or other dried red
pepper flakes), or to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon minced parsley
</P>
<P>
   Peanut oil, for cooking
</P>
<P>
   For the noodles
</P>
<P>
   1 pound fresh wheat noodles, udon or Shanghai style
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon peanut oil
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons minced garlic
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons dark soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons premium oyster sauce
</P>
<P>
   Pinch of salt
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   4 teaspoons wasabi paste
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon pure sesame oil
</P>
<P>
   11/2 cups peeled, seeded and julienned cucumbers
</P>
<P>
   Julienned green onions, for garnish
</P>
<P>
   Sesame seeds, for garnish
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Slice the pork loin into 1/4-inch slices and marinate with the
garlic, soy sauce, freshly ground black pepper, Korean red pepper
and parsley for 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   While the pork is marinating, cook the noodles in boiling water
for approximately 2 minutes. Drain and set aside. Preheat the grill
or broiler.
</P>
<P>
   Add approximately 1 tablespoon of peanut oil to the marinating
pork, then lift the pork from the marinade and grill it over medium
heat to medium or desired doneness. Let the pork cool for 5
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   While the pork is cooling, stir-fry the noodles: Pour 1
tablespoon peanut oil into a wok set over high heat. Heat, and the
2 tablespoons garlic. Stir-fry briefly, and add the noodles, soy
sauce, dark soy, oyster sauce, salt and sugar. Stir-fry rapidly to
combine.
</P>
<P>
   Remove the noodles from heat. Mix the wasabi with the sesame
oil, and toss with the hot noodles to coat. Transfer the noodles to
a plate and let cool to warm.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, slice the pork into thin strips, if desired.
</P>
<P>
   When ready to serve, arrange the cucumbers over the top of the
warm noodles. Fan out the sliced pork on top of the cucumbers,
garnish with the julienned green onions, and sprinkle with the
sesame seeds.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 429 calories, &LR;   &LR; 30 g protein, 39 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 16 g fat (4 g saturated), 68 mg cholesterol, 856 mg
sodium, 2 g &LR;   &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
