r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEARN-PEACH-SFCHRON &LR;      06-15 0838
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEARN-PEACH-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Every other week, The Chronicle features ``Learning
to Cook'' by Marion Cunningham, a cooking teacher and cookbook
author best known for her revisions of the Fannie Farmer cookbooks.
This column is intended for novices in the kitchen.    LEARNING TO COOK: Simple Peach Upside-down Cake Is Just Right 
 for the Holiday  
   
 By Marion Cunningham  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  When I was a child, the Fourth of July meant
potato salad, hot dogs, upside-down cake or strawberry ice cream,
and sparklers, plus the thrill of watching fountains of colorful
fireworks shoot into the night sky.
<TEXT>
<P>
   In those long-ago days, this event took place in back yards,
where we pooled our food and fireworks so we had a lavish supply of
food and a lengthy display of fireworks.
</P>
<P>
   The pleasure and traditions of our old holidays have changed,
but we can still enjoy sharing our traditional dishes, either
outdoors picnic-style or around the table.
</P>
<P>
   The Peach Upside-down Cake is very good and simple to make. If
the idea of making a cake overwhelms you, serve a different
foolproof dessert: sugared sliced fresh strawberries in individual
bowls with a sauce of melted strawberry ice cream on top.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Marion Cunningham, Bay Area cooking teacher, is the author of &LR; 
 &LR; ``Learning to Cook,'' ``Cooking With Children,'' ``The Fannie &LR; 
 &LR; Farmer Cookbook'' and ``The Breakfast Book,'' among others. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
PEACH UPSIDE-DOWN CAKE
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   Caramel Topping
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup (1/2 stick) butter, cut into four pieces
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup light brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   4 or 5 ripe peaches, peeled, halved and pitted (enough peach
halves to cover the bottom of a 10-inch skillet)
</P>
<P>
   Cake Batter
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup vegetable shortening
</P>
<P>
   2/3 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons vanilla
</P>
<P>
   2 eggs
</P>
<P>
   11/2 cups all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   21/4 teaspoons baking powder
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1 cup milk
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Preheat the oven to 350 degrees. Use either a 10-inch round
skillet, 2-inches deep, or any cake pan that size. The pan must be
able to hold 2 quarts. If you use a cake pan, dissolve and mix the
caramel topping in a small saucepan and then spread it over the
bottom of the cake pan. If you are using a skillet with other than
a metal handle, wrap the handle in 2 thicknesses of aluminum foil
so it won't burn when it is in the oven. It is also a good idea to
put a baking sheet under the skillet or pan so if the fruit juices
bubble over the edge of the pan the baking sheet will catch them.
It is easier to clean a baking sheet than the bottom of your oven.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Making the Caramel Topping:  &LR; Put the butter, brown sugar and
heavy cream into the skillet or a small saucepan pan. Put the
skillet or pan over low heat and stir the mixture until the butter
has melted and the topping is smooth. This only takes a minute or
two. If you are using a cake pan, spread the topping over the
bottom of the cake pan.
</P>
<P>
   Put the peach halves on top of the caramel, pitted-side up. The
smooth rounded part of the peach will show when the cake is turned
out onto a plate. Set aside while you prepare the cake batter.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Mixing the Cake Batter: &LR;  Put the vegetable shortening in a
large mixing bowl. Add the sugar and use a hand-held electric mixer
or a large spoon to mix the shortening and sugar together until
smooth. Add the eggs and vanilla and vigorously stir the mixture _
or mix with a hand-held electric mixer _ until it becomes creamy
and well blended.
</P>
<P>
   Add the flour, baking powder and salt to the shortening and
sugar. Don't worry if the mixture is rather dry and clumpy. Add the
milk all at once and stir until the batter becomes smooth and
blended.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Adding the Batter to the Pan:  &LR; Using a spatula, spread the
batter evenly over the peaches and topping. Spread it gently and
ease it to the edge of the skillet or pan. Remember, when you
finish baking the cake and turn it upside-down, the peaches that
are on the bottom will be on the top of the cake.
</P>
<P>
   Put the skillet or pan in the oven and set the timer for 30
minutes. When rings, check the cake for doneness. It should look
golden on top, but test by inserting a toothpick into the center of
the cake. If it comes out clean, the cake is done; if not, bake for
another 5 minutes and test again. When it is done, take the cake
out of the oven and let cool for 5 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   To remove the cake from the pan, run a knife around the edge of
the pan. Put a plate that is larger than the cake over the pan.
Holding the pan and the plate firmly, quickly turn the pan upside
down so the cake lands on the plate with the peaches on top.
</P>
<P>
   Serve the cake with lightly sweetened whipped cream. (Add 3
tablespoons of sugar to 1 cup of heavy cream in a mixer bowl and
beat with a rotary beater until the cream softly holds its shape.)
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6-8.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 583 calories, &LR;   &LR; 7 g protein, 82 g carbohydrate, &LR; 
 &LR; 26 g fat (11 g saturated), 110 mg cholesterol, 425 mg sodium, 2 &LR; 
 &LR; g fiber. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
