<SLUG> BC-CLASSIC-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BI-RITE MARKET RESTORES NEIGHBORHOOD SHOPPING TO MISSION 
 DISTRICT OF SAN FRANCISCO  
   
  
</HEADLINE>
  
EDITORS NOTE: Bay Area Classics profiles food-related businesses
more than a half century old.    By Tara Duggan 
 &HT;     c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR; From the time it opened in 1940 and through the
next few decades, Bi-Rite was the sort of market where neighborhood
housewives could do all their daily shopping and police officers
stopped by on their daily beats. But as supermarket chains
gradually took over, this Mission store went the way of some
independent grocers, relegated to offering a few cases of beer and
a handful of shriveled onions for stop-gap shopping.
<P>
   Last year, former restaurant chef Sam Mogannam took over the
store that had been in his family for decades. His renovation
restored not only Bi-Rite's classic look but also its dedication to
service and quality foods.
</P>
<P>
   Customers are welcomed by the original neon sign, which was
celebrated in Michael F. Crowe's book, ``Deco by the Bay'' (Penguin
Studio, 1995). Inside the store, farm carts overflow with fresh
produce, artisan breads and cheeses; the deli counter is stocked
with items like house-smoked lox and roast chicken.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the staff followed Sam to the store after the closing of
Rendezvous du Monde, the family's Financial District restaurant, so
former restaurant managers work the registers and chefs cook
prepared foods.
</P>
<P>
   Ned and Jack Mogannam, Sam's father and uncle, took over the
shop in 1964. Now 31, Sam recalls stories from a childhood filled
with afternoons working at the store alongside his sister Freida
and brother Sal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I grew up in two places _ in the Mission and in
West Portal,'' says Sam, who at age six would take the streetcar
alone from his family's home to his parents' shop.
</P>
<P>
   By 1987, when Ned and Jack sold the business to an independent
operator, the store's fresh inventory had been reduced to almost
nothing. But Bi-Rite was saved from the jaws of convenience store
death in 1997, when the transitional owner gave up the store and
Sam took over with his youngest brother, Raphael. They closed the
store for eight months while they renovated it, and reopened it
last June.
</P>
<P>
   Sam's restoration included reopening two skylights and cleaning
up the original deco light fixtures. The brightly tiled facade was
retained, with new stainless steel added for a shiny edge. Sam
worked with friends to create a logo based on the original sign and
commissioned a mosaic for the entryway.
</P>
<P>
   Sam works directly with growers to get organic produce, and
hopes that customers will get used to a more European style of
shopping, planning their menu according to what's in season instead
of a fixed recipe.
</P>
<P>
   Bi-Rite is one of several businesses in this part of the Mission
to become more upscale. Other recent entries include the sleek
Dolores Park Cafe and wildly popular Delfina restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of negative press about the gentrification of
the neighborhood,'' Sam says. ``Some people question if I'm adding
to it. I feel we're just providing a great product.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite changes in the Mission, a number of customers from the
old days still frequent the store. ``Every once in a while someone
will walk in and say, `Hey, I recognize you from when you were 10
years old,''' Sam says. ``It's encouraging to know that they
continue to shop here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
