<SLUG> BC-TASTE-BUNS-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Each week, The San Francisco Chronicle's panel of
professional tasters tries a different product available in
supermarkets.    TASTERS CHOICE: Wonder Burger Buns Come Out on Top _ Barely  
   
 By Robin Davis  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  Summertime means grilling, and although many
people make what they consider a perfect burger, few think about
the bun they put it on.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Packages suggest buns are relatively similar, varying most in
fat _ from 11/2 to 4 grams. Prices are also fairly close with most
in the $1.50-$1.75 range for eight. Some have sesame seeds; most do
not.
</P>
<P>
   Today's panel sampled nine brands of hamburger buns but the
panel couldn't reach a consensus. Different panelists had different
favorites, so no one brand dramatically outscored the others. In
fact, most of the brands were within ten points of each other.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Wonder  &LR; (eight buns, 12 ounces, $1.59 at many supermarkets)
took first place. One panelist described it as ``a cute little
bun,'' while another thought it was ``very ballpark, backyard
barbecue, all-American.'' But another disliked the sweet flavor and
limp texture. Four would buy it; one would not.
</P>
<P>
   Second place went to  &UR; The Cake Box &LR;  (six buns, 12 ounces, $1.59
at Andronico's), the most expensive bun tasted. All the panelists
liked the look, which one described as homemade. Two panelists
liked the flavor, and one thought it had the best balance of
acidity to sweetness. But another panelist thought the texture was
too soft, and the flavor both too sweet and too salty. Three would
buy it, one might buy it, and one would not.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Nature's Cupboard &LR;  (eight buns, 18.5 ounces, $1.49 at Safeway)
and  &UR; Van de Kamp's  &LR; (eight buns, 12 ounces, $.99 at Cala) tied for
third.
</P>
<P>
   Two panelists liked the look of Nature's Cupboard, but others
thought the flavor was too bland. One panelist thought it would
hold up well to a juicy burger. Two would buy it, two might buy it,
and one would not.
</P>
<P>
   The panelists loved the look of Van de Kamp's, but some
complained of a yeasty taste. One panelist described it as ``airy
as cotton candy,'' but another thought it would be good with a
burger. One would buy it, three might buy it, and one would not.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Rainbo  &LR; (eight buns, 12 ounces, $1.69 at Andronico's) came in
sixth. Some thought it looked like a traditional American hamburger
bun. Two panelists disliked the sweetness, but another described
the flavor as pleasant and wheaty. One would buy it, three might
buy it, and one would not.
</P>
<P>
   The panel also tasted Mrs. Wright's, Earthgrain and Columbo but
they all scored too low to rate.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Panelists were John P. Carroll, cookbook author; Shelley Handler,
consultant and food writer; Donna Katzl, chef-owner, Cafe For All
Seasons, San Francisco; Roland Passot, chef-owner of La Folie in
San Francisco and left Bank in Larkspur and Menlo Park; and Kirk
Webber, chef-owner, Cafe Kati, San Francisco. All products are
tasted blind. &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-15-99 1653EDT &QL; 
