A6194 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOSTON-THEATER-REVIEW     06-15 0968
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOSTON-THEATER-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BOSTON MARRIAGE': VICTORIAN WOMEN FROM MAMET 
</HEADLINE>
   (editors: production notes at end of review)  
 (bl)  
 By BEN BRANTLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ Move aside boys, with your gutter talk and
con games and slovenly ways. It's girls' night out in Mametville, a
time to give the other sex a chance to strut and fret its hour upon
the stage. And don't expect a gaggle of tough broads with
machine-gun mouths, either. These ladies are refined; they hang out
in drawing rooms. And believe it or not, they talk as pretty as
anyone out of Oscar Wilde.
</P>
<P>
   Don't bother checking the credits in your program. The author
and director of ``Boston Marriage,'' the strictly feminine,
Victorian-style comedy of manners at the Hasty Pudding Theater
here, is indeed David Mamet, the man who gave the world the sweaty,
macho bumblers and back stabbers of ``American Buffalo,''
``Glengarry Glen Ross'' and ``Speed-the-Plow.''
</P>
<P>
   As though in nose-thumbing response to critics who claim this
razor-witted writer doesn't give his female characters the time of
day, Mamet has devised a filigree work that is, on the surface, the
reverse image of ``American Buffalo,'' the play that made his
reputation. The characters, once again, are a mere but extremely
verbal few. And they again are conspiring ineptly to perpetuate a
scam of sorts.
</P>
<P>
   Here, however, the play's three inhabitants are not only all
women but, in the case of two of them, women who have no use for
men, except economically. Like so many of Mamet's works, ``Boston
Marriage,'' a production of the American Repertory Theater,
presents a world hermetically sealed by its dense language. But the
ripe street vernacular of early Mamet has been replaced by perfumed
locutions of improbable archness. Well, mostly anyway. Obscenities
explode every so often, rather like stink bombs at a garden party.
</P>
<P>
   As a writer Mamet has always been a bit of a showoff, and in
``Boston Marriage'' he is flamboyantly exhibiting his command of
Wildean artifice, which he sends up even as he precisely follows
its rules. It is as though a football player had decided to dance
in the ballet, pointing out as he soars through grands jetes that
the skills of the two disciplines are not all that dissimilar.
</P>
<P>
   The results are, from time to time, devastatingly funny. And the
work is truly blessed by its actresses, Felicity Huffman, Mary
McCann and Rebecca Pidgeon, all of whom have memorably worked with
Mamet (Ms. Pidgeon is also his wife) and give impeccably
disciplined comic performances here.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, though, ``Boston Marriage'' feels like a parlor
trick that is performed, with slight variations, over the course of
an entire evening. It is an exceptionally clever exercise, a
pastiche carried out with knowing and subversive detail.
</P>
<P>
   But there is a distancing air of contempt to the proceedings, a
faint disdain for the emptiness of posturing estheticism. Here the
characters are never much more than their rhetorical flourishes. As
a half-hour sketch ``Boston Marriage'' could be smashingly
effective. As a two-hour play it starts to look anorexic.
</P>
<P>
   The phrase of the play's title is an old-fashioned term for two
women who live together, possibly as lovers, and the comedy follows
the route to such a union. Anna (Ms. Huffman), is an elegant and
worldly sort who, though the mistress of a rich man, is really in
love with her younger protegee, Claire (Ms. Pidgeon).
</P>
<P>
   Claire, alas, has given her heart elsewhere, and she hopes to
enlist Anna's cooperation in her seduction of the young woman, whom
she has invited to Anna's house. A tangle of coincidence-woven
complications arises; Anna and Claire plot feverishly and
ridiculously to escape it with a scheme that brings to mind Mamet's
early play ``The Shawl.''
</P>
<P>
   Observing all this with bewilderment is Anna's Scottish parlor
maid, Catherine (Ms. McCann), whose name and nationality Anna can
never get right, in what turns out to be the play's funniest
running joke.
</P>
<P>
   This is all charted through fencing-match banter and elaborately
woven tropes that show a perfect satiric ear for late-19th-century
literature, plump with melodramatic invocations and Pre-Raphaelite
and biblical imagery. Mamet's upper-class women can't resist the
temptation to embroider on a metaphor, even when it means
forestalling the contrastingly plain-spoken Catherine's delivery of
essential news.
</P>
<P>
   Anna, for example, sardonically speaks of love as that thing
``which like the sea, which like religion and expensive jewelry,
conquers all.'' When she suggests serving Claire's new friend a
freshly baked pie (``Stress cannot exist in the presence of a
pie''), Claire answers: ``I am concocting a seduction. I do not
require a pastry chef.''
</P>
<P>
   And so it goes. Some of these lines sound like unmediated echoes
of ``The Importance of Being Earnest.'' Others have an explicitly
erotic content that Wilde could never have gotten away with. (``Can
you not conceive of a world above your waist?'') And every so often
Anna's and Catherine's fine webs of words are torn by descents into
vulgarity and name-calling. (``You whore.'' ``You pagan slut.'')
</P>
<P>
   A lot of this actually isn't so different from the work of many
downtown drag artists in Manhattan. In some ways it's close to what
Charles Ludlam was doing several decades ago with Theater of the
Ridiculous productions that wallowed in the conventions of period
genres even when making fun of them.
</P>
<P>
   Mamet, however, keeps a crisp intellectual distance from his
characters, a feeling underscored by the watery, Yellow Book
prettiness of the set, nicely designed by Sharon Kaitz and J.
Michael Griggs, and the use of music-hall-style signs on an easel
to herald scenes.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   While the play is meticulous in carrying out its absurd twists
of plot, that's not what holds your attention. Instead, it is
seeing whether Mamet can keep topping himself with his
self-imploding preciousness. In the long run he cannot. What is
appealing in ``Boston Marriage'' registers early and then outstays
its welcome.
</P>
<P>
   The actresses, it should be noted, remain entertainingly stylish
throughout. Ms. Huffman (the star of ``Sports Night'' on
television) and Ms. Pidgeon look ravishingly brittle in Harriet
Voyt's wasp-waisted costumes, and their delivery exactly matches
their appearance. They are especially charming when their
characters are derailed from their trains of thought. And Ms.
McCann's Catherine is a lovely, earthy foil to the others'
affectations, while still finding sport in the parody elements of
the folk-wisdom-spouting servant.
</P>
<P>
   It should also be pointed out that Mamet has been expanding
beyond the territory traditionally defined as Mametesque for years
now. As a screenwriter he has brought rejuvenating life to
everything from the all-American cops and robbers of ``The
Untouchables'' to legal drama according to Terence Rattigan in the
current ``Winslow Boy.'' And in his recent plays ``The Cryptogram''
and ``The Old Neighborhood,'' he has brought a new, searingly
personal emotional charge to his work.
</P>
<P>
   With ``Boston Marriage'' he demonstrates anew his technical
virtuosity and flexibility. But it's a minor detour for this
indisputably major playwright, a clever, mildly diverting round of
charades in a career of far more involving dramatic games.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `BOSTON MARRIAGE'
</P>
<P>
   Written and directed by David Mamet; sets by Sharon Kaitz and J.
Michael Griggs; costumes by Harriet Voyt; lighting by John
Ambrosone. Presented by the American Repertory Theater. At the
Hasty Pudding Theater, 12 Holyoke St., Cambridge, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Rebecca Pidgeon (Claire), Felicity Huffman (Anna) and Mary
McCann (Catherine).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
