<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANDERSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROOMING OF YOUNG MEN IS A MYSTERY TO BE PONDERED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MONICA FRAZIER ANDERSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Son, I am going to take you to get a haircut today AND wait,
wait, wait a minute before you start looking for someplace to hide.
I promise on your turtle's grave that I will not let them put fire
on your neck.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the script, and you have to say it just like that or the
boy will not cooperate. He hates to go to the barber. He has always
disliked the whole process of grooming. When he was younger, I
thought his fear was a result of the noise from the clippers and
the fear of falling off that high stool. Even with arm rests and a
booster seat, those barber's chairs are not really designed for
small children.
</P>
<P>
   I've seen a couple of youngsters squirm their way into a ``great
fall'' like Humpty Dumpty, and it wasn't a pretty sight. I guess
that's why the barbers put that ``Stone Cold Steve Austin choke
hold'' on the back of their necks while they use the other hand to
maneuver the clippers over the boys' scalps.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't until he began to express himself in complete
sentences that I learned the true reason for my son's timidity. He
finally told me, ``He puts fire on my neck.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, that's not good.
</P>
<P>
   I admit that I often glance through magazines or watch
television while my son gets a trim but I didn't think that I was
looking away long enough for someone to abuse him. Fire on his
neck? For goodness' sake, how could that be?
</P>
<P>
   Well, the next time his hairline disappeared into his shirt
collar, I bribed him into going to the barber. I promised him a big
cookie from the mall and that I would absolutely, positively do
harm to anyone who tried to put fire on his sweet little neck.
</P>
<P>
   Things were going well with the scissors and the clippers so my
mind wandered a bit. I found myself wondering about my own big
cookie at the mall when I heard my son screaming, ``No! No! It's
the fire!''
</P>
<P>
   I glanced up to find the barber attempting to apply Sea Breeze
to my son's neck. He uses it as an antiseptic, I guess, but as far
as my boy was concerned, it was fire on his neck.
</P>
<P>
   Well, the men in the barbershop got a kick out of that one. I
told the barber to skip the Sea Breeze. I'd take care of his neck
at home with some iodine or something.
</P>
<P>
   However, I forgot to tell Dad about the fire. A couple of weeks
ago, he told my son that he was going to take him to the barber but
he failed to issue the cease-fire order. In a panic, my son took
his father's mustache trimmer and tried to cut his own hair. It
must not have gone well because then he asked his brother to take
my husband's clippers and shave all of his hair off.
</P>
<P>
   The haircut wasn't so bad, but the 2-inch edge-up pushed his
hairline back to his ears. Dad was not pleased. I laughed _
quietly.
</P>
<P>
   Being afraid of Sea Breeze doesn't measure high on Dad's macho
meter. Oh well.
</P>
<P>
   Not that I'm pleased with what he did, but for the moment, my
bald boy is happy. That's good enough for today. Tomorrow, we'll
put out the fire.
</P>
<P>
   (Monica Frazier Anderson is a wife, mother and dentist in
Arlington, Texas. You can call her at (817) 548-5564, or write in
care of the Arlington Star-Telegram at 1111 W. Abram St., Arlington
76013. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
