<HEADER>
A6219 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STAPLES-COLUMN-TEX     06-15 0661
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAPLES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEARNING TO KEEP AN OPEN HEART, MIND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GRACIE BONDS STAPLES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the winter of 1973, my mother died of a massive heart attack.
I was 15. She was 43.
</P>
<P>
   I always figured my mother died before her time, and without
time for her or those whom she loved to prepare for her passing.
</P>
<P>
   More than 25 years later, I can't help but wonder if it was a
sick heart that killed her or simply a lonely and unhappy one. If
nothing else, I think my mother was just tired, the way you get
when it seems that for every move forward you make, there are two
or three in the opposite direction.
</P>
<P>
   Watching her, listening to her talk with friends, I learned
there was a lot of evil in this world. I also learned a fantastic
kindness existed as well.
</P>
<P>
   And so in a lot of ways, my mother's life explains my unfailing
compassion for people and my powerful commitment to try and help
whomever I can.
</P>
<P>
   I remember this as I sit in a waiting room overflowing with
other mothers, mostly teen-agers so ripe with life they look as if
they might burst. Because she has no one else, I am here with a
pregnant 17-year-old.
</P>
<P>
   With two children and one on the way, you'd think she were fully
grown but she looks and sounds like a scared kid.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him I didn't want to,'' she said, explaining her
predicament. ``I told him I didn't want to get pregnant again. I
just went on and did it because I didn't want him to be mad at
me.''
</P>
<P>
   I want to scold her but I don't think that would do any good. I
was not a pregnant teen, but I know what it is to be vulnerable and
to struggle to cope in a world that you can't always control.
</P>
<P>
   While we made small talk, I remember an e-mail from a reader
named Kathleen and I wonder what she'd make of this scene. Would
she approve of my being here or would she accuse me of helping
perpetuate teen-age pregnancy? Would she accuse me of weakening
this young woman further because I dare to try to understand her,
to want to help her?
</P>
<P>
   But let me back up.
</P>
<P>
   Kathleen sent me the e-mail two weeks ago after I wrote a column
questioning the motives of some white downtown businessmen who have
taken a sudden interest in Nash Elementary School, which has a
predominantly minority enrollment. Anything that improves the
quality of our schools should be applauded, but I wondered whether
the businessmen were motivated because kids who will be attending
Nash and living in the new apartments in downtown Fort Worth will
most likely be white.
</P>
<P>
   This seemed to set Kathleen off. In her estimation, it proved my
``disdain'' for whites and my willingness to continue to demean
minorities.
</P>
<P>
   Kathleen went on to say that she ``just plain does not have time
to seek out things to worry about.''
</P>
<P>
   I, on the other hand, am left wondering who needs me more, a
teen-age girl awaiting the birth of her third child with no means
of caring for them, or a woman too busy to care about anyone but
her own?
</P>
<P>
   ``Those people whose children attend Nash Elementary are the
appropriate people to worry about their children,'' she wrote. ``I
am not going to accept the blame for what goes on there just
because I'm white.''
</P>
<P>
   Kathleen says she's a lawyer, but her words make me realize how
removed law and perception can be from the reality of the daily
struggle occurring in people's lives.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in that waiting room the other day, I felt like giving
up. Then in the cold company of despair, my faith and the memory of
my mother offered me hope.
</P>
<P>
   Both have taught me that with an open heart, friendship and
understanding can relieve an abundance of suffering. Not just in
words, but in deeds.
</P>
<P>
   (Gracie Bonds Staples is a columnist for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call her at (817) 390-7791, or e-mail:
gbs(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services
on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-15-99 1704EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
