<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-15 17:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6236 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TECH-SUMMIT16-COX     06-15 0741
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-SUMMIT16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GATES: NOTHING TO FEAR FROM ANTITRUST LAWS
 &HT;    580&AMP;add. Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Microsoft Chairman Bill Gates lauded ``the light
hand of government in the technology area'' Tuesday as being behind
``the incredible success of this industry in the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Testifying to a Joint Economic Committee hearing on high
technology, Gates spurned a bid from Sen. Charles Robb, D-Va., to
propose specific reforms in the nation's antitrust laws to meet the
needs of an increasingly networked society.
</P>
<P>
   As Gates spoke, Microsoft, the world's largest software firm,
remained embroiled in an antitrust case brought by the Justice
Department and 19 states that is being heard a few blocks away from
Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   But Gates suggested that he wasn't worried about the outcome of
the trial, which was in recess Tuesday, telling the panel:
</P>
<P>
   ``There are many people who (would) dive into that, but I think
the laws as they are currently written are fine. Certainly
everything that's gone on in the technology industry has come about
because of things like integrating new features in is one of the
freedoms that all companies have.''
</P>
<P>
   Gates testified a few blocks from the federal courthouse where
his company is bitterly disputing the government's sweeping
antitrust allegations. While he has not testified in the trial,
those seated in the courtroom have watched hours of videotape in
which Gates was questioned by government lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   His upbeat testimony in Congress over the fresh wonders of
technology bore scant resemblance to his grudging videotaped
testimony last summer. And the lawmakers responded with uniform
praise, in contrast to the open scorn his deposition elicited from
antitrust prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   Gates also responded to questions from three groups of high
school and college students from around the country via a
videoconference link that also could be viewed on the Internet. But
the jerky images underscored the fact that Gates's vision of ``a
new era (able to) deliver the power of the information age to
anyone, anywhere and anytime'' remained a work in progress.
</P>
<P>
   In also noting both the so-called Y2K computer glitch and the
recent outbreak of computer virus assaults against Microsoft
products, Gates said: ``We need to design our systems to be far
more resilient against these attacks. We need to get on top of
these problems in advance to minimize the disruption these things
cause.''
</P>
<P>
   Not long after his appearance, the Senate voted 62-37 to approve
legislation to protect companies against lawsuits stemming from the
Y2K computer glitch.
</P>
<P>
   Gates dismissed a warning from Federal Reserve Chairman Alan
Greenspan, delivered Monday before the same panel, that the current
era of technology-driven productivity growth could not be sustained
indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will absolutely see productivity increases coming out of
this technology for many, many years to come. We are very much at
the beginning of what can be done with these devices,'' Gates said.
</P>
<P>
   Although Gates allowed that technology stocks could fluctuate in
value, ``underneath that, the actual efficiency and benefit for
consumers will continue to advance year by year,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gates, a Harvard dropout whose stock holdings in Microsoft make
him the world's wealthiest man, singled out the role of education
in fostering the nation's high-tech success rate.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing the government has done well is support higher
education,'' he said. ``The strength of our universities in
allowing these advances to take place here can't be overstated.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Although Gates was treated on Capitol Hill with a deference and
a security umbrella usually reserved for heads of state, he could
not escape controversy.
</P>
<P>
   The Consumer Federation of America filed a statement with the
committee accusing Microsoft of ``charging monopoly prices for its
operating system, resulting in consumer overcharges of tens of
billions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   And, as he spoke, a group of young people stood against the wall
of the hearing room wearing white T-shirts with such messages as
``Bust the Trust'' and ``Microsoft-Intel: Corporate predators
versus Democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
