</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-GARCIA-435&AMP;ADD-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHECKING IN WITH JERRY GARCIA FROM THE HEREAFTER 
</HEADLINE>
   By JAMES SULLIVAN  
 c.1999, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Jerry Garcia sends his fond regards.
</P>
<P>
   Life in the hereafter, he reports, is bliss. ``To be truly free
to express love,'' he says, ``is to be one with All That Is.''
</P>
<P>
   As for his former Grateful Dead band mate Bob Weir: ``Ask him to
drink more mineral water.''
</P>
<P>
   Mineral water, see, cleanses the synapses for better telepathic
reception. That's how Wendy Weir, Bob's sister, says she has been
contacting Garcia since his death in August 1995. The results of
their correspondence _ ``In the Spirit: Conversations With the
Spirit of Jerry Garcia'' (Harmony; $24) _ will be published later
this week.
</P>
<P>
   Contacting Jerry (or, more specifically, ``Jerry's Oversoul'')
was the easy part, Weir says. ``The hard part was, do I really put
myself on the line and say, `This is my experience, this is my
reality'? Because people can say, `Oh, you're nuts.'''
</P>
<P>
   A former savings and loan executive who says she was always a
``good little girl,'' the 49-year-old Weir suggests none of the
nutty qualities one might expect of the author of this peculiar
book.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is your experience,'' she reasons, ``so what you're
talking about is true, for you.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In the Spirit'' grew out of a series of personal revelations.
Weir first recognized her psychic powers in 1971, after both her
parents died of cancer within weeks of each other.
</P>
<P>
   But almost two decades passed before she devoted herself to her
muses _ psychic study, painting and environmental education. Her
inspiration came from as good a place as any: the spirit of her
brother Bob's dead dog, Otis.
</P>
<P>
   On the first anniversary of the beloved elkhound's death, Weir
writes, Otis insisted that she paint his portrait for Bob. ``Otis,
you're crazy!'' she remembers responding.
</P>
<P>
   The incident was a turning point for Weir. Soon she began
studying energetic and ``psychomotoric'' healing. In 1991, she and
Bob collaborated on the award-winning book-and-cassette package
``Panther Dreams: A Story of the African Rainforest,'' an
educational tool for kids. ``Baru Bay: Australia'' followed in
1995.
</P>
<P>
   When Garcia died, Bob Weir asked his sister to ``check in on''
the late guitarist, as she had done with Otis, the Dead's
keyboardist Brent Mydland and others close to the Weirs.
</P>
<P>
   Other than his encouragement, her brother declined to be
involved in the book, she says. ``He's too close (to the subject),
though he doesn't say that. He says he doesn't want to profit from
Jerry's friendship monetarily.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had a very close, very deep relationship with Jerry.
Everyone that knew Jerry still misses him, and that doesn't go
away.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
    &UR; (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL ADD FOLLOWS) &LR;  &QC; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The author first met the young Garcia at the Weir household in
Atherton, Calif., south of San Francisco, where the jug band that
would become the Dead often rehearsed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was always the little sister,'' she says. ``It was a real
family relationship.'' In the book Jerry's Oversoul addresses her
as ``little one.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the years she has had little interest in the band's music,
though she has gone to plenty of shows. ``I've got to be honest, I
don't think I have ever sat out in the audience through one whole
show in my whole life.'' She keeps the band's recorded output as
``a memento, or a file. I don't sit down and listen to it.''
</P>
<P>
   In the book, the spirit of the avuncular Garcia speaks in lofty
New Age psychobabble. ``It is only natural,'' he says, ``to be
drawn to the lower vibrations as represented in our first, second
and third chakras or energy vortices, but it is not our purpose to
stay stuck there.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Jerry speaks to everyone in a way they can relate to him,''
Weir explains. ``I can only write down and experience what I am.
When he comes through me, that's what I experience.''
</P>
<P>
   The Deadheads, she says, have an important message to offer.
``They've had this bad rap all these years for being drugged-out
hippies. No one has seen the healing side, the incredible love and
joy they share, as being very healing. It's a wonderful thing.''
</P>
<P>
   And Garcia, of course, is the ultimate spiritual leader. ``He's
the great Papa Bear figure,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
