<P>
   TRAVEL-LASTMINUTE _ The best kind of travel is the last-minute
kind, booked online. At least that's what the Atlanta founders of
LastMinuteTravel.com soon will be trying to convince travelers
across the nation. Their fledgling web site _ now in a limited
``sneak preview'' mode _ links spur-of-the-moment travelers with
airlines, hotels and other suppliers that have unsold inventory to
unload online. (Thurston, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   COCACOLA-EUROPE _ ATLANTA _ Coca-Cola Co.'s drinks were pulled
from shelves in Luxembourg and parts of France and the Netherlands
as a health scare that began in Belgium spread across Europe, the
soft-drink maker's second-biggest market. Coca-Cola today said it
traced the contamination that sickened consumers to the carbon
dioxide used in bottles produced in a plant in Antwerp, Belgium,
and fungicide found on the outside of cans produced at a plant in
Dunkirk, France. Coca-Cola Enterprises, which is 42 percent owned
by Coca-Cola, today said it's recalling all Coke products produced
in Belgium and distributed to the Netherlands. France today banned
a batch of drinks produced at the plant in Dunkirk, Reuters said.
And Luxembourg banned the sale of all Coca-Cola products, AFP
reported, citing a government statement. (Unger, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   RETIREMENT_SURVEY _ATLANTA _ Asian-Americans have more
confidence than the general population that they can retire
comfortably _ and more reason to think so. Blacks and Hispanics are
far behind on both counts, according to the 1999 Retirement
Confidence Survey. It was released Tuesday by two non-profit
agencies and a polling company. (Ezell, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   NETBANK-GROWTH _ Net.B(at)nk announced it now has 35,000
accounts, twice as many as at the start of 1999. The company also
added an electronic safety deposit box feature to its online
banking offerings. The story updates the news on them and talks to
two analysts who recently initiated coverage. (Clothier, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   CPI-STOCKS _ Marvin Sherman doesn't need today's Consumer Price
Index report to tell him the cost of living is going up. ``My
haircut just went up,'' he said. Still, Wall Street will pay a lot
of attention to the CPI, because its the last inflation report
before the Federal Reserve meets to consider raising interest
rates. Ahead of the report, stocks rose in early trading, with the
Dow up 61 points and the Nasdaq 18. With chart showing CPI trend.
(McNaughton, Cox News Service). 14.
</P>
<P>
   CABLE-SEX _ Some of the leading executives at top entertainment
companies striking back at critics. Labeled ``obscene'' the
criticisms of their product. Sumner Redstone says ``sex is good,
violence is bad.'' Levin also defended. Both said they couldn't
tell what's obscene or what is art until the public has a chance to
see it. Being grilled by Jeff Greenfield, veteran TV correspondent.
(Haddad, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   WEB-MD _ What is the story with WebMD and the abrupt departure
of its president, Jay Gilbertson? When he was co-prez of HBOC, he
was responsible for HBOC's investment in WebMD, pumping in cash to
WebMD when it was getting underway. Then he gave WebMD cachet on
Wall Street by abandoning HBO leaping to take the helm. Meanwhile,
HBOC is under investigation for financial troubles under JG's
regime. And now WebMD is merging with Healtheon in a multi-billion
deal but JG is out. Is this a castle that is built in the air?
(Miller/Kanell, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 20.
</P>
<P>
   HDEPOT-SUIT _ Home Depot has filed a lawsuit against James
Inglis, a former board director, for stealing trade secrets and
unfairly recruiting top-level employees in connection with a new
business venture by Inglis that's similar to Expo. Inglis, former
chief operating officer of floor-covering retailer Maxim Group, was
executive vice president of Depot and was ``instrumental in the
development'' of Expo until May 1996. Three other defendants are
named, all former employees of Home Depot who have been recruited
by Inglis. Home Depot alleges that they have placed the company's
``investment in its Expo Design Center Division and its future
business in jeopardy.'' In recent months, Home Depot has been
particularly vocal about how proud it is of the Expo concept, which
has been developing for nine years. Atlanta is set to get its
second Expo in November. (Bond, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   TECH-STOCKS _ Weekly look at how local tech stocks fared during
the past week. Clothier/ should run with techstox index. (Clothier,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   DELTA-777TALKS _ Delta Air Lines and its pilots meet again today
to try to hash out a pay agreement for the new 777 plane. The
carrier last week announced it has delayed delivery of the planes
because of the impasse. (Thurston, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   CAU-DONATE _ ATLANTA _Clark Atanta University has received a $1
million grant from the Lilly Endowment/United Negro College Fund to
enhance its computer technology program and develop a distance
learning center. The historically black college was one of several
that received part of the $41.7 million grant, the largest single
grant in the 61-year history of the endowment. (Joyner, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   COLLEGE-LOANS _ DAYTON, Ohio _ After the caps and gowns have
been returned, the parties thrown and the rejection letters thrown
away, the real business of being a would-be college student begins.
Call it Economics 101: Footing the Bill. The college-bound most
likely have become experts in their own right in the world of
student loans. But there's a whole new crop _ students and parents
_ who haven't a clue where to turn. If you're headed to college in
the fall and haven't started looking into student loans at all,
you're awfully late, but not without hope. (Townsend, Dayton Daily
News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   w/COLLEGE-LOAN-INFO _ National telephone numbers and web sites
designed to explain loan questions. (Cox News Service) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MONEYTALK _ Long-term investing is more like staying on a
healthful diet _ it goes on forever, and it requires persistent
effort. For many people, the first step is the hardest. It is the
one in which you start saving some of your money every payday. Some
tips on making investments less painful. (Ezell, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   USENET-TAKEOVER _ DAYTON, Ohio _ The Usenet forum was for owners
of Chia pets, those ceramic animals from mail-order TV. And there
in the list of subjects was a query from someone desperate to keep
her dog from chasing cars. A chia dog that chases cars? That would
be worth sending a photographer, if those TV prowl vans don't beat
us to it. And there was another pottery-pet question asking whether
a mother cat would adopt a kitten from someone else's litter. And
some advice on controlling fleas (another startling problem,
considering recent advances in ceramic technology). And someone
complaining that her landlord won't let her keep a ferret.
Wondering why a landlord would object to a pottery ferret, which
after all is no noisier nor destructive to drapes than a pottery
turtle, I had to look. And I found technological kidnapping, right
there in cyberspace. (Stough, Dayton Daily News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
