<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POPE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POPE, AILING, CANCELS APPEARANCES  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By ALESSANDRA STANLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KRAKOW, Poland _ Stunning the 1 million Poles who were waiting
for him in a rain-soaked meadow, Pope John Paul II canceled all his
planned appearances on Tuesday, sick with what the Vatican said was
a temperature of 100.4.
</P>
<P>
   ``As of the evening of June 14, 1999, the Holy Father has had a
slightly raised temperature, likely to be connected with a viral
infection,'' the Vatican spokesman, Joaquin Navarro-Valls, said in
a statement shortly after Cardinal Angelo Sodano, the Vatican
secretary of state, began saying the morning Mass in the pope's
place. ``Because of this, John Paul II has been advised to cancel
all activities scheduled for Tuesday.''
</P>
<P>
   Navarro-Valls later said the pope was treated for influenza by
his personal doctor and would stay in bed in the bishop's residence
all day. Navarro-Valls said that it was too soon to determine
whether the pope could proceed with his freshly made plans to stop
in Armenia after Poland.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even the pope has to obey someone,'' Navarro-Valls said, ``and
in this case it is his doctor.''
</P>
<P>
   The 79-year-old pope has canceled Vatican events for health
reasons before, and in 1994 was forced to postpone a trip to the
United States after falling and breaking his thigh bone. In 1985,
he canceled a planned appearance in Peru.
</P>
<P>
   But the pope, who is on his 87th foreign trip, has very rarely
failed to show up at a public event abroad.
</P>
<P>
   The news was particularly disappointing to Krakow's residents.
The ancient city, the spiritual capital of Poland, is where the
young Karol Wojtila secretly studied for the priesthood during the
Nazi occupation and where he was the archbishop from 1963 until his
election to become pope in Rome in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   He considers Krakow home and would not easily give up
celebrating Mass there. ``It 's a rather difficult thing for him,''
Navarro-Valls said. ``But there was no other choice.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mass was covered live by Polish state television. When the
news was announced on the air, a news announcer told viewers ``to
pray for the health of the Holy Father.''
</P>
<P>
   Even before the Mass had ended, hundreds left early and began
lining up behind police barricades surrounding the bishop's house,
silently praying and craning their heads for signs of activity from
inside the silent yellow building. A white ambulance stood parked
opposite the main entrance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just waiting, I cannot say for what,'' said Kazimiera
Witek, 48, a social worker in Krakow. ``I don't expect him to
appear. It's better for him to rest.'' Then-Archbishop Wojtila
officiated at her confirmation in 1965, and like so many other
Krakow natives, she feels like she knows him personally.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wanted to be here and communicate to him that we are
all with him, and let him know that he is not alone,'' she said.
``I hope he can feel our presence.''
</P>
<P>
   She had first heard the news at the Mass, when it was announced
over a loudspeaker. ``It was raining so hard I couldn't hear the
announcement _people whispered it to each other from group to
group,'' she recalled. ``It was such a shock.''
</P>
<P>
   Cardinal Franciszek Macharski, who replaced John Paul II as
archbishop of Krakow, delivered the pope's homily, adding ``Now let
us turn to the archbishop's house and the pope, who at this moment
is praying in a little chapel there while we are here,'' he told
the congregation, who listened silently under a sea of umbrellas.
</P>
<P>
   Since he arrived in Poland for a grueling 13-day visit, the
longest stay in Poland of his papacy, the ailing pope, who usually
walks with a cane, has looked tired but has spoken in a firm voice,
often straying from his prepared remarks to make puns and homey
jokes in his native language.
</P>
<P>
   He slipped last Saturday morning and cut his head, requiring
three stitches that the Vatican said were administered by his
personal doctor, Renato Buzzonetti. Asked if the pope's fever were
connected to the fall, Navarro-Valls said, ``absolutely not.''
</P>
<P>
   It is not the first time the pope has caught the flu, but the
Vatican has never given out detailed information about the exact
state of health of the pope, who never fully recovered from the
1981 assassination attempt. He was operated on in 1992 for a benign
intestinal tumor, and had an appendectomy in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   He broke his shoulder in a fall in November 1993 and broke his
thigh bone after slipping in the bathroom in April 1994, postponing
a trip to the United States until October 1995. On Christmas Day of
that year, he suddenly interrupted his traditional blessing,
broadcast live worldwide from Saint Peter's, when he was overcome
by nausea. Last February 3, he canceled his Wednesday general
audience. The Vatican said he had the flu.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last few years, the pope has shown increasing
difficulty walking; and other symptoms, most notably the trembling
of his left hand, have become obvious. Vatican officials say
privately that he is suffering from Parkinson's disease, but the
Vatican has never confirmed it officially. The pope does not like
to be coddled, and on this trip, as on others, has brushed off
aides who try to help him up from a chair.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the pope braved gray skies and chill winds at a
prayer service in Sosnowiec, a mining town in northeast Poland. He
spoke in a firm voice but looked weary. As the Vatican revealed on
Tuesday, he was already running a fever.
</P>
<P>
   ``He seemed very, very tired,'' said Tomasz Budzyn, 19, who
worked as a volunteer security aide at the service. ``I noticed
that he seemed almost asleep in his Popemobile.''
</P>
<P>
   Others began worrying late Monday night, when the pope failed to
address waiting crowds at his window, as he has on all other trips.
A local bishop came out and explained that the pope was ``too
tired'' to appear. ``I felt something was wrong, because it is such
a tradition with us,'' said Jagna Sobala, 45, a shop owner. ``He
always checks in with us there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
