<SLUG> BC-INDONESIA-VOTE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE GAINS BY OPPOSITION, INDONESIAN RACE IS UNCERTAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By SETH MYDANS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia _ Even as the main opposition party appeared
to be solidly ahead in the slow vote count one week after the
parliamentary election, analysts Tuesday predicted a hard-fought
battle for Indonesia's presidency.
</P>
<P>
   With fewer than 50 percent of the votes counted in the June 7
election, the party of Megawati Sukarnoputri maintained a
commanding lead. The governing party, Golkar, hovered between
second and third in the crowded field.
</P>
<P>
   But no party is expected to win a majority and the victor in
last week's vote may not take the big prize, the presidency.
Coalition-building is already under way, and 238 unelected members
are yet to be named to the 700-seat assembly that will choose the
president and will include the newly elected members of parliament.
</P>
<P>
   The unelected group will comprise 38 members of the military, 65
members of professional and other groups and 135 members of
provincial assemblies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people say it's going to be a very tight election
process, which could in turn be potentially very dangerous,'' said
a Western diplomat, commenting on continuing fears of violence
despite the largely peaceful conduct of the campaign and the vote.
</P>
<P>
   A hard fight over the presidency could create a renewed sense of
instability here, said Hidayat Jati, a political analyst at the
Castle Group, a consulting company for foreign investors.
</P>
<P>
   ``The prospect of polarization is less comforting to
investors,'' he said. ``Investors don't have favorites, but they
are looking for a clear winner to limit the risks of instability.
That hope is becoming less of a reality because the margin is not
going to be that big.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``The presidential election will be conducted by 700
people behind closed doors. They are not really your average Joe.
They will have different interests and different loyalties.''
</P>
<P>
   One crucial question is whether the presidential vote in the
assembly will be secret. If it is, political analysts say, the
chances of vote-buying will increase along with the chances of an
outcome that does not reflect the popular will.
</P>
<P>
   Even if these steps go smoothly, the electoral timetable itself
invites uncertainty, said Dewi Fortuna Anwar, an adviser to
President B.J. Habibie, at a public forum on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The new parliament is to meet in August, then expand with its
additional members to form an electoral assembly, then choose the
president in November. ``During those three months there will be no
president and that creates a power vacuum,'' Ms. Anwar said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the pitfalls, Hidayat Jati said, there is reason for
cautious optimism.
</P>
<P>
   ``So far, so good,'' he said. ``Each negative fear or concern
that one may have had in this delicate political process has so far
not materialized.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
