<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Wednesday, June 16, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   Rain with embedded thunderstorms will douse portions of the
Carolinas and southern Virginia Wednesday as a flow of humid air
rises up and over a slow-moving front draped across the region. The
lifting of the moist air will be augmented later Wednesday
afternoon by a jet stream disturbance passing overhead. As a
result, the rain will turn heavy for a time which will lead to
localized flooding.
</P>
<P>
   Scattered strong thunderstorms will surround the slow-moving
front from southern Alabama to Georgia with some flooding also
likely. Farther south, Florida will stay partly sunny and very
humid. Towering cumulus clouds will spawn isolated afternoon
storms, especially just inland from the coast where developing sea
breeze fronts undercut and lift the sultry air.
</P>
<P>
   The day will dawn clear and chilly across most of the Northeast.
During the afternoon, however, middle and high clouds will streak
eastward from the Ohio Valley, dimming the sunshine across the
region. The waning sunshine will be a harbinger of inclement
weather with rain expected to arrive over the northern Middle
Atlantic and southern New England States Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Moist winds from the east will further moisten upon ascending
the sloping terrain of the west-central Plains, setting the stage
for locally heavy showers and thunderstorms from central New Mexico
to Colorado. Generally dry conditions will cover the remainder of
the West, though isolated thundershowers will form near the higher
peaks of the western Rockies. Searing heat will persist in the
Southwest deserts.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Tiny Target
</P>
<P>
   A tropical storm watch was issued for Bermuda late Monday as
Arlene drifted northwest toward the tiny nation. The tropical storm
came as close as 250 miles to the southeast of Hamilton at
midafternoon on Tuesday with gale force winds only 100 miles off
the eastern shore. Bermuda has a remarkable proclivity to being a
target for tropical storms. Its location in the southwest Atlantic
is near the point where most storms from the tropics make a
sweeping turn back into the open North Atlantic. Fortunately,
Arlene will make this turn before getting any closer to Bermuda on
Wednesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
