<SLUG> BC-SEATTLE-HOLOCAUST-ARTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEATTLE MUSEUM TO RETURN LOOTED WORK  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By FELICIA R. LEE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Seattle Art Museum will return a painting by Matisse to the
heirs of a French Jewish art dealer from whom it was confiscated by
the Nazis in 1941.
</P>
<P>
   The museum's board of trustees voted unanimously to return the
painting, ``Odalisque,'' on Monday afternoon, less than a year
after descendants of the prominent dealer Paul Rosenberg filed suit
in federal district court in Seattle to recover the work. The
lawsuit was the first against an American museum concerning
ownership of art looted by Nazis during World War II.
</P>
<P>
   The museum's decision was based on a report on the painting's
provenance by the Holocaust Art Restitution Project of B'nai
B'rith, which investigates Jewish cultural losses, said Linda
Williams, a museum spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   The return of the Matisse was hailed as an important victory on
Tuesday by the Rosenberg family and others involved in claims,
potential and pending, to artworks plundered during World War II
that found their way into American museums. Since last year,
museums have begun reviewing their collections to identify works
stolen by the Nazis and have pledged to resolve claims quickly if
they arise.
</P>
<P>
   Hector Feliciano, author of ``The Lost Museum: the Nazi
Conspiracy to Steal the World's Greatest Works of Art,'' said there
were an estimated 20,000 to 100,000 art objects worldwide that the
Nazis stole from Jewish families and whose whereabouts are unknown.
He traced the provenance of ``Odalisque'' for his book, and said
that documents from the 1930s showed that the painting, dating from
in 1927 or 1928, belonged to Rosenberg.
</P>
<P>
   The whereabouts of ``Odalisque'' were unknown to the Rosenbergs
until the summer of 1997, after a grandchild of the couple who had
come to own it and had donated it to the museum read about it in
Feliciano's book.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is extraordinary,'' Feliciano said of the museum's
decision. He said that it was one of the first cases of an American
museum's returning a Nazi-looted painting. He said the only other
case he could think of was the Detroit Institute of Art's return
return of a Monet to a Jewish family in the 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   When Rosenberg fled the Nazi invasion, he left behind numerous
paintings in a bank vault in Libourne, France.
</P>
<P>
   Ori Z. Soltes, chairman of the Holocaust Art Restitution
Project, said it now seemed likely that most major museums
possessed works of art with a tainted provenance. ``The most
flourishing point of the market during the war was New York,'' he
said. ``People turned a blind eye to what came through and how it
got there.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosenberg's heirs made the claim to the painting in October
1997. The Seattle museum began researching the painting and
essentially asked the family to sue so that it could reach a
settlement that would include Knoedler &AMP; Co., the New York City art
dealer, which purchased the painting in Paris in 1954. Knoedler
sold the painting to Virginia and Prentice Bloedel, both now dead,
who donated it to the museum.
</P>
<P>
   In August 1998, the museum sued Knoedler. The suit, which is
still pending, claims that Knoedler committed fraud, negligent
misrepresentation and breach of warranty of title when it sold the
work to the Bloedels. The museum requested compensation for the
painting's market value, which may now exceed $2 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't believe they have a claim against us,'' said Lewis B.
Clayton of Paul, Weiss, Wharton &AMP; Garrison, the attorney for
Knoedler. ``The gallery did not act wrongfully in any way.'' He
said the gallery never dealt with the museum.
</P>
<P>
   Elaine Rosenberg, the widow of Paul Rosenberg's son, Alexandre,
said on Tuesday that the return of the painting meant that ``the
wind is blowing in the right direction.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy for my father-in-law, who was trying to retrieve
them one by one,'' Mrs. Rosenberg said of the lost paintings. ``His
children are finally coming home.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
