<DOCNO> NYT19990615.0175 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-15 17:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6321 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Y2K-SENATE-HNS &LR;      06-15 0765
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K-SENATE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE PASSES BILL TO LIMIT Y2K LAWSUITS LIABILITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: Filed in ``w'' and ``f'' categories)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Aiming to limit lawsuits stemming from Year 2000
computer glitches, the Senate voted 62 to 37 Tuesday to give
businesses a chance to fix problems before customers can sue them.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the legislation argued that it was needed to
protect the high tech industry against a potential litigation
avalanche arising from the Y2K glitch, referring to the possibility
that some computer micro-chips may read 2000 next Jan. 1 as 1900
and malfunction.
</P>
<P>
   The White House has threatened to veto the legislation because
administration officials say it doesn't offer enough protection to
consumers and small businesses. The Senate would need 67 votes to
override any veto.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would hope the president would not veto this bill,'' said
Sen. Dianne Feinstein, D-Calif., one of the bill's sponsors. ``It's
too important for California. You've got about one-third of the
high tech industry and 20 percent of the jobs concentrated in one
state.''
</P>
<P>
   Some 80 Y2K-related lawsuits have been filed to date, but
supporters of the bill say there may be many more after Jan. 1,
2000.
</P>
<P>
   In one case, Mark Yarsike, a grocery-store owner in Warren,
Mich., sued when the $100,000 computer system that ran the store's
cash registers crashed because it couldn't handle a credit card
with an expiration date of 2000 or later.
</P>
<P>
   After unsuccessfully trying to get the system's manufacturer,
TEC America Inc., to fix it, Yarsike installed another one and took
TEC to court. He later settled his lawsuit for $260,000.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Christopher Dodd, D-Conn., a supporter of the bill, said
``trillions of dollars'' worth of lawsuits could be filed, hurting
the high-tech industry and ultimately the U.S. economy.
</P>
<P>
   The measure calls for a 90-day ``cooling-off'' period that would
allow businesses to remedy any Y2K problems before a lawsuit is
filed.
</P>
<P>
   The 90-day period begins when a business is notified by a
customer that they have a problem. The bill also would cap punitive
damages at $250,000 against businesses with 50 or fewer employees
or a net worth of $500,000 or less.
</P>
<P>
   The bill contains provisions that would make companies
responsible only for the portion of any Y2K-related damages they
caused. That limitation responds to concerns that large companies
like Microsoft or Intel could end up paying 100 percent of the
damages even if they were found to have caused only a portion.
</P>
<P>
   ``It eliminates the incentive to sue the deep pockets who may
not be a direct cause of the problem,'' said Sen. John McCain, the
bill's author.
</P>
<P>
   Many Democrats, including Sen. Barbara Boxer, D-Calif., opposed
the measure.
</P>
<P>
   ``This bill goes too far,'' Boxer said, explaining that it
covers people who shouldn't be given special protection. ``Why
should we protect a person who sells a computer or software in the
year 1999?''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John Edwards, D-N.C., another opponent, said it ``makes
sense to pass a moderate, thoughtful bill to protect the computer
industry,'' but that the bill was unfair to small businesses
because of the limits on damages.
</P>
<P>
   ``If some innocent man is put out of business he can only
recover the cost of his computer,'' said Edwards, a former trial
lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   Other senators objected to any special treatment for the
computer industry because the potential problem has been known
about for years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Y2K bug is not something that just fell out of the sky,''
said Sen. John Kerry, D-Mass. ``The Y2K problem is a result of
conscious choices that people did or didn't make...to fix a wiring
problem.''
</P>
<P>
   During debate on the Y2K legislation many supporters pointed to
a class-action lawsuit recently filed in California as an example
of the type of case the legislation is attempting to limit.
</P>
<P>
   In that case Circuit City, CompUSA, Office Max and Staples,
among others, are being sued for not warning consumers about
potential Y2K problems in computers and software they sold.
</P>
<P>
   ``The clear intent of this litigation is a large settlement,''
McCain said. ``It's not to remedy any injury or failure.''
</P>
<P>
   The Senate legislation will be reconciled with a similar House
bill that was passed last month.
</P>
<P>
   Feinstein said she will work with the administration to make the
measure more acceptable to the White House.
</P>
<P>
   (Jennifer Corbett Dooren can be reached at 202-298-6920 and at
jennifer(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-15-99 1756EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
