A6325 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NETBANK-GROWTH-COX     06-15 0552
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETBANK-GROWTH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Online services 'the next step' in banking
 &HT;    (EDS: Replace 'a' in 'Net.Bank' with ampersand. Story not sent
to wires with ampersand to avoid garble.)By Mark Clothier
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Few argue about whether the future of banking belongs
to the Internet: Web transactions are cheaper than paper ones, and
it costs a lot less to expand a bank's Web site than to build new
branches.
</P>
<P>
   The real question is who will dominate Web banking, the
traditional banks or the upstarts, like Alpharetta, Ga.'s Net.Bank?
And will the Internet-only banks share of online banking customers
ever be a significant amount compared to traditional banks?
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Runnfeldt, an analyst with First Security Van Kasper,
initiated coverage of Net.Bank with a ``sell'' rating last month.
</P>
<P>
   In his report, Runnfeldt does not question the idea of banking
on the Web. He said he realizes online banking is taking off _ the
numbers of users is expected to triple to 25 million by 2001. He
also knows that major banks like Wells Fargo and BankAmerica are
continuing to develop Web sites, further validating the idea.
</P>
<P>
   But he questions whether the banks that operate mostly on the
Internet, such as Net.Bank, will have wide appeal despite their
high yields on deposits.
</P>
<P>
   Branchless banks such as Net.Bank have 1.3 percent of all online
banking customers, so far, according to the Online Banking Report.
</P>
<P>
   ``In our view, the appeal of these new banks will remain
severely limited to a relatively small, niche group of highly
rate-sensitive customers who are willing to accept certain
inconveniences and do not have sophisticated loan and/or service
requirements,'' Runnfeldt said.
</P>
<P>
   Net.Bank shares closed Tuesday at $29.37 1/2, up 9.8 percent.
Net.Bank is up 220 percent for 1999, but down 8.02 percent over the
last five trading sessions.
</P>
<P>
   Runnfeldt said banks are actively developing Web services.
Between 750 and 1,000 U.S. banks will offer Internet services by
the end of 1999, according to Online Banking Report. About 400
banks offer them now.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, Runnfeldt does not see online banking being much
more than the next step in the evolution of telephone banking.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is our view that most customers will look to the Internet
as just an additional delivery channel to complement the way they
currently access their bank's services, much like they already
treat ATMs and telephone banking,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   BancBoston Robertson Stephens thinks investors should buy shares
of Net.Bank. With last month's announcement that ETrade plans to
buy Telebanc, Net.Bank is the last branchless, pure Internet bank
that can grow.
</P>
<P>
   Analyst Bryan Keane said Net.Bank has established itself as the
brand name in online banking.
</P>
<P>
   ``When consumers think of online brokerage, they think of
ETrade, not Merrill Lynch,'' he said. ``If consumers want to buy a
book, they think Amazon.com, not Barnes and Noble. If I'm a
consumer, when I think of Internet banking will I think Wells Fargo
or Net.Bank? Net.Bank has the clear brand name creating a
competitive advantage over its competitors.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Clothier writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
