<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-15 17:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6326 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-LASTMINUTE-COX     06-15 0961
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-LASTMINUTE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wired travellers reap benefits of online booking
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The best kind of travel is the last-minute kind,
booked online.
</P>
<P>
   At least that's what the Atlanta founders of
LastMinuteTravel.com plan to convince travelers across the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Their fledgling web site _ now in a ``sneak preview'' mode _
promises to link spur-of-the-moment travelers with airlines, hotels
and other suppliers that have unsold inventory to unload online.
</P>
<P>
   Chief Executive and founder David Miranda, a former Holiday Inn
Worldwide vice president, said the Internet has created a ``new jet
set.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The two week vacation is almost a thing of the past. Now, it's
'When can I get away,' `` he added.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal is to own the last-minute mindset.''
</P>
<P>
   Based in a small office, Miranda's start-up plans a national
marketing campaign this summer aimed at making LastMinuteTravel.com
the hottest new travel website.
</P>
<P>
   Getting consumers' attention will be key, as the Internet
already is a burgeoning bazaar of travel sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``The number of sites is mushrooming and so is their importance
to consumers,'' said James Cammisa, publisher of Travel Industry
Indicators.
</P>
<P>
   Millions of people use established, all-purpose giants like
Travelocity.com or PreviewTravel.com to check airfares and rates
for rental cars, hotel rooms, cruises and other products. They can
click into myriad specialty pages with bargains, and sign up for
e-mail alerts when sales arise.
</P>
<P>
   Other sites, such as the heavily-advertised Priceline.com, have
a narrower focus or employ a twist. Priceline, for instance,
invites users to ``name their price'' for a flight and then tries
to meet it.
</P>
<P>
   Airlines, car rental companies and hotels also have their own
sites, many featuring weekly short-notice specials that also can be
e-mailed to potential customers.
</P>
<P>
   So far, travel websites account for a small proportion of
bookings. Atlanta-based Delta Air Lines, for instance, says
Internet reservations still account for less than two percent of
its sales.
</P>
<P>
   But the genie is out of the bottle, experts agree.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be a proliferation of sites and probably a
shakeout, but without question the consumer acceptance will keep
rising along with all forms of e-commerce,'' Cammisa said.
</P>
<P>
   LastMinuteTravel.com hopes to position itself as a ``stock
exchange'' for travel suppliers with unsold inventory and travelers
looking for last-minute seats, rooms or condos.
</P>
<P>
   The site promises offerings from a variety of suppliers,
including airlines, hotels, cruise lines and bed-and-breakfasts.
</P>
<P>
   That comprehensiveness is why travelers will come to the site
rather than use others, Miranda said.
</P>
<P>
   Someone trying to go from Atlanta to, say, Washington, on short
notice could check last-minute fares from several airlines, not
just one. Without switching sites they also could check for hotel
rooms and a rental car.
</P>
<P>
   The site will also display event tickets and even tee times.
</P>
<P>
   ``Imagine if you're looking at airline tickets to San Francisco,
a window could pop up and tell you the Giants are playing the
Braves while you're in town and here's how to get tickets. Or
there's a concert or play and you can get tickets here,'' Miranda
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no way those San Francisco businesses, unless they
are sitting in the baggage claim area, can get that information to
those potential consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   Although such offers often involve discounts,
LastMinuteTravel.com doesn't sell itself as a cheap travel site.
</P>
<P>
   ``You won't see the words bargain or discount anywhere because
we don't know it will be,'' Miranda said.
</P>
<P>
   That's because LastMinuteTravel.com provides only an Internet
sales window; participating suppliers retain total control over how
much inventory is offered and at what price. They process bookings
through links to their own sites.
</P>
<P>
   Suppliers pay a fee to post their offerings on
LastMinuteTravel.com, which also gets revenue from advertising and
``data mining,'' or the sale of market statistics.
</P>
<P>
   So far, United, Continental and Midwest Express airlines have
agreed to list on the site, along with Hilton, Radisson, Westin
Sheraton and Swissotel hotels; Carnival, Norwegian and Renaissance
cruise lines; and Avis and Alamo car rentals.
</P>
<P>
   The site also will have an e-mail service, called TravelMinder,
to alert users to specific offers.
</P>
<P>
   With his hotel background, Miranda knew that unsold inventory is
the most perishable commodity in the travel industry. He's
convinced the Internet provides the ideal forum for selling it.
</P>
<P>
   As LastMinuteTravel marketing chief Jack Arogeti puts it, ``If
you've got vacant rooms today or tonight, you can't even market
that in a newspaper. How do you get to the potential customer?
Skywriting? Well, what you do is come to LastMinuteTravel.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our job is not to maximize sales,'' said Miranda, ``it's to
minimize vacancies.''
</P>
<P>
   Miranda launched the company last winter, with financial and
technical backing from Atlanta-based iXL Enterprises Inc., a
minority owner. The company also took its idea to the Red Herring
venture capital show, where it was one of a handful invited to give
the one-minute ``elevator pitch,'' a sign of enthusiasm for the
business plan, Miranda said.
</P>
<P>
   He's confident LastMinuteTravel.com can carve out a niche in a
crowded market.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything is timing and a little luck. When I first had this
idea the critical mass wasn't there. Now the acceptance of
e-commerce has created that critical mass.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott Thurston writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
