<HEADER>
A6328 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHICAGO-RACE-ART-2TAK     06-15 0966
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHICAGO-RACE-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SPINNING INTO BUTTER:' DRAMA CONFRONTS AN AWFULLY FAMILIAR BIAS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., Ala., Vt. Iowa)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By BRUCE WEBER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ In Act II of ``Spinning Into Butter,'' the new play by
Rebecca Gilman at the Goodman Theater here, the protagonist
delivers a speech that has been stunning audiences into silence.
The character, a well-meaning college dean named Sarah Daniels, has
been unable to parse the tricky grammar of race relations in
academia. At last her frustration explodes into an anguished
monologue about her failure to accept black people, even after
years of immersion in the doctrine of inclusion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm fully aware that black people have agency and are
responsible and can help themselves,'' she tells an astonished
friend at one point in her 20-minute harangue. ``But I think they
don't do it because they're lazy and stupid.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a speech full of lines like that, that make theatergoers
whisper, ``Did she just say what I think she said?'' But by the
time Sarah, almost exuberantly dismissing her self-editor,
confesses that she would rather remain standing than sit next to a
black man on the Chicago el, the audience is generally reduced to
squirmy silence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having to deliver it is very unnerving,'' said Mary Beth
Fisher, who plays Sarah. ``The first preview I was dripping sweat.
I've gotten mostly over it, but I'd be lying if I said my blood
pressure doesn't go up just a little bit as I approach the scene.''
</P>
<P>
   The thing is that Sarah, whose sins are far more of thought than
deed and whose self-scrutiny is clearly to be seen as a virtue, is
the most sympathetic character in the play, which is about _ well,
not to mince words _ white guilt. And it has been evident, from the
atmosphere in the theater and the comments in the post-performance
discussions the Goodman is holding nightly, that many in the
audience recognize themselves. That's not entirely surprising; the
Goodman audience is overwhelmingly white.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came here because I was looking for answers, and now I find
all I have is more questions,'' one woman moaned on a recent
evening, sounding very much like Sarah herself. And also perhaps
not surprisingly, several black theatergoers had a different
reaction; they did not share in the discomfort or the shock at
Sarah's revelations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't surprised by that soliloquy,'' said Stephanie
Williams, 34, a writer for The Chicago Reporter, a local monthly
that focuses on racial issues. ``And I don't think most of my peers
would be. We know what white people think.'' She added: ``It is
intended, I think, to make white people feel OK about some of their
suppressed feelings, so they don't feel guilty about admitting
them. You can't be afraid to ask yourself those questions.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Williams and others made the point that when Sarah explodes,
well, it's about time someone did; catharsis is a necessary step.
``The thing I greatly appreciated, more than anything, was that a
white person verbally acknowledged that they do consciously behave
differently around African-Americans,'' said Carley Smelser, 38, a
former phone company engineer who is about to start law school.
``I've been on the bus. I see them do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Sarah judges herself a racist, and though many of the black
audience members interviewed would not let her off the hook, they
forgave her for it. ``She's still trying to purge herself of racist
viewpoints,'' said Marti Worell, 45, a risk-management executive,
who is black. ``But it's her reactive nature, not her reasoning
nature, that she's dealing with. The only way you can kill a demon
is face it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Gilman, who is white, acknowledged that ``quite a bit'' of
Sarah's speech drew on her own experience. She said there were
moments when she considered pulling her punches, softening Sarah's
mea culpa.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think yes, she is a racist, but if there's a good kind of
racist to be, that's what she is,'' she said. ``I took it to an
extreme on purpose for dramatic reasons, but I chose to keep going
because I trusted I wasn't alone, that I wouldn't come off as some
freak. I knew I wanted to write a character who was a thoughtful,
educated and articulate racist. You never get to see that. The
racists you see on screen or in plays are almost always
dismissible.''
</P>
<P>
   The plot of ``Spinning Into Butter'' concerns what happens when
a troubled teen-ager named Simon Brick, one of a handful of black
freshman at a small, mostly white college in Vermont, starts
receiving hostile notes. This turns the subject of discussion among
the onstage characters, mostly college faculty members, to racism
in their midst, who is at fault and what they ought to do about it.
The twist, from the dramatic perspective, is that none of those
characters are black. One secondary character is Hispanic (or
Nuyorican, as he prefers to call himself), but the only black
presence in the play is Simon, who never appears onstage.
</P>
<P>
   Whites talking about blacks; it is, in conception, a thumb in
the eye to the contemporary instinct toward inclusion (read:
political correctness). It is provocative enough that its run has
already been extended three times, through June 27. Reviews have
been largely enthusiastic.
</P>
<P>
   Every person interviewed for this article responded positively
to the play's stimulus.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was really caught off guard by it, and I loved it that it
made me feel hopeful that we can get past the issue of how we hide
racism from ourselves,'' said Ms. Worell. ``You know, sometimes we
like to feel as black people we're not racist. And we are.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The playwright, a woman of placid demeanor who is quietly
forthright in conversation, defies the expectation of a
provocateur. She is a native of Trussville, Ala., a small town
outside Birmingham known for producing fire extinguishers. She
still speaks with a bit of a drawl that is particularly noticeable
here in Chicago, where she has been living since 1994, after
finishing a graduate degree in theater at the University of Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   The central event of ``Spinning Into Butter,'' the anonymous
persecution of Simon Brick, derives from a similar episode at
Middlebury College in Vermont in the early 1980s, when Ms. Gilman
was briefly a student there.
</P>
<P>
   Her career is gathering momentum. After, by her estimate, some
150 rejections of her plays by nonprofit theaters all over the
country, Circle Theater, a tiny company outside Chicago, took a
chance on her grim look at two youthful serial killers, ``The Glory
of Living.'' The sterling reviews drew the attention of, among
others, the Royal Court Theater in London, whose production opened
in January to critical praise.
</P>
<P>
   That also resulted in a commission from the Goodman for its
smaller stage, the 135-seat Studio Theater, which turned into
``Spinning Into Butter.'' The Goodman subsequently commissioned a
second play, and she wrote ``Boy Meets Girl,'' about a young woman
who is stalked by a man with whom she has one date; it is scheduled
for the Goodman's main stage next season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think of `Spinning' and `Boy' as two sides of the same
coin,'' Ms. Gilman said. ``One is about what it is to objectify
people, and the other is about what it is to be objectified. I
guess the theme of objectification runs throughout my work.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, ``objectification isn't all bad,'' she said. ``It's how
we forge our identities, separate ourselves from other people. You
say, `There's a handsome guy!' That's objectification. It's how you
find out who you are.''
</P>
<P>
   Almost every night the first question asked at the post-play
discussion is why Simon never appears. Ms. Gilman's explanation was
twofold. One was the strategy of a dramatist: the play is about how
others view Simon, she said, not about Simon himself, and to show
him onstage would undermine that.
</P>
<P>
   But the other reason is the strategy of a white woman; she felt
uneasy, she said, putting words in the mouth of a black man. She
did, however, put words in the mouth of a Hispanic character, a
student whose prickly racial pride spurs Sarah to her excruciating
self-examination. Ms. Gilman said she could not explain the
inconsistency.
</P>
<P>
   Recently the Goodman invited several classes of students from
Chicago public schools to a special matinee. Among other things, it
brought the play its first largely black audience. The teen-agers,
a generally restless bunch, absorbed Sarah's second-act speech in
ever enveloping silence, listening as she described, and decried
her experience of taking a job at an all-black school in Chicago.
(The following transcription omits a few expletives.)
</P>
<P>
   ``But I still thought I could do a good job,'' Sarah says. ``And
then I met the students. And they were all black. Of course. And
some of them were great, and some of them were OK, and some of them
were pains, and some of them were awful. Which is how the world is,
except that the ones who were awful seemed, really, exceptionally
awful. They were loud and belligerent, and they walked down the
hall in packs, and they were so loud. . . . They were so rude and
loud and stupid.''
</P>
<P>
   It was an extraordinary moment, or so it seemed: a real group of
people being objectified by a fictional character on the stage. The
silence persisted. The play came to an end. In the discussion that
followed, the moderator, a white man, asked, How many of you think
Sarah is a racist? Not a single student raised a hand. Not one.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's the least racist of all of them,'' one student said, at
last. ``Because she's talking about it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
