<HEADER>
A6330 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEMONADE-STAND-ROBBER     06-15 0460
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEMONADE-STAND-ROBBERY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Teenagers under arrest for lemonade stand heist
 &HT;    By Rachel Kipp
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Police have arrested two Butler County teen-agers
based on a description of their getaway truck provided by a
9-year-old boy, who says the pair robbed his lemonade stand of
nearly $10 Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The boy, Aaron Faughn, said Monday that he just wants them to
apologize.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because I think it's wrong what they did,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Police, however, charged the juveniles with delinquency by
reason of complicity to theft. They are accused of being present
when the robbery occurred, said Toni Pagano, administrative
coordinator for the Butler County Juvenile Courts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now (the suspects) are blaming each other,'' Pagano
said. ``(Who actually committed the robbery) is being left up to
the court to decide after receiving all of the evidence and
information.''
</P>
<P>
   Police said they located the teen-agers with information
provided by Aaron and neighbors in the Lakota Pointe Town Homes
development in southern Butler County.
</P>
<P>
   Aaron was running his lemonade stand Thursday afternoon when two
males driving a red and gray Blazer asked him for change for $10.
When he attempted to give them the change, the pair took all of his
money.
</P>
<P>
   Debbie Faughn, Aaron's mother, said her son didn't know either
of the robbers and that she would like an apology for her son.
</P>
<P>
   Detective Debbie Brannigan said the sheriff's deputy who
identified the vehicle based on Aaron's description is an officer
who works in Liberty Twp. and recognized the truck.
</P>
<P>
   Pagano said one of the teen-agers is in the Butler County
Juvenile Detention Center and one was released to his parents. A
court date has been scheduled for June 22 at the Butler County
Juvenile Court.
</P>
<P>
   The sheriff's office offered a cash reward for information
leading to an arrest and conviction of lemonade stand robbery.
Deputies received more than 30 tips.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone has been very generous in terms of offering
information. Other people have called wanting to know if they could
do something for the boy,'' said Brad Kraemer, a sheriff's
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Aaron went out and set up his lemonade stand the day after the
robbery under the supervision of his mother, her boyfriend, and his
14-year-old sister, who helped fill out the police report the day
before. The police also drove by during the day. Debbie Faughn said
she thinks her son feels safe enough to continue his neighborhood
business. set up the stand.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think (Aaron) knows this was an isolated incident and that
these kind of things don't happen everyday,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-15-99 1800EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990615.0182 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-15 18:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6338 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CABLE-SEX-COX     06-15 0466
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CABLE-SEX-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Entertainment execs share controversial opinions at convention
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Angry with their critics, two leading entertainment
moguls fumed Tuesday that they can't tell how violent is too
violent when it comes to television programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have nothing to be ashamed of,'' said Viacom Chairman Sumner
Redstone, whose company owns the Paramount TV and movie studios.
``I'm outraged by the media criticism of us. We run the same movies
in Europe as we do here and people in Europe don't go out and kill
one another.''
</P>
<P>
   His heated comments came as part of a panel at the annual
convention of the National Cable Television Association, which runs
here through Wednesday. The other panelists included Time Warner
Chief Executive Officer Gerald Levin, billionaire media investor
Paul Allen and Comcast President Brian Roberts.
</P>
<P>
   Levin, who heads the world's largest entertainment company, said
his company tried to act responsibly, but he added, it is often
hard to determine the difference between art and offensive
material.
</P>
<P>
   Redstone agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unrealistic to think that we can determine what's obscene
and what's artistic. That's up to the viewer. I mean, is 'Saving
Private Ryan' obscene in its level of graphic violence?
</P>
<P>
   ``And let's distinguish between sex and violence,'' continued
the 73-year-old Redstone. ``Sex is good. Violence is bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Redstone's comments earned a big laugh from the audience of
several thousand cable executives, but the issue is no laughing
matter.
</P>
<P>
   Since the student massacre at Littleton, Colo., the
entertainment industry has been under heavy attack by several
prominent Congressmen and other critics. They decry the high number
of violent and sexually explicit shows.
</P>
<P>
   At Tuesday's panel, however, the entertainment executives tried
to turn the tables on those who would censor their violent or
sexually explicit programming.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's obscene what the political system is doing with media
criticism of violent programming,'' said Levin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Politicians are drawing attention away from the real issues of
gun control and drug awareness,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts, who heads one of the country's largest cable operators,
said he too was uncomfortable with censuring shows. ``It's tough as
an operator to say block this show or that channel,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We decided early on to leave those decisions to families and
support the technology that would let them do it.''
</P>
<P>
   That technology, which is now widely available, includes the
V-Chip and software such as SurfWatch.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Haddad writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
