<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT &AMP; ARTS (Moved in `e' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SURREALISM-GUGGENHEIM (New York) _ Surrealism, generally thought
of as melting watches and men in bowler hats descending from the
sky, began as a literary movement. The movement in its heyday
always had a literary bent _ a wide angle, in fact, to judge by the
large number of remarkable book illustrations and covers on view in
``Surrealism: Two Private Eyes,'' an exhibition at the Guggenheim
Museum running through Sept. 12. By Vicki Goldberg.
</P>
<P>
   BEATLES-COLLECTORS (Undated) _ Respectability has come late to
Beatles collecting. By Allan Kozinn.
</P>
<P>
   CLEVELAND-MUSIC (Undated) _ Franz Welser-Moest's scheduled
ascendance in 2002 to music director of the Cleveland Orchestra is
hopeful news. Conductors and orchestras are sometimes about
individual and collective personalities, but in some places,
Cleveland among them, the subject is chemistry. By Bernard Holland.
</P>
<P>
   VIDEO-DISKS (Undated) _ For 20 years home video has thrived on a
simple process: choose a movie, watch it, engage in some thought
and discussion, move on. Now, though, operating on the principle
that nothing gets simpler, along comes the digital video disk (DVD)
to immerse one in films to a degree that will intrigue some and
repel others. DVD invites the average viewer to become a film buff,
defined as one who wants to know all about how the movie was made
and by whom. By Peter M. Nichols.
</P>
<P>
   CHOPIN-MUSIC (Undated) _ Music history has its myths and its
debunkers of myths. Beethoven wasn't quite the political idealist
he seems in the story about tearing up the ``Eroica'' dedication
when Napoleon crowned himself Emperor; Schubert wasn't a cheerful
bohemian who died unknown. In the case of Chopin, it is so obvious
that his melodies and arabesques sound like the `bel canto'' opera
of his day that the conventional wisdom has him ``influenced'' by
opera. By Will Crutchfield.
</P>
<P>
   BESTSELLERS (Undated) (Moved.)
</P>
<P>
   PAPERBACKS (Undated) (Moved.)
</P>
