A6371 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TECH-STOCKS-COX     06-15 0410
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-STOCKS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia-based tech stocks slumping, with few exceptions
 &HT;    By Mark Clothier
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Technology stocks in general have taken a beating
recently, but the worm might have softened the blow for ISS Group,
an Atlanta company that makes software that protects computer
networks.
</P>
<P>
   News of the latest computer virus, the Worm.Explore.Zip, raised
awareness of the vulnerability of computers and computer networks,
which might have had some residual benefit on the stock of
companies that protect against viruses, said David Breiner, an
analyst with Volpe Brown Whelan.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of ISS Group are up 1.4 percent over the last five
trading sessions, a modest increase, but significantly higher than
other local technology stocks. ISS is down 39 percent from its
52-week high March 18, but up 2.3 percent for 1999.
</P>
<P>
   John F. Powers, who covers ISS Group for BancBoston Robertson
Stephens, upgraded ISS Group this month to a ``buy.'' Powers said
ISS' business is going well, and, at about half the price of its
52-week high, its shares are a relative bargain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Business is great there, both in success in marketing and
selling and in having interesting products,'' he said. ``They
consistently lead their market sector.''
</P>
<P>
   The stock of some of Georgia's more well-known technology
companies have been slumping along with the rest of the nation's
publicly traded technology companies.
</P>
<P>
   Alpharetta, Ga.'s Net.Bank is down 11.5 percent the last five
days. Net.Bank shares have dropped 66 percent since hitting a
52-week high of $83 April 14. But Net.Bank is still up 208.2
percent for 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Security First Technologies, a maker of software that lets banks
put their banking services on the Internet, is down 22.5 percent
over the last five trading sessions. Security First is down 61.5
percent from its 52-week high April 14. Overall, Security First
shares have doubled in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of MindSpring Enterprises, the Atlanta Internet Service
Provider, are down 16.2 percent the last five days. MindSpring's
stock price has dropped 54.7 percent from a 52-week high April 13
and is down 1.3 percent for 1999.
</P>
<P>
   CheckFree, the leader of the electronic bill paying and bill
presenting market, has seen its shares drop 1.1 percent the last
five days. For 1999, CheckFree is up 51.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
