<HEADER>
A6376 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIESTARS16-COX     06-15 0673
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIESTARS16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fifty big-screen actors and actresses named Tuesday to the
American Film Institute's newest list
 &HT;    EDs: List is embargoed for newspapers until Wednesday. For
internet use: List cannot be posted until 11 p.m. Tuesday June 15.
 &HT;    By Bob Longino
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   You must remember them: Humphrey Bogart and Ingrid Bergman. Fred
Astaire, Spencer Tracy, Katharine Hepburn and Greta Garbo.
</P>
<P>
   They are just six of the 50 big-screen actors and actresses
named Tuesday to the American Film Institute's newest list: the
greatest American screen legends.
</P>
<P>
   Bogart topped the list of 25 male screen legends while four-time
Oscar winner Hepburn led the 25 actresses.
</P>
<P>
   Who else made the grade? Most of the usual suspects: Cary Grant,
James Stewart, Bette Davis, Audrey Hepburn, Shirley Temple and John
Wayne.
</P>
<P>
   Sidney Poitier was the only African-American chosen.
</P>
<P>
   The star lists, announced Tuesday night during a three-hour AFI
special on CBS, follow last year's selections by the film
organization of the 100 greatest American films. That list touted
such classics as ``Citizen Kane,'' ``Casablanca'' and ``Gone With
The Wind'' as well as more modern-day hits ``Star Wars'' and
``Fargo.''
</P>
<P>
   AFI expects its star lists ``to ignite passions, spark debate
and invite criticism, all of which we welcome as a means of
engaging the nation in a discussion of American movie history and
bringing movie fans back to the classics,'' said Jean Picker
Firstenberg, AFI director and CEO.
</P>
<P>
   Left off the star rosters were such big names as Richard Burton,
Charlton Heston, Rock Hudson, Douglas Fairbanks Jr., Olivia de
Havilland, Helen Hayes and Susan Hayward.
</P>
<P>
   AFI's rules eliminated many current big-name stars such as
three-time Oscar winner Jack Nicholson, two-time winner Meryl
Streep, Paul Newman, Jack Lemmon, Shirley MacLaine, Clint Eastwood,
Tom Hanks and Jodie Foster.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, the AFI defined an American screen legend as ``an
actor or team of actors with significant screen presence in
American feature-length films whose screen debut occurred in or
before 1950, or whose screen debut occurred after 1950 but whose
death has marked a completed body of work.''
</P>
<P>
   An AFI panel offered up 500 stars as list nominees and the
finalists were chosen in ballots sent to roughly 1,800 industry
celebrities, technicians, historians, critics and other cultural
leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Thirteen stars chosen for the two lists were born outside the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   Four of those selected _ Henry Fonda, Ginger Rogers, Rita
Hayworth and Edward G. Robinson _ were once in the same movie:
1942's ``Tales of Manhattan.'' Buster Keaton, also named to the
male legend list, was an uncredited writer on the film.
</P>
<P>
   AMERICAN SCREEN LEGENDS
</P>
<P>
   MALE
</P>
<P>
   1. Humphrey Bogart
</P>
<P>
   2. Cary Grant
</P>
<P>
   3. James Stewart
</P>
<P>
   4. Marlon Brando
</P>
<P>
   5. Fred Astaire
</P>
<P>
   6. Henry Fonda
</P>
<P>
   7. Clark Gable
</P>
<P>
   8. James Cagney
</P>
<P>
   9. Spencer Tracy
</P>
<P>
   10. Charles Chaplin
</P>
<P>
   11. Gary Cooper
</P>
<P>
   12. Gregory Peck
</P>
<P>
   13. John Wayne
</P>
<P>
   14. Laurence Olivier
</P>
<P>
   15. Gene Kelly
</P>
<P>
   16. Orson Welles
</P>
<P>
   17. Kirk Douglas
</P>
<P>
   18. James Dean
</P>
<P>
   19. Burt Lancaster
</P>
<P>
   20. The Marx Brothers
</P>
<P>
   21. Buster Keaton
</P>
<P>
   22. Sidney Poitier
</P>
<P>
   23. Robert Mitchum
</P>
<P>
   24. Edward G. Robinson
</P>
<P>
   25. William Holden
</P>
<P>
   FEMALE
</P>
<P>
   1. Katharine Hepburn
</P>
<P>
   2. Bette Davis
</P>
<P>
   3. Audrey Hepburn
</P>
<P>
   4. Ingrid Bergman
</P>
<P>
   5. Greta Garbo
</P>
<P>
   6. Marilyn Monroe
</P>
<P>
   7. Elizabeth Taylor
</P>
<P>
   8. Judy Garland
</P>
<P>
   9. Marlene Dietrich
</P>
<P>
   10. Joan Crawford
</P>
<P>
   11. Barbara Stanwyck
</P>
<P>
   12. Claudette Colbert
</P>
<P>
   13. Grace Kelly
</P>
<P>
   14. Ginger Rogers
</P>
<P>
   15. Mae West
</P>
<P>
   16. Vivien Leigh
</P>
<P>
   17. Lillian Gish
</P>
<P>
   18. Shirley Temple
</P>
<P>
   19. Rita Hayworth
</P>
<P>
   20. Lauren Bacall
</P>
<P>
   21. Sophia Loren
