<DOCNO> NYT19990615.0189 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-15 18:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6382 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-HANNIBAL-AZR &LR;      06-15 1099
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-HANNIBAL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLAWS CAN'T STOP `HANNIBAL' FROM REACHING NEW LEVELS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
Hannibal 
Thomas Harris (Delacorte, $27.95) 
 
 By ANNE STEPHENSON  
 c.1999 Special to The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   You've been waiting for him to resurface for more than 10 years.
Now, he's back, and he is, for a while at least, everything you
want him to be.
</P>
<P>
   Serial killer Hannibal Lecter makes his entrance on Page 30 of
Thomas Harris' new novel, ``Hannibal'' (Delacorte, $27.95), after a
rather contrived first chapter in which FBI agent Clarice Starling
gets caught in a botched drug raid and kills five people to the
sound of ``La Macarena''on a boom box.
</P>
<P>
   Television cameras record the debacle and send Clarice's career
into a nose dive. Seven years after he made his grisly escape from
authorities, the brilliant and ever-informed Lecter writes from his
hiding place in Italy to taunt and, in his own withering way,
encourage Clarice during her professional humiliation.
</P>
<P>
   As she reads his letter, she hears Lecter's voice in her head,
just as we hear the voice of Anthony Hopkins _ a measure of how
indistinguishable the novel/film phenomenon of ``The Silence of the
Lambs'' has become. But does this new book measure up to Harris'
1988 blockbuster?
</P>
<P>
   The answer is no. And yet ``Hannibal'' is still a tantalizing
mix of the ridiculous and the sublime.
</P>
<P>
   The book is deeply gruesome, a whole new level of gore even for
Harris. Although ``Lambs'' was efficiently told, with no
distracting literary tactics to stall its story, the writing in``
Hannibal'' is slowed by changes in tense and in the flow of its
narrative voice. And what happens to Lecter and Clarice at the end
of the novel is amazing _ but surely not in the way the author
intended it to be. It does not take your breath away so much as it
leaves you staring incredulously at the page. I will not give it
away, and I'm not sure you would believe me if I did.
</P>
<P>
   But we are dealing with Thomas Harris here, and he is so far
above other writers in his genre that you can quibble with entire
endings and still admit you couldn't put the book down.
</P>
<P>
   Like his villains, he displays flashes of intelligence and humor
that are exhilarating. He is not predictable. He is not amateurish.
And whether you like the ending or not, he always gives you your
money's worth in suspense and blood-flinging entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   His specialty, of course, is his villains, the weirdos he makes
mesmerizing by endowing them with brilliance or superb taste or a
remorseless predilection for flamboyant violence. In Hannibal
Lecter, he has managed to combine cannibalism and charm so
seamlessly that we actually find ourselves a bit baffled by
Lecter's fascination with Clarice Starling. She is young,
attractive, courageous and capable. He eats his enemy's brains for
breakfast, and we wonder what he sees in her.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Hannibal,'' there are two main villains: Lecter himself and
one of his previous victims, a millionaire named Mason Verger.
Verger has survived a nasty encounter with Lecter, although he did
not survive it well. In an incident involving two starving dogs, a
mirror and a mere suggestion from Lecter (the same easy influence
he exerted over Miggs, the asylum inmate who threw semen at
Starling in ``''``Silence of the Lambs ''and later committed
suicide by swallowing his tongue), Verger has relieved himself of
his face _ he has no lips, nose or eyelids, is paralyzed (Lecter
broke his neck for good measure) and breathes through a respirator.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mason Verger, noseless and lipless, with no soft tissue on his
face, was all teeth, like a creature of the deep, deep ocean,''
Harris writes. ``Inured as we are to masks, the shock in seeing him
is delayed. Shock comes with the recognition that this is a human
face with a mind behind it. It churns you with its movement, the
articulation of the jaw, the turning of the eye to see you. To see
your normal face.''
</P>
<P>
   Verger lives in a wing of his family mansion, where he keeps a
huge eel in an aquarium by his bed and inflicts sadistic mental
torture on poor children he has brought in from the slums (before
he was rendered immobile, he liked to rape his sister and molest
boys at a Christian camp). But Verger's main interest is plotting
his revenge against Lecter.
</P>
<P>
   After much thought, he has chosen a method: He will capture
Lecter and feed him alive to pigs that eat human flesh. And, yes,
in Thomas Harris' world, there are people who raise animals for
that purpose.
</P>
<P>
   What ensues is your basic cat-and-mouse game. There is a side
trip to Italy, where Lecter has been living as Dr. Fell, the
scholarly curator of the Palazzo Capponi, a man of great education,
breeding and taste. Things go sour there when a hapless Italian
detective named Pazzi suspects Dr. Fell's true identity and
contacts Mason Verger about the huge reward he has offered for
Lecter's capture alive.
</P>
<P>
   We know the detective is not long for this world, but he
provides many opportunities to show off Harris' eye for detail
(spying on Lecter's apartment, Pazzi ``backed into the shadow
across the street, his nose the last to disappear''). Lecter
disembowels him and hangs him from a Tuscan wall, then endures a
laughable flight back to the United States as part of a package
tour, during which he contemplates airline food and the prattle of
children.
</P>
<P>
   It's when he gets home that Harris' intentions go awry. In
Italy, Lecter was still the magnificent villain of ``Lambs,'' evil
incarnate contained in an impeccable package. But when he returns
to America for a showdown with Verger and his long-awaited reunion
with Starling, Lecter turns into something altogether different.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, Harris endows him with a past. There were a mother and
father, killed by the Nazis when Hannibal was 6. There was a
sister, Mischa, whose subsequent death at the hands of deserters
provides some insight into Lecter's taste for human flesh.
</P>
<P>
   And there is, of course, Clarice Starling. At the end of``
Hannibal,'' her association with Lecter travels in new directions.
Without giving too much away, I'll just say that it is a rather
wacky way to go with these characters, one that contradicts so much
of what we know about them from ``Lambs'' and Harris' previous
book, ``Red Dragon.''
</P>
<P>
   Such a move could be fatal to a lesser novel. But ``Hannibal''
survives its flaws. It is gory and self-conscious and frequently
over the top. Its writing is occasionally clumsy and its ending is
bizarre. And I'll tell you this: I couldn't put it down. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
