<DOCNO> NYT19990615.0194 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-15 18:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6392 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BEATLES-COLLECTORS-2T     06-15 0986
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEATLES-COLLECTORS-2TAKES-$ADV20-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FETISHIST? BEATLEMANIAC? JUST CALL ME A COLLECTOR. 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, June 20)  
 (bl)  
 By ALLAN KOZINN  
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   I did not attend Sir George Martin's recent lecture on the
making of ``Sgt. Pepper,'' but not because I don't find the details
of the Beatles' recordings thoroughly fascinating. Quite the
contrary. But I had heard and read Sir George's account several
times, and reports from earlier stops on his tour indicated that
his talk, entertaining though it was, covered no new ground.
Mainly, I was confident that the excerpts he played from the
session tapes were already safely in my collection.
</P>
<P>
   OK, I admit it: if I weren't reviewing another concert, I might
have gone on the prospect that Sir George's playlist included a
snippet that had eluded me. Is $50 too much for that? Not for those
of us who happily commit time and money to the search for, say, the
Australian 45 rpm reissue of ``I Want to Hold Your Hand,'' for its
stereo mix with centered vocals (the British and American mixes put
the vocals to one side), or the latest rarity, a British mono
pressing of ``Revolver'' with the matrix number XEX 606-1 printed
into the runout groove of side two. That disk includes an otherwise
unavailable mix of ``Tomorrow Never Knows,'' which was replaced
with the common version only a few hours into the press run.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is it a steep tariff for those of us who regularly buy
bootleg disks for the sake of a few new minutes of previously
unheard session tape. Is this fetishism? Fetishism, I guess, is in
the eye of the beholder: if I collect something you regard as
manifestly trivial, you will write me off as a fetishist; if you
see the point of my collection, you'll regard it as high
appreciation, perhaps even scholarship.
</P>
<P>
   Your view, moreover, will be colored by whether you collect
anything yourself. There is a respect among collectors akin to the
honor among thieves. We recognize kindred spirits in those who seek
not only to amass a particular thing _ whatever it may be _ but to
know the history of each item in minute detail.
</P>
<P>
   I am not a serious jazz collector, but when I listen to Phil
Schaap's radio show on WKCR-FM and hear him introduce a four-minute
disk with a 15-minute rundown of session dates and locations, the
producer, soloists, sidemen, take and matrix numbers and the
history of the recording's permutations on disk, I know that this
is my kind of guy.
</P>
<P>
   Still, respectability has come late to Beatles collecting. Early
on, it seemed just another example of the adulation of rock
musicians and movie stars, something that those of a serious bent
have always regarded with a combination of amusement and disdain.
Even so, someone who collected Beatles gum cards, wigs, dolls, ice
cream wrappers and fan magazines in the 1960s would not have been
called a fetishist: in those days, pop culture was less
self-consciously analyzed, and the language was less fraught with
pop psychologizing. Beatlemania was a ``fad,'' a ``craze,'' terms
that carried the sense that such ephemera was not worthy of
chin-stroking analysis.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, someone who kept such a collection intact and in good
shape is now sitting on a small fortune, and if the people who now
shell out for those items can be called fetishists, they can point
out, soberingly, that a picture sleeve for ``Can't Buy Me Love''
that cost 59 cents (with the record) in 1964 can now fetch $450
(without the record); that a set of the smiling, instrument-bearing
Remco Beatle dolls that sold for a couple of dollars apiece now
command $500 and that a near-mint stereo copy of the 1966 album
``Yesterday and Today,'' with its original cover, which was
withdrawn _ the Beatles in butcher smocks, draped with raw meat and
broken baby dolls _ is listed in collectors guides for as much as
$20,000, a spectacular return on the original $2.99.
</P>
<P>
   In the Beatles-collecting circles I travel in, though,
investment isn't the point. Nor is adulation, for that matter, and
the amassing of 1960s trinkets, though fun in a kitschy way, is
incidental. It's about the music. The fact is, nearly 30 years
after they broke up, the Beatles' music endures for its musical
strength, not its nostalgia value. That the group's music evolved
from simplicity to sophistication with such rapidity is itself a
matter of fascination: in musical terms, the distance from ``I Want
to Hold Your Hand'' to ``Strawberry Fields Forever'' is vast. The
Beatles traversed it in three years. How they did it is a
legitimate subject of musical inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   If you visit the Beethoven Geburtshaus, in Bonn, you can peer
into glass display cases at ear trumpets, eyeglasses and personal
effects preserved with fetishistic care. You can also examine
manuscript pages full of ink blots and crossed-out sections. In
these, and in Beethoven's sketchbooks, one can follow surprisingly
mundane themes as they are reworked and transformed into the
``Eroica'' and other titanic works.
</P>
<P>
   For the Beatles, alternative mixes and unreleased recordings _
concerts, BBC radio performances and raw session tape, traded
clandestinely or sold on bootlegs _ are the sketches that fill out
their creative history. Granted, some mixing oddities are
interesting merely because they have an extra ``woo'' before the
fadeout (the stereo ``Slow Down'' . . . never mind). Mostly,
though, the attraction of these recordings is that they let us in
on the choices that went into creating some of the greatest pop
recordings ever made.
</P>
<P>
   Those choices are most dramatic in the later sessions. The group
was coining money for its label, EMI, and therefore had unlimited
studio time, so John Lennon and Paul McCartney often brought in
works-in-progress, which they fleshed out during the sessions. But
even the early sessions illuminate the compositional process.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The entire March 5, 1963, session at which they recorded their
third single, ``From Me to You,'' is available on bootlegs. The
song had been written only days before the session, and in the
first few takes, there is no provision for an instrumental break.
With take 5, they added the bit where they play two lines of the
verse melody, singing ``from me'' and ``to you'' as vocal
punctuation _ an addition they are heard discussing before they
begin playing. With take 7 they had the basic track, upon which
they overdubbed vocal embellishments (the ``da-da-da, da-da dum-dum
da'' introduction) and a harmonica (on both the newly devised
instrumental break and the ending) to create take 8.
</P>
<P>
   The tape also includes ``edit pieces,'' fragments that could be
spliced onto the body of the song if they proved sufficiently
interesting. Mainly, these were alternative versions of the
introduction. One has them humming instead of singing. Another has
a harmonica but no vocals. In a third, they double the ``da-da-da''
vocals of take 8 in falsetto, an octave higher. All those notions
were rejected _ sort of. Actually, the stereo mix is take 8,
unadorned, but the mono mix has both the ``da-da-da'' vocal and the
harmonica _ a permutation that is neither heard on the session tape
nor mentioned in the logs in which the session is documented. Even
with the materials at hand, the mysteries never end.
</P>
<P>
   Lately, bootleggers have been muddying the historical waters by
using such components to make new alternative versions. In this
they are taking a cue from the ``Anthology'' sets, in which several
outtakes were combined to create a new version in a triumph of
cosmetics over historicity.
</P>
<P>
   These concoctions, which collectors call ``outfakes,'' support
the notion that the ``Sgt. Pepper'' we know is only one possible
``Sgt. Pepper.'' A collector, though, would put it differently: the
``Sgt. Pepper'' we hear on CD is one of the  &UR; two &LR;  ``Sgt. Pepper''
albums the Beatles released in 1967. The mono mix, long out of
print, was different in some details. In ``Lucy in the Sky With
Diamonds,'' an electronic phasing effect gives Lennon's voice a
spacey, psychedelic quality lost in stereo. ``She's Leaving Home''
runs faster and at a higher pitch in mono, and sounds immensely
better for it. And the reprise of the title song has an extra bar
of drum introduction in mono.
</P>
<P>
   I once pointed out these differences to Sir George, whose first
reaction was slightly testy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We used to do an awful lot of changing our minds at the last
moment, and doing different things, mainly because we didn't think
it was that important to be consistent,'' he said. ``I don't think
it's all that significant. But I can see that it does cause a
certain amount of consternation from people who devote their lives
to analyzing the differences.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't a matter of consternation, I told him, just the kind
of details that make collecting interesting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can understand that,'' Sir George said. ``It's rather like
finding a rare coin, and finding that the milled edge is missing a
point _ that kind of thing?''
</P>
<P>
   A milled edge, a missing point? The telltale jargon of a
collector! No wonder Sir George's tone changed so quickly.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;
</P>
</TEXT>
