<HEADER>
A6395 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-KLA-0616-COX     06-15 1325
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-KLA-0616-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FLEEING SERBIAN VILLAGERS TELL OF ETHNIC CLEANSING IN REVERSE
 &HT;    EDS: Optional trim at 800
 &HT;    By JOSEPH ALBRIGHT and LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   STARI KACANIK, Yugoslavia _ Scores of terrified Serbian
civilians fled this village Tuesday, 24 hours after armed Kosovo
Liberation Army guerrillas returned from the hills and discovered a
mass grave that they blamed on Serbian troops and the local ethnic
Serb minority.
</P>
<P>
   ``The KLA fired many shots in the air. They told us, 'We don't
want to see any of you left in this village in the morning,''' said
Sasha Janicivich, 30, an ethnic Serb from this verdant farm village
20 miles south of the Kosovo capital Pristina.
</P>
<P>
   Another frightened Kosovar Serb from the village, Goran Simic,
42, said, ``The KLA came to my neighbor's house and said, 'It's not
safe for you to stay here.' We decided to leave because it was
better to save our own skins.''
</P>
<P>
   Janicivich and Simic maintained they were not members of any
Serbian paramilitary group, just peace-loving Serbian civilians.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were like brothers with the Albanians,'' said Simic, one of
about 150 Serbians from Stari Kacanik who were joining uncounted
thousands of Serbian civilians driving north out of Kosovo in cars
crammed with family members and random possessions.
</P>
<P>
   Janicivich and Simic were among six Serbians from different
families in Stari Kacanik who told a brutal tale Tuesday of reverse
ethnic cleansing at the hands of the triumphant KLA. They were
interviewed along a roadside as they headed to Serbia in a
slow-moving caravan of 30 automobiles and horse-drawn carts.
</P>
<P>
   Half an hour later, a correspondent reached the village. The KLA
soldier manning the first KLA checkpoint led the way down a grassy
hillside. There in a corner of a field was what appeared to be a
recently dug mass grave site, so fresh that the grass had not begun
to grow on the dirt covering the 17 mounds in the shape of corpses.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are many bodies here,'' said the KLA soldier,
23-year-old Sadiq Alieu. ``This town was a place the Serbian Army
had a headquarters. But we don't exactly know who did this
massacre.''
</P>
<P>
   A crew from CNN had driven into the village minutes earlier, and
a CNN cameraman was videotaping the gravesite.
</P>
<P>
   Shkurte Deda, a 16-year-old ethnic Albanian, showed up to watch.
She described how she had watched about a month and a half ago from
her house just across the road as the mass burial took place.
</P>
<P>
   ``The soldiers came here about 9 o'clock one evening with a
tractor full of bodies,'' she said. The next morning about 10 a.m.,
she said she saw Yugoslav troops digging holes for the bodies with
what she described as a ``big machine.'' From the way she gestured
with her hands, the machine could have been a backhoe.
</P>
<P>
   The Stari Kacanik suspected burial site is located roughly ten
miles from another mass grave that was discovered in a town called
Kacanik (cq) by British peacekeepers several days ago.
</P>
<P>
   The situation in Stari Kacanik is being played out, in varying
degrees, throughout Kosovo as KLA rebels emerge triumphantly from
forests and mountains.
</P>
<P>
   In Prizren Tuesday, a high-ranking rebel official sauntered into
a cafe and declared that Kosovo's second largest city was the first
one under complete KLA control.
</P>
<P>
   Mobbed by photographers and residents, the KLA's Rexha(cq) Ekram
sipped coffee as the cafe owner placed a bouquet on the table next
to his Kalashnikov rifle. A few days ago, Serb troops would have
killed him if he showed up here, but Tuesday he bantered with
reporters in good English and made an impromptu announcement.
</P>
<P>
   ``From today, the city is in KLA hands 100 percent,'' said
Ekram, known around Prizren by his war name, Commander Drini.
</P>
<P>
   The KLA, a force of an estimated 15,000 troops, seeks
independence from Yugoslavia for Kosovo and its majority ethnic
Albanian population. The army and its provisional government became
a defacto ally of NATO during its 78 days of air strikes against
Yugoslavia. It helped supply targeting information and, eventually,
may have helped bring Serbian troops into the open where NATO bombs
could kill them.
</P>
<P>
   But the newly emboldened KLA is now presenting a problem for
NATO as its peacekeepers seek to prevent acts of revenge like that
which took place in Stari Kacanik.
</P>
<P>
   Six months ago, it was a peaceful farming village with about 300
ethnic Albanian families and about 30 ethnic Serb or Croatian
families. Some of the non-Albanians had been resettled here in the
mid-1990s. It was part of a Yugoslavian government program by which
some Serbs and Croatians forced to leave Croatia in 1995 were
assigned four-acre plots to farm in some Kosovar villages.
</P>
<P>
   As of Tuesday morning, the Albanians had the village all to
themselves. But as they re-entered the houses that Serbian soldiers
had occupied for at least the last three months, they noticed that
their closets had been ransacked and their TV sets, VCRs, tools and
best clothes had been stolen.
</P>
<P>
   On the wall of one Albanian house was scrawled what appeared to
be the name of a Serbian Army unit that camped in this village:
Niski Number 8.
</P>
<P>
   Littered around the living room were beer bottles and coffee
cups and a tally sheet for a card game the Yugoslav soldiers may
have played before departing Sunday under the NATO-imposed peace
settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Outside on the courtyard wall was a chalked slogan in Serbian:
``Death to Albanians.''
</P>
<P>
   When a reporter asked how they felt about seeing the Serbian
civilians follow the troops and police in departing Stari Kacanik,
a half-dozen Albanians interviewed were unanimous in saying they
were happy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now I am angry with the Serbs,'' said Shkurte's sister,
Melvide Deda, 18. ``But now I am safe, maybe I will forget.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Story can end here. Optional add follows &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Kosovar Albanians living here said they considered many _
perhaps all _ of their former Serbian neighbors accomplices of the
departed Yugoslav soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   One family leader, Hamdi Deda, 43, said: ``The Albanians are not
the people who don't want to live together with the Serbs. Nobody
said they had to leave. But they know what was done, so they
decided they couldn't stay here.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no independent verification of exactly what the
returning KLA rebels told the Serbian villagers on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   However, one fact in the Serbian villagers' version can be
confirmed: on Monday, the KLA moved in on the heels of the
departing Yugoslavian Army contingent and soon fired repeated
bursts of Kalashnikov bullets into the air.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were happy about NATO coming to rescue our country, so we
celebrated by firing,'' said KLA soldier Sadiq Alieu, one of three
KLA soldiers who acknowledged that at least a few shots were fired
into the air.
</P>
<P>
   The nearest American peacekeeper, Sgt. Allen McDonald, 29, of
Jonesboro, Ark., was stationed on a tank of the First Armored
Division guarding a highway intersection about one mile from the
village.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were multiple bursts of shooting throughout the day
(Monday),'' said McDonald.
</P>
<P>
   Of all the participants, perhaps the most forlorn were the ten
members of a Croatian-origin farm family who were found huddled on
their horse-drawn cart as part of the northbound convoy from Stari
Kacanik to Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the second or third time we have become refugees,''
said Milan Pajic, 43. ``My father was driven out of his home at the
time of Hitler. In 1946, he returned to Croatia to make a new
family. But then in 1995, authorities in Croatia deported our
family to Kosovo. And now the KLA wants to deport all Serbs from
Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked how he felt about his predicament, Pajic said, ``My heart
is very much destroyed.''
</P>
<P>
   (Albright reported from Stari Kacanik. Kaplow reported from
Prizren).
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
