A6410 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VIDEO-DISKS-$ADV20-2T     06-15 1147
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-DISKS-$ADV20-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DVD MAY MAKE FILM SCHOLARS OF US ALL
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, June 20)  
(nk) 
 By PETER M. NICHOLS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For 20 years home video has thrived on a simple process: choose
a movie, watch it, engage in some thought and discussion, move on.
(What else do most people do with a movie?) Now, though, operating
on the principle that nothing gets simpler, along comes the digital
video disk (DVD) to immerse one in films to a degree that will
intrigue some and repel others.
</P>
<P>
   DVD invites the average viewer to become a film buff, defined as
one who wants to know all about how the movie was made and by whom.
Before DVD, enthusiasts in want of that kind of information relied
on the stately 12-inch laser disk, which often included sidebar
material about a film. At roughly 5 inches, the DVD is the same
size as a compact disk, but being a digital video medium (laser is
analog) it has vastly larger amounts of space for such extras:
feature-length commentary by filmmakers presented as a sort of
play-by-play as the movie runs, deleted scenes and alternative
endings discarded by the director, cast biographies and interviews
with actors, documentaries about the making of the film, trailers,
scripts, storyboards, production notes, set designs and the like.
</P>
<P>
   Not all DVD's have all of these items, or anywhere near all, but
most disks have at least a couple. The new reigning added-features
champion appears to be ``Ghostbusters,'' to be released June 29 by
Columbia Tri-Star. On that disk the director Ivan Reitman, the
actor Harold Ramis and the producer Joe Medjuck appear in
silhouette as they deliver a commentary. There will also be a
split-screen comparison of the film with its original storyboards,
a separate version of the film annotated with subtitles drawn from
a book about the making of ``Ghostbusters'' and ``animated 3-D
menus.''
</P>
<P>
   On top of all this, the disks work in newer computers equipped
with DVD-ROM drive (not be confused with the CD-ROM drive in most
machines). Plug in the DVD and connect to the Web for even more
features like chat rooms and live events organized around the film.
At the ``Ghostbusters'' site, the original shooting script will be
``hyperlinked'' to the film to allow viewers to jump from one to
the other and compare every little detail.
</P>
<P>
   But who has the interest or time for this kind of thing? Of
course, one remains free to ignore all the added features and just
watch the movie. But including these extras presupposes an audience
for them, and the question becomes to what extent is the general
public as obsessive about cinematographic trivia as the true
collector, scholar or fan? Except the film fetishist, who has the
motivation for endless rumination and reconsideration of what
usually is, after all, a pop-culture product?
</P>
<P>
   In any event, all of this is a far cry from lugging home a
couple of videos. The reasons are mercantile: DVD is video's great
leap forward, with a more up-to-date packaged product to counter an
expected rush of movies into the home from cable, satellite and
other broad band services. Whether consumers avail themselves of
all the features may not matter much. ``People like the fact that
they're available,'' said Benjamin Feingold, president of Columbia
Tri-Star Home Video.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say that most people are perfectly satisfied with their
tapes and VCR's. It is also true, however, that after a sputtering
start in 1997, DVD has had a faster rate of growth than the audio
CD or the VCR had when they were introduced in the early '80s, and
that DVD is expected to be in four million households by the end of
the year.
</P>
<P>
   To date, though, the disk owes its success not to extras but to
sharpness and clarity of image. DVD is strikingly superior to
videotape and outdoes the laser disk, which was also far better
than tape. That helps with big visual films _ action movies are the
biggest sellers _ especially when they're played on newer and
larger television sets. The sound, depending on one's equipment,
can be fuller and richer. Production people say it is better than
in many movie theaters.
</P>
<P>
   Viewers who never before noticed or cared much about clarity and
sharpness of image are beginning to appreciate a good picture when
they see one. ``In our minds, 75 percent of the appeal is title and
audio and video quality, not the extra features,'' said David
Miller, director of DVD development at MGM.
</P>
<P>
   Title supply is critical. If it hopes to enter the mainstream,
DVD needs to have big movies available as soon as they appear on
cassette. About 2,900 titles are out on DVD (some mail order
sources list 60,000 tapes or more), with about 250 a month being
added. For the most part, studios are releasing new movies quickly,
but now and then some of the biggest films are delayed.
``Titanic,'' for example, won't appear until September, a year
after its release on tape. ``Saving Private Ryan'' is now out on
cassette, but there has been no announcement about DVD. Reasons are
various, but some studios and directors (including Steven
Spielberg, director of ``Saving Private Ryan'') are said to have
withheld films to see whether DVD would catch on sufficiently to
warrant their release.
</P>
<P>
   Older films are another proposition. It has always been supposed
that the studios would embrace DVD as another means of selling
their libraries all over again. While that spirit prevails to some
extent, the supply of old movies has been selective. MGM, for
instance, concentrates on the big action and sci-fi epics, from
James Bond to ``The Great Escape,'' and the best-known classics,
from ``Singin' in the Rain'' to ``Raging Bull.'' The reason, Miller
said, is that the DVD audience has spread beyond enthusiasts who
collect everything on laser disk to include people who appreciate
quality but aren't buffs or collectors. ``They like good-looking,
good-sounding movies, but they aren't library builders,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Extra features add another layer of selectivity. Not every great
old film warrants them.
</P>
<P>
   `` `Key Largo,' for example, is a must for serious collectors,
but not for others despite what you do,'' Miller said. On the other
hand, ``Thelma and Louise,'' about two women on a fatal ride to
Pyrrhic liberation, has enough broad appeal to warrant a
full-length commentary by the director, Ridley Scott.
</P>
<P>
   Producers say the extras will become an acquired taste once DVD
has been around for a while. ``The average DVD viewer has just
traded up from a VCR,'' said David Goodman, president of DVD
International, a disk producer in New Jersey. ``On tape the color
red was purple or the color blue was green. It didn't matter.
Quality was never an issue. Now people are still getting over how
good video can be. The next phase will be, let's explore it and see
what it does.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Extras may not yet excite the mainstream, but they can be fun
and instructive. In the thriller ``Ronin,'' a best seller on
digital video disk, two carloads of mercenaries barrel over a
divider and scream off at speeds approaching 100 mph. That's
stepping on it, all right, and there's a complication. Having
landed on the wrong side of the highway, they are going against
traffic.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are 300 stunt drivers coming at us,'' says John
Frankenheimer, the film's director, in his full-length commentary.
``You can see with the suspensions working on these cars, nothing's
fake.''
</P>
<P>
   Frankenheimer, whose films range from from ``The Manchurian
Candidate'' to ``French Connection II,'' drove race cars himself
once and specializes in the car chase. This one was staged in
Paris. The French, he says on the disk, closed off large portions
of the city for the film. Most of the drivers had experience at Le
Mans.
</P>
<P>
   At the wheel of the pursuing vehicle, looking determined but
definitely as if he wished he were elsewhere, is Robert De Niro.
Actually, Frankenheimer explains, in many of the chase shots the
wheel is a dummy. The real wheel is on the other side of the car
and in the hands of a French Grand Prix driver. Car chases, and
there are several hair-raising ones in ``Ronin,'' are plotted
painstakingly on storyboards and shot once, using several cameras.
No retakes. Actors are expected to be in the cars and have been
sent to race school to see what it will be like.
</P>
<P>
   British commandos advised on the gun battles. Frankenheimer
talks about quick, clean transitions in dramatic scenes. No
dissolves. And no slow motion in the action sequences. ``Violence
happens fast,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Commentaries by directors can be pedestrian _ particularly when
larding on effusive praise of movie stars _ but they are often
fascinating. Recently DVD International released a fine two-disk
edition of Armistead Maupin's ``More Tales of the City,'' the
acclaimed six-hour mini-series that appeared on Showtime last June.
If a film like ``Ronin'' demonstrates how DVD enhances the big
action movie, ``More Tales'' shows how the format can add insight
into an intimate drama.
</P>
<P>
   Like ``Tales of the City,'' its noted and controversial
predecessor on PBS, the series is drawn from Maupin's novels about
life emanating from 28 Barbary Lane, the San Francisco
boardinghouse run by the deeply intuitive transsexual Anna Madrigal
(Olympia Dukakis). During a four-and-a-half-hour commentary spread
across six one-hour episodes, Maupin and others discuss everything
from the show's literary roots to its political difficulties over
sexual content. Three cast members _ Ms. Dukakis, Laura Linney and
Barbara Garrick _ reflect on their characters and the feelings of
family, both fictionally and on the set, that emerged during the
course of two long projects.
</P>
<P>
   Lengthy commentary works well for titles with large followings.
Fans of the show will surely want to watch the series once without
the commentary and then again with it, and take in all the other
extras, which run from deleted scenes to correspondence.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get to hear the footnotes as to what went on,'' Maupin
said in an interview. ``Until now only books provided that for
people who cared about film.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
