<SLUG> BC-SOCIAL-SECURITY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPUBLICAN URGES QUICK BIPARTISAN ACTION ON SOCIAL SECURITY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Rep. Bill Archer, R-Texas, who chairs the House's
chief tax-writing committee, urged his congressional colleagues
Tuesday to forget their partisan ties and work to rescue Social
Security.
</P>
<P>
   Archer's comments followed the release of a survey Tuesday
revealing that most Americans want quick action by Congress to
preserve Social Security, the federal retirement program that also
provides money to disabled people and surviving dependents.
Republicans and Democrats, fearing political fallout from
constituents, have historically refused to tamper with Social
Security, which faces financial trouble in the next 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to act now,'' said Archer, chairman of the House Ways
and Means Committee. ``Every Congress that we wait makes the job
more difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   As the baby-boom generation reaches retirement, the system will
begin to pay out more than it collects and faces depletion in 2034,
reported the bipartisan group Americans Discuss Social Security,
which conducted the survey last month.
</P>
<P>
   Privately funded by The Pew Charitable Trusts, the survey of
1,003 Americans showed 58 percent of U.S. citizens want Congress to
reform Social Security before the 2000 elections. Survey results
also revealed that rescuing Social Security is a top priority of
Americans, trailing only enhancing education and improving health
care.
</P>
<P>
   Noting the findings, Archer pressed lawmakers to ``put principle
above politics and ideas above ambition.'' The Houston Republican
said he will meet privately with GOP and Democratic committee
members Thursday to discuss their proposals for a long-term
solution to the retirement system's problems.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Charles Rangel of New York, the top Democrat on the ways
and means panel, echoed Archer's call for quick bipartisan action.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has to be an American, congressional plan that's accepted
by the president of the United States,'' Rangel said of a proposed
solution. ``If we can change the (partisan) climate ... I think we
can really get something done.''
</P>
<P>
   In a note of good news for Archer, 58 percent of survey
respondents welcomed his proposal to allow employees to invest some
of their Social Security tax privately rather than pay it all to
the government. Meanwhile, 52 percent of the respondents rejected
President Clinton's counter-proposal that the federal government _
and not employees _ invest Social Security tax revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Another potential remedy to the looming shortfall _ politically
controversial but popular among survey respondents _ is ``means
testing,'' or reducing the amount of Social Security funds paid to
retirees who receive lucrative private pensions of more than
$60,000 annually. This proposal garnered the support of 58 percent
of the respondents.
</P>
<P>
   A third proposal, favored by 61 percent, would end the payment
exemption for workers receiving annual salaries of more than
$72,600 and require these well-paid employees to begin paying
toward Social Security. But 74 percent of respondents rejected
proposals that would gradually increase the full-benefit retirement
age from 65 to 70.
</P>
<P>
   During the past two years, Americans Discuss Social Security
examined the views of a cross section of U.S. citizens regarding
the federal retirement system. The group's May survey revealed that
68 percent of the population believes that everyone will have to
forgo some Social Security benefits to ensure that the program
continues.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
