A6421 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-NBA-FINALS-COX     06-15 0698
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-FINALS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Spurs try to keep confidence in check; Knicks' best hope is
getting early lead
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO, Texas _ If you listen to the pundits, it's only a
matter of time before the Spurs are celebrating an NBA championship
at the Alamo. But if you look at what the New York Knicks have done
this postseason, such widespread thinking would be irresponsible at
worst, premature at best.
</P>
<P>
   The NBA Finals begin tonight, with many people anticipating
dominance by the San Antonio Spurs. Not to be overlooked is that
the Knicks have displayed a propensity for playing their best when
least expected.
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs are not.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know everyone around here knows we have to go out and win
this championship,'' Spurs center David Robinson said. ``The Knicks
didn't just show up here. They earned the right to be here by
beating some pretty good teams. For us to be overconfident when
you're playing for the NBA championship would be crazy. It'd be a
big mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks have a formidable chore in front of them. The Spurs
have won 42 of their last 48 games. They swept the Los Angeles
Lakers and the Portland Trailblazers. And they are healthy.
</P>
<P>
   New York's best hope _other than playing outstanding basketball
_- is jumping ahead 1-0 in the series against a team that has
developed some rust from nine days off.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't simulate game conditions, especially game conditions
in the finals,'' said Spurs guard Steve Kerr, who experienced the
challenge while playing with the Bulls. ``So, the time off could be
a factor. We've practiced hard. It's just a matter of seeing how we
respond to a game that's far more important than any game most of
the guys have ever played.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Knicks, only backup center Herb Williams, 41, has played
in the finals; the 1994 Knicks lost in seven games to Houston. The
seldom-used Williams, 41, stands to receive playing time tonight if
forward Larry Johnson's sprained right knee keeps him sidelined.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson has not tried to run or play basketball since going down
in the second quarter of New York's decisive Game 6 of the Eastern
Conference finals against Indiana. His availability figures to be a
significant factor for a team already shorthanded by a
season-ending injury to center Patrick Ewing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel better today than I did yesterday,'' Johnson said
Tuesday. ``It's a tough situation. To get to the NBA Finals and
then have to watch from the sidelines, to not even be able to
practice _ it's tough. And then if I do come back, I'll be wearing
a bulky brace after five days off, out of rhythm and a little out
of shape. So, all the way around, it's just tough.''
</P>
<P>
   With Johnson's status a game-time decision, coach Jeff Van Gundy
probably will start former regular Kurt Thomas up front with center
Chris Dudley and Latrell Sprewell. Not exactly an imposing trio
against Robinson, Tim Duncan and Sean Elliott _ all former or
current all-stars.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we still have to play the games,'' said energetic Marcus
Camby, who figures to be a key for the Knicks. ``I don't think
we're a team of destiny; we've just gone out and won the games we
needed to. It's a great story to get where we are after so much
craziness going on, on the court and off it. But we're here, and we
have a chance to add to our great story.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the craziness has been the controversialSprewell, who was
signed and then steamed over his backup role in the regular season;
general manager Ernie Grunfeld, who was fired; and coach Jeff Van
Gundy, whose job has been insecure all year.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks' biggest challenge is coping with San Antonio's
peerless inside tandem of Duncan and Robinson. Van Gundy observed
that they usually deter dribble penetration, so he expects outside
shots to fly.
</P>
<P>
   ``They reduce teams to be jump-shooting teams,'' he said. ``And
then you'll be an inconsistent team, which is why they go on big
runs against teams. So, we're going to have to make some open
shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we're here. We'll play our game and we'll take our best
shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
