<HEADER>
A6422 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-FALCONS-NOTES-COX     06-15 0669
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-NOTES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Anderson, new deal out of Reeves' reach
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Falcons coach Dan Reeves said Tuesday he tried to call
All-Pro running back Jamal Anderson, but the two sides remain far
from an agreement on a contract extension.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson's agent, Jim Sims, said Monday he and Anderson were
looking for signs that talks were ``moving forward'' before the
player attends voluntary passing camp.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons consider their five-year, $26 million contract offer
as proof their intentions are earnest. That's $1 million shy of the
franchise-record five-year, $27 million contract quarterback Chris
Chandler got last season.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson, though, wants more money, and is believed to be
seeking a signing bonus of at least $10 million. The franchise
record is the $6 million bonus Chandler got.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to renegotiate . . . but we're a ways apart,''
Reeves said after a 75-minute session on the second day of the
two-week camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did leave a message, and hopefully I'll talk to him soon.
Whether that will change Jamal's thinking . . . we'll just coach
the ones we have.''
</P>
<P>
   Attempts to reach Anderson Tuesday in Salt Lake City failed.
</P>
<P>
   But on his Web site Monday night, he wrote, ``In case anyone
wants to know, the contract situation is going in the right
direction, and I expect to be back in camp any day now.''
</P>
<P>
   Money matters
</P>
<P>
   If the Falcons sign Anderson to an extension, the team will have
more cap room available to consider extending some of the other
nine starters who are potential unrestricted free agents.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson is to earn $1.6 million in salary this season and more
than $1 million in incentives earned last season. His charge
against the salary cap, however, is about $3.6 million.
</P>
<P>
   Because his salary-cap charge already is so high, an extension
probably would drop that number and create more than $1 million in
cap room.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the other potential unrestricted free agents have cap
charges low enough that extensions would increase their charges.
</P>
<P>
   Beefing up
</P>
<P>
   Second-year player Bob Hallen continues to work with the first
unit at right guard because of the absence of Gene Williams.
Williams is missing workouts because he is unhappy the team won't
tell him if it plans to extend his contract.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-4 Hallen, the team's second-round draft choice in
1998, has added 12-15 pounds and weighs ``about 300 to 305,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive tackle Ben Huff, who was on the practice squad last
year, has bulked up about 15 pounds to 300.
</P>
<P>
   Injury update
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons are pleased that running backs Byron Hanspard and
Bob Christian are participating in camp while they recover from
knee injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Hanspard tore the anterior cruciate ligament and patellar tendon
in his left knee in the final preseason game last summer.
</P>
<P>
   As a rookie in 1997, Hanspard averaged 6.3 yards and had three
of the 12 longest carries in franchise history _ 77, 57 and 53
yards. He also returned two kickoffs for touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm feeling a lot better. The Lord has blessed me with great
trainers and strength coaches,'' said Hanspard, who appears to have
no problems changing directions.
</P>
<P>
   Christian partially tore the ACL in his left knee in a Dec. 13
game at New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bob appears to have built up the strength in his leg,'' Reeves
said. ``He looks really good.''
</P>
<P>
   Middle linebacker Jeff Kelly, a sixth-round draft choice, has
been slowed by a pulled hamstring.
</P>
<P>
   Extra points
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons signed kicker Mike Panasuk, 30, who was in the
Chiefs' training camp in '93 and Denver's camp last summer. Atlanta
has 79 players, and can carry 80. . . . The team is off today and
will resume passing camp Thursday and Friday. . . . The team holds
a mandatory minicamp July 7-9.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Winkeljohn writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
