<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-15 18:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6427 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-MONTY-COX     06-15 0841
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-MONTY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Montgomerie ready to conquer U.S. Open for Europe
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PINEHURST, N.C. _ Scotland's Colin Montgomerie brings a new
mindset this week to the U.S. Open, where he often has felt the
heat on both sides of the ropes. After three near-misses in the
major championship he enjoys more than any other, the dominant
player of Europe is calling on help from all challengers on his
side of the pond.
</P>
<P>
   No U.S. Open has been won by a European player since England's
Tony Jacklin in 1971. With that fact in mind, after his initial
tour of Pinehurst No. 2 Tuesday, the 35-year-old Montgomerie seemed
all but ready to hoist a European flag over the Carolina Hotel.
</P>
<P>
   ``The runoffs (of the greens) are quite similar to (the Masters
in) Augusta in many ways,'' Montgomerie said, ``and we've won 11
out of the last 20 of them, so it might well favor the European
player here for the first time in many years.''
</P>
<P>
   Montgomerie's comments came with a touch of playfulness, but
they were delivered with authority. While there's really no
explaining how Montgomerie can win six consecutive money titles on
the European Tour but go totally winless in America, it's equally
puzzling why the U.S. Open has not been as pleasant as Augusta
National for the Europeans. And enough is enough, Monty said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's motivation for every British golfer and also
every European golfer to try and emulate that feat (by Jacklin),''
he said. ``I think it's been too long, really. It's almost 30 years
now. (Nick) Faldo has lost in playoffs, and so have I, so we've
been quite close. It's just a matter of being patient and trying to
walk through when that door is half ajar. It's the point of walking
through it and not finishing second.''
</P>
<P>
   This year could be different. The rough is manageable by USGA
standards, and with creativity around the greens at Pinehurst No. 2
more crucial than driving the ball long and straight, the European
factor could be more noticeable. For those who doubt, remember the
Ryder Cup at Valderrama. And while chipping and putting might not
be Montgomerie's strong suit, it surely finds itself on the resume
of Masters champion Jose Maria Olazabal.
</P>
<P>
   ``This type of course brings in the possibility of a win for the
likes of a player like Olazabal,'' Montgomerie said, ``who might
not hit the ball as straight off some of the tees. These fairways
are giving him more of a chance of doing that, and to use his
enormous talent around the greens, and his imagination, which this
will take.''
</P>
<P>
   Sadly, Montgomerie's chances could again depend on outside
forces. American crowds have never warmed to him, unfortunately,
and on several occasions they have shouted insults. Last year,
David Duval and Jim Furyk said they were embarrassed by fan
comments to the Scot, who actually is one of the more likeable
players around.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as Monty does not let the crowd get to him,'' Olazabal
said, ``he's got to have a great chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked how he is perceived by American audiences and why they
have not warmed to him, Montgomerie played dumb to the question,
but he recognized it as a no-win situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never really thought about it, to be honest,'' he said,
smiling. ``Such a good question, you've stumped me. . . . I really
do feel I get similar treatment to any other European or foreign
player that comes over to America.''
</P>
<P>
   For certain, Montgomerie's game could not be much sharper. He
won twice in three weeks in Europe, including a smashing Sunday at
the Volvo PGA Championship with a closing 64.
</P>
<P>
   ``Colin is probably playing the best he has ever played, and
that's saying a lot,'' Ernie Els said. ``He is just lapping the
field, and the way he is playing now he will probably win a major.
``
</P>
<P>
   Montgomerie came into Congressional two years ago on a similar
run and opened with a 65, eventually finishing second to Els.
Although much has been made of the seven-footer for par that
Montgomerie missed at the 71st hole, after a long wait because of
rowdy fans, his real demise that week was a second-round 76. He
calls the opening 65 ``as good as I can play,'' but he termed the
64 two weeks ago at Wentworth nearly as fine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just haven't managed to find the necessary form for four
days,'' Monty said. ``I did it for three at Congressional and threw
in a 76 in the second round. You can't afford to do that. . . .
It's just a matter of trying to maintain form and confidence,
because the game is there. I've just got to go out with the same
belief that I take into the European tournaments, and hopefully it
will work out.''
</P>
<P>
   If so, Montgomerie's putting will have to be near-perfect. When
he tied Steve Elkington in the 1995 PGA at Riviera, eventually
losing the playoff, he had used 17 putts more than the Australian.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never blamed my long game,'' Monty said. ``I just haven't
holed out as well as the winner has.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
