<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-15 18:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6430 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SURREALISM-GUGGENHEIM     06-15 1033
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SURREALISM-GUGGENHEIM-$ADV20-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GEORGES HUGNET, SURREALIST OF MANY TALENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, June 20)  
(mk) 
 By VICKI GOLDBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Surrealism, generally thought of as melting watches
and men in bowler hats descending from the sky, began as a literary
movement. In 1924, when the writer Andre Breton published his
``Manifeste du Surrealisme,'' he didn't bother to mention visual
artists until he got to the footnotes. This was troubling. Some in
the movement were not certain that painting could match Breton's
``pure psychic automatism'' of verbal expression, which he
described as going beyond the constraints of reason and ``beyond
any aesthetic or moral preoccupation.''
</P>
<P>
   After a couple of years, painting that engaged in automatism and
courted dreams squeaked through the Surrealist door as well. Today
the painters _ Salvador Dali, Rene Magritte, Max Ernst, Joan Miro
and Yves Tanguey, among others _ are thought to have stolen the
movement away and run off with the prize.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the group around Breton had several talents, and they
collaborated with one another just about every other Wednesday,
photographing one another, making films and founding magazines
together, writing articles for their friends, illustrating one
another's books. Lots of books. The movement in its heyday always
had a literary bent _ a wide angle, in fact, to judge by the large
number of remarkable book illustrations and covers on view in
``Surrealism: Two Private Eyes,'' an exhibition at the Guggenheim
Museum running through Sept. 12.
</P>
<P>
   For a more concentrated view of the literary/artistic side of
the movement, the Zabriskie Gallery on 57th Street is offering,
through July 16, ``Georges Hugnet (1906-1974): Collages,'' a show
of 37 collages made by Hugnet between 1936 and 1961 plus multiple
copies of three of his books, enabling both the covers and some of
the illustrations to be shown.
</P>
<P>
   Both the published and the unpublished collages reveal a tasty
sense of humor, the standard Surrealist obsession with naked women
and the required Surrealist penchant for highly improbable
meetings. Hugnet also had a positively saucy sense of naughtiness.
Put him next to the French Surrealist Pierre Molinier or the Czech
Jindrich Styrsky at the Guggenheim (not to mention Robert
Mapplethorpe or Nan Goldin more recently), and Hugnet's petites
scandales begin to look faintly Victorian.
</P>
<P>
   In his visions, there are goats that pursue a nude who is trying
to squeeze through the window of a cottage, a penguin that appears
to lift the skirt of a woman whose head is a metal disk with bunny
ears of fabric, and a bra and half slip that proudly stand in the
air before an erupting volcano. In the 1940s, Hugnet was rather
more explicit in a project called ``La Vie Amoureuse des
Spumifieres'' (``The Love Life of the Spumifieres''), in which he
used risque Victorian postcards, drawing over them strange little
creatures, half insect and wholly libidinous.
</P>
<P>
   His 1936 book, ``Septieme Face du De'' (``Seventh Face of the
Die''), scatters across a page cutouts of photographs and printed
phrases from magazines, making a kind of collage poetry. The words
form a kind of ``exquisite corpse,'' a game best known for the mad
drawings that resulted when a piece of paper was folded in three
and three people then drew pictures on it of adjoining parts of the
body, from the head down, without knowing what the previous part
looked like.
</P>
<P>
   The game had actually begun as a word game, with three or four
people completing sentences without knowing how they started.
Hugnet cut his words and phrases from periodicals and assembled
them as if they were the babblings of a poet after a particularly
delicate dose of peyote: ``Will someone elucidate a rainbow?''
``Because it's the sun that's wrong Because a heel can be compared
to a young woman who dreams of love.''
</P>
<P>
   This method involved more rational choice _ something the
Surrealists claimed not to value highly _ than a true exquisite
corpse does. Hugnet knew what came before. Well, maybe he threw a
lot of phrases into the air and let chance take them wandering, but
if so, he cheated afterward. Chance is seldom so poetic, or so
grammatical. Whichever, the result is a kind of free association
that would drive an analyst to drink or, worse yet, to
deconstruction.
</P>
<P>
   In the book ``Huit Jours a Trebaumec'' (``Eight Days in
Trebaumec''), Hugnet spoofed both the Guide Michelin and
traditional travel diaries. He recounted a trip that Lewis Carroll
might have booked: When their hostess danced an ancient Celtic
dance called the Hair-do on the beach, he illustrated it with a
``snapshot'' of two heads of hair atop one pair of legs that seem
to have misplaced their torso and arms yet can gaily dance in high
heels at the edge of the surf.
</P>
<P>
   Hugnet designed a choice book cover _ it's on display at the
Guggenheim _ for Hans Bellmer's photographs of his notorious doll,
a female mannequin with removable parts that Bellmer removed or
multiplied to sinister effect. Both the front and back covers of
this book sport an actual pink garter with a bit of white lace
above and a bit of black stocking below. In one of his own
collages, Hugnet used a favorite form of Bellmer's: two pairs of
female legs atop each other, one right side up, the other upside
down.
</P>
<P>
   Bellmer's doubled legs _ women without bodies, defiantly
artificial in Mary Janes _ seem severed, slightly monstrous,
borderline schizophrenic. Hugnet's leg-women _ full-color
photographs clipped from magazines _ have downright perky
personalities in comparison; they're sweet, they're cute, they wear
taffeta skirts. Bellmer and Hugnet deserve a certain dubious amount
of credit for discovering that legs have personalities.
</P>
<P>
   Virgil Thomson described Hugnet as ``small, truculent and
sentimental,'' a man of outrageous and, if you liked outrage,
hilarious conversation. Sounds like just the personality for that
febrile group of artists in the '30s. He will probably not be
remembered as a major player in Surrealism, partly because he was
not a painter, but he had plenty of talent.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Plenty of talents, actually. A poet, at age 14 he so impressed
the writer Max Jacob that Jacob introduced him to Cocteau, Picasso,
Duchamp, Ernst, Calder and the rest of his group. Duchamp later did
covers for two editions of a Hugnet book, and Dali did a
frontispiece for another. Hugnet wrote early and widely on
contemporary art, including the preface to the Museum of Modern
Art's 1936 show ``Fantastic Art, Dada, and Surrealism.'' He is
probably assured his own firm place in the history of art as a
historian of Dada and Surrealism, and a minor place in the history
of Surrealism for the charm of his art as well.
</P>
<P>
   He also wrote the script for a 1929 film called ``La Perle'' and
starred in it, wrote plays, translated Gertrude Stein into French,
founded his own publishing house and his own literary review,
collected art and popular objects, was an art dealer for a while
and a rare book dealer for another, designed book covers and made a
multitude of collages. Virgil Thomson set some of his poems to
music.
</P>
<P>
   Visual collage seems like child's play now, as do mobiles, which
once upon a time, before Alexander Calder made them look easy, were
not made by elementary school children. Photographic collage, which
goes back to the 19th century, is embedded in 20th-century life.
The art critic Harold Rosenberg once remarked that the photographic
esthetic of finding _ the photographer combing the world for
subjects worth dignifying _ had had an immense influence on
contemporary culture, from the spread of insatiable collecting to
the massive revision of art through incorporation of real-world
objects and representations in collage and assemblage.
</P>
<P>
   He might have noted that the commercial districts of modern
cities, and modern highways that have not yet retired their
billboards, present variations on collage, with phrases on one sign
abutting unrelated phrases on the next, and photographs and
drawings in wildly disparate styles cut into appropriate shapes for
display, then pasted on the sides of buildings and buses, phone
booths, newsstands and store windows.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to know what to call a collage that moves, but we have
that too, as people wearing photographic portraits and logos and
cartoon heroes on their T-shirts pass one another on the street,
and stacked television sets showing the same program perform their
Nam June Paik imitations in the aisles of Nobody Beats the Wiz.
Times Square is simply an overgrown collage that blinks. The
computer has made cutting and pasting so easy that everyone may yet
be Georges Hugnet.
</P>
<P>
   The Surrealist impulse (which goes beyond collage but which
collage readily satisfies) has been unusually tenacious because
even during working hours our streets are full of sewing machines,
umbrellas and dissecting tables. Lost souls cry for spare change in
front of boutiques selling diamonds as big as the Ritz. A woman
covered head to foot with blue makeup brushes her hair in a store
window on Fifth Avenue. Not to mention the great TV surfing
experience, where the click of a button transports you from cartoon
rabbits with big teeth to threatening lady preachers, from Serb
atrocities to Ricky Martin kissing passionately even as he sings in
the background.
</P>
<P>
   Television really ought to have put Surrealism to bed, but
instead it has kept it awake for 24 hours at a time, and
computer-driven special effects have pumped up the remains of that
literary and artistic movement with infusions of grandeur.
</P>
<P>
   Hugnet was more modest _ and more amusing. The Surrealists may
not have been any more ambitious than other artists (which is
ambitious enough), but they succeeded even beyond their own daft
dreams, by infiltrating the environment and leaving their impress
on the whole of modern life.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
