<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-CAMPAIGN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS GOVERNOR WINDS UP FIRST CAMPAIGN SWING WITH RAVE REVIEWS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RON HUTCHESON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DERRY, N.H. _ The welcome sign outside Madden's Family
Restaurant on Tuesday pretty well summed up the campaign debut of
Gov. George W. Bush: ``Wow! What a start!''
</P>
<P>
   Even Bush's opponents acknowledged that the Texas Republican's
initial foray to Iowa and New Hampshire confirmed his front-runner
status in the race for the GOP presidential nomination. It wasn't a
flawless performance, but Bush's four-day campaign blitz did not
disappoint supporters with sky-high expectations.
</P>
<P>
   At stop after stop, the first-time presidential candidate
generated the kind of enthusiasm and media attention that typically
occurs in the closing days of a primary campaign.
</P>
<P>
   One New Hampshire newspaper dubbed the governor's whirlwind tour
``Hurricane Bush.'' His GOP rivals can only hope that the winds die
down before they get flattened.
</P>
<P>
   ``This may be the Second Coming, but I don't think so,'' said
Keith Fortmann, who is directing former Vice President Dan Quayle's
Iowa campaign.
</P>
<P>
   After a final day of campaigning in New Hampshire, Bush ended
his first outing with side trips to fund-raisers in Boston and
Greenwich, Conn. Organizers said the Boston event raised more than
$800,000, a record for a Republican in the state.
</P>
<P>
   But the real point of Bush's trip was to test his appeal to
voters in Iowa and New Hampshire, the traditional leadoff states
for presidential politics. Bush ended his New Hampshire visit with
the kind of one-on-one campaigning that the state is known for.
</P>
<P>
   Although his Texas drawl may sound foreign to New Hampshire
ears, Bush's hands-on campaign style seemed to impress shift
workers at HADCO Corp., a circuit board manufacturing plant in
Derry. The media horde following Bush complicated his efforts to
meet face-to-face with voters, but it also added to the feeling
that he is not just another presidential long-shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``He seems like a down-to-earth kind of guy,'' worker Bill Brown
said after Bush joined Brown and some friends at a picnic table
just before shift change. ``I really didn't expect him to come sit
down with us.''
</P>
<P>
   At the nearby Madden's restaurant, Bush grabbed a coffee pot and
filled diners' cups.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the only governor I've had pour coffee for me,'' said a
delighted Jerry Muzzey of Hooksett.
</P>
<P>
   But many of Bush's fans conceded that they know little about his
political views. Bush deliberately avoided specifics on his first
trip, saying that he wanted to focus on broad concepts.
</P>
<P>
   On one issue that he did address head-on, abortion, the governor
may have hurt his standing with some anti-abortion activists. Bush
said he would not use an anti-abortion litmus test in selecting
Supreme Court nominees.
</P>
<P>
   At times, especially when he seemed tired, the candidate fumbled
applause lines in his standard stump speech. His audiences didn't
seem to care.
</P>
<P>
   ``He looks good to me so far,'' said New Hampshire State Rep.
Eileen Dawe of Nashua. ``We'll have to see if he has a direction
for the nation.''
</P>
<P>
   Aides to Bush's rivals predicted that fascination with the Texas
Republican _ and his stellar poll ratings _ will fade with time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew that this period of romance had to come. But when it
wears off, we'll be there waiting,'' said Steve Grubbs, a top Iowa
adviser to candidate Steve Forbes.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, whose campaign days started before dawn and stretched into
the night, said he was pleased with the results.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a fantastic experience,'' he said after the final New
Hampshire stop. ``It's a long road. It's just the beginning. I'll
be back.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
