<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUNS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Clinton calls on Congress to pass tougher gun legislation
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With the House set to open an emotional debate on
teens and violence today, President Clinton on Tuesday pleaded with
Congress to enact new laws to keep guns out of the hands of
juveniles and criminals.
</P>
<P>
   In a Rose Garden ceremony attended by families of children
killed in gun violence, Clinton urged members of Congress to reject
the strong-arm tactics of the gun lobby and strengthen the 1993
Brady bill, requiring criminal background checks for handgun
purchases, to also include gun shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``Congress has another vitally important choice before it,''
Clinton said. ``Are they going to strengthen the Brady bill or
weaken it? The Brady law has worked. It's worked so well, in fact,
that criminals now have to buy their weapons at places not fully
covered by the gun laws, like gun shows and flea markets.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton released new Justice Department figures showing that the
Brady bill and subsequent instant background checks system that
went into effect last year had prevented more than 400,000 firearms
from falling into the hands of people barred by law from having
them. Two-third of those denied guns had felony convictions or
indictments, Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   On Capitol Hill, meanwhile, Republican leaders wrestled with how
to structure the floor debate on the proposed gun control measures
and a raft of other proposals geared toward dismantling the
``culture of violence'' that young people are exposed to in movies,
television shows and video games.
</P>
<P>
   The House will debate the gun control provisions, including
requirements that guns be sold with trigger locks and a new ban on
large ammunition clips, either today or Thursday. Members will vote
on scores of amendments, but the bulk of the debate will be focused
on how best to close the so-called gun show loophole.
</P>
<P>
   An amendment offered by Rep. Carolyn McCarthy (D-N.Y.), whose
husband was gunned down in a train shooting in 1993, would closely
mirror language adopted by the Senate, giving law enforcement three
business days to conduct criminal background checks at gun shows.
It would also require sellers to collect information on buyers that
could be used to trace the guns sold. Clinton and many other
Democrats back this language.
</P>
<P>
   Judiciary Chairman Henry Hyde (R-Ill.) and Rep. Bill McCollum
(R-Fla.) have another alternative that would require background
checks, but allow law enforcement three consecutive days to do
them. It would also exempt small gatherings of gun sellers from the
requirements and allow dealers to ship guns across state lines,
which they have been barred from doing since 1968.
</P>
<P>
   A third option, sponsored by Rep. John Dingell (D-Mich.) and
other conservative Democrats, would weaken the Hyde bill even
further by reducing the 72 hour time for checks to 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
   With the deep ideological divisions in the House, few House
leaders were willing to predict the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to tell where the votes will be,'' said Rep. Dick
Armey (R-Texas), the House majority leader, adding he might support
the Dingell alternative. ``Neither side is going to win. Everybody
understands that every individual member has got to come to terms
with themselves and their district on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also acknowledged that it will be tough for the House to
vote for new gun control, even though most Americans support new
restrictions in the wake of the shootings at high schools in
Colorado and Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of our members who desperately want to vote for this bill
come from congressional districts which are less populous than
almost all states, and where the influence of the NRA and their
ability to promote scare tactics and misinformation is relatively
greater,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents and proponents of new restrictions on the types of
movies, video games and literature available to juveniles also
geared up for today's floor debate.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Jack Kingston (R-Ga.) and several other GOP lawmakers
pushed a sense of Congress resolution calling on the entertainment
industry to stop portrayals of ``gratuitous violence in movies,
television, music and video games.''
</P>
<P>
   Displaying a graphic ad for a game called, ``You're gonna die,''
Kingston chided Congress for focusing on guns at the exclusion of
other societal pressures.
</P>
<P>
   ``This debate has been focused on the National Rifle
Association...and sidestepped the issue of violence on
television,'' said Kingston, who opposes new gun control measures.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Mark Foley (R-Fla.), meanwhile, assailed Hyde for his
proposal to hold the distributors of violent video games and movies
responsible for distributing the material to juveniles 17 and
younger. Hyde's proposal calls for five year sentences for those
who knowingly break the law, and would also require music stores to
provide copies of song lyrics to parents who want to see them.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a Republican, I thought our party was committed to
lessening government interference in the affairs of commerce and
our personal lives,'' said Foley, chairman of the Republican
Entertainment Task Force. ``This reckless proposal would
dramatically increase the power of the federal government in far
too many areas.''
</P>
<P>
   Ken Foskett writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
