<SLUG> BC-ROSA-PARKS16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ROSA PARKS AWARDED CONGRESSIONAL GOLD MEDAL
 &HT;    By RAVEN HILL
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Hailed as the ``mother of the civil rights
movement,'' Rosa Parks received the Congressional Gold Medal on
Tuesday in a ceremony in the Capitol Rotunda.
</P>
<P>
   Parks's activism during the civil rights movement and in the
years since were recounted by a panoply of leaders that included
President Clinton, House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., and the
Rev. Jesse Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Julia Carson, D-Ind., recalled Parks's famous refusal to
give up her bus seat to a white man in December 1955, which sparked
the Montgomery bus boycott and lent a major impetus to the civil
rights movement.
</P>
<P>
   Comparing Parks to the biblical Job, ``unmovable and
unshakable,'' Carson said the medal is a celebration of Parks's
life, and she is grateful that it could be presented ``while she
can still feel it and while she can still see it.''
</P>
<P>
   Carson introduced the measure honoring Parks on Feb. 4. It was
approved unanimously by the Senate and by a vote of 424-1 in the
House, where Rep. Ron Paul, R-Texas, said he opposed spending
federal funds on such awards.
</P>
<P>
   Parks, 86, who now lives in Detroit, thanked all of the people
who participated in the bus boycott nearly 44 years ago and urged
everyone to ``continue until all people have equal rights.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Spencer Abraham, R-Mich., said that Parks's arrest was
intended to show that Alabama would not tolerate defiance against
its segregationist laws, but instead sent an entirely different
message _ ``that people would no longer tolerate second-class
citizenship.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton noted that he was 9 when Parks committed her act of
defiance, and that he and some of his friends were so impressed
that ``we began to sit on the back of the bus when we got on.''
</P>
<P>
   The Congressional Gold Medal, the highest honor the country can
bestow on a civilian, has in recent years been awarded to Mother
Teresa, Frank Sinatra, Winston Churchill and most recently, Nelson
Mandela.
</P>
<P>
   House Minority Leader Dick Gephardt, D-Mo., said it is only
fitting that Parks follow Mandela.
</P>
<P>
   ``She helped break the same chains that held back millions of
Americans simply because of the color of their skin,'' Gephardt
said.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle, D-S.D., recalled that rays
of sunlight shone upon the bust of Dr. Martin Luther King Jr. in
the Rotunda as Mandela began to speak after receiving his medal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looked, for an instant, like Dr. King had come back to life
and was smiling at what he was seeing,'' Daschle said. ``I believe
Dr. King is smiling again today.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
