<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Page 1, Wednesday, June 16. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The N.Y. Times News Service
Night Supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-GRAVES (Djakovica, Yugoslavia) _ The Serbs' most brutal
force in their campaign to drive out Kosovo's ethnic Albanian
majority fell on this city and a swath of villages around it in the
shadow of the Accursed Mountains. On Tuesday, in a landscape of
gravesites, burned homes, toppled mosque minarets and smashed shops
it became clear just how ferocious that campaign had been. By John
Kifner and Ian Fisher. 1,900 words.
</P>
<P>
   With map and photos.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MILOSEVIC (Belgrade, Yugoslavia) _ President Slobodan
Milosevic has thrown himself into an unusually energetic campaign
to rally a disillusioned and depressed public against signs of
political discontent that includes a call for his resignation from
the Serbian Orthodox Church. By Carlotta Gall. 1,200 words.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RDP (Pristina, Yugoslavia) _ Roundup: The Yugoslav
military largely complied with NATO's demands to leave a large part
of Kosovo by midnight Tuesday, with thousands of soldiers involved
in President Slobodan Milosevic's war withdrawing on tanks, trucks
and tractors. By Steven Lee Myers.
</P>
<P>
   With photo and map.
</P>
<P>
   MEDICARE-DRUGS (Washington) _ What may be one of the last great
health care struggles of the Clinton administration _ providing a
major new drug benefit for older Americans _ has begun on Capitol
Hill. And the politics around it are so ferocious, so inextricably
linked to the battle over control of the House and the White House,
and so reminiscent of health care battles past, that no one is
quite sure whether the end result will be a policy or a campaign
issue. By Robin Toner. 1,900 words.
</P>
<P>
   SILICON-VALLEY (Palo Alto, Calif.) _ In Silicon Valley, these
are the days of miracles and wonder. In the midst of the longest
sustained boom in the nation's high-technology heartland, there is
an air of unreality that has come to color the outlook of the
computer engineers, venture capitalists and software hackers,
leading to a growing sense of unease ``The valley is now divided
into two camps,'' said John Shoch, a partner at Alloy Ventures,
``there are those people who are firmly inside a reality-distortion
field, and there are the rest of us who realize that this is going
to end but who can't help going along for the ride.'' By John
Markoff. 1,500 words.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-GUNS (Washington) _ More details on the proposed
anti-violence legislation, and other developments on guns. By Frank
Bruni.
</P>
<P>
   Reefers:
</P>
<P>
   POPE (Lowicz, Poland) _ Racing to mend the centuries-old breach
between Orthodox and Roman Catholic believers, Pope John Paul II
has turned Vatican planning upside down and decided to go ahead
with a previously canceled meeting with the head of the Armenian
Apostolic Church in Yerevan after leaving Poland. By Alessandra
Stanley. (MOVED)
</P>
<P>
   KOREA-CONFRONT (Tokyo) _ An early morning firefight in disputed
waters in the Yellow Sea recedes into a verbal clash, as North
Korea demands an apology and lashes out at South Korea for sinking
one of its warships. Each side contends that the other fired first,
but the result is not disputed. By Sheryl WuDunn. (MOVED)
</P>
