<SLUG> BC-POLITE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lawmakers want fourth 'R' _ 'Respect' _ taught in schools
 &HT;    By Anne Rochell Konigsmark
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ If kids talk like their grandparents did, maybe
they'll act like them.
</P>
<P>
   That's the logic behind Louisiana legislation requiring public
school students to address teachers and other school employees as
``sir'' and ``ma'am.'' That means this fall, students will have a
fourth ``R'' to learn: Respect.
</P>
<P>
   The bill sailed through the Senate and then passed the House
this week on an 81-19 vote. Pending some discussion of minor
amendments and the governor's signature, it will become law.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bill is intended to encourage courtesy and respect and to
help people learn good habits of civility,'' said state Rep.
Charles Hudson, a Democrat from Opelousas. ``I think it will make
students better behaved. When you practice the Golden Rule, it
becomes a habit.'' But Dennis Boudreaux, a teacher and a parent
from Erath, thinks the law is useless. ``I have kids who never
misbehave and never told me `yes sir' or `no sir,' and I have kids
who are very polite and very bad,'' he said. ``I'd rather have a
law that gives me more power to discipline.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, the ``sir'' and ``ma'am'' bill requires only elementary
school students to use the terms of respect. But it will expand to
include middle and high schools.
</P>
<P>
   In earlier versions, the bill was even stricter: It would have
forced students to stand every time a principal entered the room,
and teachers would have addressed students as ``Mr.'' and
``Ms.''Anne Rochell Konigsmark writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
