<DOCNO> NYT19990615.0222 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-15 19:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6453 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-PEC-0616-COX     06-15 0748
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-PEC-0616-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FROM GHOST-TOWN TO GHOST-CITY, ALBANIANS MISSING FROM WESTERN
KOSOVO
 &HT;    With KOSOVO-KLA; KOSOVO-SERBS.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEC, Kosovo _ With hundreds of people missing and thousands of
homes destroyed, southwestern Kosovo looks like the scene of a
natural disaster.
</P>
<P>
   But it was nearly three months of ethnic cleansing that pounded
this region, and in the eye of the storm was the city of Pec, today
eerily still and abandoned by its Albanian majority.
</P>
<P>
   Downtown Pec revolves around a central square, a 10-story bank
building, a shopping center and a park. But the only signs of life
there Tuesday, four days after NATO troops began overseeing a Serb
troop withdrawal from Kosovo, were a dozen Serb men lounging on
park benches and the occasional passing NATO vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   In one of the first visits from foreign journalists and while
life is slowly being rebuilt in other Kosovo cities, Pec was still
a shell of a city. NATO troops sometimes walk back-to-back to keep
an eye out for snipers. Women on the outskirts furtively seek
information about family members who have been arrested by Serb
police.
</P>
<P>
   Pictures of Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic still stand in
the window of a downtown store, but all the stores are closed. Dogs
wander the streets and, outside town, cattle wander through the
broken windows of greenhouses for grazing space.
</P>
<P>
   As the home of the Serbian Orthodox Church, Pec is a central
element to the claim Serbs make for Kosovo. The partriarchate was
the bastion of Serb identity when the Serbs faced rule by the
Ottoman Muslims for nearly 500 years. Currently, thanks largely to
a campaign of Serbian repression that intensified with NATO bombing
of Yugoslavia, that church is the home to some of the city's few
inhabitants.
</P>
<P>
   The middle-aged Serb men sharing park benches and bottle of
brandy in the central square Tuesday say they are sleeping in the
patriarchate because they fear what the ethnic Albanian majority
would do to them. The men's families are already elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``This partriarchate is our own and the land is our own,'' said
Serb Mishko Milonovic, 47.
</P>
<P>
   In words that rang somewhat hollow coming in an abandoned public
square, these men said they wanted to live in peace with ethnic
Albanians and that they were just afraid of the Kosovo Liberation
Army (KLA), which they called a terrorist organization.
</P>
<P>
   They blamed ``extremist elements'' among their fellow Serbs for
the burning of Kosovar Albanian homes and note that some of the
damage on the nearby roads was caused by NATO airstrikes, which had
touched off the intense Serb terror.
</P>
<P>
   Down the road, the grim details of Serb atrocities were being
revealed. In Velika Krusa, an abandoned village of red-block homes
that once housed 6,000 ethnic Albanians, KLA troops showed their
NATO counterparts a home with the charred remains of 20 Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   Other sites were being unearthed throughout the region, exposing
body parts and personal affects.
</P>
<P>
   But, it was the broad sweep of the devastation in the region,
possibly the hardest hit in the province, that showed the effect of
Serb efforts to remove ethnic Albanians. In most Albanian villages,
it seemed that more than half the homes were burned. Meanwhile, a
new development of cookie-cutter white Serb homes stood untouched.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the Albanians have fled either to neighboring Montenegro
or Albania and are still there in refugee camps. But, even for
those who stayed, the misery did not end with the entrance of NATO
troops.
</P>
<P>
   In the city of Djakovica, there was widespread destruction. In
the city's historic Ottoman bazaar section, block after block of
shops were burned and strewn with rubble. There was no merchandise
visible, indicating that looting preceded the arsons. A mineret at
a mosque had its top blown off.
</P>
<P>
   On the main street, residents swarmed foreign reporters to ask
for word of hundreds of relatives they say were arrested by Serbs
and still not released.
</P>
<P>
   Serbs arrested six young men from the home of electrician
Muharem Kumnova, 56. The missing include his son and son-in-law. As
the withdrawal became inevitable last week, they returned to take
his property.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not asking about my car or my furniture. I don't give a
damn about that,'' he said. ``I just worry about my son and my
people.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
