<SLUG> BC-UTILITY-DEALS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LATEST DEALS CONSOLIDATE N.E.'S UTILITY SCENE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER J. HOWE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The consolidation of New England's power industry accelerated
Tuesday, with announcements that a New York utility is buying
Central Maine Power for $1.2 billion and Northeast Utilities is
merging with Connecticut's largest gas distributor.
</P>
<P>
   The moves raise new questions about how Boston Edison's parent
company can reach its stated goal of adding another 700,000
customers by the end of next year to reach the size it thinks it
needs to stay efficient and independent.
</P>
<P>
   Assuming Tuesday's deals and several other pending utility
mergers are approved by regulators, Edison's parent, BEC Energy, is
looking at a very short list of New England utilities smaller than
itself to buy or merge with _ and it might increasingly look like a
prime takeover candidate, industry analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't view these announcements as anything close to the end
of the transaction chain,'' said John Reed, president of the Reed
Consulting Group, who has advised Edison and several other
utilities on power plant sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody that is left is a target,'' said industry analyst
Ethan L. Cohen of the Yankee Group, and Edison itself increasingly
looks like ``an ideal acquisition target.''
</P>
<P>
   In the larger of Tuesday's deals, Energy East Corp., which has 1
million gas and electric customers in upstate New York, said it
will buy Central Maine for $957 million in cash, plus another $271
million in assumed debt and preferred stock.
</P>
<P>
   The $29.50 offered for each CMP share outstanding is a 43
percent premium over CMP's Monday closing price. Energy East's
moves follows its April merger with Connecticut Energy Corp., which
has 160,000 gas customers.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, Northeast Utilities, which has 2.3 million electric
customers in Connecticut, Massachusetts, and New Hampshire, said it
will merge with Yankee Energy System Inc. in a deal worth $679
million. Yankee, spun off from NU in 1989, has 183,000 customers in
68 cities and towns.
</P>
<P>
   Yankee shareholders will get $45 a share, paid 45 percent in NU
stock and 55 percent in cash, with individual shareholders able to
ask for more or less cash or stock subject to proration.
</P>
<P>
   In trading Tuesday, Central Maine stock soared 5 11/16 to close
at 25 3/4, and Yankee stock jumped 7 7/16 to 39 15/16. Energy East
rose 1/16 to 26 5/16. Northeast slipped 1/16 to 17 1/4, and BEC was
up 1/2 to 42 7/8. All five trade on the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   The moves fuel what has been a frenzied rush among utilities to
combine into ever-larger units as state-level deregulation pushes
them to sell off power plants and grow into larger distribution
companies.
</P>
<P>
   BEC Energy chairman Thomas J. May has set a goal of growing to 2
million customers by the end of next year. May has said that in the
new world of power distribution, ``bigger is better'' to achieve
BEC's goal of becoming a premier New England ``wires and pipes''
company also involved in telecommunications through a venture with
RCN Corp. Edison had no comment on Tuesday's deals.
</P>
<P>
   Edison shareholders later this month are expected to consummate
a $4 billion-plus merger with Commonwealth Energy System, which has
600,000 gas and electric customers in Cambridge, New Bedford, Cape
Cod and elsewhere. That would bring the combined company to 1.3
million customers and get Edison into gas distribution for the
first time.
</P>
<P>
   One senior advisor to a Massachusetts generating company said
the Central Maine and Yankee deals complicate May's plans to grow
his firm to the 2 million customer mark.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got to eat or be eaten, and arguably he has to go outside
the region to do acquisitions or he gets eaten here,'' said the
advisor, who asked not to be named.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's moves further shrink the list of companies smaller
than the Edison-ComEnergy combination that might be acquisition or
merger candidates, including United Illuminating in Connecticut,
Fitchburg Gas and Electric, and Bangor Hydro-Electric in Maine.
</P>
<P>
   One plausible partner might be Eastern Enterprises, parent of
Boston Gas, which last fall announced deals to buy Colonial Gas and
Essex Gas for $600 million to grow to 725,000 customers. Such a
combination, though, could raise antitrust concerns among
Massachusetts regulators.
</P>
<P>
   Geographically, Edison would fit well with New England Electric
System, which has 1.3 million customers in Central Massachusetts,
New Hampshire, and Rhode Island. New England Electric is in the
process of taking over the parent company of Eastern Edison and
Nantucket and Rhode Island utilities and in turn becoming a
subsidiary of British energy giant National Grid Group plc.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts speculate that the rush to consolidate could soon
include takeovers of some municipal electric departments in
Massachusetts. Vermont utilities, such as Central Vermont Power and
Green Mountain Power, are seen as less attractive takeover
candidates because of delays in the state working out industry
restructuring and deregulation issues.
</P>
<P>
   Reed, who advised Edison on its sale of the Pilgrim nuclear
plant and units in Everett, Mass. and South Boston, said, ``BEC is
going to be looking at every other property in the region, and I'm
sure others are looking at them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
