<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAYTHEON-RADAR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAYTHEON TEAM WINS $1.3 BILLION BRITISH RADAR CONTRACT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A team led by Raytheon Co. received a $1.3 billion order to
build a British military radar system, a boost for the Lexington
defense contractor as it consolidates recent acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of the 10-year agreement announced by the United
Kingdom Ministry of Defense Tuesday, the Raytheon team will build
and maintain a system known as the Airborne Standoff Radar, or
ASTOR, for joint use by the country's army and air forces starting
in 2003.
</P>
<P>
   Raytheon beat out teams led by Lockheed Martin Corp. and
Northrop Grumman Corp. Peter McKee, managing director of Raytheon's
London-based subsidiary, said it expects to add about 2,500 jobs
connected to the program, mainly in Northern Ireland, Scotland, and
Wales where trade union members lobbied heavily for the work.
</P>
<P>
   ASTOR uses sensors carried as high as 50,000 feet on modified
commercial jets, providing military officers with images of ground
activities over hundreds of kilometers. ASTOR is built around radar
technologies Raytheon acquired from General Motors' Hughes Aircraft
unit in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts had expected Raytheon to win the award after
unconfirmed reports appeared in British newspapers. Still, the
company's widely traded class B shares rose 2 1/16 to close at 74
1/16 in New York Stock exchange trading after Tuesday's formal
announcement. Class A shares added 1 13/16 to 72 1/16.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good win for them, and certainly it could be the
predecessor of other similar programs,'' said analyst Paul Nisbet
of JSA Research Inc. in Rhode Island. Said William Fiala, analyst
at the Edward Jones brokerage in St. Louis, ``You need these kinds
of awards to justify the high price they paid for Hughes, and it
gives them some encouragement the integration is working.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts also said the order could help Raytheon win an order
for a similar system expected to be made by the North Atlantic
Treaty Organization in coming years. The NATO order, it is
estimated, might be worth around $2 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The US military deploys similar radar systems aboard U-2 spy
planes and on rebuilt 707s known as the Joint Surveillance and
Target System, or JSTARS. But US versions are less integrated.
</P>
<P>
   The contract, the biggest assigned to date by Britain's Labor
government, will team Raytheon with General Electric Co., Motorola
Inc. and Marshall SV, in addition to Montreal-based Bombardier.
Raytheon competes with Bombardier to sell business jets but doesn't
make versions as large; Bombardier will supply five of the jets,
costing about $30 million apiece.
</P>
<P>
   Raytheon employs about 2,300 in the United Kingdom. The company
said it could add as many as 4,000 new jobs from potential sales to
other NATO countries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
