</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AKAMAI-WEB-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEB SITES LOOK TO BAY STATE FIRM FOR MORE SPEED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Massachusetts firm has signed deals to soup up the performance
of 20 major World Wide Web sites, including Time Warner Inc.'s
Cable News Network and the Walt Disney Co.'s Go Network.
</P>
<P>
   Akamai Technologies Inc., of Cambridge, uses software developed
by MIT mathematician Frank Leighton, as well as a worldwide network
of server computers, to speed up the distribution of pictures,
advertisements, audio, and video clips over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are delivering their content faster and more reliably over
the Internet than they were able to do before,'' said Akamai chief
executive George Conrades, former chief of Internet pioneer BBN
Corp. of Cambridge.
</P>
<P>
   Monty Mullig, vice president of CNN Internet Technologies, says
his firm hopes to gain a 20 percent improvement in site performance
by using the Akamai system, known as FreeFlow. ``It's cheaper and
faster than the way we currently serve up images,'' Mullig said.
</P>
<P>
   Other firms that announced deals with Akamai include The New
York Times Web site, the Motley Fool financial information service,
the SportsLine USA sports site, and Internet portals Infoseek,
About.com, and Looksmart. Akamai earlier this month announced a
similar deal with Yahoo Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Akamai charges companies by the amount of data transmitted
through the FreeFlow network. The company would not give revenue
projections, but said each client would be paying thousands of
dollars per month for the service.
</P>
<P>
   The Akamai system is a variation on the idea of Internet
caching, a system in which information from a Web site is copied
onto a network of servers scattered throughout the Internet. When
somebody requests information from the Web site, that request is
routed to the nearest cache server, rather than the Web site
itself. As a result, the user gets a faster response.
</P>
<P>
   But caching is difficult when the information stored at the main
Web site changes frequently. A site such as CNN may put up new
pictures several times an hour, so that the cached versions of the
site quickly become obsolete.
</P>
<P>
   Akamai claims to have solved this problem. The company operates
about 600 servers, connected to 20 major Internet service
providers. These servers can transmit a total of 11 billion bits of
data per second. In addition, Akamai's MIT-developed software
attaches a digital fingerprint to the cached information. In this
way, each server can constantly check to make sure it has the most
current version of all the data.
</P>
<P>
   Conrades said the Akamai service will enable major Web sites to
``richen up'' their content by adding more pictures, video, and
sound files to Web pages. Web sites currently keep such materials
to a minimum because they slow down site performance, but Conrades
said Akamai will reduce this problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``What they're doing is very cool, no doubt about that,'' said
Peter Christy, principal analyst for Collaborative Research, a
network research firm in Los Altos, Calif. Christy said privately
held Akamai has good prospects, because Web-site operators are
scrambling to meet their users' demands for richer content and
faster performance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
