<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-15 19:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6466 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEDICARE-DRUGS-2TAKES     06-15 1066
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDICARE-DRUGS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LINES ARE DRAWN IN MEDICARE DRUG PRICING BATTLE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Minn., Maine, Fla., Texas, Va., Ore., La.)  (nk) 
 By ROBIN TONER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sen. Paul Wellstone, D-Minn., talks about elderly
Minnesotans forced to travel across the border to Canada to buy
affordable prescription drugs. Rep. Tom Allen, D-Maine, talks about
an elderly woman who stopped taking her medications because her
husband was sicker than she was, and they could not afford
prescriptions for two.
</P>
<P>
   House Democratic leaders sent their members home for the last
recess with an informational packet organized around a simple
message: ``Prescription Drug Prices Are Out of Control.'' White
House officials are racing to finish their Medicare restructuring
proposal, which includes a major new drug benefit for older
Americans. And the pharmaceutical industry, dismayed at the
possibility of becoming a prime whipping boy for the 2000
elections, is warning of dire consequences in research and
innovation if government bureaucrats get involved in drug pricing.
</P>
<P>
   In short, what may be one of the last great health care
struggles of the Clinton administration has begun on Capitol Hill.
And the politics around it are so ferocious, so inextricably linked
to the battle over control of the House and the White House, and so
reminiscent of health care battles past, that no one is quite sure
whether the result will be a policy or a campaign issue.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans contend that what the Democrats really want is the
latter. ``They've already printed the bumper stickers on this,''
said Rep. Thomas M. Davis III of Virginia, chairman of the National
Republican Congressional Committee. ``What we want to do is get the
problem fixed.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Martin Frost of Texas, chairman of the House Democratic
Caucus, countered, ``They may want to spin this as a diabolical
plot, but that's just not correct. This is an issue that seniors
care deeply about, and we have something to say about it and the
Republicans have nothing to say about it.''
</P>
<P>
   There is little debate over the substance of the drug issue:
that more than a third of Medicare beneficiaries lack coverage for
outpatient prescription drugs, that their numbers will probably
grow as private sources of coverage get more expensive and harder
to keep, and that this coverage gap becomes more of a hardship as
drugs grow more expensive and more important in treating the ills
of old age.
</P>
<P>
   But as is so often the case in health care policy, consensus
breaks down on how to solve the problem _ particularly over how to
pay for it within a system that already faces difficulties in
paying for existing benefits over the long term.
</P>
<P>
   While there were efforts in the past to address this need _ a
new drug benefit was part of the Clinton health care plan of
1993-94 _ many Democrats say they have been stunned at the power of
the issue in recent months. Unlike so much of Medicare policy,
which revolves around complicated discussions of reimbursement
rates and managed competition, prescription drug coverage is ``a
very digestible concept,'' as one White House adviser put it.
</P>
<P>
   And Democrats have done their part to stoke interest in it. Over
the last year, Democratic staff members on the House Government
Reform Committee have conducted surveys in 55 congressional
districts, comparing the prices for drugs paid by favored customers
like the Veterans Administration, which the committee staff asserts
is close to what big health maintenance organizations pay, with the
prices paid by the elderly without drug coverage, who are buying
retail.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats assert that these studies show rampant ``price
discrimination'' against the elderly, that millions of older
Americans not only have to pay for their own prescriptions but are
also charged top dollar, compared with the industry's ``preferred''
buyers, who negotiate better prices. The pharmaceutical industry
contends these studies have serious methodological flaws. But in
district after district, Democratic lawmakers have announced their
findings to local newspaper headlines like ``Gouging Granny'' and
``Study: The Elderly Get Taken on Drugs.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was absolutely amazed,'' said Rep. Karen Thurman, D-Fla.,
who announced results of a study in her district earlier this
month. ``I'd be at the Wal-Mart or whatever and people would come
up and say, `Thank you. This has needed to be addressed for so
long.' ''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, so potent is the prescription drug issue that it has
suddenly become the tail wagging the dog of a broader Medicare
overhaul, needed to shore up the program for the retirement of the
baby boomers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody thinks Medicare is in trouble,'' said Celinda Lake,
a Democratic pollster. ``Everybody opposes almost all the reforms.
And everybody's top idea for reform is prescription drug coverage,
which they acknowledge is an expansion of benefits.''
</P>
<P>
   Political analysts say this is not surprising. Robert Blendon,
an expert on public opinion and health at Harvard, said surveys had
shown that over-60 voters, who are the people most likely to vote
on the basis of Medicare issues, are decidedly ``risk averse.'' As
a result, they are likely to be leery of the kind of sweeping,
market-oriented restructuring that was proposed by Sen. John
Breaux, D-La.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, there is some nervousness among Democrats about
Clinton's decision to produce a detailed Medicare plan, which is
expected to be unveiled later this month, after he returns from
Europe. He pushed ahead with a proposal after assailing the plan
produced by Breaux, who headed a bipartisan Medicare commission
that ended in a deadlock over whether to approve a final report.
</P>
<P>
   Aides and allies say it is very much in keeping with this
president to want to produce an alternative of his own.
</P>
<P>
   But as Democrats learned to their horror in 1993-94, the details
of health care proposals can be deadly. In fact, even the details
of a popular drug benefit can be problematic. For example, health
care veterans say, how much will the premium be? Administration
aides say one obvious goal is keeping it below the $70 to $90 a
month a drug benefit would cost in a Medigap policy, while making
the benefit more generous. Since the benefit is expected to be
optional, it needs to be an attractive deal, analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   How high will the deductible be or will there even be one? Both
Congress and the White House remember the political disaster of the
quickly repealed, 1988 law on catastrophic health care, which would
have provided prescription drug coverage for Medicare beneficiaries
but with high deductibles that some older Americans felt they would
never meet.
</P>
<P>
   How high will the co-payment be? Which drugs will be covered?
And, of course, how exactly will the benefit be financed?
</P>
<P>
   Bill McInturff, the Republican pollster who worked for the
health insurance industry in the 1993-94 struggle, and has also
polled for the pharmaceuticals industry, argues that three iron
laws of health care politics apply.
</P>
<P>
   ``The unacceptable options are that you cannot ask people to
reduce their own quality of care so more people have care; you
cannot displace them from private coverage to enter a government
program; and you cannot ask them to voluntarily go into a
government program if it's less generous than the private coverage
they already have,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   This struggle, in short, is filled with political pitfalls.
Moreover, the pharmaceutical industry is widely considered to be
one of the most powerful and effective lobbyists around.
</P>
<P>
   They came under fire in the 1993-94 health care struggle, when
both the president and Hillary Rodham Clinton assailed them for
their prices _ and more importantly, proposed a variety of measures
in their ill-fated health plan to hold those prices down. Since
then, the industry has engaged in a significant advertising
campaign to burnish their image, and it has produced results, many
analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   One recent television commercial, for example, featured a drug
company researcher talking about the ``heartbreaking'' damage
children suffer from ear infections, using his son as an example.
``My pharmaceutical company has been working on a new vaccine that
will prevent ear infections in children,'' the researcher says.
``It would be really nice if children didn't have to go through
what my son went through.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Alixe Glen Mattingly, senior vice president for public affairs
at the Pharmaceutical Research and Manufacturers of America,
declared this week, ``The pharmaceutical industry is very committed
to policies and laws that will ensure not only seniors but
everyone's access to affordable medicines. But a big government
solution will inevitably lead to price controls which will
inevitably lead to a decrease in industry's research into
tomorrow's cures.''
</P>
<P>
   The pharmaceutical organization issued a statement earlier this
year embracing the concept of expanding prescription drug coverage
for Medicare beneficiaries _ provided it comes through private
health plans that ``rely on market competition, not government
regulation or price controls, to improve quality, integrate care
and manage costs.''
</P>
<P>
   The group has withheld judgment on the final version of Clinton
plan, but is raising alarms about several bills that have already
been introduced, either creating a new drug benefit for Medicare or
trying to regulate prices for its beneficiaries. Among the latter
is Allen's bill, ``The Prescription Drug Fairness for Seniors
Act,'' which would allow pharmacists to purchase prescription drugs
for older Americans at the same low prices available to favored
customers, like HMO's.
</P>
<P>
   Industry spokesmen assert the Allen bill would place 40 percent
of the market under price controls and thus ``discourage investment
in developing tomorrow's cures.''
</P>
<P>
   Sens. Olympia Snowe, R-Maine, and Ron Wyden, D-Ore., presented a
proposal Tuesday that would use an increase in the tobacco tax to
subsidize prescription drug benefits for older Americans, depending
on their incomes. Medicare beneficiaries would be able to choose
from a variety of competing, private plans, monitored by a federal
board.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for the pharmaceutical research group described
that plan as ``a helpful contribution'' because it was
``market-based,'' but stopped short of an endorsement.
</P>
<P>
   The fear of government intervention in a private health care
marketplace was a powerful factor in the defeat of the Clintons'
health care plan five years ago, when the insurance industry ran
the commercials starring ``Harry and Louise,'' a couple fretting
over the government restructuring their health care.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the Pharmaceutical Research and Manufacturers of
America planned a public opinion campaign to counter the current
legislative efforts, Ms. Mattingly replied, ``No decisions have
been made, but we are considering increasing our communication to
the general public about the stark crossroads that Congress is at,
on this issue of a drug benefit.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
