<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-15 19:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6473 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-PHYSICIANS-BOS     06-15 0623
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-PHYSICIANS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEDICAL GROUP ALLEGES SERB ABUSES IN KOSOVO CAMPAIGN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAMES BANDLER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Serbian forces engaged in a systematic campaign of
violence and destruction in their drive to expel Kosovar Albanians
from the province, Physicians for Human Rights said in a report
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Boston group said interviews with 1,180 refugees showed that
one in every three households reported some sort of human rights
abuse, including killing, beatings, torture, and shootings. The
survey also contradicts claims by the Yugoslav government that
refugees fled because of NATO bombings.
</P>
<P>
   The survey is said to be the first comprehensive population
study of Kosovar Albanian refugees.
</P>
<P>
   ``The level of violence against the Kosovar Albanians was really
quite extraordinary,'' said Leonard Rubenstein, the executive
director of Physicians for Human Rights. ``This helps us understand
more what the Serb campaign has been about. It wasn't simply to get
people out of Kosovo. It was a campaign of destruction.''
</P>
<P>
   The report is based entirely on interviews with randomly sampled
refugees in camps in Macedonia and Albania.
</P>
<P>
   Until this week's agreement between NATO and Belgrade, no
independent observers had been allowed in Kosovo in recent weeks.
The sample cannot be generalized to apply to all Kosovar Albanian
refugees as it did not involve those who left the camps for
resettlement elsewhere or refugees who arrived in camps after May
3.
</P>
<P>
   Physicians for Human Rights was one of the first rights groups
to call for ground troops to allow for the repatriation of Kosovar
Albanians. The group has also demanded the indictment of Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosovic for war crimes.
</P>
<P>
   The 148-page report was designed to assess the extent and
pervasiveness of abuse suffered by the refugee population from
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Respondents reported human rights abuses in 23 of the 29
districts in the Connecticut-size province, with the greatest
number of abuses in densely populated areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``It shows how systematic and widespread these abuses are,''
said Dr. Vincent Iacopino, who supervised the project.
</P>
<P>
   But the report also suggested that the experiences of Kosovo
Albanian refugees were sharply different from those of Tutsis in
Rwanda who were subjected to a massive genocidal campaign of rape
and murder.
</P>
<P>
   Respondents reported a total of 59 killings out of 11,458
household members. The report documented only 44 cases of torture
and four cases of sexual assault by Serb forces.
</P>
<P>
   Iacopino said that while the numbers might seem low, they
reflected the brief exposure refugees had to Serb troops.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are serious abuses that happened in a very short period
of time,'' said Iacopino. ``It represents an example of the speed
and brutality with which Kosovar refugees were displaced and
abused.
</P>
<P>
   More than 90 percent of the refugees reported that their chief
reason for leaving Kosovo was direct or indirect expulsion by
Serbian forces. None stated they had left their homes because of
NATO bombing. The majority of the abuses were committed in March
and April of 1999, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
   The survey also found:
</P>
<P>
   --The homes of nearly a third of respondents were burned by Serb
forces.
</P>
<P>
   --Twenty-three percent of respondents witnessed the destruction
of medical facilities.
</P>
<P>
   --Serb soldiers demanded money from half of all respondents.
</P>
<P>
   The Physicians for Human Rights survey was conducted in
conjunction with the Program on Forced Migration and Health, and
the Center for Population and Family Health of the Joseph L.
Mailman School of Public Health at Columbia University.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
