<HEADER>
A6474 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SAHARA-COLONIALIZE-AR     06-15 0899
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAHARA-COLONIALIZE-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROSPECTS SHAKY FOR REFERENDUM ON DISPUTED WESTERN SAHARA 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By JOHN F. BURNS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BIR-LAHLOU, Western Sahara _ The sun beats down ever more
harshly as summer approaches, raising noontime temperatures above
130 degrees. The desert is silent, the only movement tumbleweed
blown by oven-hot gusts.
</P>
<P>
   Inside a cluster of mud-hut billets, fighters grown wizened
through long years of war, and now by an endless truce, drift down
a cycle of empty days. Weapons are dismantled, cleaned and cleaned
again. Sand is swept from doorways and floors, then swept some
more. Mangy dogs scrounge for scraps, then slope outside to bark in
the blinding sun.
</P>
<P>
   Bir-Lahlou _ ``a place of sweet water'' in Arabic _ lies deep
inland from the Atlantic rim of North Africa, in a region where the
Sahara's coastal dunes turn to flat, rocky, inhospitable terrain.
</P>
<P>
   Once an oasis for camel trains, the whitewashed billets are now
an outpost of the Polisario Front, a guerrilla force that has spent
most of the last decade idled in the desert, waiting out a
cease-fire that ended 16 years of war with Morocco.
</P>
<P>
   The disputed territory, with a population of perhaps 300,000,
including 180,000 who live as refugees in Algeria, has drawn notice
mainly as the last of dozens of former European colonies in Africa
still classified by the United Nations as awaiting
``decolonization.''
</P>
<P>
   Preparations are under way for a long-postponed referendum in
March. But with competing claims of heritage so entrenched, U.N.
officials are skeptical about its chances.
</P>
<P>
   ``This may seem like the end of the earth to you, but it is not
for us,'' said Ibrahim Salam Bouseif, 42, a Polisario official who
was born in a desert tent and became the first in his nomad family
to go to school. ``The desert for us is home. In the desert we are
free; there are no restrictions. We can see forever. We can cast
our eyes to the horizon, and all we see is sand and sky. In the
desert our spirits can fly.''
</P>
<P>
   The rebels' cause dates from 1975, when Spain, after 130 years
of colonial rule, abandoned Western Sahara to Morocco and
Mauritania, countries that flank the territory to the north and
south. Mauritania withdrew in 1978, but Morocco's forces and
Polisario, which seeks independence, fought on until a cease-fire
in 1991 that left Morocco in control of all but a distant
hinterland bordering Algeria.
</P>
<P>
   In 1983 Polisario leaders agreed with King Hassan II of Morocco
to settle the dispute with a referendum among the territory's
original inhabitants, the Saharawis, a people of Arab and Berber
descent who lived as nomads for a thousand years.
</P>
<P>
   The choice is between independence and integration into Morocco.
But a dispute over who should vote _ in effect, over over who is
and who is not a Saharawi _ has caused repeated postponements.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Morocco and the Polisario agreed to the March
deadline and to a renewed, six-month U.N. effort to complete the
list of voters.
</P>
<P>
   But Morocco's insistence that thousands of Moroccan loyalists be
added to a provisional U.N. roll of 83,000 people _ and Morocco's
threat to block the referendum again if the additional voters are
excluded _ could prolong the impasse well into the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
   The United States, which backed Morocco under Cold War policies
aimed at pushing back Marxist influences in Africa, has been active
since the Soviet Union's collapse in seeking a settlement as part
of a wider push for regional stability.
</P>
<P>
   Former U.S. Secretary of State James Baker has served since 1997
as special envoy on the territory for U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan, but U.S. diplomats familiar with Baker's views say he has
concluded privately that the world organization should consider a
new approach.
</P>
<P>
   Baker's solution, secretly broached with Morocco and the
Polisario last year, could involve Morocco's retaining sovereignty
for 25 or 30 years in return for Saharawi autonomy and a pledge to
reopen the sovereignty issue later, say diplomats familiar with the
proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Something similar has been hinted at by Algeria, where the newly
elected President, Abdelaziz Bouteflika, who was born in Morocco,
has advocated a Western Sahara settlement in which, in his words,
there would be ``neither winner nor loser.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the Polisario fighters took up arms against the Spanish
occupiers as teen-age boys in the early 1970s. Others, like Omar
Sid Ahmed Omar, 58, the garrison commander at Bir-Lahlou, were
soldiers in Spain's colonial army before defecting to the rebels.
With his wife, children and several grandchildren living in the
refugee camps in Algeria, a half-day's drive east of Bir-Lahlou, he
longs for the war to end.
</P>
<P>
   Yet neither the commander nor any of his men at Bir-Lahlou seem
ready to accept any deal with Morocco that falls short of Western
Sahara's independence.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I do not wish to grow old here sitting in the sun,'' Omar
said, over a tin of U.N.-supplied tuna shared with visitors. ``But
compromise with Morocco? Never! We will never accept the rule of
King Hassan! We will die in the desert rather than live under the
Moroccan flag.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In Morocco, attitudes seem equally hard set. The issue has
become inseparably linked with King Hassan, who made the annexation
a touchstone of his reign in the 1970s and poured huge sums _ at
least $20 billion by Moroccan officials' accounting _ into the war
and into showcase development projects that have turned Aiun, the
territorial capital, into a modern town from the shabby backwater
bequeathed by Spain.
</P>
<P>
   Since King Hassan led a march of 350,000 Moroccans into the
Western Sahara in 1975, few Moroccans have disputed his contention
that the territory, which represents more than a third of Morocco's
land area, was part of precolonial Morocco, reaching back more than
a thousand years to a time when Moorish dynasties ruled all of the
territory from Spain to Mauritania.
</P>
<P>
   The truce left a Morocco in control of a region about twice the
size of England, with a 750-mile Atlantic coastline teeming with
fish and a hinterland with rich phosphate deposits but little else
of proven economic worth. Under the cease-fire, a small U.N.
peacekeeping force separates about 80,000 Moroccan troops from
15,000 Polisario fighters and reservists.
</P>
<P>
   Publicly, King Hassan has embraced the new referendum deadline
and assigned his most powerful aide, Interior Minister Driss Basri,
to what Basri calls a ``permanent election campaign.'' At carefully
scripted public meetings, Basri has urged Moroccan loyalists to
present themselves to U.N. scrutiny as potential voters.
</P>
<P>
   He has also warned that the new voting deadline is the last that
Morocco will accept. ``In March 2000, the referendum will settle
the issue in Morocco's favor once and for all,'' he told a
gathering in Smara, a town deep in the desert interior. ``And if
the United Nations cannot hold to the date, so be it _ the Sahara
will remain Moroccan, now and forever.''
</P>
<P>
   U.N. officials familiar with the voter enumerations say
privately that they expect few of the 65,000 nominees Morocco wants
added to the provisional voters list to qualify under the tight
rules accepted by the two sides in 1983.
</P>
<P>
   In essence, the rules limit eligibility to residents of the
territory included in a 1974 Spanish census, their direct
descendants and a narrow range of others, including those missed by
the Spanish count. Morocco is insisting that the vote be extended
to thousands of people living elsewhere in Morocco who can
demonstrate Saharawi tribal links.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. officials familiar with the list of 83,000 voters already
registered say a referendum based on that list would be likely to
produce at least a narrow majority for the Polisario, which could
rely on strong support from voters in refugee camps in Algeria and
Mauritania, as well as among disaffected Saharawis in the
Moroccan-occupied parts of Western Sahara.
</P>
<P>
   If most of the new voters put forward by Morocco are rejected,
Morocco's likeliest move would be to pull out of the process again.
Basri has already signaled that Morocco will not proceed with any
referendum it is not certain of winning.
</P>
<P>
   As his plane flew over the Atlas Mountains on a recent trip to
Aiun, the interior minister said nobody should think Morocco could
countenance a referendum defeat. ``Anybody who was prepared to
consider the loss of the territory would be considered a traitor,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Polisario leaders have said they believe that no final
settlement can be reached until the death of the 69-year-old king,
who has been in declining health.
</P>
<P>
   Although Moroccan officials say nothing is amiss, Moroccans have
noted King Hassan's pallor on public occasions and the increased
prominence he has given to his heir, Crown Prince Sidi Mohammed.
The crown prince attended the funeral of King Hussein of Jordan in
his father's place earlier this year and later traveled to Paris,
again in his father's place, to attend opening ceremonies for a
Moroccan cultural festival.
</P>
<P>
   Over dinner at a Polisario guest house near Tindouf, Polisario
defense minister Mohammed Lamin Bohali said the 32-year-old crown
prince's succession could be the breakthrough the Polisario has
awaited for 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``King Hassan has been the main source of our problems,'' Bohali
said, ``and the main obstacle to resolving them. From all we hear,
Sidi Mohammed is more flexible and might want to relieve his people
of a burden they never wanted.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
