<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-15 19:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6481 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RELIGION-INTERNET-100     06-15 0922
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-INTERNET-1000(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RELIGIOUS LEADERS EXPAND THEIR MINISTRIES TO THE INTERNET
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TARA DOOLEY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ From the front bedroom of his Fort Worth
home, Brian Oakes can enter a Christian mission field.
</P>
<P>
   With the flip of a switch on his computer, Oakes can join a
gathering of about 300 Christians from a registration list of
15,000 to discuss everything from Jesus Christ to the latest trends
in Christian music to the politics of a church youth group.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't think this type of ministry is relevant,'' said
Oakes, 23, a self-described computer geek and founder of the
Christian Chat Network. ``But let's look at people's lives. What do
people do? They spend most of their time on the Internet. If the
church is not willing to embrace it, then the church is going to
get left behind.''
</P>
<P>
   Though perhaps not a place where people spend ``most of their
time,'' the Internet has affected how many people do business, and
the business of religion is increasingly no exception. More
Christians are going online, changing the ways that spiritual
communities interact and discuss matters of the soul.
</P>
<P>
   Church leaders are e-mailing congregation members, preachers are
broadcasting sermons, peddlers are selling their religious wares,
and individuals, such as those gathered by Oakes, are reaching out
to one another for solace and inspiration.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe it is as significant a new medium as the printing
press was, and we know now what the printing press did,'' said Fran
Maier, chancellor of the Catholic Archdiocese of Denver, making
reference to the Protestant Reformation that was propelled by the
printed word. ``We want to be ahead of the curve rather than behind
it the next time.''
</P>
<P>
   As Christians strive to stay ahead of the curve, however, many
religious leaders are concerned that widespread Internet use could
erode the church's calling to bring people together, physically and
spiritually.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we try to say is, `If you use the Internet, you need to
use it as a tool to move people toward embodied relationships,'''
said Robert DeVargas, an assistant professor at Southwestern
Baptist Theological Seminary in Fort Worth, who is creating an
ethics and technology course on the Internet and ministry. ``That
means first in a relationship to God, to the church, and in a
relationship with friends and family.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, there appears little danger that disembodied multitudes
will forsake the pews for their computers, according to a 10-month
survey of religion online conducted for a division of the United
Methodist Church.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there is a lack of people saying, `Oh good, I don't
have to get up and get dressed and go to church. I can log onto the
Internet and go to church,' '' said the study's author, Ken Bedell,
vice president of the Forum Foundation in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Like most Internet users, those using the technology for
religious matters log on to improve communications and find
information, according to the study, which was completed last year.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, the movement toward the Internet is part of a
progression starting with radio and television that has led
religion away from the pulpit or the camp meeting ground and into
the home. But the difference now is that the Internet also allows
for more individual autonomy and privacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not unique to the Internet but, because of the
interactive nature, it is more compelling to be disembodied,''
DeVargas said.
</P>
<P>
   The flip side is that it allows users the chance to attend an
online Bible discussion or hear a sermon that a child's soccer
practice or other commitments might have pre-empted.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can sit down at your computer once the kids are in bed and
everyone is settled down ... and listen to it while you are paying
your bills,'' said Paula Golway, marketing manager for the
Dallas-based Lightsource.com, which provides Christian programming
on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Lightsource.com, run by an advertising agency that specializes
in Christian ministries, funnels popular Christian radio programs
such as Focus on the Family onto the Internet and broadcasts
services from churches such as Preston Hollow Presbyterian Church
in Dallas onto the personal computer, making it available for
consumption at the user's discretion.
</P>
<P>
   The number of possible people accessing the programming has also
expanded. Since January 1997, Lightsource.com has had an exclusive
contract to provide Christian programming for Broadcast.com, which
was recently bought by Yahoo!. And that will provide an
evangelizing link to one of the busiest sites on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Back when Christ walked the Earth, he did it via himself and
12 disciples,'' Golway said. ``Now we have a way of expanding it
around the world in milliseconds. It's a very interesting and very
hip way of doing what people have been doing for 2000 years.''
</P>
<P>
   There is, however, the possibility that the technology will not
only enhance but alter what people have been doing for 2000 years.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the Archdiocese of Denver sponsored a four-day
seminar examining how emerging technologies will affect the ways
faith is communicated in the next millennium.
</P>
<P>
   It included computer industry professionals, theologians and
church leaders who looked at how to use technologies such as the
Internet to ``make disciples of all nations.'' But it also looked
at the social implications of the new technology, Maier said.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
