<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990615.0238 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-15 19:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6483 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RELIGION-INTERNET-2nd     06-15 0951
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-INTERNET-2ndTake-TEX </SLUG>
 
FORT WORTH, Texas: Maier said. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The technology has to do with how we deliver the message,'' he
said. ``The psychological implications have to do with who it is
that we are reaching.''
</P>
<P>
   Internet use at Calvary Lutheran Church in Richland Hills is
probably most typical of how the technology is used by churches to
reach people.
</P>
<P>
   The church's leaders use e-mail to keep in touch with
denominational leaders and congregation members and to reach
potential newcomers. The church's Web site provides basic
information through its online newsletter and listings of weekly
services and events such as The Calvary Cafe, a weekly dinner
prepared by the Rev. Phil Heinze, the church's associate pastor.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, church members and Web site visitors can e-mail
prayer requests, read devotionals and join a discussion board where
topics range from a sick child in the community to a recent sermon.
</P>
<P>
   For example, by logging onto the Web site, congregation members
can keep up with the progress of 4-year-old Mason Renner, who has
leukemia, and send prayers for the child and his family.
</P>
<P>
   Though his use of the Web site has slowed since Mason's illness,
the child's father, Dan Renner, said he had participated in an
online discussion group that tackled topics such as Thomas the
Doubter and Lazarus.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is somewhat different because people generally have to
gather their thoughts together instead of rambling on and on,''
Renner said. ``I think you get more concise thoughts.''
</P>
<P>
   The church's Web site also provides links to online resources
such as the Internet Christian Library, a selection of Bibles and
Bible tutorials, and The Desperate Preacher,' a lectionary
discussion site for preachers preparing sermons.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we have at Calvary is a Web site, and it's a reflection
of our real community at Calvary Lutheran Church,'' said Michael
Middleton, a computer professional and congregation member who
helped design the Web site. ``It's an invitation for people to join
us. It wouldn't exist if we didn't exist.''
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, Oakes' Christian Chat Network has produced
Christian relationships that exist because of the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Oakes steers clear of calling those who enter the network's chat
rooms a community, he said, because he believes that term should be
reserved for gatherings in rooms with pews.
</P>
<P>
   No matter what term he uses, Oakes has created an Internet
assembly that allows Christians to discuss religious convictions
and secular concerns while offering a way to forge friendships.
</P>
<P>
   The user can enter the network by signing on with a self-chosen
name. The user enters a ``lobby'' and can stay there and talk for a
while or head into specialty sections for teen-agers, single adults
or women, Oakes said. Some users will schedule times to meet online
and chat.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of times, it is not the most outgoing person on the
computer,'' Oakes said. ``With the anonymity, that baggage can be
taken away.''
</P>
<P>
   Oakes also rebroadcasts a Christian music radio show online and
broadcasts a call-in show that he moderates over the network.
</P>
<P>
   Kathy Lee, a divorced mother of four from Cedar Lake, Ind.,
found out about Oakes' network from a friend.
</P>
<P>
   In the confines of chat rooms protected by a filtering system
that will eject any user that contributes inappropriate material,
Lee said she has spent many evenings discussing spiritual issues
online and has made friends. She is now a monitor for two All
Singles Believers chat rooms on the network.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a lot of fun,'' she said. ``But some of it is serious.
Sometimes people come in and have a problem, and they want to talk
about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Enhancing the virtual with the real, Lee has physically met and
made friends with chat network users in Michigan and Illinois, she
said. A group of the users is planning to gather in Florida in
August.
</P>
<P>
   Bedell found that the people he surveyed believe that the
Internet will likely play an even more important role in religious
life in the future.
</P>
<P>
   But how it will change and help shape spiritual matters is
unclear, said Bedell, a sociologist and ordained United Methodist
minister.
</P>
<P>
   The potential exists for meaningful theological discussion to
take place on the Internet, he said, especially because it is a
means of communication worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   Viewing it simply as a tool for the local church may be to
underestimate its effects and potential, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a real possibility that the future of spirituality
and religion will get worked out on the Internet,'' Bedell said.
</P>
<P>
   But even enthusiasts approach that era cautiously.
</P>
<P>
   Taking into account concerns about disembodied spiritual
communities, Oakes said he personally makes sure that he doesn't
become mesmerized by his computer screen and forsake the rest of
life.
</P>
<P>
   Oakes said he spends a chunk of most weekday evenings online,
but he also has a demanding job as a protocol engineer for a
computer company, a fiance and Kruger, his attention-hungry hound.
</P>
<P>
   The Christian Chat Network operates through donations and the
fees Oakes collects for hosting Web sites, mostly for Christian
ministries and bands.
</P>
<P>
   Some months, it breaks even. Some months, Oakes uses part of his
paycheck from his regular job to pay the network's bills, which run
about $1,200 a month, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly, the network is Oakes' contribution to Christian
ministry, his way to give something back.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet is truly the last open mission field,'' Oakes
said. ``I can get past the door into the bedroom and tell people
about Christ.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
