<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-POWERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TITLE OF `AUSTIN POWERS' SEQUEL TOO MUCH FOR SOME BRITISH TASTES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROBERT L. JAMIESON JR.  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ One person's blasphemy is another's hilarity _
depending on which side of the Atlantic Ocean you are standing on.
</P>
<P>
   Exhibit No. 1: ``Austin Powers: The Spy Who Shagged Me,'' the
comedy whose makers guffawed all the way to the bank last weekend
with an opening of $54.9 million, a record for a comedy or a June
debut.
</P>
<P>
   But not everyone is laughing lightheartedly about the name of
the hit spy flick. It's stirring a mini-tempest in the British
teapot.
</P>
<P>
   You see, in England the word ``shag'' would be uncouth if
slipped from the lips of polite folks at a cocktail or dinner
party.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, (use it) only if you wanted to be thrown out on your
ear,'' says British-born author Jonathan Raban, who calls Seattle
home.
</P>
<P>
   In formal terms, ``shag'' - a Brit will point out - means to
copulate. But the word seems to have whizzed by American
moviegoers, who have chosen either to ignore the word's racier
connotations or embrace more benign meanings.
</P>
<P>
   The Dictionary of American Slang, for example, defines shag as,
among other things, ``to hurry'' (Hey, shag it, will ya?) or ``to
chase something'' (shagging baseballs).
</P>
<P>
   Raban remains astonished.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like putting on a movie, `The Spy Who (BLEEPED) Me.' It's
just as obscene as the American word (to BLEEP!).''
</P>
<P>
   He adds, ``I thought, `Boy oh boy, do they know what it means?'
''
</P>
<P>
   The British Consulate in Seattle on Monday was handling the
``Shag Rag'' with, well, diplomacy.
</P>
<P>
   `` `Oh, no, tell him we have no comment,' '' Tina Lencioni, a
consulate officer from Seattle, said her British colleagues
shrieked when a reporter raised the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are way too embarrassed to discuss that,'' she added.
``Very proper.''
</P>
<P>
   The British interpretation of ``shag'' was immortalized by Eric
Partridge, dubbed ``the greatest of all slang men.'' He researched
words from the Reading Room of London's British Museum and produced
``A Dictionary of Slang and Unconventional English'' before his
death in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   Partridge cut to the chase; he defined ``shag'' as ``to coit.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the years - and across country borders - the word has taken
on myriad meanings, from describing dance crazes of the 1930s and
'40s _ performed with vigorous hopping on each foot in turn _ to
flagging down baseballs.
</P>
<P>
   Public sport, however, was likely the farthest thing from the
minds of Singapore government officials who recently pressed to
have the movie's title shagless. They later relented.
</P>
<P>
   But Raban wonders, ``Are they going to be able to play this
movie in England under that title?'' (It opens in England at the
end of July.)
</P>
<P>
   ``It is interesting that an American-distributed film can get
away with words in English which manage to sound quaint to an
American audience,'' Raban says. ``(But) to an English ear like
mine, they are still taboo.''
</P>
<P>
   New Line Cinema, the distributor of the film, says the ``topic
had been brought up'' but no decision had been made about whether
``shag'' will play in the title on British marquees.
</P>
<P>
   A company representative said the only calls about the word have
been from media. The movie, she added, ``is all about fun - and
that's the bottom line.''
</P>
<P>
   American audiences flocked to the flick to such a degree the
movie, um, shagged the No. 1 weekend spot at the box office from
George Lucas' ``The Phantom Menace.''
</P>
<P>
   Already, legions of teens and young adults _ the film's core
audience _ are laughing and repeating ``shag-a-delic phrases'' from
the adventure about a spy (played by comedian Mike Myers) seeking
to reclaim his stolen mojo (libido.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
