<DOCNO> NYT19990615.0240 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-15 19:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6487 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-FINALS-NYT &LR;      06-15 1157
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-FINALS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNLIKELY SURVIVORS PREPARE FOR NBA CHAMPIONSHIP BATTLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO, Texas _ The tumultuous parallel lives of the Knicks
and Spurs will cross on Wednesday night when the players duck out
of the tunnel at the Alamodome and appear on the court of the
National Basketball Association finals like lost twins reunited
before a live audience.
</P>
<P>
   Beneath the crush of pressure, these two teams will stand as
unlikely survivors of a season when they were casts as
disappointments at the start, when their ashen film-junkie coaches
were under fire, and when their All-Star centers were being nudged
into the background to make room for the hip and young Generation
Next.
</P>
<P>
   By way of miraculous recoveries during the cram session of the
lockout-shortened season and through star-aligned shots used as
charms during the playoffs, the Knicks and Spurs will find out
exactly whose side destiny is on as they begin their four-of-seven
series for the championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're similar in that here are two teams that have traveled on
a path people called fate,'' said the Spurs' Malik Rose after
Tuesday's practice session. ``But now, all similarities will end
with the team that wins it all.''
</P>
<P>
   It would seem the Knicks are least likely to succeed. They
wandered into the cavernous Alamodome for practice as a team held
together with rubber bands and paper clips. Patrick Ewing was in a
cast, and Larry Johnson was in pain. Ewing will watch his team try
to win a title without him from the sidelines, while Johnson will
do his best to recover from a sprained knee and give the Knicks a
much-needed body.
</P>
<P>
   They are as thin as cellophane at this point. With Johnson's
availability left as a game-time decision, the Knicks have nine
healthy bodies, including the 41-year old Herb Williams. Meanwhile,
the Spurs will flaunt a healthy glow. They are rested and ready to
unleash Tim Duncan and David Robinson, their version of the Twin
Towers. The Spurs may be a bit stale from their 10 days off, but
size does not slump.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know San Antonio is the prohibitive favorite and have been
the dominant team in the league from March 1 on,'' Coach Jeff Van
Gundy said. ``And what we want to do is try to hang around, be in
the game down the stretch and find a way to win.''
</P>
<P>
   This is how the Knicks operate. They live for the comeback and
thrive off the drama of a dire situation. They defy all logic and
savor no-win situations. And the manifestation of this attitude has
been shown in their ability to steal Game 1 on the road in each of
their three playoff series.
</P>
<P>
   Now, here they are again. If the Knicks can sneak away with Game
1, they can put the pressure on the favored Spurs, leave them a
little tighter and a lot less confident. Although they won 10 out
of their 11 playoff games, the Spurs were vulnerable at home. They
lost Game 2 to the Timberwolves in the first round, received the
benefit of Kobe Bryant's last-second mistakes to squeeze past the
Lakers on their floor in Game 2 of the second round, and were saved
in the third round against Portland as Sean Elliott won Game 2 by
sending a thrilling 3-pointer into the dome sky off his tip-toes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't play as poorly at home as we did in the first three
rounds,'' Spurs point guard Avery Johnson said. ``We can't do it
against the Knicks and get away with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither the Heat, Hawks nor the Pacers got away with it. To put
themselves in a position to shake the Spurs, the Knicks have to
pull out all of the elements they used to overwhelm the Indiana
Pacers without Johnson for the last 30 minutes of their
series-clinching victory last Friday. That means the pressure is on
the Knick guards. Allan Houston has to fight his laid-back habit of
waiting for the game to come to him, and must drive into the teeth
of the Twin Towers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They try to turn teams into jump-shooting teams,'' Van Gundy
said. ``That's why they lead the league in defense. We were second.
Usually, that's a strength that we have over other teams. We can't
just be a jump-shooting team. We have to drive and get to the
free-throw line.''
</P>
<P>
   And the Knicks need to be undaunted by the shot-blocking tandem
of Duncan and Robinson. Another way to dilute their presence is to
attack before they set up in the paint.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to have to run,'' said Latrell Sprewell, who feeds
off the fast break. ``If we're running and getting out in
transition, that means we're getting stops. When that happens, we
can play with anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   That's confidence. Sprewell was oozing it today. When someone
told him that his counterpart, the Spurs' Sean Elliott, was noting
how Sprewell always drives to his right, he responded with a smirk.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's no secret,'' he said. `'Just because he knows it,
doesn't mean he's going to stop me.''
</P>
<P>
   To open up the floor for Sprewell, the Knicks have to rebound.
This is Marcus Camby territory. But for the lanky player who has
had the tethers on his talent removed by Van Gundy and has
blossomed into a playoff star, finding a shaft of light to dash
through between Duncan and Robinson won't be as easy as it was
against Indiana. Out of nowhere, Camby sliced through the lane for
tip-ins off missed layups and swiped defensive rebounds around the
pedestrian Pacers. The Spurs watched and took note.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been unbelievable,'' Robinson said. ``Camby has really
become another player. It's like in our last series with Portland.
Brian Grant was playing awesome. We were watching TV thinking,
`Man, how are we going to stop this guy?' He's pure energy, and
that's what Camby is going to be. We're going to have to get a body
on him.''
</P>
<P>
   And just who puts a body on Robinson and Duncan? Chris Dudley is
the likeliest candidate for the Knicks, while Camby and Kurt Thomas
will alternate coverage on Duncan. The Knicks have to guard
Robinson and Duncan aggressively, but with care. Any foul trouble
could doom the chances of a team so thin on resources.
</P>
<P>
   But then, the Knicks have embraced certain doom before and
turned it into motivating force. As have the Spurs. There was a
time when San Antonio was 6-8, when its coach, Gregg Popovich, was
feeling pressure to move aside, when Robinson was being asked to
submerge his ego and relinquish the go-to role to the young Duncan
and when Mario Elie challenged his team to strip off its soft label
and irritated a few teammates.
</P>
<P>
   They got it together, though. It took longer for the Knicks, who
had to endure turmoil through 42 games of the season before their
enchanted ride to the finals took flight, before the divisions
healed and the winning began.
</P>
<P>
   ``So far, with what they've been through to get here, they're a
team of destiny,'' said Avery Johnson. ``I mean, Indiana was at
full strength and the Knicks kept losing players. So obviously,
they've had something on their side.''
</P>
<P>
   So far.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
