<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-15 19:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6488 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WEB-MD-COX     06-15 0784
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEB-MD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Confusion arises over WebMD president's resignationBy Michael E.
Kanell
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Like a long goodbye, the pending departure of Jay
Gilbertson from WebMD has been awkward for both parties.
</P>
<P>
   The company said Monday he resigned after seven months as
president and chief operating officer, only to shift into
no-comment mode Tuesday after Gilbertson denied having left.
</P>
<P>
   But Gilbertson did not vow to stay on, an apparent sign that
only the terms of the separation need hashing out.
</P>
<P>
   For a company that has enjoyed a stunningly rapid rise,
climaxing with April's announcement of a multi-billion-dollar
merger with Santa Clara, Calif.-based Healtheon, other executives
can certainly be found to fill the gap. But the anticipated exit is
still a striking loss: When he goes, WebMD will lose the executive
whose influence in the company's evolution is probably second only
to founder Jeff Arnold.
</P>
<P>
   Gilbertson, formerly co-president and chief financial officer of
HBO &AMP; Co., brought to the nascent Internet health information
company the luster of experience in helping to run a $1
billion-a-year corporation accustomed to wooing Wall Street.
Analysts greeted his arrival at WebMD as proof that the ambitious
Internet plans of the 20-something Arnold were for real.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Gilbertson, 39, did not come from just any huge
outfit. He was integral to HBO &AMP; Co., which made a critical $10
million investment in WebMD in August as the company was launched.
He left HBO &AMP; Co. after the company agreed to be purchased by
McKesson Corp. _ much as he is expected to leave WebMD before its
pending merger is complete.
</P>
<P>
   And _ as before _ the explanation for Gilbertson's exit could be
as simple as corporate-style musical chairs. A merger combines two
executive teams, but there is only one set of seats. In fact, when
the deal with Healtheon was announced, a number of slots were
reserved _ but not for Gilbertson. At the time, Arnold said
Gilbertson would stay ``in an operational role.''
</P>
<P>
   But then came Monday's announcement that Gilbertson had resigned
_ and his assertion that he had not. A day later, spokesman Walter
Montgomery declined to confirm the previous day's statement and
declined all comment.
</P>
<P>
   Reached at home Tuesday, Gilbertson said he would not provide
details until the company is ready to offer a formal statement.
``Given the fact that we are in the midst of a merger, I'd rather
not comment on it. All I can tell you is that I still work there.''
</P>
<P>
   Speculation about Gilbertson has also been pegged to the
investigation of McKesson HBOC for accounting problems that
occurred when he had been CFO of HBO &AMP;Co. Gilbertson vehemently
denied a connection.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, they may have seen him as damaged goods,'' said William
Michalak, analyst at Wachovia Securities. ``But when you put two
companies together, there's not always room at the top _ especially
with the plethora of management talent in the two companies.''
</P>
<P>
   Either way, Gilbertson leaves a company that is vastly different
from the one he joined. Healtheon stock was worth about $5.4
billion at the close of trading Tuesday, and the merger deal values
WebMD at an equal worth. Together, their stock value surpasses all
but a handful of Georgia companies.
</P>
<P>
   That value hinges on expectations that the combined company will
dominate the Internet's potentially lucrative health care sector.
WebMD has not started reporting quarterly results, but there is no
indication that the company is profitable.
</P>
<P>
   And the Net's health care sector grows more crowded by the day.
Companies like Atlanta-based Medcast, IDX Corp. and Eclipsys aim at
various health care providers. Sites like Dr. Koop, Intellihealth
and Atlanta-based Adam.com target consumers. On Monday,
AmericasDoctor.com filed for a public offering that could raise $60
million.
</P>
<P>
   The market is potentially huge _ but only a handful of companies
will dominate, said analyst David Restropo of Jupiter
Communications. ``Consumers are driving this, and WebMD is going to
have to snap up some consumer content companies and even some
consumer commerce companies.''
</P>
<P>
   Healtheon and WebMD are planning to file details of their merger
agreement with the Securities and Exchange Commission, perhaps
within a few days. Until the deal is complete in September,
Healtheon will decline comment on management decisions of WebMD,
said spokeswoman Laura Nicholson. ``They are still two separate
companies.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael E. Kanell writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
