<DOCNO> NYT19990615.0244 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-15 19:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6494 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-SERBS-0616-COX     06-15 0985
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-SERBS-0616-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SERB WITHDRAWAL LEAVES DESTRUCTIVE WAKE THROUGHOUT KOSOVO
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    With KOSOVO-KLA; KOSOVO-PEC.
 &HT;    By MARCIA KUNSTEL 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia _ For Kosovar refugee Ramzi Krasnici, the
first stage of Serb troop withdrawal ended a few hours too late
Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   NATO troops may call the phased withdrawal smooth and successful
so far, but this ethnic Albanian wholesaler sees his future crushed
in the destructive wake of the Serbs' angry departure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Catastrophic,'' was the single word Krasnici, 43, found to
describe what was left at the house Yugoslavia's ethnic Serbian
military had occupied since they drove his and his brothers'
families out of the three-family building now transformed into a
junkyard of filthy, ravaged
</P>
<P>
   rooms.
</P>
<P>
   What tears his heart is that Krasnici is certain much of the
stealing and damage was done on Monday and Tuesday, as he stood
watching behind a NATO tank on the corner of his street. He
expresses no anger that NATO troops did not stop the wreckage, but
he also does not quite understand why the soldiers were so
helpless.
</P>
<P>
   He certainly is not the only Kosovar Albanian painfully aware of
the fury that attended the presence and the leavetaking of Serb
soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   Smoke spiralled into the sky as late as Tuesday afternoon,
signalling where the Serbs were leaving their eloquent calling card
of torched buildings.
</P>
<P>
   Tanks and artillery rumbled through the streets of the
provincial capital Pristina all day and into the night to conform
with the Military-Technical Agreement Yugoslavia and NATO signed
last week. It calls for a three-staged withdrawal of Serb troops,
with southern Kosovo cleared by midnight Tuesday. Full withdrawal
is due by June 20.
</P>
<P>
   So far an estimated 20,000 Yugoslav forces are moving out or
have left, leaving an equal number yet to mobilize. At the same
time, 15,000 peacekeeping troops, mostly from NATO countries, have
advanced as part of the KFOR or Kosovo Force operation. Another
10,000 are waiting to enter.
</P>
<P>
   The benumbed ethnic Albanians, who were forced to leave their
homes under the Serbs' ethnic cleansing campaign, are beginning to
return like Krasnici now that withdrawal looks like a sure thing.
And, like Krasnici, they are finding appalling destruction and a
sense of powerlessness to put their lives in any order.
</P>
<P>
   In the village of Shale about 30 miles southwest of Pristina,
59-year-old Agim Hoxha was among the thousands of people just
returning to their homes after spending as much as 10 weeks
roughing it in the nearby mountains. It was a return with mixed
emotion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our houses are burned. We are living under plastic sheets,''
he said, describing conditions much like what his family just left
in the mountains. ``Now I am afraid to go in my fields. Maybe there
are mines.''
</P>
<P>
   Others also have spoken helplessly of wanting to rebuild homes
and go back to work, but having no means to do either.
</P>
<P>
   The main reason Hoxha said he came back to the village is
because his family had nothing left to eat. The villagers had been
resourceful enough to build a water mill to grind grain for a
coarse flour, and most apparently had eaten little except that
bread.
</P>
<P>
   A look around the village confirms these people have not been
decently fed in some time. Children run around on skinny little
legs. Men have made new belt notches to hold up pants that gather
in small bunches around the waist.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday did bring the first relief shipment of food, 35 metric
tons of goods including real wheat flour, cooking oil, sugar and
yeast. It was supplied by the International Committee of the Red
Cross, the first organization to get big shipments of bulk food out
to the hungry countryside.
</P>
<P>
   The Serb legacy this village and countless others never will be
able to overcome is the deaths of so many people. Here the count is
27, including both those killed in Serb attacks on the village and
those who expired in the meagre conditions of life on the mountain.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's my duty to keep this list,'' said Mohamed Karpuzi, 39, an
elementary school teacher who can say how and when each one died.
``The people gave me this responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   The villagers wanted to be sure these people would not be
forgotten.
</P>
<P>
   So far Krasnici in Pristina has not had to deal with that kind
of contribution from the Serb forces. His family is intact, and
that ultimately must be his focus if he wants to overcome this
setback.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything, they took everything,'' he said, sweeping his hand
to encompass the downstairs warehouse once filled with goods from
coffee to motor oil, and the spacious upstairs apartments once
endowed with a wealth of appliances and furniture.
</P>
<P>
   Rooms that were not empty were trashed, littered with broken
window glass, empty bottles, busted furniture, food and even feces.
Toilets and sinks were smashed, and Krasnici found a suit jacket
with a three inch, v-shaped cut in the sleeve that clearly had been
made by someone wielding a pair of scissors.
</P>
<P>
   When he asked the NATO troops stationed on the corner to
intervene on Monday afternoon, a British major did cross over and
down the street to tell the Serb troops they were being closely
watched. But he said upon returning that KFOR has no right to
interfere with Serb positions until the deadline for their
departure.
</P>
<P>
   Both on Monday and Tuesday, Krasnici sometimes was so overcome
with the loss that he quietly cried, thinking about the work he had
done to achieve this place for his family.
</P>
<P>
   But that thought of family -- the fact that all had survived --
seemed the key to helping him endure and achieve again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will sleep here tonight,'' he said. ``I'll start cleaning it
one room at a time, from the ground floor up.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
