<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-15 19:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6496 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-TRIP-BOS &LR;      06-15 1045
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-TRIP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON BEGINS EUROPEAN TRIP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANN SCALES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ President Clinton arrives in Europe Wednesday to meet
with his counterparts in the European Union and the Group of Seven,
plus Russia, with Russia's role in Kosovo still unsettled and
Europe asserting itself in diplomacy and security on the continent.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's schedule during the weeklong visit, which includes
stops in Geneva, Paris, Bonn and Cologne, Germany, and Ljubljana,
Slovenia, will be dominated by a series of bilateral talks with
America's principal partners, who also are expected to implement an
aid pact to rebuild war-ravaged Kosovo and its neighbors in
southeastern Europe.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials are exploring the possibility of adding a
stop by the president either in Macedonia to visit Albanian
refugees or in Aviano, Italy, to salute American forces who
participated in NATO's bombing raids and humanitarian missions in
Yugoslavia. The logistics of such a trip are still being worked
out.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's visit comes at a critical juncture in US-European
relations, one in which disputes exist over various trade issues
and plenty of loose ends remain vis-a-vis Kosovo _ including
reconstruction of Kosovo, the immediate problem of refugees, as
well as longer-term questions of resettlement and reconstruction of
the Balkans region.
</P>
<P>
   Europe has said it wants to provide the overwhelming economic
and security presence in Kosovo, despite a weak economy,
particularly in Germany.
</P>
<P>
   ``The United States for several decades has long talked about
the idea that we want Europe to be more capable, we want Europe to
be more united, we want Europe to take on a larger role in the
world,'' said Richard N. Haas, vice president and director of
foreign policy studies at the Brookings Institution.
</P>
<P>
   ``As some people have pointed out, be careful what you wish for.
That may indeed be happening, and the real question is: What is
Europe prepared to do? What is on Europe's agenda in the way of
enlargement? What is on Europe's agenda in the way of a new foreign
and defense policy role? How does the United States perhaps want to
influence that?'' Haas asked, framing some of the questions likely
to greet Clinton during his visit here.
</P>
<P>
   Ann L. Phillips, an assistant professor of international
relations at American University in Washington, said: ``At this
juncture, at least for the near term, what seems to have happened,
ironically, is a kind of growing sense of European self-confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a sense that the United States is going to distance
itself from European problems anyway so that the only way they are
going to do deal with future situations like Kosovo is to do it on
their own,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, she said, Clinton will find a group of European
leaders who will not be asking, ``What can you do for us?'' but
will be seeking a more equal partnership with the United States.
``It's setting off a new trajectory,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The G-8 summit will be the first since several European nations
adopted a universal currency, the Euro, which has not performed as
well as expected and certainly has not been the challenge to the
dollar that many analysts had thought it would.
</P>
<P>
   While America's economy has been humming alone just fine,
Germany is facing high unemployment and low growth rates.
</P>
<P>
   In several major European countries, dissatisfaction exists over
US barriers on steel imports, and there is tension between the US
and the European Union over such trade issues as bananas,
genetically modified organisms and hormone-fed beef, with the
United States often complaining that Europeans are not open enough
to US goods.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign policy analysts say Russia is likely to use the
three-day G-8 meeting to press for greater economic aid. It is
unclear how much Russian President Boris Yeltsin, who is expected
in Cologne on the summit's final day on Sunday, will try to tie
economic aid from the West to resolving the stumbling blocks that
remain on the question of Russian's role in the NATO-led
peacekeeping force in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   James Goldgeier, who teaches at George Washington University and
is a visiting fellow at the Brookings Institution, said he would
not be at all surprised if Yeltsin asks his counterparts at the
summit for ``some public signal of a commitment to a greater
economic package. He often, when he gets together with his fellow
heads of states in new settings, does ask for more money, and why
should (the summit) be any different,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For the first two days of the summit, Russia will be represented
by Prime Minister Sergei Stepashin. Yeltsin will come for the final
day of talks and a private meeting Sunday with Clinton. Clinton's
National Security Adviser Samuel R. (Sandy) Berger speculated that
``a question of physical stamina'' may be why Yeltsin is not
attending the first two days.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton arrives Wednesday in Geneva, where he will pay a brief
courtesy call on President Ruth Dreifuss before delivering an
address on child labor to the International Labor Organization, the
world's leading body on promoting workers' rights and improved
labor conditions.
</P>
<P>
   He will then travel to Paris, where he will hold bilateral
sessions Thursday with French President Jacques Chirac and later
Prime Minister Lionel Jospin.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday through Sunday, he will attend the G-8 meeting, where
besides Kosovo and a ``stability pact'' for Southeastern Europe,
leaders are expected to hold forth on subjects ranging from
international financial reforms and debt relief for heavily
burdened nations to nuclear safety in the Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Clinton will take part in the US-EU summit in Bonn
with German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder, who is European Union
chairman. He later travels to Slovenia where he will meet with
Slovenia President Milan Kucan and Slovenia Prime Minister Janez
Drnovsek. Slovenia is a leading candidate for NATO, if and when
NATO goes forward with a second round of enlargement.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is being accompanied on the trip by Hillary Rodham
Clinton. His delegation includes Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright and some 65 other officials and White House staffers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
