<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-15 19:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6497 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NASDAQ-MARKETPLACE-NY     06-15 1078
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NASDAQ-MARKETPLACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKETPLACE: NASDAQ-JAPAN IS ON ITS WAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Please note that the word STAR within parentheses has been
used in the 15th and 19th grafs instead of the symbol, which is
non-transmittable to many newspaper systems.) 
(mk) 
 By EDWARD WYATT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The National Association of Securities Dealers took a
big step Tuesday toward the creation of an around-the-clock, global
stock market with the announcement that it will team up with
Softbank Corp. to develop a version of its electronic NASDAQ Stock
Market in Japan to trade U.S. and Japanese stocks.
</P>
<P>
   The new market, to be known as NASDAQ-Japan, will offer trading
of the 100 or so largest stocks from the U.S. NASDAQ market and
will recruit new Japanese companies that are seeking to raise
capital from Japanese and American investors. In addition, it will
seek to jointly list companies whose shares are now listed on the
Tokyo Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   The new market, which is expected to open in the fourth quarter
of 2000, will seek to accommodate investors' desires to trade both
while the NASDAQ market is open in the United States _ while most
of Japan is asleep _ and during the normal Japanese trading day,
which lasts until about 1 a.m. EST or 2 a.m. during daylight time.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, the two markets could together provide investors
with the ability to trade for up to 21 hours a day, closing only
for a short period either before or after the standard hours of
trading in the United States, said Frank Zarb, chairman and chief
executive of NASD, the parent of the NASDAQ market.
</P>
<P>
   Coming less than three weeks after NASDAQ said it would begin
preparing to extend its trading hours in the United States,
Tuesday's announcement demonstrates how rapidly markets around the
globe are being transformed by technology and a global economic
boom.
</P>
<P>
   ``To the extent we are successful here, it could have
implications beyond Japan,'' Zarb said in a reference to his
organization's attempts to cooperate with other financial markets
around the world.
</P>
<P>
   In a possible signal of its intentions, NASD recently registered
potential names for Internet sites that combine the NASDAQ market's
name with Hong Kong, China, Brazil, India and Germany, according to
a report Tuesday by Newsbytes, an Internet news service.
</P>
<P>
   In Japan, Masayoshi Son, the chairman and chief executive of
Softbank, heralded the new venture as nothing less than ``a
historic moment for the whole Japanese economy and society.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a great opportunity for young, entrepreneurial
companies that would like to have access to the equity markets in a
different fashion than they currently do,'' Son said.
</P>
<P>
   But he also made clear that much of the interest in Japan would
come from Japanese investors who wanted to explore what many of
them view as a potential gold mine: initial public offerings,
particularly of U.S. Internet companies.
</P>
<P>
   Relatively few Americans have wanted to invest recently in
Japanese stocks, which have been in a brutal bear market for most
of the decade. But some investment managers say the new market
could make it easier for Japanese companies to raise money from
investors, thereby stimulating the Japanese market and the economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The obvious benefit is that this will be another venue for
companies to raise money in Japan,'' said David Herro, portfolio
manager of two Oakmark International mutual funds. ``If the market
has good standards, it might give Japanese companies an incentive
to be more shareholder-oriented,'' a characteristic whose absence
has often frustrated U.S. portfolio managers who invest in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Herro said, NASDAQ's entry into the Japanese
financial markets is one more blow against the monopolistic forces
that have kept foreign competitors out of Japan for so long.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most difficult thing about doing business in Japan is the
closed nature of the economy,'' he said. ``Anything that eats away
at the strength of Japan Inc. is for the better.''
</P>
<P>
   The NASDAQ-Japan venture will initially receive an investment of
$4.9 million, half of which will come from NASD and half from
Softbank, the Japanese venture capital firm that has backed
successful Internet ventures like Yahoo, E(STAR)Trade, Ziff-Davis
and Geocities.
</P>
<P>
   But the success of the market is dependent on winning the
approval of regulators in both countries, as well as its ability to
cobble together the complex systems needed to support online
trading. The NASDAQ-Japan market will rely heavily on the Internet
to connect its American and Japanese constituents rather than on a
dedicated electronic system.
</P>
<P>
   Zarb cautioned that joint ventures are tricky by nature, and
they become more complicated when they involve partners from
different countries who speak different languages. Approvals for
the new market must be gained not only from Japanese regulators,
including the Ministry of Finance, but also from the U.S.
Securities and Exchange Commission. Both Zarb and Son acknowledged
that two sets of regulations could make the hurdles the venture
faces twice as tall.
</P>
<P>
   The NASDAQ-Softbank venture is clearly aimed at expanding the
popularity of electronic trading. With NASDAQ-Japan, NASD hopes to
establish an important beachhead in a country where electronic
trading is, so far, insignificant.
</P>
<P>
   Only 36,000 online trading accounts exist in Japan. In the
United States, where online transactions account for 16 percent of
all stock trades, Charles Schwab alone has 2.5 million active
online accounts. In Japan, however, E(STAR)Trade, the electronic
broker that is 27-percent-owned by Softbank, is planning a rapid
rollout of its services in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the NASDAQ-Japan market hopes to offer Japanese
investors the opportunity to buy and trade futures contracts,
options and index products, investment vehicles that are still
oddities in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone is enthusiastic about the planned venture. Alan
Davidson, president of Zeus Securities, a small broker-dealer based
in Jericho, N.Y., who is also a director of NASD, said the venture
raises the same problems for small firms as the recently approved
proposal to extend NASDAQ's trading hours _ that is, how to afford
to remain open all that time if customers want to trade.
</P>
<P>
   Zarb said Tuesday that NASD would work to limit the
inconveniences posed by extended trading hours on small securities
firms.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
