<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIGHTHOUSE-MOVE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Final preparations being made for lighthouse move
 &HT;    By Chris Burritt
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUXTON, N.C._As soon as Thursday, the 4,800 tons of granite and
brick, wrapped in a swirl of black and white paint, that has been
an east coast landmark for 129 years begins its slow, creaking
journey to safety from crashing Atlantic waves.
</P>
<P>
   Crowds awaiting the controversial, $11.8 million rescue of the
Cape Hatteras Lighthouse are growing daily, hoping to glimpse a
move so slow it will barely be noticeable.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not going for an over-land speed record,'' project
manager Joe Jakubik said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Now that local officials have dropped their legal fight to block
the lighthouse's move, fearing it might be damaged, many here are
hoping that bad weather does not interfere with its projected
month-long trip.
</P>
<P>
   Churning southeast of Bermuda, Tropical Storm Arlene does not
appear to be a threat. In case of a big storm, Jakubik said his
company, International Chimney Corp., and Expert House Movers, a
subcontractor, are prepared to protect the lighthouse.
</P>
<P>
   One of the biggest concerns, he said, would be waves crashing
over the sand dunes and possibly undermining the lighthouse along
its 2,900-foot trip inland to its new foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Crews are building a hard-packed gravel road on top of sand. The
first 850 feet of the road runs behind dunes, making it especially
vulnerable to overwash, Jakubik said. From that point, the road
travels southwest away from the ocean.
</P>
<P>
   In case of flooding on this windy eastern tip of North
Carolina's Outer Banks, bulldozers would push sand to reenforce the
dunes while crews would stabilize the lighthouse with timbers,
Jakubik said.
</P>
<P>
   The odds of the lighthouse falling over are slight, he said,
because of its low center of gravity. Two-thirds of its massive
weight is in the lower third of the structure.
</P>
<P>
   ``It resists overturn,'' Jakubik said.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past week, powerful hydraulic jacks have hoisted the
lighthouse 5 feet-4 inches from its sandy hole overlooking the
Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the railing you could feel a little vibration, but it was
not like an elevator,'' said Mike Booher, a photographer
documenting the move for the National Park Service. He stood on the
208-foot-tall lighthouse's balcony June 5 when its upward move
started.
</P>
<P>
   The 208-foot-tall structure is now at the same level as the
road, paving the way for the final tasks before the move starts.
</P>
<P>
   Attached to the lighthouse base are seven steel beams. They are
resting temporarily on 9,000 4-foot long timbers, stacked like
Lincoln logs.
</P>
<P>
   Attached to the bottom of the beams are 100 metal rollers. They
will travel on top of seven ``roll beams'' which are now being put
into place. Crews will lay out a mat of hardened steel on top of
the gravel over which the massive structure will roll.
</P>
<P>
   In equal bursts of power, the 100 hydraulic jacks will push the
lighthouse a foot every one or two minutes. When the structure
travels five feet, crews will reset the jacks for the next five
feet.
</P>
<P>
   The start-and-stop process makes it hard to predict when
onlookers might actually see the lighthouse move.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a very slow process,'' Jakubik said, ``and we want to
keep it that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Chris Burritt writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
