<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-BANFF-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KEYNOTE SPEAKER DISPELS MYTHS ABOUT TV AT BANFF FESTIVAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BANFF, Alberta - It is somehow appropriate that this postcard
community a mile up the Canadian Rockies would host an intellectual
exchange of ideas about television at the close of the millennium.
Like television, Banff has, as they say in the business, arresting
visuals. On closer inspection, though, it's also got enough
tourist-trap cheesiness for a lifetime of macaroni casseroles.
</P>
<P>
   Sound like something you were watching last night? Perhaps it's
why the Banff TV Festival, a sort of Cannes for the small screen,
has been going for 20 years. But neither its superficial
similarities to TV nor the absence of 24-karat Riviera excess make
Banff a tin Cannes.
</P>
<P>
   On the contrary, its Canadian provenance is its lasting and most
endearing legacy. The festival's mission is simply to celebrate
excellence in television around the world, and with Canadian
earnestness it refuses to succumb to the popular notion that
``quality'' and ``TV'' are inherently oxymoronic.
</P>
<P>
   Typical Canadian honesty means it doesn't duck the issue,
either. So Monday's keynote address kicking off BTVF '99 was the
perfect entree to a week that includes a black-tie awards ceremony,
several seminars on writing and producing, and scores of
opportunities for writers/directors/
</P>
<P>
   producers to pitch their dreams to the movers and shapers of TV
in the 22nd century.
</P>
<P>
   The keynoter was Mark Kingwell, associate professor of
philosophy at the University of Toronto and putative successor to
the ``media maven'' mantle worn for years by another Canadian,
Marshall McLuhan. Kingwell, who used to write a TV column, called
his speech ``Fear and Self-loathing in Couchland: Why There Is So
Little Intelligent Discourse About Television, and What We Can Do
About It.'' He offered eight persistent ``myths'' about television
that create a ``buffer of protective nostrums that keeps us from
penetrating to what really matters.''
</P>
<P>
   Myth No. 1: Television is a neutral medium.
</P>
<P>
   Kingwell finds it odd that, in an age when media understanding
is still ruled by the legacy of McLuhan, many in TV cling to the
impression that ``the medium itself is just an empty conduit, a
pure vessel for content.''
</P>
<P>
   He counters: ``Television is a neutral medium the way a loaded
gun could be used to hammer in nails.'' He says the media ``extend
our senses in particular ways,'' restructuring our experiences and,
ultimately, our world. ``They are never simple chutes moving data
from one place to another; they are, instead, world-creating
machines.''
</P>
<P>
   Myth No. 2: Television is controlled by individuals.
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, right. And Doogie Howser is the preferred provider in my
HMO.
</P>
<P>
   Kingwell says every field has its internal norms, the things
that determine what ``makes sense.'' In the field of TV, these
norms dictate our programming choices, ``and yet we almost never
pause to examine them, ask where they came from, or wonder what
purpose they serve.''
</P>
<P>
   He adds, ``We are all players on this field. But the rules are
set somewhere else,'' - see Madison Avenue - ``and every time we
make a play ourselves, or single out an individual and hold him or
her responsible for a good or bad play, we reinforce the invisible
power of those rules.''
</P>
<P>
   Myth 3: Television is democratic.
</P>
<P>
   Nielsen, shmielsen. Kingwell says the people fingering their
Nielsen buttons ``are no more genuinely responsible for the way
television is than the world-weary producers who go on giving it to
them.'' And the ``viewer'' is not so much an individual as ``an
undifferentiated mass or, at best, a demographic niche-market
slice.''
</P>
<P>
   Myth 4: Television is all junk.
</P>
<P>
   This is so obviously not true that it almost defies
mythification. But Kingwell says a preponderance of TV criticism
perpetuates the idea because the columns of so many critics after a
while ``begin to smack of disdain - for the medium, for the
readers, for themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Myth 5: Television is responsible for the world's evils.
</P>
<P>
   People fear complexity, Kingwell says, and they also fear
``their own complicity in events or systems that are ugly or
corrupt.'' Thus, it's always easy to embrace the suggestion that
somebody - or something - specific is responsible for the bad
things in the world. But that, he adds, is sloppy thinking.
Unfortunately, television thrives on quick judgments of this
nature, which leads to the next myth.
</P>
<P>
   Myth 6: You can talk about television on television.
</P>
<P>
   Kingwell, a frequent TV pundit who says he's slowly learning how
to say no to producers of talk shows, used to think it was possible
to do genuine media criticism within the medium he was criticizing.
</P>
<P>
   ``To have intelligent discourse about television,'' he
concludes, ``you must at some point turn the television off. You
must go somewhere else.''
</P>
<P>
   Myth 7: Intellectuals are right to disdain television.
</P>
<P>
   A popular assumption is that if Socrates were alive today he'd
be hosting a talk show on TV. Kingwell thinks not, but he does
believe Socrates would make an occasional appearance ``to ask
demanding, unsettling questions of his audience.''
</P>
<P>
   So, to all those with their noses in the air, he says: ``If it's
true that to think intelligently about television you have to turn
it off sometimes, it's also true that sometimes you have to turn it
back on - and sometimes you have to be on it. The art is in
choosing when.''
</P>
<P>
   Myth 8: Television is beyond saving.
</P>
<P>
   Kingwell is certain that individual choices do matter, ``even if
the world is larger than the sum of its individuals,'' and that
change for the better is possible. But that means ``taking more
real chances, trusting vivid imaginations, seeking the non-obvious,
the unsettling, the truly challenging.''
</P>
<P>
   His imperatives, then, for dispelling the myths and conquering
our fear and self-loathing: Go more slowly. Judge less quickly.
Reserve your blame. Challenge what seems to make sense. Question
your instincts. Never underestimate yourself (even if programmers
do). Embrace complexity. Think more.
</P>
<P>
   As McLuhan said, the medium is the message. It might as well be
a positive one.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
