<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBITUARY-POWERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
J.F. POWERS, ACCLAIMED WRITER OF SHORT STORIES, NOVELS; AT 81 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK FEENEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   J. F. Powers, a National Book Award-winning novelist and one of
the most admired American short story writers of the 1950s, died of
natural causes June 12 at his home in Collegeville, Minn. He was
81.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Powers, whose work won him the admiration of such authors as
Evelyn Waugh and V.S. Pritchett, was a key figure in the cultural
emergence of American Catholicism in the postwar years. What the
Kennedys were to national politics, Mr. Powers, Flannery O'Connor,
and Thomas Merton were to literature.
</P>
<P>
   As Waugh wrote of Mr. Powers's first short story collection,
``Prince of Darkness'' (1947), he ``is almost unique in his country
as a lay writer who is at ease in the Church; whose whole art,
moreover, is everywhere infused and directed by his Faith.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of Mr. Powers's fiction centered on the priesthood. Mixing
the sacred and the sociological, he wrote of parish priests at
their most mundane: tallying the collection plate, buying furniture
for the rectory, watching a ball game on TV. Mr. Powers portrayed
clerics as neither Bing Crosby matinee idols of sanctity nor Graham
Greene burnout cases. It was his special insight to realize that
men of the cloth are men like any other _ only sometimes more and
sometimes less so.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Powers had no rival as a chronicler of (in Waugh's memorable
description) ``the Middle West Irish priest _ chaste, philistine,
prosaic, energetic in youth, run rather to fat in age _ who
provides the strength and the limitations of the American Church.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Mr. Powers did not write exclusively of the priesthood,
he became, in a sense, a prisoner of the pre-Vatican II world he
limned. He published only two books in the 34 years since the
conclusion of the Second Vatican Council.
</P>
<P>
   James Farl Powers was born in Jacksonville, Ill., on July 8,
1917, the son of James Ansberry Powers and Zella (Routzong) Powers.
He attended night classes at Northwestern University and published
his first short story in 1942.
</P>
<P>
   After the success of ``Prince of Darkness,'' Mr. Powers moved to
Ireland in 1951. He divided his time between there and the Midwest
for the next quarter century, settling in Collegeville in 1975.
</P>
<P>
   His second collection, ``The Presence of Grace'' (1956), moved
O'Connor to write Mr. Powers that ``I admire your stories better
than any others I know of.'' ``Morte d'Urban'' won the National
Book Award in 1963. ``Look How the Fish Live'' (1975) and ``Wheat
That Springeth Green'' (1988) were, respectively, a story
collection and novel. The latter was a finalist for a National Book
Critics Circle Award and a National Book Award.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Powers, who counseled his students to forgo literature for
business, taught writing at Marquette University, Smith College,
and St. John's University in Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   He leaves four children: Katherine Anne of Cambridge, Mass., and
James, Hugh, and Jane, all of Ireland; and four grandchildren. A
daughter, Mary, died in 1992. Mr. Powers's wife, Elizabeth (Wahl),
died in 1988.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-15-99 1941EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
