<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-15 19:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6502 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BAPTIST-MAIN-COX     06-15 0672
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAPTIST-MAIN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Baptist president calls for new Christian network
 &HT;    By Gayle White
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Twenty years after engineering a rebellion that took
control of the Southern Baptist Convention, the Rev. Paige
Patterson took the platform as its president in the Georgia Dome
Tuesday and called for Southern Baptists to take their message to
the nation's cities, possibly through creation of a Southern
Baptist Superstation.
</P>
<P>
   The operation of such a station would probably fall under the
Alpharetta, Ga.-based North American Mission Board.
</P>
<P>
   Patterson, who was re-elected by acclamation Tuesday, told his
fellow Baptists gathered in Ted Turner's hometown that there are
``critical reasons'' for a major television ministry.
</P>
<P>
   While face-to-face evangelism is best, he said, ``television
reaches through brick walls, past gated compounds, and even into
closed countries.''
</P>
<P>
   With their own station, he said, Southern Baptists could control
the message ``without the compromise we often face on Christian
networks.''
</P>
<P>
   And, since ``God has given Southern Baptists the greatest
pulpiteers in Christendom,'' he said, the whole world should be
able to hear them.
</P>
<P>
   The SBC president cited the success of ``In Touch,'' the
television ministry of the Rev. Charles Stanley, pastor of First
Baptist Church of Atlanta, as example of what individual Southern
Baptist ministers have been able to do with broadcast efforts.
Stanley has become an internationally know figure through his
television preaching.
</P>
<P>
   To fund a superstation and other urban missions, Patterson told
Southern Baptists, they must more than double their annual gifts to
denominational missions, reaching a goal of $750 million annually.
</P>
<P>
   Patterson, whose conservative resurgence had as its theme the
inerrancy of the Bible, also urged his fellow Baptists on Tuesday
to stick to the Bible for preaching, counseling and doctrine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Messengers'' to this year's convention, which ends tonight,
said they appreciated the tenor of the meeting. For many years the
convention was driven by hotly contested presidential elections.
With conservatives firmly in control, both infighting and
attendance have decreased drastically.
</P>
<P>
   From a high of more than 40,000 registrations in the mid-1980s,
this year's convention had drawn only about 11,600 messengers by
late Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been to conventions for several years and this is about
as smooth as it can go,'' said the Rev. Rob Grimm, pastor of First
Baptist Church in Sioux Falls, S.D. ``I think the focus is on
evangelism and mission, the positive side of why we're here instead
of all the political issues of the past.''
</P>
<P>
   But David McNair, a land developer from Jackson, Miss., and also
a veteran convention-goer, said he was disturbed by the low
attendance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the leadership has lost some touch with the
churches,'' he said. ``We're still hearing the wonderful things our
convention is doing. We have the largest evangelical mission
movement in the world. It's a wonderful gathering. I question why
it's not a whole lot larger.''
</P>
<P>
   Any controversial action to come out of this year's meeting is
likely to involve the country's most powerful Southern Baptist
layman, President Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The convention is scheduled to vote tonight on a motion by the
Rev. Wiley Drake, pastor of First Southern Baptist Church in Buena
Park, Calif., to ``communicate to President Bill Clinton our
strongest disapproval'' of a proclamation naming June Gay Pride
month in America.
</P>
<P>
   Another motion to tell Clinton's home church, Immanuel Baptist
in Little Rock, to discipline the president for his gay rights
stance or be ``disfellowshipped'' by next year's convention, was
ruled out of order since one year's meeting cannot bind another
year's convention to any specific action.
</P>
<P>
   Gayle White writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
