<SLUG> BC-BKN-LIPSYTE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 SPORTS COLUMN: THE '90s ABERRATION: ITS UP TO YOU NEW YORK  
(jt) 
 By ROBERT LIPSYTE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For most of the century as the Babe consumed
everything and Sam Huff knocked down everybody and then Clyde and
Dollar Bill created perfect harmony, the rest of the country came
to hate New York teams. Justifiably.
</P>
<P>
   They were rich, big, mean, powerful bullies. They ate your
lunch, took your cake, and left laughing.
</P>
<P>
   The line ``If you can make it in New York, you can make it
anywhere,'' obviously meant that the Apple was the toughest, most
demanding arena of all.
</P>
<P>
   If you can't make it in New York, loser, take yourself to a bush
league city, which is any other city, and become the Royal of
Nowhere. Come back and we'll kill you again.
</P>
<P>
   That was for most of the century. But by the late '90s, other
teams and cities had emerged triumphant. The Dallas Cowboys, the
Chicago Bulls, even the Mighty Ducks of Anaheim had become
America's teams.
</P>
<P>
   Nike was associated with Portland. The heart of American
Olympism was in Colorado Springs, its grasping paw in Salt Lake
City. Boxing came from Las Vegas and Atlantic City. The women's
sports wave was not visible from the Battery. New York was no
longer the sporting capital.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, the recent championship New York teams had to be
reinterpreted, by New Yorkers, to fit the new order. The Giants,
the Rangers and the Yankees of the '90s could not be viewed as a
return to normalcy _ the greatest generation comes back! _ but
rather as aberrations, needy, overachieving therapy groups who won
in spite of themselves because the only alternative was their
destruction.
</P>
<P>
   The line was changed to ``If New York can make it, then even you
can make it.'' Take heart and be inspired by the lesson of the
Apple.
</P>
<P>
   It was a lesson that the country wanted to learn. But because
the country had been conditioned for so long to hate and fear New
York as superior, it did not completely absorb the lesson until
last week. And then it hit. If the dysfunctional Knicks could get
to the final, every city's sewer has a trophy struggling to get
out. By last week, the pattern was clear: neediness wins.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants had won because otherwise Lawrence Taylor would have
laid waste most of downtown before imploding. The Rangers won so
that Mark Messier could overcome his Great Gretzky complex and find
peace. The Yankees won as complementary medical treatments for
Frank Torre's heart transplant, then Darryl Strawberry's colon
cancer. It wasn't Gotham gargantuism anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Should the Knicks go all the way it would be so Latrell Sprewell
and Marcus Camby can finally get the amateur shrinks, ethicists and
probation officers off their backs.
</P>
<P>
   The redemption of those once unwanted Knicks (plus their coach
and former general manager) may complete this decade's renovation
of New York's image from dirty to clean, hard to soft, from a
testing site to a nesting place. Times Square will have truly
become Disneyland and Madison Square Garden its Space Mountain.
</P>
<P>
   But the Knicks, as usual, have a slightly more complicated
situation than those other New York teams. While the coach is still
a central figure, his role has more texture and ambiguity. Mad Mike
Keenan and Gentle Joe Torre and Bad Bill Parcells, for all their
surface differences, were seen as managers of men who could by
force of personality or devious manipulation make their wills
prevail.
</P>
<P>
   The coach as Sergeant Svengali is a stereotype that even wannabe
coaches love. New York's mayor may look like a water boy but he has
been able to snarl and sneer his way to the kind of posture of
intimidation that Parcells enjoys.
</P>
<P>
   But Jeff Van Gundy, despite his Bill Gates look, has not even
been portrayed as a killer nerd. All those years at the Garden and
we have never got a sense of his court intelligence or work ethic.
</P>
<P>
   Could he have been Pat Riley's brain all along? We missed that
because of the traditional politics of the Garden and the custom of
reporters, in their scramble for leaks, to take public sides to
reward their sources.
</P>
<P>
   As the cases for or against Ernie Grunfeld, Dave Checketts and
Van Gundy's resistance to trading for Camby or playing Sprewell
were built, there was no easy consensus that would have answered
key questions. Could Van Gundy be a genius? Could Camby have grown
up before our eyes? Could Sprewell have been misunderstood? Or was
this just New York's new nice neediness at work? Or _ and this is
our only hope for a return to greatness _ did David Stern yearn for
Reggie Miller to misfire and spare the country a San
Antonio-Indiana final and salvage the National Basketball
Association season?
</P>
<P>
   If that's true, it means the NBA can only make it in New York.
And we're back.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
