<DOCNO> NYT19990615.0255 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-15 19:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6507 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-EUROPE-HNS &LR;      06-15 1238
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-EUROPE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRITISH, GERMAN LEADERS REFLECT MODERATE SHIFT IN ECONOMICS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CRAGG HINES 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ The war in Kosovo obscured something of a revolution in
another part of Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past few months, the leaders of Britain and Germany
have formalized a centrist manifesto to further distance their
leftist parties from decades of higher taxes, stringent government
economic controls and a social welfare system that is cushy by
American standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we need is a new balance between economic dynamism on one
side and social justice on the other,'' German Chancellor Gerhard
Schroeder said last week as he and British Prime Minister Tony
Blair announced the publication of their plan. ``We would like to
reclaim some economic competence.''
</P>
<P>
   The new plan, called ``The Third Way'' by Blair and ``The New
Center'' by Schroeder, stresses labor and welfare reform,
entrepreneurship and tax cuts to encourage creation of new jobs.
</P>
<P>
   The new pact will greet, and no doubt be hailed by, President
Clinton as he arrives Wednesday for a European visit that includes
the annual economic summit of the seven leading developed market
democracies and Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Much as the conservative troika of President Reagan, British
Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher and German Chancellor Helmut Kohl
dominated the trans-Atlantic alliance of the 1980s as the Cold War
wound down, the refashioned center-left pragmatism of Clinton,
Blair and Schroeder is seeing out the century and dominates Western
planning for the new millennium.
</P>
<P>
   Blair and Schroeder also would clearly like their moderated
vision of the role of government, already informally accepted by
other national leaders on the continent, to overtake the
traditional leftist agenda that has been the blueprint for the
European Union.
</P>
<P>
   An EU move to the right will almost certainly _ and for Blair
and Schroeder unexpectedly _ be hastened by the left's poor showing
in European Union Parliament elections held last Thursday through
Sunday. The body's center-right grouping won the largest number of
seats for the first time since the supra-national body first met in
1979.
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly, Clinton's first overnight stop will be in France,
where Socialist Prime Minister Lionel Jospin pointedly refused to
sign on to the Blair-Schroeder project.
</P>
<P>
   Among the major leftist parties, only Jospin's Socialist held
its own in the EU voting.
</P>
<P>
   Much as former French President Francois Mitterrand often
enjoyed being odd-man-out in the trans-Atlantic alliance in the
1980s, Jospin says he will go it alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must be true to ourselves first of all,'' Jospin told a
political rally in Toulouse last week. ``There is a certain
originality in French socialism that must be preserved.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, during his two-day state visit to France, may find he
has more in common with President Jacques Chirac, a center-right
Gaullist, than Jospin.
</P>
<P>
   Francois Bayrou, leader of Union for French Democracy, said
Jospin's coolness to the Blair-Schroeder enterprise confirmed that
French Socialism meant more regulation, a 35-hour work week and
more taxes. ``Jospin is really the most archaic of European leaders
_ the last of the left-wing Mohicans,'' Bayrou told London's
Guardian newspaper last week.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton flew from Washington to Geneva for a speech Wednesday to
the International Labor Organization and was then to travel on to
Paris. The annual summit is in Cologne, Germany, over the weekend.
Clinton will visit briefly in Slovenia, one of the most
economically dynamic pieces of the former Yugoslavia, before a
scheduled return home Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is a model for many of the European leftists who
recently have led their parties to victory after years out of power
because voter distrusted their economic policies. The U.S.
Democrats' losing years embodied by George McGovern, Walter Mondale
and Michael Dukakis have many European leftist counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   Blair, whose Labor Party languished in opposition from 1979 to
1997, sent representatives to consult closely with Clinton
operatives as he began to wean Britain's Labor Party from its
socialist past.
</P>
<P>
   In the run-up to the 1997 British election campaign, Blair used
phrases and symbols straight from Clinton's voter-tested message of
moderation.
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder, whose Social Democratic Party had been out of power
almost as long as British Labor, was less directly dependent on
Clinton's rhetoric in his victory last year but clearly was
impressed by the American's electoral success.
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder, who recently said the social welfare system cannot be
``a hammock,'' claims to have been working on moderation of his
party for a decade. In 1994, he was forced out as a government
opposition spokesman after his claim that there were no left-wing
or right-wing economic policies, only ``correct ones.''
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder faces a more difficult road in getting his party,
which is further to the left than his compatriots in either the
United States or Britain, to buy into the ``new center'' plan. The
path was cleared somewhat in March when one of the Social
Democrats' old big-government mandarins, Oskar Lafontaine, quit as
finance minister and party chairman, in a dispute over Schroeder's
more moderate line.
</P>
<P>
   In unveiling their proposal, Blair said center-left parties will
be allowed to remain in power only ``if we back to the hilt the
potential for innovation and enterprise to generate new growth
potential and more jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   In advance of European Union Parliament elections, Blair sought
to use his new deal with Schroeder to deflect voter attention away
from his party's plan to eventually adopt the new euro currency and
ditch the British pound.
</P>
<P>
   Blair said his proposal with the German chancellor was proof
that Britain faced only one choice, ``leading Europe or leaving
Europe.'' The new plan, he said, showed Britain was ``a modern
nation with influence again.''
</P>
<P>
   Blair may want to rethink his tactic, because British
Conservatives, on the heels of an anti-euro campaign, doubled their
share of EU Parliament seats in the voting. Schroeder's forces
fared as poorly in balloting in Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the election, Francis Maude, the Conservative Party
economic spokesman, said the prime minister's venture with
Schroeder was splashed with hogwash.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody is going to be fooled by Tony Blair's ludicrous claims
that he and Chancellor Schroeder are committed to cutting taxes in
Europe,'' Maude said. ``The German government is committed to tax
harmonization (throughout the EU), which would mean higher taxes in
Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as Clinton's dedication to ``New Democrat'' centrism has
been questioned in the United States, some skeptics wonder whether
Blair and Schroeder really believe in the policies they are
advancing or fear the voters' reaction to unvarnished socialist
economic doctrine.
</P>
<P>
   ``We agree that there must not be any reversion to the failed
policies of the 1970s,'' Blair said in a news conference last week
with Schroeder. But is that a core belief or bit of political
pragmatism?
</P>
<P>
   The text of the Blair-Schroeder pact takes strong note of the
political realities, saying:
</P>
<P>
   ``Public expenditures as a proportion of national income has
more or less reached the limits of public acceptability.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
