<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-15 19:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6508 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISRAELI-ARAB-ART-NYT &LR;      06-15 1293
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAELI-ARAB-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAELI ARAB LOTTERY MILLIONAIRE TRIES TO PROMOTE PEACE AND MUTUAL
RESPECT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill.)   (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ABU GHOSH, Israel _ Driving his gleaming black Cadillac through
the rutted roads of this village outside Jerusalem, Jawdat Ibrahim
talked about his miserable childhood. It was miserable even by the
relatively abject standards of an Israeli Arab born 34 years ago in
a country that considered him second class.
</P>
<P>
   When he was 4, he sat beside his father on a bed as the man, for
reasons never known, took his life _ drinking poison, then fading
away. His mother, bereft, raised her six children in a cellar with
a dirt floor, the only finished part of the house his father had
intended to build. There was rarely enough to eat, and what Ibrahim
remembers most is feeling lonely in a village that was technically
one big family.
</P>
<P>
   Today, in a melancholy mood, Ibrahim still seems somewhat
lonely, although he has literally gone from the cellar to the
penthouse. He narrated his story on the expansive terrace of one of
his marbled, Jacuzzi-filled townhouses here, a few blocks from his
fancy restaurant in the center of town. Then, in butter-soft
leather loafers, he glided down the polished stairs.
</P>
<P>
   The terrible circumstances of his youth, he said, created a
philosophy in his home. Determined to treat others with the respect
she was often denied, Ibrahim's mother raised her children not only
to consider themselves the equal of everyone, Jew or Arab, but also
to consider everyone their neighbor. It was a mindset that planted
itself deep inside Ibrahim as a bud of self-confidence.
</P>
<P>
   It stayed with him even as he fled to Chicago, where his uncle
lived, and as he drove a tow truck through frigid Midwest winters,
bailing out luxury vehicles trapped in snowbanks.
</P>
<P>
   Ibrahim had no grand design for the future when he bought his
first and last lottery ticket in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   But when he won a $17.5 million jackpot in the Illinois State
Lottery, he took it as destiny. He was forced to sue to get the
prize, denied him on a technicality; the lawsuit increased his
earnings to $22.7 million. He embarked first on an extended
shopping spree. Then, in 1992, with the option of moving anywhere
in the world, he chose to return with his millions to this
pocket-sized traditional town _ to his home, his clan.
</P>
<P>
   Ibrahim has parlayed the money into a peculiar role for himself
_ not only inside the town, which he helped remake, but in Israel
as a whole, where he used new-found access to designate himself an
emissary of peace, brotherhood and protexia (the Hebrew word for
pull, or connections).
</P>
<P>
   ``Jawdat is an open guy after all those years in the States,''
said Sallah Tarif, an Israeli Arab member of Parliament with the
Labor Party. ``This is the kind of type we need here in order to do
something with ourselves, to advance.''
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after he returned from the United States, Ibrahim opened
the elegant Abu Ghosh restaurant, starting a trend that has
considerably helped the economy of the town. Abu Ghosh, whose
working people used to solely commute to factories every day, now
has a full row of locally owned restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturdays, the town is jammed with secular Israeli Jewish
tourists. For most of the tourists, it is their only contact with
Arabs at all, inside or outside Israel. But most do not come for
political reasons; almost every restaurant in nearby Jerusalem is
closed for the Sabbath.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Ibrahim, who shmoozes in Hebrew with his customers,
thinks of it as a kind of peace industry. And he points to the
Israeli-U.S.-Palestinian negotiations that have taken place at his
restaurant as evidence that he has created a kind of halfway house
between worlds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to think that I have put Abu Ghosh on the map as a
symbol of peace,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We Israeli Arabs should be the bridge of peace. Israelis have
to have peace with us first, then they can think about Lebanon and
Syria.''
</P>
<P>
   Abu Ghosh has always had a strange standing in the Israeli Arab
world. It was seen as a ``collaborator's village,'' because the
mukhtar, or leader, of the clan who lived there made a decision 50
years ago not to fight the Israelis in order to preserve the town.
</P>
<P>
   Superficially it looks better off than most Israeli Arab towns,
but Ibrahim said that four or five families are squeezed into
almost every house. The town, half the size it used to be, is
hemmed in by a highway and Jewish developments. Now, when someone
is tempted to sell land to an outsider, Ibrahim rushes to buy it
first.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love buying land, especially in Israeli Arab villages,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Part of Ibrahim's goal has been to reconnect Abu Ghosh with the
Israeli Arab world, to make it clear that their problems are
shared, that ``we are brothers.'' His Abu Ghosh Foundation finances
projects for Israeli Arabs throughout the country, from youth
leadership programs and technology training to prenatal care and
direct cash grants to cover the medical costs of the very poor.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation also awards about 40 scholarships a year, to both
Arab and Jewish students _ ``so that maybe some Jewish foundation
will do the same in reverse,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He himself barely made it through high school, mostly because he
was working nearly full time after class, tending the backyard
gardens of Israeli Jews. Possessed of considerable chutzpah, he
later tried his hand at running a small ceramics factory in the
heart of Jerusalem _ after talking the aging Jewish owner into
leasing it to him for a pittance.
</P>
<P>
   But he was not a businessman, and when he ran to the United
States, he was fleeing a mountain of debts. He persuaded a travel
agent to sell him a plane ticket on credit, and flew off to Chicago
to find his uncle.
</P>
<P>
   Personally, his return was triumphant but difficult, reconciling
the pain of his past with the power that the lottery money has
brought him.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people come and ask me for things now,'' he said, ``I
can't help but ask myself where were those people when I was a
child.''
</P>
<P>
   His first marriage, to an American he fell madly in love with,
started in Las Vegas and ended in divorce.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, his second wedding was a grand affair, a Muslim
wedding held at the Notre Dame Church in the heart of town and
attended by a who's who of Israeli, Palestinian and Jordanian
political figures. His mother and his 100-year-old grandmother
beamed with pride. They had persuaded him to consent to an arranged
marriage to a young woman from his extended family.
</P>
<P>
   He was told that love would grow, he said, but it didn't work.
He and his wife are separated, he said sadly, standing in front of
a birthday card framed and displayed on the bar of his restaurant.
It's from President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The break-up was not his only recent disappointment.
</P>
<P>
   For the last five years, the Interior Ministry, which was
controlled by the ultra-Orthodox Shas Party, has run the town. The
mayor and the entire council were religious Jews, appointed by
Shas. Finally, the town held its first elections for Mayor early
this year. Ibrahim ran _ and lost.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's young, and he was away for a long time,'' said Dr. Subhi
Abu Ghosh.
</P>
<P>
   ``And we behaved no differently from those in any other
democratic race, we didn't necessarily elect the best.'' Pensive
about his ups and downs, Ibrahim has tired of the assumption that
his lottery earnings have fueled his successes and fed his
failures.
</P>
<P>
   ``I make myself myself,'' he said. ``It's not the money. It's
me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
