<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Delta, pilots recess 777 talks after failed meeting
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Negotiators for Delta Air Lines and its pilot union
met Tuesday but exchanged no new proposals on Boeing 777 pay rates,
dimming the chances of a last-minute deal that would salvage
Delta's original plans for adding the big jets. Both sides say they
remain willing to meet again.
</P>
<P>
   Delta last week announced it was postponing all further 777
deliveries and laying plans to sell the two it now has, citing an
impasse over pilot pay rates after five months of negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   The carrier, which had planned to have 11 777s by next summer,
said it would reschedule the deliveries ``if and when'' a pay pact
is reached. The issue may become part of new contract negotiations
that begin in September.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Thurston writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
