<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-15 19:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6515 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-MILOSEVIC-NYT     06-15 1150
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MILOSEVIC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SERBIAN CHURCH URGES MILOSEVIC AND HIS CABINET TO QUIT 
</HEADLINE>
 (See also KOSOVO-CHURCH) 
(nk) 
 By CARLOTTA GALL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia _ In a rare direct challenge to President
Slobodan Milosevic, the Serbian Orthodox Church called on him to
resign Tuesday, as Milosevic has thrown himself into an unusually
energetic campaign to rally a disillusioned and depressed public.
</P>
<P>
   ``We demand that the federal president and his government resign
in the interest and the salvation of the people, so that new
officials, acceptable at home and abroad, can take responsibility
for the people and their future as a National Salvation
Government,'' the holy synod, the church's highest body, said in a
statement, the independent Beta news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
   Although the church has been critical of Milosevic's policies in
the past, it has never before demanded his resignation. The timing
of the announcement, so soon after the peace deal, also suggests
that the influential church would like a new leader for a new era
in Serbia. Opposition politicians are also increasingly calling for
new elections and a change of government.
</P>
<P>
   In what some analysts are interpreting as a desperate action to
salvage his political career, Milosevic has embarked on a rare tour
around the country, making his second visit to inspect bomb damage
in two days. His visit to Novi Sad on Monday, and his walk amid
crowds of cheering supporters Tuesday, marked his first public
appearances since October 1997, when he toured Mionica in central
Serbia, which was devastated in an earthquake, the VIP news agency
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is certainly unusual what he is doing,'' said one local
journalist.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic still controls the crucial levers of power, namely the
security forces, and does not look close to losing his grip. But
the Orthodox Church's call for his resignation has added to the
speculation about Milosevic's political future, when he is already
damaged by the recent indictment from the International War Crimes
Tribunal, and as he faces the end of his presidential term in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   While only a small minority of the population practice religion,
the church does bear some moral weight. But the church's position
represents the loss of an important portion of support for
Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   The church also expressed deep concern over what has happened in
Kosovo, in particular the recent exodus of Serbs. The church called
on the international peacekeeping forces to provide protection to
the Serb civilians and to the many Orthodox monasteries and
churches there, including the ancient seat of the Serbian Church in
the town of Pec in western Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The holy synod also urged Serbs not to leave the province. ``We
also appeal to our brothers in Kosovo to stay in their homes and
not to leave their relics, convinced in the truth of Jesus Christ's
words that `Those who endure till the end will be saved.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic, who built his career on championing the Kosovo Serbs,
has now dropped them unceremoniously. Well over 30,000 have fled
their homes in the province in the last four days, according to the
Yugoslav Red Cross, and they have received barely a mention on
state television.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic clearly feels the need to woo back the public to his
side after the war, which at first drew the people behind him in
patriotic fervor against NATO but which is now widely seen as
disastrous for the country.
</P>
<P>
   In his speech Monday he announced the launching of the
reconstruction of Serbia. Tuesday he was back on the road, visiting
Aleksinac in southern Serbia, walking onto the city's main highway
bridge, which was hit several times by NATO missiles. The visit was
covered extensively on state television, along with a laudatory
appraisal of the president's patriotic performance during the war.
</P>
<P>
   While many Serbs still blame NATO, opposition politicians are
becoming more outspoken.
</P>
<P>
   The Serbian Radical party, the ultranationalist party of deputy
premier Vojislav Seselj, announced it was leaving the government on
Monday. Seselj and his followers, who include 15 ministers in the
current government, had vowed to leave their posts if foreign
troops ever occupied Serbian land.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since Kosovo is now occupied we have no reason to remain in
the government,'' Seselj said, adding that one of the only reasons
the Radical Party joined the government had been to defend Kosovo
Metohija, giving the province its full Serbian name.
</P>
<P>
   The departure from the government of the Radical Party was
immediately placed in doubt by the Serbian president, Milan
Milutinovic, who adopted a decree Tuesday ordering all government
officials to remain in their posts.
</P>
<P>
   Seselj, who sees himself as a rival to Milosevic, is a skillful
politician but may lose support once he loses access to the
national media.
</P>
<P>
   If the Radical Party does leave the government, it opens the way
for changes. Milosevic may invite the main democratic opposition
leader, Vuk Draskovic, head of the Serb Renewal Party, to join the
government.
</P>
<P>
   Draskovic, who participated in Milosevic's government as deputy
prime minister for several months this year, said Tuesday he would
demand ``fundamental democratic reforms'' before joining the
government again.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they are not ready, and are ready to continue with their
wrong policy of leading Serbia to disaster, the majority of Serbs
would not allow that,'' he told a news conference here.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Draskovic did not go as far as calling for Milosevic's
resignation but suggested he should perform a more ceremonial role
as a head of state. Draskovic instead attacked the powerful
Yugoslav prime minister, Momir Bulatovic, saying he should be
replaced.
</P>
<P>
   It may suit the Yugoslav president to shuffle his government.
Milosevic may try to use politicians such as Draskovic, and the
president of the republic of Montenegro, Milo Djukanovic, to court
western aid and investment to help rebuild Serbia. A change may
also appease the public who face a grim next six months of economic
hardship, including shortages of electricity, heat and jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Unless he changes the rules, Milosevic is not permitted to run
again, after two consecutive terms as president of the Federal
Republic of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   He may be tempted to call early elections and change the rules,
analysts say, although that would be both expensive and risky. He
is also hampered by the situation in Kosovo, since many of his
party seats were won in the southern province. It is unlikely that
Kosovo will participate in national elections soon and Milosevic
can no longer count on strong support from the region.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are fed up and that's all I have to say,'' says a man in
Nis, out window-shopping with his wife and small daughter. As for
the future, he refused to say.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
