<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SENATE-DISABLED-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE TO OK BENEFITS BILL FOR DISABLED WHO WANT TO WORK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LOUISE D. PALMER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Hoping to encourage millions of disabled Americans
to join the work force, the Senate reached agreement Tuesday on a
bill that will allow them to keep their federal health benefits if
they find a job.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate is expected to vote overwhelmingly Wednesday for what
supporters call a ``bill of independence,'' co-authored by Senators
Edward M. Kennedy, Democrat of Massachusetts, and James M.
Jeffords, Republican of Vermont. It would allow states to extend
Medicaid benefits to any of the 7.5 million Americans who are
qualified as disabled and become employed.
</P>
<P>
   The bill addresses what some say is a Catch-22 in current law,
which forbids people who work from receiving federal disability
benefits, including health insurance. The measure is estimated to
cost $838 million over five years, but that is expected to be
offset somewhat by a $68 million savings, as more disabled people
pay taxes and fewer rely on Social Security Insurance, a cash
benefit many disabled now receive.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference, President Clinton hailed the agreement as
a step toward equality for the 54 million people who live with
mental or physical impairments.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a profoundly important piece of legislation,'' Clinton
said. A version of the bill has been approved by a House committee
but no vote has been scheduled by the full House.
</P>
<P>
   As well as bringing opportunity and independence to the working
disabled, Clinton said the measure represents an economic victory
because more Americans would become taxpayers, contribute to Social
Security, and broaden the consumer market.
</P>
<P>
   Mounting pressure from Democrats and Republicans alike, as well
as effective lobbying by disability groups, prevailed over
opposition to the bill by some conservative Republican members,
including Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott of Mississippi and
Senator Phil Gramm of Texas, who had concerns about how to pay for
the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, disability groups picketed Lott's Mississippi
offices, and Senate Democrats, all of whom supported the bill,
threatened to criticize Lott and other Republicans for refusing to
move the legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We live in a culture where work is highly valued, and people
with disabilities have been denied the chance to work,'' said Paul
Spooner, director of the Metrowest Center for Independent Living in
Framingham, Mass. ``This is the best thing that could happen to
us.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal is to remove the unconscionable barriers that prevent
so many citizens with disabilities from working and living
independent lives,'' Kennedy said.
</P>
<P>
   Under current law, disabled people are discouraged from working
because they lose their disability coverage if they earn $500 a
month. Because so many people with disabilities have expensive
medical needs and are excluded from private health plans, the law
is a barrier to those who want to work but cannot afford to give up
benefits.
</P>
<P>
   ``The work-incentive bill will raise this cap to a realistic
level of $75,000 (a year), allowing many disabled individuals to
return to the work force,'' Jeffords said.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 7.5 million Americans who receive disability benefits,
only one-half of 1 percent work. But while 75 percent of all
disabled people are unemployed, a 1998 Harris poll found that 72
percent of the unemployed want to work.
</P>
<P>
   According to Jeffords, if only 1 percent of those with
disabilities work, taxpayers would save $3.5 billion over those
workers' lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   As well as allowing states to extend Medicaid benefits, the bill
gradually phases out cash benefits to disabled Americans as they go
back to work. And it would fund job-training and worker-assistance
programs, as well as provide the security that if the job did not
work out, the workers with disabilities would still have access to
their benefits and cash assistance.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would also set up a $300 million program over 10 years
to allow some people to keep Medicare coverage while working, as
well as a pilot project to allow states to give people threatened
with disability in the future _ those with arthritis, multiple
sclerosis, or HIV _ access to Medicaid coverage for prescriptions
that might allow them to stay healthy and keep their jobs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
