<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KENNEDY-SCHOOL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHOOL RESPONDING TO MINORITY TENURE CHALLENGE, DEAN SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KAREN HSU  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Last week, in a graduation address at Harvard
University's John F. Kennedy School of Government, the Rev. Jesse
Jackson challenged the school's administration to double the number
of tenure-track minority faculty in the next one to two years.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 106 professors at the Kennedy School, only six are black,
a school spokesman said. Of those, only one is tenured and two are
on tenure tracks. The other black tenured professor, Judge A. Leon
Higginbotham Jr., died last December.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are pushing on an open door,'' said Dean Joseph S. Nye,
Jr., who said that since he had become dean three years ago, half
of the 24 new faculty members were minorities or women.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is that enough? No. Are we trying? Yes,'' Nye said.
</P>
<P>
   In terms of matching the actual number Jackson called for,
academic dean Fred Schauer said he couldn't give a definite answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``But in terms of efforts, we should double, triple and
quadruple,'' said Schauer, who has served as academic dean for the
last two years. ``It is a source of enormous concern and enormous
focus.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a serious problem with the number of African-American
faculty,'' said Schauer, who added that the problem with the number
of black tenured faculty was more serious than any other ethnic
group. Associate professor Keith Reeves, who is black, is leaving
for Swarthmore College.
</P>
<P>
   The school also has two Latino-Americans and seven
Asian-Americans on its faculty, said Schauer.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't the first time Jackson has criticized Harvard for its
faculty hiring practices. In 1990, he came to Harvard at the
request of Harvard Law School students to discuss minority hiring
at the school.
</P>
<P>
   Today, out of 76 tenured law faculty, six are African American,
one is Latino and one is Native American, said a spokesman for the
law school.
</P>
<P>
   Sociologist and university professor William Julius Wilson, the
Kennedy School's only tenured black, said that he and the school
administration have been working on identifying outstanding
minority scholars to recruit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a problem we are trying to correct. For the last several
weeks, we have been putting together a wish list of people,'' said
Wilson. In the fall, a faculty committee will start reviewing
applications for positions.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem is the pool of qualified candidates who
emerge from the rigorous selection process is small, said economist
Ronald Ferguson, a black who has been a member of the faculty since
1983.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really musical chairs. We are just trying to suck up a
larger fraction of a very small pool,'' said Ferguson.
</P>
<P>
   ``The law school got Lani Guinier, but now the University of
Pennsylvania doesn't have her,'' Ferguson said.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, Lani Guinier became the first tenured minority woman
professor at Harvard Law School.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are willing to compete within the pool, Nye said. ``But the
best is to expand the pool.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson said one reason for the small pool of candidates is
because it has only been recently that African-American scholars
have paid more attention to public policy issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before, they were addressing more pure science, non-policy
relevant issues. They were focused on testing hypotheses instead of
applying theories to correct major problems,'' said Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   ``If any school is in the position to attract these scholars, it
would be the Kennedy School.''
</P>
<P>
   Identification and recruitment of minorities into academic paths
must start earlier, so they aren't lured into the business and law
worlds, said Nye.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those opportunities are just more lucrative. They can go to
school for half the time and earn twice as much,'' said Nye.
</P>
<P>
   ``The opportunity to hire more minority faculty is there, since
there is a reasonably high degree of faculty turnover at the
Kennedy School,'' Schauer said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
