<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: ONCE FOUNDERING, A TEAM DISCOVERS ITS GRAND
SPOTLIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By HARVEY ARATON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ A very astute friend of mine made an interesting
observation the other day. She compared the Knicks to the Olympic
figure skater, Nancy Kerrigan, who once took a well-timed whack to
the knee and then went on to the performance of her life.
</P>
<P>
   She didn't win the ultimate prize, but under duress and the
global celebrity scope, she did glide triumphantly away from her
reputation as an underachiever in the grand spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   A number of Knicks have indeed taken a Tonyaesque whack or two
as they made an unsuspecting turn from the road to ruin, leading to
the National Basketball Association finals beginning here tonight
against a quality Spurs team that doesn't yet know what it's got
itself into.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Ewing, the franchise player who was relegated to
ordering his teammates to ``get me my ring.'' Ernie Grunfeld, the
general manager who's been banished from his own architectural
triumph. Jeff Van Gundy, Larry Johnson, Allan Houston, Latrell
Sprewell, Marcus Camby, the two-headed point guard known as Chris
Childs and Charlie Ward _ they have all taken turns getting whacked
in various and most creative ways and occasionally by each other
for being in the way of a competing or antagonistic agenda.
</P>
<P>
   Conventional basketball wisdom suggests these Knicks are about
to meet their match but somehow, some way, they have made a most
unlikely transformation from a fractious gathering of victims whose
battle cry was a well-known Nancyism _ ``Why me?'' _ to a spirited
collective that is sizing up the favored Goliaths from San Antonio
and asking, ``Why not?''
</P>
<P>
   These Knicks have become, according to Coach Van Gundy, ``a true
team,'' an assertion recently given a most flattering validation
when Chris Dudley got a telephone call from Dick Kuchen, his former
coach at Yale.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `As a coach, it's just so nice to see a team discover
itself,' '' the Knicks' gangly center said. ``Everybody has found
his role. It sounds so easy, but it's not so easy to achieve.''
</P>
<P>
   Considering the self-destructive mediocrity this very team was,
it is also difficult to understand, which could be why, in the
spirit of a season previously given to assigning blame, we have now
entered the equally contentious realm of granting credit. To wit:
Camby is the primary reason for the Knicks' sudden surge. No,
Sprewell is, and you've got to be blind not to see that. Wait, but
wasn't it Van Gundy who nurtured these indifferent refugees from
losing teams, hardened them to the point where they could be
Broadway stars? Please, he never wanted either of them, and is now
unjustly reaping the fruits of the deposed Grunfeld's labor.
</P>
<P>
   Just in time for Game 1, came permission to focus on the sum and
not the parts.The authentic team stamp of approval from a living,
breathing, retired-number Old Knick.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bradley and I were talking about it,'' Dave DeBusschere said
the other day. ``When Childs is pushing the ball, and they have
Sprewell, Camby and Houston running, they're the fastest team in
the NBA.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, all right, he didn't say smartest, the distinction
delicately preserved through the years for the championship Knicks
of 1970 and 1973. DeBusschere did say his children have admitted to
him that while they are happy for these Knicks, they are concerned
about this motley crew treading into sacred territory, should it
win it all.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them, `Jeez, what are you talking about?' ''
DeBusschere said. ``We won our second title 25 years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-six, but who's counting? What should be noted is that the
Houston-Camby-Sprewell Knicks just finished dispatching from the
playoffs an Indiana Pacers team whose egalitarianism was
reminiscent of the Old Knicks. Eras pass. Styles change. Forget,
for the moment, Red Holzman's teams. These Knicks who are sleek and
swift are much more fun, night in, night out, than the canned
vegetables cooked up in New York by Pat Riley earlier in the
decade, a repulsive form of thug ball still being served to the
audiences in south Florida.
</P>
<P>
   It has been my contention for a couple of years that only some
kind of emotional coup d'etat was going to dislodge Riley's
coach-must-control ethos that was so infused in the New York
basketball psyche. Don Nelson's insurgence never had a chance. Van
Gundy was hired to restore peace, to please Patrick by continuing
to subsist by posting him up. The Knicks plodded along, four years
running a second-round loser.
</P>
<P>
   Fearing for his job, Van Gundy rode Ewing until he got hurt.
Whack. The new players, Sprewell and Camby, stumbled about as a
team so accustomed to playing one way shifted suddenly to another.
Whack. At 21-21, facing exclusion from the playoffs, Dave Checketts
decided he needed to find an organizational sacrifice before the
television moguls began blaming him. Whack.
</P>
<P>
   There was no way to anticipate the startling results since the
``reassigning'' of Grunfeld _ 23 games played, 17 won. The critics
should stop apologizing for reporting what they legitimately saw, a
team that was succumbing more to its own dysfunction than the
opposition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who would have thought this a year ago, even two months ago?''
DeBusschere said. ``Not a soul would've suggested they'd get to the
finals. And I'll tell you the guy that surprises me more than
anyone is L.J. I thought he was done.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, of course, may be done as an effective contributor, if
the sprained ligament in his right knee does not heal fast. There
are alternate interpretations of what this latest Knick injury
could mean.
</P>
<P>
   One, it leaves them without a low-post presence that will enable
Tim Duncan and David Robinson to roam with impunity, assist with
the defense against Houston and Sprewell, the Knicks' go-to
scorers. Two, it gives the Knicks one more victim to play and win
for, as this television event, this unlikely epic, enters its final
round.
</P>
<P>
   Holzman, who died of leukemia, seven months too soon. Ewing,
reduced to a cheerleader in his 14th year in pursuit of a ring.
Grunfeld, watching bitterly from home. Pick your persecution. They
have all been whacked, but, beware Spurs: These Knicks are way
beyond ``Why me?'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
