<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-15 20:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6524 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-BENGALS-CAMP-COX     06-15 0443
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-BENGALS-CAMP-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    On first day of camp, RB Dillon not his usual self
 &HT;    By Marty Williams
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI _ Even though the Cincinnati Bengals open their
locker room to the media on a regular basis, Corey Dillon has
seldom made himself available.
</P>
<P>
   During the time he was supposed to be available, he either
declared himself off limits to reporters or hid out in the
players-only training room.
</P>
<P>
   But on the first day of a voluntary three-day minicamp that
began at Spinney Field on Tuesday, the running back never displayed
the aloofness and surliness that had been his trademarks.
</P>
<P>
   Dillon said his new mellowness and changed outlook began in
February when Desiree Antoine, his fiance, gave birth to a
daughter, Cameron.
</P>
<P>
   ``The labor lasted 28 hours and I was there for all of it,''
Dillon said. ``I thought I was strong until I saw what Desiree went
through.''
</P>
<P>
   Dillon described the baby's birth as ``the most beautiful
experience I've ever dealt with. I can't really describe it, but
now that I'm responsible for her, I just feel more mellow, more
complete, more calm. Every time I look at her, I feel like I'm on
top of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Dillon did not join the 50-plus veterans who have been working
out at Spinney in recent weeks, but said he had other obligations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't because I didn't want to be here,'' he said. ``She
(Desiree) was going to school and I stayed home to take care of the
baby. I thought I was doing the right thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Dillon is the only running back in Bengal history to start his
career with back-to-back 1,000-yard seasons. Last year, however, he
was limited by a series of nagging injuries.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had problems with my shoulder, knee, ribs, back and ankle.
There always seemed to be something wrong. I had hoped to do a lot
more, so in that respect it wasn't a year I will cherish. It was an
OK year, an average year.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though this minicamp is voluntary, 81 rookies and veterans
under contract are participating. The only invited player who
failed to make an appearance on Tuesday was 10-year man James
Francis, listed No. 2 on the depth chart at left outside linebacker
behind Steve Foley.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Bruce Coslet was obviously displeased with Francis'
decision and there's a good chance he won't be invited to training
camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``James chose not to be here and everyone else did,'' Coslet
said. ``That speaks volumes and we'll go on from there. Let's talk
about the 81 guys who are here.''
</P>
<P>
   Marty Williams writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
