<SLUG> BC-BUSH-2000-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH `A REGULAR SORT OF GUY' IN NEW HAMPSHIRE  

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN C. HENRY 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DERRY, N.H. _ Wearing a blue windbreaker with the state seal on
one breast and his name on the other, Texas Gov. George W. Bush
stepped off his campaign bus Tuesday at Hadco Industries, one of
the final stops on his maiden foray outside Texas as a presidential
candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Bush glanced toward the four suited company officials standing
at the head of the sidewalk. Behind them, a gantlet of 14
television cameras and too many newspaper photographers and
reporters to count, waiting to record his every word, every move in
the 25-yard walk into the plant.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush did not follow the script, which campaign officials
acknowledge designing to avoid missteps that might break the string
of glowing reviews of his four-day campaign trip. Instead, he
angled toward a tree-shaded picnic table where five Hadco workers
had paused for a smoke before going inside to help make circuit
boards.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope you don't mind me and 250 of my new best friends
joining you,'' Bush said with a laugh as the media scrum
immediately surrounded the table, pointing cameras from every
direction and dangling fuzzy boom microphones close overhead.
</P>
<P>
   Moments later, he was off, headed toward the plant entrance.
</P>
<P>
   Like the thousands encountering Bush in Iowa and New Hampshire
since Saturday, the five workers were awed, as much by the
spectacle of the entourage as the candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought, the way he sat down and talked to us, he's a
regular sort of guy,'' said Bill Brown, a maintenance worker. ``He
seems to have a sense of humor. And looks a lot like his dad
(former President Bush). And that's good.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess down the road we're going to learn what he stands
for,'' Brown added, drawing nods from his co-workers.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, generally an unknown quantity outside Texas except for the
name, arrived in New Hampshire as a new public opinion survey found
him with more support among Granite State Republicans than all 10
of his GOP rival combined.
</P>
<P>
   The survey by American Research Group also showed that 74
percent of New Hampshire Republicans have a favorable opinion of
Bush, and 2 percent have an unfavorable opinion, making him by the
far the most popular of the GOP presidential hopefuls.
</P>
<P>
   His closest rival, Elizabeth Dole, was favored by 15 percent of
New Hampshire Republicans, down from 25 percent in February, the
poll showed. It also found Dole was viewed favorably by 64 percent
of state GOP voters; unfavorably by 12 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Despite plans to avoid specifics until the fall so opponents
will have less to shoot at, Bush provided an outline of a few
positions during his trip to the two key states in the presidential
nominating process.
</P>
<P>
   Bush supports a constitutional ban on flag burning and opposes
using abortion opposition as a litmus test for Supreme Court
appointments. He wants to increase spending on the military. At the
same time, he promises to veto any effort to raise income tax rates
but would not rule out other tax increases.
</P>
<P>
   The 52-year-old candidate opposes quotas and racial preferences,
but wants to increase minority access to higher education and
government contracts. In Iowa, a major corn-producing state, Bush
endorsed subsidies for ethanol production, which relies on corn for
making the alternative fuel.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also favors medical savings accounts _ a program that
allows people to deduct money before taxes to pay health care
bills. Asked about tougher gun controls, Bush sidestepped a direct
answer, saying he defends the right to bear arms and officials
``need to enforce the laws on the books.''
</P>
<P>
   Other specifics _ such as how he plans to boost military
preparedness and cut taxes _ would be forthcoming, he said,
acknowledging that he broke little new ground on issues. ``There's
going to be a lot of time for 10-point programs,'' he said, adding
that he would offer detailed proposals ``on my own timetable.''
</P>
<P>
   The likely Democratic nominee, Vice President Al Gore, took a
sideways swipe at Bush as he flew to Tennessee for his own
announcement Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to just deal in platitudes,'' he said. ``I'm
going to deal with policies and specific choices.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, asked on CNN about Gore's entry into the race, was
unimpressed. ``He's the status quo,'' Bush said. ``If people like
the status quo, then the rest of the country can come fishing with
me in Texas next year.''
</P>
<P>
   For Bush's GOP opponents, the details cannot come soon enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eventually he's going to have to walk into the living rooms
and the diners, on to a stage where (Bush's aides) don't have total
control of the environment,'' said Tom Rath, the New Hampshire
campaign coordinator for Lamar Alexander. ``That's when any
weakness will show.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Until now we've been competing, not against George W. Bush the
man, but against a mythology,'' Rath said.
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to draw him out, two of his more conservative Republican
opponents _ Gary Bauer and Steve Forbes _ have challenged him to a
series of debates. His staff dismisses the invitations as coming
too early.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Democratic operatives have begun trailing him,
characterizing him as an extremist disguising himself as a
moderate. At several stops, national Democratic Party Chairman Joe
Andrew reminded reporters that Bush is from the same state that
elected House Majority Leader Dick Armey of Irving and Majority
Whip Tom DeLay of Sugar Land, two conservative congressmen who take
credit _ and share the blame _ for partisan congressional politics.
</P>
<P>
   Bush took the tactics in stride. ``I'm pleased the Democrats are
paying attention,'' he said. ``I like to talk about me, and I'm
glad that others are talking about me too. They must be worried.''
</P>
<P>
   Before leaving New Hampshire, Bush stopped at the Madden Family
Restaurant in Derry, where he slipped behind the counter to help
serve coffee before speaking to supporters who packed the
restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Otto, a customer, said he supports Bush even though he did
not learn anything new about the Texas governor except that ``he
pours a good cup of coffee.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
