<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-GIULIANI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIULIANI SEEKS CHARTER CHANGE TO THWART FOE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRED KAPLAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani has not yet announced he is
even running for the Senate, but already he is plotting to block
one of his foes from succeeding him in City Hall should he win the
race and move to Washington.
</P>
<P>
   For months now, Giuliani and his aides have gritted their teeth
over what they see as the one downside of his running for national
office _ that he might have to turn over the city's reins to Mark
Green.
</P>
<P>
   Green, a liberal Democrat who has unsuccessfully run for mayor
and senator, is New York City's popularly elected public advocate
and, as such, has written many reports criticizing Giuliani's
policies. The two men stand yards apart ideologically, and do not
like each other personally.
</P>
<P>
   The next mayoral election is scheduled for November 2001 _ one
year after Giuliani is expected to run for Senate. The city charter
designates the public advocate as next in line in case the mayor
leaves office prematurely. Therefore, if Giuliani wins the Senate
race, Green would become acting mayor for a year _ and, given the
advantages of incumbency, would stand a good chance of winning the
job for a full four-year term beyond that.
</P>
<P>
   So, Tuesday, Giuliani named a 15-member special commission _
dominated by his close political allies _ to revise the city
charter.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani reportedly would like to keep the public advocate as
his successor, but only for 60 days, and then to hold a special
election.
</P>
<P>
   Any proposals made by the charter commission would be placed on
a ballot and voted upon, as a referendum, as early as November.
</P>
<P>
   Green called a press conference Tuesday, a few hours after the
mayor named his panel, to denounce the move as ``a vindictive power
grab,'' a ``clear abuse of power,'' and another sign that Giuliani
``governs by tantrum and vendetta.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani made no bones about the political nature of his action.
``This is politics,'' he told reporters. ``That's what I do. I'm
the mayor . . . and the city charter gives the mayor certain
powers, which I exercise.'' He also said his views of Green are
well known, adding for those who remain in the dark that a Green
mayoralty would be ``a disaster.''
</P>
<P>
   Green, at his news conference, released a scholarly report
showing that the current rules of mayoral succession are consistent
with 167 years of tradition, and have survived six major revisions
of the charter, including the last one, 10 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The position of public advocate has been around only since 1993,
but it is the explicit successor to a former office called
president of the City Council and, before that, president of the
Board of Aldermen. And all of those positions, Green said, have
been designated as the one that should step up to acting mayor in
case of a vacancy.
</P>
<P>
   Green said he would join with major civic groups to campaign
against a charter revision. ``It's a fight we won't lose,'' he
said. ``The public will understand that it's simply wrong to change
the rules during the game _ wrong to move the fences in the 9th
inning because your team is losing.''
</P>
<P>
   The spice in this fight is that quite a few Democrats, including
many who have no fondness for Giuliani, will refrain from joining
Green's side.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Hevesi, a Democrat and the city comptroller, has said he
would support a change to the charter. Hevesi very much would like
to be mayor himself, and would rather run for an open seat than
have to unseat an incumbent, even one who has been in office for
only a year and who was put there under strange circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   Hevesi, who has explicitly aligned himself with many of
Giuliani's policies and approaches to governing, is widely thought
to be the mayor's preferred successor.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Vallone, another Democrat, who is the speaker of the City
Council and also a prospective mayoral candidate, agrees that the
succession rules should be changed, though he agrees with Green
that it is wrong to change the rules just because of the
personalities involved. His spokesman, Mike Clendinin, summarized
his stance Tuesday in significantly neutral fashion: ``It's a
legitimate issue for debate.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
