<SLUG> BC-MA-TEACHER-CERTIFY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PANEL SEEKS TOUGHER TEACHER RECERTIFICATION STANDARDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KATE ZERNIKE AND DOREEN IUDICA VIGUE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Conceding that a six-year old effort to improve
teacher quality has failed, Massachusetts officials plan to toughen
the requirements for educators when they renew their certification
every five years.
</P>
<P>
   The Joint Commission on Educator Preparation is proposing to
eliminate a controversial provision of the Education Reform Act
that requires recertifying teachers to complete 120 hours of
professional development courses. Some of those courses have been
dismissed even by supporters of reform as ``Mickey Mouse'' and a
waste of time.
</P>
<P>
   Teachers would still have to take courses to renew
certification. But the new plan shifts the focus from how many
hours teachers spend to the quality of programs.
</P>
<P>
   When the recertification provision was established with the
reform act in 1993, the state required only that teachers take
courses registered with the department of education. In one
celebrated fiasco, the department allowed teachers to sign up for a
professional development cruise aboard a luxury liner.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know there are many programs that are taken simply for
convenience, for getting the seat time,'' said the state's
Chancellor of Higher Education Stanley Z. Koplik. ``In the past,
anybody has been able to offer programs and call it teacher
preparation. What we want now is some quality control. The emphasis
is on quality, not quantity.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the new proposal, the number of course hours would be
reduced, but teachers could take only those courses that had been
examined and approved by the department, which would set specific
quality standards. School principals or superintendents would also
have to approve the courses, to make sure they are relevant and
meet the school's needs.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Gorrie, president of the state's largest teacher's union
said Tuesday the majority of teachers choose high quality courses
and ``another layer of bureaucracy'' is unnecessary to ensure that.
He also said if the proposal is approved by the state Board of
Education, money should be part of the plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some districts are strapped financially and even though they
get a bit of money for the programs, it's not always enough,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   While Gorrie agreed that higher quality programs are a good
idea, he warned that ``miring'' the process in ``approval details''
will not get anything accomplished.
</P>
<P>
   The recertification requirement came under fire almost as soon
as it was passed. But the complaints have increased over the past
year as the five year deadline has come closer. More than 65,000
educators must complete their recertification this year.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, nine veteran teachers filed a lawsuit challenging the
requirement, and arguing that the ``lifetime'' certification they
earned when they began working should be honored. If an injunction
is not granted by a judge this week, they could lose their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   The change proposed by the commission, made up of members of the
state boards of education and higher education, would not address
the main complaint of the lawsuit _ that teachers shouldn't have to
renew their certification at all. But it would eliminate some of
the chief complaints about recertification by making the programs
more relevant to reform.
</P>
<P>
   The commission also did not address whether the required number
of professional development points would increase or decrease.
</P>
<P>
   James A. Peyser, chairman of the state Board of Education, said
professional development programs offered by providers in the
future must focus on content knowledge for specific certifications,
and noted that greater emphasis should be placed on advanced
studies of topics.
</P>
<P>
   He also said that teachers should take courses on their own, not
just to satisfy recertification requirements, but to enrich
themselves as educators.
</P>
<P>
   ``Professional development does not exclusively and should not
exclusively be connected to points,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal made Tuesday would also require teachers to take
professional development courses in three of the five years in the
recertification cycle. Now, Koplik said, many teachers wait until
the last year before they begin taking courses, so end up taking
what is available, rather than what will improve their teaching.
</P>
<P>
   Educators would have to show how the courses they take are
linked to individual improvement, or to the improvement goals of
their school or district, and demonstrate that the courses they
have taken have improved their teaching, either through test scores
or evaluations.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal must be approved by the state board of education.
But as three members of the commission that made the proposal are
on the board, as is Koplik, it is expected to win easy approval.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
