<DOCNO> NYT19990615.0275 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-15 20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6538 &Cx1f; tth-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ART-NAZIS-MATISSE-SPI     06-15 0788
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-NAZIS-MATISSE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEATTLE ART MUSEUM RETURNING MATISSE PIECE STOLEN BY NAZIS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By REGINA HACKETT  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The Seattle Art Museum on Monday agreed to return a
Henri Matisse painting to the heirs of Paul Rosenberg, a Jewish art
dealer whose collection was stolen in France by the Nazis during
World War II.
</P>
<P>
   The museum board unanimously approved the decision Monday, more
than two years after the Rosenbergs claimed ownership of the 1927
oil painting titled ``Odalisque.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Elaine Rosenberg, widow of Paul Rosenberg's son,
Alexandre, and her sister-in-law, Rosenberg's daughter Micheline
Nanette Sinclair, expressed frustration last year that the museum
was taking so long to make a decision, they said through their New
York attorney Laura Hoguet they were happy with the result.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm entirely sympathetic with the Rosenbergs,'' said Mimi
Gates, SAM's director. ``But we had a responsibility to undertake
thorough and exhaustive research into the painting's ownership
history.''
</P>
<P>
   She said the museum had to be sure its Matisse, valued at more
than $2 million, was the one stolen and it had never been returned
to or sold by a Rosenberg heir.
</P>
<P>
   ``We said from the beginning we'd do the right thing, and that's
what we're doing.''
</P>
<P>
   The museum had research conducted by its curatorial staff,
independent French scholars and the Holocaust Art Restitution
Project (HARP) in Washington, D.C., which was created by the B'nai
B'rith Klutznick National Jewish Museum to form a database and
investigate Jewish cultural losses. All evidence, said Gates,
points to the legitimacy of the Rosenbergs' claim. ``Once that was
determined, we acted quickly,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   SAM was the first U.S. museum sued for restitution of artwork
lost through German looting during World War II. Last year, the
Chicago Art Institute was involved in a similar case, but the work
in question - a Degas pastel landscape - was only a promised gift
and was owned by drug company heir Daniel C. Searle.
</P>
<P>
   When confronted by the claims of the heirs of Friedrich and
Louise Gutmann, both murdered by the Germans during the war, Searle
said he refused to be extorted. Last August, on the eve of going to
court, Searle settled, ceding half interest in the landscape to the
Gutmann heirs and half to the Art Institute, which acquired the
Degas by paying the Gutmanns half of the its value.
</P>
<P>
   Gates said the Rosenbergs expressed no interest in working out a
deal to let the painting stay in Seattle. ``They wanted their
painting back,'' she said. ``We're honoring that.'' The museum now
owns one painting, two prints and a sculpture by Matisse.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Vineberg, director of the American Jewish Committee of
Greater Seattle, praised the museum for its ``precedent-setting act
of moral courage that will go a long way in helping to resolve
future and pending cases in the United States involving artwork
stolen by the Nazis during World War II.''
</P>
<P>
   Seattle collector Prentice Bloedel bought the painting in 1954
from New York's Knoedler Gallery and hung it in his living room
until it was donated after his death to the Seattle Art Museum in
1991.
</P>
<P>
   The location of ``Odalisqaue'' came to light after it was
reproduced as ``whereabouts unknown'' in Hector Feliciano's 1995
book, ``The Lost Museum: The Nazi Conspiracy to Steal the World's
Greatest Works of Art.'' Bloedel's grandson, the New York artist
Bing Wright, saw the painting in Feliciano's book and notified the
Rosenbergs.
</P>
<P>
   Art collector and museum trustee Virginia Wright, daughter of
the late Prentice Bloedel, said Monday that she's glad the issue is
resolved. She said she's sure the return of the painting will
create no tax problems for her parents' estate.
</P>
<P>
   ``The museum is doing absolutely the right thing,'' she said.
``My parents would have hated the publicity, but I'm sure they
would be in favor of returning the Matisse to the rightful
owners.'' She said her parents couldn't have known about the
painting's real history. ``When they bought it, the Knoedler
Gallery had a great reputation. In those days, if you went to a
reputable gallery, you assumed the gallery would stand by its
material.''
</P>
<P>
   SAM attorney Stuart Dunwoody said the museum will continue its
suit against the Knoedler Gallery for ``lying about the painting's
provenance and breach of warranty.''
</P>
<P>
   The case is slated for trial in Seattle Jan. 3, but Dunwoody
said he intends to file a motion for summary judgment against
Knoedler in the fall. Lewis Clayton, attorney for Knoedler, said in
response that he doesn't think the museum has a viable claim
against his client.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
