<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-15 20:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6548 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-GRAVES-ART-2TA     06-15 0932
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-GRAVES-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOUR REVEALS EXTENT OF SERB ATROCITES IN ONE PART OF KOSOVO  
</HEADLINE>
  (See also KOSOVO-RDP, KOSOVO-MILOSEVIC) 
(ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Photos
are being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By JOHN KIFNER with IAN FISHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DJAKOVICA, Yugoslavia _ The Serbs' most brutal force in their
campaign to drive out the ethnic Albanian majority from Kosovo fell
on this city and a swath of villages around it in the shadow of the
Accursed Mountains. On Tuesday, in a landscape of gravesites,
burned homes, toppled mosque minarets and smashed shops, it became
clear just how ferocious that campaign had been.
</P>
<P>
   As German soldiers in the NATO force secured the highway running
northwest from Prizren and Italian troops moved here southeast from
Pec, foreign journalists were allowed into the area for the first
time since the Serbian drive began in late March. What they found
confirmed _ often with uncanny precision _ were refugees' widely
reported accounts. But the actual sight was nonetheless shocking.
</P>
<P>
   Suspected mass graves were located by NATO officials Tuesday on
the sites of previously reported massacres in Velika Krusa (called
Krush-e-Mahde in Albanian) and Bella Crkva. Residents told
reporters of other gravesites, and it seemed certain that many
additional sites would be found.
</P>
<P>
   All along the highway and up back roads, farmhouses,
particularly substantial ones, were charred and broken.
</P>
<P>
   In Djakovica, the Old Town, a picturesque Ottoman-era
marketplace was gutted, the shops nothing but a jumble of fragments
of orange roof tiles. Bullet holes were everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Only a few clumps of people walked the ruined streets of
Djakovica, most for the first time in two and a half months. For
they had been hiding, ducking through holes knocked in the walls of
interconnecting houses and gardens to escape Serbian raids. Tens of
thousand of residents fled in the first few days of burning and
killing.
</P>
<P>
   But the relief was tempered with fear.
</P>
<P>
   More than 1,000 men had been taken away by the Serbs, residents
said, often breaking into tears as they approached foreign
reporters in hopes of finding information, and no one knows what
happened to them.
</P>
<P>
   There are several reasons the Serbs were so harsh here. Almost
entirely Albanian, Djakovica has long been a center of Albanian
nationalism. The whole region, known as Has on both sides of the
border, is regarded by the interrelated Albanian clans as one
entity.
</P>
<P>
   The Kosovo Liberation Army bases are on the other side of the
craggy mountains, in lawless northern Albania, and their supply
routes run down the mountain passes into the valleys here. Thus the
town has enormous strategic importance.
</P>
<P>
   Tactically, the area lies on a main highway close to the border.
In the Serbs' well-planned and organized campaign, mass killings in
the first days spread terror, emptying villages near the borders,
encouraging others to follow on the routes now cleared.
</P>
<P>
   Until NATO began its security operations on Saturday, more than
900,000 Albanians had fled over the borders, and an additional
500,000 were driven from their houses, living in forests and
mountains, the alliance said.
</P>
<P>
   The evidence of the Serb's atrocities was spread across the
countryside.
</P>
<P>
   In Mala Krusa (Krush-e-Vogel to the Albanian-speaking
villagers), northwest of the southern city of Prizren, a farmhouse
with 21 bodies on the bottom floor was secured by NATO peacekeepers
on Tuesday morning. The bodies _ 15 in one room and six in another
_ were badly burned, witnesses said, and just one skeleton appeared
intact.
</P>
<P>
   Bullet holes pocked the outside walls in a yard-high ring around
the house. At least one body belonged to a child, and another to a
woman.
</P>
<P>
   Across the main road, in Velika Krusa, German forces inspected a
patch of churned earth, perhaps 10 yards by 20 yards, next to a
small cemetery. The grave was pointed out by Kosovo Liberation Army
soldiers, who said up to 100 people were buried there after a
massacre in late March.
</P>
<P>
   To the northwest several miles, in Bela Crkva, villagers pointed
out seven sites where they said 64 people were killed in a massacre
early in the morning on March 25, the day after NATO began bombing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nazmi is here,'' said Teki Zhuniqi, 41, a villager who helped
bury the bodies after the Serb police had left the town.
</P>
<P>
   Zhuniqi pointed slightly to the right and added: ``Nesim is
here. They are brothers. Shundeti is here, then Agon. Then it's
Etem and Etem's son. I don't know his name.
</P>
<P>
   ``The youngest was 14. The oldest was 82, in this grave here.''
</P>
<P>
   He stood at the site where he said villagers _ working at night
using small flashlights hidden under their jackets so that the
Serbs would not spot them _ buried 39 men three days after the
massacre. Over two nights the villagers buried 62 people in the
area.
</P>
<P>
   Two others, wounded in the massacre, died later at another
village, witnesses said.
</P>
<P>
   Zhuniqi and other witnesses who had been interviewed earlier in
Albania said the Serb police and soldiers stormed the town with
tanks and artillery at 3 a.m. after the bombing started. The
villagers fled to a stream next to a railway bridge. Zhuniqi said
the soldiers followed stragglers to the stream, separated the men
from the women and began firing. Thirty-nine men died next to the
stream as Zhuniqi and 12 others hid in a wheat field 150 yards
away.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a hill of dead bodies,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   An additional six men, including the local Muslim clergyman,
fled into a ditch several hundred yards down the railroad tracks
but were found and are now buried there.
</P>
<P>
   An additonal 12 people _ seven children, four women and two men
_ died on a slope further down the stream.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, near that grave, Zhuniqi and a friend, Xhafer Gashi,
41, picked through the children's pink snow boots, a child's
colorful shirt and a baby's bottle, still full. There was one
survivor, a 2-year-old.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we came at midnight,'' Zhuniqi recounted, ``he was
between his mother and father. He was crying. How can there be
anything more evil than this? Sometimes I can't sleep because I saw
so many dead bodies.''
</P>
<P>
   In the town itself, villagers said, they buried three people _
one man in a wheelchair and his wife, and another man missing a leg
_ who could not run when the Serbs attacked. On Tuesday, villagers
uncovered the remains of one man, burned and wrapped in a plastic
bag, at the request of a foreign television crew.
</P>
<P>
   Gashi said he could not believe the Serbs' explanation that the
war began merely to search out and destroy the guerrillas. Simply
too much was destroyed, too many civilians killed, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In Bela Crkva, where 300 families lived, nearly every house
needs to be completely rebuilt. The mosque was bombed, its 81-foot
minaret crumbled in a heap in the front. Dogs and livestock rot
where they were shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``That dead cow was not in the KLA,'' Gashi said.
</P>
<P>
   Journalists roaming through the area found Albanians offering to
lead them to other, less well-known death sites. In Guske, east of
Djakovica, Mark Kqiraj, 32, led the way up a long dirt road up to
his family's spacious farm, which had been used as a Serb barracks,
then along a path to a mound of freshly turned earth he said held
the bodies of 11 of his relatives. In Koronice, villagers showed
the skeletons of five people killed in a house.
</P>
<P>
   In a cemetery on the edge of Djakovica are about 150 hastily dug
graves marked by sticks or wooden stakes _ some marked not with a
name, but only a village _ where people tried to give a proper
burial to what villagers said were victims of the Serbs dug up from
mass graves or found on the street. Some of the graves have no
marker.
</P>
<P>
   In Djakovica itself, nearly all the stores were smashed and
houses burned throughout the city, but the heaviest damage was in
the narrow, cobblestone streets of the traditional marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the old part _ antique _ all the stores were filled
with things,'' said Pranvera Daija, pushing a baby carriage on the
street for the first time since March. `'This was the most
beautiful part of all.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a ruin, now, with every shop gutted and the very top of
the central mosque's minaret, where the muezzin calls to prayer,
collapsed, people said, by an exceedingly accurate rocket-propelled
grenade. As in Bosnia, the cultural artifacts of the Ottoman empire
_ even the beautiful bridges and architecture _were particular
targets for the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the first night, this place was burned,'' Petrit Daija, her
husband, said, beginning the story, told by both refugees and those
who remained of how the Serbs had swept from neighborhood to
neighborhood, killing, looting and burning.
</P>
<P>
   Like others who managed to stay, Mrs. Daija said, they kept
constantly on the alert and escaped ``from one house to another
through holes we made in the walls.''
</P>
<P>
   A friend, Linditi Rudi, also pushing a baby carraige, put in,
``and by keeping our children's mouths shut like this,'' clamping
her hand over her lips.
</P>
<P>
   The house where Hani Hoxha's family was killed was exactly as
the old man had described it to a reporter in Albania weeks ago,
except of course, the walls were now scorched and tumbled where the
Serbs had burned it down, the car they had put in front of the gate
in a futile attempt to block the entrance was rusted out and the
yard was overgrown with weeds and shaggy roses.
</P>
<P>
   In late April, in a cafe in the Albanian capital Tirana, called
Snow White, after the mountaintops here, not the fairytale
princess, Hoxha had taken this reporter's notebook and
painstakingly diagrammed the family compound where they had sought
refuge, and the places where 18 people were slaughtered by the
Serbs while he listened in hiding, wedged between two buildings.
</P>
<P>
   It was all there. In the corner was the pool hall, so riddled
with automatic weapons fire that a corner of the pool table was
chewed off, and the charred basement underneath where a dozen
people had been sleeping and were slain. There was the car, an old
Zastava, plate DJ-295-90, still parked fruitlessly in front of the
gate.
</P>
<P>
   And there was the burned-out building where his wife, two
daughters and a six-year-old granddaughter were executed, just as
he had so carefully drawn.
</P>
<P>
   The Carrapatok neighborhood around his house was almost
completely empty, its shops closed with only a few cats wandering
the streets. But on a side street a few blocks away were perhaps
the last victims here of the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday morning, Nazmi Haqibeqiri, 57, went to have coffee as
was his habit with his elderly neighbors, Nreke Nushi and his wife,
Marije. He found their bodies, each with five bullets, on the
bloody floor of the basement.
</P>
<P>
   Nushi, he said, had been forced by the Serbs to build fake
bridges out of pine boards and plastic sheeting in hopes of fooling
the NATO bombers, in his little odd-jobs factory behind his house.
Because of the factory, he said, it appeared Serb soldiers thought
he must have money and tried to rob him.
</P>
<P>
   Haqibeqiri called the police, still controlled by the Serbs,
twice to report the crime but nothing happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said just take the bodies and bury them,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-15-99 2019EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990615.0280 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-15 20:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6550 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-RDP-ART-NYT &LR;      06-15 1237
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-RDP-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YUGOSLAV MILITARY MEETS NATO DEADLINE FOR WITHDRAWING FROM KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo and map are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By STEVEN LEE MYERS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia _ The Yugoslav military largely complied
with NATO's demands to leave much of Kosovo by midnight Tuesday,
with thousands of soldiers involved in President Slobodan
Milosevic's war here for more than a year withdrawing on tanks,
trucks and tractors.
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials said that Yugoslavia's Serb-dominated army and
interior police had, so far, withdrawn nearly half of the 40,000
troops who had been amassed in Kosovo at the height of the
conflict. The troops included 12,000 in a region from Djakovica to
Gnjilane to Pristina that NATO had said on June 9 would be required
to pull out within six days after Yugoslav generals accepted terms
for ending the allied air war. The officials said the withdrawal
had accelerated in the last 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
   With the withdrawals, NATO extended its control over nearly a
third of Kosovo, but tensions remained and security was by no means
certain.
</P>
<P>
   NATO troops have had few confrontations with retreating Yugoslav
forces, but on Tuesday British paratroopers arrested five members
of the Kosovo Liberation Army, the Kosovo Albanian rebel group, who
were accused of shooting and killing a Serb in a town near the
capital.
</P>
<P>
   The presence of the rebels has become particularly nettlesome
for NATO. Although the terms for ending the war called on the
rebels to disband, NATO has done little to stop its members from
taking on more and more trappings of official power. That has
prompted many of Kosovo's Serbian residents to flee along with the
withdrawing troops.
</P>
<P>
   Across the province, Yugoslav army troops were on the move
Tuesday in enormous, bedraggled, but evidently organized convoys.
By afternoon, they abandoned their checkpoints around the airfield
southwest of Pristina, after blocking access to it for three days.
Like NATO's commanders, they left control of the airfield to the
200 Russians who arrived unexpectedly on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``They all left,'' a Russian soldier said at the airport's gate,
guarded by two armored personnel carriers.
</P>
<P>
   As the deadline came and went, Serbian soldiers could still be
seen in several cities, including Urosevac and Pristina, and NATO
officials acknowledged that not every last soldier or police
officer was likely to leave. Early Wednesday morning, a large
contingent remained at a headquarters in the center of Pristina,
and there was some gunfire heard throughout the evening. But NATO
officials said the Yugoslav authorities had made a good faith
effort to hand over control of Kosovo to NATO troops.
</P>
<P>
   ``There may well be the odd straggler or broken down vehicle,''
said Lt. Col. Robin Clifford, spokesman for NATO's Kosovo
peacekeeping force, ``but that we are quite content with.''
</P>
<P>
   There were reports that Serbs on their way out of Kosovo were
torching buildings owned by Kosovo Albanians. Serbian soldiers
carrying gas cans could be seen moving through the village.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday evening, two Kosovo Albanians were shot and killed and
another two were wounded in a Pristina neighborhood called Suncani
Breg after arguing with a group of Serbian civilians on a
basketball court.
</P>
<P>
   Outside Pristina, a rocket-propelled grenade was fired near
where the Russian troops have stationed themselves. NATO officials
said they had no information on the incident, but a spokesman for
the Russians blamed it on the KLA.
</P>
<P>
   On a rural road near Kosovo Polje, a Serbian village west of
Pristina, Veljko Bangur helped his sister load a sofa, chairs and
other belongings into a tractor on Tuesday. He said it was no
longer safe to stay now that the Yugoslav army was withdrawing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are leaving because we are afraid of the people who kill _
NATO'' and the KLA, he said.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. refugee officials said they have grown increasingly worried
that the end of the war is creating a new refugee crisis. Dennis
McNamara, the special envoy of the U.N. High Commissioner for
Refugees, said NATO should move quickly to provide assurances to
the Serbs that it is safe for them to stay.
</P>
<P>
   ``The return of refugees to Kosovo must not lead to a new
refugee exodus,'' he said at a news conference Tuesday in
Pristina's Grand Hotel. ``And we're starting to see signs that that
is happening.''
</P>
<P>
   Seeking to provide such assurances, the commander of the
peacekeeping force, Lt. Gen. Michael Jackson of Britain, held a
news conference Tuesday for Serbian journalists and pledged that
NATO would be evenhanded in overseeing the province.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do understand the concerns of the Serb population,'' he
said. ``I've made it clear to my soldiers that they must share my
concern.''
</P>
<P>
   Serbian leaders in Kosovo were not convinced. Vojislav Vukcevic,
the secretary general of the local branch of the Serbian Renewal
Movement, a political party, said the peacekeeping effort is
senseless if the Serbs who stay are not protected. ``Their mandate
is to implement the security and safety for both Serbs and
Albanians,'' he said of the NATO troops.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of the agreement for ending NATO's air strikes,
the Yugoslav army and interior police forces must withdraw entirely
by Sunday. At that point, NATO will control all of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   NATO and U.N. officials have already begun discussions about
establishing some sort of civilian political and police authority
to govern the province, but for now there is none.
</P>
<P>
   Officials acknowledged that there were limits to NATO's control.
``You can't have a soldier on every street corner, in every hamlet
and in every village,'' Clifford, the NATO spokesman, said on
Tuesday.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   After 78 days and tens of thousands of NATO bombs, the Yugoslav
army units that left on Tuesday remained, for the most part,
defiant and proud.
</P>
<P>
   In the evening, a three- to four-mile convoy of army vehicles _
including tanks, armored personnel carriers, troop transports and
trucks hauling all manner of military equipment _ rumbled northwest
on the road toward Serbia from the Drenica Valley, scene of some of
the heaviest fighting in the war against the rebels.
</P>
<P>
   One armored combat vehicle was festooned with balloons, while
another carried a sign saying ``Taxi'' and half a dozen soldiers on
its top. Others bore large pin-ups, including one of Marilyn
Monroe. Still another carried a street sign for the predominantly
Albanian city of Malisevo. Serbian flags flew from all of them.
</P>
<P>
   The size of the convoy _ and the number of heavy weapons _
appeared to undercut NATO's statements that it had seriously ground
down the Yugoslav army. NATO officials said the army had withdrawn
37 tanks, 65 artillery pieces and 115 armored personnel carriers in
just the first phase of the withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
   As the convoy passed Kosovo Polje, a village sacred to Serbs as
the scene of the epic battle against the Turks in 1389, people
gathered on the streets to salute the withdrawing troops. Soldiers
responded with their traditional three-fingered salute. The scene
mirrored the reception received by NATO troops as they passed
through Albanian villages, except that the crowds were smaller and
more subdued.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
