<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-2000-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE TERMS CLINTON AFFAIR `INEXCUSABLE' 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Vice President Al Gore says that President
Clinton's extramarital affair with Monica Lewinsky was
``inexcusable'' and that the president had lied to him, just as he
had lied to everyone else.
</P>
<P>
   ``What he did was inexcusable, and particularly as a father, I
felt that it was terribly wrong, obviously,'' Gore said in an
interview with Diane Sawyer of ABC News. The comments, to be
broadcast on ``20/20'' on Wednesday night, were the vice
president's most extensive yet on the topic of Clinton's affair.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the president lied to him, Gore said, ``Certainly the
impression that he gave me and the others that he worked with was
not the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he believed Clinton last year when he wagged his finger
and said he ``did not have sexual relations with that woman, Ms.
Lewinsky,'' Gore said, ``I didn't like that moment at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere in the half-hour interview, Gore said he wanted to
expand the gays-in-the-military policy that was begun by Clinton to
make it easier for homosexuals to serve. ``I'd like to see the
policy implemented differently,'' Gore said. ``I don't think
there's been enough compassion in that policy.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore clearly did not relish the questions about the president's
affair and dodged some of them. ``You can imagine how I felt,'' he
said at one point, without elaboration and without emotion.
</P>
<P>
   But being broadcast on the day of Gore's announcement for
president, the comments come as part of a larger effort by the vice
president to separate himself from the Clinton scandals.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's announcement on Wednesday will highlight his devotion as
a husband and father. Throughout the ABC interview, he and his
wife, Tipper, held hands.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Gore was reportedly outraged at the president's behavior,
but she was less emphatic in the interview, saying she was ``very
surprised.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Sawyer asked her what she would have done if she had been in
Hillary Rodham Clinton's shoes. ``I would _ I don't _ I can't
imagine it being me,'' Mrs. Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Sawyer noted that the vice president had said last year that
Clinton would not admit to lying as part of a censure deal because
misleading statements were different from actually lying. She asked
Gore: ``Is that the article of faith that you want to run your
presidential campaign on?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, no, of course not,'' Gore answered quickly. Those remarks,
he said, were in the context of the partisan impeachment process.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-15-99 2025EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
