<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-EARTHQUAKE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRONG EARTHQUAKE HITS CENTRAL MEXICO  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By SAM DILLON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ A strong earthquake rattled central Mexico
Tuesday, injuring dozens of people and killing at least one woman
as buildings collapsed in the capital of Puebla state, east of
Mexico City, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   Landslides blocked several rural highways in Puebla and Oaxaca
states, and some bridges were reported damaged, television and
radio reports said.
</P>
<P>
   In Mexico City, the quake was felt strongly. Thousands of
residents fled into the streets as buildings swayed and the ground
roared, but damage appeared to be minor. Phone service was
interrupted in much of the city for several hours.
</P>
<P>
   The National Earthquake Information Center in Golden, Colorado
measured the quake at 6.5 on the Richter scale. Mexico's National
Seismological Center put it at 6.7.
</P>
<P>
   Both services recorded the quake at the same moment, 3:42 p.m.,
and located its epicenter in a rural area 125 miles southeast of
Mexico City, along a volcanic border dividing Oaxaca and Puebla
states.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities in Oaxaca said they had been unable to establish
communication with Huajuapan, the rural county northeast of the
state capital, that was the quake's epicenter.
</P>
<P>
   The worst damage reported was in the city center of Puebla, 55
miles east of Mexico City, where a 45-year-old woman was killed in
the collapse of an unidentified building, said reports on TV
Azteca.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the Puebla Red Cross reported that the Puebla
City Hall collapsed, trapping a dozen municipal workers. The Red
Cross said a University of Puebla building that had housed
classrooms and the rector's office also was badly damaged.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities at the Volkswagen plant in Puebla, the world's only
supplier of the Volkswagen Beetle and the New Beetle, suspended
production during the quake and ordered the plant inspected for
damage.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-15-99 2028EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990615.0286 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-15 20:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6564 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-GUNS-HNS &LR;      06-15 1010
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-GUNS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON URGES HOUSE NOT TO WEAKEN NEW GUN CONTROL LEGISLATION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By NANCY MATHIS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Declaring America's heart and soul on the line,
President Clinton on Tuesday urged the House to embrace background
checks at gun shows and flea markets and resist weakening new gun
control legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton stepped up his rhetoric as Republican leaders adopted a
new strategy that may make it easier for the House to defeat
legislation for a background check for felony and mental illness
records when guns are sold at gun shows and flea markets _ two
areas exempted from 1994 gun control legislation.
</P>
<P>
   The president cited a new Justice Department report that shows
the Brady bill's background check stopped 400,000 illegal handgun
sales in the 5{ years since the hotly contested system became law.
</P>
<P>
   He also surrounded himself in the Rose Garden with women members
of Congress and families of crime victims. He urged women, whom
polls show overwhelming support gun control efforts, to make their
voices heard on the gun control issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is too important an issue to be decided by strong-arm
lobbying tactics in Washington. The heart and soul of America is on
the line,'' Clinton said, prior to leaving for Europe where he will
attend an economic summit.
</P>
<P>
   The House will begin debate Thursday on the legislation.
</P>
<P>
   House Republican leaders this week agreed to separate the gun
control issues from a juvenile justice reform bill. A Senate
version, passed with Vice President Al Gore breaking the tie vote,
would extend the Brady bill, which requires a background check
within three business days.
</P>
<P>
   Michigan Rep. John Dingell, a key Democratic ally of the pro-gun
forces, will offer an alternative for a 24-hour background check.
If the background check could not be performed within 24 hours, the
purchaser would receive the weapon anyway. The Senate rejected a
similar provision last month after a public outcry.
</P>
<P>
   Dingell's effort now has the blessing of GOP Whip Tom DeLay,
R-Texas, and lends an aura of bipartisanship.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the changing politics of the gun debate, House
Majority Leader Dick Armey of Texas told Reuters that it would be
hard for Democrats to make gun control a campaign issue next year,
if Democrats took the lead in passing weaker laws.
</P>
<P>
   Armey said he wanted to see Dingell's final draft but said ``it
is not inconceivable'' that he will vote for it.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton accused the National Rifle Association of being ``wrong,
wrong, wrong'' on every argument it made against the Brady bill in
1994 and said the group tries to frighten its members with
untruths.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want every member of Congress to think about this before
they vote on Thursday. What did they say six years ago? They said
the Brady bill threatened the right of citizens to own firearms.
Well, today we know the Second Amendment, hunting and sport
shooting are alive and well in America, just as alive and well as
they were in 1994,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   The president said the gun lobby argued in 1994 that the Brady
bill would not affect crime rates, yet gun crimes have fallen by 23
percent. And, the opponents argued that background checks would
have little effect because criminals don't buy guns at stores, yet
the law has stopped hundreds of thousands of such sales, Clinton
said.
</P>
<P>
   He cited the new Justice Department report that showed 400,000
gun sales were stopped because of the background check. Two-thirds
of those sales would have been to people indicted or convicted of
felony crimes, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I'll say again: Every single red flag they threw up about
all the danger and all the burden and all the problems this would
be to gun owners was wrong, wrong, wrong,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Wayne LaPierre, executive vice president of the NRA, insisted
the gun lobby has always supported an instant background check and
blasted the administration for failing to prosecute those felons
who attempt to illegally buy handguns.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the White House to somehow try to characterize the NRA as
opposed to the instant check system is simply a lie,'' LaPierre
told CNN.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what they are really after is trying to dismantle this
great American freedom, the Second Amendment, piece by piece, and
it has nothing to do with crime or even checks, which the NRA has
always supported the instant check,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   LaPierre recalled Clinton's remarks recently in which he said he
supported gun registration. Clinton, during a television interview,
also said gun registration would never pass Congress.
</P>
<P>
   LaPierre also chastised the vice president and president for
repeatedly misstating the age law. Both Gore and Clinton said they
support raising the age limit to purchase handguns from 18 to 21
but 21 alreadyis the law, LaPierre said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton stressed he supported increasing the age limit for
possessing a handgun from 18 to 21 as well as mandatory sales of
child safety locks with each handgun.
</P>
<P>
   Polls show widespread public support for all the
administration's gun control provisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``About the only ones who are against it still are the NRA and
its allies in Congress. It seems that every day, they try another
procedural or rhetorical trick to confuse everyone and avoid
responsibility. These are the same kind of tactical smoke screens
they threw up six years ago,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton maintained the times have changed for the gun lobby.
He said America is in a different place than it was six years ago
because of the series of school shootings such as the deaths of 15
at Colorado's Columbine High School and the average daily shooting
deaths of two to three children that never make the national news.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want the House to reject these bills and pass legislation
that will strengthen, not weaken, the Brady law. I want us to honor
the sacrifices of those people in Littleton, Colorado, not turn our
backs on them,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
