<DOCNO> NYT19990615.0287 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-15 20:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6566 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GA-RAPE-DNA-NYT &LR;      06-15 1075
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GA-RAPE-DNA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DNA TEST FREES MAN AFTER 16 YEARS IN PRISON 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By DAVID FIRESTONE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JONESBORO, Ga. _ Just before he was sentenced to life in prison
for a rape he did not commit, Calvin Johnson Jr. told the judge
that his moment of redemption would one day come.
</P>
<P>
   ``With God as my witness, I have been falsely accused of these
crimes,'' he said in court in November 1983. ``I did not commit
them. I'm an innocent man, and I just pray in the name of Jesus
Christ that all this truth will be brought out, the truth will
eventually be brought out.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, nearly 16 years later, Johnson's truth was finally
brought out. After a DNA test _ unavailable in 1983 _ proved that
Johnson could not have committed the crime, a different judge
signed the papers that released him into a hazy spring afternoon
and the arms of his family. He gamely shook the hand of the
prosecutor who put him into Hancock State Prison, thanked God and
his lawyers for the blessings of freedom, and wondered where he
would find a job.
</P>
<P>
   But Johnson is more than just the latest of 61 prisoners in the
United States exonerated because of DNA evidence. In many ways, his
journey into prison was as dramatic as his hasty exit, revealing
the racial underpinnings of so many convictions in Georgia and the
rest of the Deep South, and raising questions about how many other
prisoners might also have lost their liberty on the basis of thin
witness identifications.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, who is black, was 25 when he was convicted by an
all-white jury here in Clayton County, a suburban area 30 miles
south of Atlanta that was the setting for Tara in ``Gone With the
Wind.'' The jury took only 45 minutes to convict him, rejecting the
testimony of four black witnesses who supported his alibi, but
accepting the courtroom identification of the white victim, even
though she had failed to pick him out of a lineup. She had
originally picked him out of photo array, where his picture had
been placed because he matched the general physical description of
the suspect and had a 1981 burglary conviction.
</P>
<P>
   The jury even set aside the testimony of an expert from the
Georgia State Crime Lab, who testified that a ``negroid pubic
hair'' found on the victim's bedsheet could not have been
Johnson's, based on a microscopic comparison. Robert Keller, who
prosecuted the case, convinced the jury that the expert's analysis
did not mean anything, saying the pubic hair might have become
attached to the sheet at a laundromat, or that the victim might
have somehow have picked it up in a public bathroom, mixing with
black people.
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks after Johnson was convicted in Clayton County, he
was put on trial in Atlanta for a rape that had similar
characteristics. Although the same witnesses testified for and
against him in both trials, the jury in Atlanta contained both
blacks and whites. He was acquitted on that rape, even though the
jury knew he had just been convicted of rape a few weeks before.
</P>
<P>
   ``This case is just part of the legacy of a court system in
Georgia that has excluded, and still excludes, African-Americans
from participation,'' said Stephen Bright, director of the Southern
Center for Human Rights, which provides legal representation for
inmates and poor defendants. ``The all-white jury in Clayton County
gave no credit to his testimony or the testimony of his four
witnesses. And of course the racially mixed jury came to a
dramatically different conclusion, and now we see that it was
right. What worries you is, there's no telling how many people
there are in the Georgia prison system convicted by all-white
juries who didn't have any DNA evidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, at least six Georgia prisoners who were executed
were condemned by all-white juries, Bright said, and hundreds more
were convicted on that basis.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson was freed through the work of Peter Neufeld and Barry
Scheck, two well-known New York lawyers who served on the O.J.
Simpson defense team and whose organization, the Innocence Project,
has now helped to exonerate 36 prisoners around the country through
DNA evidence. Of those, Johnson served the longest term before
being released. Standing on the courthouse steps with his client
Tuesday, Neufeld gave credit to Keller, now the district attorney
of Clayton County, for willingly turning over the vaginal swab
taken from the victim so that it could be matched with Johnson's
DNA, and not challenging the results.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not every DA has been as willing to do this, and we hope this
will be a model for other DAs throughout the state of Georgia,''
Neufeld said. ``This case hopefully will be a watershed event for
the people of Georgia to realize how unreliable eyewitness
identification can be.''
</P>
<P>
   But even though Keller was gracious in agreeing to Johnson's
release _ at one point extending his hand to Johnson in the
courtroom and saying, ``I'm sorry this happened'' _ he said he
would not have done anything differently as prosecutor, and denied
that race had anything to do with the verdict.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't feel good when something like this happens,'' he
said in an interview. ``It makes you go back and re-examine your
essence, how you deal with your fellow man, how you handled the
case. But I don't think anyone did anything wrong here. I dealt
with him the way I would have wanted to be dealt with.'' He added
that his office was unable to locate the victim in the case.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, who held a small New Testament in his hand as the judge
signed the order, said he bore no bitterness toward Keller, the
victim or the legal system. ``Bitterness will just destroy you,''
he said. But he added that he knew when he saw the all-white jury
in 1983 that he would never be acquitted. On three occasions,
Johnson rejected offers of parole because he would not sign an
admission of guilt.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, who holds a bachelor's degree in mass communications
from Clark Atlanta University, said his religious faith got him
through each day of those 16 years, never allowing him to despair.
Now, he said, he was only looking forward, not back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've spent the last 16 years working for free, and now I need
a job,'' said Johnson, 41, who had worked as a courier. And with
that, he and his 70-year-old father got in a car and drove to a
hospital to see his mother, who suffered a stroke four months ago.
She had not been told in advance that he was a free man.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
