A6568 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BAPTIST-NOTEBOOK-COX     06-15 0624
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAPTIST-NOTEBOOK-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Baptist convention notebook: PETA protests fast food speaker
 &HT;    By Gayle White
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ With protesters near the Georgia Dome proclaiming that
``Jesus was a vegetarian,'' Chick-Fil-A-King Truett Cathy welcomed
Southern Baptists to Atlanta on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Cathy left a little stuffed cow on the podium from the company's
``Eat More Chicken'' advertising campaign. It quickly became known
as the ``holy cow.''
</P>
<P>
   The protesters, from People for the Ethical Treatment of
Animals, included a man dressed as Jesus.
</P>
<P>
   PETA also has its message on a billboard that greeted Baptists
as they arrived for the convention.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of billboards, by the beginning of the convention, more
than 5,000 people had called a toll-free number appearing on
billboards and included in television, radio and newspaper
advertisements sponsored by the Southern Baptist Convention. The
campaign is part of ``Arms Around Atlanta,'' a joint effort of the
Southern Baptist North American Mission Board, the Georgia Baptist
Convention and several local Baptist associations.
</P>
<P>
   Southern Baptists, who have a reputation as tee-totalers, were
asked to go on the record with abstinence Tuesday by signing cards
pledging not to use alcohol or illegal drugs. Pushing the effort
was the Rev. Ted Stone, a North Carolina preacher who once served
four years in prison for shooting a man. Stone was hooked on
amphetamines at the time. ``We're trying to reach out and convince
people that a sober, self-controlled lifestyle is the best,'' he
said. Stone walked across the country twice, Washington to L.A. in
1996 and San Francisco ito Virginia Beach in 1998, to promote
sobriety.
</P>
<P>
   The Alpharetta, Ga.-based North American Mission Board of the
Southern Baptist Convention is unveiling a high-tech ``Vision
Center'' today. The center, a 5,000 square foot, $1.2 million
facility housed in the board's headquarters promises ``a phenomenal
interactive educational theme-park experience'' that propel
visitors ``through a global time capsule of past and present
mission fields.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Garner Clark from Autaugaville, Ala. always enjoys
attending the annual meeting of the Southern Baptist Convention.
``It's a chance for preachers to get preached to,'' Garner said
Tuesday. And that's good news for members of Garner's church. They
``always tell me my preaching improves when I come home from these
conventions,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The woman whose voice you couldn't quite hear during a concert
at Centennial Park Tuesday night was Pamela Valle of Bedford, Tex.
She was to take part in the evening event but lost her voice after
getting caught in thunderstorms that moved across Atlanta Monday
afternoon. Valle, who is the secretary-treasurer of the Conference
of Southern Baptist Evangelists, decided to take part in the
concert anyway. ``I'll just be lip-synching,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Hoyle is spending some of his free time in Atlanta,
trying to make a good impression. Hoyle, pastor of Sharon Baptist
Church in Rural Retreat, Va., says he's getting to know people from
Atlanta that he meets in downtown hotels and restaurants. ``I want
people to see Southern Baptists as spiritual people who really care
about others,'' he said Tuesday. ``People are suprised when we
don't grab them and tell them they are going to hell.''
</P>
<P>
   Baptists and others who want to keep up with the Southern
Baptist Convention from outside the Georgia Dome can log onto a
live webcast: www.namb.net/resources/convention99
</P>
<P>
   Gayle White writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
