<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-NO-COD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAPE RESTAURANTS FEAR EFFECT OF US COD-FISHING BAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ELLEN O'BRIEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHATHAM, Mass. _ Summer is here, and that means one thing: Pack
the car with beach blankets, binoculars, and bait and rods and head
to Cape ...Pollack?
</P>
<P>
   It may not sound as sweet, and many sea captains and restaurant
owners say pollack doesn't hold up as well as codfish as the
centerpiece of a Fishermen's Platter, but a federal crackdown on
cod fishing due to start in July has plenty of people predicting
that fresh cod will be as scarce as affordable housing for the
summer help.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the New England Fishery Management Council say a
30-day moratorium on cod is needed so that the tasty
bottom-dwelling fish have a chance to spawn without being trapped
in a cycle of overfishing that threatens the industry and the
species.
</P>
<P>
   But they aknowledge the ban on cod fishing on Georges Bank was
originally intended for May, when the demand for cod is not as
intense. But the council has been preoccupied with the cod crisis
in the Gulf of Maine, according to spokeswoman Pat Fiorelli, and
hours of public argument over that area meant the council was only
recently able to forward its Georges Bank recommendations to the
National Marine Fisheries Service.
</P>
<P>
   Now, approaching peak tourist season, many local fishermen and
market owners are predicting a cod catastrophe, and blaming a slow
bureaucratic process for ruining the summer for them, and for
anyone hoping for a taste of a traditional Cape Cod meal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it will eliminate fresh cod for half the summer,''
said Robert Ahearn, owner of Swan River Seafoods in Dennisport, a
market and restaurant that has become a must-stop for summer
visitors. Swan River sells about 1,000 cod filets (that's 2,000
pounds of whole fish) during a typical July day.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one is saying we shouldn't do something to preserve Cod,''
said Ahearn, who gets most of his cod from boats at the Chatham
Fish Pier. ``But the greatest demand is in July.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of the things people come to Cape Cod for,'' said
Ahearn, who last week petitioned the offices of Massachusets
Governor Paul Cellucci and Sen. John Kerry in hopes of a change in
policy. ``I talk to the customers out front,'' said Ahearn, whose
family has owned the market and restaurant 50 years. ``Fresh cod is
part of their vacation experience.''
</P>
<P>
   If cod dinners keep tourists coming in droves, they also keep
dinner on the table for the people who make a living on small
fishing boats.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Taylor, a 44-year-old member of the Cape Cod Hook
Association, said he sees no benefit in the July restriction, and
that while May, or June, was OK with him and others in his fishing
community, July is too productive a month to cut out of his fishing
calendar.
</P>
<P>
   ``There won't be any fish _ any fresh ground fish _ for the
tourists,'' Taylor said. ``I don't think anyone even thought of
that,'' he said. Pollack was named as a possible cod substitute by
Fiorelli, but fishermen say that the cost of fishing just for
pollack would not be worth it in the long run.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, striped bass season will open in July, but, as any old salt
knows, bass is not for frying.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead the tourists are going to get frozen fish,'' Taylor
said. ``Frozen fish from Iceland. And I've seen plenty of it. In my
opinion, it's horrible.'' Taylor said his own economic analysis
shows he will lose 16 percent of his annual income when the July
ban goes into effect.
</P>
<P>
   But Tuesday officials for the local council, which includes
fishermen, and the National Marine Fisheries Service, said the
restraints were necessary, despite the delay.
</P>
<P>
   ``The intention of this measure is to keep the cod mortality
rate down,'' said Teri Frady, spokeswoman for the National Marine
Fisheries Service.
</P>
<P>
   She added that not all of George's Bank will be closed to Cod
fishing, and that many boats will be able to travel outside the
imposed boundaries.
</P>
<P>
   Council spokesman Fiorelli said the proposed closings will be
reviewed in the next two weeks by officials at the federal agency,
and then go to US Commerce Secretary William Daley for final
aproval.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-15-99 2034EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
