<DOCNO> NYT19990615.0290 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-15 20:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6570 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COCACOLA-EUROPE-COX     06-15 0878
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COCACOLA-EUROPE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Although source of contamination found, European countries pull
Coke
 &HT;    (EDS: Moving in (f) Financial and (i) International categories.)
 &HT;    By Henry Unger
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ First Belgium. Now Luxembourg, France and the
Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
   Those nations are pulling Coca-Cola Co. beverages from store
shelves or stopping product shipments as a health scare spread
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the 113-year-old Atlanta institution, facing
an unprecedented assault on its brands in Europe, announced it had
found the sources of contamination that have sickened more than 100
Belgians.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola identified two causes: defective carbon dioxide
injected into drinks at a plant in Antwerp, Belgium, and an
offensive odor on the outside bottom of cans produced at a plant in
Dunkirk, France. The odor originated from a fungicide on wooden
pallets carrying cans that were sent to Belgium.
</P>
<P>
   The bottling plants, which ship beverages to the affected
European countries, are operated by Atlanta-based Coca-Cola
Enterprises. Coca-Cola Co. owns a 40 percent stake in CCE.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola spokesman Robert Baskin said discovery of the two
separate problems was coincidental.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is Coke having some more bad luck,'' said Scott Wilkins,
a beverage analyst for Deutsche Bank. ``That's unbelievable.'' The
company has had to deal with a series of recent setbacks abroad and
at home:
</P>
<P>
   _ Antitrust opposition overseas to its proposed purchase of
Cadbury Schweppes' brands,
</P>
<P>
   _ Antitrust opposition to its buyout of Orangina in France,
</P>
<P>
   _ Declining worldwide beverage case sales,
</P>
<P>
   _ A racial discrimination lawsuit in the U.S.,
</P>
<P>
   _ And a falling stock price.
</P>
<P>
   With the contamination in Europe now identified, Coca-Cola hopes
it will soon get the green light to begin restocking the shelves.
</P>
<P>
   The company said the defective carbon dioxide supply has been
replaced and that it is ``taking all necessary steps'' to eliminate
the offensive odor from the outside of its cans.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, the company said it ``continues to work closely
with the Belgian Health Ministry ... to assure the safety and
quality of our products for Belgian consumers, in order to obtain
final clearance for sales of the products in the Belgian market.''
</P>
<P>
   Luxembourg, which receives Coca-Cola products from Belgium,
banned them Tuesday after Belgium did so Monday. Coca-Cola also
withdrew from the Netherlands all products made in Belgium.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, France banned shipments of the drinks produced at the
Dunkirk plant. Today, France is expected to prohibit the sale of
Dunkirk-produced cans throughout the entire country as well as
recall ones already on the shelves. But Coca-Cola will be allowed
to stock the shelves with drinks produced at other Coke plants.
</P>
<P>
   The company insisted Belgium was the only nation affected by the
health problems. Many sickened were students _ a key target of
Coke's marketing efforts _ who were hospitalized for nausea,
vomiting or stomach aches. At least one showed symptoms of
hemolysis, in which red blood cells are destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the students were drinking Coca-Cola to gain points that
could be redeemed for prizes.
</P>
<P>
   The health scare originating in Belgium goes to the very heart
of a company that prides itself on quality throughout the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a bit disturbing that a big firm with worldwide fame ...
did not take far-reaching measures more spontaneously and more
promptly,'' said Belgian Health Minister Luc Van den Bossche. The
government estimated 15 million bottles or cans were involved.
</P>
<P>
   Several industry analysts predicted the company will be able to
recover from the short-term hit to its image.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as the management of Coke and CCE respond in a
forthright manner, there will not be a lasting impact on their
image when handled correctly,'' said Marc Cohen of Goldman Sachs.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts expect the company to reassure consumers in Europe with
aggressive marketing programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the programs will be successful,'' said John Sicher,
editor and publisher of Beverage Digest. ``Consumers respect
companies that deal with problems on an aggressive basis.''
</P>
<P>
   Baskin, the company spokesman, said it was ``premature to
comment'' on that issue.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola could hardly have picked a worse time or place to have
these problems. Belgium has been hit with a major public health
crisis that started last month when chicken, eggs, beef, pork and
dairy products were found to be contaminated with cancer-causing
dioxin.
</P>
<P>
   Financially, it is too early to assess the impact, although most
analysts predicted it would be minimal since only a small
percentage of its sales come from the countries involved so far.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see this as an issue from a financial standpoint,''
Wilkins said.
</P>
<P>
   Analyst Cohen said CCE might have to take moderate, one-time
charges related to the recall of its products.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola shares, which are down 6 percent over the past five
trading sessions, closed lower Tuesday at $63.75, down $1.06 1/4.
CCE also closed down $1.06 1/4 at $34.18 3/4. Its shares are also
down 6 percent since last week.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-15-99 2034EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990615.0291 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-15 20:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6571 &Cx1f; tad-z
