<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-QUAKE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUAKE ROCKS CENTRAL MEXICO; SIX REPORTEDLY KILLED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD CHACON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ The strongest earthquake since a 1985 temblor
killed thousands shook central and southern Mexico Tuesday
afternoon, reportedly killing six people, injuring hundreds and
sending panicked residents into the streets as homes and buildings
swayed.
</P>
<P>
   The earthquake had a preliminary magnitude of 6.7 on the Richter
scale, according to the National Seismological Service. Mexican
seismologists placed the epicenter in the southern state of Oaxaca,
about 135 miles southeast of the capital city.
</P>
<P>
   There were no immediate reports of serious damage or injury in
the Mexico City area although electricity and telephone service was
temporarily cut off throughout much of the city immediately after
the quake hit.
</P>
<P>
   In Puebla, a city of about 4 million residents that lies about
50 miles east of Mexico City and closer to the quake's epicenter,
officials reported five deaths. A dozen others were said to be
trapped under rubble and another 200 injuries were reported. There
were sporadic accounts of structural damage to buildings and homes.
One death was reported in Veracruz.
</P>
<P>
   Police and civil protection authorities blocked access to
Puebla's historic downtown out of fear that many buildings had
become unsafe.
</P>
<P>
   Aerial pictures transmitted by the TV Azteca television network
showed throngs of frightened residents milling in streets and on
sidewalks outside their homes and office buildings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Conditions appear to be relatively unharmed in Mexico City,''
Alberto Rodriguez, a spokesman for the Red Cross, told the network
during a live broadcast. ``What we are more concerned about are the
interior areas away from the capital. We are now beginning to
monitor our reports from there very carefully.''
</P>
<P>
   Experts said an earthquake greater than a 6 magnitude can cause
serious damage, while a 7 means a major earthquake, capable of
causing severe and widespread destruction.
</P>
<P>
   Reports from rural areas further south in Oaxaca and the
neighboring state of Guerrero, home to the resort city of Acapulco,
were still sketchy. Some emergency officials said they noted new
cracks along some roads, damaged homes and cars that were knocked
from one side of a street to another.
</P>
<P>
   The strong temblor struck the region at 3:42 p.m. local time,
the traditional lunch hour in this part of the country. Many of
those who stood out in the street were workers who had come home to
eat or students who had just arrived from school.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in the kitchen with my family when we started to feel
things shaking,'' said Mario de la Rosa, 37, who lives in a
southern Mexico City neighborhood. ``We're accustomed to feeling
things shake a little, but this was pretty scary.''
</P>
<P>
   Some seismologists expressed surprise that the quake's epicenter
appeared to be on land rather than along the coast, where most of
the country's tremors tend to originate. TV Azteca reported that
shaking was felt in five Mexican states, including Morelos and
Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Mexican President Ernesto Zedillo, who was on a day trip to the
Yucatan state of Quintana Roo, east of the earthquake, canceled his
visit and headed directly to Puebla to begin assessing the damage.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's quake instantly brought back painful memories of the
major temblor that struck the country in September 1985. That
earthquake, the largest to ever hit Mexico, was recorded at a
magnitude of 8.1 on the open-ended Richter scale and killed some
10,000 people, who were crushed by old buildings that toppled
because they had been built without strict codes.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of that incident, new building regulations and
emergency drills were put in place.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
