<TEXT>
<P>
   The Seattle Post-Intelligencer plans to move the following for
clients of the NYTimes News Service for editions of Wednesday, June
16, and thereafter. If you have any questions, please call Veronica
Villarreal at (206) 448-8342.
</P>
<P>
   PIPELINE (Seattle) _ In most cases, Olympic Pipeline was there
first, laying its 400 miles of pipe more than 30 years ago. On the
Eastside of King County, houses and school that have that
paint-barely-dry look flank the pipeline as it carries jet fuel,
gasoline and diesel fuel south to Sea-Tac Airport, then the
Columbia River. But in North Bend, the homes and schools have come
first and town leaders have no intention of allowing a pipeline in
their midst. Yet Olympic, even as it tries to repair the damage
done from a deadly explosion of its pipeline in Bellingham, won't
stand for that.
</P>
<P>
   By Scott Sunde. (Story will move in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   TICKETMASTER-COMPLAINTS (Seattle) _ Peter Laurie of Poulsbo,
Wash., called Ticketmaster Northwest recently to order tickets to a
Tom Jones concert. Several weeks later, the Lauries received a copy
of Entertainment Weekly in the mail. When the Lauries called, they
found Entertainment Weekly would bill them using the credit card
number they'd given Ticketmaster to buy concert tickets. The
Lauries and another consumer, who filed a complaint with the
Attorney General's Office, were outraged. Ticketmaster says it does
not condone signing people up for the magazine without their
permission.
</P>
<P>
   By Jane Hadley. (Story will move in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   KINGDOME-DEMOLITION (Seattle) _ Two companies have been selected
to implode the King Dome next year. One blew up an old department
store in Detroit and accidently did $5 million in damage to a
nearby light rail station. Here, they'll have to drop the dome
without banging up the new exhibition center, which is as close to
the dome as the light rail station was to the building in Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   By Alan Snel. (Story will move in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   ART-NAZIS-MATISSE (Seattle) _ The Seattle Art Museum has agreed
to return a Henri Matisse painting to the heirs of Paul Rosenberg,
a Jewish art dealer whose collection was stolen in France by the
Nazis during World War II. The museum board unanimously approved
the decision Monday, more than two years after the Rosenbergs
claimed ownership of the 1927 oil painting titled ``Odalisque.''
</P>
<P>
   By Regina Hackett. (Story has moved in the ``a'' and ``e''
categories.)
</P>
<P>
   BOEING-ORDER (Paris) _ Boeing lands an order for 50 planes and
options for 50 more from International Lease Finance Co., worth _
including the options _ about $4.5 billion. It was the most
anticipated order of the Paris Air Show, though the fact that half
of it was options dampens the enthusiasm a bit. Also, some analysts
say Boeing once again had to give away the airplanes to get the
order.
</P>
<P>
   By James Wallace. (Story will move in the ``f'' and ``i''
categories.)
</P>
<P>
   LABOR (Seattle) _ The U.S. Department of Labor on Tuesday
awarded $20 million to the state of Washington to help retrain an
estimated 24,000 Boeing workers here being laid off by the
aerospace giant by the end of next year.
</P>
<P>
   By Paul Nyhan. (Story will move in the ``f'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   MOVIE-POWERS (Seattle) _ ``Austin Powers: The Spy Who Shagged
Me,'' the hit spy flick comedy which opened this past weekend, is
stirring a mini-tempest in the British teapot. You see, in England
the word ``shag'' would be uncouth if slipped from the lips of
polite folks at a cocktail or dinner party.
</P>
<P>
   By Robert L. Jamieson Jr. (Story has moved in the ``e''
category.)
</P>
<P>
   TV-BANFF (BANFF, Alberta) _ The mission of the Banff TV
Festival, a sort of Cannes for the small screen, is simply to
celebrate excellence in television around the world, and with
Canadian earnestness it refuses to succumb to the popular notion
that ``quality'' and ``TV'' are inherently oxymoronic.
</P>
<P>
   By John Levesque. (Story has moved in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   TV-AWARDS (BANFF, Alberta) _ The judges for the Banff TV
Festival bestowed Banff Rockie Awards on an eclectic group of
productions that trace their origins to Austria, Canada, Denmark,
France, Germany, Ireland, Israel, the Netherlands, Poland, Sweden,
the United Kingdom and the United States.
</P>
<P>
   By John Levesque. (Story will move in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   BBA-MARINERS (Detroit) _ Seattle plays the Detroit Tigers.
</P>
<P>
   By Tyler Kepner. (Story will move in the ``s'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   BBA-MARINERS-NOTEBOOK (Detroit) _ Notebook items from Tuesday's
game against the Tigers.
</P>
<P>
   By Tyler Kepner. (Story will move in the ``s'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   BKN-SPURS-JOHNSON (San Antonio) _ Avery Johnson is the San
Antonio Spurs' player opponents target. And why not? The Spurs
feature the best front line in the game and their off-guard, Mario
Ellie, is a savvy veteran with two championship rings. But the
Spurs will tell you that the little man is the heart and soul of
their team. The bigger the challenge, the better his performance.
</P>
<P>
   By Ron Tillery. (Story will move in the ``s'' category.)
