u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PARKS-MEDAL-560&AMP;ADD-N     06-15 0744
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PARKS-MEDAL-560&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROSA PARKS, HERO OF CIVIL RIGHTS MOVEMENT, RECEIVES CONGRESSIONAL
GOLD MEDAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By ADAM CLYMER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Rosa Parks, the Alabama seamstress whose 1955
refusal to give up her seat on a Montgomery bus to a white man
sparked the peaceful demonstrations of the civil rights movement,
accepted Congress' highest honor on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   In a wan voice that was the antithesis of the strength President
Clinton, House Speaker Dennis Hastert and others praised her for,
Mrs. Parks, 86 and frail, said, ``This will be encouragement for
all of us to continue until all people have equal rights.''
</P>
<P>
   An audience of perhaps 1,000 strained to hear her, moments after
the soprano Jessye Norman filled the Capitol Rotunda to its
180-foot ceiling with the notes of the Negro National Anthem,
``Lift Ev'ry Voice and Sing.''
</P>
<P>
   Among those behind the diva, the only white face that appeared
to sing along was Clinton's.
</P>
<P>
   The award, the Congressional Gold Medal, the 121st in a line
that goes back to George Washington, was voted in April and hailed
her as ``a living icon for freedom in America.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Parks, an official of the Montgomery Chapter of the
National Association for the Advancement of Colored People, was
returning from work at the Montgomery Fair Department store late on
the afternoon of Dec. 1, 1955.
</P>
<P>
   The bus filled up, with whites in the front and blacks in the
black. The driver ordered four blacks in the front-most seats of
their section to get up and make room for whites. Three did. Mrs.
Parks did not. She was arrested under a city ordinance requiring
segregated buses.
</P>
<P>
   Four days later, thousands of blacks in Montgomery stayed off
the buses. They shared rides, took taxis or walked to work. Mrs.
Parks and many others were fired from their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   A young Baptist minister, Dr. Martin Luther King Jr., led the
movement that maintained the boycott for more than a year,
insisting on nonviolence and telling blacks that ``the great glory
of American democracy is the right to protest for right.''
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court threw out the bus ordinance the next December.
</P>
<P>
   After 381 days, blacks returned to the buses.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Sen. Tom Daschle of South Dakota observed that for
decades the medal was awarded only for military valor. Daschle, the
Senate minority leader, said, ``We offer this medal to Mrs. Parks
for helping us to understand that there is a force even greater
than military strength; that is the strength to love.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. J.C. Watts Jr. of Oklahoma, chairman of the House
Republican Conference and the only black Republican in the House,
said, ``We are in a room where we have too often gathered to mourn
our fallen leaders _ and too seldom have gathered here to celebrate
our living treasures.''
</P>
<P>
   After death threats, Mrs. Parks moved to Michigan, where for 14
years she worked for Rep. John Conyers Jr., a Detroit Democrat. He
was on hand Tuesday, as was the only current member of Congress who
was serving when she was arrested, Sen. Strom Thurmond of South
Carolina, then a Democrat and now a Republican. At the time, he was
a fierce, filibustering enemy of civil rights legislation. Thurmond
changed his stand over the years.
</P>
<P>
   In his remarks, Clinton said Mrs. Parks reminded America that
for millions the promise of liberty was illusory, saying, ``And so
she sat, anchored to that seat, as Dr. King said, by the
`accumulated indignities of days gone by and the countless
aspirations of generations yet unborn.'''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Mrs. Parks' Republican senator from Michigan, Spencer Abraham,
said, ``Few of us, with all our high offices, will accomplish what
Rosa Parks did with just one action.''
</P>
<P>
   Hastert said he, too, had been uplifted by the medal, because
while a speaker meets ``many outstanding individuals, from sports
stars to heads of state,'' he had ``never felt so honored, as when
I was able to share an afternoon with Mrs. Parks not too long ago.
As we sat there, enjoying our tea, I couldn't help but feel
privileged.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Julia Carson, the Indianapolis Democrat who led the effort
to award the medal, said Mrs. Parks, unlike those honored after
their deaths, was ``receiving the honor while she can still see it,
while she can still feel it.'' But the gold medal has not yet been
struck by the mint, and instead an artist's rendering was
presented.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
