<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-15 20:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6585 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HDEPOT-SUIT-COX     06-15 0845
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HDEPOT-SUIT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Home Depot sues former senior exec
 &HT;    By Patti Bond
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Home Depot alleges that a former senior executive
raided its stores for employees and stole trade secrets for a
venture planned to compete with its Expo Design Centers.
</P>
<P>
   James W. Inglis, a former executive vice president and former
board member, is named as the lead defendant in a lawsuit filed in
Fulton County Superior Court last week. Home Depot claims that
Inglis improperly recruited and hired key Expo employees earlier
this year.
</P>
<P>
   Home Depot wants the court to prevent Inglis from recruiting
more employees and seeks unspecified monetary damages.
</P>
<P>
   Inglis is chief executive officer of Dekor Inc., according to
corporate documents filed in September with the Secretary of
State's office. The Marietta, Ga.-based business doesn't have any
stores, but plans to sell products such as kitchen countertops,
wallpaper and paint. The lawsuit indicates Inglis' first store
would open within two years.
</P>
<P>
   The suit also names as defendants Herb Biggers, Lawrence J.
Crawford and Kathy Schaag Haffamier, all former Home Depot
employees and metro Atlanta residents who are now working for
Inglis. The suit charges Inglis with cherry-picking a team of
experts in several crucial areas. For example, Crawford developed
proprietary Expo products from European vendors, while Haffamier
specialized in domestic products.
</P>
<P>
   Home Depot won't say if Inglis, who left Home Depot in 1996, had
a noncompete agreement. Inglis and the other defendants declined to
comment on the lawsuit. According to the suit, Crawford and
Haffamier entered agreements with Inglis that were ``inconsistent''
with those they had at Home Depot. Home Depot declined to elaborate
on the allegations in the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Inglis' connection to Home Depot goes back to 1983, when he was
named vice president of merchandising after being recruited from
San Diego retailer Dixieline Lumber. He became a key player in Home
Depot's expansion. It was Inglis who first had the idea for Expo,
according to ``Inside Home Depot,'' a recently published book by
journalist Chris Roush. (Interestingly, Inglis is not mentioned in
``Built From Scratch,'' a new history of the company written by
founders Bernie Marcus and Arthur Blank.)
</P>
<P>
   Soon after joining Home Depot, Inglis got the idea for Expo,
according to Roush's book. By 1991, Inglis had persuaded the
company to open the first Expo as a test in San Diego, followed by
the Expo in suburban Atlanta in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   The Expo concept, held up as a laboratory to test decor products
and services on a more upscale audience, went through a series of
ups and downs over the next eight years. Expo executives were
constantly trying and discarding products in an effort to find the
right formula. By the time the sixth Expo opened in Davie, Fla.,
last year, the concept had been completely revamped. The current
format differs dramatically from the Perimeter Expo with a sleeker
look and better organized floor plan, for example.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts have applauded the changes. With average sales per
store of more than $43 million, the Expo division could represent
10 percent of Home Depot's revenue within four years, according to
Prudential Securities analyst Wayne Hood. Home Depot announced last
year it would roll out the Expo concept nationwide with at least
200 stores over 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   But the finished concept and long-awaited expansion came two
years after Inglis left Home Depot. Inglis, by then executive vice
president of strategic development, left in May 1996. Almost
immediately, he joined Kennesaw, Ga.-based flooring retailer Maxim
Group, a Home Depot competitor, as chief operating officer. He
later consulted for another Home Depot competitor, Chilean retailer
Sodimac Home Center, to help it get ready for Home Depot's foray
into Santiago.
</P>
<P>
   A key point of the claims in the lawsuit will be the degree to
which Inglis is allegedly copying Expo, said Ken Bernhardt,
professor of marketing at Georgia State University. ``Ideas get
stolen all the time in retail. The issue is whether he took
intellectual property, because retail concepts can't be patented.''
</P>
<P>
   The suit takes on added importance because Inglis was a board
member, said Erik Gordon, director of the center for retailing
research at University of Florida. ``Running a store is a lot
harder and a lot more subtle than it looks,'' Gordon said. ``If you
have non-public information about expansion plans and products,
then you have a competitive advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   Plagued by high turnover rates, other retailers have been taking
their employment problems to court. For example, Wal-Mart recently
sued Amazon.com for stealing computer experts and trade secrets.
The online bookseller agreed to reassign some former Wal-Mart
employees and return information it obtained from the employees.
</P>
<P>
   Patti Bond writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
