<SLUG> BC-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOW ADVANCES BY 31.66; INFLATION DATA ARE AWAITED 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Stocks inched higher Tuesday in thin, convictionless
trading in advance of an important inflation report scheduled to be
released Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Concern about what the May Consumer Price Index might show
caused bond traders to pare positions late Tuesday. And the sight
of rising long-term interest rates brought stock prices down from
their highs.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average rose 31.66 points, or
three-tenths of a percent, to 10,594.99. Blue chips that have been
punished recently _ a list that includes Procter &AMP; Gamble,
Citigroup and Merck _ led the advance Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Among broader indexes, a rise in large technology stocks helped
to lift the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index by 7.16 points, or
five-tenths of a percent, to 1,301.16. The NASDAQ market, hit hard
on Monday, recovered a bit Tuesday as prices of some Internet
stocks came off their lows. The NASDAQ composite index rose 16.36
points, or seven-tenths of a percent, to 2,414.67. And the Russell
2000 index of smaller company stocks gained 2.48 points, or
six-tenths of a percent, to 434.01.
</P>
<P>
   ``All in all, the market gave a great account of itself a day
before an important number'' like the consumer price report, said
Ned Collins, head of stock trading at Daiwa Securities America.
</P>
<P>
   ``But there is no conviction about anything. Until we get some
definitive statement from the Fed about interest rates and start to
see some second-quarter earnings reports, the market will lack a
catalyst to take off.''
</P>
<P>
   Trading activity reflected the lack of enthusiasm many seem to
have for stocks just now.
</P>
<P>
   On the New York Stock Exchange, 696 million shares changed
hands. Volume on NASDAQ was 837 million shares.
</P>
<P>
   As Collins suggested, uncertainty is likely to remain mired in
the market for the rest of the week at least even if the consumer
price report shows that inflationary pressures are subdued. That is
because Alan Greenspan, the chairman of the Federal Reserve, is
scheduled to testify before the Joint Economic Committee of
Congress on monetary policy and the economy. And Friday is a
``triple witching'' session, when options, futures contracts and
options on futures all expire. Trading on those days is often
volatile.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would not be surprised to see the market trade in this
directionless fashion until the Fed holds its meeting at the end of
the month,'' said Hug Johnson, chief investment officer at First
Albany Corp.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed's policy-making Open Market Committee is scheduled to
hold two days of meetings beginning June 29. Most financial market
participants expect the central bank to raise short-term interest
rates by a quarter-point at the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday was a good one for semiconductor stocks, which rallied
after a Merrill Lynch analyst raised his estimate for the growth
rate in semiconductor revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Instruments gained 5 1/8, to 134 3/8. Broadcom jumped 9
5/8, to 110 5/8. And Intel, the industry leader, rose 1 5/16, to 55
11/16.
</P>
<P>
   Oil companies also did well on expectations that demand for
gasoline is rising as the summer driving season gets under way.
</P>
<P>
   Exxon, a Dow component, rose 1, to 82 1/8. BP Amoco gained 2
5/16, to 113 3/16. And Royal Dutch Petroleum was up 7/8, to 60 1/8.
</P>
<P>
   Other market movers included Coca-Cola, which fell 1 1/16, to 63
3/4 after a health scare in parts of Europe led the company's
drinks to be pulled from shelves in some countries.
</P>
<P>
   CMP Group, which owns Maine's largest electric utility, saw its
shares jump 5 11/16, to 25 3/4, on news that Energy East, which
owns a New York utility, had offered to buy it for $1.2 billion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
