A6601 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-BRAVES-NOTES16-CO     06-15 0730
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-NOTES16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves Notebook: Remlinger doesn't focus on ERA
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Mike Remlinger insists his quality pitching is the
product of his new environment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very confident that whatever I did this year I'd have a
chance to have the best year I've had,'' Remlinger said. ``The No.
1 reason is the people around me. I fully believe when you're
surrounded by a lot of ability you elevate your game to their
level.''
</P>
<P>
   After the weekend barrage of offense, the reliever who came to
the Braves in the Denny Neagle trade from Cincinnati stands as the
only Braves pitcher with an ERA under 2.00. Through Monday's
scoreless inning, Remlinger was 2-1 with a 1.42 ERA in 28
appearances.
</P>
<P>
   But don't tell Remlinger his ERA. Taking the advice of former
Reds teammate Jeff Shaw, who's now the Dodgers' closer, he looked
at his statistics a month into the season to figure out what he
needs to improve on, and he hasn't looked at them since. Granted
the former Dartmouth College pitcher probably has a pretty good
idea of what they are, but he's not going to check.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every night I want to go out and do at least as good as I did
the night before,'' Remlinger said. ``If you start looking at your
numbers, you start believing in them.''
</P>
<P>
   For a guy who'd been dubbed a pitcher with control problems,
Remlinger's done a good job of hiding it. He's limited the walks to
14 in 31 2/3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the main reasons I've had control problems in the past
is some of the same reasons Odalis (Perez) is now,'' Remlinger
said. ``I was trying to do too much with my fastball. The key is to
stay under control with it. You'll have better command but you'll
also have better velocity. It's a hard lesson to learn. It's taken
me 13 years to figure it out.''
</P>
<P>
   Power output
</P>
<P>
   Javy Lopez's home run Monday night in the Astrodome was his
seventh of the year, ending a stretch of 17 games without a home
run. This time last year, Lopez had hit 13 home runs on his way to
his career-high of 34.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't what I was expecting, but I'm dealing with it,''
said Lopez, who's hitting a team-high .314. ``I understand every
year is different. I say the season's not over yet. I've just had a
slow start. So far what I'm doing is not focus on what I've done so
far and to focus on what I'm going to do. I'm hitting the ball
hard, sometimes I can't lift it.''
</P>
<P>
   Rocker react
</P>
<P>
   So John Rocker's streak of 16 scoreless innings ended in the
eighth inning on Monday night with a bang, as in Jeff Bagwell's
home run to the second deck of seats in left field. Rocker gave up
another run on two hits and a pair of wild pitches for runs No. 9
and 10 in the 10-4 loss. That was the first home run Rocker had
allowed this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it had been 5-4, I wouldn't have given up anything,'' said
Rocker, who's ERA rose from 1.69 to 2.28. ``It's tough. When I come
in and it's a save situation, I've got a better idea of what I want
to do, instead of going through the motions.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves had gone six games without a save situation, this
after Rocker had been getting around four chances a week. It was
Rocker's first appearance in five days, his longest stretch without
pitching since the middle of May.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't feel exactly comfortable out there,'' Rocker said.
</P>
<P>
   Etc.
</P>
<P>
   In the latest all-star balloting, Chipper Jones was still
trailing Matt Williams at third base, 203,745 votes to 195,454.
Outfielder Brian Jordan had moved up to eighth among outfielders
with 109,601 votes. Those two and Rocker will be Atlanta's best
hopes for the All-Star team in a rare year where a Braves starting
pitcher isn't expected to make it....
</P>
<P>
   The Braves have signed three more of their draft picks, all
right-handed pitchers, including 23rd round pick Kyle Colton of
Longwood, Fla., 38th round pick Anthony Sclafani of Staten Island,
NY and 49th round pick Nathan Kent from the University of Kentucky.
All three have been assigned to Braves rookie Gulf Coast Braves
team. The Braves have signed 21 of their 49 draft choices. They've
also signed six free agents, including catcher Earl Guilliams from
Danville, Va.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll Rogers writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
