<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-COMMENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPURS A GAMBLER'S BET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ In this most unusual season, we have two
appropriate teams still left standing. There are the heretofore
spineless Spurs against the heretofore dysfunctional Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   All is well in both camps now, spiritually speaking. Larry
Johnson has found Allah, if not a cure for his ailing right knee.
David Robinson has found Tim Duncan and, we suspect, won't mind
this summer if Duncan shows up at his house with foam shaving cream
instead of Edge gel.
</P>
<P>
   Both teams are on a roll. The Knicks have fashioned the most
unlikely of playoff runs, one fraught with corporate intrigue,
injuries to key personnel, and the emergence of postseason
supernovae. By comparison, the Spurs have been quiet and efficient,
steamrolling two pretty good teams en route to their first berth in
the NBA Finals and saying all the right things.
</P>
<P>
   As matchups go, this one looks hopelessly lopsided in San
Antonio's direction. The Spurs have the inside game with two of the
best big men of all time. They have snipers. They remain one of the
most difficult teams to score against, even more so in this season
of the offensively challenged. They have veterans who've been
there, done that.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks, however, have defied all conventional laws of hoop
physics ever since Allan Houston got that Nelsonian roll in Game 5
against Miami. They didn't match up with Indiana, either, and look
what happened. They had no inside game against the Pacers and
outshot them, 33-9, at the line in deciding Game 6. They have
unleashed an unstoppable Marcus Camby on the basketball world and
he has gotten better and better as the games got more meaningful.
They have brushed aside the loss of Patrick Ewing.
</P>
<P>
   Statistically, the teams are fairly even entering the series,
which starts Wednesday night at the hideous Alamodome. The Spurs
shoot a little better. So do their opponents. San Antonio has a
better scoring differential (8.1 to 4.3) and a big edge in assists
per game (which comes as no surprise, given the Knicks' two point
guards). Each team has had postseason success on the road; the
Spurs are 6-0, New York is 6-2.
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs also have had the tougher road. While the Knicks were
gift-wrapped the pathetic Hawks in Round 2, the Spurs went up
against the Lakers. San Antonio then had to deal with Portland in
the conference finals, while the Knicks got 4-point plays and an
overconfident Pacers team.
</P>
<P>
   Las Vegas likes the Spurs, which is to be expected. Looking at
the matchups, it's not hard to see why:
</P>
<P>
   FRONTCOURT: This is Reagan-Mondale stuff. Duncan, Robinson, and
Sean Elliott form as cohesive and effective a front line as there
is. Not only can Robinson and Duncan score and pass, they also
defend, rebound, and block shots. Elliott (and the designated
shooter guards) give San Antonio a perimeter presence much like the
Rockets had in their title years. New York will present Chris
Dudley, Latrell Sprewell, a wobbly Larry Johnson, Kurt Thomas and,
we assume very quickly, Camby. Who's going to rebound in this
bunch? Camby is almost required to come up huge and Sprewell has to
utilize his quickness, put the perimeter jumper in his locker, and
drive to the basket. He can break down Elliott, but there's going
to be someone there once he does. All in all, if the game is won in
the trenches, the Spurs look very solid.
</P>
<P>
   BACKCOURT: Stephon Marbury said at the end of the season that
the Knicks would never, never, ever win a championship with Charlie
Ward and Chris Childs. At the time, it seemed like an accurate, if
boorish, statement. Point guard isn't the Knicks' strength. Ward
might as well be invisible. Childs has his moments, but they're
infrequent. Allan Houston, however, stepped into the Knicks' Big
Time Game Hall of Fame with his 32-point submission in Game 6. It
was heroic. Emboldened by that, he has to take a similar approach
to motormouth tough guy Mario Elie. So far, however, Houston has
been maddeningly inconsistent; that big game against Indiana was
about his fourth such effort in three years. Elie and Avery Johnson
don't exactly conjure up images of Monroe and Frazier, but they've
been a succesful tandem. Johnson continually gets left alone on
double-teams and has made the Timberwolves, Lakers, and Trail
Blazers pay for such stupidity. Elie is in a shooting slump, but
he's a prime time performer with two rings and an ornery streak the
Spurs need. The Knicks can't leave these guys open on rotations or
they will kill them.
</P>
<P>
   BENCH: With LJ iffy, does Camby start or stay where he is? If he
starts, that gives the Knicks only Childs and Thomas as regular
reserves. Camby was a game-changer coming off the bench against
Indiana. San Antonio, meanwhile, can go big (Malik Rose, Will
Perdue) and small (Jerome Kersey, Jaren Jackson, Steve Kerr) off
the pine. They're deeper and have more balance. The Knicks
basically will be down to seven men if Johnson can't go. San
Antonio can go to its 11th man if need be (Antonio Daniels) and
still keep a beat.
</P>
<P>
   INTANGIBLES: The Knicks clearly are operating on some parallel
universe in getting here with three straight upsets. They have
managed to become almost likable _ almost _ despite the presence of
some lads with, shall we say, shady pasts? San Antonio presents the
NBA version of ``Got Milk?'' Look at it this way. Can you envision
David Stern standing at halfcourt at Madison Square Garden next
November and presenting a championship ring to Sprewell? Neither
can we.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-15-99 2058EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
