<HEADER>
A6605 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-JACKSON-LADN     06-15 0490
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-JACKSON-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ABC LURES BACK JACKSON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Keith Jackson will rumble once again.
</P>
<P>
   The dean of college football play-by-play will come out of
self-imposed retirement to do an exclusive schedule of weekly
Pac-10 games for ABC. It will end with his customary position at
the Rose Bowl, which in 2002 will host the national title game.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson's agreement with new ABC Sports president Howard Katz
allows him to decide year by year whether to stay.
</P>
<P>
   In Jackson's mind, all ABC had to do was ask _ or more
specifically, Katz had to present a travel-light schedule _ and
he'd think about coming back. The previous ABC Sports regime,
headed up by Steve Bornstein, never broached him about returning or
gave him the other option, Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``My sense was they wanted to change and that was fine,''
Jackson said about ABC under Bornstein and his decision to retire.
</P>
<P>
   Katz asked him about returning at a social event. Jackson and
his wife, Tori Ann, who live in Sherman Oaks and vacation
frequently in Vancouver, decided it was worth it, just months after
he had called it quits following 28 years of service.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very simple _ Howard called,'' Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cutting travel 90 percent is probably the single biggest
factor. It also means finishing where I started. I settled in the
West in 1950 (attending Washington State after leaving the Marines)
and that's not going to change. The fact I can do what I like to do
best and sleep in my own bed was a relatively easy decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it sounds easy to retire and suddenly resurface, but I
wouldn't have done it if I could not stay in the West. Others will
do the big games and that doesn't bother me a bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Katz: ``I was taking a shot in the dark. He's an
extraordinary man and staying close to home was a critical
ingredient to him. There are not very many people any of us know
who'd be willing to enter into this kind of arrangement.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson will do up to 13 Pac-10 games this season, but at least
half will be at places he can drive _ not just USC and UCLA, but
even up to the Bay Area and to Arizona. His first assignment,
however, will be Cal's game at Nebraska, which he was planning to
attend anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Along with being able to stay out West _ he's expecting his
first granddaughter in August _ the other factor is that Jackson
will remain with his partner of the last 12 years, Bob Griese. The
only problem for Griese is he lives in Miami and will have to fly
to the West Coast each week.
</P>
<P>
   But Griese looked like ABC's odd-man out anyway. Rather than
naming a new No. 1 play-by-play man to replace Jackson, the network
has decided to keep the Brent Musburger-Dan Fouts and Brad
Nessler-Gary Danielson teams intact and rotate them to games
considered the top national contest of the week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
