<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-AWARDS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BANFF TV FESTIVAL BESTOWS ITS ROCKIE AWARDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BANFF, Alberta _ Where the mountains meet the sky in this part
of Canada, it's as if a huge steak knife were resting against the
blue-plate special of the gods. Patches of white on the steel-gray
serrations could be remnants of horseradish, or maybe heavy cream
sauce the gods can eat because deities don't diet.
</P>
<P>
   The bill of fare is just as rich at the Banff TV Festival, which
each year honors outstanding television productions from around the
world. But while nominees like ``NYPD Blue'' and ``Law &AMP; Order''
may give comfort to someone up from the States, the menu is
actually more like what a first-timer would encounter at a sushi
bar.
</P>
<P>
   It is foreign: This year's field of 952 entries included the
first from Indonesia, as well as productions from Ukraine, Iran and
South Korea.
</P>
<P>
   It is different: A finalist in the animation category was a
6-minute Australian/German co-production about the lives of rats,
cockroaches and flies, and what happens when the garbage bin in
which they usually dine is empty. (Its take on the old
fly-in-my-soup gag is a classic.)
</P>
<P>
   And, to anyone with an open mind and an adventurous spirit, it
is inspiring: Not everything is A-plus work, but I doubt any of the
81 finalists in 14 categories would fall below a B-plus. As Pat
Ferns, president and CEO of the 20-year-old festival says,
``Quality must be our guide.''
</P>
<P>
   With that uppermost in their minds Monday night, the judges for
the Banff TV Festival bestowed Banff Rockie Awards on an eclectic
group of productions that trace their origins to Austria, Canada,
Denmark, France, Germany, Ireland, Israel, the Netherlands, Poland,
Sweden, the United Kingdom and the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The grand prize, symbolic of ``the best television program in
the world,'' went to ``Amongst Women,'' a dark Irish/U.K.
miniseries about an obstinate, repressive widower whose
relationships with his daughters and sons could only be described
as tortured. ``Amongst Women,'' which also won in the miniseries
category, has had limited release as a theatrical film in the
United States, but its TV future in North America is undetermined.
</P>
<P>
   For the third time, ``NYPD Blue'' won the Rockie as best
continuing series, while ``Ally McBeal'' took the honor for best
comedy, making it a two-trophy night for prolific creator David E.
Kelley, who also received the festival's annual Astral Award of
Excellence for a body of work that also includes ``Picket Fences,''
``Chicago Hope'' and ``The Practice.''
</P>
<P>
   Noting that the previous winners of the award, including the
likes of Walter Cronkite, Laurence Olivier and ``60 Minutes''
producer Don Hewitt, were much older than he, Kelley, 43, said he
wasn't sure he was either qualified or worthy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope to get to do this job 10 or 15 years more,'' he said,
``and that you'll call me up and say, `One just wasn't enough.' But
I'm going to hang onto this one in the meantime.''
</P>
<P>
   Andre Bureau, chairman of Astral Communications, Canada's
multichannel equivalent of Turner Broadcasting, said Kelley's
mastery of the human condition combines artistic genius with wry
social commentary.
</P>
<P>
   ``But most of all,'' Bureau said, ``he has invented characters
we care about. This is the mark of a real human being.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelley acknowledged one of those characters, the feisty, wacky
and eminently vulnerable Ally McBeal, has so captured the
imaginations of some viewers that they can't let go.
</P>
<P>
   ``Female lawyers come up to me all the time and say, `I am Ally
McBeal, I am Ally McBeal,' '' Kelley remarked. ``I never know
whether to say, `Congratulations,' or, `Get help!' ''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps his best advice, something he has said repeatedly to
those who would hold Ally up as a representative of all womankind,
is: ``Please do not take us too seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   Hard to say if those words are taken to heart in Canada. ``Ally
McBeal'' gets even better ratings here than in the United States.
But Canadians do know how to laugh, and the festival admits as much
each year with the Peter Ustinov Award, which it bestowed this time
upon favorite son Martin Short.
</P>
<P>
   The other winners of Rockie Awards, by category, were: animation
program, ``Gogs: Gogwana,'' United Kingdom; arts documentary,
``M.C. Escher,'' the Netherlands; children's program,
``Blabbermouth and Sticky Beak,'' United Kingdom; history and
biography program, ``Chronique couleur du ghetto de Lodz,''
France/Poland/Germany; information program, ``Honourable Murder,''
Sweden/Denmark; made-for-TV movie, ``Aharon Cohen's Debt,'' Israel;
performance program, ``Les lecons de tenebres,'' France; popular
science and natural history program, ``Bees _ A Life for the
Queen,'' Austria; short drama, ``The Breakfast (Short Cuts),''
Ireland; social and political documentary, ``True Stories: The
Valley,'' United Kingdom; sports program, ``Hitman Hart: Wrestling
with Shadows,'' Canada/USA/UK/France; special jury prizes, ``Vanity
Fair,'' United Kingdom, and ``Cinema itinerant _ Reves et
illusions,'' Germany/Poland.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-15-99 2107EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990615.0316 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-15 21:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6613 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIA-SCULPTURE-ART-NYT     06-15 1111
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIA-SCULPTURE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CIA'S ARTISTIC ENIGMA YIELDS ALL BUT FINAL CLUE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Va., Calif.)  (editors: text of cipher at end of article) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By JOHN MARKOFF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   It has stood in a courtyard inside the CIA for almost a decade,
a sculptural mystery inside an enigma.
</P>
<P>
   But last week Jim Gillogly, a Southern California computer
scientist, did what has until now been done _ quietly, and
incompletely _ only inside the agency's halls. He succeeded in
breaking almost all of a cipher embedded in a sculpture called
Kryptos _ the Greek word for ``hidden'' _ that was dedicated at the
CIA in October 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the 865-character message etched into the sculpture
by the artist, Jim Sanborn, has defied all attempts to completely
unravel its conundrum. Even Gillogly acknowledges that he has
deciphered only its first 768 characters. Still unbroken are the
last 97 characters, apparently the same section that has also
stumped both the CIA and the National Security Agency.
</P>
<P>
   Sanborn said this week that the sculpture contains a riddle
within a riddle _ one that will be solvable only after the four
encrypted passages are known. The complete answer was handed to
William Webster, the director of Central Intelligence when the
sculpture was completed, and has been held in confidence by his
successors.
</P>
<P>
   The tantalizing clues uncovered last week are likely to rekindle
interest in a complete solution: The three sections include a
poetic phrase, a reference to a point near the CIA's headquarters
in Langley, Va. (with the enticing passage, ``Who knows the exact
location? Only WW''), and an excerpt from an account of the opening
of King Tut's tomb in 1922.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really have a good idea of what it might be,'' said
Gillogly, a 53-year-old cryptographer at Mentat Inc., a Los Angeles
software maker, who started designing cryptograms with his brother
as a child in an attempt to stump their father.
</P>
<P>
   A computer hacker in the best sense of the word and a past
president of the American Cryptogram Association, Gillogly
(pronounced gill-OH-glee) began exploring the Kryptos message in
1992, but he abandoned it until nine days ago, when he saw it
briefly alluded to in an Internet discussion group.
</P>
<P>
   This time he was armed with a better weapon than the pencil and
paper he had seven years ago: his home computer, a highly powered
Pentium II. And the key to solving the first three sections of the
message proved to be a program that Gillogly had written as part of
his cryptographic passion.
</P>
<P>
   The program, he said, is intended to help solve what he refers
to as classical cryptographic systems used by kings, armies and
spies before World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Even with more computational power, he had to apply traditional
cryptographic methods, using his logical powers of deduction.
``There was a fair amount of skull sweat,'' he said. ``You work on
it and you see something that is a little out of whack and you
start pulling on it to see what unravels.''
</P>
<P>
   When he contacted the CIA's press office last week, Gillogly
learned that he was not the first codebreaker to succeed at
unraveling the first part of the mystery.
</P>
<P>
   In February, David Stein, who works for the agency as a
physicist and senior analyst, and not as a professional
cryptographer, had quietly uncovered the same three passages. Like
Gillogly, he has been stumped by the final section, although he
believes that it will eventually be solved.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Kryptos puzzle is a layered puzzle,'' he said Tuesday,
``and we may find that it has layers within layers within layers.''
</P>
<P>
   Stein sounded a bit miffed when he learned that Gillogly had
used a computer in his pursuit of the hidden codes. ``Kryptos was
meant to be solved with pencil and paper,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   There were no written rules in this contest, Gillogly responded.
``As far as I'm concerned a crack is where you find it,'' he said.
``The choice of tool isn't the important part, but rather the
decisions about how to use the tools.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Webster said Tuesday that he had long since
forgotten the answer. ``I have zero memory of this,'' he said. ``It
was philosophical and obscure.'' But he sided with Gillogly on
using a computer. ``Who set the rules here?'' he asked. ``This is
precisely what the agencies do when they try to break codes.''
</P>
<P>
   Sanborn, the artist, who has designed a number of sculptures
that are puzzles, has said he believes that the ultimate secret
hidden in the text of Kryptos will never be deciphered. It was
designed by Edward Scheidt, a former chairman of the CIA's
Cryptographic Center.
</P>
<P>
   That has not stopped either Gillogly or Stein from speculating
on what the full message may contain. And Gillogly has even
contemplated exploring the bag of tricks of some of the world's
acknowledged past spy masters in search of the complete solution.
</P>
<P>
   ``There're still those last few lines waiting to be decrypted,''
he wrote last week in an Internet discussion group. ``I'll review
the `Mission Impossible' movie for tips on getting into the vault,
if all else fails.''
</P>
<P>
   KRYPTOS UNMASKED
</P>
<P>
   Here are the first three passages of the code on the Kryptos
statue as deciphered by Jim Gillogly, including misspellings (of
``illusion,'' ``underground'' and ``desperately''). The second
passage identifies a location near the CIA headquarters; the third
is taken from Howard Carter's account of the opening of King Tut's
tomb in 1922.
</P>
<P>
   1. Between subtle shading and the absence of light lies the
nuance of iqlusion.
</P>
<P>
   2. It was totally invisible. How's that possible? They used the
earth's magnetic field. x The information was gathered and
transmitted undergruund to an unknown location. x Does Langley know
about this? They should: it's buried out there somewhere. x Who
knows the exact location? Only WW. This was his last message. x
Thirty-eight degrees fifty-seven minutes six point five seconds
north, seventy-seven degrees eight minutes forty-four seconds west.
ID by rows.
</P>
<P>
   3. Slowly, desparatly slowly, the remains of passage debris that
encumbered the lower part of the doorway was removed. With
trembling hands I made a tiny breach in the upper left-hand corner.
And then, widening the hole a little, I inserted the candle and
peered in. The hot air escaping from the chamber caused the flame
to flicker, but presently details of the room within emerged from
the mist. x Can you see anything?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
