<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-POINTGUARDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPURS, KNICK POINT GUARDS OFTEN MALIGNED 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By MIKE WISE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO, Texas _ Avery Johnson has been released seven times
during his 11-year career. He was out of work when he was wearing
in a tuxedo at David Robinson's wedding.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that wasn't the worst,'' the truculent point guard of the
San Antonio Spurs said Tuesday. ``The worst was being cut on
Christmas Eve by Denver in the airport. Paul Westhead came up and
gave me my walking papers.
</P>
<P>
   ``On David's day,'' he said, ``I was just really happy for him
and that he was getting married rather than thinking about my own
sad self and how am I going to get a job.''
</P>
<P>
   While Johnson was bouncing around the National Basketball
Association, Chris Childs had graduated from the Continental
Basketball Association in 1994, and was backing up Kenny Anderson
on the Nets for $60,000 a year. At the same time, across the Hudson
River, Charlie Ward's attempt to show Pat Riley he was more than a
Heisman Trophy winner resulted in fewer minutes.
</P>
<P>
   As it turns out, you do not need a dazzling crossover dribble, a
catchy nickname or a monster contract to lead your team to the
league championship series. For three unremarkable but effective
floor leaders, the National Basketball Association finals has a
10-year reunion feel to it _ the senior quarterback is bloated, the
class president is divorced and the real movers and shakers from
the unpopular corner of the lunch room get to exact their sweet
revenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all just wanted a chance,'' said Ward. ``We're not great. I
think we just do the best we can to lead our team. That's all you
can ask for from guys who aren't glamorous, in a sense.''
</P>
<P>
   What did Portland's Damon Stoudamire, outplayed by Johnson in
the Western Conference finals, say about Johnson never being able
to lead his team to the finals? And what of the cocksure Stephon
Marbury who said, ``The Knicks will never win anything with Chris
Childs and Charlie Ward as their point guards?''
</P>
<P>
   Stoudamire re-evaluated his comments from two years ago. Asked
if he felt any vindication in reaching the finals after Marbury's
comments earlier this season, Childs shrugged his shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I'll say is, I'm practicing and he's chillin,' '' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Maligned at home and on the road _ indiscriminately by their
fans and their peers _ either Ward, Childs or Johnson will achieve
the ultimate in their profession over the next two weeks. Given the
litany of criticism, it is an extraordinary feat. But not
unprecedented.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago won six of the last eight championships with John
Paxson, Ron Harper and B. J. Armstrong running the team at times.
And while it could be said that Michael Jordan played the role of
point guard as well as anyone during the playoffs, Boston did
fairly well with Dennis Johnson and Danny Ainge during the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really does not matter who is running the team,'' said the
veteran reserve center Herb Williams. ``Who's a basketball critic
that can accurately predict the future? I mean, how may great point
guards did Chicago have? How many great point guards did Boston
have? You get a great point guard and you don't have anyone else to
get you over the top, you have a problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those guys do what they do to help their teams win. With all
the scoring and highlights these days, some people forget that
that's what a point guard's job used to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Ward: ``You look at the point guards that have been in the
finals recently. John Stockton has been the league for a long time,
but he's not a top scorer anymore. He's not very flashy. He plays
hard, does what he has to do. That's all that counts.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he felt a sense of satisfaction after all the
criticism, he added, ``I'm not in the business of trying to verify
what I do. I go out and play to the best of my abilities. I don't
doubt myself. Other people doubt me. I'm just very grateful God has
placed me where I am.''
</P>
<P>
   Ward has been spotty during the post-season, but whenever he has
faltered Childs has been there. His defense on Mark Jackson and
Reggie Miller at times during the Knicks' victory over Indiana in
the Eastern Conference finals was as instrumental as any clutch
3-pointer he knocked down.
</P>
<P>
   Ornery, ruthless and sometimes an annoying chatterbox, Johnson
brings a serated edge to the court. He draws parallels between
Childs and Greg Anthony, the reserve Portland point guard who
disrupted John Stockton in the second round and hawks the ball from
end line to end line.
</P>
<P>
   For all his liabilities as a consistent jump-shooter, Johnson is
respected by Childs and Ward for his ability to break defenses down
with his hesitation moves and his skill going to the basket.
</P>
<P>
   As Game 1 looms on Wednesday night, they seemed to have formed a
three-person support group: Persevering Point Guards Whose Fans
Still Want Them Traded.
</P>
<P>
   ``The criticism will never stop,'' Ward said. ``That's just the
nature of this job. The only thing you can do is not listen to it
and believe in yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Johnson: ``I still feel like I'm going up the side of the
mountain and have a long way to go. If you're fortunate enough to
have success this year, you want to come back and show you can do
it again.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
