<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-US-REFUGEE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN THE WOODS OF GEORGIA, ECHOES OF BALKAN TERROR 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By DIANA JEAN SCHEMO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   COMER, Ga. _ Hysnije Hoxha was studying the arrangement of
spoons, fruits and other objects on a wooden table last week as her
English teacher, Catherine Giller, circled vegetables around a
wristwatch. ``Hysni,'' Ms. Giller asked, ``where is the watch?''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Hoxha, a refugee from Kosovo, was learning English at the
age of 45, but under the surface of her concentration swam visions
of her two sisters and her brother _ stranded with their families
in the mountains of Kosovo, surrounded until now by Serbian troops.
``The watch,'' Mrs. Hoxha said haltingly, ``is in the middle of
vegetables.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Giller turned to Mrs. Hoxha's husband, Ilir, and asked him
the color of his house. Hoxha (pronounced HO-jah) did not mention
his two-story, four-bedroom pride of Pristina, turned into a
station for the Serbian military and now probably booby-trapped or
burned. Instead, he described the cabin here in the Georgia woods
where he is staying with his family. ``My house is black,'' he
said, and then corrected himself. ``My house is blue.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether the subject is prepositions or predicates, the Hoxhas
and their three children _ their son, Arben, 20, and their
daughters, Arbresha, 17, and Teuta, 15 _ are caught between worlds.
They study the language of their new home, even if they are not
sure where home will ultimately be. A month ago it was a barracks
at Fort Dix, N.J., where they were among the first refugees from
Macedonia. Two months from now, home will probably be in Atlanta.
Or it may be back in Pristina, the Kosovo capital, in a house
either familiar or beyond repair.
</P>
<P>
   For now, home is just outside Comer, northeast of the university
town of Athens, in a quiet compound built 20 years ago by a group
of Christian pacifists called the Jubilee Partners, who have
dedicated themselves to easing refugees into American life. It is
here that the Hoxhas, their world turned completely upside down,
have wound up along with Ali and Raze Beshiri, neighbors and close
friends from Pristina, and three other Kosovar families. They are
to stay for two months before heading for Atlanta, where they will
be resettled if they remain in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Daily, almost hourly, the grapevine news from Kosovo changes,
elating the refugees one moment and crushing their spirits the
next.
</P>
<P>
   When she heard that the Yugoslav army was withdrawing from
Kosovo, Arbresha's reaction was typically American: she threw up
her right palm for a high-five with Kosovare Ramadani, a friend she
had met at Fort Dix. Ilir Hoxha sang softly about his homeland, and
the girls joined in.
</P>
<P>
   But their song had barely ended when another of the Kosovar
families received a call from Switzerland relaying a rumor that the
army was torching Pristina as it pulled out. Hoxha, a former music
producer, held his head in his hands. ``Today all our hope is
destroyed,'' he said. ``We thought of going home, but this news is
very bad.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hoxhas learned that they would be going to Atlanta only a
day before they took the plane south from Newark (N.J.)
International Airport. During the two-hour flight, Hysnije and Ilir
wondered how they would make their way through the Atlanta airport
and where they would live. ``I was afraid I would not meet any
Albanians at all,'' Hoxha said.
</P>
<P>
   It was the presence in Georgia of another Kosovar Albanian, a
scientist who volunteered to translate for the Hoxhas, that had
opened the way for the Jubilee Partners to bring them here. When he
learned that refugees would be leaving Fort Dix for resettlement
around the United States, he called Jubilee Partners and
volunteered to translate, making it easier for the group to
accommodate them. The scientist, who does not want to be identified
because he still has relatives in Kosovo and fears for their
safety, welcomed the Hoxhas at the Atlanta airport. So did
reporters and television crews.
</P>
<P>
   But the isolation of the compound's woods was hard to bear.
Arbresha was haunted by the memory of Serbs' kicking in the door
and separating the women in the family from her father and Arben.
The others could not name their fear, though it was undeniable.
</P>
<P>
   That reaction was not unusual, said Jennifer Drago, who is in
charge of helping the Kosovars at Jubilee and who notes that the
woods can echo newly arrived refugees' nightmares: The Vietnamese
of the early 1980s feared tigers. The Bosnians feared land mines.
On their first night here, Ms. Drago said, many women weep
themselves to sleep.
</P>
<P>
   Jubilee Partners will sign up the Hoxhas and other Kosovars for
food stamps and medical assistance. It gives them $20 a person each
week, part of a one-time $740-a-person resettlement grant that the
United States government pays resettlement agencies. The payments,
while minimal, are comparable to those given to members and
volunteers of Jubilee Partners, each of whom lives on $10 a week
and has no group medical insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Jubilee's two dozen or so members are largely people who have
left mainstream society to work here, on the grounds of a former
cow pasture, and live in simplicity, eating no meat, wearing
hand-me-downs and shunning conveniences like television. The
group's founder, Don Mosley, also founded Habitat for Humanity, the
charity that builds and repairs homes for the poor.
</P>
<P>
   Hoxha says he has no plans to take his family back to Kosovo
now. The Hoxhas are all but penniless and fear that returning
prematurely could land them in danger or desperation. But while the
Hoxhas' energies are devoted to preparing for life in America,
their hearts remain back home. ``I'm trying to prepare for the
future, but the reality is that I'm living in the past,'' Hoxha
said.
</P>
<P>
   Most obviously affected by the trauma of exile is the
17-year-old, Arbresha. She no longer lowers her head as she did
despondently after her arrival at Fort Dix in early May. But she is
having trouble sleeping, and cries easily.
</P>
<P>
   Arbresha has begun to keep a diary of the past, recounting the
horrors of Kosovo. But much of the diary is written as if the
horrors have not ended. In Albanian, she describes hiding in the
cellar, and getting word that the Serbs are advancing neighborhood
by neighborhood, marching the Kosovars out of their province.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can feel death before our eyes, all around us,'' says a
passage read by the scientist-translator who has linked up with
Jubilee Partners. ``We think the worst will come later. The
telephone rings, and we learn that another neighborhood is being
cleaned.''
</P>
<P>
   Soon she sees people who are ``the heart of the neighborhood''
being marched out of their homes, with masked members of the
Serbian paramilitary behind them. ``We started to put on our shoes,
and a soldier kicked in the door.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The soldiers separated me, Mom and Teuta from Dad and Arben,''
she wrote. The Serbs held guns under the chins of Hoxha and Arben,
demanding money they did not have, while the women stood outside
imagining the worst. ``I prayed to God to save them,'' Arbresha
wrote. Why should she march out of the city if her father and
brother were killed? ``I should just die here,'' she wrote.
</P>
<P>
   It was a five-minute eternity before her father and brother
reappeared. Arbresha wept. ``I looked at my house for the last
time,'' she wrote, ``and at my whole neighborhood.''
</P>
<P>
   The translator looked up. Around the table, the Hoxhas were
sobbing, as were their neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is enough,'' the translator said as tears rolled down his
cheeks as well. ``We will save the rest for next time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
