<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
 (pr) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WITH SILICON VALLEY BOUNTY COMES UNEASE ABOUT BOOM
</P>
<P>
   In Silicon Valley, the nation's high-technology heartland, the
good times have arrived in abundance and have stayed longer than
ever before. Wage rates are about 60 percent above the national
average and are growing far more quickly than average, and the
trappings of wealth can be seen everywhere. But the indicators of
affluence have in turn led to a growing sense of unease among many
valley longtimers who oscillate between a faith in what has been
called the ``long boom'' and the knowledge that each of the
valley's booms in the last half-century has inevitably been
followed by a bust.
</P>
<P>
   SENATE APPROVES YEAR 2000 BILL
</P>
<P>
   After months of partisan squabbling, the Senate approved
legislation that would limit lawsuits arising from Year 2000
computer failures. But the vote fell short of the two-thirds
majority needed to override President Clinton's promised veto.
</P>
<P>
   GLOBAL TRADING TAKES STEP FORWARD
</P>
<P>
   The National Association of Securities Dealers took a big step
toward the creation of an around-the-clock, global stock market
with the announcement that it would join with Softbank to develop a
version of its electronic Nasdaq Stock Market in Japan. Eventually,
the two markets could together provide investors with the ability
to trade for up to 21 hours a day, said Frank Zarb, chief executive
of the NASD.
</P>
<P>
   STOCKS EDGE UP IN WEAK TRADING
</P>
<P>
   Stocks inched higher in thin trading in advance of the consumer
price index report, which will be released this morning. The Dow
Jones industrial average rose 31.66 points, to 10,594.99. The
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index was up 7.16 points, to 1,301.16,
while the Nasdaq composite index rose 16.36 points, to 2,414.67.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICIAN ACCUSED OF EXTORTION
</P>
<P>
   Foreign investors in Far Eastern Shipping Co. of Russia have
accused a top politician of using extortion to try to wrest away
their stakes in the concern, causing a shareholder rights scandal.
</P>
<P>
   HONG KONG COMPANY CHANGES NAME
</P>
<P>
   Hong Kong's local telephone company, Hong Kong
Telecommunications, said that it would change its name to Cable and
Wireless HKT to tighten ties with its London-based parent company,
Cable and Wireless. Linus Cheung, the chief executive of Hong Kong
Telecom, said the new name was intended to convey the company's
broader ambitions in Asia.
</P>
<P>
   ORACLE RESULTS BEAT EXPECTATIONS
</P>
<P>
   Oracle reported fourth-quarter revenue and earnings that
surpassed analysts' estimates and announced that it was laying off
325 employees to trim costs.
</P>
<P>
   TENSIONS ESCALATE OVER INTERNET
</P>
<P>
   In the latest sign of escalating tension between the Internet's
new oversight board and Network Solutions, the company that
controls the distribution and registration of Internet addresses,
the board's interim chairwoman, Esther Dyson, said that the company
was fostering unfounded criticism of her group.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
