<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-15 21:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6621 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN &LR;      06-15 0570
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GARBAGE DISPOSAL IS AN ECONOMIC PROBLEM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Undated) _ Sunday's Parade story on garbage showed why
Americans have so much trouble solving basic problems.
</P>
<P>
   The cover photo of a family surrounded by a month's trash
production proclaimed, ``We're running out of ways to dispose of
it.'' The story, however, didn't much explore that premise.
</P>
<P>
   Proposed solutions included more recycling and less superfluous
packaging. The effort thus not only failed to break new ground, but
also recycled the same old feel-good panaceas.
</P>
<P>
   These stories fail to bring fresh perspectives because they
ignore the reality that trash is an economic problem, which means
costly and inconvenient trade-offs. This isn't what most Americans
want to hear, which locks analysts into tired old ways of
considering the problem.
</P>
<P>
   First of all, think about the claim, ``We're running out of ways
to deal with it.'' This simply isn't so. The options have always
been limited. Since societies became civilized enough to worry
about sanitary garbage disposal, the primary choices have been to
bury it, burn it or reuse it.
</P>
<P>
   What interferes mostly with America's quest to deal with garbage
is an aversion to acknowledging that the problem isn't trash per
se, but the cost of disposing of it at acceptable locations.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most interesting aspect of the Parade article was
its inclusion of William Rathje to no enlightening effect. Rathje
is America's foremost expert on garbology. His 1992 book, Rubbish,
remains the most insightful work on the issue, but it has never
been much embraced by environmentalists.
</P>
<P>
   While the article did feature Rathje, it used him to discuss
only the archaeology of garbage rather than focus on his insights
into what he considers the best solutions. He was quoted, for
instance, about the durability of garbage, including the
mummification of hot dogs still recookable after 30 years in a
landfill. There was no discussion, though, of how he would deal
with trash.
</P>
<P>
   By using Rathje to titillate rather than inform, the article
ignored the most useful advice in his book, which was to understand
that ``we do not necessarily know the things we think we know.''
Another admonition in Rubbish was for Americans to be willing to
pay for garbage disposal.
</P>
<P>
   If Americans don't want garbage buried near them, they must pay
for this convenience. Contrary to what many experts say, it's not a
matter of running out of room. It's a matter of paying whatever's
necessary to use space far removed from everyone's back yard.
</P>
<P>
   For example, according to Rathje's estimates, ``all of America's
garbage for the next 1,000 years would fit into a landfill space
120 feet deep and 44 miles square ... less than 0.1 percent of the
surface area of the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Putting it all in one isolated place obviously isn't realistic,
but it illustrates that space isn't the problem. The real problem
is America's unwillingness to pay the price of ridding itself of
the mountains of refuse created daily by America's humongous
propensity for consumption.
</P>
<P>
   A new challenge? Not at all. In 1889, Washington's chief health
officer warned that ``appropriate places for garbage are becoming
scarcer ... already inhabitants in proximity to the public dumps
are beginning to complain.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
