<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR WEDNESDAY, JUNE 16
</HEADLINE>
 Eds.: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Wednesday. Days and dates refer to the original article's
transmission by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be
adjusted by NYT clients.)  
(gc) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-KOSOVO-DIPLO-NYT (moved on Monday, June 14)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Monday, June 14,
about Peter Castenfelt, a financier who recently held secret talks
with President Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia, misstated his
nationality. While he owns a London financial company, Mr.
Castenfelt is Swedish, not British.
</P>
<P>
   BC-POLAND-POPE-NYT (moved on Monday, June 14)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Monday, June 14,
about Pope John Paul II's trip to Poland and his plan to visit the
Patriarch of Armenia ended with an incomplete sentence. The passage
should have read, ``While the Armenian patriarch is on good terms
with Patriarch Aleksy II, the head of the Russian Orthodox Church,
Patriarch Aleksy is considered unlikely to change his steadfast
refusal to meet with the Pope or invite him to Russia.''
</P>
<P>
   BC-ISRAEL-CABINET-NYT (moved on Monday, June 7)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Monday, June 7,
about the new Israeli Parliament referred imprecisely to Rabbi
Chaim Druckman, a member of Parliament from the National Religious
Party. While he did not serve in the last Parliament he is not a
newcomer, having served from 1977 to 1988.
</P>
<P>
   BC-JAPAN-ECON-NYT (moved on Thursday, June 10)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Thursday, June 10,
about data showing strong Japanese first-quarter economic growth
misstated the forecast of economists polled by Bloomberg News one
day before the data were released. The forecast predicted the data
would show Japan's economy had contracted by two-tenths of a
percent, not eight-tenths of a percent.
</P>
<P>
   BC-DELTA-JETS-NYT (moved on Friday, June 11)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Friday, June 11,
about Delta Air Lines' deferral of an order for 11 Boeing 777
aircraft because of a pay dispute with pilots misstated a
comparison with other airlines. Delta's pilots have asked for $319
an hour to fly the 777, while Delta has offered them $239 an hour.
Delta said its hourly figure, not the pilots', was 5 percent above
what American Airlines pays its pilots, 25 percent higher than what
United Airlines pays and 26 percent higher than Continental
Airlines' rate.
</P>
<P>
   BC-IBM-CRYPTOGRAPHY-NYT (moved on Wednesday, June 9)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Wednesday, June 9,
about quantum cryptography referred incorrectly to a new I.B.M.
system. It is based on the different polarizations of photons, not
protons.
</P>
</TEXT>
