A6624 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ORACLE-ORACLE_SFCHRON     06-15 0661
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ORACLE-ORACLE </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Oracle to Lay Off 325 in U.S.  &HT;     By Deborah Solomon 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
Oracle Corp. said yesterday that it will lay off about 325
employees, including an undisclosed number of workers in the Bay
Area, as it trims its operations and shifts more of its business
online.
<P>
   The No. 1 database software-maker announced the cuts just hours
before releasing record fourth-quarter and year-end earnings that
exceeded analyst expectations.
</P>
<P>
   The layoffs, which will affect less than 1 percent of Oracle's
43,000 employees, will be spread across the company's departments,
said Jennifer Glass, an Oracle spokeswoman. Glass could not say how
many workers in Silicon Valley would be affected but said most of
the cuts will take place at Oracle's U.S. operations.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, Oracle Chairman Larry Ellison pledged to cut
$1 billion in costs during over  &LR; the next 18 months to make his
company more efficient. One way he plans to achieve that is by
moving much of Oracle's day-to-day business online and selling more
products over the Web, a move Glass said will reduce the need for
some personnel.
</P>
<P>
   Ellison reiterated his commitment to becoming an e-business
yesterday while announcing stronger-than-expected financial
results.
</P>
<P>
   Oracle said net income for the fiscal fourth-quarter rose to
$527.4 million (36 cents per share), up from $402.8 million (27
cents) from the same period a year ago. Revenue increased 22
percent to $2.94 billion from $2.41 billion last year.
</P>
<P>
   The company credited increased sales in its database and
applications software for the revenue growth. The fourth-quarter
earnings surprised Wall Street, which had predicted earnings of
about 32 cents per share, according to First Call.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts were expecting a somewhat disappointing quarter from
Oracle because of a slowdown in the software market. Many
corporations have been postponing software purchases until after
the year Year  &LR; 2000. Companies have been concentrating on
preventing Y2K problems instead of buying the database and
applications software that Oracle and other companies sell.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Henley, Oracle's chief financial officer, said the Y2K
slowdown was not as much of an issue as some had feared but
cautioned that there are still six months left in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``Year 2000 is still out there. We're halfway through the
calendar year, but the industry isn't quite sure what will happen
as we move through this year,'' Henley said. ``However, we don't
see anything that leads us to believe (the first) quarter is
slowing down.
</P>
<P>
   The company also had a strong fiscal year overall. Earnings for
the fiscal year ended May 31 were up 58.5 percent to $1.29 billion
(87 cents per share), compared to $813.7 million (54 cents) a year
ago. Revenue was also up 24 percent to $8.83 billion from $7.14
billion last year.
</P>
<P>
   Ellison said Oracle's database software sales are stronger than
those of such rivals as Microsoft and IBM and predicted the company
would continue to snatch market share.
</P>
<P>
   ``All you need to use any Oracle application is a standard
Internet browser,'' Ellison said. ``In contrast, all of our
competitors (with the exception of Ariba, a database software
competitor) still sell older, more costly client-server
technology.'' Ellison said Oracle is also outselling Ariba in some
areas.
</P>
<P>
   He pointed to strong growth in software license revenue, which
was 22 percent higher than last year's fourth quarter. New sales of
database software rose 21 percent to $1.21 billion from $993.5
million a year ago, while database services revenues increased 21
percent to $971 million from $802.2 million.
</P>
<P>
   The earnings were released after financial markets closed
yesterday while the layoffs were disclosed during trading. Oracle
stock slumped 5 percent, closing at $25.13 a share on the Nasdaq
Stock Market, down $1.31 for the day.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
