<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-15 21:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6628 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-HELSINKI-NYT &LR;      06-15 1096
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-HELSINKI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. OFFERING COMPROMISES ON ROLE OF RUSSIANS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also KOSOVO-RUSSIA; note byline change from early budgets) 
(mk) 
 By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GENEVA _ In an effort to break an impasse over how Russian
troops will operate in Kosovo, Secretary of Defense William Cohen
is to suggest to his Russian counterpart that the troops be
allotted an ``area of responsibility'' within one of the five
established NATO sectors, administration officials said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen also plans to propose a command structure that he hopes
will satisfy the Russians' demand that their troops not report
directly to an allied commander, but will not violate NATO's
insistence on a unified command for the entire security force, the
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen and his counterpart, Igor Sergeyev, are to meet in
Helsinki, Finland, on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen is bringing two possible compromises on the sensitive
issue.
</P>
<P>
   The first is that the Russians report to a commander from a
neutral, non-NATO country, like Sweden or Finland, an
administration official said. This commander would report to a more
senior NATO officer.
</P>
<P>
   The other possibility is that the Russians duplicate the pattern
used in Bosnia, where Russian troops operate in the American sector
and report to an American commander. He in turn reports to a
Russian liaison officer at NATO headquarters in Brussels, Belgium.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of involving Cohen and Sergeyev in the talks _ and
moving the dispute away from diplomats _ came from the Russians, an
administration official said, after Deputy Secretary of State
Strobe Talbott and the Russian foreign minister, Igor Ivanov,
failed to come to a solution over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   But on the eve of the defense secretaries' talks, senior NATO
military commanders are concerned that the political need to keep
good relations with Russia will interfere with the allies' military
need to insure control over the peacekeeping troops.
</P>
<P>
   The alliance will not be represented during the talks. Instead,
the NATO secretary-general, Javier Solana, and the alliance's top
military commander, Gen. Wesley Clark, will be kept informed by
telephone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Remember, this is an administration that prides itself on
constructive engagement with Russia,'' a senior NATO official said
Tuesday. ``These administration officials do not wish to
acknowledge that Russian high officials have been stringing them
along all week.''
</P>
<P>
   But Kenneth Bacon, the Pentagon spokesman, said: ``It doesn't
seem to me we're sweeping this under the rug _ quite the contrary.
We are spending a lot of time and high-level energy and so are the
Russians on this issue. That's a sign we want a solution that's
good for the Russians and for NATO.''
</P>
<P>
   The standoff has touched a raw nerve in the administration, and
not only because the surprise arrival of Russian troops at the
airport in Pristina, the capital of Kosovo, robbed NATO of a grand
entry into Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The underlying concern, administration officials assert, is that
while Russian involvement is welcome, it is welcome on grounds that
do not subvert two administration goals: that there be no partition
of Kosovo and that the allies maintain a unified command of all
security forces.
</P>
<P>
   In arguing that the Russians take an ``area of responsibility''
and the proposed command structure, Cohen will not cross the ``red
lines'' of partition and unified command, administration officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   The ``area of responsibility'' for Russia _ most likely in the
north and thus most likely in the French zone, where there is the
largest concentration of Serb civilians _ would have a
concentration of Russian troops but allied forces would be able to
come and go, an official said.
</P>
<P>
   The session in Helsinki comes as President Clinton arrives here
for the start of a six-day European trip, including a meeting with
President Boris Yeltsin of Russia on Sunday in Cologne, Germany.
The two presidents have spoken on the phone three times in three
days, a rare number of back-to-back calls and a measure of the
volatility of the issue.
</P>
<P>
   The administration would like to have the Russian role settled
by Sunday so the men can publicly embrace a deal at a summit
meeting of the seven major industrial nations and Russia.
</P>
<P>
   The Russians showed no signs Tuesday of leaving the Pristina
airport; indeed, a convoy of 11 vehicles is en route from Bosnia to
resupply the approximately 200 Russians in Pristina with fuel and
food.
</P>
<P>
   But NATO officials said they were encouraged that this time the
Russians requested permission from the NATO commanders in Bosnia to
leave their posts and take the supplies. Last week, when the convoy
of Russians left Bosnia for Kosovo, they did so without informing
the commanders in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   The unexpected fuss over the Russian troops was in part a price
to be paid for the help that Moscow provided Washington in getting
President Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia to accept a withdrawal
from Kosovo, allied officials said.
</P>
<P>
   It is still unclear how high the price will be, or which faction
in the Russian political elite will be decisive in reacting to
Cohen's proposals.
</P>
<P>
   But the Russians have always made it clear that their main
objective in Kosovo is to protect the Serbs, an administration
official said.
</P>
<P>
   The largest concentration of Serbs is in the north, the area
monitored by the French. The British military control a sector
centered on Pristina, and the Americans are operating a zone in the
southeast. Germany and Italy are moving into two other sectors, in
the south and west.
</P>
<P>
   Another interest for the Russians, according to officials, is to
protect what is left of the the economic interests of the Serbs in
Kosovo. The Trepca smelting complex, which includes the Stari Trg
lead and zinc mines, is in northern Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   By giving the Russians an area of responsibility inside a
NATO-led zone, administration officials argue, their presence
should not deter the return of Albanian refugees. Many refugees
have told officials of the U.N. high commissioner for refugees that
they would not go back to their homes if Russian troops were
patrolling where they lived.
</P>
<P>
   But in any area where a lot of Serbs are still living, the
return of Albanians is unlikely anyway, one administration official
said.
</P>
<P>
   It is also not clear how big the ``area'' for Russia would be. A
realistic number of Russian soldiers for Kosovo is in the vicinity
of ``several thousand,'' so the area would have to be
``decent-sized,'' the official said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-15-99 2126EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990615.0326 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-15 21:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6630 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Y2K-Y2K_SFCHRON &LR;      06-15 0907
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K-Y2K </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Senate OKs Limits On Y2K Lawsuits  &HT;     By Benny Evangelista 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
The Senate handed Silicon Valley an important win yesterday by
handily passing legislation protecting companies from lawsuits
stemming from the Year 2000 computer problem.
<P>
   High-tech firms are eager to head off a flood of lawsuits that
could top an unprecedented $1 trillion in damages if computers run
amok next year. However, the industry still has to overcome a
threatened veto from the White House, which objects the bill erodes
the legal rights of consumers and reduces pressure on computer
companies to solve Y2K problems.
</P>
<P>
   The 62-to-37 vote fell five votes short of the two-thirds
majority needed for the ``veto-proof'' bill some high-tech industry
supporters were predicting last week.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation, by Republican presidential hopeful John McCain
of Arizona, would delay the filing of Y2K lawsuits during a 30- to
90-day cooling-off period, make it harder for consumers to file
suits if their computers crash and limit punitive damages in
certain cases.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &LR;   &LR; House Version Differs
</P>
<P>
   The bill now goes to a congressional conference committee to
reconcile differences between the Senate version and one passed by
the House on May 12.
</P>
<P>
   High-tech leaders fear the White House will try to water down
the bill. The industry wants to protect a provision that would hold
companies liable only for the losses they caused, not for damages
attributable to suppliers or others.
</P>
<P>
   Under current law, companies that are held responsible for a
portion of damages can be forced to pay the entire amount, which
could inspire a rash of lawsuits against ``deep pocket'' firms like
Microsoft and Intel, even if they had only marginal responsibility
for a Y2K problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a significant victory, but the key is now the role of
the White House,'' said Bill Calder, spokesman for Intel, the Santa
Clara chipmaker that has been one of the major proponents of the
bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to be able to try to get through this without a flood
of frivolous lawsuits and so far, the White House has not indicated
they are going to support high technology,'' Calder said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &LR;   &LR; Software Problem
</P>
<P>
   The Y2K problem stems from a widely used software programming
shortcut that may cause computer systems to crash because they
don't recognizing dates on Jan. 1, 2000, and afterward.
</P>
<P>
   Flexing their new-found political muscle, computer firms made
passage of the bill their top legislative priority.
</P>
<P>
   The industry framed the issue as a vote for or against high
tech, and it aligned support from a wide array of business
interests, from retailers to manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   The bill had the support of 12 Democrats and 50 Republicans,
with 33 Democrats and four Republicans voting against it.
California's two Democratic senators were split on the vote, with
Dianne Feinstein voting yes and Barbara Boxer voting no.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still haven't won,'' said Marc Pearl, general counsel for
the Information Technology Association of America, the trade group
leading lobbying efforts for the bill. ``When we went into this, it
was viewed as an information technology bill. In essence, it became
a pro-business bill, it became a pro-economy bill.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &LR;   &LR; `Laundry List'
</P>
<P>
   Pearl said the White House has signaled that it wants to include
language requiring companies to go through ``a laundry list of
steps'' to prove they did everything possible to avoid Y2K
problems.
</P>
<P>
   The bill's opponents warned that it will hurt consumers. Joan
Mulhern of Public Citizen, a consumer advocacy group, told the
Associated Press that the bill ``is clearly just a special interest
giveaway to the high-tech and business lobby.''
</P>
<P>
   Senator Ernest Hollings, D-S.C., the most vocal opponent of the
legislation, told reporters Congress was moving to ``do away with
200 years of liability law at the state level'' in the chase for
political donations from the business and high-tech industries.
</P>
<P>
   Both the House and Senate versions of the bill would place
limits on lawsuits and damages, although the House version is
regarded as stronger.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate's version would limit punitive damages to $250,000
for companies with 50 or fewer employees. The House version
includes a general $250,000 punitive damages cap and routes all Y2K
class action suits to federal courts instead of state courts.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Lawyer Calls Bill Unnecessary
</P>
<P>
   Curtis E.A. Karnow, a San Francisco attorney handling Y2K cases
for the firm Sonnenschein, Nath and Rosenthal, said the bill is
unnecessary because current tort laws give businesses enough
protections from frivolous Y2K claims.
</P>
<P>
   He also said the proposed legislation leaves enough loopholes
for lawyers to file Y2K liability suits.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have an umbrella there, lawyers will see it as their
job to find a way to get out from under the umbrella,'' Karnow
said.
</P>
<P>
   Silicon Valley is making no secret that a White House veto could
turn the Y2K bill into a Year 2000 campaign headache for Vice
President Al Gore, who is courting the technology industry for
support in his bid for president.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an extremely important issue for us now,'' said Intel's
Calder. ``We're counting on Vice President Gore and the White House
to come to the table and declare their support for the bill that
was passed today, in its current form.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
