<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GROW-GROW </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROW A BUSINESS/PETER SINTON 
</HEADLINE>
 A BUSINESS _ SF CHRON   Quietly Publicizing the Sale of a Business 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Q: &LR;  I have a successful business and am interested in tips on how &LR; 
 &LR; to sell it in a most confidential way. &LR;
<P>
   &LR;   &LR; A: Selling a business definitely can be tricky. You want to
get out the word and attract the highest price. But you don't want
to scare off customers, employees and suppliers or expose them to
attack from sharklike rivals.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco business consultant Paul Terry offers some advice.
Most small businesses that sell out are acquired by employees,
competitors or others within their industry. One way to contact
potential outside buyers is to enlist the help of an accountant,
attorney, consultant, insurance or business broker or other
intermediary.
</P>
<P>
   Have them make quiet referrals. They should provide enough
information to prospective buyers to gauge their interest but not
enough to give them a blueprint on how to raid your clientele or
staff.
</P>
<P>
   Another approach is to advertise discretely in a trade magazine,
business opportunity section of the classified ads, or online.
However, you probably won't want to provide the exact name or
location of your enterprise at the outset.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most important rules of selling a business is to
``run it as if it were not being sold,'' says Terry. Owners who
forget to mind the store they are selling often end up with less
business and a lower sales price.
</P>
<P>
   If employees hear that you plan to sell the business before you
are ready to tell them, there are ways to provide an answer without
going into all the details. Terry suggests that you might say the
business is always open to buyout offers for the right price.
</P>
<P>
   Remember, too, that the new owners most likely are paying for a
successful operating business, not just the assets. That includes
talented employees and your customer relationships.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Liability Coverage
</P>
<P>
   Q: I work on design services and project management as a
subcontractor for architecture and engineering firms. What are my
professional liability-insurance requirements?
</P>
<P>
   A: In many cases, the prime contractors (the firms you work for)
have their own liability insurance requirements. Or their customers
mandate a certain amount of coverage. You might check with them.
</P>
<P>
   There is no law that you must have your own insurance. But for
peace of mind and protection of your assets, insurance experts
suggest that you should have your own professional liability
coverage, often called errors and omission insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Ingrid Merriwether, CEO of Merriwether &AMP; Williams Insurance
Services in San Francisco, often recommends that consultants such
as yourself take out coverage of at least $1 million. If you are
sued for errors or omissions in your work, you would be covered for
legal costs as well as claims. Insurance premiums often are based
on your revenues. If your annual gross receipts are about $100,000,
Merriwether suggests that the yearly premium for a $1 million
policy would be about $2,200.
</P>
<P>
   You also might want general liability coverage to protect you
from personal injury and property damage claims. This might cost an
additional $500 to $750.
</P>
<P>
   For best rates, check with the American Institute of Architects
or other industry organizations with which you may be associated.
These typically refer members to carriers with the appropriate
coverage at favorable rates.
</P>
<P>
   You also can check with independent insurance agents in the
phone book or associations such as the Independent Insurance Agents
of America in Alexandria, Va.  &LR; (www.independentagent.com). &LR;  This
Web site also offers a guide to small-business insurance.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
