<HEADER>
A6633 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HERBGUYS-HERBGUYS_SFC     06-15 1745
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HERBGUYS-HERBGUYS </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Herbal Wellness Is Big Business  &HT;     By Peter Sinton 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Second-grade teacher Victoria Knight-McDowell got so sick of
catching colds from her students in Salinas that she and her
husband developed effervescent tablets from Chinese herbs and other
ingredients to help ward off germs and viruses.
<P>
   Commercial sales of their first effort, fittingly called
Airborne, have done so well that their company plans to introduce
other formulations, including herbally laced ice pops for kids.
</P>
<P>
   Airborne is not the only herbal product to take off recently.
Other so-called ``eco-entrepreneurs'' are jumping on the herbal
bandwagon. In Sausalito, for instance, chiropractor David Schanaker
and his wife Erika Trice-Schanaker  &LR; have cooked up a new type of
high-energy snack called Bodhi Bar with therapeutic doses of roots
and herbs.
</P>
<P>
   And near Santa Cruz, Brian Lovejoy, a former Odwalla fruit juice
designer, has created DrinksThatWork, which packs a similar
botanical punch.
</P>
<P>
   Northern California has long been a mecca for fresh ideas and
organic products free of man-made chemicals. Now it is playing an
important role in the so-called herbal renaissance movement of the
1990s, where roots and herbs increasingly are being added to
products for their reputed, but not always proven, health benefits.
</P>
<P>
   That is because the market for health foods and vitamin, herbal
and other supplements has shifted during over  &LR; the past three
decades from ``health fanatics, body builders and `crunchy granola'
types'' to a much broader group of consumers, said David Wright, a
director of the Hartman Group in Bellevue, Wash.
</P>
<P>
   Driving this new ``green'' mainstream is the aging population,
changing attitudes about food (from getting enough to getting the
right stuff) as well as increasing interest in alternative medicine
and warding off illness.
</P>
<P>
   The shift is certainly evident in the rising sales of herbal
products. While overall food sales grew only about 2 percent last
year, natural food sales were up 8 percent and organic food sales
were up 14 percent., according to Nutrition Business Journal in San
Diego. Meanwhile, sales of botanical and dietary supplements soared
33 percent, which was double the 1997 growth rate.
</P>
<P>
   Experts at Natural Business Communications' third annual
investment and market trends conference in Berkeley last week also
made these observations about this fast-growing market segment:
</P>
<P>
   _Natural products companies raised about $1 billion in public
offerings last year, five times as much as they did in 1997, and
there were 65 mergers and acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   _Mainstream food vendors such as General Mills, Kellogg, Lipton
and Pillsbury are launching their own natural products.
</P>
<P>
   _Major pharmaceutical companies such as Bayer, Unilever and
Warner-Lambert are entering the less-regulated dietary supplement
market. Last week, Warner-Lambert took a minority stake in San
Francisco's Healthshop.com, a leading Web site for natural health
products and information.
</P>
<P>
   _There are now about 1,300 1300  &LR; companies in natural foods,
beverages and supplements, including more than 30 online
specialists. Total U.S. revenues top $23 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Among the new buzzwords are ``nutraceuticals,'' which refers to
food, drinks and supplements purchased primarily for health
reasons, and ``functional foods,'' which are fortified with
botanical ingredients to provide health benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Popular functional ingredients include ginseng, ginkgo biloba,
echinacea, goldenseal, Saint-John's-wort St. John' wort &LR;   &LR; and kava,
a Polynesian root used for ceremonial and medicinal purposes.
</P>
<P>
   Bodhi Bar of Sausalito is taking its energy bar to new and
pricier levels. In addition to the usual organic nuts, fruits and
seeds, the Bodhi Bar throws in what the owners call therapeutic
doses of ``adaptogenic'' (stress-reducing) herbs such as Siberian
ginseng, astragalus and schizandra.
</P>
<P>
   The gritty-tasting bars sell for $1.75 to $1.89 retail and come
in three flavors: pineapple ginger ginseng, cardamom mango
astragalus and schizandra cherry ginseng.
</P>
<P>
   The company was started two years ago by David  &LR; Schanaker, 42,
and his wife, Erika Trice-Schanaker, 35. Their aim was to produce a
new natural food bar that in addition to providing a shot of energy
was easy to digest, could relieve stress, strengthen the immune
system and perform other feats.
</P>
<P>
   Bodhi Bars are manufactured by Barbara's Bakery in Sacramento
and are sold at Whole Foods, Molly Stone, Raley's and other
outlets. The company produces about 60,000 bars a month and is
developing new products, including a calcium-rich bar designed for
women and gel packs with a shot of herbal elixir.
</P>
<P>
   Another local herbal startup is DrinksThatWork. The company was
started two years ago by Brian  &LR; Lovejoy, the former Odwalla
marketing vice president Brian Lovejoy,  &LR; who designed such drinks
as C Monster, Mo' Beta and Super Food for the big natural juice
company
</P>
<P>
   But Lovejoy wanted to move from nutrition to herbal therapies.
He teamed with ethnobotanist Dennis McKenna, former Odwalla Chief
Operating Officer Michael Young and Joel McCleary, who has a kava
farm on Molokai in Hawaii. The company now &LR;   &LR; occupies Odwalla's old
headquarters in Davenport, north of Santa Cruz.
</P>
<P>
   DrinksThatWork come in three seven-ounce formulations: Forza,
including Saint-John's-wort St. John's wort  &LR; and ginseng for
sustainable energy; Kava, with 500 milligrams of Polynesian kava,
to improve well-being; and Luna, a spicy soy milk blend that
includes valerian root, chamomile and griffonia seed, to help one
sleep better.
</P>
<P>
   The $2.69 suggested retail price is prices are  &LR; double what many
other beverages sell for, or a multiple of that considering their
small size. But like its name, DrinksThatWork promises more than
refreshment. ``We're not selling juice,'' said Lovejoy, 36. ``The
purpose is to provide a therapeutic dose of herbs.''
</P>
<P>
   The company says it packs 10 to 100 times as much botanical
punch in its elixirs as other herbal beverages. That extra punch
can get expensive. For example, West African griffonia seed extract
processed in India costs about $545 a pound.
</P>
<P>
   As for the taste, several shoppers, who got free samples at
Whole Foods in San Francisco last week, said it was ``pretty good
for an herbal drink'' but not exactly delicious.
</P>
<P>
   Lovejoy notes that most people do not love the taste of beer or
coffee the first time they try them, either. Just as people move
from soda pop to more-adult beverages, he hopes they will migrate
to herbal therapy in a bottle. Since March, the company has won
shelf space in more than 120 retail stores, including Wild Oats,
and  &LR; Rainbow Foods and some fancy hotels.
</P>
<P>
   There are plenty of other New Age beverage-makers who are adding
botanicals to their blends. But sometimes these are little more
than cleverly packaged sugar water and fruit juice concoctions
containing only traces of medicinal herbs.
</P>
<P>
   Among the new vendors of these ``New Age'' herbal beverages are
AriZona and South Beach of Norwalk, Conn. SoBe, as it is called,
branched into herb-spiked drinks two years ago when its line of
conventional cold tea drinks fizzled. With the help of clever
marketing and a cute lizard logo, sales of SoBe's Lizard Blizzard,
Zen Blend and other colorful drinks are approaching $200 million,
and health-conscious Northern California is the biggest market.
</P>
<P>
   Odwalla has a successful line of ``nutra smoothies.'' Ice
cream-maker Ben &AMP; Jerry's launched a line of botanically bolstered
frozen smoothies last month, and Snapple also has a new line of
Elements drinks.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes entrepreneurs catch the business bug almost by
accident. Teacher Knight-McDowell, 39, and her writer-husband,
Rider McDowell, 38, turned herbal entrepreneurs to help ward off
infection.
</P>
<P>
   ``Schools are rife with germs, and I was always getting a cold
from my second-grade kids at Spreckels Elementary School near
Salinas,'' said Knight-McDowell. ``And Rider was always getting
sick on airplanes.''
</P>
<P>
   She tried various pills and potions to ward off germs and
viruses, but they didn't seem to work.
</P>
<P>
   So when Hallmark paid McDowell Rider  &LR; $150,000 to turn a script
into a TV movie, they invested the proceeds and then some to
develop their own cold-fighting formula. They set set up
Knight-McDowell Labs in Carmel and hired nutritionists and
herbalists to come up with the formula, which includes organic
herbal extracts of lonicera, forsythia and schizonepeta.
</P>
<P>
   To market their product on the cheap, they Knight-McDowell &LR; 
 &LR; initially handed out postcards with tablets attached in crowded
urban malls and put them on the windshields of cars in airport
parking lots.
</P>
<P>
   Until January, they relied on online and telephone sales. Then
they got placement in Trader Joe's stores where Airborne has been
selling briskly at $5.99 per 10-tablet tube. They also are selling
at several Long's Drug, independent travel and other stores.
</P>
<P>
   Fans of Airborne include actor Kevin Costner and 49ers head
athletic trainer Lindsey McLean. With annual revenues approaching
$1 million, Knight-McDowell is selling a third of the company to
the head of a $100 million a year East Coast manufacturing company
who will run it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Growing a business so quickly is exhilarating but also a
little scary,'' said Rider. &LR; McDowell. ``Sometimes you don't realize
what you don't know.
</P>
<P>
   Knight-McDowell, who has not given up teaching, hopes to spend
less time running the new business. Still, she and her husband are
pursuing new products: Doc-Pops, out this fall, are freezer pops in
four fruit flavors fortified with menthol, echinacea, ginger and
other additives.
</P>
<P>
   Recovery MD is a new line of effervescent tablets with herbs and
enzymes designed to help heal athletic injuries and treat hospital
patients before and after surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Importers of herbal ingredients also are doing well.
</P>
<P>
   At Starwest Botanicals in Rancho Cordova near Sacramento, sales
increased nearly close to  &LR; 30 percent to around $10 million last
year, according to salesman James Lynn. Prices vary widely
depending on the herb or root and the specific active ingredients.
Powder extract for Siberian ginseng (0.8 percent active ingredient)
sells for about $12 a pound, while kava extract powder (30 percent
active ingredient) goes for about $73 a pound.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
