<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-15 21:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6634 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SNAKEOIL-SNAKEOIL_SFC     06-15 1230
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SNAKEOIL-SNAKEOIL </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Herbal Remedies Can't Make Claims  &HT;     By Tom Abate 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
Five years after Congress simplified the rules for selling herbs,
minerals and nutritional supplements, Food and Drug Administration
regulators are still struggling with how to label these products.
<P>
   A lot is at stake. The herbal and nutritional supplement vendors
feel federal law inhibits what they can say about the health
benefits of their products. But some consumer groups want the
federal government to do more testing to ensure that these products
are safe. At the same time, large pharmaceutical companies are
entering this lucrative market with their own ax to grind on the
issue of labeling.
</P>
<P>
   On July 20, the agency will hold a daylong public hearing on
these matters and other issues arising from the Dietary Supplement
Health and Education Act of 1994, the law that spurred the
so-called herbal renaissance.
</P>
<P>
   Supplements have become a huge industry, with Americans spending
more than $12 billion annually on products ranging from herbs that
purportedly improve memory to proteins that supposedly help people
bulk up.
</P>
<P>
   With supplement sales beginning to rival the $17 billion that
Americans spend each year on over-the-counter drugs, some large
drug companies like Bayer, Warner-Lambert and American Home
Products have jumped into the growing market for herbs and
supplements.
</P>
<P>
   FDA regulators find themselves caught between those who want
them to hurry up and those who want them to slow down this new
market.
</P>
<P>
   In Congress, Representative Dan Burton, R-Ind., chairman of the
House Government Reform Committee, held two hearings this spring in
which he accused the FDA of impeding the supplement industry out of
what he considers a misplaced concern for safety. He said only 16
people reportedly died last year from herb overdoses, compared to
106,000 deaths from prescription drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is more likely that you will be struck by lighting and die
in this country than it is that you will die from using a dietary
supplement,'' Burton said.
</P>
<P>
   But some consumer groups, led by the Center for Science in the
Public Interest of Washington, D.C., think the potential health
risks of herbal remedies have been vastly understated, because the
FDA has not yet created a central system that requires
manufacturers to report adverse effects.
</P>
<P>
   ``The law went too far too fast in the direction of
deregulation,'' said center legal director Bruce Silverglade. Among
other reforms, the center thinks supplement-makers should be
required to pay for studies proving the safety of their products
before they go on sale, as do makers of drugs or medical devices.
</P>
<P>
   But any such move would drastically alter the law Congress wrote
in 1994, when it put herbs, vitamins, minerals and proteins in a
special regulatory category, said Annette Dickinson, director of
the herb industry trade group Council for Responsible Nutrition, of
Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Dickinson said Congress decided in 1994 that supplements, most
of which had been sold as folk remedies or food additives before
the law took effect, had been proven safe by years of use.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are things that have been around for a long, long time,''
Dickinson said.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Congress freed supplement-makers from the
requirements placed on drug manufacturers, such as performing
safety tests and winning FDA approval before they can market a new
remedy.
</P>
<P>
   Supplement-makers skip this approval step, Dickinson said. If
supplement-makers want to sell a well-known herb or protein
extract, they just do it, she said. Even companies that want to
sell entirely new herbal or protein concoctions follow a simple
process. They tell the FDA what they plan to sell. The agency has
75 days to object if it thinks the new product might not be safe.
This procedure contrasts with the drug preapproval process, which
can take up to 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   But there is a catch in the 1994 law. While it expedites the
process for delivering products to market, it limits what can be
said about them, according to Rob McCaleb with Colorado's Herb
Research Foundation. Herbal manufacturers cannot claim their
products treat, cure or mitigate disease.
</P>
<P>
   This might stun consumers who have heard about the supposed
beneficial effects many herbs have on a variety of diseases. But
that consumer information must come from health newsletters or
other media, because the law restricts what herb vendors can say on
product labels or in ads.
</P>
<P>
   McCaleb used the example of garlic, which many people buy for
its supposed cholesterol-lowering properties.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a company says, `Garlic helps prevent health disease,' that
would be a drug claim'' and a no-no under the 1994 law, McCaleb
said. Instead, supplement-makers would have to say something like,
``garlic helps maintain cardiovascular health,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The difference between mentioning a specific disease and talking
about general health effects may seem like semantics, but that is
the nature of rule making. And so far, the FDA has been unable to
find the words to please all the groups interested in the labeling
issue.
</P>
<P>
   Burton, echoing complaints from supplement-makers, has berated
the FDA for proposing to define menopause, pregnancy and aging as
diseases _ thus preventing herbmakers from using these words in
labels or ads.
</P>
<P>
   The entry of drugmakers into the nutritional supplement market
has complicated the regulatory situation. Over-the-counter drugs
are generally former prescription drugs that have gone off patent.
Before a drug becomes generic, the patent holder seeks FDA approval
to sell a version of the drug directly to consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Once that approval is secured, the OTC vendor can say the drug
treats a specific disease, according to Joe Doss of the Consumer
Healthcare Products Association of Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   The association _ which was until recently called the
Nonprescription Drug Manufacturers Association _ wants to make sure
the new FDA labeling rules for supplements do not give the herbal
manufacturers the ability to make disease-fighting claims that OTC
manufacturers enjoy.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, McCaleb of the Herb Research Foundation thinks the
entry of the OTC drugmakers into the herb patch will prove a
blessing to the whole industry, as well as consumers.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, McCaleb thinks drug vendors will demand clear
rules from the FDA governing the manufacturing of herbal
supplements. One consistent consumer complaint is that herbs and
supplements vary greatly in quality or concentration even between
batches from the same manufacturing plant.
</P>
<P>
   The 1994 law ordered the FDA to set up a manufacturing review
program, but that process has lagged. McCaleb thinks big drugmakers
like Bayer or AHP will light a fire under the FDA's inspection
efforts.
</P>
<P>
   FDA regulators will hear these and other critiques at their July
20 hearing in Oakland. In testimony before Burton's committee
earlier this year, new FDA Commissioner Jane Henney acknowledged
the ``great faith'' many Americans place in supplements and the
frustration some feel with the agency's implementation of the law.
</P>
<P>
   ``The challenge to FDA is to strike the right balance'' between
safety concerns and the expansion of the herbal marketplace, Henney
said.
</P>
<P>
