<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-15 21:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6635 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MICROSOFT-MICROSOFT_S     06-15 0734
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-MICROSOFT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 _ SF CHRON   Gates Wows 'Em at Summit On High Tech 
 &HT;     By Carolyn Lochhead 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; Microsoft Chairman Bill Gates swept into a Capitol Hill hearing
room yesterday like an international celebrity, cameras flashing
and senators genuflecting before the undisputed uber-mogul of
American business.
<P>
   Despite his nondescript testimony, Gates drew a
standing-room-only crowd to the cavernous Hart Building on day two
of the Joint Economic Committee's three-day ``National Summit on
High Technology.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan, whose utterances
are as closely dissected as the pope's, couldn't draw half the
crowd for his testimony the day before.
</P>
<P>
   Politicians often don't show up for hearings, especially those
held by powerless panels like the Joint Committee, but Gates filled
the raised dais with everyone from Silicon Valley representatives
Tom Campbell, a South Bay Republican, and Anna Eshoo, D-Atherton,
to Washington state  &LR; Senators Slade Gorton and Patty Murray.
</P>
<P>
   Gorton, a Republican, and Murray, a Democrat, share a loyalty to
the Redmond, Wash., software giant that trumps their usual partisan
differences. Gorton called Gates ``a constituent and a friend.''
</P>
<P>
   Other politicians flashed their own high-tech credentials, with
Representative Carolyn Maloney, D-N.Y., boasting of Manhattan's
``Silicon Alley.''
</P>
<P>
   A self-described computer geek and the world's richest man,
Gates hunched over the witness table and spoke in his
characteristic high-pitched voice punctuated by the occasional
squeak. Outlining his vision of a technological transformation of
the world, he urged the government to tread lightly.
</P>
<P>
   ``The incredible success of this industry in the United States
owes a lot to the light hand of government in the technology area,
the fact that people can take incredible risks and, if they're
successful, they can have incredible rewards,'' Gates said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The risk-taking attitude is unique to the United States ...
and is the envy of the world,'' he said. ``The basic philosophy of
letting the marketplace work has been vindicated.''
</P>
<P>
   Inside a federal courthouse just a few blocks away, Microsoft is
fighting for its life in an epic antitrust battle. The Justice
Department accuses Microsoft of monopolizing personal computer
software and illegally taking over the Internet browser market.
</P>
<P>
   Senator Charles Robb, a Virginia Democrat, tentatively asked
Gates, ``without regard to the specifics of pending litigation,''
whether he would alter the nation's antitrust laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are many people who dive into that, but I think the laws
as they are currently written are fine,'' Gates said. But he
touched on the heart of the trial, obliquely defending Microsoft's
right to incorporate Internet browsers into its Windows platform.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; ``Certainly everything that's gone on in the technology
industry has come about because of  &LR; things like integrating new
features in  &LR; is one of the freedoms that all companies have,''
Gates said.
</P>
<P>
   Eight young protesters glared silently from against one wall,
their T-shirts declaring, ``Limit Wealth'' and ``Bust the Trust.''
They said they were from the Ralph Nader-backed groups Public
Citizen and the Congressional Accountability Project.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of twentysomething lobbyists seated in the front rows
behind the witness table glanced back scornfully, shaking their
heads in bemused disapproval.
</P>
<P>
   They then turned back to listen to Gates talk about the
high-tech industry creating ``the greatest time of innovation and
change in history.''
</P>
<P>
   The Internet and the convergence of telecommunications,
computers and consumer electronics, Gates said, will create ``a
proliferation of smart, connected devices, from palm-size digital
assistants and `tablet' personal computers to smart TVs and
Web-enabled cell phones.''
</P>
<P>
   He envisioned a world where consumers manage their work and
their lives from a personal ``digital dashboard'' and a time ``in
the not too distant future (when) computers will be able to see,
listen and speak.''
</P>
<P>
   Gates then took a few more friendly questions from students
hooked up via satellite video conferencing from several high
schools and a college.
</P>
<P>
   Finishing his appearance, he left the room, and much of the
audience left with him.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
