   (NYT24) NEW YORK -- June 15, 1999 -- SUB-MORGAN-STANLEY, 6-15 --
Charles Joseph Luethke is a self-styled whistle blower whose
dealings with Morgan Stanley Dean Witter put them both under
criminal investigation. Luethke's jousting with Morgan Stanley over
a $10,000 payment embarassed that top Wall Street firm and led to
the resignations of two top lawyers there. (Jeffery A. Salter/New
York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) ABU GHOSH, Israel -- June 15, 1999 -- ISRAELI-ARAB, 6-15
-- Jawdad Ibrahim visits his grandmother, Umm Jawdad. When he lived
in the U.S., Ibrahim won a $17.5 million jackpot in the Illinois
State Lottery in 1990. Forced to sue to get the prize denied him on
a technicality, the lawsuit increased his earnings to $22.7
million. Ibrahim has parlayed the money into making himself an
emissary of peace trying to bring Israelis and Arabs together in
his home village just outside Jerusalem. (Rina Castelnuovo/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) NEW YORK -- June 15, 1999 -- VIRTUAL-ORCHESTRA, 6-15 --
David Leighton, the Operaworks conductor, with J. Patrick Casey,
who operates a computer and keyboard to provide a ``virtual
orchestra.'' ``We have a bank of about 30 sounds'' says Casey.
``Strings, strings playing pizzicato, flute, trumpet, cymbal
crashes, whatever.'' (Susan Farley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) NEW YORK -- June 15, 1999 -- HEMINGWAY-SON-PROFILE, 6-14
-- Jack Hemingway and Papa bonded as they hunted, fished and boxed.
Hemingway's firstborn probably had the best of his Papa, in the
early years before the ego ballooned and darkness fell. (Fred R.
Conrad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) LITTLETON, Colo. -- June 15, 1999 --
