they were grabbed by Serb forces from refugee convoys trying to
escape into Macedonia or Albania, just like tens of thousands of
other men reported to have been separated from families trying to
leave Kosovo. (Marcia Kunstel/Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) PRISTINA, Yugoslavia -- June 15, 1999 --
KOSOVO-MEN-COX-1, 6-15 -- Bahtir Zeciri, 26, tells his story of
being shot by Yugoslav forces and then placed in a local hospital
which he says was worse then being in a prison. At left is Dr.
Murat Abazi who provided medical attention to Zeciri and several
others while Yugoslav forces were in Pristina. (Marcia Kunstel/Cox
News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEW YORK -- June 15, 1999 -- ZUCCHINI-BLOSSOMS-3, 6-15 --
Views of Chef Romano, of the Union Square Cafe, making a pasta dish
using the zucchini flower. Zucchini blossoms are the fragile
precursor to the fruit on a zucchini plant. They are so visually
remarkable that it is easy to see them as nothing more than
decoration. But they have long been a part of Italian, French and
Mexican cooking. (Jeffery A. Salter/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) ROADSTOWN, N.J. -- June 15, 1999 -- ZUCCHINI-BLOSSOMS-2,
6-15 -- Zucchini blossoms are harvested in a greenhouse before
being shipped to New York City restaurants. Zucchini blossoms are
the fragile precursor to the fruit on a zucchini plant. They are so
visually remarkable that it is easy to see them as nothing more
than decoration. But they have long been a part of Italian, French
and Mexican cooking. (Laura Pendrick/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) NEW YORK -- June 15, 1999 -- ZUCCHINI-BLOSSOMS, 6-15 --
Squash and zucchini blossoms filled with white cheddar cheese,
scallions and poblano chiles prepared by chef Gary Jacobson at
Zarela, a Mexican restaurant in Manhattan. Zucchini blossoms are
the fragile precursor to the fruit on a zucchini plant. They are so
visually remarkable that it is easy to see them as nothing more
than decoration. But they have long been a part of Italian, French
and Mexican cooking. (Jeffery A. Salter/New York Times Photo)
