<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-15 21:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6653 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SUGEN-SUGEN_SFCHRON &LR;      06-15 0449
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUGEN-SUGEN </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Pharmacia Will Buy Sugen for $680 Million  &HT;     By Tom Abate 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
Sugen Inc., a South San Francisco biotech firm, yesterday agreed to
be acquired by New Jersey's Pharmacia &AMP; Upjohn Inc. for $650
million in stock. The companies said the price represented a 38
percent premium on Sugen's closing price yesterday.
<P>
   Executives from both firms said Sugen will retain its name and
local offices, adding that no major layoffs are anticipated. Sugen
employs 210 people in the Bay Area.
</P>
<P>
   This is the latest in a string of deals in which huge
pharmaceutical companies have acquired biotech firms, which have
had trouble raising money on Wall Street to support their costly
drug trials.
</P>
<P>
   Outgoing Sugen chief executive Stephen Evans-Freke alluded to
this yesterday, saying ``the hostile environment for financing''
made it difficult for his company independently.
</P>
<P>
   Pharmacia &AMP; Upjohn chief executive Fred Hassan said his company
is most interested in three Sugen anti-cancer products that are in
late-stage human trials in preparation for seeking Food &AMP; Drug
Administration approval. Sugen is a leader in the field of
anti-angiogenesis, the attempt to shrink tumors by crimping the
supply of blood that fuels their runaway growth.
</P>
<P>
   Jim McCamant with the Medical Technology Stock Letter in
Berkeley, said the current stock slump in biotech seems to have
finally started the sort of consolidation that has been predicted,
but not materialized, in years past.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so tough to raise money, that shareholders are somewhat
impatient and CEOs are not as cocky as they once were to go it on
their own,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The deal was announced after the market closed. Sugen fell 50
cents to $22.50 yesterday, which was close to the stock's 52-week
high.
</P>
<P>
   But though the deal may look good in the short run, Mark
Lampert, a principal with the Biotechnology Value Fund in San
Francisco, said it should concern investors that biotech companies
with products in late-stage trials feel they can't market a hit
drug on their own.
</P>
<P>
   The deal, which is subject to shareholder and regulatory
approval, is planned to close in about three months. Sugen is 20
percent owned by British drugmaker AstraZeneca Group Plc, which has
agreed to vote its shares in favor of the acquisition.
</P>
<P>
   The deal is Pharmacia &AMP; Upjohn's most aggressive move since
1995, when the company formed itself by merging Sweden's Pharmacia
with the U.S.  &LR; Upjohn of the United States. With roughly $7 billion
in sales growing at a 12 percent rate, Pharmacia ranks 10th in size
among U.S. drug companies.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
