<SLUG> BC-BBC-BATS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New bats change college game
 &HT;    By Ron Jackson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Offensive production is down at the College World
Series and one of the reasons is the new restrictions placed on the
aluminum bats used by college baseball players.
</P>
<P>
   Gayston Corp. of Springboro, Ohio is a bat maker for Rawlings.
The company has complied with the new restrictions while others,
like Easton Sports of Van Nuys, Calif., the country's largest
aluminum bat manufacturer, sued the National Collegiate Athletic
Association for $267 million, charging illegal restraint of trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``The NCAA wants a 'wood-like' performance and feel from the
bats,'' said Mark Stone, owner and president of Gayston. ``The
restraints put less bat speed through the zone. It's like a war
club and not as much a safety hazard. It protects pitchers and
infielders.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the bats are shorter and heavier, slowing the
college hitters down.
</P>
<P>
   Stone said changes may be on deck at the high school level.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been a favorable response to the new bat
modifications,'' Stone said. ``I look for the high school
federation to follow the NCAA lead next year, adopting the same
measures.''
</P>
<P>
   Gayston's main business is making metal parts for the military
and auto industry. But several years ago, ``it struck us that we
could use the same process to make a bat,'' Stone said.
</P>
<P>
   Today, about 15 percent of the company's total sales come from
bat sales. Stone declined to reveal sales figures, but said the
company makes ``hundreds of thousands'' each year and that ``it's a
growing part of our business.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Aldridge, a catcher who played four years at Eastern
Michigan University and is now a pitcher for the New York Yankees'
rookie team in Tampa, recalled last year's College World Series
championship when Southern California defeated Arizona State,
21-14. The game lasted four hours as the teams combined for nine
home runs and 39 hits. He said the lean high-tech bats are still
mean.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year they called the College World Series 'Gorilla-ball',
because of all the home runs,'' Aldridge said. ``Now you're seeing
more bunting, running and hit-and-runs in this year's series. The
new bat is heavier coming through the strike zone, but it has still
has some pop.. . . Balls fly off those bats.''
</P>
<P>
   University of Dayton catcher Jason Siegfried, now playing for
the Oneonta (N.Y.) Tigers, a Detroit Tigers Class A team, said it
took him three weeks to adjust to the new bats.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just don't see as many cheap hits with the new bats,''
Siegfried said. The restricted bats have done their job. According
to NCAA records, the Division I batting average was .301, down from
the 1998 average of .306. Home runs per game were 0.93, down from
1.06 last year. A record 62 home runs were hit in the 1998 College
World Series, 14 more than the previous high.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Jackson writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
E-mail: ronjackson(AT)coxohio.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
