<HEADER>
A6656 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSH-NODEBATE-COX     06-15 0782
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-NODEBATE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    George W. may forgo debate, convention
 &HT;    By Brian E. Crowley
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Unlike his dad who competed in two
Republican presidential straw ballots in Florida, Texas Gov. George
W. Bush has forced the GOP to scuttle any idea for a ballot, and
his campaign is even balking at participating in a nationally
televised candidate forum.
</P>
<P>
   ``George Bush doesn't even want to show up at the state party
convention,'' said a frustrated organizer of the October event.
``His campaign is more than interested in coming here to raise
money, but they don't want to do anything else.''
</P>
<P>
   Expecting a $1 million payday June 25, Bush is attending $1,000
per person events in four cities next week in Fort Myers, Tampa,
Fort Lauderdale and Miami. The events are being organized out of a
Miami office by Ann Herberger, who worked for Bush's younger
brother, Jeb, during the race for governor.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, most of the Florida campaign team worked for Jeb Bush
last year. Al Hoffman, chief executive of Watermark Communities
Inc., is the campaign's state finance chairman. Mark Guzzetta, a
partner in Blue Lake development in Boca Raton, is the vice
chairman. Jillian Inmon, director of scheduling in both the
campaign and governor's office, will become the state campaign
manager in September. And unofficially, Bush's chief of staff,
Sally Bradshaw, and director of communications, Cory Tilley, have
assisted the Bush presidential effort.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Jeb Bush has on occasion gone to a private office
in Tallahassee to make phone calls in an effort to raise money for
his brother. While all that is going on, however, some Republicans
are complaining that the Texas governor's campaign is trying to
diminish the impact of the state's fourth presidential convention.
</P>
<P>
   In 1979, former CIA director George Bush fought hard to win
votes in the first GOP presidential straw ballot. Up against Ronald
Reagan, former Texas Gov. John Connally, U.S. Sen. Bob Dole and a
handful of other hopefuls, Bush finished a surprising third behind
Reagan and Connally, who were favored to win.
</P>
<P>
   Eight years later, then-Vice President Bush won the GOP ballot
in a hotly contested race with television evangelist Pat Robertson.
Other contenders included former Secretary of State Alexander Haig,
New York Congressman Jack Kemp and Dole.
</P>
<P>
   CNN's Larry King was the featured attraction at Presidency III,
the 1995 convention. He moderated a debate among the nine
Republican candidates that was broadcast nationwide. The chairman
of the convention was Jeb Bush, who insisted on a high profile
straw ballot and the appearance of all the candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Dole won the ballot, defeating Texas Sen. Phil Gramm, former
Tennessee Gov. Lamar Alexander and six other GOP candidates. Bush
hailed the convention as a huge success.
</P>
<P>
   Now, his big brother wants no part of a straw ballot or
televised debate, even one hosted by ABC's Cokie Roberts, an anchor
of the Sunday program This Week. ``Why would he want to do a
forum?'' asked an adviser to the Bush campaign. ``Why give credence
to his opponents in a state where he doesn't have to?''
</P>
<P>
   Instead of a debate, the Bush camp is leaning toward allowing
each candidate to speak for a few minutes and have separate rooms
for hosting meet-the-candidate gatherings.
</P>
<P>
   GOP state chairman Al Cardenas insists that the convention will
be the best political event in the country this year. ``We are
going to have a lot of national and state press, and when the fever
pitch gets really high, I think you'll find all of the candidates
will participate,'' he said. ``We still absolutely plan on having
Cokie Roberts and some type of forum.''
</P>
<P>
   Cardenas flew to Texas recently to meet with Bush and his
campaign staff. They talked about many things, including the
convention. ``They are just not ready to make a commitment yet,''
he said. ``That's understandable; they have a lot to do right
now.''
</P>
<P>
   Among those are next week's money raising events, which include
among their hosts businessman Wayne Huizenga and U.S. Reps. Mark
Foley of West Palm Beach and E. Clay Shaw of Fort Lauderdale.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter being sent to potential Florida donors, the Bush
campaign is making it clear that money should be contributed soon.
``We must send a strong message of support by contributing now.
Early contributions to this exploratory committee will be the most
important.''
</P>
<P>
   Said one recipient of the letter, ``I think they hope they can
starve out the other candidates long before the state convention.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
