<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MACEDONIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OVER 2,500 RETURN TO KOSOVO; MINE KILLS A WOMAN ON TREK 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By DAVID ROHDE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BLACE, Macedonia _ A woman was killed Tuesday morning by a land
mine as she tried to walk back into Kosovo over a hillside near
here, the first casualty of the journey home. As the number of
refugees joyously returning home from here swelled, the death
pointed up the validity of the warnings from the U.N. high
commissioner for refugees about the dangers the refugees face as
they return.
</P>
<P>
   More than 2,500 refugees surged out of Macedonia back into
Kosovo Tuesday _ seven times the number of refugees who crossed the
border Monday _ traveling on foot, in cars and, in one case, by
chartering their own bus.
</P>
<P>
   The woman's death and the sharp rise in the number of refugees
crossing the border alarmed officials of the refugee agency, who
fear a chaotic rush back into Kosovo. If refugees return to Kosovo
before the one-month period NATO has said it needs to secure the
province, they not only face danger from the land mines, but also
may not be able to support themselves once they return home, the
agency's officials say.
</P>
<P>
   But refugees who gleefully crossed the border here Tuesday
discounted the dangers and said it was their right to return home
now. By midafternoon, a mile-long line of cars had formed at the
border as Macedonian guards slowly processed the refugees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, we're worried about it but there is nothing we can do for
now,'' said Makfride Krasniqi, who was waiting with her parents,
teen-age brother and three young children to return to the nearby
town of Kacanik. ``We just want to go back.''
</P>
<P>
   By dusk the flow had slowed, but Astrid van Genderen Stort, a
refugee agency spokeswoman, said she expected more refugees to make
the trip Wednesday. Her fear, she said, is that the charter bus
idea that was executed successfully Tuesday will spread. The bus
was chartered by a family of 36, who had been living in a refugee
camp, for about $1,200.
</P>
<P>
   The refugee killed by the land mine Tuesday morning was a woman
trekking back into Kosovo with her husband and two friends, the
refugee officials said. The explosion killed her instantly and
wounded her husband.
</P>
<P>
   He made his way to a U.S. Army checkpoint on the Kosovo side of
the border, where he was treated for minor wounds, the officials
said. The man then continued on his way, seemingly determined to
not let anything separate him from his home.
</P>
<P>
   For the last two days, dozens of men sent out by their families
as scouts to determine what living conditions are like inside
Kosovo have been making their way to the towns of Kacanik, Vitina
and Urosevac in southeastern Kosovo, five to 25 miles from the
Macedonian border.
</P>
<P>
   In Kacanik Monday and Tuesday, refugees and men in uniforms of
the insurgent Kosovo Liberation Army let out whoops and shrieks of
joy as they spied each other in the debris-littered streets of a
town where the Kosovars and Yugoslav soldiers had fought fiercely.
</P>
<P>
   The insurgent group has taken de facto control of the town,
setting up its own checkpoints. But nearly all of its troops here
are following orders from their superiors not to carry weapons and
American troops patrolling the town said they have been cooperative
and ``very helpful.''
</P>
<P>
   At the border Tuesday, workers handed out pamphlets describing
the dangers of land mines. But one refugee, Jonos Emini, said,
``Why would I be scared if I am going to my home town? I was never
scared of the Serbs.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
