<HEADER>
A6660 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CPI-STOCKS-COX     06-15 0468
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPI-STOCKS-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Higher interest rates seen on horizon
</P>
<P>
   By David McNaughton
</P>
<P>
   C. 1999 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Marvin Sherman doesn't need today's government report
on consumer prices to know the cost of living is increasing.
</P>
<P>
   ``My haircut just went up,'' he said Tuesday outside a
supermarket. ``You know why? Because the rent went up.''
</P>
<P>
   Housing. Insurance. Gasoline. Autos. College tuition. They've
all gone up in price, too, Sherman says, but not so fast as to jump
out at you.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything has increased, very gradually,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Until the haircut. Until last month.
</P>
<P>
   In mid-May, the government reported the Consumer Price Index
jumped 0.7 percent in April. That surprise knocked the Dow Jones
industrial average back almost 194 points on the day of the
announcement.
</P>
<P>
   The change from what had been a long pattern of small increases
in inflation heightened Wall Street's interest in today's
announcement of the May CPI numbers.
</P>
<P>
   That's because the numbers will help determine whether the
Federal Reserve pushes interest rates higher when its policy-makers
meet June 29 and 30. Or whether there will be more than one
increase aimed at slowing the economy and limiting inflation.
</P>
<P>
   A rate boost at the end of June is pretty much a foregone
conclusion, according to Donald Ratajczak, director of the Economic
Forecasting Center at Georgia State University.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the Fed has already made up its mind to go (up) a
quarter'' percentage point, Ratajczak said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   He expected an increase of 0.3 percent in May's overall CPI, and
0.2 percent for the core rate, which excludes food and energy
prices.
</P>
<P>
   Those are better than the April figures but would signal
``gradually accelerating'' inflation, Ratajczak said.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks recorded modest gains Tuesday ahead of the CPI numbers _
as well as today's news on housing starts, industrial production
and capacity utilization, and the Fed's Beige Book report on
regional economies.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average finished up 0.3 percent, and
the Nasdaq composite added 0.68 percent.
</P>
<P>
   While he thinks inflation will continue to accelerate for
several months, Ratajczak said the consumer price numbers he
forecast for May should not be high enough to trigger more than one
interest rate boost.
</P>
<P>
   Still, inflation, even without leading to an interest rate
boost, affects everyone, he noted, from Social Security recipients
to consumers with variable-rate loans. It can also affect their
expectations, Ratajczak noted:
</P>
<P>
   ``If they hear the CPI is accelerating, they may wonder why
their wages aren't accelerating.''
</P>
<P>
   David McNaughton writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
