<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-15 21:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6663 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DRUGS-OHIO-COX     06-15 0390
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRUGS-OHIO-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    OHIO COUNTIES DESIGNATED DRUG-TRAFFICKING AREA
 &HT;    Attn: Cox Ohio papers.
 &HT;    By RAVEN HILL
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Several northern Ohio counties have been designated
a High Intensity Drug Trafficking Area, the White House Office of
National Drug Control Policy announced Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Cuyahoga, Lucas, Summit, Stark and Mahoning counties are
affected by the designation, which allows federal officials to work
more closely with state and local efforts to reduce drug
trafficking and related violence.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the drug policy office has allocated $700,000 to be
spent this fiscal year for law enforcement initiatives in the area,
and about $2 million in subsequent years.
</P>
<P>
   According to the office, areas around Cleveland, Toledo, Akron,
Canton and Youngstown are plagued by crack cocaine and heroin
trafficking. Law enforcement investigations have found that most
drugs arrive in Cleveland from multiple sources, which ``ensures
the constant flow of drugs into the 'consumer' area of northern
Ohio.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are delighted with the designation,'' said Sen. Mike
DeWine, R-Ohio, who has long requested the federal funding.
</P>
<P>
   DeWine said that state and local authorities have become
overwhelmed by the volume of drug trafficking in the area, located
at the intersection of major north-south and east-west
transportation routes.
</P>
<P>
   He said that in his early years working as an assistant county
prosecutor, he saw the importance of sharing information among
various law enforcement agencies, and the new partnership ``brings
to critical mass the different law enforcement agencies.''
</P>
<P>
   Barry McCaffrey, director of the drug policy office, said the
new funds will be used for ``intelligence, training, coordination
and automation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The drug challenge is clearly more than destroying criminal
organizations. It is prevention treatment that won't work unless
law enforcement agencies are doing their jobs,'' McCaffrey said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to northern Ohio, McCaffrey announced similar drug
trafficking areas in central California, Oregon, New England and
Hawaii. They join 21 other areas previously designated across the
United States. The program started with five in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
