<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-15 21:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6665 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MORGAN-STANLEY-ART-NY     06-15 1251
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORGAN-STANLEY-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORGAN `WHISTLE-BLOWER' HAD PLAYED ROLE BEFORE 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By JOSEPH KAHN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A self-styled whistle-blower whose dealings with
Morgan Stanley Dean Witter &AMP; Co. put them both under criminal
investigation has had a previous tussle with Corporate America.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Joseph Luethke, the whistle-blower, conducted an
extended letter-writing campaign three years ago to put pressure on
Seagram Co. chief executive Edgar Bronfman Jr. and other sponsors
of the Bronx Gauchos amateur basketball club. He called on the
corporate backers to exclude Lou D'Almeida, the club's founder,
from an active role in managing the Gauchos, a well-known training
club that has produced several National Basketball Association
stars.
</P>
<P>
   Amid a swirl of charges that never led to any indictments,
D'Almeida stepped down from his executive role in the Bronx-based
basketball club two years ago. Friends cited Luethke's allegations
and the dispute that ensued as a big reason for D'Almeida's
decision to relinquish his day-to-day duties.
</P>
<P>
   The conflict about the Gauchos has some parallels to Luethke's
dealings with Morgan Stanley, lawyers involved in both cases said.
In both, Luethke parlayed initial presentations as a do-gooder
exposing wrongdoing into what the corporations would later view as
exortion. Luethke denies trying to extort money. He calls himself a
``whistle-blower extraordinaire.''
</P>
<P>
   The previous brush with a top corporation adds to the mystery
surrounding Luethke, whose jousting with Morgan Stanley over a
$10,000 payment embarrassed that top Wall Street firm. It has led
to the resignations of two top lawyers there and invited an
investigation by the Manhattan district attorney's office in which
Morgan Stanley and Luethke are still subjects.
</P>
<P>
   While corporate officers and white-shoe lawyers who have tangled
with Luethke say they suspect that his goal is to extort money,
Luethke seems as eager to humiliate his antagonists publicly as he
is to extract money from them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was reading about the Morgan Stanley case and I could not
believe my eyes,'' said a member of the nonprofit board of the
Teamwork Foundation, which sponsors the Gauchos.
</P>
<P>
   ``The details were very familiar,'' said this person, who spoke
on condition of anonymity. ``Then I realized we were talking about
the same guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Luethke, a 29-year-old who has no full-time employment, first
approached Morgan Stanley last year with a tip that Christian
Curry, a former analyst at the firm, was conspiring to plant fake
e-mails on Morgan Stanley's computers to bolster a discrimination
lawsuit he wanted to file. Luethke took part in a police undercover
operation that resulted in Curry's arrest. Morgan Stanley quietly
paid Luethke $10,000 shortly after the arrest.
</P>
<P>
   In hindsight, Morgan Stanley officials may wish they had done a
little more checking up before accepting Luethke's offer of help.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan Stanley lawyers said in court documents that when they
first met Luethke last summer, they thought of him as a good
Samaritan, adding that the firm paid him $10,000 as a ``reward''
for thwarting a crime. After that, the lawyers said, Luethke used
the payment as a hook to demand much more money, arguing that
without a formal business relationship, the payment could get
Morgan Stanley into trouble. ``The informant made vigorous and
extensive efforts to extort large sums from Morgan Stanley,'' the
documents state.
</P>
<P>
   But just a year before he called on Morgan Stanley, and just
several blocks away from the securities firm's corporate
headquarters in midtown Manhattan, Luethke had engaged in another
prolonged cat-and-mouse game with Lankler, Siffert &AMP; Wohl, a law
firm representing the Teamwork Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Luethke, a native of Haworth, N.J., said he played for the
Gauchos and later worked as a tutor for children enrolled in the
program. The Gauchos serve inner-city youths ages 5 to 19, helping
them realize their potential in basketball while keeping up on
academic studies.
</P>
<P>
   D'Almeida started the Gauchos 30 years ago. A child of a
well-connected Argentine family who attended Yale University,
D'Almeida attracted support for his program from prominent people
in business, sports and entertainment. Bronfman, Jonathan Tisch of
Loews Hotels, actress Lauren Bacall and former basketball star
Willis Reed have been among the Gauchos' prime backers and board
members.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, Luethke wrote letters and sent repeated faxes to
Bronfman and other members of Teamwork Foundation, alleging
improprieties in the way the Gauchos were run. He also claimed to
have evidence of a sex scandal involving D'Almeida. The board hired
Lankler, Siffert &AMP; Wohl to investigate the charges, said a
foundation board member. Luethke also told law enforcement
authorities about his claims.
</P>
<P>
   When pressed to provide evidence, Luethke asked lawyers
representing the foundation to pay him money, said two people who
later investigated the events. They said that letters from Luethke
support the contention that he asked for money, but added that he
did not couple his requests with specific threats _ a combination
that would qualify his actions as extortion in a legal sense.
</P>
<P>
   Luethke refers to the suspicions about his motives in a letter
he wrote to top executives of Seagram in October 1996. In the
letter, Luethke says, ``The claim made by Teamwork Foundation's
lawyers and employees that I intend to extort the Foundation is
shameful.''
</P>
<P>
   He said Tuesday that he never asked for and nor received any
money in connection with the Gauchos matter and that his only goal
was to make sure that D'Almeida was removed from his post.
</P>
<P>
   If he had evidence about wrongdoing by D'Almeida, Luethke never
produced it, several people involved in the matter said. The Bronx
district attorney's office said it conducted an investigation based
largely on Luethke's allegations. But a spokesman said Tuesday that
the office found no evidence of wrongdoing and closed the case
without bringing any charges.
</P>
<P>
   D'Almeida, who pleaded guilty to a charge of criminally
negligent homicide in 1971, also had problems at the Gauchos. The
National Collegiate Athletic Association investigated charges that
he paid team members in violation of NCAA rules, jeopardizing their
amateur status. There is no evidence that the NCAA took any steps
to sanction D'Almeida, though the pay-for-play charges received
wide publicity.
</P>
<P>
   D'Almeida stepped down from an active role in the club after
several New York newspapers and the sports industry press reported
on concerns about D'Almeida's past and the way the Gauchos were
run. Luethke's role in D'Almeida's departure was never publicly
revealed. But people close to D'Almeida and Bronfman say they still
smart when Luethke's name is mentioned.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were allegations several years ago that were thoroughly
investigated,'' said Austin Campriello, D'Almeida's lawyer, when
asked about Luethke's charges. ``Nothing came of them and I hate to
see this matter dredged up again.''
</P>
<P>
   The Teamwork Foundation board member who recalls Luethke's role
also said it had no positive effect. ``Lou stepped down because of
all the bad publicity,'' said the board member. ``It wasn't a great
outcome for anybody, but we wanted to protect the program.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
