<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-15 21:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6672 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-RUSSIA-NYT &LR;      06-15 0885
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-RUSSIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
END OF WAR LEAVES RUSSIANS FED UP WITH OVERBEARING WEST
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By   MICHAEL WINES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ As a military operation, it was insignificant. But as a
symbol, there is no more potent metaphor for Russia's regard of the
West than the image last weekend of 200 Russian soldiers seizing a
Kosovo airfield, and then lining up armored personnel carriers to
keep NATO troops out.
</P>
<P>
   Kremlin officials offered a strategic explanation for the move,
involving the need to acquire bargaining chips in talks on Kosovo's
future and to establish Moscow once and for all as a player in the
peace process.
</P>
<P>
   But most Russians were uninterested in the diplomacy. For them,
it was a moment to savor, a rare act of one-upmanship by a faded
power against a military that once viewed them with fear and awe.
But it was a chance to say vicariously what they increasingly feel:
that they are fed up with the overbearing West in general, and the
United States in particular.
</P>
<P>
   It is not easy for most Westerners to understand. But 78 days of
war in Yugoslavia, a country a thousand miles removed from Moscow
and no special soul mate of Russia in any case, seems to have
convinced many Russians that the West is their enemy.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the anti-Western attitudes that were accumulating in the
society resulted in this explosion when the war began,'' Igor
Bunin, a historian and director of Moscow's Center for Political
Technology, said in an interview. In focus groups involving scores
of Moscow residents, he said, ``many respondents said at the time
that the bombs were not falling on Yugoslavia, but on their own
heads.''
</P>
<P>
   The feeling is not universal. Some polls show Russian opinion of
the Unite States and the West has softened somewhat since the
war's peak. But even Russian newspapers, which viewed last
weekend's operation in Kosovo as a diplomatic and public-relations
debacle, called it ``dashing'' and lightning-fast.
</P>
<P>
   One noted with satisfaction that Deputy Secretary of State
Strobe Talbott's airplane had been forced to perform a mid-air
U-turn and return to Moscow when news of the troop movement
surfaced _ just desserts, because former Prime Minister Yevgeny
Primakov had been forced to abandon a Washington trip in mid-air
when the bombing began in March.
</P>
<P>
   If Russia's pleasure at such slight victories seems out of
place, one need only listen to politicians and military leaders to
realize the depths of their anger at the West's supposed efforts to
feed on Russian weakness.
</P>
<P>
   In anonymous remarks this weekend, Russian military officials
repeatedly talked of ending their humiliation by American and NATO
forces, which bombed Yugoslavia with impunity. Ordinary Muscovites
frequently express the conviction that NATO and the West have
Russia in their sights, and that the Yugoslavia war was merely a
test run for a larger conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Much of their reasoning is no secret. In the former Soviet
Union, average people suffered, but could still take pride in
military and scientific achievements. Democratic Russia promised
affluence, peace and full membership in the club of Western nations
that many Russians had admired for decades.
</P>
<P>
   But none of it has come about. Russia's foundering transition to
capitalism was plotted largely by American academics and business
leaders and carried out by pro-Western politicians; some now see it
as a Western plot to impoverish the nation. Except for honorary
memberships in organizations like the G-8 group of industrial
nations and NATO's Partnership for Peace, Moscow has largely been
shut out of Western decision making.
</P>
<P>
   NATO itself has proven far more of a sticking point than many
Westerners realized. The West rebuffed Russia's early proposals to
move toward full membership in the alliance. When the United States
and Europe first announced plans to admit new members to NATO from
Central Europe, Russian leaders immediately complained that they
were being encircled by a potentially hostile military force _
fears that NATO tried to allay by giving Russia an advisory seat in
the organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``The decision to enlarge NATO could not be understood by
anybody in Russia because Russians know very well how weak Russia
is today,'' said Sergei Rogov, who heads the government's Institute
of the U.S.A. and Canada. ``On the other hand, Russians felt that
we ended the Cold War and started to behave nicely by dissolving
the Warsaw Pact, withdrawing troops, cutting arms. And thus the
very maintenance of NATO was seen as strange.''
</P>
<P>
   Rogov argued that the West consistently underestimated the
Russian public's suspicion of NATO's expansion. That raised the
prospect of an anti-Western explosion should NATO became involved
in a European crisis, he said.
</P>
<P>
   And Bunin, of the Moscow center, said Yugoslavia provided the
spark. The problem, he said, was not that Russians saw Yugoslavia
or its president, Slobodan Milosevic, as allies or martyrs; rather
the problem was the Russians had no opinions about them.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no anti-Milosevic propaganda in Russia,'' he said.
``Nobody looked at Milosevic as a new Hitler or as the person who
is seen in the West. And so the NATO and U.S. attack looked to us
as completely unprovoked, as the step toward world hegemony.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-15-99 2157EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990615.0353 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-15 21:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6673 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEXICO-AID-NYT &LR;      06-15 0806
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-AID-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEXICAN PRESIDENT TRIES TO ENSURE A NIGHTMARE WON'T RECUR 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JULIA PRESTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ The former Mexican president, Carlos Salinas de
Gortari, was a political hero when he ended his term in 1994. But
just a few weeks later, the peso dived, jobs and savings were
annihilated, and Salinas was soon forced into disgrace and exile.
</P>
<P>
   Now his successor, President Ernesto Zedillo, is trying to
insure that an end-of-term economic nightmare does not recur when
he leaves office next year.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Mexico announced that it has pulled together financing
and credits worth $23.7 billion to ``armor'' the economy, as
President Zedillo put it, through December 2000. That is when he
will turn over his office after six years to a new president chosen
in the most democratic _ and therefore the most unpredictable _
elections in Mexican history.
</P>
<P>
   To add to the reassurance that top finance officials are
offering ahead of time to international markets, they also pledged
to maintain the disciplined economic policies that have allowed
Mexico to ride relatively smoothly while other Latin American
countries, especially Brazil, were buffeted by global turbulence
during the last year.
</P>
<P>
   Finance Minister Jose Angel Gurria said Mexico would stick to a
modest government deficit of 1.25 percent of the nation's gross
domestic product this year, and to plans to lower it further, to 1
percent, next year. Guillermo Ortiz, the head of Banco de Mexico,
the central bank, said the battle against inflation would remain a
priority.
</P>
<P>
   Gurria said the finance package, including a $4.2 billion credit
from the International Monetary Fund, would ``allow us all to sleep
easier.''
</P>
<P>
   The IMF is providing the funds under a 17-month Standby
Arrangement, one of the agency's regular, non-emergency programs.
Mexican officials said the monetary fund is showing confidence in
Mexico, which is continuing to pay down $5.9 billion it owes from a
1995 bailout.
</P>
<P>
   The package includes $5.2 billion from the World Bank, mainly
for investments in social programs and government reforms, and $4
billion from the Export-Import Bank of the United States to help
underwrite some of the $200 billion in trade each year between the
two countries.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the Inter-American Development Bank announced that
it would provide $3.5 billion in loans through the year 2001 for
big construction projects and reforms to strengthen local
governments.
</P>
<P>
   Enrique Iglesias, the president of the bank, joined the chorus
of praise for Mexico on Tuesday, saying that by negotiating the IMF
loan Mexico ``provides additional comfort'' to international
markets about the coming elections.
</P>
<P>
   Like a patient struggling with mood swings, Mexico went far
toward controlling its habitual end-of-term depressions by just
acknowledging that they existed. Throughout his presidency, Zedillo
has built up foreign reserves so that the country would not be
caught short in case political events during the next year make
investors want to pull back. Now reserves stand at $30 billion, a
record high.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of the imbalances that existed in 1994, and that led to
the crisis of 1995, are present today,'' Ortiz, the central banker,
announced triumphantly Tuesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico is expecting at least $9 billion in long-term foreign
investment this year, Gurria said. Overall foreign debt, by one
measure, is about half what it was in 1994, the finance minister
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost overkill,'' said Walter Molano, the head of
research at BCP Securities in Greenwich, Conn. ``They are so
heavily armored, they seem to be expecting something much worse
than even what the markets expect.''
</P>
<P>
   Steep downturns also came in 1982, when President Jose Lopez
Portillo nationalized the banks just before leaving office, and to
a milder degree in 1988 when Salinas took over.
</P>
<P>
   Economic collapse did not come until weeks after the end of
Salinas' term in 1994, but a series of unsettling events during his
final year in office undermined confidence in the economy. The
Zapatista Indian uprising in the southern state of Chiapas and the
assassination of the governing party's first presidential
candidate, Luis Donaldo Colosio, made investors nervous. They
bolted en masse when Mexico disclosed that its debts were far
outrunning its foreign reserves.
</P>
<P>
   Zedillo spent his first years in office picking up the pieces of
the economy and started it growing again. He also promoted reforms
that made it much more difficult for him to control the outcome of
the presidential elections in July 2000.
</P>
<P>
   He has said he is anxious to spare Mexicans the losses they have
routinely suffered at the end of presidential terms. He is also
anxious to be spared the ostracism that fell to Salinas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-15-99 2158EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
