<DOCNO> NYT19990615.0357 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-15 22:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6683 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VIRTUAL-ORCHESTRA-ART     06-15 0977
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIRTUAL-ORCHESTRA-ART-2TAKES-$ADV20-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SINGER IS REAL, BUT THE ORCHESTRA CANNOT HEAR HER 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By ANTHONY TOMMASINI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Producing opera is a notoriously expensive
undertaking. The biggest budget item, especially for smaller
companies, is hiring union orchestra musicians for rehearsals and
performances. Many fledgling companies have been sunk by the
expense.
</P>
<P>
   This nearly was the fate of Operaworks, a small but determined
company founded in 1983 by David Leighton, a conductor and coach
who began his career in the 1970s as an assistant chorus master and
assistant conductor at the Metropolitan Opera.
</P>
<P>
   But for the last 10 years, while other companies have been
struggling to raise money to pay musicians, Operaworks has been
bypassing the cost with a controversial technological alternative,
the ``virtual orchestra,'' as the company's publicity materials
call it: in effect, a computer-realized electronic substitute.
</P>
<P>
   An artistic travesty? No doubt many opera fans and critics will
be appalled by the very idea of a virtual orchestra and dismayed by
its oddly processed sound. But Leighton, 48, says that his little
company is blazing a path to the techno-musical future and that
other smaller companies will soon be following suit.
</P>
<P>
   And although Operaworks is making scant money, the company
manages to present 8 to 12 staged productions a year, often of
unusual repertory, for modest-sized but seemingly loyal audiences.
The curious can hear for themselves when the company concludes its
current Strauss festival with a performance of ``Ariadne auf
Naxos'' on Friday night at the West-Park church on Amsterdam Avenue
and 86th Street.
</P>
<P>
   So how does the virtual orchestra work? And more important, how
does it sound? To find out, I attended a recent Operaworks
performance of ``Salome'' and afterward visited with J. Patrick
Casey, the company's general factotum, who directs the productions,
designs the sets, sometimes translates librettos into English, and
programs and runs the virtual orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   During performances Leighton stands before the stage to conduct
the singers. There is no orchestra pit at West-Park church; that
does not matter, since the company uses no orchestra. The virtual
equivalent is in the rear balcony where Casey mans a computer,
following the performance by watching Leighton. But the real work
has been done already.
</P>
<P>
   The actual sounds of the instruments are taken from a series of
CD-ROMs _ samplers, as they are called. One CD will contain nothing
but, say, the digitally recorded sounds of a clarinetist playing
long, sustained expression-neutral pitches, right up the chromatic
scale. These disks cost about $300 to $400 each, though more
expensive ones are available.
</P>
<P>
   A standard $4,000 sequencer, a mixer with 16 tracks, and of
course the computer are the essential components of the orchestral
music. Basically, Casey enters every single note, every line of the
complex Strauss score into the computer by playing it on a silent
keyboard which borrows sounds from the sampler CDs. So, for
example, the slinky, insinuating solo clarinet line that ``Salome''
begins with is performed by Casey at the keyboard with the desired
tempo, dynamics, articulations and so forth.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a bank of about 30 sounds,'' Casey explained,
``strings, strings playing pizzicato, flute, trumpet, cymbal
crashes, whatever.''
</P>
<P>
   Entering the information into the computer is a time-devouring
process. Casey estimates that he must spend on average three or
four hours for each minute of music. So ``Salome,'' a two-hour
opera, could take anywhere from 360 to a staggering 600 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Once completed, Casey ``performs'' the score by simply sitting
at the computer, punching keys and controlling the flow as the
music emits from speakers placed discreetly around the stage. Casey
and Leighton make much of the fact that tempos, phrasing and shape
in the virtual orchestra are worked out carefully during rehearsals
with the singers and that tempo, at least, can be adjusted by Casey
during a performance. But to do more than slight adjustments on the
spot is difficult.
</P>
<P>
   And dynamics, once set, are fixed. Gone, it would seem, is the
possibility for a singer to shape a phase in performance with a
slightly different inflection from what she did in rehearsal,
trusting that an alert conductor and sensitive orchestra players
will catch the difference and respond accordingly.
</P>
<P>
   As for the sound of the virtual orchestra, those listeners
accustomed to hearing orchestra tracks on pop and rock records and
in film scores, where this computer audio technology is most
common, will probably have an easier time accepting a virtual
orchestra's performance of ``Salome.'' I found it weird.
</P>
<P>
   Even when, say, a clarinet sounded sort of like a clarinet, the
tone seemed synthetic. The strings have an accordionlike quality.
Crescendos have a way of leaping out at you. One reminded me of
when the organist at Yankee Stadium gives an unintended extra nudge
to the swell pedal and a clipped chord jumps out of a melodic line
in an odd place (``Take me out  &UR; to &LR;  the ball game'').
</P>
<P>
   At full volume, Strauss' low brass and horns had a buzzing
quality, like the rude, blasting sounds made by the alien spaceship
in ``Close Encounters of the Third Kind'' when it answers the
earthlings' five-note musical greeting. And because the sound emits
from speakers, the spatial separation of instruments that is the
hallmark of a live orchestra is gone. Admittedly ``Salome,'' with
its famously voluptuous orchestration, is particularly hard to
replicate virtually. But Operaworks chose it.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Leighton says that once composers get accustomed to the virtual
orchestra, they will start to compose for it, or at least
incorporate its resources into the standard orchestra. But
composing new music for this new technology is one thing. Trying to
recreate the sound of a Mozart or Strauss orchestra with
computerized, rhythmically constricting high-tech resources, no
matter how sophisticated, will always be frustrating, like getting
a kiss over the telephone.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the musicians' union, Local 802, which is fiercely
protective of its members' rights and the status quo, has paid
little attention to Operaworks productions. The virtual orchestra
must seem an unlikely threat to the livelihood of classical
musicians. But that's what pop musicians once thought. Orchestras
were once used regularly for everything from soaring string tracks
on Motown songs to disco. Nowadays, if the sound of an orchestra is
desired in pop, it is as likely provided by digital keyboards and
computers.
</P>
<P>
   Operaworks would seem for now to be almost alone among classical
organizations in adopting this technology. Expect virtual
instruments to invade the Broadway orchestra pit, already the
domain of digital keyboards and ear-numbing amplification systems.
</P>
<P>
   Leighton is quick to compare his use of a virtual orchestra
favorably to the occasional use by many ballet companies of
recordings in place of live musicians. ``We are one step up from
that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But that is not entirely a fair comparison. For example, during
the recent two-week Stravinsky festival at the New York City
Ballet, the company's fine orchestra had to prepare 18 difficult
Stravinsky scores. In two additional cases the company used
recordings: the complex ``Movements for Piano and Orchestra'' and
``Les Noces,'' with a cumbersome scoring involving full chorus and
four pianos, far too cumbersome for an orchestra pit. Most critics
would say this represented a fair compromise.
</P>
<P>
   Casey says the high cost of hiring union orchestras is
``strangling opera in America.'' Actually opera is thriving in the
United States as never before, and a lot more can be accomplished
if smaller companies concentrate on less well-known or small-scale
works and let the major houses take care of ``Parsifal'' and
``Salome.''
</P>
<P>
   Leighton maintains that, by using a virtual orchestra, his
company can focus on developing a close ensemble of singing actors.
But the Operaworks performance of ``Salome'' was woefully uneven
vocally, with a gifted soprano in the title role who probably
should not have been attempting this famously taxing music and a
couple of singers in supporting roles who were undone by the vocal
challenges.
</P>
<P>
   It may be hard to recruit solid singers into something that
looks so gimmicky. Leighton should consider whether in his desire
to direct a company he is giving young singers chances or leading
them astray.
</P>
<P>
   As opera becomes more popular, there will be increased pressure
to make it less expensive and more accessible. As in pop music, the
virtual orchestra may creep into the field.
</P>
<P>
   What's the harm? My unscientific polling after a ``Salome''
performance found many people either intrigued by the virtual
orchestra or blase about it. One man who professed enthusiasm
claimed to be an avid operagoer.
</P>
<P>
   We have virtual special effects in the movies, virtual
simulations of space travel at science parks and now the virtual
orchestra. What next? A virtual soprano to sing Salome? Don't
laugh. It may be coming. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
