<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASTROS-DIERKER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASTROS MANAGER HAS SUCCESSFUL BRAIN SURGERY  
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By TODD ACKERMAN 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Astros manager Larry Dierker had successful brain
surgery Tuesday to remove a life-threatening mass of tangled blood
vessels that had caused his seizure in Sunday's game.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Rob Parrish, who performed the surgery at Methodist
Hospital, said he was confident he removed the entire malformation
and wants Dierker to convalesce for four weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Then, Parrish added, ``we'll evaluate on a week-to-week basis if
he's ready to manage.'' But he said he sees no reason why Dierker
shouldn't return this year.
</P>
<P>
   Asked to assess how well the operation went on a 1 to 10 scale,
the surgeon said 10.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's doing very well,'' Parrish said. ``He's awake and alert
and he even makes sense when he talks. He gave me a high-five after
the surgery.''
</P>
<P>
   Parrish removed the problem blood vessels, known as
arteriovenous malformation (AVM), from the frontal lobe in the
right side of Dierker's brain during a five-hour surgery. Pathology
confirmed the clot contained no tumor.
</P>
<P>
   After determining that Dierker's remaining vessels still had an
abnormal blood flow, doctors found a second area of malformation
and removed it.
</P>
<P>
   Parrish said the blood vessels likely ruptured a few days before
Dierker's seizure and could have killed him. AVM is the
second-leading cause of fatal brain hemorrhaging, behind aneurysms.
About 17 percent of victims die the first time it happens.
</P>
<P>
   Dierker, 52, collapsed in the dugout during the eighth inning of
the Houston-San Diego game at the Astrodome. He went into violent
seizures and was tended to by paramedics before taken by ambulance
to Methodist.
</P>
<P>
   Parrish said Dierker should make a full recovery now. He will
spend another day bedridden in intensive care and remain in the
hospital 5-10 days. He will have an angiogram _ an X-ray of the
blood vessels _ in a few days and again in about a year to make
certain everything is out.
</P>
<P>
   Astros owner Drayton McLane Jr. and general manager Gerry
Hunsicker, who were at the hospital, expressed their relief, as did
players and coaches at the Dome before Tuesday night's game with
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the best we had hoped for,'' McLane said. ``This is
great progress and we rejoice in the outcome.''
</P>
<P>
   Hunsicker described Dierker as very positive when he visited him
after the surgery _ ``he was smiling and gave the thumbs-up sign.''
But he said it was ``ridiculous'' to set a timetable for Dierker's
return to the dugout.
</P>
<P>
   Interim manager Matt Galante said that ``everything since Sunday
has been good, positive news. Yesterday they talked about what they
were going to do, today they did the operation and everything
turned out well. It's been uplifting because Sunday was a really
down day for us.''
</P>
<P>
   For surgery Parrish described as ``treacherous,'' the mood at
the news conference afterward was decidedly light. Parrish said
Dierker asked before the surgery whether this means ``no more
head-butts?''
</P>
<P>
   Needling Dierker about his predilection for aggressive
base-running, Parrish wondered after the surgery if he got out the
part of the manager's brain that allowed stealing third base with
two outs. Parrish said he hoped he got it out, but Dierker
responded that no, the surgeon must not have removed it because he
still plans to steal in such situations.
</P>
<P>
   Parrish, who has known Dierker for a few years, said Dierker was
``pumped up'' for the surgery and had no fear about it. Dierker
joked with Parrish that people usually tell you, ``Don't worry, it
isn't brain surgery. But this is brain surgery.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy goes through a seizure, has brain surgery and he's
still able to joke around, said Astros second baseman Craig Biggio.
``That's typical Dierk. That`s why everyone loves him so much.''
</P>
<P>
   The procedure required Parrish to cut a ``window'' in Dierker's
skull. After removing the malformation, Parrish put the bone flap
back over the window with 19 titanium screws and four
micro-titanium plates. They will stay there permanently.
</P>
<P>
   Parrish said the malformation was about 4-by-3 centimeters _ or
``bigger than a walnut, smaller than a lemon, maybe the size of a
lime or a really big jalapeno. Larry would like that.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
