<HEADLINE>
AN UNCONFIRMED BID FOR CAESARS CASINOS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds.: This story, eliminated earlier is now shorted and
restored.) (sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The self-described owner of the world's biggest pornographic Web
site, Ocean Fund International, contended on Tuesday in a release
on PR Newswire that it had offered to buy the eight Caesars casinos
from Park Place Entertainment for $3.6 billion in cash.
</P>
<P>
   But Starwood Hotels and Resorts, which agreed in April to sell
the casinos to Park Place Entertainment for $3 billion, said it did
not receive any such offer, nor was Park Place aware of one.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Dow Jones news service said that Ocean Fund was
not registered as a mutual fund in the British Virgin Islands, as
it had stated. And by the end of the day, PR Newswire asked Ocean
Fund's lawyer for proof it had sent its offer to Starwood and Park
Place by certified mail, as it also contended. But that proof was
not forthcoming by Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street appeared unmoved by the release. Starwood shares
rose 43.75 cents on Tuesday, to $36.875, while those of Park Place
fell 18.75 cents, to $9.50.
</P>
<P>
   ``After following gambling stocks for 10 years,'' said Jason
Ader, an analyst at Bear, Stearns, ``you think you've seen it all.
Then something like this comes along that makes you shake your
head.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
