<SLUG> BC-HONGKONG-TELECOM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANOTHER COMPANY TAKES THE `HONG KONG' OUT OF ITS NAME 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By MARK LANDLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ Score another one for globalism over localism. Hong
Kong's local telephone company, Hong Kong Telecommunications Ltd.,
said Tuesday that it would change its name to Cable and Wireless
HKT to tighten ties with its London-based parent company, Cable and
Wireless PLC.
</P>
<P>
   Hong Kong Telecom said the new name was intended to convey the
company's broader ambitions as a supplier of Internet connections
and electronic commerce, as well as traditional telephone services,
throughout Asia.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are rooted in Hong Kong and will continue to focus on Hong
Kong with investment,'' said Linus Cheung, the chief executive of
Hong Kong Telecom, at a news conference. But he added, ``For the
future performance of our company, we will have to move out of Hong
Kong.''
</P>
<P>
   To some people here, the move is more discouraging evidence that
Hong Kong is losing its brand-name prestige as a commercial center.
Last November, HSBC Holdings, the parent of the Hongkong and
Shanghai Bank, announced plans to drop the ``Hongkong'' from the
English name of its flagship bank in favor of the HSBC
abbreviation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time the Hong Kong name is removed from a major company,
you reduce the publicity for Hong Kong,'' said Ian Perkin, the
chief economist of the Hong Kong General Chamber of Commerce. ``It
downgrades the world's perception of Hong Kong, which is
disappointing.''
</P>
<P>
   Perkin also questioned Hong Kong Telecom's decision to tie its
image to Cable and Wireless, a 127-year-old British company that
cobbled together its global network by constructing telephone
operations in onetime British colonies, from the Caribbean to India
to Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cable and Wireless is a company that followed the British
Empire around the world,'' he said, ``The name seems to be a
throwback.''
</P>
<P>
   To Hong Kong Telecom, however, the Cable and Wireless name
symbolizes a thoroughly modern company no longer wholly dependent
on either its home market or traditional voice communications. Its
ventures outside Hong Kong include building the first fiber optic
cable linking Chinese cities.
</P>
<P>
   Hong Kong Telecom's nonvoice services range from fax and data
transmission to Internet access and interactive television. Voice
communications generate only 40 percent of the company's profits,
Cheung said, and that figure could fall to 25 percent in three
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our vision is to make Hong Kong the Internet hub and
e-commerce center of Asia,'' Cheung said, noting that the company
had spent $2.58 billion (United States) to upgrade its networks
here.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts said the name change might have been dictated more
by corporate imperatives in London. Although Cable and Wireless had
one of the first genuinely global telecommunications networks,
investors have not rewarded the company with a commensurate
valuation in the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   ``They weren't getting credit for it because most of the assets
weren't named for Cable and Wireless,'' said Lloyd Fischer, a
telecommunications analyst at Salomon Smith Barney in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   Fischer predicted that the name change would have little effect
in the home market because the company would not be changing its
Chinese name, which translates as ``Hong Kong Telecom.'' More than
95 percent of Hong Kong's residents are Chinese. HSBC also kept the
Chinese name of the Hong Kong bank.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
