<SLUG> BC-KOREA-ECON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLANNED KOREAN SHARE ISSUE ANGERS A BIG U.S. HEDGE FUND 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Includes material budgeted earlier as JAPAN-MARKETS) 
(HLW) 
 By STEPHANIE STROM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ A leading American hedge fund that has prominently
invested in South Korea's rebounding economy is protesting a plan
by the nation's biggest mobile phone operator to issue more shares.
</P>
<P>
   The objection from Tiger Management LLC, operated by the
well-known fund manager Julian H. Robertson, calls the plan by SK
Telecom unfair because the larger SK group may benefit
disproportionately. Tiger's complaint is regarded as another in a
series of signs that the momentum of South Korea's economic
modernization is slowing as the country regains financial strength.
</P>
<P>
   Tiger said on Tuesday that it was calling for a special
shareholders meeting on the matter and threatened to take its case
to court if SK Telecom's board did not cancel the plan to issue
shares.
</P>
<P>
   Lee Jung-dong, a spokesman for SK Telecom, said on Tuesday that
the company's board had approved the plan. He expressed surprise at
Tiger's reaction.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that such a complaint has been made against SK Telecom
_ which has been regarded as an example of how foreign investors
can impose Western-style corporate governance and disclosure on
Asian companies _ is one measure of how unhappy those investors are
becoming. SK Telecom's minority investors, in addition to winning
the right to recommend outside directors, had succeeded in
appointing an outside auditor.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps feeding such unhappiness, the government has delayed
selling two big banks it nationalized in the financial crisis,
which took hold in December 1997 and required a $58 billion aid
package from the International Monetary Fund.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the government said it was dissatisfied with the
offers made in its second attempt at selling Korea Life Insurance
and announced a third round of bidding. The first attempt failed
when the government's terms scared away big foreign insurers like
Metropolitan Life and AXA of France.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, officials said they might reopen bidding for a 25
percent stake in Korea Gas, a state-owned monopoly, because bidders
including the Osaka Gas Co. of Japan and BG PLC of Britain had not
met its price demands or reached an agreement on management
participation.
</P>
<P>
   There is concern among foreign investors that the rights
offering is an attempt to prevent them from increasing their stake
in the company when the government lifts the restrictions on
foreign ownership of telecommunications companies to 49 percent
from the current 33 percent.
</P>
<P>
   They say the SK group is worried that if foreigners own such a
substantial part of SK Telecom, the company may slip from its
control.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
