<SLUG> BC-SUPERIOR-DEALS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPERIOR INDUSTRIES LOOKING FOR PLANT SITE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY ENRIQUE RIVERO  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Superior Industries International Inc. said
Tuesday it has won multiyear contracts worth an annual $250 million
and plans to build a new plant to handle all the new business
coming its way.
</P>
<P>
   Among the deals, Superior will provide its aluminum wheels for
the 2000 models of the Mercury Sable, Chevrolet Suburban/Tahoe, GMC
Yukon, Oldsmobile Intrigue, Buick Regal, Cadillac DeVille and BMW
Z3 Coupe.
</P>
<P>
   Superior had already been supplying some of these models, and
the contract calls for providing redesigned wheels.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the company will supply wheels for a new car or light
truck that R. Jeffrey Ornstein, company vice president and chief
financial officer, said he was not permitted by the maker to
identify.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the company is casting about for a place to build a
new plant, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just now searching plant sites,'' Ornstein said. ``It
will definitely be in North America and probably an important
consideration will be geographical proximity to one of our existing
plants.''
</P>
<P>
   The company hopes to open it by September 2000, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Superior's plants are in suburban Van Nuys, where the company is
also headquartered; Fayetteville and Rogers, Ark.; Johnson City,
Tenn.; Pittsburg, Kan.; and Chihuahua, Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   In the first quarter ended March 31, the company earned $15.5
million, or 57 cents per diluted share, compared with last year's
$12.8 million, or 46 cents per diluted share. Revenues were $136.9
million vs. the previous year's $136.4 million.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Superior is expanding its Van Nuys plant's capacity by
about 20 percent, according to Ornstein. The expansion includes
installing more equipment and possibly boosting the plant's work
force, which now numbers about 750. About 150 people work in the
headquarters, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The company has about 4,500 employees worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   The new contracts, and the fact that the company needs another
plant, indicates Superior's solid place in the market for wheels,
said Nicholas Lobaccaro, an industry analyst at Lehman Brothers in
New York City.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's just consistent with the fact that their
customers recognize them as a great supplier,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Wall Street was unimpressed with Superior's announcement.
Shares of the company increased only 18.75 cents to $24 on 75,900
shares traded.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
