<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-FAREST-EXTORT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHAREHOLDERS CHARGE EXTORTION IN RUSSIAN FAR EAST 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By NEELA BANERJEE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Foreign investors in Far Eastern Shipping Co. of Russia
have accused a top politician of using extortion to try to wrest
away their stakes in the concern, causing a shareholder rights
scandal that is the latest of several to erode the weak faith
remaining in the Russian equities market.
</P>
<P>
   Based in Vladivostok, Far Eastern Shipping is the nation's
largest commercial shipping line and is 42 percent owned by foreign
investors. Andrew Fox, chairman of a Vladivostok brokerage firm,
Tiger Securities, and a Far Eastern Shipping board member
representing nearly all foreign investors, said in a telephone
interview Tuesday that the provincial governor, Yevgeny
Nazdratenko, summoned him June 3 to express displeasure with the
extent of foreign ownership in the company.
</P>
<P>
   Fox said Nazdratenko demanded that foreign stockholders
surrender at least 7 percent of their shares to him, and he vowed
to limit foreigners' voting rights at companies in his Primorsky
region. If Fox failed to comply, he quoted Nazdratenko as saying,
he would face imprisonment.
</P>
<P>
   Reached by telephone early Wednesday, , Nazdratenko's press
secretary, Natalya Vstovskaya, said she could not confirm that he
had met with Fox, and that ``if there was a discussion, I hardly
think the discussion had anything to do with Nazdratenko's own
interests.''
</P>
<P>
   Other foreigners briefed on the meeting said Fox's account was
credible.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the nationalist overtones, the attempt to grab these
shares may have monetary motives. Gubernatorial elections in
Primorsky are scheduled in December, and it is not unheard of for
incumbents to take over local companies and use their cash flow to
finance campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is really not about foreigners, though that plays well as
far as the public is concerned,'' said Fox, who has worked in
Vladivostok since 1993. He said Far Eastern Shipping, ``as one of
the biggest and richest companies in the region, is one worth
having influence over.''
</P>
<P>
   The case is just the most recent instance of conflict between
major Russian companies and foreign shareholders. The oil
conglomerate Sidanko is in bankruptcy and BP Amoco, one of its
major shareholders, is struggling to have a say in the process and
to recoup some of its investment. Another oil concern, Yukos, has
been accused of trying to dilute minority shareholdings with new
stock issues.
</P>
<P>
   Privatized Russian companies, used to decades of secrecy under
communism and to running things their own way, have proved hostile
to outsiders. Theft and currency flight are rampant at businesses,
and outside shareholders often threaten to halt such activities.
</P>
<P>
   When the Russian stock market performed well, few investors
cared about corporate governance because there was money to be made
without getting involved in such tricky questions, said James
Fenkner, an equity strategist with the Moscow brokerage firm Troika
Dialog. But since default and devaluation last summer devastated
their holdings, investors have sought to recoup as much of their
money as possible _ which brings them into conflict with big
shareholders, managers and the powers backing them.
</P>
<P>
   Although the initial threats have not been followed by further
harassment, Fox, who is also British honorary consul for the
Russian Far East, said he felt endangered.
</P>
<P>
   The British Embassy in Moscow will send a letter of complaint to
the Russian Foreign Ministry on Wednesday , Fox said. An embassy
spokeswoman confirmed only ``that Mr. Fox has been in consultations
with the embassy on how to proceed on the matter.''
</P>
<P>
   Though representing foreign shareholders, Fox and his firm hold
a negligible stake themselves in Far Eastern Shipping, whose market
value is estimated at $32 million.
</P>
<P>
   A new board, elected in late May, wants to insure more openness
in the company's financial practices and determine why Far Eastern
Shipping continues to lose money despite strong revenue.
</P>
<P>
   In their meeting, Fox said, Nazdratenko gave him a week to
convene yet another shareholders meeting and elect a different
board and chairman more to his liking. Two generals from a security
service and the police were present at the discussion, Fox said,
and ``I was told that a general would take me on a tour of the
local prisons so I could see where I'd end up if I didn't comply.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
