<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-JACKSON-LAKERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BICOASTAL BIDDING ENDS: JACKSON GOES TO LAKERS
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By MIKE WISE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ The New Jersey Nets offered him wheelbarrows of
cash and the New York Knicks tried to sell him on their future
during a clandestine meeting. But in the end, Phil Jackson decided
that the combination of Shaquille O'Neal and Kobe Bryant beat
anything the New York metropolitan area offered.
</P>
<P>
   The courtship of Jackson ended Tuesday when the Los Angeles
Lakers announced that Jackson, who coached the Chicago Bulls to six
championships, had agreed to terms on a multiyear deal.
</P>
<P>
   The official announcement, which is scheduled to come at a news
conference on Wednesday in Inglewood, Calif., ends months of
speculation and rumor surrounding the future of Jackson. According
to a person close to Jackson who requested anonymity, Jackson will
sign a deal worth nearly $30 million over five seasons.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers' management structure will not change. Jerry West
remains the team president and Mitch Kupchak stays as general
manager, but Jackson will have a major role in personnel matters.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson will replace Kurt Rambis, who was promoted to interim
coach from assistant when Del Harris was fired as coach 12 games
into the season. Rambis will remain with the team; Jackson will
decide whether he will be part of the coaching staff.
</P>
<P>
   After a calamitous season that included the acquisition and
release of the tardy and troubled Dennis Rodman, the Lakers were
swept out of the playoffs for the second year in a row, losing in
the second round to San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to inheriting two of the league's marquee players,
O'Neal and Bryant, Jackson will coach a team opening a new arena.
The Lakers have left the Great Western Forum and will play in the
new Staples Arena next season.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, 53, had a 545-193 record in nine seasons at Chicago and
was 111-41 in the playoffs, the highest post-season winning
percentage of all NBA coaches.
</P>
<P>
   According to an Eastern Conference team official with knowledge
of Jackson's plans, he was genuinely interested in coaching the
Lakers, Nets and Knicks, but firmly believed that the Lakers' job
had more potential, based on their talent.
</P>
<P>
   West and Kupchak spoke by telephone to Jackson on Monday, after
he returned to Montana from an Alaskan fishing trip.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson was already scheduled to be in Los Angeles on Wednesday
and Thursday to campaign for Bill Bradley, the former Knick and
U.S. senator now seeking the Democratic presidential nomination.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-15-99 2230EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
