<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUDGET-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: DIFFERENT TAKES ON BUDGET RENT-A-CAR'S ACCOUNT
REVIEW 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A funny thing happened on the way to the end of a review for a
large advertiser's creative account: the company and two agencies
traded conflicting versions of the final rounds.
</P>
<P>
   Budget Rent-a-Car Corp., a unit of Budget Group that rents and
sells vehicles, said Tuesday that it had ended the review, which
began in April, by selecting Cliff Freeman &AMP; Partners in New York
to handle the creative portion of the account. Billings were
estimated at $40 million to $50 million.
</P>
<P>
   But just hours before Budget made that announcement, Fallon
McElligott in Minneapolis, one of four finalists in the review,
issued an unusual statement, saying it had decided to withdraw
after being told by Budget executives that it had been ``the
preferred choice.''
</P>
<P>
   Budget countered by asserting that Fallon McElligott had issued
the statement only because the agency had learned the account was
being awarded to Freeman, a unit of Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi PLC.
</P>
<P>
   Then, the head of the Chicago office of Publicis &AMP; Hal Riney,
the incumbent agency on the creative account, weighed in, saying
Budget executives had assured him his agency was going to be kept
on _ until he received a call Wednesday disclosing Freeman's
selection.
</P>
<P>
   The disagreement is indicative of the ferment roiling relations
between agencies and clients as accounts change hands faster and
more frequently than before.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, there have been several disputes recently centered
on agencies that unexpectedly announced they were resigning
accounts. Those statements were challenged by the clients involved,
who countered that the agencies had neglected to mention that those
resignations had come only after the accounts were placed in
review.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing surprises me in this business anymore,'' said Donny
Deutsch, chairman and chief executive at Deutsch Inc. in New York,
which had been a finalist in the Budget review before withdrawing
in May.
</P>
<P>
   In its statement, Fallon McElligott attributed its withdrawal to
a failure to reach agreement on compensation after two weeks of
contract negotiations with Budget.
</P>
<P>
   ``It became clear, after many protracted conversations,'' said
Fallon McElligott chairman Patrick Fallon in the statement, ``that
Budget was not willing to enter into an agreement that from our
point of view made sense.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the first time in our 18-year history where a potential
partnership broke down based on financial considerations,'' he
added.
</P>
<P>
   Kimberly Mulcahy, a spokeswoman for Budget, which is based in
Lisle, Ill., replied that Freeman, not Fallon McElligott, was the
agency the company wanted.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we had narrowed the review, we were in final rounds of
negotiations and discussions with both Fallon and Cliff Freeman,''
Ms. Mulcahy said. ``I think the bottom line was that Fallon got
wind they weren't the agency of choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``By saying they were pulling out,'' she added, ``maybe they're
saving face. But I can't speak for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Someone who  &UR; can  &LR; speak for them _ Julie Thompson, a spokeswoman
for Fallon McElligott _ said the agency was ``disappointed'' by the
dispute.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're told by the VP of marketing and the president and
the chairman that you're the agency, what part of that were we not
supposed to understand?'' she asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just want to be very clear and forthright about what
happened,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   Another disappointed party was Barry Krause, president of
Publicis &AMP; Hal Riney in Chicago, part of Publicis SA. His agency
has handled the creative duties on the Budget account since July.
</P>
<P>
   Krause said he believed he would keep the account ``until this
morning,'' when Budget called to inform him of Freeman's selection.
</P>
<P>
   ``They continued to assure us we `blew them away''' in creative
and strategic presentations that were part of the review, he added.
``We've been sitting here asking each other, `If we were that
excellent, why haven't we heard something?'''
</P>
<P>
   ``They're trying to do the right thing,'' Krause said, ``but
they're having a hard time creating a real partnership with an
agency.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When you've gone through three agencies in three years,'' he
added, ``there's something wrong with the system.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the Budget creative duties have been at three agencies
since January 1997: Freeman, Publicis &AMP; Hal Riney and Hill,
Holliday, Connors, Cosmopulos in Boston, a unit of Interpublic
Group of Cos.
</P>
<P>
   Cliff Freeman, chairman and chief creative officer at Freeman,
said that he had been unaware of the contretemps between Fallon
McElligott and Budget until he had been briefed by his new client.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sort of amazing to me,'' Freeman said, adding: ``It seems
like sour grapes. You don't get the business, so you pull out? I've
got to try that next time.''
</P>
<P>
   There is also a change affecting the media duties on the Budget
account. Media planning, which had been handled by Publicis &AMP; Hal
Riney, is being shifted to Starcom Media Services in Chicago, a
unit of Leo Burnett Co. that has already been handling media
buying.
</P>
<P>
   For the record, the fourth finalist in the creative review was
GSD&AMP;M in Austin, Texas, a unit of Omnicom Group. Roy Spense, the
agency's president, had a succinct response when the dispute was
described to him: ``Wow.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
