<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-USOPEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMPROVED WOODS READY FOR A SERIOUS OPEN BID
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PINEHURST, N.C. _ At this point in Tiger Woods' young career,
the U.S. Open is the major championship that has given him the most
trouble.
</P>
<P>
   In four appearances, Woods has never finished higher than 18th.
And in his 13 previous rounds at the Open, Woods has shot under par
just twice.
</P>
<P>
   At times, he has been too aggressive, hitting difficult shots
out of deep rough, which only led to more trouble. At times, he has
become frustrated, losing the patience necessary to win a
tournament where pars are precious and bogeys are to be expected.
But when the 99th U.S. Open begins Thursday morning, Woods will tee
off at Pinehurst Resort &AMP; Country Club's world-famous No. 2 course
with momentum, confidence, a different strategy and a different
mindset.
</P>
<P>
   Woods has been the world's best player this month, winning his
last two starts _ the Deutsche Bank SAP Open in Germany and the
Memorial Tournament, where Woods displayed a brilliant short game
under pressure to prevail by four strokes over Vijay Singh.
</P>
<P>
   The months Woods spent sharpening his short game and improving
his distance control have not been wasted, and Woods' game suits
Pinehurst, where short-game ability and creativity will be crucial.
</P>
<P>
   Woods believes he has never been more ready to win an Open,
because he has never been a more complete player. With Woods,
expectations are always high. But this week, he hopes to turn those
expectations into results.
</P>
<P>
   ``The previous U.S. Opens, I wasn't as good a player as I needed
to be,'' said Woods. ``That's just plain and simple. In U.S. Opens,
if you hit the ball poorly, you're not going to be around.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's one of the reasons I changed my game to become more
consistent. When I do miss, it's not two fairways over like it used
to be. I kept telling everybody that I'm making changes in my game,
and it's going to take time. I'm learning how to play the game. I'm
only 23. I have a long way to go. But I've come a long way. I've
learned by watching other players. I've learned from my own
mistakes. But I think most importantly, I'm not afraid to apply
what I've learned.''
</P>
<P>
   While Woods will be one of the favorites, a long list of players
could contend. This will be an unusual Open, with wider fairways
and lower rough than normal, which could keep more players in the
hunt. It rained Tuesday at Pinehurst, and if it rains again
Wednesday, the greens will be even softer once the tournament
begins, allowing players to fire with more daring at the flag
sticks.
</P>
<P>
   But when Woods is playing well, he can win anywhere, and those
close to him sense his determination. Woods and Mark O'Meara are
sharing a house this week, and O'Meara was not about to bet against
Woods.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's hitting it as good as he can hit it,'' said
O'Meara. ``Tiger will play well this week because No. 1, he's
putting good, and No. 2, he's confident.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Memorial, Woods displayed the shot-making skills around
the greens that he will need to prevail at Pinehurst, where
chipping and putting will be crucial. When he is near the green,
expect to see Woods use his 3-wood to roll the ball close to the
hole, a creative play that has become one of his signature shots.
</P>
<P>
   And from past experiences at the Open, Woods has learned that it
is often better to accept bogeys rather than to try heroic shots
that can lead to bigger problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Tiger has learned to be more patient,'' said Butch
Harmon, Woods' coach. ``After the 1997 Open, I sent Tiger a note
with two words on it _ chip out. He's gaining more and more
experience all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods said he didn't like the way he played in 1997, ``even
though I won some tournaments. I didn't like the fact I wasn't
consistent. Anybody can win when they're hot. But it's hard to win
when you're off.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the Memorial on Sunday, I wasn't playing that well, but I
used my short game to my advantage to beat Vijay. A player may not
win every week, but they want to have a chance to win Sunday on the
back nine. I want to keep giving myself those chances.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
