<HEADER>
A6707 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WOODPECKER-COX     06-15 0800
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOODPECKER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Woodpeckers make golf course a love nest
 &HT;    By Chris Burritt
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PINEHURST, N.C. _ Always on the lookout for lovebirds, Peter
Campbell could hardly believe what he saw. Two red-cockaded
woodpeckers were flitting in a grove of longleaf pines.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service biologist had longed for this
moment for 2 1/2 years, ever since he became chief matchmaker for
the endangered species of woodpeckers in North Carolina's
Sandhills.
</P>
<P>
   At the site of this week's U.S. Open golf championship, federal
officials, conservationists and private landowners who are
restoring the woodpeckers' habitat claim they've scored an
environmental hole in one.
</P>
<P>
   One recent afternoon, Campbell shared his binoculars with
golfers who were curious to see the darting black-and-white
woodpeckers. ``We have a potential breeding pair,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The more exciting discovery of a love nest came a few days
later. Two baby birds were nestled in a hole their parents had
tapped in a pine tree.
</P>
<P>
   Reclaiming longleaf pine woods for red-cockaded woodpeckers was
the goal four years ago when Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt
traveled to Pinehurst to unveil a program called Safe Harbor. The
first private landowner to sign up was Pinehurst, the company that
owns eight local golf courses, including the legendary No. 2 course
hosting the U.S. Open.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1995, 24 additional landowners in the Sandhills _
including nine golf courses _ have joined Safe Harbor. They are
working with the U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service and the nonprofit
Sandhills Ecological Institute to reclaim habitat for 50 groups of
red-cockaded woodpeckers. The latest tally found 34 groups in the
Pinehurst area.
</P>
<P>
   Last month's discovery of the nestlings was the most encouraging
development yet. ``It is the first instance of Safe Harbor doing
what it was set up to do _ creating new sites of birds,'' said
Kerry Brust, the ecological institute's senior biologist. The U.S.
Fish and Wildlife Service is crowing about the woodpecker project
during this week's golf tournament. In coming months, the agency
plans to recommend Safe Harbor as a national model for protecting
other endangered species.
</P>
<P>
   One of Safe Harbor's rules is that property owners must clear
their longleaf pine groves of scrub oaks and underbrush. That
leaves an uncluttered, airy stand of pines, the habitat preferred
by red-cockaded woodpeckers.
</P>
<P>
   When underbrush grows as high as woodpeckers' nesting cavities,
it creates a natural ladder for predators such as black rat snakes.
That scares off the woodpeckers. In centuries past, natural fires
rid longleaf forests of underbrush. As people have moved into the
woodpeckers' habitat, fires have largely been stamped out. At the
same time, development and logging have eliminated more than 95
percent of the Southeast's original 92 million acres of longleaf
ecosystem.
</P>
<P>
   In turn, the number of red-cockaded woodpeckers had dwindled to
roughly 5,000 groups in 13 Southeastern states. The uncluttered
habitat preferred by the woodpeckers happens to be a neat fit for
the manner in which Pinehurst maintains the longleaf groves through
which its golf courses meander. By clearing underbrush, maintenance
crews make it easier for golfers who hit errant shots to retrieve
their balls.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why would we not do something to enhance the species?'' said
Brad Kocher, Pinehurst's director of golf course maintenance who
eagerly endorsed Safe Harbor in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Safe Harbor has critics, as do most federal programs to protect
endangered species. Some complain about the cost in tax dollars _
more than $800,000 in the case of the Sandhills project.
</P>
<P>
   Near Pinehurst, sprawling Fort Bragg is home to the largest
number of red-cockaded woodpeckers, and Army officials there are
helping fund Safe Harbor. U.S. Sen. Jesse Helms (R-N.C.) has
questioned whether U.S. military bases should concern themselves
with protecting birds at the risk of diverting attention from
training. Among the sharpest critics have been longleaf tree
farmers who fear the discovery of red-cockaded woodpeckers on their
property could prevent them from cutting trees in the birds'
habitat.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, some property owners took steps _ including
clear-cutting longleaf acreage _ to discourage the woodpeckers from
returning to their land. Safe Harbor is the brainchild of the
Environmental Defense Fund, a nonprofit conservation group. It
promises worried property owners that if they agree to take steps
to encourage the woodpeckers to move in, the government will not
prevent them from developing the property.Chris Burritt writes for
the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
