u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSINESS-TRAVEL-NYT &LR;      06-15 0926
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSINESS-TRAVEL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS TRAVEL: GOING BY RAIL; SIDE TRIPS; TWOFERS IN BRITAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JOE SHARKEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you're going where the tracks go, the train can be a
realistic, pleasant alternative to air travel. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the train doesn't have anywhere near the reach of the
plane. But for business travelers who happen to be headed where the
train tracks go, the railroad offers a realistic alternative to the
dread airport departure lounge.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a report on one recent business trip on Amtrak's
Metroliner, which travels between New York City and Washington,
D.C.:
</P>
<P>
   The train departed precisely on time. Seats were large
(comparable to business-class seats on an airplane), with big
pull-down trays and 120-volt outlets for electronic gear.
Throughout the trip, computers and cellular phones were widely in
use (though, in the case of cell phones, not ostentatiously).
</P>
<P>
   In the first-class car, the seats were the same as coach, but
attendants served free drinks and a hot meal or sandwich and
snacks. Arrival was exactly on time three hours later at
Washington's bustling Union Station. The ride was smooth and
pleasant.
</P>
<P>
   According to Amtrak, more business travelers are opting to go by
rail, at least on the well-trod Metroliner route between New York
and Washington. Last year, 2.1 million passengers took the
Metroliner; so far this year, ridership is up more than 6 percent,
according to an Amtrak spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Largely because of its growing popularity with business
travelers, the Metroliner makes a profit of about $10 million a
year for Amtrak, which recently announced an ambitious revamping of
the service. Starting late this year, the Metroliner will be called
Acela, with routes expanded to cover the whole Boston-New
York-Washington corridor.
</P>
<P>
   Metroliner fares are competitive with those for air travel, an
important consideration for many business travelers and employers,
who cringe at the huge disparity between air fares for unrestricted
business travel and discounted leisure travel. On the airlines, for
example, typical business fares now are nearly four times higher
than the lowest discounted leisure fares (whereas three years ago,
they were only about two and a half times higher), according to the
American Express Business Airfare Index.
</P>
<P>
   The weekday round-trip Metroliner fare from New York to
Washington is $230 ($376 for the first-class accommodations, which
means that the meal, drinks and extra service cost a very pricey
$146). Unrestricted round-trip fares on both the Delta Air Lines
and US Airways shuttles from New York to Washington are $404.
</P>
<P>
   Incidentally, the train-plane fare difference is far more
pronounced in California, which generously subsidizes some Amtrak
routes. The round-trip fares on the Amtrak San Diegan trains
between San Diego and Los Angeles, for example, are $50 ($72 for
business class). By air, UAL's United Express and Skywest
round-trip fares from Los Angeles to San Diego are $226.
</P>
<P>
   Side Trips
</P>
<P>
   Summer travel season is here, with mounting stresses on
air-traffic control. Late Monday afternoon, flight controllers
contending with thunderstorms in the Midwest ordered 50-mile
intervals between all flights converging on New York City, with
delays of an hour or more as flights piled up all across the
country.
</P>
<P>
   Usually, this is a recipe for more tension between
long-suffering air travelers and haughty airlines, especially when
a flight has left the gate only to idle interminably on the tarmac
while captive passengers fume at the lack of information and the
sit-down-and-shut-up attitude of the flight crew.
</P>
<P>
   Not so, however, on American Airlines Flight 1968 from Chicago
to Newark, N.J., on Monday afternoon. The cockpit crew and flight
attendants provided a textbook example of how to handle a long
delay with skill.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after announcing that the plane had been held
indefinitely on the ground in Chicago, the captain came back on and
said, earnestly, ``Folks, I didn't know about this when we left the
gate or, believe me, we would not have left that gate.''
</P>
<P>
   The captain then invited passengers to use their cell phones.
Flight attendants passed out cold drinks and magazines, while
making an inventory of passengers' connecting flights. Every 10
minutes, the pilot came back on to describe what he did and did not
know about the delay. And more than an hour later, after the plane
finally took off, a flight attendant announced that the captain had
persuaded both American and Continental Airlines in Newark to hold
connecting flights to Britain in order to accommodate several dozen
passengers on the delayed flight from Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   The upshot: Because of heads-up customer service, grumbles
turned to approval in the air. Most of the passengers actually
 &UR; thanked &LR;  the pilot as they filed out, well over an hour late.
</P>
<P>
   Twofers to Britain
</P>
<P>
   British Airways said Tuesday that it would offer a free
round-trip ticket to London with each seven-day advance-purchase
round-trip economy ticket bought before June 30 for summer travel.
(Sample round-trip fares for such British Airway tickets are: $598
from New York, $778 from Dallas and $798 from Los Angeles.)
</P>
<P>
   But there's a hitch: The free ticket is only good for travel
from Nov. 1, 1999, through March 31, 2000 (except Dec. 15 through
Jan. 15). This means the two tickets cannot be used together.
However, it's a good deal for a business traveler who has to make a
summer and winter trip to London. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
