<DOCNO> NYT19990615.0376 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-15 22:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6709 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSHWRAP-COX     06-15 0955
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSHWRAP-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush gleefully shaking hands with a crush of admirers
 &HT;    By Scott S. Greenberger
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DERRY, N.H. _ As television news soundman Ed Lewis stood outside
Madden's Family Restaurant and watched Gov. George W. Bush
gleefully shaking hands with a crush of admirers, he made a
comparison that might annoy Bush but which bodes well for his
chances of winning the White House in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's how Clinton was,'' marveled Lewis, who has covered four
New Hampshire primaries. ``It's rare that you see people who can be
that relaxed around so many people.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though Bush stuck to his pledge to remain in Texas until
the end of the legislative session and didn't officially become a
candidate until Saturday, he has been dominating his Republican
rivals in the polls and in the chase for campaign cash. But he
hadn't yet strode upon a national stage, and his much-anticipated
first campaign trip attracted a media horde of about 200, poised to
pounce on any mistake.
</P>
<P>
   Bush showed himself to be an enthusiastic and disciplined
campaigner who plunged into crowds with Clintonian glee and stayed
remarkably ``on message.'' He deftly handled a potentially
dangerous Monday news conference with a slew of national media
heavyweights, many of whom came away impressed with his politicking
prowess _ so far.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't make one.
</P>
<P>
   ``He managed to get through it without any real nicks and cuts,
much less any gaping wounds,'' said Larry Sabato, a University of
Virginia political scientist. ``It doesn't mean anything. It's too
early. It is impossible to say whether he can sustain this
unbelievable momentum.''
</P>
<P>
   At every stop, Bush dutifully plugged away at his main themes:
lower taxes, education, ``compassionate conservatism,''
inclusiveness, hope, optimism. He made the same jokes (the Clinton
administration ``didn't invent prosperity any more than it invented
the Internet'') and hit the same applause lines (marrying Laura was
``the best decision I ever made''). He always spoke a few lines in
Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, Bush barely mentioned any policy specifics, and
nearly all of the events during his four day trip to Iowa, Maine,
New Hampshire and Massachusetts were filled with people who already
support the governor. With a large lead in the polls _ a Boston
Herald poll during the trip put him at 45 percent, with Elizabeth
Dole and John McCain stuck at 11 percent _ he had nothing to gain
by taking stands on hot-button issues.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Smith, a pollster from the University of New Hampshire,
said Bush's numbers almost certainly will decline as takes specific
stands on issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now I think there's a tendency among Republican voters
to look at George Bush and see themselves in him,'' Smith said.
``He can't be all things to all people.''
</P>
<P>
   Opponents are counting on that. Ari Fleischer, spokesman for
Elizabeth Dole, was pleased that Bush took some heat on his first
trip for saying he would not use abortion as a ``litmus test'' in
selecting judges.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just the beginning of what is going to turn into the
challenges the governor is going to face as he defines himself.,''
said Fleischer. ``It's issues like that, as he takes stands, are
going to whittle down his great popularity.''
</P>
<P>
   Before Bush arrived, the conservative and influential Manchester
Union Leader compared Bush to ``one of those minor Hollywood
celebrities who is famous for being famous.'' But there's no doubt
that star power goes a long way in a political campaign _
particularly in a Republican party that is desperate for a winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's got the charisma and energy and ideas to unify
the party and be a real strong candidate,'' said Karen Maiola, a
pre-school teacher from Bow, N.H. after hearing Bush speak at a
fire station there.
</P>
<P>
   Herb Skogland, a retired obstetrician from Rome, N.Y., drove
five hours to hear Bush at St. Anselm's College in Goffstown, N.H.
Like many of those at Bush events, he said he didn't know much
about Bush's record or stands on the issues. But, Skogland said,
``He's the man, and I think he's going to make it.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the little things that counted. At the Bow fire station,
he removed his jacket with a comic flair that drew chuckles from
the audience. He dropped his ``g's'' and wore cowboy boots in Iowa
to play up his folksy Texas roots rather than his Eastern blueblood
pedigree _ a trick his father never could master. And when he
picked up a baby outside Madden's he rotated to give every camera a
clear shot. Bush said several times during the trip that he felt
energized by the beginning of his quest and, like Clinton, he
appears to enjoy the hand-shaking and baby-kissing that is crucial
in Iowa and New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday at Hadco Industries, a circuit board plant in Derry,
N.H., Bush skipped the tie and donned a blue windbreaker to greet
employees during an early morning shift change. With a half-dozen
microphones bobbing over his head and cameramen frantically
jockeying for position, the governor seemed aware that the
situation _ reminiscent of a scene in the 1970s Robert Redford film
``The Candidate'' _ was a bit ridiculous, and he exchanged knowing
glances with reporters. He appeared to love every minute of it.
</P>
<P>
   By the time he reached Boston for a fund-raiser at the Park
Plaza, he was once again wearing jacket and tie. Massachusetts Gov.
Paul Cellucci called it ``the largest ever fundraiser for
Republican in Massachusetts'' netted over $800,000 _ more than
double what was expected.
</P>
<P>
   Scott S. Greenberger writes for the Austin American-Statesman,
Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
