<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CAMBY-SPREWELL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAMBY AND SPREWELL STICK TOGETHER AND HELP TRANSFORM KNICKS
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ The second day of training camp passed and Marcus
Camby was spotted standing near the door of the gym while several
teammates slipped by his lanky frame without two words to him.
</P>
<P>
   At first, it was lonely not being Charles Oakley. Camby
understood the emotional connection that the Knicks, the city and
the coach had with the folk hero he replaced last June, but it
wasn't him who made the trade. No one seemed to understand.
</P>
<P>
   But during that same week, there was one teammate who came
along, a free-spirited person who had no ties to Oakley and no
preconceived notions to color his opinion of Camby.
</P>
<P>
   On the third day of camp in walked another outcast, Latrell
Sprewell. If anything, the two had their isolation in common.
</P>
<P>
   Camby arrived as a young, talented player who had been blemished
by his contacts with slippery agents at the University of
Massachusetts and marked as frail after two injury-prone seasons in
Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell was coming off a suspension for choking his former
coach, P.J. Carlesimo, and seemed the symbol of a league gone
horribly awry.
</P>
<P>
   It is no wonder the two have become inseparable ever since.
Side-by-side in every mall and record store on the road,
side-by-side in a fast-break style that has made everyone's memory
of the Charles Oakley-John Starks era fade just a bit, Sprewell and
Camby have endured a difficult season together.
</P>
<P>
   And together, they are just one series away from winning a title
for a city, a team and a coach that once hesitated to embrace them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coming into a new situation, it's hard to reach out and find
someone you can hang with on and off the court,'' Camby said
Tuesday, the day before Game 1 of the Knicks' league championship
series against San Antonio. ``You need someone similar to you and a
guy who has been where you've been. And I think Latrell and I both
came into a new city, a new team, a new system and I think we both
confided in each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once we sat down we just had a great vibe. We had great talks
and conversation. Here's a guy who had trouble last year, but he
needed someone to relate to, and I think I was that guy.''
</P>
<P>
   They had more than just their pasts to relate, too. Both had to
deal with a sometimes strained relationship with Coach Jeff Van
Gundy and wait patiently for their time to be set free on the
floor.
</P>
<P>
   As the season began, Sprewell was a starter, but soon lost that
role when he came back from a stress fracture. Upon his return, he
seemed too selfish to function in the system. At the same time,
Camby was lost in the rotation and can vividly remember the
humiliation of playing only 19 seconds in the Knicks' season opener
in Orlando.
</P>
<P>
   ``Spree and I used to talk about how things were going to change
for the better,'' Camby said. ``We held to the belief that with
both of us in the game together, we could make things happen.''
</P>
<P>
   They were right. By midseason, they became the most adored of
Knicks. No two receive louder applause than Sprewell and Camby. No
two left the Madison Square Garden crowd so breathless as when
Sprewell exploded for menacing dunks and Camby soared through the
air with the sleek lines of a Concorde.
</P>
<P>
   In time, they have transformed the Garden into their cozy home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everyone has to have a home, eventually,'' assistant
coach Don Chaney said. ``Both of those guys were sort of like
homeless at first. They found themselves in a situation they had to
come to accept. Now, when they come into a game, they change the
whole tempo of things. In their minds, there's that bond anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can say, `We are the key to this team succeeding.' I
think it started off the court with their closeness. They were the
outsiders, but they were the ones to help this team get to where it
is. They are together on and off the court.''
</P>
<P>
   Their ties aren't limited to basketball and their difficult
paths to acceptance. Camby owns a laptop now. Nearly classified as
an egghead with his love of computers, Sprewell has opened Camby's
eyes to a high-tech world beyond a CD player. This is not to say
the two never venture out, but there are a lot of nights when they
kill time on the road by renting an Eddie Murphy movie, surfing the
net and talking about cars.
</P>
<P>
   ``They talk cars all the time,'' Chris Childs said. ``They're
real tight. But I think that it's like when I came here, it takes
time to gradually work your way into the family. With this team, I
think everyone has come to click. But those two, they have the same
character and have gone through the same things with the
expectations people have had of them, so it's good to see them get
along. It's good to see everyone get along.''
</P>
<P>
   There were some strained moments at first. The city, some
pockets of the team, and critics were skeptical of the newcomers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was definitely tough for both of us in the beginning,''
Camby said. ``I know for me, just because of who I was traded for,
there was going to be a lot of animosity toward me because of the
deal. You're looking for someone to identify with, and someone you
can talk to. I think we helped each other out a lot in that way.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-15-99 2249EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
