<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-15 22:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6721 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-CHARTER-SCHOOLS-NY     06-15 0981
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CHARTER-SCHOOLS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
N.Y. STATE'S FIRST CHARTER SCHOOLS ARE PICKED 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ANEMONA HARTOCOLLIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A state board selected the first eight charter schools for New
York state Tuesday, setting the stage for a new and hotly disputed
system of taxpayer-financed schools operating outside the regular
public school system. Four of them will be run by profit-making
corporations, and one will be in a school building owned by a
church.
</P>
<P>
   The newly created charter schools, like those in other states
across the country, will receive public money but be freed from the
constraints of local school district rules and union contracts.
</P>
<P>
   But the most radical change for the state and for New York City
is the inclusion of profit-making schools in the first round of
selections. The teachers' union, one of the most effective lobbying
forces in Albany, has fought hard against creating schools outside
of the public system, and is particularly opposed to having
profit-making companies running charter schools. So are most school
superintendents in the state, including Chancellor Rudy Crew in New
York City.
</P>
<P>
   The schools chosen Tuesday represent a mix of ethnic and
regional interests, from a Dominican-oriented school in the
Washington Heights section of Manhattan to a Chinese-oriented
school in Flushing, Queens, and a school sponsored by the Urban
League in Albany. Three of the schools will open in the fall, and
the other five in the fall of 2000. Among the first three, two are
profit-making, one in New York City and one in Albany. The third,
also in New York City, will be nonprofit.
</P>
<P>
   The profit-making school in New York City brings together an
unusual coalition of civil rights advocates, community leaders,
church leaders and wealthy Wall Street business executives, who say
they are looking for alternatives to failing public schools in poor
neighborhoods. It will be called the Sisulu Children's Academy,
after Walter Sisulu, the South African freedom fighter, friend of
Nelson Mandela and fellow leader of the African National Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Union officials attacked the initial round of selections
Tuesday, saying that they had been made in secret and that they
appeared to advance the interests of private companies in taking
over education.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George Pataki, who pushed hard for the charter school
legislation, hailed the first round of schools Tuesday as ``the
single greatest improvement in education in state history.''
</P>
<P>
   Pataki's staff reviewed the charter school applications, said
Scott Steffey, a vice chancellor at the State University of New
York, which, under the law, has the authority to issue charters for
50 new schools. But Steffey said the governor and his staff played
no role in selecting the schools. Steffey said he supervised the
screening of the applications, which were reviewed by two panels of
charter-school founders, academicians and consultants across the
country.
</P>
<P>
   Their recommendations were approved unanimously Tuesday by the
SUNY trustees, meeting in midtown Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   The Sisulu Academy, the profit-making school in New York City,
will be run by Victory Schools Inc., a private management company
set up by Steven Klinsky, a general partner in Forstmann Little &AMP;
Co., the leveraged buyout firm. Another partner, Theodore
Forstmann, made news two months ago when he raised $170 million for
scholarships to send poor children to private schools, attracting a
million applicants nationwide for 40,000 slots.
</P>
<P>
   Sisulu will be in a school building owned by the Canaan Baptist
Church of Christ in Harlem, at 115th Street between St. Nicholas
and Lenox Avenues, but officials said that in accordance with the
charter law, no religious instruction would be given, and that the
church would be only a landlord. Rent, Klinsky said, will be about
$16,000 a month, which he said was market rate.
</P>
<P>
   Klinsky said Tuesday: ``One of the toughest things in the
charter school movement is going to be to find real estate. It's a
beautiful new building, and Harlem is so symbolically important a
place to start.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he expected to earn a profit by managing the school more
efficiently than other public schools. He and other applicants said
they expected to get $6,000 per pupil in state, federal and local
spending, about $2,000 less than New York City spends on its
students. The typical profit margin for a charter school in other
states is 7 to 15 percent, according to Steffey.
</P>
<P>
   All but one of the charter schools are starting with fewer than
250 students, which under the law will make them exempt from
teachers' union contracts, even if they grow in subsequent years,
Steffey said.
</P>
<P>
   The New Covenant Charter School in the Arbor Hill neighborhood
of Albany, which is also scheduled to open this fall, will be
managed by Advantage Schools, a profit-making company that runs
schools in other parts of the country, in conjunction with the
Urban League of Northeastern New York.
</P>
<P>
   The third school to open this fall is the John Reisenbach
Charter School, a nonprofit school to be run by the Learning
Project Inc. It will also be in Harlem, at Lenox Avenue and 126th
Street.
</P>
<P>
   The five schools approved Tuesday for the fall of 2000 are
these:
</P>
<P>
   _ The Amber Charter School, a nonprofit to be run in partnership
with the Community Association of Progressive Dominicans in
Washington Heights.
</P>
<P>
   _ Flushing International Charter School, a profit-making school
to be run by SABIS Educational Systems Inc., in Flushing, Queens.
</P>
<P>
   The Syracuse Charter School, a nonprofit to be run by Margaret
Brooks, a former teacher, in Syracuse.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Victory Children's Academy in Roosevelt, Long Island,
which also will be run by Klinsky's management company.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Harbor Science and Arts Charter School, a nonprofit to be
run by Boys' Harbor in East Harlem.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
