<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Slide ends for Braves, Glavine
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ You had to know it wasn't going to come the easy way.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves finally worked their way out of the season-long
four-game losing streak with a 4-3 win over the NL Central-leading
Astros on a ninth-inning bloop hit by Brian Hunter.
</P>
<P>
   Javy Lopez lead off the inning with an infield hit. Pinch
running for him, Otis Nixon then stole second by sneaking a hand
into the base just ahead of a Ricky Gutierrez tag. After watching
6-foot-7 Houston reliever Scott Elarton strike out Ryan Klesko and
Andruw Jones back-to-back, Hunter worked a first pitch into center
field for a single.
</P>
<P>
   Using a season-high eight strikeouts, Tom Glavine pitched truer
to form on Tuesday night and got his first win since May 19 to show
for it. He had to fight his way through the last four innings but
was rewarded. The 4-7 Glavine had gone four starts without a win.
</P>
<P>
   He gets little sympathy from Houston's fifth starter Chris Holt.
Holt, who missed all of last season after rotator cuff surgery, was
seeking his first win since Aug. 21, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves, faced with a barrage of questions this season and a
barrage of runs in the previous two games, finally came up with an
answer against Holt on Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   After watching the Astros jump on Glavine with three runs on
three hits in the fourth, the Braves came ripping back with three
consecutive hits of their own to even the game 3-3 in the top of
the fifth inning. A two-run homer by Andruw Jones cut the lead to
3-2. A Randall Simon double and a two-out error by Craig Biggio
allowed the Braves to even the score as Simon took off from second
on Keith Lockhart's ground ball and slid in safely ahead of
Biggio's recovery throw home.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Glavine had gone four starts without a win and collected
only three in the first third of the season, after a 20-win Cy
Young award-winning season last year.
</P>
<P>
   He gets little sympathy from Houston's fifth starter Chris Holt.
Holt, who missed all last season after rotator cuff surgery, was
seeking his first win since Aug. 21, 1997. He's lost all six of his
decisions this season and had taken back-to-back no-decisions
despite leaving with leads in each of his last two starts.
</P>
<P>
   Through six innings it was a draw.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves, faced with a barrage of questions this season and a
barrage of runs in the previous two games, finally came up with an
answer on Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   After watching the Astros jump on Glavine with three runs on
three hits in the fourth, the Braves came ripping back with three
consecutive hits of their own to even the game 3-3 in the top of
the fifth inning. A two-run homer by Andruw Jones cut the lead to
3-2. A Randall Simon double and a two-out error by Craig Biggio
allowed the Braves to even the score as Simon took off from second
on Keith Lockhart's ground ball and slid in safely ahead of
Biggio's recovery throw home, which Tony Eusebio failed to catch
cleanly.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves made it out of the first inning without a deficit to
deal with for the first time since Friday night's game against the
Devil Rays. Glavine made it through the order the initial time
without allowing a run for the first time in three starts.
</P>
<P>
   Then Jeff Bagwell got busy. He pumped a homer to left field, his
second in as many nights, to start a three-run fourth inning, which
featured a Richard Hidalgo double off the center-field wall and a
Carl Everett sacrifice fly.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll Rogers writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
