<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TWA-UNION-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWA AND UNION NOW AWAIT MEMBERS' VOTE ON NEW PROPOSAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RANDOLPH HEASTER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ TWA and Machinists union officials are
endorsing new contract proposals for 16,000 of the carrier's
employees, but the decision will rest with union members.
</P>
<P>
   The union Tuesday confirmed that, under terms of the tentative
18-month agreement, the employees would receive an 8.5 percent
raise on Aug. 1 and a 3 percent raise in August 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Trans World Airlines also would increase benefits and pension
fund contributions, according to Glenn Sanders, secretary-treasurer
of Machinists Local 1650.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nothing to jump up and down about,'' Sanders said. ``In
my opinion, it's a little better than what was previously offered.
But the members will have the final say.''
</P>
<P>
   In voting last week, TWA workers appeared to be rejecting a
contract that the company said would bring wages to 90 percent of
the industry standard by July 2001.
</P>
<P>
   The new proposal, tentatively agreed to Sunday, would expire in
January 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders said TWA employees he has talked to were mixed in their
reactions to the latest proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they're split right now,'' he said. ``But we don't
have all the details yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Sanders said the local hoped Friday to distribute copies of the
proposal to the area's 2,300 TWA mechanics. A meeting to discuss
and vote on the proposal is expected next week, tentatively
scheduled for the Music Hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``That will give everybody about four or five days to study the
contract and make their decision,'' Sanders said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the mechanics and ramp workers, the Machinists
union represents TWA's flight attendants and customer-service
employees. If one of those groups rejects its contract proposals,
the agreement does not take effect.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders said one advantage of the proposal was that it expires
in January 2001. That would allow the union to re-evaluate industry
standards before negotiating a long-term deal.
</P>
<P>
   After accepting concessionary contracts to keep TWA afloat
throughout the 1990s, the union had demanded that TWA wages be
brought up to industry standard in the next contract.
</P>
<P>
   The maximum hourly pay for TWA mechanics now is $17.93. Under
the tentative agreement, that would rise to $20.03 in August 2000.
</P>
<P>
   But the proposal does not account for TWA employees working
under terms of a previous contract since September 1997, when the
pact was to have expired. That means no back pay.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing is retroactive, and that's a disadvantage,'' Sanders
said.
</P>
<P>
   The union also agreed to some use of regional jets by TWA's
commuter partners, a provision that aviation experts said TWA
needed to compete with other major airlines.
</P>
<P>
   Industry analysts said TWA and union officials had found a
workable compromise for now.
</P>
<P>
   ``This essentially buys TWA more time,'' said Linda Bannister,
airline analyst with Edward Jones in St. Louis. ``This gives TWA 18
months to get its house in order, from a financial standpoint.''
</P>
<P>
   It also gives the union time to assess William F. Compton, the
company's new chief executive officer, said David Levine,
contributing editor of PlaneBusiness, an industry financial
newsletter. Compton last month succeeded TWA Chairman Gerald
Gitner, who was much maligned by the union for his downsizing
tactics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Will Compton continue shrinking the airline, or will TWA start
growing again?'' Levine said. ``The employees will find out whether
Compton truly is interested in improving relations between himself
and the unions.''
</P>
<P>
   But Levine also sees problems with the tentative agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``The downside obviously is that it will put TWA back into the
negotiating cycle very quickly,'' he said. ``Talks could start
again as early as spring.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
