<SLUG> BC-BLOCK-PROFIT-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
H&AMP;R BLOCK'S OLD AND NEW UNITS DO WELL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GENE MEYER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ H&AMP;R Block Inc. on Tuesday reported a
larger-than-predicted 29 percent increase in profit from its
continuing tax and financial services operations.
</P>
<P>
   Complex new tax rules brought more customers to Block's
traditional tax preparation centers last filing season, producing
20 percent growth for the company in what is generally called a
mature industry.
</P>
<P>
   But market analysts following the stock say they also were
impressed by a near doubling of Block's much newer mortgage lending
business, as well as its other expansion efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Block's newest business services unit, which is composed of
regional accounting firms the company began buying 13 months ago,
turned a $7.1 million profit for the year.
</P>
<P>
   And when Block reported its earnings Tuesday, the company also
announced that its Ohio, Arizona and Indiana tests of new expanded
Block Financial Centers during the recent filing season went so
well that 70 new centers will be opened by the end of December. The
precise locations are still being picked, the company said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, Block has its plate full, but I think the outlook is
quite positive,'' said Pete Heckmann, a research analyst at George
K. Baum &AMP; Co. in Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   Block reported that its profit from continuing operations rose
to $237.8 million, or $2.36 a share, during the year ending April
30, from $183.8 million, or $1.71 a share, the previous year.
</P>
<P>
   However, the Kansas City financial services company's total
profit for fiscal 1999 dropped from year-earlier levels, to $215.4
million, or $2.14 a share, from $392.1 million, or $3.65 a share.
</P>
<P>
   Final profit was lower because of one-time losses on credit card
operations that Block sold in January and a much larger one-time
profit the company made on its sale of CompuServe Corp. in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Revenue rose to $1.64 billion from $1.27 billion a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Block's core tax services and its newer mortgage lending
operations were the biggest contributors to the higher
continuing-operations profit, said Frank L. Salizonni, the
company's president and chief executive officer.
</P>
<P>
   Higher revenue, lower bad debt expenses in the company's refund
anticipation loan program and improved tax software sales all
improved tax service profits, he said.
</P>
<P>
   As usual, the largest share of profit and revenue occurred
during Block's fourth quarter, which spans the peak filing season
for U.S. taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   Block had earnings of $297.3 million, or $3.05 a share, on
revenue of $1.2 billion during the latest fourth quarter, up from
$256.9 million, or $2.43 a share, on revenue of $967.6 million a
year earlier.
</P>
</TEXT>
