A6846 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-WISH-COME-TRUE-CO     06-15 0524
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-WISH-COME-TRUE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Man lives his dream at Cinergy Field
 &HT;    By Sam Borden
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI _ The words are in shaky print, with mostly capital
letters, as though the author's hand could not keep up with his
flowing thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is from the memory of a soon-to-be 78-year old,'' the
note read, ``and I could go on and on.''
</P>
<P>
   But he won't.
</P>
<P>
   Cancer has ravaged Dewitt Sparks' lungs, draining the life out
of his body with each passing hour. But while the malignant tumor
has left the long-time Dayton resident's body in a battered,
withered state, his eyes _ and his dreams _ remain immune.
</P>
<P>
   Sparks had written down some of the things he wanted to say to
two of his heroes, Cincinnati Reds radio announcers Marty Brennaman
and Joe Nuxhall, and Tuesday night he was able to pass the message
on as he spent two innings in the broadcast booth at Cinergy Field.
</P>
<P>
   ``I grew up with baseball and listening to the Reds,'' Sparks
whispered, his voice barely audible above the din of the crowd.
``I've been here many times but this is something that I've always
wanted to do.''
</P>
<P>
   With the help of The Angel Foundation, which arranged for the
visit during the fourth and fifth innings of the game with the New
York Mets, Sparks' wish came true.
</P>
<P>
   It seemed as though an angel was watching, too, as a foul ball
from the Mets' John Olerud found its way into the press box while
Sparks looked on. Gripping the ball in hands that have tuned his
radio dial to listen to the Reds for decades, Sparks talked with
Nuxhall about ``the good old days.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We talked about the old ballparks and where he used to play,''
Nuxhall said. ``His spirits are great _ if we can make someone feel
good for a day, or week, or anything, it's worth it.''
</P>
<P>
   It's unknown how many days and weeks Sparks has left, but the
1939 Roosevelt High School graduate began his life with baseball,
playing catcher in Little League because, he says, ``that's where
the action was.''
</P>
<P>
   Clutching faded black-and-white pictures of rare Indian Chief
motorcycles and talking about the airplanes he flew without a
license, it became clear that Sparks holds his past tightly against
his present. For about 30 minutes Tuesday, they were one and the
same.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Joe started pitching about the same time I started
working for NCR, so I've followed him for a long time,'' Sparks
said. ``I've always admired the guy. Tonight is a dream come true
for me.''
</P>
<P>
   A dream that may have come just in time for Sparks, who is
forced to spend most of his time in a wheelchair. As he and
Brennaman chatted about radio announcers, a photographer moved in
and asked Sparks if he would give the Reds play-by-play man a big
smile.
</P>
<P>
   ``These days, most of the time it hurts to smile,'' Sparks
choked out, his blue eyes suddenly shining brightly.
</P>
<P>
   But then he flashed a toothy grin, like a man who had been
filled with joy.
</P>
<P>
   Or, like someone who had been touched by an angel.
</P>
<P>
   Sam Borden writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
