<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-DISCIPLINED-PRINCIPAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRINCIPAL'S 6-YEAR LEGAL BATTLE NEARS END 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ANTHONY RAMIREZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The six-year legal battle that put a Westchester County
elementary school principal in legal limbo and led to legal bills
of nearly $1 million, and whose almost Dickensian bureaucratic
inertia embarrassed the school district that brought the case, has
reached a tentative conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   Raymond Kuntz, the lawyer for the Hendrick Hudson Central School
District, said in an interview Tuesday night that the district and
Joanne Falinski, the principal that the district tried to
discipline in 1993, had settled out of court. He declined to give
details, including whether Dr. Falinski would be reinstated or
would receive money in a settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Reading from a draft statement, Kuntz said, ``Both sides have
agreed to resolve these matters in order to avoid the expense and
length of time necessarily involved in pursuing legal procedures to
their conclusion.'' The settlement, he said, also includes Dr.
Falinski's federal lawsuit against the district charging that
rights to free speech were abridged.
</P>
<P>
   Kuntz said that the agreement would not be legally binding until
Tuesday and that he could not comment on it. Robert Saperstein, Dr.
Falinski's attorney, declined comment. Dr. Falinski's telephone
number is not listed.
</P>
<P>
   Stacie Cignarale, president of the school board, declined to
discuss the settlement, but said, ``The community wants this.''
</P>
<P>
   The Falinski case has lasted so long that all 325 children at
the Furnace Woods School in Cortlandt when she was the principal
have since graduated. Now 46, Dr. Falinski, once one of the
youngest principals in the state, has been preparing schedules and
doing other clerical work while collecting her $100,000 annual
salary. In six years, the district has held 64 days of hearings.
</P>
<P>
   The superintendent who suspended her has retired and the
principal who replaced her has herself been replaced. And there is
a largely new school board and president.
</P>
<P>
   The act under which she was accused, known as 3020a, was
intended to oust criminal or incompetent teachers.
</P>
<P>
   The worst misconduct charge involved telling a child's parents
that unless the boy was taken off the drug Ritalin, the school
would not provide counseling.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-15-99 2315EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
