<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-POLICE-RACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACCUSATIONS OF RACIST LEADERSHIP PROMPT N.J. TROOPERS' UNION TO
SPLIT
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By DAVID KOCIENIEWSKI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. _ Two months after Gov. Christie Whitman issued a
report confirming that State Police routinely discriminate against
minority drivers, the force was shaken by two new racial incidents
Tuesday, when both the acting superintendent and the head of the
officers' union came under fire for allegedly making offensive
comments about women, Latinos and blacks.
</P>
<P>
   A group of 70 minority and female officers announced that they
are withdrawing from the State Troopers' Fraternal Organization,
saying that the union president routinely referred to them using
racial epithets and crude references to female genitalia.
</P>
<P>
   And Acting Superintendent Michael Fedorko _ who assumed command
when the previous superintendent was fired for making racially
insensitive comments in February _ was forced to defend himself
after a newspaper published transcripts from a police gathering in
1995, in which he made jokes about Latin music and made vulgar
comments suggesting that female troopers lack the bravery to do
their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Fedorko said the newspaper had taken his comments out of context
because they were made at the equivalent of a celebrity roast.
</P>
<P>
   ``It bothers me that they attacked my leadership,'' Fedorko said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman said that she would let the attorney general determine
whether Fedorko's statements warranted disciplinary action. But she
said that statements Fedorko made in 1995 _ they were videotaped
and reported in The Record of Hackensack _ were troubling.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't sound like jokes that I would think are
particularly funny,'' Whitman said.
</P>
<P>
   The flare-ups come at a particularly troubling time for Whitman,
who this spring became the first New Jersey official to acknowledge
that troopers used racial profiling to stop and search minority
drivers illegally. The governor had hoped to put the issue behind
her and was trying to revamp the force before the U.S. Justice
Department civil rights division takes legal action.
</P>
<P>
   But the governor's offer to Col. Andre Parker of the Illinois
State Police to become New Jersey's first black police
superintendent has set off a chain reaction of lobbying, political
posturing and heated words.
</P>
<P>
   Many legislators are pushing the governor to promote from within
the ranks, saying that the appointment of an outsider would damage
morale.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Iskrzycki, president of the troopers union, has also
spoken out against Parker. He was quoted in the Star-Ledger of
Newark this week as saying that ``I'd rather have them choose Al
Sharpton.''
</P>
<P>
   Iskrzycki's comments so infuriated minority troopers that they
decided to withdraw from the union.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing Colonel Parker has in common with Al Sharpton
is that he's a black man who the union officials obviously don't
like,'' said Phil Moran, a lawyer who is helping minority troopers
form their own fraternal organization.
</P>
<P>
   Moran said Iskrzycki has for years ``referred to people using
racial slurs, sexist comments and has utterly failed to represent
anyone other than white troopers.''
</P>
<P>
   Iskrzycki did not return calls requesting comment, but a
spokesman said he was misquoted.
</P>
<P>
   Parker, the only outside candidate on the short list of five
finalists for the superintendent's job, has not accepted the offer.
Whitman administration officials say that Parker thinks it will
take three years to transform the force and is concerned that if
Whitman is elected to the Senate in 2000, his tenure could end in
less than 15 months.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
