<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NY-CHARTER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: POLITICIZING THE CITY CHARTER 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Wednesday, June 16:
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's plan to revise New York City's Charter
is a political power play and a terrible civics lesson. The mayor
announced a new Charter Revision Commission on Tuesday that he
hopes will consider what happens if he leaves office early. Under
the current Charter, Public Advocate Mark Green would become the
mayor, and Giuliani clearly does not want one of his most vocal
critics to take over if he is elected to the U.S. Senate next year.
</P>
<P>
   As the Charter now reads, if the mayor leaves for Washington in
January 2001 Green would take charge for almost a year before the
next mayoral election, in November 2001. From this City Hall perch,
Green would have much higher visibility in the next contest for
mayor against other possible contenders, including Council Speaker
Peter Vallone, Comptroller Alan Hevesi and Bronx Borough President
Fernando Ferrer. The new commission is expected to consider
changing the system so that if the public advocate or perhaps even
the comptroller takes over from the mayor, there would be another
city election in 60 days.
</P>
<P>
   As succession mechanisms go, a quick special election can be a
valid way to fill a vacancy. But this effort to change the rules in
the middle of the game will open the door to all sorts of mischief.
However satisfying to the mayor in the short term, there are
long-term hazards to tampering with the city's fundamental
structure. Once convened, this commission can be expected to
address some of the city's most controversial issues _ including
term limits for politicians, land use planning, nonpartisan
elections and the budget process. The commission, headed by the
mayor's friend and former deputy, Randy Mastro, is loaded with
Giuliani supporters. There is little time to produce thoughtful and
well-aired recommendations for the ballot this November. Because
this off-year election involves only a few scattered city races,
voter turnout should be about a third of the turnout in regular
elections. The mayor says that New York voters could then focus on
revising the charter without other electoral distractions. More
likely, voters would simply forget to go to the polls. This is no
way to change the basic structure of New York City government.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
