<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-RATLIFF-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLOYD RATLIFF IS DEAD AT 80; LINKED VISUAL ARTS TO SCIENCE
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: N.M., Colo.)  (nk) 
 By WOLFGANG SAXON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dr. Floyd Ratliff, a physiological psychologist and biophysicist
who explored the depths of consciousness and perception, died on
Sunday in Santa Fe, N.M., where he moved after retiring from
Rockefeller University in New York. He was 80.
</P>
<P>
   Ratliff combined expertise in his specialties with a keen
interest in the history and philosophy of science. One focal point
was the thought of Ernst Mach, the Austrian physicist, psychologist
and philosopher of science (1838-1916), who was a leader of modern
positivism.
</P>
<P>
   Ratliff, who taught at Rockefeller for 31 years and became a
professor emeritus in 1989, also studied the relations binding the
visual arts and visual sciences as witnessed in 19th-century
science, Neo-Impressionism and the contrast and contour effects of
art of the Sung Dynasty. With this in mind, he examined the neural
mechanisms of vision, especially how the retina analyzes and
reduces the apparent chaos of incoming data.
</P>
<P>
   His laboratory explored molecular events elicited by a single
particle of light within a single nerve cell. The findings have
been used to diagnose visual and other neurological disorders.
</P>
<P>
   His retinal studies led to investigations of the scientific
basis for subjective visual phenomena _ like the ``optical
illusions'' in contrasts of color and brightness _ that have served
to inspire artists. It was Mach who first mathematically formulated
the psychophysiological bases of such contrast effects.
</P>
<P>
   Ratliff wrote extensively in his field and published the
textbook ``Mach Bands: Quantitative Studies of Neural Networks in
the Retina'' (Holden-Day, 1965) as well as ``Paul Signac and Color
in Neo-Impressionism'' (Rockefeller University, 1992).
</P>
<P>
   Signac, in association with Georges Seurat, developed the
divisionist school, also known as Pointillism, in which the painter
employed small dabs of color for the eye of the viewer to blend for
intense color effects.
</P>
<P>
   Floyd Ratliff was born in La Junta, Colo., and served in World
War II. He graduated from Colorado College in 1947, and went to
Brown University for an M.A., followed by a Ph.D. in psychology.
</P>
<P>
   He was elected a member of the National Academy of Science and
the American Academy of Arts and Sciences. For most of the 1980s he
was president of the Harry Frank Guggenheim Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Ratliff is survived by his wife of 57 years, Orma Vernon Priddy
Ratliff; a daughter, Merry Alice Muraskin of Manhattan; a sister,
Edith Johnson, and a grandson.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-15-99 2330EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990615.0394 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-15 23:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6863 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMMIG-DRUGS-2TAKES-NY     06-15 0957
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMMIG-DRUGS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW INSIGHTS ON TREATING IMMIGRANTS FOR DRUG AND ALCOHOL ABUSE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By SUSAN SACHS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For years, Mohammed Arif denied he had a drinking
problem. He saw himself as an immigrant success story: He had
mastered a new language, earned enough to support relatives back in
his native Pakistan, and fit right in when his fellow construction
workers hit the bars at the end of the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing about drinking was this false pride,'' Arif said,
recalling the dark years when he failed to see how alcohol was
corroding his new life. ``There was all this finger-pointing in my
family, and it would get me so mad. Why is everyone telling me I've
got a drinking problem when it's me who's taking care of
everybody?''
</P>
<P>
   He eventually sought help, ricocheting from one detoxification
program to another. It was not until he landed at Nav Nirmaan, the
only New York City substance-abuse treatment program run by and for
immigrants from Southeast Asia, that he pulled himself and his
family together.
</P>
<P>
   ``It made a big difference,'' said Arif, who now tells his story
as a means of counseling other immigrants at the center, which is
in Elmhurst, Queens. ``When you're with people from your own
background, your own culture, it's like there's no more curtain in
front of your eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   Nav Nirmaan, which means ``new beginning'' in the Gujrathi
language of western India, is at the vanguard of a growing trend in
drug and alcohol treatment programs that not only provide
counseling in the native language of immigrants, but also consider
their cultural background and the traumas of the immigrant
experience itself.
</P>
<P>
   Immigrants arrive with specific cultural attitudes and family
dynamics that influence how they respond to treatment. In a Russian
family, for example, a teen-ager on drugs often listens more to a
grandparent's guidance than a parent's. An Asian man arrested for
drunken driving is more likely to let down his defenses and talk
with a female therapist. And the therapy offered in mainstream drug
abuse and alcoholism programs, counselors say, does not work for
immigrants who fear or distrust authority figures, feel deep shame
at revealing family problems to strangers, and do not relate to
their self-help jargon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Immigration and acculturation stress are very pronounced in
immigrants,'' said Luis Zayas, a psychologist and professor of
social work at Fordham University who has studied drinking patterns
in Latin American immigrants. ``But it's only recently that we have
culturally adjusted treatment, as more clinicians become attuned to
the impact of immigration.''
</P>
<P>
   Spanish-language social service groups proliferated in the
mid-1980s, and there are now many substance-abuse centers with
Spanish-speaking professional staff members. But there have been
far fewer services adapted to the non-Hispanic immigrants who have
poured into the New York City area in the last decade, bringing
with them their own cultural idiosyncrasies.
</P>
<P>
   The White House Office of National Drug Control Policy has now
recognized that an antidrug message aimed at American-born parents
and their children may not make sense to immigrant families who do
not even recognize drug slang.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning next month, its new $185 million youth campaign will
feature material in 11 languages tailored to Hispanic, Vietnamese,
Korean and other cultures. ``The issue is not that they have
greater drug use _ many of these groups have drug rates that are
lower than whites,'' said Alan Levitt, the manager of the antidrug
campaign. ``It's just that for some of these audiences
_first-generation immigrants, for example _ there is a whole
different kind of information you have to supply.''
</P>
<P>
   That immigration is stressful, now and in the past, is obvious.
For people who do not speak English, it means first and foremost
the inability to communicate. Often, especially for those from the
former Soviet Union and some Asians, it means a substantial loss of
economic and social standing.
</P>
<P>
   Female immigrants usually find work faster than the men,
straining traditional family roles, because they are more willing
to take low-status jobs. Children adjust to the new culture and
learn English before their parents, giving them more independence
and more adult-like responsibilities.
</P>
<P>
   In short, psychologists say, what many people experience when
they come to the United States is a tremendous sense of loss. Some
immigrants try to cope by turning to drugs or alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually, we hear the phrase `I'm nobody here,' '' said Helen
Kagen, a social worker who runs a substance abuse program for
Russian-speaking immigrants at the Educational Alliance in
Manhattan. ``People find themselves in a situation where they are
not capable of doing anything.''
</P>
<P>
   She said the pressures are particularly debilitating to
immigrants from the former Soviet Union, who are products of a
culture that embraced drinking and a totalitarian system that
undermined individuality.
</P>
<P>
   Counselors who deal with Russian-speaking immigrants said they
were also seeing serious drug use in youngsters, who experience
both the exhilarating freedom and the burdens typical of immigrant
children.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kids are under stress, even more than the adults,'' said
Anna Snol, who counsels teen-agers in Brooklyn with her husband,
Arkadiy, a former doctor in a Soviet prison camp for drug users.
``They come here and everything is possible: sex freedom, work
freedom, school freedom.
</P>
<P>
   ``They learn English and they know more than their parents. They
begin to feel themselves heroes. They say to themselves, I see
everybody smoking marijuana. Why not me?''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Problems arise when old habits combine with immigration stress,
boredom and lack of knowledge about local laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``Drinking is so deeply rooted in the culture, especially with
male identity,'' said Mina Chang, the director of the Asian
American Mental Health Institute in Queens, who has created an
alcohol treatment program for Korean immigrants. ``The more you
drink, the more you show you can control yourself and the more you
are male.''
</P>
<P>
   For immigrants, as for anyone else, one family member's drinking
problem can spawn other problems, like spouse and child abuse, and
that is the behavior that often brings them forcibly into
treatment.
</P>
<P>
   ``In our cultural makeup, the cry for help is the last stage,''
said Roy Tellis, the Indian-born executive director of Nav Nirmaan.
``There's a lot of shame involved, and there's the isolation.''
</P>
<P>
   The typical Nav Nirmaan client, he said, is a man who lives in a
cultural cocoon. He drinks as a form of socializing with other men
from his home region, reads newspapers and watches television shows
in his native language, and feels confusion and rage when his wife
and Americanized children try to venture outside the tight circle
of Southeast Asian culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a male-dominated patriarchal society,'' Tellis said.
``And the father says: I work hard, I put food on the table. So
what if I take a few drinks?''
</P>
<P>
   An approach like that used in Alcoholics Anonymous, counselors
said, rarely works with immigrants. People from the former Soviet
Union, for example, often distrust not only their peers, but also
people with authority. ``We are talking about an enormous level of
resistance to outside persuasion, because all the messages, all the
lies, in the totalitarian society were delivered by authority
figures,'' said Dr. Kagen of the Educational Alliance.
</P>
<P>
   And it is particularly difficult for those who lived in the
Soviet system to admit they are alcoholics, a term that was
reserved for those in the physically incapacitated late stages of
the disease.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Russia, there is a difference between a drinker and an
alcoholic,'' said Michael, one of Dr. Kagen's clients who spoke
only on the condition that his last name not be published. ``The
drinker can stop. The alcoholic can't. So if you ask for help, it
is admitting you're an alcoholic.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael, 63, a former professor in Moscow, started drinking
heavily after he lost his first job in New York City and became
homeless. ``When you sleep on a bench,'' he said, ``it's not so bad
when you drink, but it's impossible when you're sober.''
</P>
<P>
   He was sent to shelters, to hospitals and to detoxification
programs. ``They were nice and very professional,'' he said, ``but
all their experiences connect with American realities. Here I don't
have to explain a lot of things. They understand already.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
