<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-PRIMARY-CHANGES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATAKI LOWERS BAR FOR GOP PRESIDENTIAL PRIMARY 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By CLIFFORD J. LEVY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Gov. George Pataki and Republican leaders are
making it somewhat easier to obtain a spot on the ballot in the
Republican presidential primary in New York, responding to
criticism that the party was trying to control these contests with
arduous requirements that were a throwback to old-style machine
politics.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki announced Tuesday that candidates who wanted to enter the
Republican primary next year would have to gather fewer signatures
than required in the 1996 primary, which was marked by accusations
that the state party used the rules to insure that only the
leadership's favorite, former Sen. Bob Dole, was on the ballot.
</P>
<P>
   The requirements have historically been more restrictive than in
any other state. They were considered so onerous in 1996 that
besides Dole, only two Republicans, Steve Forbes and Patrick
Buchanan, sought to take part in the primary.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes spent more than $1 million for workers to round up
signatures and for lawyers to fend off challenges to his petitions
by the party leadership, ultimately getting on the ballot across
the state. Buchanan was listed in most parts of the state. Dole
ended up winning the primary, and the nomination.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, candidates in the Republican primary had to collect
signatures in all 31 congressional districts in the state. The
number per district was 5 percent of registered party voters or
1,250 signatures, whichever number was smaller. The new rules still
require signatures from all 31 districts, but the number required
has been reduced, to one-half of 1 percent of registered party
voters, or 1,000, whichever figure is smaller.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki hailed the changes, which bring the requirements for the
Republican primary in line with the less stringent ones for the
Democratic primary. By tradition, the leaders of the two major
parties decide on the primary requirements every four years and
then present them to the governor and the state Legislature, which
ratify them.
</P>
<P>
   The new rules ``will help insure that New York Republicans have
a choice of candidates,'' the governor said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   But the campaign of Forbes, who is running again, dismissed the
changes as inadequate. Campaign manager Bill Dal Col said that even
with the reduction in the number of signatures, it was still more
difficult to get on the ballot in New York than in any other state.
</P>
<P>
   He noted that in most states with petition requirements, the
campaigns need gather only a total number of signatures statewide,
rather than a certain number per district. And in some states, the
secretaries of state have the power to put candidates on the
primary ballot.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they truly wanted to open up the election process in New
York state, they would streamline it significantly,'' Dal Col said.
``This still leaves the party apparatus in control, rather than the
people.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that the Forbes campaign planned to spend $500,000 to
win a spot in the New York primary, which is to be held on March 7,
2000.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
