<HEADLINE>
ITALY DOWNPLAYS GIANT TASK AHEAD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM BARRERO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Of the four teams scheduled to play at the Rose
Bowl in their first games of the 1999 Women's World Cup on Sunday,
Italy was the last to arrive in Los Angeles, getting into town
Monday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   But it didn't take long for the Italians to begin some serious
work.
</P>
<P>
   At 10 a.m. Tuesday, the Azzurriu hit the practice pitch at
Loyola Marymount for the first of two sessions. Italy also
practiced from 4-6 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   The double duty schedule is the same for the next four days
leading up to Sunday's match against Germany, which the Italians
enter as a decided underdog.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had a few problems physically this morning because of
the time change and the travel,'' Italy coach Carlo Facchin said
through an interpreter. ``But we were prepared for this.''
</P>
<P>
   What the Italians also continue preparing for are the three
grueling first-round matches awaiting them in the so-called Group
of Death, which also includes Brazil, Mexico and the aforementioned
Germans.
</P>
<P>
   But that seems to be the least of Facchin's worries as he
focuses his team on its game and away from any media perceptions of
what is ``supposed to happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The media) says this, but we are very much alive,'' said
Facchin, who seems comfortable that most don't expect Italy to make
it past the first stage after advancing to the quarterfinals in its
only other World Cup appearance in 1991. ``There is no use crying
over this.''
</P>
<P>
   (BOX) Nigeria used Tuesday to scrimmage the Torrance Elite
Soccer Club, a team of mostly college players from the South Bay,
in an afternoon match at West Los Angeles College.
</P>
<P>
   The Super Falcons were flawless in a 9-0 victory with their ``B
team scoring five second-half goals, including a beautiful
one-timer by Stella Mbachu.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Ismaila Mabo, who was pleased with his team's 4-3
scrimmage victory over China on Saturday, didn't know what to think
after Tuesday's game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will not be able to assess most of my team because the
opponents were no match,'' Mabo said. ``But a couple of players
played well for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Nigeria opens World Cup play Sunday against North Korea.
</P>
</TEXT>
