<SLUG> BC-ORACLE-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ORACLE'S 4TH-QUARTER EARNINGS EXCEED EXPECTATIONS
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: Calif.)  (nk) 
 By LAWRENCE M. FISHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Confounding its critics, the Oracle Corp.
reported revenues and earnings for its fiscal fourth quarter
Tuesday that surpassed analysts' estimates.
</P>
<P>
   Oracle, which reported its financial results after the close of
the market, announced earlier that it was laying off 325 employees
_ less than 1 percent of its total 43,000-person global work force
_ effective immediately, as it moved to trim costs. The job cuts
are part of an effort to reduce operating expenses by $1 billion
over the next 18 months and remake Oracle as an Internet company.
</P>
<P>
   Oracle shares closed at $25.125, down $1.3125, in Nasdaq trading
Tuesday, but traded as high as $28.875 after hours.
</P>
<P>
   For the quarter ended May 31, Oracle said that earnings rose 31
percent to $527.4 million, or 36 cents a diluted share, from $402.8
million, or 27 cents a share, a year earlier, as revenues grew 22
percent to $2.94 billion from $2.41 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts had expected Oracle to earn 32 cents a share, according
to the First Call Corp. That estimate represented a downward
revision of the consensus from 34 cents a share; several analysts
lowered their estimates before a meeting at Oracle headquarters
last month.
</P>
<P>
   ``They really pulled it off,'' said William Epifanio, an analyst
with J.P. Morgan, who had been among those who lowered their
numbers. Oracle's strong sales were in contrast to sluggishness
reported by most vendors of what is known as enterprise resource
planning, or ERP, software, including SAP, Peoplesoft, BAAN and JD
Edwards. They have said that Year 2000 concerns have prompted
companies to defer purchases.
</P>
<P>
   ``What this tells me is that Oracle is successfully gaining
market share from some of the others,'' Epifanio said.
</P>
<P>
   In the third quarter, Oracle, too, had reported slowing sales of
its key data base management program, Oracle 8i, and its corporate
applications, like Oracle Financials. In the fourth quarter,
Oracle's software license revenue grew by 22 percent, year over
year. Data base software sales grew by 25 percent, while
application sales grew by 28 percent. Service revenues grew by 22
percent.
</P>
<P>
   For the year, Oracle reported a 35 percent gain in earnings to
$1.29 billion, or 87 cents a diluted share, from $813.7 million, or
54 cents a share, in fiscal 1998. Revenues grew 24 percent to $8.83
billion from $7.14 billion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
