</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NUKE-LABS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: NEW MANAGEMENT FOR THE NUCLEAR LABS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Wednesday, June 16:
</P>
<P>
   The Energy Department, in charge of America's nuclear weapons
labs for the past two decades, has proved incapable of assuring
security or effective management at these vital facilities. The
department's prolonged failure to pursue serious nuclear espionage
allegations at Los Alamos and its resistance to last year's White
House directive on improving security are only the latest alarming
examples of a deep-rooted institutional problem. That is the
scathing conclusion reached by a presidential advisory board after
a three-month review with full access to classified material. The
board rightly recommends reorganizing nuclear weapons programs to
establish clear lines of accountability.
</P>
<P>
   The report, by the President's Foreign Intelligence Advisory
Board, headed by former Sen.r Warren Rudman, offers two
alternatives _ a semi-independent agency within the Energy
Department or a fully independent agency reporting directly to the
White House. Either way, the new agency would have responsibility
for scientific research, security and the labs' exchange programs
with Russia and China designed to promote nuclear arms control.
Based on the report's account of Energy Department security
failures, bureaucratic arrogance and resistance to reform from
within, a fully independent agency accountable to the highest
political authorities seems best. Although the panel recognized the
changes ordered by Bill Richardson since he took over the Energy
Department last year, it judged that these had not yet transformed
the department's ``dysfunctional'' culture.
</P>
<P>
   While security issues need more focused attention, it would be
wrong to return to Cold War secrecy. An important part of the labs'
work today consists of work that should not be classified, like
improving techniques for verifying compliance with arms treaties
and developing methods for the safe disposal of discarded bomb
plutonium and uranium. It is also important that lab scientists not
be blocked from interchange with American universities.
</P>
<P>
   But the new agency must safeguard vital military secrets. Rudman
and his colleagues have shown how to do that in a powerful,
balanced report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-15-99 2337EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
