<HEADER>
A6882 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-OBSERVER-BUSH-NY     06-15 0738
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-OBSERVER-BUSH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL OBSERVER: AN EPIDEMIC OF GRINS HITS THE GRANITE STATE
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By GAIL COLLINS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   George W. Bush is literally golden, with a ruddy glow that gives
him the look of having been perfectly toasted. ``I know what
matters is that a candidate have a positive, hopeful, upbeat,
optimistic message,'' he said at a rally in New Hampshire this
week, going on to assure the crowd that he himself was positive,
hopeful, upbeat and optimistic as all get-out.
</P>
<P>
   At this point, the governor of Texas had been campaigning for
president for approximately 40 hours, and appeared to have pretty
much wrapped up the Republican nomination. The average voter, who
could not identify Bush in a lineup, nevertheless seems to like him
much better than Al Gore, rating him higher in almost every
possible category of achievement. The way things are going we will
probably soon hear that polls show most Americans think Bush would
do a better job as Tipper's husband. It would be enough to make
even Bob Dole giddy.
</P>
<P>
   The cheer absolutely pulsates through his campaign. Bush has a
Clintonian determination to win over every single individual in a
crowded ballroom, and if one stray voter seems oblivious to his
presence he will go after that lost little sheep, grabbing an arm
or clapping a back until contact is made. He can work a room for
hours, till no hand is left unshaken. This is a good day to be
alive! Later he will make his formal speech, which is always about
being a compassionate conservative, and he will perhaps tell a
little story about his mother, the former first lady, or his dad,
the ex-president, or remind them of all the successes he achieved
governing Texas during one of the greatest economic booms in the
nation's history.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love being in New Hampshire!'' Bush says over and over.
</P>
<P>
   And New Hampshire loves Bush. Its famously dour inhabitants are
making money hand over fist these days, and they are positive,
hopeful, upbeat and optimistic, too. Frankly, the Republicans there
do not seem nearly as interested in the principles of compassionate
conservatism as they are bonded to Bush's euphoria. They like all
the candidates! Larry Emerton, an uncommitted state legislator, has
hardly had time to decide whom to support this time around, what
with the way his real estate business has been going like
gangbusters. He thinks Bush would be a terrific nominee even though
he has been a longtime backer of Lamar Alexander (``He's a nice
guy'') and admires just about everybody else as well. ``I even like
Bill Bradley,'' says Emerton, as he watches Bush spreading cheer at
the Republican Women's Lilac Luncheon.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is supposed to be on a mission to recapture the Republican
Party from extremism, just as Bill Clinton took back the Democrats
for the moderate middle in 1992. At this moment, his job seems
beyond easy. The forces of right-wing righteousness whose howling
scared away voters over the last two elections are already in
retreat. When Bush implicitly declares war against Pat Buchanan in
the free-trade section of his stump speech (``The fearful build
walls, the confident tear them down!'') he is really paying
Buchanan the compliment of pretending he's on the radar screen.
</P>
<P>
   However, the old, angry Republican Party is still alive and
yelping in Washington, where it is currently engaged in a war
against gun control and a fratricidal feud over the budget. Bush
actually shares many of its positions on matters like guns and
abortion and tax cuts. (When asked to name the first two things he
would do as president, Bush, who didn't appear to have thought
quite that specifically about the future, basically said he would
build more antiballistic-missile systems and cut taxes for the
wealthy.) But the mean-spiritedness of the capital is anathema to
his message of cooperation and inclusion _ there's plenty to go
around and nobody should be left out.
</P>
<P>
   It would be interesting to see Bush and the House Republicans
trying to inhabit the same ticket. At the candidate's first stop in
New Hampshire, someone asked him what he had to say about Congress'
accomplishments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought the welfare package was great,'' he said, reverting
to Bill Clinton's first term. Asked for something more recent he
laughed, and called 1996 ``recent memory.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the only time all week that George W. Bush looked
backward.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
