<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LABOR-1ST-LEDE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$20.4 MILLION GRANT WILL HELP LAID-OFF BOEING WORKERS  
 CORRECTS IAM LODGE NO. TO 751 FROM 752, IN 4TH GRAPH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAUL NYHAN  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The U.S. Labor Department is sending up to $20.4 million to
Washington state to help the growing number of laid-off Boeing
workers develop skills to land new jobs.
</P>
<P>
   The federal agency announced a 26-month grant on Tuesday
designed to help thousands of Boeing employees grappling with the
latest round of layoffs at the aerospace giant. Now, former
machinists, engineers and other workers will be able to tap a wider
range of employment services, ranging from help in drafting resumes
to training in new professions.
</P>
<P>
   The award comes at a critical time for Boeing's workers. The
company has already announced plans to eliminate roughly 24,000
jobs in Washington state by the end of 2000, as part of a broader
initiative to make the company leaner and more profitable. Unlike
past layoffs, however, not all the laid-off workers will be rehired
when business picks up, according to the International Association
of Machinists.
</P>
<P>
   ``This grant is needed because aerospace machinists have skills
that are unique to airplane production,'' said Bill Johnson,
president of IAM Lodge 751, which represents more than 40,000
machinists.
</P>
<P>
   Under the grant, the state's Employment Security Department will
funnel the money to a network of private councils and consortiums.
The groups will then offer employment aid directly to both union
and non-union workers from Boeing.
</P>
<P>
   A collection of public officials, including President Clinton
and Washington Gov. Gary Locke, hailed the development as a
necessary step to help U.S. firms and their workers cope with the
demands of the global economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``In spite of an overall healthy economy, many companies are
having to reorganize and downsize to remain competitive,'' Clinton
said in a statement released in Washington, D.C., Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, the grant will target the 2,400 Boeing employees
slated to be let go by the end of December, according to the Labor
Department. However, state officials have yet to receive details on
the scope of the award. And they say the federal agency may also
award additional funds to cover the rest of the workers Boeing says
it will lay off in the region by the end of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Often in these cases with large layoffs the Department of
Labor will accept additional requests to provide additional funding
later on,'' said Michael Wilson, a spokesman for the Employment
Security Department.
</P>
<P>
   To kick off the effort, the Labor Department is making $10
million immediately available.
</P>
<P>
   The assistance will come on top of career centers that Boeing
has already established to assist former employees struggling to
shift from the aerospace industry to other fields.
</P>
<P>
   The award also arrives only two months before Boeing enters
direct talks on a new contract for its 46,000 machinists. A key
negotiating point will be how the manufacturer will manage its work
force during the next four years. In the past, Boeing and its
unions have battled over the company's efforts to hire outside
contractors because the move threatened union jobs.
</P>
<P>
   In a related development, the Labor Department announced a
separate $4 million grant that will assist 375 laid-off workers at
Packard Bell NEC in Fife, Intel Corp. in DuPont and Matsushita
Semiconductor in Puyallup, all in Washington state.
</P>
<P>
   On the Internet, Boeing workers can contact
www.reachingout-washington.com for other information on employment
services.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
