u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-HKN-SABRES-STARS-NY     06-15 0705
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-HKN-SABRES-STARS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUSH COMES TO SHOVE, AND GRITTY SABRES GET EVEN
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating to correct garbling)  (nk) 
 By JOE LaPOINTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. _ A good Stanley Cup championship round took
another determined step toward greatness Tuesday night when the
Buffalo Sabres evened the series with a 2-1 victory over the Dallas
Stars in the happy bedlam of Marine Midland Arena. All four games
have been low-scoring, with tight checking, hard hitting and
scoring chances preciously earned.
</P>
<P>
   This time, Buffalo won the test of wills with two goals after
turnovers uncharacteristic of the Dallas defensemen.
</P>
<P>
   Geoff Sanderson, who scored one of the goals on a breakaway,
said: ``We were lucky we finally capitalized. They make so few''
turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   Dominik Hasek, Buffalo's world-class goalie, stopped 30 of 31
Stars shots and participated in a few collisions, one of which
earned him a roughing penalty.
</P>
<P>
   The series resumes in Dallas on Thursday night and returns here
for Game 6 on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   In four games, the Sabres have eight goals and the Stars have
nine, one of which was an empty-net goal. But low scores don't mean
boring games in baseball or soccer, and these hockey games have
been anything but dull. The older Stars and the younger Sabres are
well matched.
</P>
<P>
   The game had an angry snarl, with Buffalo forwards frequently
slamming their bodies into Derian Hatcher, the Stars' big and
rugged captain. The Dallas players responded by jostling Hasek, who
has been known to lose his temper when provoked. In one of the
game's defining moments, Hasek started an angry scrum by moving
from his crease to bump Hatcher.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars played without Brett Hull, who left in the first
period of Game 3 with a groin injury. It is not known if Hull will
be available for Game 5.
</P>
<P>
   Both teams scored in the first period Tuesday, with Buffalo's
goal coming at even strength and Dallas's on the power play. The
Sabres went ahead by 1-0 when Sanderson scooped up a loose puck
after it got by Dallas defenseman Shawn Chambers at the right
point. Sanderson raced down ice, drew Stars goalie Ed Belfour down
with a fake, and put the puck past him at 8:09.
</P>
<P>
   But after Buffalo's Wayne Primeau took a charging penalty at
9:32, the Stars tied the score at 10:14 when Jere Lehtinen beat
Hasek with a low wrist shot that he took quickly after receiving
Mike Modano's pass from behind the goal line.
</P>
<P>
   The second period was among the best in the series. It ended
with the Sabres leading by 2-1 and both captains arguing with the
referees about four roughing penalties. One went to Hasek, who
charged out from his crease to run into Hatcher.
</P>
<P>
   Hasek was knocked to the ice, face forward, by Pat Verbeek, a
small but tough player. Belfour, on the way to his locker room,
then approached Hasek as they left the ice and had words with him,
the second such scene in this series.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Dallas' Joe Nieuwendyk was not penalized for crashing
into Hasek, but Buffalo's Brian Holzinger was penalized for
boarding Hatcher.
</P>
<P>
   Those were not the only chippy plays in the period. The Stars'
Brian Skrudland was penalized for roughing after knocking off Mike
Peca's helmet after the Sabres' captain tried to check Skrudland.
On another hit, the Sabres' Rhett Warrener knocked off Dave Reid's
helmet.
</P>
<P>
   The Sabres scored the only goal in the period and almost had
another. They went up by 2-1 at 7:37. The goal followed a turnover
by a Dallas defenseman, Craig Ludwig, who lost the puck in his end.
Buffalo's Dixon Ward came up with it and beat Belfour from close
range.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Belfour stopped Miroslav Satan in close with a brilliant
stick save. Satan, who had 40 goals in the regular season but has
none this series, has been under pressure from Ruff, the local news
media and fans. As the second period ended with the home team
ahead, the packed arena was filled with a steady roar.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas Coach Ken Hitchcock said Sabres fans and neutral
observers were wrong to give up on Buffalo after Dallas won by 2-1
here on Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``The series is just getting started, and people had it
ending,'' Hitchcock said. ``It was a real good game, well played by
both sides.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
