</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-RANGERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKS ROCK RANGERS ROOKIE IN 6-2 WIN 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JOE DRAPE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ History dictated that Ryan Glynn never had a chance.
For the Texas Rangers' right-hander to notch his first major league
victory, he had to outpitch David Cone. Sixteen previous pitchers
had sought their first victory when they faced the Yankee ace.
Their record? O-12.
</P>
<P>
   Glynn, a 24-year-old rookie, lasted six innings, gave up six
hits and was rocked for six runs as the Yankees won Tuesday night
for the fifth time in six games, 6-2, before 28,200 at Yankee
stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The beginning of the end came early and from the sweet spots of
the Yankees' most consistent bats: Chili Davis and Derek Jeter.
</P>
<P>
   Davis, the 39-year-old designated hitter who was back in the
starting lineup after the team's weeklong tour of the National
League, ignited a six-run second inning with a single to the right
field gap that scored Bernie Williams. Jeter finished the rally
with a three-run homer to right field that put the Yankees ahead by
6-1.
</P>
<P>
   In between, the Yankees batted around for the 14th time this
season and cranked out more than five runs for the 11th time.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get a lead like that you can afford to make a few
mistakes,'' said Cone, who, while running his record to 7-2, made
very few of them.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees took advantage of every mistake made by a pitcher
making just his seventh appearance in the big leagues. Glynn (0-1)
walked Bernie Williams to open the second, then watched Tino
Martinez rip a grounder by him and up the middle. Next came Davis,
who spent last week's interleague road trip in Florida and
Philadelphia taking extra batting practice because the designated
hitter rule is not in effect in the National League cities.
</P>
<P>
   No one has ever accused him of being a glove man _ in fact, he
set the California Angels' team record for errors by an outfielder
with 19 in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   But he takes his role seriously and, despite getting just four
at bats in six games last week, Davis is now 4 for 8 in the last
two games. He went 2 for 3 against the Rangers to raise his average
to .332.
</P>
<P>
   When Glynn offered him a fastball, he drilled it into the right
field gap for a single to score Williams and tally his 42nd RBI _
second on the Yankees only to Jeter.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a good, professional hitter,'' said manager Joe Torre,
who appreciated Davis taking his week off without complaint. ``He
works the pitcher until he gets something he can hit.''
</P>
<P>
   Glynn got Shane Spencer to fly out before Luis Sojo snapped out
of his 0-for 14 slump with a double to left that brought Martinez
home and put the Yankees up by 2-1. But then the pitcher threw ball
four past Chuck Knoblauch, as well as his catcher Greg Zaun, and
Davis scored.
</P>
<P>
   But the pitcher hadn't even been welcomed to the majors yet by
the game's hottest hitter. Jeter came into the game with seven
consecutive multiple-hit games, a .382 batting average, and little
desire to talk about numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to do well, but I think people get caught up in the
stats just because you're hitting certain numbers,'' said Jeter,
who came into the game with a major-league-leading 91 hits.
</P>
<P>
   When Glynn tried to get Jeter to chase an 0-1 curve, the
shortstop poked it into the right field bleachers for a 6-1 lead.
It was enough for the Yankees, but not for Jeter, whose
multiple-hit streak was snapped _ he struck out in his other three
at bats. ``I really didn't swing the bat that well,'' Jeter
conceded. ``But I had one big hit and more often than not when you
give David Cone a six-run lead, you're going to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Before turning the game over to Ramiro Mendoza in the eighth,
Cone scattered four hits and struck out six. In the second, he
walked Rafael Palmeiro, then gave up a run-scoring double to Lee
Stevens to fall behind, 1-0. Those two also got to Cone in the
seventh inning when Palmeiro singled and Stevens moved him to third
with a double. Zaun hit a sacrifice fly to score Palmeiro for the
Rangers' last run.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's held us together all year,'' said Torre. ``We've had
problems in our rotation with El Duque being flat and Clemens not
being where he wants. David has been consistent all year long.''
</P>
<P>
   Since coming to the Yankees in 1995, Cone has won consistently
even when he hasn't had his best stuff. He is 55-19 with a 3.20 ERA
in a Yankee uniform and 31-6 with a 3.00 ERA in Yankee Stadium. And
Tuesday night, he said, he found some of the old pop.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get a lead and you can rear back and find that fastball,''
he said. ``What I've been proud of is that even without my best
stuff I've been able to keep us in the game.''
</P>
<P>
   When reminded of his dominance over rookie pitchers trying to
get that first victory under their belt, Cone smiled. He cautioned
that Yankee Stadium and the fact that the Yanks were the defending
World Series champions contributed to Glynn's problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a huge test and I thought he threw pretty well,'' Cone
said. ``He had one bad inning, really.''
</P>
<P>
   But that's all it took.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
