<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-REDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS DEFEAT REDS, 11-3 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI _ Rickey Henderson has two trademarks: the stolen
base and the leadoff home run. Make that three, if you count the
way Henderson always picks at his uniform jersey leaving the
batter's box when he knows he has just hit a home run.
</P>
<P>
   On a night when the Mets matched a club record with six home
runs and Henderson hit two, Henderson led off Tuesday's game with a
homer for the first time as a member of the Mets. It was one of
three homers by his team in the first 18 pitches of a game that
turned into an 11-3 rout of the Cincinnati Reds.
</P>
<P>
   But Henderson did not pick at his jersey, even though he had
just extended his major-league record to 74 homers leading off a
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I hit the first one, they all asked me why I didn't do
it,'' Henderson said referring to his teammates. ``So I had to hit
another one.''
</P>
<P>
   Henderson did just that in the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   The homer splurge helped make it a day to remember for Manager
Bobby Valentine. His two-game suspension and $5,000 fine were
upheld Tuesday afternoon by National League president Leonard
Coleman after Coleman heard Valentine's appeal over the phone. The
suspension will cover the game here Wednesday afternoon and one in
St. Louis Thursday night. Bench coach, Bruce Benedict, will be in
charge.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night, Valentine was in the Mets' dugout, too busy
high-fiving homer hitters to worry about his ban. With Henderson
leading the way, the Mets homered three times off the the first 18
pitches delivered by Brett Tomko. By the time the first inning was
over, John Olerud and Mike Piazza had homered in consecutive
at-bats. Olerud's came with a man on. Piazza's extended his hitting
streak to 18 games. And the Mets had a 4-0 lead before a Reds'
player had batted.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the evening was over, Edgardo Alfonzo and Matt
Franco had homered off Tomko, and Henderson had homered again, this
time off Jason Bere. Only once before in the 38-year history of the
franchise had the Mets homered six times in a game: on April 4,
1988, opening day, in Montreal. Darryl Strawberry hit two, as did
Kevin McReynolds, and Kevin Elster and Lenny Dykstra belted the
other ones.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night, six of the Mets' first eight hits were home runs,
which accounted for the Mets' first seven runs. All of which helped
Rick Reed (4-3) coast to his first victory since May 12, a span of
six starts, even though he was pitching with a urinary tract
infection that almost made it necessary for him to return to New
York this morning instead of taking the mound tonight.
</P>
<P>
   But Reed woke up feeling better at 4 a.m, and felt even better
after allowing 2 runs and 8 hits in 8 innings, matching the longest
outing by a Mets' starter this season. As for Tomko, he somehow
made it through 6 innings, allowing 6 runs on 7 hits, of them home
runs.
</P>
<P>
   In the three times the Mets have faced Tomko this year, they
have hit 9 home runs. The last time they had hit consecutive home
runs, it was against Tomko, of course.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night's outburst by Henderson means he has reached base
seven times in nine plate appearances over the last two days (4
walks, 1 double, 2 home runs).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
